<DIV1 TYPE="prologue">

<PB REF="00000009.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>Roberd of Brunne's "Handlyng Synne."</HEAD>
<HEAD>[Harl. MS. 1701; Bodl. 415.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Readings in the English notes are from Bodl. 415 (generally named <I>O</I>.) except when markt <I>Harl</I>. for Harl. 1701, or D. for Dulwich 24.</NOTE></HEAD>
<OPENER>Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e boke &thorn;at men clepyn yn frenshe Manuele pecche, &thorn;e whych boke made yn frenshe, Roberd Gros-test, Bysshop of Lyncolne.</OPENER>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">Bodl. 415 has this too. The Dulwich MS. 24 has only 'Manuel de Pecche,' and at top in a later hand, 'God be &thorn;e fyndere,' and the first four lines of the text repeated.</NOTE>[THE PROLOG.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bodl. 415 has this too. The Dulwich MS. 24 has only 'Manuel de Pecche,' and at top in a later hand, 'God be &thorn;e fyndere,' and the first four lines of the text repeated.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FADYR, and Sone, &amp; holy goste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at art o god of my&yogh;t&euml;s moste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is oo god . and my&yogh;t ha&thorn; most D.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">his . . . we schul D.</NOTE> wurschyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">worshepe [o inserted] O.</NOTE> shul we bygynne,</L>
<L N="4">To shame &thorn;e fende &amp; shew<NOTE PLACE="foot">shewe O, schoue D.</NOTE> oure synne;</L>
<L>Synne to shew&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shewe O, shew <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> vs to frame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">eschewe vs &thorn;er D.</NOTE></L>
<L>God to wurschyp,<NOTE PLACE="foot">worshepe [o inserted] O.</NOTE> &thorn;e fende to shame.</L>
<L>Shameful synne ys gode to lete,</L>
<L N="8">Al &thorn;at men do, bo&thorn;e smale &amp; grete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at men don smale or D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e grete, withoutyn pryuyte,</L>
<L>That ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, is D.</NOTE> commune to me &amp; the,</L>
<L>Of hem wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> y telle &yogh;ow nede<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;erof telle I wil and not hyde D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">As y haue herde &amp; red<NOTE PLACE="foot">rede O.</NOTE> yn dede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">red. herd and sayde . D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;yse &thorn;an ys my<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &thorn;e ferste &thorn;an is oure D.</NOTE> sawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e commaundementys of the old&euml; lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys&euml; ten were fyrst vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;o ten . . vs be D.</NOTE> &yogh;euyn,
<PB REF="00000010.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>And fyrst we wylyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">welyn O.</NOTE> of hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hem we schuld D.</NOTE> be shreuyn,</L>
<L N="17">Yn what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhatt D.</NOTE> poyntys &thorn;at we falle</L>
<L>Yn opon synne a&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-&yogh;ens D.</NOTE> hem alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sy&thorn;en of &thorn;e seuene synnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnys OD.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">In what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwaht D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge D.</NOTE> &thorn;e fende vs wynnes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wynnys OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sy&thorn;en of synne of sacrylege,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sacrilage O, and &thorn;e s. of sacrylege D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to holy chyrche outrage;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sacramentys seuene</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at techyn vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">teche &yogh;ow D.</NOTE> to &thorn;e blys<NOTE PLACE="foot">blysse O, blisse D.</NOTE> of heuene;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sy&thorn;yn of &thorn;e twelu&euml; poyntes of shryfte,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e twelue gracys of here<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;e . . . goddis D.</NOTE> &yogh;yfte;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at touche&thorn; dedly synne,</L>
<L N="28">In any spyce<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony speche D.</NOTE> &thorn;at we falle ynne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ys oponly seen or<NOTE PLACE="foot">opynly in dede D.</NOTE> wrou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of pryuytes<NOTE PLACE="foot">pryuytees O. See line 83 of French.</NOTE> speke y ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;t D, <I>om</I>. HO.</NOTE> nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pryuytes<NOTE PLACE="foot">pryuytees O. See line 83 of French.</NOTE> wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> y nat name</L>
<L N="32">For none<NOTE PLACE="foot">noun, or none O.</NOTE> &thorn;arefor&euml; shulde me<NOTE PLACE="foot">bere D.</NOTE> blame;</L>
<L>Leuer ys me &thorn;at &thorn;ey be hydde,</L>
<L>&thorn;an for me were oponly kydde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oponly were kydde O, &thorn;orwh me opynly were kyd D.</NOTE></L>
<L>No&thorn;eles &thorn;ey mote be shreuyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">but &yogh;it be-hovyth vs &thorn;er-of be schreue D, shreuyen O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">&yogh;yf &yogh;yfte of grac&euml; shal be &yogh;euyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ys clerkys<NOTE PLACE="foot">See line 91, etc. of the French.</NOTE> wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> y nou&yogh;t seye;</L>
<L>To greu&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">greuyn D.</NOTE> hem y haue grete eye,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey wote &thorn;at ys to wetyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei knowe wel &thorn;at is to wete D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="1a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">And se hyt wel before hem wrytyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; sen it ofte b. h. wrete D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at may be weyl on englyssh tolde,</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ow &thorn;at, y may be bolde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow I am be-hold D (part of the leaf is torn off).</NOTE></L>
<L>For lewd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lewede O, lewyd D. See l. 113 of the French.</NOTE> men y vndyr-toke
<PB REF="00000011.tif" N="3"></L>
<L N="44">On englyssh tunge to make &thorn;ys boke.</L>
<L>For many ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, a[rn] D.</NOTE> of swyche manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at talys and rymys wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, rymys woldyn here D. See ll. 79-80 of the French.</NOTE> ble&thorn;ly here;</L>
<L>Yn gamys, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn O.</NOTE> festys, &amp; at &thorn;e ale,</L>
<L N="48">Loue men to lestene trot&euml;uale:<NOTE PLACE="foot">trotouale O, to telle trotyuale D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at may falle ofte to vylanye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">velanye O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To dedly synne, or o&thorn;er folye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; o&thorn;er foly&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For swyche men haue y made &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O.</NOTE> ryme</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ey O, <I>om</I>. Harl.</NOTE> may weyl dyspende here tyme,</L>
<L N="53">And &thorn;ere-yn sumwhat for to here,</L>
<L>To leue al swych&euml; foul manere,</L>
<L>And for to kunn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">kun O.</NOTE> knowe &thorn;erynne</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at &thorn;ey wene no synne be ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To alle crystyn men vndir sunne,</L>
<L>And to god&euml; men of Brunne,</L>
<L>And spec&iuml;ali, alle be name,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e felaushepe of Symprynghame,</L>
<L>Roberd of Brunn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Robert of brunne D, leaf 1, back.</NOTE> grete&thorn; &yogh;ow</L>
<L>In al godenesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle godenes O, al goodness D.</NOTE> &thorn;at may to prow.<NOTE PLACE="foot">be prow D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Brunn&euml;wak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Brunne wake D, brymwake HO.</NOTE> yn Kesteuene,</L>
<L>Syxe myle be-syde<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro D.</NOTE> Sympryngham euene,</L>
<L N="65">Y dwelled<NOTE PLACE="foot">duellyde O.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> pryorye</L>
<L>Fyften&euml; &yogh;ere yn cumpanye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">compayne O, good cumpany D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of gode dane Ione<NOTE PLACE="foot">Daun Ioh D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">Of Camelton, &thorn;at now ys gone:</L>
<L>In hys tyme was y &thorn;ere ten &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>And knewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">knew O.</NOTE> and herd of hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">his goode D.</NOTE> maneres;</L>
<L>Sy&thorn;yn with dane<NOTE PLACE="foot">dan O, dan Joh Ioh Clatton D.</NOTE> Ione of Clyntone,</L>
<L N="72">Fyue wyntyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eer D.</NOTE> wy&thorn; hym gan y wone;</L>
<L>Dane Felyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">Philipp D.</NOTE> was mayst&eacute;r &thorn;at tyme</L>
<L>&THORN;at y began<NOTE PLACE="foot">be ganne O.</NOTE> &thorn;ys englyssh ryme.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;eres<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ers O, &yogh;eer D.</NOTE> of grace fyl &thorn;an to be
<PB REF="00000012.tif" N="4"></L>
<L N="76">A &thorn;ousynd &amp; &thorn;re hundred &amp; &thorn;re.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;at tym&euml; turnede<NOTE PLACE="foot">tournede O, turned D.</NOTE> y &thorn;ys<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On englyssh<NOTE PLACE="foot">In to ynglysch t. o. of frensch D.</NOTE> tunge out of frankys,</L>
<L>Of a boke as y fonde ynne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Out of . . . . &thorn;er inne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men clepyn &thorn;e bok&euml; "handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">callyd &thorn;e book handlyng of D.</NOTE> synne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="81">In<NOTE PLACE="foot">of D.</NOTE> frensh&euml; &thorn;er a clerk hyt sees,</L>
<L>He clepy&thorn; hyt "manuel de pecches."<NOTE PLACE="foot">pecchees O, callyd it . . pecches D.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Manuel' ys 'handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">handlynge O.</NOTE> with honde;'</L>
<L N="84">'Pecches'<NOTE PLACE="foot">pecchees O, callyd it . . pecches D.</NOTE> ys 'synne,' y<NOTE PLACE="foot">to O.</NOTE> vndyrstonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn synnys to vnderstond D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ese twey wurdys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O.</NOTE> &thorn;at beyn otwynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to . . . arn a twynne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Do<NOTE PLACE="foot">put D.</NOTE> hem to gedyr, ys "handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">handlynge O.</NOTE> synne."</L>
<L>And weyl ys clepyd, for &thorn;ys skyle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">callyd . . skele D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">And as y wote, &yogh;ow shew<NOTE PLACE="foot">shewe O.</NOTE> y wyle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fond schewyn I wele D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We handel synn&euml; euery day;<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer dayly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In wurde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrde O.</NOTE> and ded&euml;, al<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;at O.</NOTE> we may,<NOTE PLACE="foot">or dede with o&thorn;er foly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lytyl or mochel,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> synne we do,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;e fend and oure flesh tysyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e flesch techith D.</NOTE> vs &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>ff&oacute;r &thorn;ys skyle hyt may<NOTE PLACE="foot">may wel D.</NOTE> be seyde</L>
<L>'Handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">handlynge O.</NOTE> synne' for oure mysbreyde;</L>
<L>ffor euery day &amp; euery<NOTE PLACE="foot">day . many an D (rest of leaf torn).</NOTE> oure</L>
<L N="96">We synne &thorn;at shal we bye ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">we a bey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> soure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">A nou&thorn;yr O, and ofte handlyng it D (part of leaf gone).</NOTE> handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">handlynge O.</NOTE> &thorn;er shuld be,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; shryfte of mou&thorn;e to clens&euml; &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Handyl &thorn;y synn&euml; yn &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghte O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lytyl &amp; mochel, what &thorn;ou hast wroght;</L>
<L N="101">Handyl &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">remembre &thorn;o D.</NOTE> synne to hau&euml; drede;</L>
<L>No&thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">No&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> but peyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne O.</NOTE> ys &thorn;arfore mede.</L>
<L>Handyl &thorn;y synnes, &amp; weyl hem gesse,</L>
<L N="104">How &thorn;ey fordo<NOTE PLACE="foot">fordoun O.</NOTE> al &thorn;y godenesse.</L>
<L>Handyl &thorn;y synnes, <SUP>31</SUP>&amp; weyl hem euene,<SUP>31</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">31_31 alle weyl <I>and</I> euene O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ell&euml;s forbarre &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">how &thorn;ei f. D.</NOTE> &thorn;e blys<NOTE PLACE="foot">blysse O.</NOTE> of heuene.
<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Handyl hem at onys euerychone,</L>
<L N="108">Noght on&euml; by hym self alone.</L>
<L>Handyl so to ryse from alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non&euml; mak&euml; &thorn;e eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">oft to O.</NOTE> falle,</L>
<L>With shryfte of mou&thorn;e, &amp; wyl of herte,</L>
<L N="112">And a party, with penaunce smerte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys a skyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">skyle O.</NOTE> &thorn;at hyt may<NOTE PLACE="foot">shyl &amp; may D (leaf 2).</NOTE> be tolde</L>
<L>Handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Handlynge.</NOTE> synn&euml; many a folde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in many fold D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Handlynge.</NOTE> yn spech&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e handlyng in spycys D.</NOTE> ys as weyl<MILESTONE N="1b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">As handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Handlynge.</NOTE> yn ded&euml; euery deyl.</L>
<L>On &thorn;ys manere handyl &thorn;y dedys,</L>
<L>And lestene and lerne whan any hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat I &thorn;e D.</NOTE> redys.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou darst neuer recche where &thorn;ou bygynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he &thorn;ar not rekke wher he gynne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For euery-whare ys bygynnyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">begynnynge O, &thorn;er &thorn;e begynnyng is D.</NOTE> of synne;</L>
<L N="121">whedyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">whedyr outys O, qwhere he be-gynnyth to opene his book D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wylt opon<NOTE PLACE="foot">opone O.</NOTE> &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt fynde begynnyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">begynnynge O, &thorn;er &thorn;e begynnyng is D.</NOTE> oueral<NOTE PLACE="foot">on O, ha&thorn; a begynnyng on D.</NOTE> to loke:</L>
<L>Oueral ys bygynnyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">begynnynge O, &thorn;er &thorn;e begynnyng is D.</NOTE> oueral<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; oueral D.</NOTE> ys ende;</L>
<L N="124">Hou &thorn;at &thorn;ou wylt turne<NOTE PLACE="foot">turne hyt O, how so euere it turne D.</NOTE> or wende,</L>
<L>Many &thorn;yngys<NOTE PLACE="foot">See l. 73, etc. of French, and 79 for l. 127 English.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;eryn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er yn mayst &thorn;ou O, maybe &thorn;erinne D.</NOTE> here;</L>
<L>With oft<NOTE PLACE="foot">oft <I>Harl</I>., oftyn O.</NOTE> redyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">redynge O.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">men may it D.</NOTE> lere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst nat,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O, He may not D.</NOTE> with onys redyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">redynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">knowe &thorn;e so&thorn;e of euery &thorn;yng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Handyl, hyt behoue&thorn;, oft<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e ofte O.</NOTE> sy&thorn;ys,</L>
<L>To many maner synnes hyt wry&thorn;ys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">handle it ofte for to wete D, for many synnys here-in be wrete. D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Talys shalt &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">schal he D.</NOTE> fynde &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>And chauncys &thorn;at ha&thorn; happed for<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue happyde O, for &thorn;at han falle for dyuers D.</NOTE> synne;</L>
<L N="133">Meruelys, some as y fonde wrytyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fynde wrete D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">ou&thorn;yr O.</NOTE> &thorn;at haue be seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye O.</NOTE> &amp; wetyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">han be seyn &yogh;e noun wete D.</NOTE></L>
<L>None ben &thorn;are-yn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be &thorn;er ynne O, Now am &thorn;erin. D.</NOTE> more ne lesse,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at y founde wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fonde wrete O, &thorn;an I fond wreten D.</NOTE> or had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde O, &amp; haue D.</NOTE> wytnesse.</L>
<L N="137">&THORN;arefore may hyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">it may D.</NOTE> &amp; gode skyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">skyle O, skele qwhy D.</NOTE> why,</L>
<L>'Handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Handlynge O, handlyng of D.</NOTE> synne' be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be O, be callyd D, ys H; still, <I>is</I> is a root, and in the Northern dialect we find <I>I is, they is</I>, etc. Phil. Soc. Proc. ii. 150-1.</NOTE> clepyd oponly;</L>
<L>For hyt touche&thorn; no priuite,</L>
<L N="140">But opyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">opon O.</NOTE> synne &thorn;at called may be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Begynne we &thorn;an to telle yn hast,<NOTE PLACE="foot">haste O, &thorn;anne now yn hast D.</NOTE></L>
<L>with fadyr and sone and holy gost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hely gaste O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And yn wurschyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O, In &thorn;e wurschepe D.</NOTE> of oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">our O.</NOTE> lady,</L>
<L N="144">And al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle O, alle seyntis &thorn;at ben hir by D.</NOTE> &thorn;e halewys &thorn;at beyn hem by:</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yue O.</NOTE> vs grace ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn; O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> so to deme,</L>
<L>Vs to profyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">proffyte O, note D.</NOTE> and god to queme.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Commandments]</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The First Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Amen // Primum mandatum D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Non habebis deos alienos coram me. D.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The first commaundment<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundement O, ferste comaundement of euerychon D.</NOTE> ys of echone</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou shalt haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">houyn D.</NOTE> no god but one,'</L>
<L N="149">N&eacute; but o<NOTE PLACE="foot">on .o. O, And in oo g. &thorn;ou schal D.</NOTE> god shalt &thorn;ou leue,</L>
<L>Ne on no &thorn;yng &thorn;at wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge &thorn;at wyle O, to don no &thorn;ing &thorn;at schal D.</NOTE> hym greue.</L>
<L>Now<NOTE PLACE="foot">loke &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> be&thorn;enke &thorn;e weyl on &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="152">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou a&yogh;en &thorn;ys haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">hast O.</NOTE> do ou&yogh;t mys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">do owht a-&yogh;ens hym a mys D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fyrst askyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">askynge O, ferste askyng D, D <I>om</I>. ys.</NOTE> ys yn oure boke,<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer god forsoke;'</L>
<L>Any tym&euml;, as for nede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony t . . drede D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">Or for folye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">foly OD.</NOTE> or for drede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nede D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or ou&thorn;er chaunce &thorn;at you weyl woste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wost O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsoke fadyr and sone and holy goste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">gost O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ys ys one &thorn;e most&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">is &thorn;e moste D, most HO.</NOTE> synne</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at any man may fallyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony . . . falle D.</NOTE> ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue synned<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnyd O.</NOTE> &thorn;us gretly,</L>
<L>With sory herte &thorn;ou aske<NOTE PLACE="foot">drery herte aske D.</NOTE> mercy.</L>
<L>For god ys ful euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere ful OD.</NOTE> of pyte,</L>
<L N="164">Hys mercy ys euer redy to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;e noght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O.</NOTE> &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wylt craue,</L>
<L>Hys mochel<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret D.</NOTE> mercy shalt &thorn;ou haue.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl.</NOTE> [i-]preuyd be</L>
<L N="168">Wy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">be D.</NOTE> a tale of auctoryte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tale ys wrytyn, al and sum,</L>
<L>In a boke of<NOTE PLACE="foot">callyd D.</NOTE> 'Vitas Patrum:'&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Vit. Pat.</I> p. 579; <I>Libro de los Exemplos</I>, no. 35 (Spanish MS.); Gaston Paris, in <I>Hist. Litt. de la France</I>, xxviii. 193.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Tempted Monk.] A Tale</HEAD>
<L>Hyt was onys a munke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, monk D.</NOTE> and had a celle</L>
<L N="172">In a wyldernes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyldyrnesse O, wildernesse . &thorn;ere D.</NOTE> for to dwelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys munk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, monk of holy D.</NOTE> of relygyoun</L>
<L>Had a<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde a D, had <I>Harl</I>. O.</NOTE> grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret O.</NOTE> temptacyoun;</L>
<L>He was so temptyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">temptyd O, fondyd D.</NOTE> with lecherye,</L>
<L N="176">He &yogh;ede fro hys celle to seke folye;</L>
<L>He dede hym sone to a cyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">cytee O.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to egypte, &thorn;at yche cuntre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">cuntree O, ilke cuntre D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, as h&eacute; cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">com O, cam in to D.</NOTE> yn a strete,</L>
<L N="180">with a womman he gan mete;</L>
<L>Hys flesshe on<NOTE PLACE="foot">of O.</NOTE> here was so abeyted,<NOTE PLACE="foot">abeytyd OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yke<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;eke O.</NOTE> womman<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at woman sore D.</NOTE> he cou&eacute;ytyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">coueytyd OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>To here fadyr swy&thorn;e he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="184">And asked here to haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym hir to han D.</NOTE> yn dede.</L>
<L>Here fadyr was prest of sarysyne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sar&yogh;yne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In maummetry<NOTE PLACE="foot">maumetrye OD.</NOTE> he leued ynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">leuyd ynne O, leuyde he D (<I>om</I>. ynne).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest seyd &thorn;e munke<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, &thorn;at monk D.</NOTE> vn-to,
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="8"></L>
<L N="188">As my god<NOTE PLACE="foot">god.</NOTE> wyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, without my goddis wil I not D.</NOTE> so wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, without my goddis wil I not D.</NOTE> y do.</L>
<L>She shal noght<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O.</NOTE> to any be sette<NOTE PLACE="foot">to no man ben sett D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Withoutyn leue of my maumette.</L>
<L>The munk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, monk seide I graunt wel D.</NOTE> seyd he graunted weyl<MILESTONE N="2a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="192">Aftyr hys maumette to<NOTE PLACE="foot">I graunt wel, after &thorn;i mamett D.</NOTE> do euery deyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sarysyne to hys god<NOTE PLACE="foot">god O, &thorn;at s . . . D.</NOTE> &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And askede cunseyl of swyche a dede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he were of &thorn;e munk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk D, monk O, &thorn;at monk apay&yogh;ed D.</NOTE> payde,</L>
<L N="196">Or, &thorn;e &yogh;yfte shulde be delayde.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">delay&yogh;ed D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an answered hys termagaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">teruagaunt O, &thorn;at termagaunt D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;yue hym &thorn;y doghtyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">dou&yogh;tyr O, doutter D.</NOTE> on &thorn;ys cunnaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vp &thorn;is comenaunt D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he forsake, &amp; quyt&euml; clene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">quyt cleyme O (quit claim, give up), clene H, he must forsake qwy&yogh;t &amp; clene D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">God of heuene and hys bapteme,</L>
<L>And alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al OD.</NOTE> &thorn;e godenesse of hys munkhede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese &thorn;re forsak&euml;, mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">muste D.</NOTE> he nede;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he forsake hem apertly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">apertely O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="204">&YOGH;yue hym &thorn;y dou&yogh;tyr hard&euml;ly."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. hardly, O hardely, D hardily.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys prest come<NOTE PLACE="foot">com O.</NOTE> to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O, cam to &thorn;is D.</NOTE> munke, &amp; tolde</L>
<L>what<NOTE PLACE="foot">how D.</NOTE> he seyd, and what<NOTE PLACE="foot">how O, qwat D.</NOTE> he wolde;</L>
<L>'And &yogh;yf he wolde forsake &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if he forsake &thorn;ese alle D.</NOTE> &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="208">Hys dougtyr shulde hys own&euml; be.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">lete &thorn;i dou&yogh;tter his wyf be D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She was so moch&euml; yn hys &thorn;oght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou&yogh;t O, meche in his foul &thorn;ought D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Had he here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hadde he hir D.</NOTE> he rou&yogh;te of noghte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Allas O, Allas &thorn;er D.</NOTE> Ihesus he forsoke,</L>
<L N="212">And &thorn;e crystyndom &thorn;at he toke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e state of relygyoun,</L>
<L>And ches&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ches &thorn;er D.</NOTE> hys Dampnacyun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">damnacyun O, dampnacyoun D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Certys he dede grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">a gret D.</NOTE> outrage,</L>
<L N="216">To make &thorn;e deuyl so moche omage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">suych seruage D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>whan he had grauntede al hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde grauntyde O, qwen he had grauntyd his D.</NOTE> folye,</L>
<L>Out of hys mou&thorn;e he say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe O.</NOTE> flye<NOTE PLACE="foot">mou&thorn; &thorn;er fley a flyte D.</NOTE></L>
<L>A dowue vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">dowe in to D.</NOTE> &thorn;e fyrmament;</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e holy gost &thorn;an from hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro hym &thorn;an O, &thorn;o fro hym D.</NOTE> went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sarysyne wente to hys maumet,</L>
<L>And tolde hym how &thorn;e munke<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk D, monk O, &thorn;at monk apay&yogh;ed D.</NOTE> had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde O, had D.</NOTE> het:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ose O.</NOTE> &thorn;re &thorn;yng&euml;s" he wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, ha&thorn; D.</NOTE> forsake;</L>
<L N="224">Shal y, hym my dou&yogh;tyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">doghetyr O, dou&yogh;tter D.</NOTE> take?</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;ou me &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sey me now D.</NOTE> certeyn of alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">al OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>whe&thorn;er y shal, or y ne shalle."<NOTE PLACE="foot">shal OD, schal I &yogh;euyn hir . or I not schal D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e maumet<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at deuyl D.</NOTE> answeryd hastyly,</L>
<L N="228">"Y warne &thorn;e for enchesoun<NOTE PLACE="foot">nay I warne &thorn;ee . &amp; a cause qwhy D.</NOTE> why;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he forsake hys god for euere,<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hys god forsake&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyl forsaken D.</NOTE> hym neuere,</L>
<L>For he ys euer ful of pyte;</L>
<L N="232">Men clepyn hym god of cristianite;<NOTE PLACE="foot">callen . . cristiente D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;yf he wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil D.</NOTE> hym mercy craue,</L>
<L>Redyly mercy shal he haue;</L>
<L><SUP>19</SUP>&THORN;ou&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghe O, &thorn;owh D.</NOTE> he to-day fro hys god weyue,</L>
<L>To-morwe<NOTE PLACE="foot">morue O.</NOTE> hys god wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> hym receyue.<SUP>19</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">19_19 &THORN;owh he &thorn;is day his god forsake, to morwyn he wil a-&yogh;en hym take D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="237">&THORN;arfor,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore O.</NOTE> y forbede &thorn;e weyl,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> del&euml; with hym neuer a deyl."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest vnto &thorn;e munk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, &thorn;at monk D.</NOTE> went<NOTE PLACE="foot">wente O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyd, "y haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">he hadde in D.</NOTE> commaund&euml;ment<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundemente.</NOTE></L>
<L N="241">&THORN;at y ne shal del&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">delyn D.</NOTE> with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne my doghtyr &thorn;y wyfe to be;</L>
<L>For &thorn;y god ys of swych<NOTE PLACE="foot">sweche O, &thorn;at D.</NOTE> manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou forsake hym ryght now<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn;tnow O.</NOTE> here,</L>
<L N="245">To-morwe<NOTE PLACE="foot">morue O.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou com<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou mayst soone after comyn D.</NOTE> a&yogh;eyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a&yogh;eyne O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>And make with hym acorde certeyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">acorde wy&thorn; hym certeyne O, &amp; haue for&yogh;eue|nesse of al certeyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou haue do<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun O.</NOTE> neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer O.</NOTE> so ylle</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylle O.</NOTE> he graunte &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">aske mercy. &amp; &thorn;ou schalt han D.</NOTE> hys gode wylle.</L>
<L N="249">My god me bad on none<NOTE PLACE="foot">no D.</NOTE> wyse</L>
<L>To dele with &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym D.</NOTE> ne none of hyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e munke<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, &thorn;at monk D.</NOTE> rependyd hym &thorn;an, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">repentyd hym in &thorn;at D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>"Alas!" he seyd, "what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> have y wroght</L>
<L N="253">&THORN;at y shulde euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer O, hym euere D.</NOTE> hym forsake</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys so redy me efte<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere me D.</NOTE> to take.</L>
<L>&THORN;y mercy, god, ys mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">his mercy is mechil D.</NOTE> to telle;</L>
<L N="256">when<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whan O, qwan D.</NOTE> y see a maumet of helle</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer O.</NOTE> &yogh;yt loued &thorn;e,</L>
<L>He speky&thorn; of &thorn;y mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret D (<I>om</I>. he).</NOTE> pyte.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;yn &thorn;ou art<NOTE PLACE="foot">and si&thorn;&thorn;in he is D.</NOTE> so mylde and meke</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;y mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">His mechil D.</NOTE> mercy wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil I now D.</NOTE> y seke;</L>
<L>Here y forsak&euml; &thorn;at y toke,</L>
<L>To hym y me betake<NOTE PLACE="foot">take OD.</NOTE> &thorn;at y forsoke."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="263">Se&thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Se&thorn;&thorn;yn O, Si&thorn;&thorn;in D.</NOTE> he &yogh;ede to an ermyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heremyte D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And shrofe hym of hys synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle his synnys D.</NOTE> astyte;</L>
<L>And tolde hym &thorn;at he had y-doun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">how &thorn;at he hadde doun O, how he had don D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsaken god and hys relygyoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">cristendom D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ys forsayde ermyte ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e hermyte &thorn;erfore D.</NOTE> sory was<MILESTONE N="2b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at he had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde O, had don D.</NOTE> do so grete trespas;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, he bad hym dwelle<NOTE PLACE="foot">to dwelle O, dwelle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;re wokys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;o &thorn;re woukys O, &thorn;re wykis D.</NOTE> with hym yn his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his D, <I>om</I>. HO.</NOTE> celle;</L>
<L>For hys synne he shulde &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">he shulde D.</NOTE> faste,</L>
<L N="272">And yn preyers wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, with wil D.</NOTE> to laste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">laste OD, last H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ys ych&euml; munke<NOTE PLACE="foot">munk O, ilke mong D.</NOTE> &thorn;at was so madde,</L>
<L>Dyde ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn; O.</NOTE> as &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O.</NOTE> ermyte badde.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey preyden<NOTE PLACE="foot">prey&yogh;eden D, preyd H, preyde O.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e &thorn;at seueny&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="11"></L>
<L N="276">To god, for hys mochel<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wulde haue of hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">on hym haue D.</NOTE> mercy;</L>
<L>&THORN;us preyd &thorn;ey bo&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyed &thorn;ey bo&thorn;en D.</NOTE> specyaly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e fyrste<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyrste O, fyrst H, ferste sueny&yogh;ttis ende D.</NOTE> seueny&yogh;t ende,</L>
<L N="280">&thorn;e ermyte seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hermyte seyde D.</NOTE> "bro&thorn;er hende,</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou any<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou ony good D.</NOTE> grac&euml; see</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;y preyers as &thorn;ou hast be<NOTE PLACE="foot">now hast ben D.</NOTE>?"</L>
<L>"&yogh;e,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o D.</NOTE> he seyde, "y sagh a syght</L>
<L N="284">Yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;e' <I>om</I>. OD.</NOTE> lykenes of a dowu&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">dowuys O.</NOTE> flyght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a dowe qwhy&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aboue me<NOTE PLACE="foot">Aboue me O, Aboue D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e firmament,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at dowue &thorn;at fro me went."</L>
<L>&thorn;e ermyte &thorn;oght &thorn;an astyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;owht as ty&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at hyt was &thorn;e same spyryte</L>
<L>&thorn;at went from<NOTE PLACE="foot">wente fro CD.</NOTE> hym when<NOTE PLACE="foot">wan O, qwan D.</NOTE> he began</L>
<L>God forsake<NOTE PLACE="foot">forsake god D.</NOTE> for &thorn;at womman.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To gret penaunce eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">to gret penaunce D, to penaunce eft HO.</NOTE> he hym toke</L>
<L N="292">For hys cristyndom &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">crystendome &thorn;at O, cristendom D.</NOTE> he forsoke;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt a woke<NOTE PLACE="foot">wouke O, &thorn;at wyke D.</NOTE> he badde hym faste</L>
<L>For his flessh &thorn;at hym downe<NOTE PLACE="foot">down O.</NOTE> caste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at no more &thorn;urghe<NOTE PLACE="foot">no man &thorn;orw his D.</NOTE> lecherye</L>
<L N="296">He fordo<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-do not.</NOTE> hys grace so gretly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ermyte preyed<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e . . preyed D, preyde O, preyd H.</NOTE> nyght and day</L>
<L>&thorn;at hys penaunce were take to<NOTE PLACE="foot">were to his D.</NOTE> pay.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde O, qwan &thorn;ei had D.</NOTE> preyd&euml; day &amp; nyght</L>
<L N="300">Alle &thorn;at woke<NOTE PLACE="foot">wouke O, &thorn;at wyke D.</NOTE> yn goddys syght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ermyte seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e . . seyde D.</NOTE> "benedicite;</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er," he seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e . . seyde D.</NOTE> "how &thorn;enke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynke O, &thorn;inki&thorn; H.</NOTE> &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"weyl," he seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e . . seyde D.</NOTE> "&thorn;urgh goddys grace,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;e dowue ha&thorn; be<NOTE PLACE="foot">was here D.</NOTE> byfore my face,</L>
