<L>At &thorn;e woke<NOTE PLACE="foot">wouke O, &thorn;at wyke D.</NOTE> ende, spake &thorn;e ermyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at hermyte D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="316">And asked &thorn;e munke of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> spyryte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e munk&euml; seyde, "y haue hyt seyn,</L>
<L>And on my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn OD.</NOTE> hede syttyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">setyn O, sotyn D.</NOTE> and beyn;</L>
<L N="319">y sagh hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">I say it to me D.</NOTE> so mylde and spake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn OD.</NOTE> hande y myght hyt take;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;oght hyt was &thorn;at fro me steye,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn yn-to my mou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">mou&thorn; O, in-to my mou&thorn; wol euene D.</NOTE> hyt fleye."</L>
<L>&thorn;e ermyte &thorn;anked god almyght<NOTE PLACE="foot">of my&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="324">&THORN;at &yogh;afe hym grace to see &thorn;at sy&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">syght O, sen &thorn;at sy&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Now art &thorn;ou clene," he seyde, "of<NOTE PLACE="foot">clene of al &thorn;i D.</NOTE> synne,</L>
