<L>&THORN;at yn &thorn;is worlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys wrlde O, &thorn;is word D, yn worlde H.</NOTE> come aftyr &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;ey shulde &thorn;e wurlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrlde O, world D.</NOTE> gouerne;'</L>
<L N="452">yn &thorn;y &thorn;oght &thorn;ou gunne<NOTE PLACE="foot">gan D.</NOTE> hyt &yogh;erne;</L>
<L>And god shewyd hyt yn &thorn;y sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;at dremed &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ilke drem D.</NOTE> &thorn;e tou&thorn;er ny&yogh;t."</L>
<L>He tolde &thorn;e profyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">prophete OD.</NOTE> &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;anne O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> euery deyl;</L>
<L N="456">And &thorn;e profete<NOTE PLACE="foot">prophete OD.</NOTE> redde hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">radde hym D.</NOTE> weyl:</L>
<L>wysly he seyd, and weyl &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;orw D.</NOTE> soght,<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan he hede toke to &thorn;at &thorn;e kynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whanne . . heyd . . kynge O, &thorn;at he &yogh;ern (<I>glost</I> 'leer') D, took of &thorn;e kyngis D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>And god shewyd what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> shuld betyde;</L>
<L>what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> manere folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">maner folke O, m. of folk D.</NOTE> shulde aftyr a-byde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="461">Se&thorn;yn &thorn;er beyn dremys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Si&thorn;&thorn;in dremys arn D.</NOTE> so many ma|nere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">maneyr O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;anne O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> ys doute &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">is it in dou&yogh;tte &amp; in gret D.</NOTE> gret&euml; were<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret weyr O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wyt&euml; where<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete whar O, w. qwher D.</NOTE> of dremys come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euery ny&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyght O.</NOTE> dremyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">dremyth D.</NOTE> &thorn;urgh custome;</L>
<L N="465">&THORN;er beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o &thorn;at arn D.</NOTE> so many dremys yn veyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man wot&euml; no<NOTE PLACE="foot">woot no O, wot non in D.</NOTE> certeyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">certeyne O.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o OD.</NOTE> &thorn;at beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o &thorn;at arn D.</NOTE> with god pryue,</L>
<L>To whom ys graunted<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwom is &yogh;ouyn D.</NOTE>, swych &thorn;yng to see:<NOTE PLACE="foot">se O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="469">Swych men deseyue&thorn; nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noghte O, disceyuyn not D.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuyl,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey haue no grace to knowe hys euyl;</L>
<L>Ellys may no man fynde hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">so may . . . knowyn hym D.</NOTE> stable,</L>
<L N="472">So ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O.</NOTE> dremys<NOTE PLACE="foot">For dremys ben so D.</NOTE> d&eacute;seyuable.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="18"></L>
<L N="473">&yogh;yf &thorn;ou telle hem, &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;owh &thorn;ou . . &yogh;it D.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou erre;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ow trow<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe O.</NOTE> hem, &thorn;at ys wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, and &thorn;ou trowe hem &yogh;it is it &thorn;e D.</NOTE> werre;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou mayst dreme of sum<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t dreme ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE> euyl &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at may turne to better for &thorn;y preyyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="477">"&THORN;ou, leudman, &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue O, lewde man &yogh;eue good D.</NOTE> god&euml; tent,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tente O, good entent D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trow<NOTE PLACE="foot">Trowe O, Trowe not a&yogh;ens D.</NOTE> noght a&yogh;en &thorn;e comaundment."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe D.</NOTE> yn wycch&euml;craft</L>
<L>To chaung&euml; &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> be &thorn;e deuylys craft,<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuyls crafte O, with deuelys aw&yogh;t D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="481">Swych beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">swech arn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuyl betaght,</L>
<L>with holy chyrche &thorn;ey ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">with &thorn;e holy gost &thorn;ei arn D.</NOTE> vnsaght,</L>
<L>And all&euml; &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle &thorn;o D, also <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at on hem trowe</L>
<L>Mow<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mowe O.</NOTE> drede hem self to brenne yn lowe<NOTE PLACE="inter">fyre</NOTE>;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mon dredyn hem to be in helle lowhe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh &thorn;ey fynde hyt so&thorn;e o&thorn;er whyle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei fynde suyche sumqwhile D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="486">Hyt ys &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;at is &thorn;orw D.</NOTE> &thorn;e fend&euml;s gyle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend fondy&thorn; with alle hys my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="488">To put<NOTE PLACE="foot">putte O.</NOTE> sumwat<NOTE PLACE="foot">sumqwat D.</NOTE> yn her&euml; syght</L>
<L>&THORN;at shal make hem swych &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at &thorn;ei schulde trowe &amp; leve D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And god almy&yogh;ty myspay and<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; so al my&yogh;tty god to D.</NOTE> greue.</L>
<L>For &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D.</NOTE> was neuer womman ne man</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;at any wycch&euml;craft be-gan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O.</NOTE> bryng hyt to an ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a nende O, neuere m. truly brynge to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ende D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But fals beleue &thorn;at wyl hem shende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-leue hem hadde blende D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e wurdys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O.</NOTE> certys beyn ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hem be D.</NOTE> noght,<MILESTONE N="4a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="496">But fals beleue make&thorn; dede y-wroght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wroghte O. be fals b. &thorn;e dede is wrou&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ou trowyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowst O, qwan &thorn;ou trowist D.</NOTE> yn a fals &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuyl hyt shewy&thorn; for &thorn;at trowyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>lo here a tale of a wycche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leued no better<NOTE PLACE="foot">more D.</NOTE> &thorn;a[n] a bycche.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="19"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Witch and her Cow-sucking Bag;<NOTE PLACE="foot">See a later version in Laud 416 (A.D. 1459), leaf 1: extracts printed in <I>Reliq. Antiq.</I>, ii. 27.</NOTE> and how a Bishop faild to work her Charm, because he didn't be|lieve in it.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ere was a wycche, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">It was D, and <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> made a bagge,</L>
<L>A bely of le&thorn;yr, a gret&euml; swagge,</L>
<L>She sygaldryd so &thorn;ys bagge bely<NOTE PLACE="foot">bagbely O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="504">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> hyt &yogh;ede and soke mennys ky,</L>
<L>At euene, &amp; at morw<NOTE PLACE="foot">on morue O, at morwe D.</NOTE> tyde,</L>
<L>yn here pasture, o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or OD; D <I>om</I>. ellys.</NOTE> ellys be syde.</L>
<L>long<NOTE PLACE="foot">Longge O.</NOTE> hyt &yogh;ede about&euml; fast,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alaboute faste O, oueral faste D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="508">Tyl hyt was parceyued<NOTE PLACE="foot">parseyuyd O.</NOTE> at the last;<NOTE PLACE="foot">laste OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an al<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;anne alle O, alle D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;anne).</NOTE> &thorn;e godemen of &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e bysshop dyden<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-forn . . . dede D.</NOTE> here somoune;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey dyden &thorn;e bagg&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bagge O, &thorn;ei do &thorn;e bagge D, bag H.</NOTE> with here bere,</L>
<L N="512">To wet&euml; what she shuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat she schal D.</NOTE> answere.</L>
<L>hyt was shewyd byfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">to D.</NOTE> &thorn;e bysshop,</L>
<L>&THORN;at she dyde to goo<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede go O.</NOTE> swych a melk<NOTE PLACE="foot">melke O.</NOTE> slop,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede it gon with a meche sop. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;urgh wycchecraft &amp; mys&aacute;uenture,</L>
<L N="516">To sugke here keyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">soukyn her ken D.</NOTE> yn here pasture.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop merueyled, &amp; o&thorn;er mo,</L>
<L>how &thorn;at she my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O.</NOTE> do hyt go.<NOTE PLACE="foot">so go O.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Dame," seyd &thorn;e bysshop, "do &thorn;y quen|tyse,</L>
<L N="520">And late vs se<NOTE PLACE="foot">see O, sen D.</NOTE> how hyt shal ryse."</L>
<L>&THORN;ys wycche here charme began to sey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-gan a-non D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e slop ros vp, and &yogh;ede &thorn;e weye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wey O, &thorn;e bagge vp ros &amp; gan to gon D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop seyd, "&thorn;ys haue we seyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Isen D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="524">Do hyt now to lygge a&yogh;eyn."<NOTE PLACE="foot">stente a&yogh;en D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wycch&euml; dede al at hys wylle:<NOTE PLACE="foot">al his wil D.</NOTE></L>
<L>She made &thorn;e slop a&yogh;en lygge<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; bad &thorn;e bagge stonde D.</NOTE> stylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop made a clerk<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede . . &thorn;er D.</NOTE> &thorn;an wryte</L>
<L N="528">Al &thorn;at she seyd, mochel<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde meche D.</NOTE> and lyte,</L>
<L>And all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al OD.</NOTE> how she made here went;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sche dede &amp; mente D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop &thorn;arto &yogh;af gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;affe gode O, &yogh;af his D.</NOTE> entent.</L>
<L>"&THORN;an," seyde &thorn;e bysshop, "now shal y,</L>
<L N="532">As &thorn;ou hast do, do<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou dedyst don. D.</NOTE> &thorn;y maystry."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop bygan &thorn;e charme to rede,<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And as she dyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde D.</NOTE> he dyde yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede yn O, dede in D.</NOTE> dede;</L>
<L>He seyd and ded&euml; euery deyl,</L>
<L N="536">Ry&yogh;t as she dede, he dede as weyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">al weyl O, al weel D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sloppe<NOTE PLACE="foot">bagge D.</NOTE> lay stylle, as hyt ded wore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">oor D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hym ne ros hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym it sterede D.</NOTE> neuer &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>"why," seyd he, "wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, qwhy . . . wil D.</NOTE> hyt nat ryse,</L>
<L N="540">And y haue do<NOTE PLACE="foot">don D.</NOTE> &thorn;e sam&euml; wyse,</L>
<L>And seyd &thorn;e wurdys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O, wurdis D.</NOTE> lesse ne mo,</L>
<L>And for my seyyng wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, qwhy . . . wil D.</NOTE> hyt nat go?"</L>
<L>"Nay," she seyd, "why<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhy D.</NOTE> shuld hyt so?</L>
<L N="544">&YOGH;e beleue nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O, &thorn;ou trowist not D.</NOTE> as y do:</L>
<L>wlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wolde O, it wil D.</NOTE> &yogh;e beleue my wrdys as<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowyn as do D.</NOTE> y,</L>
<L>Hyt shulde a<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha O.</NOTE> go, and sokun<NOTE PLACE="foot">schulde gon &amp; soukke D.</NOTE> ky."</L>
<L>He seyd, "&thorn;an fayle&thorn; noght<NOTE PLACE="foot">nou&yogh;t O, not D.</NOTE> but beleu|yng;"<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="548">She seyd, "&thorn;at helpe&thorn; al my &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>And so hyt ys for<NOTE PLACE="foot">of OD.</NOTE> our&euml; lawe,</L>
<L>Beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e D.</NOTE> ys mor&euml; &thorn;an &thorn;e sawe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawhe . . . sawhe D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>For, &thorn;ou mayst sey what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wylt,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou beleue hyt, ellys ys alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe it is ellis D.</NOTE> spylt;</L>
<L N="553">Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al.</NOTE> &thorn;at y seyd, y beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe D.</NOTE> hyt weyl,</L>
<L>My beleue ha&thorn; do<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun O.</NOTE> &thorn;e dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowyng dede it D.</NOTE> euery deyl."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop comaundyd &thorn;at she shuld no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="556">Beleue ne wurche as<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe no wycchecraft D.</NOTE> she had wro&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here<NOTE PLACE="foot">Heyr O.</NOTE> mow we wyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete O, may &yogh;e wete D.</NOTE> beleue wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, qwhy . . . wil D.</NOTE> make</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;e wurde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrde O, &thorn;o wurdis D.</NOTE> no my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er wurd ne my&yogh;t ne D.</NOTE> may take.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshop seyd &thorn;e wurdys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O, wurdis D.</NOTE> echoun,</L>
<L N="560">But, beleue &thorn;eryn hadde he noun.</L>
<L>Nomore shall hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">it schal D.</NOTE> auayl&euml; &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at beleuest not &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at trust not in &thorn;at. &thorn;i D.</NOTE> beleue shulde be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou herdyst a fals &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> or lay&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="inter">foule<NOTE PLACE="foot">fowl O.</NOTE></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">spokyn a fals &thorn;ing D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="564">&THORN;at were spoke a&yogh;ens &thorn;e fey&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">were a-&yogh;ens &thorn;e feith brekyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou ne wuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou woldyst not D.</NOTE> &thorn;era&yogh;en seye,</L>
<L>But beleuyst, o&thorn;er for loue, o&thorn;er for eye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">but lete it passe f. l. or ay D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast synned, &amp; a&yogh;en went</L>
<L N="568">&THORN;ys ych&euml; fyrst<NOTE PLACE="foot">In &thorn;e ferste D.</NOTE> comaund&euml;ment.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e law&euml; &thorn;at men hauntes,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou forhelyst, weyl &thorn;ou grauntes.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-hile &thorn;at it grauntys D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou trowest or vndyrstondys<MILESTONE N="4b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at &thorn;re sustren ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O.</NOTE> shapandys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sustrys arn schaphandys D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And comun &thorn;ere &thorn;e chylde ys bore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come . . . born D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And shapyn hyt wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O.</NOTE> or euel before;<NOTE PLACE="foot">schape . . be-forn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="575">For wykked beleue &thorn;at &thorn;ou art<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben D.</NOTE> ynne</L>
<L>&THORN;ey make &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y O, cause &thorn;e D.</NOTE> chylde to falle yn synne;</L>
<L>Swyche beleue &thorn;ou shuldest nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">sueche trou&thorn;es &thorn;ei schulde not D.</NOTE> werche</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e D.</NOTE> of holy cherche.</L>
<L N="579">&THORN;er nys no shapper<SUP>33</SUP> but god almy&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys no shaper . . almyghte O, is no schappere of alle &thorn;inge D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="22"></L>
<L N="580">&THORN;at yn &thorn;e vyrgyne Mary ly&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyghte O, ly&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ys shapper<SUP>33</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">33_33 Left out of D.</NOTE> of al &thorn;yng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at ys, he wote &thorn;e endyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">woot &thorn;e endynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ys bo&thorn;&euml; god and man;</L>
<L N="584">Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al O, alle &thorn;inge was be-gynnynge D.</NOTE> he wote,<NOTE PLACE="foot">woot O.</NOTE> and alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al O, alle &thorn;inge was be-gynnynge D.</NOTE> he can.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er shappers &thorn;at men of telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">D leaves out lines 585-6.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beteche we hem &thorn;e fende of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou trowyst synne shal be for&yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowe &thorn;i . . . for &yogh;euyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="588">without&euml; r&eacute;pentaunce &amp; shryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">repente here &amp; be clene schreuyn D. D leaves out lines 589-596.</NOTE></L>
<L>As sum<NOTE PLACE="foot">some.</NOTE> of &thorn;ys lewed men seys,</L>
<L>'God of heuene ys so curteys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shal on domysday certeynly</L>
<L N="592">For-&yogh;yue &thorn;e synne of lechery;</L>
<L>lechery ys but lyght synne,</L>
<L>he wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle.</NOTE> haue mercy on al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle.</NOTE> &thorn;erynne;'</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey &thorn;ey &thorn;at can no gode,</L>
<L N="596">And &thorn;ou&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghe.</NOTE> &thorn;ey hemself vndyrstode.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e certeyn wylt lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn for&yogh;euenes mote be<NOTE PLACE="foot">must gynne D.</NOTE> here;</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e tou&thorn;er werlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">In o&thorn;er word D.</NOTE> &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrlde &thorn;er.</NOTE> we shul come</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;ere ys but ry&yogh;tfulnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;twysnesse D.</NOTE> of dome;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere ys al ry&yogh;tfulnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">is ry&yogh;twysnesse D.</NOTE> at &thorn;e last ende;</L>
<L>Aske mercy or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar O, or D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou &thorn;edyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">hens D.</NOTE> wende,</L>
<L>Elles gest<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ellys getyst O, ellis getyst D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou no for&yogh;euenes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for&yogh;euenesse OD.</NOTE></L>
<L N="604">Here ne &thorn;er&euml;, more no lesse.</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue vs grace, or we be went,</L>
<L>To kep&euml; &thorn;ys fyrst c&oacute;maundment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e ferste comaundement D.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment"><PB REF="00000031.tif" N="23">
<HEAD>[The Second Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Secundum mandatum. 'Non assumes nomen dei tui in vanum' D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="607">THe tou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">That o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> comandement ys,</L>
<L>'Swere nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noghte O, not D.</NOTE> hys name yn ydulnys.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">ydylnes O, ydilnesse D.</NOTE></L>
<L><MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio">whan &thorn;ou yn ydulnes swerest<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan . . . sweryst be D.</NOTE> hys name,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost hym bere wytnes of blame.</L>
<L>Vndyrstond<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vndyrstonde O, Vnderstonde &thorn;is menyng D.</NOTE> &thorn;ys,&mdash;&thorn;e menyng ys,</L>
<L N="612">Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al O, As D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e, &thorn;e wykednes ys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">as in &thorn;e is wikkydnesse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou sweryst fals, &thorn;y wetande,<NOTE PLACE="foot">suere fals wetende D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for so&thorn;enes ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is D.</NOTE> vnderstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere takyst &thorn;ou god yn &thorn;y sweryng</L>
<L N="616">To bere wytnesse of a fals &thorn;yng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">of fals lesyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y ask&euml; 'whe&thorn;yr ys grettyr eye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qweche is more unhable D.</NOTE></L>
<L>A lesyng, or a fals tale seye.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">a tale culpable D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here mayst &thorn;ou lerne<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t &thorn;ou knowe D.</NOTE> a queyntyse,</L>
<L N="620">To knowe of bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">knowyn of bothin D.</NOTE> &thorn;e ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn;t O, ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE> asyse;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst here and beleue a<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnderstonde &thorn;e trewe &amp; D.</NOTE> fals</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys seyd of a-no&thorn;er als,</L>
<L>And telle hyt for&thorn; &thorn;e sam&euml; wyse,</L>
<L N="624">Ryght as he vn-to &thorn;e seyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he telli&thorn; his a-vyse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ef &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at D.</NOTE> sawe ys ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn;t O, ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghe O, &thorn;owh D.</NOTE> hyt be fals, &thorn;ou hast no ply&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot">plyght O, ply&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="627">For, &thorn;yn ynwyt, &thorn;e shal saue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wenyst to seye<NOTE PLACE="foot">wenyst seye O.</NOTE> weyl, no ply&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">he sey wel &thorn;onk D.</NOTE> to haue,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lesyng ha&thorn; weyl wers<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lesyng ha&thorn; a wers D.</NOTE> wey:</L>
<L>&THORN;e tokyn of a lesyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">tokene of lesynge O, tokyn of lesyng D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;e).</NOTE> y shal &thorn;e sey.</L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D (<I>om</I>. a).</NOTE> ys a lesyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesynge.</NOTE> but &thorn;an ys hyt</L>
<L N="632">whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D (<I>om</I>. a).</NOTE> hyt ys seyd a&yogh;ens ynwyt;</L>
<L>So&thorn;ely<NOTE PLACE="foot">So&thorn;ly O, trewe D.</NOTE> to sey, a lesyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesynge.</NOTE> ys</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at &thorn;ou seyst mys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhan &thorn;. w. &thorn;ou s. a mys D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou make a grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">make gret D.</NOTE> sweryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">swerynge O, sueryng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="636">For to manteyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">susteyne D.</NOTE> &thorn;y lesyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hym &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;anne.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou by sweryst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">swerys O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fals wytnes on hym &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> beryst.<NOTE PLACE="foot">berys O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou by god, or oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">our O, be god &amp; be oure D.</NOTE> lady,</L>
<L N="640">Or ou&thorn;er seyntes &thorn;at &thorn;ou sweryst by,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dost hym ber&euml; fals<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals O, beryn fals D, fas <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> wytnes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;y lesyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesynge O.</NOTE> &thorn;at so&thorn; yt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt O.</NOTE> ys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at so ysse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>How shul<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde OD.</NOTE> &thorn;ey &thorn;an help<NOTE PLACE="foot">helpe O, &thorn;ei helpe D.</NOTE> &thorn;e at &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> nede,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou hem drawyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">draghst O.</NOTE> to &thorn;y falshede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &thorn;ow drawyst hem to f. D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="645">And &thorn;yn inwyt, &thorn;yn own&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">owyn D.</NOTE> skyle,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e sey&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A&yogh;ensey&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;an O, a-geyn sei&thorn; &thorn;e D.</NOTE> and euermore wylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="5a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou trowest<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowst O, trowe D.</NOTE> &thorn;at god was nat byfore</L>
<L N="648">Or<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ar O, not be-forn or D.</NOTE> he was of &thorn;e maydyn bore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">beforn . . . . mayde born D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou trowyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowst O, trowe D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he was noght</L>
<L>Befor&euml; or<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ar O, not be-forn or D.</NOTE> &thorn;e worlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrlde O.</NOTE> was wroght;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is D.</NOTE> verement,</L>
<L N="652">Hyt ys a&yogh;ens &thorn;ys comaundement.</L>
<L>God was euer wy&thorn; outyn bygynnyng</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;e worlde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrlde O.</NOTE> or man, or ou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or &thorn;e word was mad or ony D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou trowyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowst O, trowe D.</NOTE> &thorn;at hys manhede</L>
<L N="656">Ha&thorn; no powere with &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue no p. w. his D.</NOTE> godhede,</L>
<L>Repent&euml; &thorn;e, &thorn;ou art yn synne,</L>
<L>For ydylnes hast &thorn;ou hys name<NOTE PLACE="foot">In ydilnesse hast &thorn;ou name with D.</NOTE> ynne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou trowest<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowst O, trowe D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he may naght<NOTE PLACE="foot">noghte O, not D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn heuene and er&thorn;e hys wyl haue wro&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wroghte O, in er&thorn;e h. w. have wrou&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="661">&THORN;e manhede &thorn;at toke flesshe &amp; bone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with &thorn;e godhede ys al one;&mdash;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou repente &thorn;e byfore &thorn;y fyn,<NOTE PLACE="inter">ende</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">beforn for &thorn;i synne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst be lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t be lorn D.</NOTE> sey&thorn; seynt Austyn.
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Against Swearing Oaths.]</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou were euer so fole<NOTE PLACE="foot">fole <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> hardy</L>
<L>To swer&euml; grete o&thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;is &amp; D.</NOTE> grysly,</L>
<L>As we folys do alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, don al D.</NOTE> day,</L>
<L N="668">Dysmembre Ihesu alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al D.</NOTE> &thorn;at we may.</L>
<L>Gentyl men, for grete gentry,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret gentrye OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>wene &thorn;at grete o&thorn;ys beyn curteysy<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei wene gret o&thorn;is were curteysye D.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, blode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne&thorn;eles bo&thorn;in blod D.</NOTE> fete, &amp; y&yogh;en,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ygne O, yne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey scorne Ihesu, and vpbreyde hys pyn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">pyne O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="673">Of hys woundys he ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wondys he ha&thorn; O, handys he was D.</NOTE> vpbreyd,</L>
<L>Oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">or D.</NOTE> shame hyt ys &thorn;at yt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> ys seyd;</L>
<L>Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he suffred<NOTE PLACE="foot">sufferyd O, suffryd D.</NOTE> for oure frame,</L>
<L>As yn vpbreydyng we sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye O, in vpbreyd we seyn D.</NOTE> hym shame;</L>
<L>Hys flesshe, hys blode, he shedde for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>woundys he<NOTE PLACE="foot">wondys he ha&thorn; O, handys he was D.</NOTE> suffred<NOTE PLACE="foot">sufferyd O, suffryd D.</NOTE> to make &thorn;e fre;</L>
<L>So mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche D.</NOTE> ys oure shame &thorn;e more,</L>
<L N="680">&THORN;at we eft pyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">eft we pynyn D.</NOTE> hym so sore.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o men fallyn more yn ply&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at sweryn o&thorn;er fals<NOTE PLACE="foot">ey&thorn;er soth D.</NOTE> or ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>By any menbre<NOTE PLACE="foot">membre O, be ony member D.</NOTE> of hys manhede</L>
<L N="684">Byne&thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">be ne&thorn;e D.</NOTE> &thorn;e gyrdyl, y &thorn;e forbede;</L>
<L>For y haue herd men swere swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">I herde m. sw. sweche D.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys;</L>
<L>To &thorn;enke on hem, forso&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o &thorn;ingis of hym hy&yogh;ly D.</NOTE> me lo&thorn;ys.<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A lytyl tale y shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">I wil D.</NOTE> &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L N="688">&THORN;at y herde onys a frer&euml; spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Bloody Child.]</HEAD>
<L>Hyt was onys a rych&euml; man<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Narracio D.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at gret&euml; o&thorn;ys swere bygan;
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>For ryche men vse<NOTE PLACE="foot">vse D, <I>om</I>. HO.</NOTE> comunly</L>
<L N="692">Sweryn<NOTE PLACE="foot">to swere [contra iuratores <I>in margin</I>] D.</NOTE> grete o&thorn;ys grysly.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys rych&euml; man wld&euml; nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde not D.</NOTE> lete</L>
<L>But &thorn;at he swore euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">but euere swor D.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys grete.</L>
<L>An euyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">A neuyl HO.</NOTE> toke hym on a day,</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;at he syke yn hys bedd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bed D.</NOTE> lay;</L>
<L>A ny&yogh;t, as he lay a-lone,</L>
<L>A womman he herd&euml; make here<NOTE PLACE="foot">he herde a woman make D.</NOTE> mone;</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche womman come hym byfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at woman cam his bed be-forn D.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="700">with a chylde yn here armys bore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">born D.</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>Of &thorn;e chylde &thorn;at she bare yn here armys</L>
<L>Al to-draw&euml; were &thorn;e &thorn;armys<NOTE PLACE="inter">guttys</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Of handys, of fete, &thorn;e flessh of drawyn,</L>
<L>Mou&thorn;e, y&yogh;en, &amp; nose, were alle to-knawyn,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">10_10 gretly &thorn;at disfyguryd is . brokyn &amp; rent were his armys. of hand &amp; feet &thorn;e flesch of drawe . Mou&thorn;. ey&yogh;e &amp; nose . as al to-gnawe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="705">Bakke &amp; syd&euml;s were<NOTE PLACE="foot">weryn D.</NOTE> al blody:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys womman sorful<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. sorful and, was wunder D.</NOTE> was, and sory.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys man for here wax sore agrysyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sor agresyn O, hir was sore agresyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="708">he spak,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spake to here O, &amp; spak to hir qwan D.</NOTE> whan he was rysyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">resyn OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>"what art &thorn;ou womman, &thorn;at makyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">makst O, qwat . . . makist &thorn;is D.</NOTE> swych cry?</L>
<L>ho ha&thorn; made<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ho made D.</NOTE> &thorn;y chyld so blody?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou," she seyd, "hast hym so<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;us D.</NOTE> shent,</L>
<L N="712">And with &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys al<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;in o&thorn;is hym al D.</NOTE> to-rent.</L>
<L>&THORN;us hast &thorn;ou drawen my dere chylde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">drawyn my child D.</NOTE></L>
<L>with &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys wykked and wylde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou makest me sore to grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">glost <I>wepe</I> in O.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="716">&thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;yn o&thorn;ys wylt nat lete.</L>
<L>hys manhede, &thorn;at he toke for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou pynyst hyt, as &thorn;ou mayst se;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn o&thorn;ys done hym more greuesnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">greuusnesse O, care &amp; dred D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="720">&thorn;an alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, alle D.</NOTE> &thorn;e Iewys wykkednesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wikkydhed D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey pyned hym onys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">onys, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &amp; passed a-way,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>But, &thorn;ou, pynest hym euery day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> pyne, he suffred<NOTE PLACE="foot">sufferyde O, suffred D.</NOTE> for &thorn;y gode,<MILESTONE N="5b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="724">And &thorn;ou vpbreydyst hym of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> rode;</L>
<L>Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O.</NOTE> hys flessh, &thorn;an &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">flesch &thorn;ou al to D.</NOTE> teryst,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou falsly by<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &thorn;ou so grysly be D.</NOTE> hym swerest;</L>
<L>And y<NOTE PLACE="foot">y &thorn;an O.</NOTE> am euer so<NOTE PLACE="foot">I am euere of suych a D.</NOTE> [in] mynde</L>
<L N="728">For to pray<NOTE PLACE="foot">preye O, prey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> for al mankynde.</L>
<L>how shulde y lengyr prey<NOTE PLACE="foot">preye O, pray D.</NOTE> for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So rulyche makyst &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">makst &thorn;ou O, ruly &thorn;ou makist D.</NOTE> hym to be,</L>
<L>And ou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">ou&thorn;ere O, o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> many mo &thorn;an &thorn;ou;</L>
<L N="732">How shulde y &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">he &thorn;anne D.</NOTE> be meke to &yogh;ow?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e caytyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">kaytyffe O, &THORN;at caytyf D.</NOTE> &thorn;at lay yn hys bedde,</L>
<L>For here seyyng wax sore adredde,</L>
<L>And seyd&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And seyde O, &amp; seyde lady D.</NOTE> "&yogh;yf hyt be &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L N="736">Helpe me, lady, &thorn;at y ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">not D.</NOTE> spylle.</L>
<L>For al men seyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyyn O.</NOTE> o &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle men seyn of &thorn;e D.</NOTE> lady,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art modyr of<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e moder of al D.</NOTE> mercy!"</L>
<L>She answeryd to &thorn;e caytyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kaytyffe O, &THORN;at caytyf D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="740">"yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">In grete D.</NOTE> fals o&thorn;ys ys alle &thorn;y lyfe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffe O.</NOTE></L>
<L>what mercy mayst &thorn;ou aske &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat mercy my&yogh;t &thorn;ou aske of D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou &thorn;us my sone hast<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &thorn;ou hast &thorn;us my dere sone D, Whan &thorn;ou my sone hast &thorn;us ydyghte? O.</NOTE> dyght?"</L>
<L>"Lady, alle my<NOTE PLACE="foot">al myn O, alle myn D.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys grete</L>
<L N="744">Fro &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys day O.</NOTE> forward wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, &thorn;is tyme forth euere wil D.</NOTE> y lete;</L>
<L>And preche to euery man &thorn;y lore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey o&thorn;ys swere<NOTE PLACE="foot">suere o&thorn;is D.</NOTE> no more."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt of<NOTE PLACE="foot">so &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt &thorn;in D.</NOTE> o&thorn;ys blynne,</L>
<L N="748">&THORN;an wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, &thorn;is tyme forth euere wil D.</NOTE> y pray<NOTE PLACE="foot">preye O, prey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> for &thorn;y synne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey m&aacute;y be &thorn;e for&yogh;yue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">moun be &thorn;e for&yogh;euyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And do<NOTE PLACE="foot">do &thorn;y O, do D.</NOTE> penaunce whan &thorn;ou art shryue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan . . schreuyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="751"><SUP>33</SUP>For alle men &thorn;at hauntyn grete o&thorn;ys,</L>
<L>To helpe hem at nede, certys me lo&thorn;ys;<SUP>33</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>33_33 For alle &thorn;o &thorn;at grete synnys haunte,</L>
<L>to helpe hem me lo&thorn;e to graunte D.</L>
</LG></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>And my son&euml; wlde noght<NOTE PLACE="foot">wil not redyly D.</NOTE> here</L>
<L>For fals o&thorn;ys, any prayere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">falce o&thorn;is. no prey&yogh;ere D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he comaunde&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to HO, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L N="756">'Swere nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noghte O, suere not D.</NOTE> hys name yn ydulnesse.' "</L>
<L>&THORN;ys womman with here chylde gan wende;</L>
<L>Blessyd be she with-outyn ende!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hem &thorn;at ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, &thorn;ou &thorn;at art D.</NOTE> of o&thorn;ys bolde,</L>
<L N="760">For hem haue y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e I haue D.</NOTE> &thorn;ys tal&euml; tolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys gentyl men, &thorn;ys gettours,<NOTE PLACE="foot">summe gentilmen &amp; &thorn;ese gettourys D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="6a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, &thorn;ou &thorn;at art D.</NOTE> but Goddys turmentours;<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn . . . tourmentourys D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey turment hym alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al D.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ey may,</L>
<L N="764">with fals o&thorn;ys ny&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e nyghte O, falce o&thorn;is bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t D.</NOTE> and day.</L>
<L>But &yogh;e leue &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O, leuyn &yogh;oure (<I>om</I>. fals) D.</NOTE> fals sweryng,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O, leuyn &yogh;oure (<I>om</I>. fals) D.</NOTE> vnkynd&euml; vpbreydyng,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shul go a deueyl weye</L>
<L N="768">But &yogh;e amende &yogh;ou, ar &yogh;e deye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwyl &yogh;e may D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For euery gadlyng nat wur&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wr&thorn; O, a gadelyng &thorn;at is not wur&thorn; D.</NOTE> a pere</L>
<L>Taky&thorn; ensample at &yogh;ow<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;ere D.</NOTE> to swere,</L>
<L>So euery man vn-to ou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;er O, til o&thorn;er D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="772">&THORN;e por&euml; to &thorn;e ryche ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">to ryche is his D.</NOTE> bro&thorn;er&mdash;</L>
<L>yn o&thorn;ys and yn wykkedhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e toon<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at oon D.</NOTE> &thorn;e to&thorn;er to helle shal lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euere swore<NOTE PLACE="foot">swore euer O, suere euere D.</NOTE> by oure lady<NOTE PLACE="foot">leuedy O, lady D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="776">yn any<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony D (<I>om</I>. yn).</NOTE> tyme fals or wykkedly,</L>
<L>Hastly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hastely O, hastily D.</NOTE> &thorn;e [&thorn;erfro] withdrawe;</L>
<L>Vengaunce com&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">comy&thorn; O.</NOTE> for swych myssawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">or venoiounce come for &thorn;at sawe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou sweryst by here &thorn;at he ly&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyghte O, lay D.</NOTE> ynne,</L>
<L N="780">He taky&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">taky&thorn; O, taki&thorn; D, tak&thorn; H.</NOTE> more to wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">more hed to hate &thorn;e D.</NOTE> synne</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou mysdedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dedist D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens hym</L>
<L>with worde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrde O.</NOTE> or dede neuer so grym.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="29"></L>
<L N="783">And as moche, he to hym meke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche he meki&thorn; D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at here wurschyppy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepy&thorn; O (here <I>om</I>. D).</NOTE> or here besechy&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">be seki&thorn; D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;us sey&thorn; seynt Anselme, &thorn;at hyt wrote</L>
<L>To &thorn;ys clerkys &thorn;at weyl hyt wote:<NOTE PLACE="foot">his clerk wel I wot D.</NOTE></L>
<L>More drede ys, by<NOTE PLACE="foot">dere it is be D.</NOTE> here to swere,</L>
<L N="788">&thorn;an ys by<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is be D.</NOTE> hym &thorn;at she dede bere;</L>
<L>Sunner<NOTE PLACE="foot">sonere O, sunnere D.</NOTE> he takyth for here<NOTE PLACE="foot">for hir he taky&thorn; D.</NOTE> veniaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">vengaunce O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an for any o&thorn;er chaunce:<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony o. greuaunce D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at shal y shewe when we be<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &yogh;e arn D.</NOTE> went</L>
<L N="792">Vnto &thorn;e &thorn;ryd<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;redde O, In &thorn;e &thorn;ridde D.</NOTE> comaund&euml;ment.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e tal&euml; ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryghtely O, a-ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE> canst here,</L>
<L>Twey &thorn;yng&euml;s &thorn;eryn mayst &thorn;ou lere:</L>
<L>&THORN;e toon<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at oon D.</NOTE> ys, 'holde weyl &thorn;yn halyday;'</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er, 'oure lady &thorn;ou wurschyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O, &thorn;at o&thorn;er wurschip D.</NOTE> ay.'</L>
<L N="797">Now shul we leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">letyn D.</NOTE> oure o&thorn;ys sweryng,</L>
<L>And speke fyr&thorn;er of ou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">for&thorn; of o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>we shul eft touche<NOTE PLACE="foot">touche eft D.</NOTE> of &thorn;ys synne<MILESTONE N="6a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="800">when we be come<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan we comyn D.</NOTE> fyr&thorn;er withynne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Third Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&para; Memento vt sabbatum sanctifices. tercium mandatum D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The &thorn;ryd<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;redde O, &thorn;ridde D.</NOTE> commaundement yn oure lay</L>
<L>ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hys O.</NOTE> 'hold&euml; weyl &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewe wel &thorn;e D.</NOTE> halyday,'</L>
<L>And come blelyche to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y O, redily to goddes D.</NOTE> seruyse</L>
<L N="804">whan holy chyrche setty&thorn; asyse.</L>
<L>Of al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle O, alle D.</NOTE> &thorn;e festys &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at om. D.</NOTE> yn holy chyrche are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">aren D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holy sunday men oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e holy s. m. owe to sparen, D.</NOTE> to spare;
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>Holy<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> sunday ys byfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-forn D.</NOTE> alle fre,</L>
<L N="808">&THORN;at euer &yogh;yt were, or euer shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shul OD.</NOTE> be.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e pope may, &thorn;urgh hys powere,</L>
<L>Turne &thorn;e halydays yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle &thorn;e halyday&yogh;is of D.</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>How as he wyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">With counseyl . . owyn D.</NOTE> at hys owne wyl,</L>
<L N="812">But &thorn;e sunday shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">muste D.</NOTE> stond&euml; styl.</L>
<L>&THORN;e halydays<NOTE PLACE="foot">halyday&yogh;es D.</NOTE> &thorn;at yn heruyst are,</L>
<L>In &yogh;ol&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">at &yogh;ool D.</NOTE> he may sette hem &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e &yogh;ol&euml; euery feste<NOTE PLACE="foot">fest O, &yogh;ool . . feste D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="816">May he sett&euml; yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn &thorn;e O, he may setten in D.</NOTE> herueste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">heruest O.</NOTE></L>
<L>But, he may, &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne may be D.</NOTE> no resun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunday puttyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. put; putte O, puttyn D.</NOTE> vp no dowun;<NOTE PLACE="foot">down O, ne doun D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e sunday specyaly</L>
<L N="820">ys hyest to halew,<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewe O, hei&yogh;est to haue D.</NOTE> and most wur&thorn;y;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wr&thorn;y O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at day &thorn;ou owyst and shal<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by license for</I> shalt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to her&euml; &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou to here &thorn;in seruyse al D.</NOTE> seruyse al;</L>
<L>Matyns messe here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">matenys &amp; masse D.</NOTE> to rede or syngge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">syngge O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="824">Euery deyl to &thorn;e endyngge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">euerydele . . endyngge O, eche sunday D.</NOTE></L>
<L>weyte &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits &thorn;y; &thorn;i D.</NOTE> tyme, and be nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat OD.</NOTE> &thorn;e last</L>
<L>To come whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> holy watyr ys cast.</L>
<L>Come fyrst to matyns, &yogh;yf &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="828">For hyt ys goddys own&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cristis owyn day D.</NOTE> day.</L>
<L>God made &thorn;e wrld&euml;, este<NOTE PLACE="foot">est O, word est D.</NOTE> &amp; west,</L>
<L>yn syx&euml; days; &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e to reste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he rest OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an restyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">restede O, restyd D.</NOTE> he hym fro al er&thorn;ly werkys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro euere werk D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="832">How dur<NOTE PLACE="foot">dur &thorn;an O, dar &thorn;an ey&thorn;er prist or clerk D.</NOTE> o&thorn;er prestys or clerkys,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou lewed<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony lewd D.</NOTE> man, &thorn;at day werche,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at day ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan it is D.</NOTE> halewed yn holy chyrche?</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruyng man, &thorn;at seruy&thorn; yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">a seruaunt seruynge be D.</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="836">Owe&thorn; to come when<NOTE PLACE="foot">Howith . . qwan D.</NOTE> he ha&thorn; leysere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou come noght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat O, not D ('Nota bene' in margin of B).</NOTE> algate y rede<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>Ete noght ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">not til D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou haue holy brede,</L>
<L>For to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> many &thorn;yng&euml;s hyt may auayle,</L>
<L N="840">To soule helpe, or<NOTE PLACE="foot">(To <I>om</I>.), soulehelpe for D.</NOTE> lyu&euml;s trauayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;y body, &yogh;yf it &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D, &thorn;an HO.</NOTE> smartly endes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">endys O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt ys for housyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">housul O, hosil D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens &thorn;e fendes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fendys O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And holy watyr take of &thorn;e prestys<NOTE PLACE="foot">of pristis D.</NOTE> hand,<NOTE PLACE="foot">honde O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="844">For anoylyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">a noyntyng D.</NOTE> hyt wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> &thorn;e stande.<NOTE PLACE="foot">stonde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum tyme hyt was wnt to be dowun<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun O, wont be don D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To halewe &thorn;e satyrday at &thorn;e noun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">at non D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nam&euml;lyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">a namely D.</NOTE> yn Ing[e]londe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ynglande O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="848">And nawer<NOTE PLACE="foot">nawher O, nowhere D.</NOTE> so moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> y vndyrstand.</L>
<L>when &thorn;at custome<NOTE PLACE="foot">custum O, qwan . . custum D.</NOTE> was wnt to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was grace, &amp; grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret O, &thorn;er grace &amp; al D.</NOTE> plente;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere men haunted<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er men hauntyn O, &thorn;er men hau D.</NOTE> &thorn;at custome<NOTE PLACE="foot">custum OD.</NOTE> lest,</L>
<L N="852">Falle&thorn; oft tym&euml; grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte . . . gret O, often many D.</NOTE> tempest.</L>
<L>&THORN;e satyrday ys specyaly<NOTE PLACE="foot">specyally . is D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ordeyned to wurschype<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O, honoure D.</NOTE> oure lady,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ladye O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at for<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys for O, is for D.</NOTE> a grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret O.</NOTE> resun;&mdash;</L>
<L N="856">whan Ihesu deyd &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan i. dey&yogh;ede &thorn;orwh D.</NOTE> passyun,</L>
<L>hys dyscyplys douted<NOTE PLACE="foot">dou&yogh;ttedyn D.</NOTE> echoun<NOTE PLACE="foot">echone O.</NOTE></L>
<L>whe&thorn;er he shulde ryse or noun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">none O, qwe&thorn;er . . non D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at beleued yn hym byfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at trowedyn . . . beforn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="860">Alle here beleu&euml; was nygh forlore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e was forlorn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e fryday &thorn;at he deyde,</L>
<L>To tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">dey&yogh;ed . til D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he ros, as he seyde.</L>
<L>But hys modyr, vyrgyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">blessid D.</NOTE> Marie,</L>
<L N="864">She bare &thorn;e beleue vp<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e tru&thorn;e D.</NOTE> stedfastly</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e fryday at &thorn;e noun</L>
<L>Tyl alle &thorn;e satyrday was doun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">non (<I>om</I>. alle) . . al don D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="867">And alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O.</NOTE> &thorn;e ny&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyght O.</NOTE> tyl &thorn;at he ros,</L>
<L>Of alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O.</NOTE> oure beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e D.</NOTE> she bare &thorn;e los;&mdash;
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>&THORN;at, crystyn men beleuyn now<NOTE PLACE="foot">leuyn D.</NOTE> echon,</L>
<L>In here &thorn;at tyme was hyt alone;<NOTE PLACE="foot">was a lon D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for &thorn;at skylle, &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;en O.</NOTE> &thorn;ynke&thorn; me,</L>
<L N="872">&THORN;e satyrday may here oun&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">owyn D.</NOTE> be:</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore &thorn;at day al holy cherche</L>
<L>&THORN;eyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">Her O.</NOTE> seruyse of here<NOTE PLACE="foot">her seruyse for her D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey werche.</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&thorn;t.</NOTE> now for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O.</NOTE> sam&euml; skylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ilke skil D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="6b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="876">A tale &thorn;erfor&euml; telle y wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Tale of the Vine-Storms and the Saturday half Holy-Day.</HEAD>
<L>In Nauerne, be-&yogh;unde &thorn;e see,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale<NOTE PLACE="foot">narracio D.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>In Venyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. a later hand has inserted <I>in</I> before <I>a</I>.</NOTE> a gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete D.</NOTE> cyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cytee O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dwellyd a prest of Yng[e]lond,</L>
<L N="880">And was a-uaunsed, y vndyrstond.</L>
<L>Euery &yogh;ere at &thorn;e florysyngge,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e vynys shuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan her vynnys gunne to D.</NOTE> spryngge,</L>
<L>A tempest &thorn;at tyme began<NOTE PLACE="foot">gan D.</NOTE> to falle,</L>
<L N="884">And fordede here vynys alle;</L>
<L>Euery &yogh;ere withoutyn fayle,</L>
<L>And fordyde here grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-dede al her D.</NOTE> trauayle.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor &thorn;e folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">folke O.</NOTE> were alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, weryn alle D.</NOTE> sory</L>
<L N="888">&THORN;urgh &thorn;e cyte comunly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle comounly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest seyd, "y shal &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> shal best &thorn;ys tempest felle:</L>
<L N="891">On Satyrday shul &yogh;e ryngge noun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e s. s. &yogh;e rynge non D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And late no lenger no werke be doun:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lengere werk be don D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But halewe[n]<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewyn D.</NOTE> alle comunly</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e wurschype<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O.</NOTE> of oure lady;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;at manere<NOTE PLACE="foot">maner O.</NOTE> halewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">be &thorn;at maner halewyd D.</NOTE> we
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="33"></L>
<L N="896">&THORN;urgh Inglond yn oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, In ynglond my D.</NOTE> cuntre;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euy&thorn; O, &yogh;eue &yogh;e D.</NOTE> better &yogh;oure offryngys<NOTE PLACE="foot">offryng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ty&thorn;eth weyl alle &yogh;our&euml; &thorn;ynges.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ty&thorn;e &yogh;e bettere &yogh;oure newyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="899">And<NOTE PLACE="foot">O and D omit And.</NOTE> &yogh;yf &yogh;e do &thorn;us goddys heste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hest O, be-hest D.</NOTE></L>
<L>He saue&thorn; &yogh;oure vynys fro &thorn;e tempest."<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro tempest D.</NOTE></L>
<L>At hys cunsel, on &thorn;ys manere</L>
<L>Halewede &thorn;ey, al &thorn;at yche<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewedyn D, <I>om</I>. yche.</NOTE> &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>And whan hyt come to<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e O, qwan it cam &thorn;e somerys D.</NOTE> somer tyde,</L>
<L N="904">Tyme of &thorn;e tempest to vnryde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">suyche tyme as tempest gan vp hyde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here vynys florshed&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">floreschedyn D.</NOTE> feyre &amp; weyl</L>
<L>withoutyn tempest euery<NOTE PLACE="foot">with out tach a D.</NOTE> deyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;an commaunded &thorn;ey, and made<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ei comaundyd &thorn;an &amp; madyn D.</NOTE> a cry</L>
<L N="908">Yn the wurschyp,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O.</NOTE> of oure lady,</L>
<L>'On satyrday shulde men noun ryngge,</L>
<L>And sy&thorn;yn halew of all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, halewyn of alle D.</NOTE> &thorn;yngge,</L>
<L>And here ty&thorn;ys to &yogh;eu&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ty&thorn;is &yogh;euyn D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryght O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="912">Moch&euml; bettyr at here myght.'</L>
<L>And so, grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e gret O, &thorn;e grete D.</NOTE> tempest secede al,<MILESTONE N="7a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;eyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">here O, here vynys w. wont D.</NOTE> frutys was wnt to fal.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;yn, oueral yn &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="916">&THORN;ere &thorn;ey made nat &thorn;ys solemnyte,</L>
<L>were<NOTE PLACE="foot">weryn D.</NOTE> here vynys al destroyed,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">folke O.</NOTE> mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; all &thorn;e folk meche D.</NOTE> a-noyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fel hyt on<NOTE PLACE="foot">it fel so D.</NOTE> a satyrday</L>
<L N="920">A man hyr&eacute;d folke t&oacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">herede folk to &thorn;e D.</NOTE> ful pay;</L>
<L>&THORN;e half day ne hal&eacute;wd<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewede O.</NOTE> he noght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">haleday he halewid not D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For al<NOTE PLACE="foot">al an O.</NOTE> hole day hyt shulde be wroght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">for on &thorn;e holyday be wrout D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e tym&euml; come<NOTE PLACE="foot">com O.</NOTE> &thorn;at noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">cam . noon D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey rong,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ronge O, runge D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="924">As &thorn;ey hadde<NOTE PLACE="foot">as it was D.</NOTE> ordeyned hem among:<NOTE PLACE="foot">amonge O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>Alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al O.</NOTE> &thorn;e wyrkmen homward<NOTE PLACE="foot">homwarde O, homward &thorn;ei D.</NOTE> &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>But he and hys dede fur&thorn; hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">here D.</NOTE> dede.</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er men seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seidyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey shuld nat werche</L>
<L>Lengyr &thorn;an &thorn;ey rong<NOTE PLACE="foot">ronge O, runge D.</NOTE> none at &thorn;e chyrche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">at cherche D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="929">"Comy&thorn; alle home, &amp; hauy&thorn; doun,</L>
<L>And halewe&thorn; with vs at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is.</NOTE> noun</L>
<L>In &thorn;e wurschype<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O.</NOTE> of oure lady,</L>
<L N="932">As now ys custome<NOTE PLACE="foot">custum OD.</NOTE> comunly."</L>
<L>One of hem swore hys o&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wlde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">schulde not D.</NOTE> for lefe ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">no O.</NOTE> lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Halew<NOTE PLACE="foot">Halewe O.</NOTE> mor&euml; at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">halewyn m. a. &thorn;at D.</NOTE> none<NOTE PLACE="foot">noun O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="936">&THORN;an hyt w&aacute;s wnt to be done;<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun O, for t. be don D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne he ne shulde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he wold not D.</NOTE> for oure lady,</L>
<L>But wyrch&euml; for&thorn;e &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&thorn; &thorn;at O.</NOTE> day holy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">forth al dayly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dowun<NOTE PLACE="foot">Down O, Doun D.</NOTE> he smot&euml; hys mattok,</L>
<L N="940">And fyl hym self ded as a stok.<NOTE PLACE="foot">at &thorn;at strok D.</NOTE></L>
<L>(<SUP>21</SUP>Mattok<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mattoke O.</NOTE> is a pykeys,</L>
<L>Or a pyke, as sum men seys.<SUP>21</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">21_21 not in D.</NOTE>)</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> caytefe lay, and my&yogh;t nat speke;</L>
<L N="944">Fur&thorn;, for ded, men gan hym streke;</L>
<L>Men cryd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">creydyn D.</NOTE> fast 'a prest, a prest.'</L>
<L>But no wrde come out of<NOTE PLACE="foot">wurd cam fro D.</NOTE> hys brest.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey stode, &amp; made grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret O, stodyn &amp; madyn get D.</NOTE> &thorn;rong,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ronge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="948">A gode man stod&euml; hem a-mong,<NOTE PLACE="foot">amonge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde O.</NOTE> "&thorn;ys man ys at &thorn;e ded;</L>
<L>wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> &yogh;e do all&euml; at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wil &yogh;e don alle be D.</NOTE> my rede?</L>
<L>All&euml; men &thorn;at &thorn;ys chaunce sees,<MILESTONE N="7a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="952">Sytty&thorn; dowun vpp-on &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">down opon &yogh;oure O, oure H.</NOTE> knees;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seen . . kneen D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pray we god, &thorn;at alle &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;ynge to god &thorn;at al D.</NOTE> may,</L>
<L>And to oure lady &thorn;at owy&thorn; &thorn;ys day,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="35"></L>
<L N="955">&THORN;at she graunte vs swyche a<NOTE PLACE="foot">graunt vs &thorn;at D.</NOTE> &yogh;yfte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may speke, &amp; take hys shryfte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; take . schrifte D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In swych a forward, &thorn;at he &amp; we</L>
<L>Shul euer more chastyed<NOTE PLACE="foot">chastyde O, chastysyd D.</NOTE> be."</L>
<L>when &thorn;ey to prey on knees<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &thorn;ei on knees doun D.</NOTE> gan falle,</L>
<L N="960">&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> man spake fyrst among<NOTE PLACE="foot">amonge O, among D.</NOTE> hem alle:</L>
<L>"whan y swore, he seyd, so hastly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; seyde qwan I swor stedfastly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at y wlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">I schuld D.</NOTE> nat leue, for oure lady,</L>
<L>Ne halewe &thorn;ys day of my<NOTE PLACE="foot">to halewe . . myn D.</NOTE> note,</L>
<L N="964">An<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; D.</NOTE> hande y sagh come to my &thorn;rote,</L>
<L>And hyld&euml; me &thorn;arby so sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">held me &thorn;erby sore D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at y to &yogh;ow my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O, my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> speke no more.</L>
<L>Oure lady was with me so wro&thorn;e</L>
<L N="968">&THORN;at y swore by here an o&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y wlde nat leue for here to werche</L>
<L>&THORN;oght men rong<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghe men runge O, &thorn;owh men runge non D.</NOTE> noun at &thorn;e cherche;</L>
<L>Ne here helpe hadde be, &thorn;at was<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde here helpe be &thorn;at was O, ne wer hir helpe &thorn;at is D.</NOTE> so nere,</L>
<L N="972">&THORN;e hand me hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at hand me schulde a D.</NOTE> strangled here.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;at stonde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stondyn OD.</NOTE> me bysyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at preyd for me &thorn;at ych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyedyn for me in &thorn;at D.</NOTE> tyde,</L>
<L>Blessed mote &yogh;e all&euml; be</L>
<L N="976">For &yogh;oure preyers ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;oure preyer ha&thorn; O, &yogh;oure preyerys han D, oure . . . H.</NOTE> saued me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ys tale ys alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al OD.</NOTE> &thorn;e entent</L>
<L>To kepe weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">holdyn wel D.</NOTE> &thorn;e commaund&euml;ment,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys, to holde wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, to <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;yn halyday</L>
<L N="980">In all&euml; &thorn;yng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;ynge O, alle &thorn;yng H.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou may.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in clene lyuyng . man wyf &amp; may. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt swere vnwurschyply,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne swere not vn-wur&thorn;ly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>By oure lorde, ne by<NOTE PLACE="foot">by <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> oure lady.</L>
<L>Swyche men halewe nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">sweche men halwyn not D.</NOTE> gostly,</L>
<L N="984">&THORN;at on &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> halyday leuyn no foly.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou make karol or play,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou halewyst nat &thorn;yn halyday.<NOTE PLACE="foot">brekyst &thorn;in holyday D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou come ouergladly &thorn;ar tyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come gladly &thorn;ertille D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="988">And &yogh;yuest &thorn;arto mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue &thorn;erto meche D.</NOTE> &thorn;y wyl,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at hast &thorn;ou mochyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">haddist &thorn;ou meche D.</NOTE> ply&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For synne wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> come &thorn;urgh swych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">swylke O, of &thorn;at D.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer settyst swerde ey&thorn;er ryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">settyst euer swerde or rynge O, &yogh;if &thorn;ou cause peple to gret gaderyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="992">For to gadyr a wrastlyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gadere a wrastlynge O, to make revel or D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i D.</NOTE> halyday &thorn;ou holdest noght</L>
<L>whan swyche bobaunce for &thorn;e ys wro&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan suych ryot . . wrout D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cuntek<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cunteke D.</NOTE> &thorn;ere comy&thorn;, or ou&thorn;er bobaunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot">or o. dystaunce O, &amp; distaunce D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And summan<NOTE PLACE="foot">summe men D.</NOTE> slayn, or lost<NOTE PLACE="foot">and lost O.</NOTE> &thorn;ur&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;urghe O, &amp; lorn be D.</NOTE> chaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &yogh;if D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou euer yn felde, ey&thorn;er in<NOTE PLACE="foot">or in O, or D.</NOTE> toune,</L>
<L>Dedyst floure-gerland or coroune<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sette fflour garlond vp on &thorn;i croun D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mak&euml; wommen to gadyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">wommen gadere O, to do women gadere D.</NOTE> &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="1000">To se<NOTE PLACE="foot">see O, sen weche &thorn; . . ore were D.</NOTE> whych &thorn;at feyrer were;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys a&yogh;ens &thorn;e commaund&euml;ment,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e halyday for &thorn;e ys shent;</L>
<L>Hyt ys a gaderyng for lecherye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of lecchery&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1004">And ful grete pryde, &amp; hert&euml; hye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">herte enuy&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer ianglyst at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou make Iangelyng at ony D.</NOTE> messe</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e cherche with<NOTE PLACE="foot">with <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> more or lesse,</L>
<L>And lettyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">to lette D.</NOTE> men of here preyers,<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyerys OD.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1008">For hem perel so&thorn;ely<NOTE PLACE="foot">al here pereyl forso&thorn;e D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou berys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e halyday &thorn;ou holdest nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">haldyst nat O, &thorn;in holiday . . . not a D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And lettyst to wurschyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshype O, &thorn;at lettyst to wurschep god of my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> god almy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Halyday<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e haliday D.</NOTE> was made for preyere,
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="37"></L>
<L N="1012">To god oure herende<NOTE PLACE="foot">erende O, arende D.</NOTE> for to bere.</L>
<L>Certys we ou&yogh;t &thorn;an with ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">owyn to be ful of D.</NOTE> mynde</L>
<L>To preye god vs of synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; pray god out of synne vs D.</NOTE> vnbynde,</L>
<L>And yn gode lyfe vs wysse &amp; rede,</L>
<L N="1016">And for-&yogh;eue vs al<NOTE PLACE="foot">he for&yogh;eue vs D.</NOTE> oure mysdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hauntyst to make &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">haunte . . &thorn;is D.</NOTE> play</L>
<L>At &thorn;e tauerne on &thorn;e halyday,</L>
<L>To many on comy&thorn; &thorn;arfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">many come &thorn;eder for to do D.</NOTE> euyl</L>
<L N="1020">&THORN;urgh cumberaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;orw encoumbraunce D.</NOTE> of &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L>Holy chyrch&euml; wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> &thorn;e werne</L>
<L>&THORN;e halyday to go<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at day to gon D.</NOTE> to &thorn;e tauerne,</L>
<L N="1023">And namly byfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">be forn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e noun</L>
<L>whan goddys seruyse owy&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwil . . . schulde D.</NOTE> be doun.</L>
<L>Tauerne<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e tauerne D.</NOTE> ys &thorn;e deuylys knyfe</L>
<L>Hyt sle&thorn; &thorn;e, o&thorn;er soule or<NOTE PLACE="foot">sleth bo&thorn;e soule &amp; D.</NOTE> lyfe;</L>
<L>One of &thorn;ys, shal hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ese it schal D.</NOTE> do,<MILESTONE N="7b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1028">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haunte comunly &thorn;arto.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou it vse to gon D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hytshorty&thorn; &thorn;y lyfe, ouer moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche D.</NOTE> drynkynge,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D.</NOTE> sle&thorn; &thorn;y soule with bakbytyngge;</L>
<L>Hyt wasty&thorn; &thorn;y body, and make&thorn; &thorn;e drye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">it drey&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1032">And gadryd lecherye<NOTE PLACE="foot">gadery&thorn; lechours O, gaderith many D.</NOTE> to glotonye;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e comaundment ys brokun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e halyday, byfore of spokun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e holy day is ofte broken; &amp; &thorn;e comaunde|ment al fore-spoken D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do any man o dawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">of dawhe D, <I>O.</I> gloss 'to &thorn;e de&thorn;.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="1036">On &thorn;e halyday for any lawe,</L>
<L>Swych&euml; men greuusly<NOTE PLACE="foot">sueche m. g. &thorn;ei D.</NOTE> werche</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e state of holy chyrche:</L>
<L>For holy preyere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyer O, to be holy in lyuyng D.</NOTE> and for &thorn;e pees,</L>
<L N="1040">&thorn;e halyday god hyt chees.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ordeyned is D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer with iogeloure,
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>with hasadoure, or<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;er O, or (ony roytour) D.</NOTE> with rotoure,</L>
<L>Hauntyst tauerne, or were to any pere<NOTE PLACE="foot">were helpere D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1044">To pley at &thorn;e ches<NOTE PLACE="foot">at ches D.</NOTE> or at &thorn;e tablere,</L>
<L>Specyaly before &thorn;e noun</L>
<L>whan goddys seruyse owy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghte O, qwan . . schulde D.</NOTE> to be doun,</L>
<L>Hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">It were D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens &thorn;e comaundment</L>
<L N="1048">And holy cherches<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at al holy cherche D.</NOTE> asent.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if he were D, 'ordred' inserted in a later hand.</NOTE> 'infra sacros,'</L>
<L>And art a clerk, &amp; hast &thorn;e los<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; he were clerk &amp; hadde &thorn;e loos D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of subdekene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sodeke (<I>om</I>. of) D.</NOTE> or dekene by name,</L>
<L N="1052">So moche art &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche he were D.</NOTE> &thorn;e more to blame.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys lerned<NOTE PLACE="foot">lerenyde O, &thorn;ese lerede D.</NOTE> men &yogh;yuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyn OD.</NOTE> ensample so</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e lewd<NOTE PLACE="foot">lewede O, lewde (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> men &thorn;e more mysdo.</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue us grace &thorn;e halyday<NOTE PLACE="foot">oure holiday D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1056">To kep&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at it be D.</NOTE>, Ihesu cryst to pay.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Fourth Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quartum mandatum &para; Honora patrem &amp; ma|trem, vt sis longeuus D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The four&thorn;e comaundment ys, "oure</L>
<L>Fadyr &amp; modyr we shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou schalt D.</NOTE> honoure."</L>
<L>Certys &thorn;e chylde trespasy&thorn; ful yl<NOTE PLACE="foot">do&thorn; ful ille D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1060">&THORN;at wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> nat do &thorn;e fadrys wyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;e chylde owy&thorn; hys wyl al<NOTE PLACE="foot">to D.</NOTE> do,</L>
<L>But dedly synne be &thorn;ar-vnto;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;erto D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For god forbede&thorn; swych synne algate,</L>
<L N="1064">For loue, or for<NOTE PLACE="foot">O omits 'for.'</NOTE> drede, erly or<NOTE PLACE="foot">Not to do . erly ne D.</NOTE> late.</L>
<L>Ellys yn al &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> &thorn;at we<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;at euere &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> may,<MILESTONE N="8a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fadyr &amp; modyr wurschype<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O.</NOTE> we ay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ay <I>and glossed</I> 'euere' <I>in O</I>, D <I>om</I>. we.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1067">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer, yn euyl wetand<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if ony man in euyl euere wetende D.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>On fadyr or modyr leydest &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">leyd on D.</NOTE> hand,
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>Hyt ys comaunded yn sum lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawhe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at swych men shulde be doun o dawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a man schulde be slawe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1071">Vnne&thorn;ys shuld &thorn;ey mercy<NOTE PLACE="foot">mercy shulde &thorn;ey O, Vnne&thorn;e mercy schulde he D.</NOTE> fynde,</L>
<L>For swyche a chylde ys kalled vnkynde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">on kynde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>No bysshope may &yogh;yue &thorn;erfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er of O, &thorn;e byschop &thorn;erof may not &yogh;eue doom D.</NOTE> dome</L>
<L>But &thorn;e pope of &thorn;e court<NOTE PLACE="foot">curte O, pope of gret Rome D.</NOTE> of Rome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou were euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &yogh;if ony be D.</NOTE> so felun</L>
<L N="1076">To &yogh;yue fadyr or modyr &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">her D.</NOTE> malysun,</L>
<L>Or stonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">stant D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens hem yn answere,</L>
<L>And wldest nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">or wil not D.</NOTE> bow&euml; ne forbere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast synned &thorn;an dedly,</L>
<L N="1080">To end&euml;les penaunce wur&thorn;y,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wr&thorn;y O, &amp; endeles pyne art wur&thorn;i D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But son&euml; &thorn;ou &thorn;er-of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er of &thorn;ou &thorn;e O, &thorn;ou &thorn;erof Harl., &thorn;ou &thorn;er-of &thorn;e clene D.</NOTE> shryue</L>
<L>And be bowyng yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; to hem bowe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> D.</NOTE> al &thorn;y lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;y fadyr or modyr bydde<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if fader or moder D.</NOTE> &thorn;e ou&yogh;t do,</L>
<L N="1084">And &thorn;ou wylt nat ble&thorn;ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">blely O, woldist nat wende D.</NOTE> &thorn;arto</L>
<L>By<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be OD.</NOTE> &thorn;y wyl, but euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> gruchande,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er of wel D.</NOTE> vndyrstande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou do for&thorn;e &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">al&thorn;owh &thorn;ou do it in D.</NOTE> dede,</L>
<L N="1088">&THORN;at synne ys moch&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;it &thorn;. s. mechil is D.</NOTE> to drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou oghtyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">owyst D.</NOTE> to bere penaunce grym,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou greuyst a lytyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">a litil greuedyst D.</NOTE> hym.</L>
<L>with al &thorn;y myght, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">in D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t gode wyl,</L>
<L N="1092">&THORN;y fadrys<NOTE PLACE="foot">fadyrs O.</NOTE> byddyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">faderys entent D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt fulfyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf fadyr or modyr falle<NOTE PLACE="foot">fallyn D.</NOTE> yn elde,</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ney&thorn;er D.</NOTE>, for pouert<NOTE PLACE="foot">pouerte O.</NOTE>, may hem self<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym selfe O, hem be D.</NOTE> welde,</L>
<L>Here chyldryn are hold&euml; &thorn;an, &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn holde be D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1096">To susteyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">susteyne O.</NOTE> hem at alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, after her D.</NOTE> here myght.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey se<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;ei sen D.</NOTE> hem so at mysese</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey may lyu&euml; wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, moun lyuyn wel at here D.</NOTE> at ese,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey help hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem helpe OD.</NOTE> &thorn;ey are<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn D.</NOTE> to blame</L>
<L N="1100">And wr&thorn;y to haue wrld&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrldys O, &amp; were wur&thorn;i worldys D.</NOTE> shame.</L>
<L>&THORN;oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oghe O, &thorn;owh &thorn;ei han to D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey hau&euml; &thorn;e mysdoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt n&aacute;t fynde<NOTE PLACE="foot">fynde none OD (eschesoun D).</NOTE> enchesoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yn help<NOTE PLACE="foot">helpe O, &thorn;i helpe be not fro D.</NOTE> be fro hem went,<MILESTONE N="8a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1104">For hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D (<I>om</I>. For).</NOTE> were a&yogh;ens &thorn;e comaundment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y se men &thorn;at purchasours<NOTE PLACE="foot">I se pourchasourys in labour D.</NOTE> are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at coueyte catel with sorwe &amp; kare</L>
<L>Here chyldryn god&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; for her childryn good D.</NOTE> to wynne,</L>
<L N="1108">And here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;owh her D.</NOTE> soul&euml;s synke for synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And o&thorn;er men also y<NOTE PLACE="foot">many men now I D.</NOTE> see,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;yue here chyldryn bo&thorn;e lond &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyn here childryn good in D.</NOTE> fee</L>
<L>For to fynde hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">to fyndyn hem her D (<I>om</I>. For).</NOTE> sustynaunce</L>
<L N="1112">yn here age<NOTE PLACE="foot">her elde D.</NOTE>, for all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, alle D.</NOTE> chaunce.</L>
<L>&THORN;o men, me &thorn;ynke&thorn;, most<NOTE PLACE="foot">gretly D.</NOTE> mysdo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;yue here god&euml; fro hem so;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euy&thorn; her lond so hem fro D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt were<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yt were hem OD.</NOTE> bettyr holde here land,<NOTE PLACE="foot">better to here lond D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1116">&THORN;an begge hyt at a-nou&thorn;ers hand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">a no&thorn;er hond D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men wexen sone sadde of hem &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">orkyn soone with hem to D.</NOTE> craue</L>
<L>When &thorn;ey weyl wete &thorn;at &thorn;ey naght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at wetyn wel &thorn;ei no good D.</NOTE> haue.</L>
<L>By a tale, y shal &yogh;ou mone,<NOTE PLACE="inter">warne</NOTE></L>
<L N="1120">&THORN;at fyl betwyx &thorn;e fadyr &amp; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-twen &thorn;e good man &amp; his D.</NOTE> sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Fond Father.]</HEAD>
<L>Of a man &thorn;at sum tyme was,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>y shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">I wil D.</NOTE> &yogh;ou telle a lytyl pas.</L>
<L N="1123">Of hys sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">child D.</NOTE> he was gelous,
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>And &yogh;aue hym alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al OD.</NOTE> hys land &amp; hous,</L>
<L>And al hys catel in toune &amp; felde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde kepe hym wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, schulde hym &yogh;euyn D.</NOTE> yn hys elde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys &yogh;ong man wax fast<NOTE PLACE="foot">faste O, wex (<I>om</I>. faste) D.</NOTE>, &amp; was iolyfe,</L>
<L N="1128">hys cunseyl was<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af O.</NOTE> to take a wyfe;</L>
<L>he weddyd one, &amp; broght here home</L>
<L>with alle &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">O omits '&thorn;e.'</NOTE> myr&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;erto come;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al mery he spak to hir &amp; com D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1131">He badde here fyrst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O inserts 'bo&thorn;e;' bad of . . . bo&thorn;e D.</NOTE> loude and stylle,</L>
<L>To serue<NOTE PLACE="foot">servyn (<I>om</I>. weyl) D.</NOTE> hys fadyr weyl at hys wylle.</L>
<L>Sone aftyrwarde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">after &thorn;at D.</NOTE> &thorn;ys &yogh;ong&euml; man,</L>
<L>Hys herte, hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">he his D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght, chaunge began;</L>
<L N="1135">Tendrere he was of wyfe and chylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an to hys fadyr o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> meke or mylde.</L>
<L>Of o day, he<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym OD.</NOTE> &thorn;oght [four or] fyue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">iiij or fyue D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Long<NOTE PLACE="foot">Longe O.</NOTE> hym &thorn;oght hys fadyr a-lyue;</L>
<L>And euery day, bo&thorn;e &thorn;e toon and &thorn;e to&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot">day after o&thorn;er D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1140">Serued hym weyl wers &thorn;an o&thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym wers . &amp; with wil lo&thorn;er D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y trowe &thorn;ys man, whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">I &thorn;ou&yogh;te . . qwan D.</NOTE> he gan mone<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;oght &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> he &yogh;af so meche<NOTE PLACE="foot">moche O, meche D.</NOTE> hys sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys old&euml; man was broght so logh<NOTE PLACE="foot">brout . . . lowhe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1144">&THORN;at he lay ful colde besyde a wogh.<NOTE PLACE="foot">and lay . . be &thorn;e wowe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys old&euml; man, vp-on a day,</L>
<L>Pleyned hym &thorn;at he cold&euml; lay:</L>
<L>"Sone," he seyde, "for goddys loue</L>
<L N="1148">wrye<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyl D. (Wrye, A.S. <I>wr&iacute;han</I>, cover.)</NOTE> me with sum clo&thorn;e aboue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone, &thorn;at was &thorn;e husband</L>
<L>To whom was &yogh;yu&euml; alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, &yogh;owyn al his D.</NOTE> &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>Clepyd hys sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he callid his child D.</NOTE> &amp; bade hym take</L>
<L N="1152">A sak<NOTE PLACE="foot">sake O.</NOTE> of &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">his D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he dede make,</L>
<L>And badde hym turn&euml; hyt tweyfolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">twofolde O, to fold D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>And ley<NOTE PLACE="foot">leye O, leyn D.</NOTE> hyt on hys fadyr for colde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chylde [dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede D, <I>om</I>. HO.</NOTE>] as he bad hym do,</L>
<L N="1156">Toke a sak<NOTE PLACE="foot">sake O.</NOTE> &amp; karf<NOTE PLACE="foot">karfe O.</NOTE> hyt yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">he tok . . . on to D.</NOTE> two.</L>
<L>Hys fadyr spak&euml; to hym &yogh;orne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. glossed 'vaste.' he seyde to &thorn;e child hym be-forn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sey, why hast &thorn;ou &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhy hast &thorn;ou &thorn;us &thorn;is D.</NOTE> sak shorne?"</L>
<L>&thorn;e chylde answered hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym answerde D.</NOTE> yn haste</L>
<L N="1160">A wurd&euml; &thorn;urgh &thorn;e holy gaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hely gast D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ys ded&euml; haue y do for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Gode ensample &yogh;yuyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfst O, &yogh;eue D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>How y shal serue &thorn;e yn &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn O, &thorn;us schal I &thorn;e serue in &thorn;in D.</NOTE> elde,</L>
<L N="1164">whan &thorn;ou, &thorn;y self, mayst nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhan &thorn;ou mayst not &thorn;e be D.</NOTE> welde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys halfe sak<NOTE PLACE="foot">sake O.</NOTE> shal lygge<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;y fadyr aboue,</L>
<L>And kepe &thorn;e tou&thorn;er part<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; I schal kepe &thorn;at o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> to &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn D.</NOTE> behoue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>D adds 2 lines:</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou must han nedis cloth &amp; corn</L>
<L>&amp; I provyde for &thorn;e be-forn.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Vnkyndly &thorn;ou techyst me &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">lernyst me to be D.</NOTE> gode;</L>
<L N="1168">Of unkynde cum&thorn; vnkynd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">onkynde . comy&thorn; onkynde D.</NOTE> blode."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This example were good to knowe.</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e for &thorn;e hy&yogh;e &amp; lowhe D.</L>
</LG></NOTE>&THORN;ys ensample were gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">is good D.</NOTE> to kone,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to &thorn;e fadyr &amp; eke to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for &thorn;e fader &amp; D.</NOTE> &thorn;e sone.</L>
<L>God ys noght payd, here<NOTE PLACE="foot">not plesyd as D.</NOTE> we fynde,</L>
<L N="1172">&THORN;at &thorn;e sone to &thorn;e fadyr ys nat kynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er &thorn;e . . . vnkynde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor spek&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">speky&thorn; O, seyth &thorn;e wyse D.</NOTE> Salamon</L>
<L>To fadrys &amp; to husbandys echon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">euerychon.</NOTE></L>
<L>'&THORN;e whylys &thorn;at &yogh;e may drawe &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O, qwhyl . . . &yogh;our ond D.</NOTE> hand,</L>
<L N="1176">Ne &yogh;yue&thorn; neuer awey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue neuer a-wey al D.</NOTE> &yogh;oure land,</L>
<L>And make &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow O, &yogh;our D.</NOTE> self, sogettys to be<NOTE PLACE="foot">to be soget D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at owyn &yogh;ow seruee.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">serue O, to serue &yogh;ow bet D. D again adds 2 lines: 'do be counseyl &amp; make it sekyr; &thorn;at it be truly sauyd fro bekyr'; but then leaves out two, 1183-4, 'Ne &thorn;y . . a-&yogh;ene.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er wysdom a clerk vs telle&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="8b:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>Senek, &thorn;at moche of wysdom spelly&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil of wysdam telli&thorn; D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1181">'Ne be &thorn;ou neuere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'neuere;' D omits 'Ne.'</NOTE> yn swych errour</L>
<L>To make &thorn;yn eyr &thorn;y secutour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">secatour D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;y sekutoure &thorn;y fysycyene,</L>
<L N="1184">Yn hop&euml; for to leue a-&yogh;ene.'</L>
<L>For &thorn;y &thorn;yng, &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge &thorn;yn O, Of al &thorn;i good . &thorn;in D.</NOTE> eyr sey&thorn; &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at byfore was &thorn;yn, he halt hyt hys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;at was or is . he tellith his D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;yn executure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">exekutour O, executour D.</NOTE> to haue &thorn;y &thorn;yng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O, &thorn;ing D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1188">wlde &thorn;at &thorn;ou madyst &thorn;yn endyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">endynge O, Wolde &thorn;ou . . endyng D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou owyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">owst O.</NOTE> to do no &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O, Do no &thorn;ing lowd ne D.</NOTE> stylle</L>
<L>withoute leue of &thorn;y fadrys wylle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">D adds 2 more lines: &thorn;at is to seyn . tak &thorn;ou no &thorn;ing. with-out &thorn;i faderys byddyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to sey&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyn D.</NOTE> take no wyfe</L>
<L N="1192">For to make betwyxe<NOTE PLACE="foot">betwen D.</NOTE> &yogh;ou stryfe;</L>
<L>Ne no grete &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret &thorn;ynge O, gret &thorn;ing D.</NOTE> beye ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">bey&yogh;e ne D.</NOTE> selle</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou vndyr hys gouernaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">gouernayle O, kepyng D.</NOTE> dwelle.</L>
<L>To relygyun &thorn;ou mayst<NOTE PLACE="foot">In-to religioun mayst &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> go</L>
<L N="1196">without&euml; cunseyl of any<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony D.</NOTE> mo;</L>
<L>And to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e OD.</NOTE> holy land, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou haue hyt hette;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;ou it hete D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Syb, ne vnsyb, may<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne may O.</NOTE> hyt lette.<NOTE PLACE="foot">for sibbe ne frend schalt &thorn;ou not lete D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A clerk &thorn;at folylyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e clerk sei&thorn; . he &thorn;at folyly D.</NOTE> dyspendyth</L>
<L>&thorn;e godys &thorn;at hysfadyr hym&yogh;yue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf&thorn; O.</NOTE> or sendy&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1201">And wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> nat &yogh;yue hym for to lere</L>
<L>Clergye ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">er D.</NOTE> craft, or ou&thorn;er mystere,</L>
<L>wykkedlyche al &thorn;at gode he dyspendy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stely&thorn; O, &thorn;at good &thorn;ou stelyst wikkydly I gesse D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1204">&thorn;at hys fadyr for godenesse spely&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">godenes. &thorn;at &thorn;i fader spendith for &thorn;i good|nesse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hard a-cuncte<NOTE PLACE="foot">acomptis D.</NOTE> shall he be sette</L>
<L>At hys endyng, whan he shal be<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan he is D.</NOTE> fette,</L>
<L N="1207">&THORN;at so hys tyme ha&thorn; al forlore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; for-lorn D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="44"></L>
<L>And a&yogh;ens hys fadyr so hym mysbore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">so mys born D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But<NOTE PLACE="foot">But &yogh;yf O.</NOTE> he &yogh;elde hym, &yogh;yf &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">it &yogh;if D.</NOTE> he may,</L>
<L>Or preye for hym bo&thorn;e nyght and day;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou mayst, &amp; wylt noght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou may &amp; wil not D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1212">&THORN;ou art yn weye to peyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e pyne D.</NOTE> be broght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For a-no&thorn;er also<NOTE PLACE="foot">also <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou mayst be shent:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou destroblyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">desturblyst O, distourble D.</NOTE> here testament</L>
<L N="1215">Yn here lyfe, or aftyr here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> ded,</L>
<L>with powere<NOTE PLACE="foot">power or &yogh;yfte O, power &yogh;ifte D.</NOTE> or &yogh;yft, cunseyl or rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast trespast apertly<NOTE PLACE="foot">trespasyd a gret party D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="9a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys c&oacute;maundment so hy.</L>
<L>Of alle wykked men &thorn;at men<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle men &thorn;at wikkid we D.</NOTE> calle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota bene</NOTE></L>
<L N="1220">&THORN;e fals executours be<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn D.</NOTE> werst of alle;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey ne reche<NOTE PLACE="foot">rekke not D.</NOTE> how &thorn;e soul&euml; fare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vare O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mennys owne eyres<NOTE PLACE="foot">chyldyr O, &amp; her owyn childryn D.</NOTE>, werst with hem are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>y tolde erwhyle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">erwhyl O, qwhyle qwy D.</NOTE> for no socour</L>
<L N="1224">&THORN;ou make<NOTE PLACE="foot">mak &thorn;ou not D.</NOTE> &thorn;yn eyre &thorn;yn executour;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at was langere<NOTE PLACE="foot">longe D.</NOTE> &thorn;y catel,</L>
<L>he halt<NOTE PLACE="foot">now he holdi&thorn; D.</NOTE> hyt hys, euery deyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">euerydel O.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Loue &thorn;ou &thorn;y chyldyr out of wytte;</L>
<L N="1228">Trust to hem, and helples sytte.'</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er ensample nedy&thorn; &thorn;e noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">thore &yogh;e non D.</NOTE> take;</L>
<L>what dost<NOTE PLACE="foot">duste O, qwat dost D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou for &thorn;y fadrys sake,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt shal &thorn;y sone do for &thorn;e, les;</L>
<L N="1232">For euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer O.</NOTE> &thorn;e last&euml;, &thorn;e werst es.<NOTE PLACE="foot">is the werse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>On hem y rede &thorn;yn herte so<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym . . &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> kest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou lou&euml; &thorn;y self<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e selfe O, loue &thorn;i self . &amp; &thorn;i god best D.</NOTE> best;</L>
<L>Loue so &thorn;y chyldyr, loue so<NOTE PLACE="foot">loue &thorn;ou childryn &amp; loue D.</NOTE> &thorn;y wyff,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyffe O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="45"></L>
<L N="1236">&THORN;at &thorn;ou saue &thorn;e, bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou loue bo&thorn;e &thorn;i D.</NOTE> soule &amp; lyff.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loue fadyr &amp; modyr, &thorn;at &thorn;e for&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&thorn; O, forth D.</NOTE> brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on &thorn;at loue whan &thorn;ey may nou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">her loue qwan &thorn;ei moun nat D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt poule &thorn;at sagh<NOTE PLACE="foot">Poule saw D.</NOTE> goddys pryuyte,</L>
<L N="1240">he<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; D.</NOTE> sey&thorn; yn hys autoryte</L>
<L>A feyr&euml; wurd<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyr wrde O, fayr wurd D.</NOTE> vs for to saue,</L>
<L>And specyaly to hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o D.</NOTE> &thorn;at chyldryn<NOTE PLACE="foot">chyldyr O.</NOTE> haue:</L>
<L>He sey&thorn; "be &yogh;e neuer so fole hardy</L>
<L N="1244">To curse<NOTE PLACE="foot">kurse O, waryen D.</NOTE> &yogh;oure chyldryn byttyrly;</L>
<L>Ne greuusly, for lytyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">no D.</NOTE> trespas,</L>
<L>Betech&euml; hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-take hem not D.</NOTE> to satanas."</L>
<L>Moche ys &yogh;our malysun<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil is &yogh;oure maleys for D.</NOTE> to drede;</L>
<L N="1248">Curse&thorn; hem noght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cursith not D.</NOTE> y &yogh;ow forbede.</L>
<L>Oft<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ofte O.</NOTE> haue men bo&thorn;e herde &amp; see<NOTE PLACE="foot">Oftyn man hau herd &amp; sen D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at moche veniaunce &thorn;erfor ha&thorn; bee.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil . . . ben D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For to leue &yogh;oure cursyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our cursynge O, &yogh;oure bannyng D.</NOTE> bolde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1252">Y shal &yogh;ow telle what<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> me was tolde</L>
<L>Of a prest &thorn;at sagh and fonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">saw &amp; fond D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys chaunc&euml; yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-fil in D.</NOTE> &thorn;e holy londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Mother who curst her Child.]</HEAD>
<L N="1255">A womman on a day ful ra&thorn;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;ede to a watyr here<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir D.</NOTE> for to ba&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And to[ke]<NOTE PLACE="foot">bad D.</NOTE> here doghtyr here clo&thorn;ys to kepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">clo&thorn;is kepe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And badd&euml; here<NOTE PLACE="foot">bade here &thorn;at O, chargid hir D.</NOTE> she shuld nat slepe;</L>
<L>"But, as sone as y &thorn;e kalle,</L>
<L N="1260">Be redy with my clo&thorn;ys alle."</L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> she was ba&thorn;ed, she kalled<NOTE PLACE="foot">calde O, callyd D (<I>om</I>. her).</NOTE> here faste,</L>
<L>And bade here brynge here clo&thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">bad bryngyn hir clo&thorn;is to hir D.</NOTE> yn haste.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>Here dou&yogh;tyr was nat alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">not al D.</NOTE> redy,</L>
<L N="1264">Ne com&euml; nat at here fyrst<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; cam not at &thorn;e ferste D.</NOTE> cry.</L>
<L>&THORN;e modyr &thorn;at sat in here ba&thorn;</L>
<L>wax<NOTE PLACE="foot">wex D.</NOTE> ful of ire and of wra&thorn;,</L>
<L>And cle&thorn;yd<NOTE PLACE="foot">clepede OD.</NOTE> eft-sonys aftyr here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">. . hyre O, clepede hir hastyly D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1268">kursyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Kursynge O.</NOTE> with ryghte gret&euml; yre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">waryed hir ful bitterly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyd, "&thorn;e devyl come on<NOTE PLACE="foot">sche seyde &thorn;e deuyl mote come with D.</NOTE> &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For, &thorn;ou art nat redy to me."</L>
<L N="1271">"And y am redy," seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o seyde D.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuyl,</L>
<L>"To take &thorn;at &thorn;ou me betaght<NOTE PLACE="foot">betakyst D.</NOTE> with euyl."</L>
<L>he flegh on her&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fley in-to hir D.</NOTE> &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er.</NOTE> she stode,</L>
<L>And mad&euml; her&euml; wytte<NOTE PLACE="foot">here of here wyt O, hir out of hir wit D.</NOTE> al wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys god&euml; man for a-nou&thorn;er &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">made a gret spekyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1276">Tolde hyt oft<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte.</NOTE> yn hys prechyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at non come ny&yogh;e hire for no &thorn;ing D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at none durste speke with here sy&thorn;yn</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> he wer&euml; clen&euml; shryuyn;</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; D.</NOTE> &yogh;yf he were yn dedely synne,</L>
<L N="1280">&THORN;e fend&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuyl D.</NOTE> &thorn;at was here with-ynne</L>
<L>Made here seye hym so moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede hir seyn hym so mechil D.</NOTE> shame</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men wundred<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at alle wundredyn D.</NOTE> on hys blame.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was preued with<NOTE PLACE="foot">be D.</NOTE> many one</L>
<L N="1284">&THORN;at to &thorn;e holy lond was gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erfore, &yogh;e chyldryn, before al &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O, for alle &thorn;inge D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dredy&thorn; &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O, &yogh;e D.</NOTE> modrys warryng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">waryynge, glossed 'cursynge,' O; moderys waryynge D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, &yogh;e wyuys, &thorn;enke&thorn; on &thorn;ys cas,</L>
<L N="1288">werry&thorn; nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">Waryy&thorn; noghte O, waryyth not for a D.</NOTE> for lytyl trespas.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;at wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, For &yogh;e &thorn;at wil D. D has in margin, 'be war of waryyng.'</NOTE> gladly warye,</L>
<L>hem warry&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">waryy&thorn; O, warye hem D.</NOTE> god &amp; seynt marye.</L>
<L>For ho-so haunte&thorn; hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">haunty&thorn; hyt O, it hawnte D.</NOTE> comunly
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="47"></L>
<L N="1292">Yn ernest<NOTE PLACE="foot">in sclaunder D.</NOTE> or yn rybaudy,</L>
<L>He shall haue warryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">waryynge O, warnyng fro (corr. from 'wary|yng') D.</NOTE> for blysse,<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of<NOTE PLACE="foot">'his' inserted in a later hand.</NOTE> blessyng shal he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he schal D.</NOTE> mysse;<NOTE PLACE="foot">glost 'fayle' in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ho-so curse&thorn; withoutyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ho so warye with-out D.</NOTE> gylt<NOTE PLACE="foot">gylte O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1296">Hyt shal on hys hede be pylt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">pylte O, spylt D. <I>O</I>. gloss 'caste.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Curser[y]s yn alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Kurserys yn al O, for waryerys in al D.</NOTE> here lyue</L>
<L>Shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shul O.</NOTE> neuer haue grace for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei shul neuere han grace to D.</NOTE> &thorn;ryue;</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey vse, so shal hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">so schal &thorn;ei D.</NOTE> falle,</L>
<L>For kursyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">kursynge O, waryyng (<I>om</I>. shal) D.</NOTE> shal come on hem alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wurschepy&thorn; &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O.</NOTE> fadrys, &amp; &yogh;oure fadrys &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>&THORN;an queme &yogh;e God, and doun &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O.</NOTE> prow.<NOTE PLACE="foot">honouri&thorn; &yogh;oure fader &amp; moder euene; &thorn;an plese &yogh;e god &thorn;at sit in heuene. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>God &yogh;yue vs grace to oure endyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">endyngge O, endyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1304">To kepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">kepyn D.</NOTE> vs fro modrys cursyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kursyngge O, waryyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">oure O.</NOTE> fadrys so to queme;</L>
<L>&THORN;at goddys comaundement we may &yogh;eme.<NOTE PLACE="foot">goddis c. &thorn;at we may queme D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Fifth Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quintum mandatum. Non occides D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO &thorn;e fyf&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">fy&thorn;e O, fyfte D.</NOTE> now shul we go,</L>
<L N="1308">&THORN;at ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> '&thorn;ou shalt no man slo.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyf&thorn;&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fy&thorn;e O, fyfte D.</NOTE> shalt &thorn;ou vndyrstonde,</L>
<L>Ys, 'sle no man with &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys <I>om</I>. D. sle no man with wil ne D.</NOTE> honde,</L>
<L>with-outyn iustyce, for felonye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for no &thorn;ing . ne for no foly&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1312">Ne for no manere of robbrye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do any man yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">or &thorn;if &thorn;ou do ony in to D.</NOTE> prysun,</L>
<L>wykkedly, as a fals<NOTE PLACE="foot">as fals D.</NOTE> felun,</L>
<L>Or bynde yn upland or in burgh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">byndyn hym . . . borw D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1316">&THORN;at he haue hys de&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">de&thorn; O.</NOTE> &thorn;er-&thorn;urgh,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>Certeyn &thorn;e shal no &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'kepe.' A-&yogh;ens god schalt &thorn;ou &thorn;e not forbere D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> for hys de&thorn; &thorn;ou shalt<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne shalt O, schalt &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> answere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer yn any tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">in ony stryf D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1320">Reft&euml; any man hys lyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">reftyst ony man of his lyf D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or hyt was reft&euml; &thorn;urgh &thorn;y rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art enchesun of hys dede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be a&yogh;ens hys wylle<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyl O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1324">Or hys asent, &thorn;ou synnest ful ylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">yl O, &thorn;ou schalt fulfille D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;urgh wykked ordynaunce</L>
<L>Fordost pore mannys<NOTE PLACE="foot">mans O, for-dedyst p. mennys D.</NOTE> sustynaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;at aftyrward he may nat lyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue O, my&yogh;t not leue (<I>om</I>. he) D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1328">&thorn;ou art coupable,<NOTE PLACE="foot">culpable D.</NOTE>&mdash;a &yogh;yfte y &yogh;yue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue O.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a por&euml; man<NOTE PLACE="foot">'of' inserted in a later hand O, of D.</NOTE> &thorn;e craue</L>
<L>A melys mete, hys lyfe to<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys lyffe to O, it may hym D.</NOTE> saue,&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou mayst &yogh;yue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue O.</NOTE> hym, &amp; nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t &yogh;euyn hym &amp; not ne D.</NOTE> wylt,<MILESTONE N="9b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1332">Befor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-forn D.</NOTE> god &thorn;ou hast hym spylt.</L>
<L>Seynt Ambros&euml; sey&thorn; hardly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hardyly O, hardily D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt ys slaghtyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is manslau&yogh;tter D.</NOTE> gostly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what shul we sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye O, qwat schul seynt &thorn;ese doctourys D.</NOTE> of &thorn;ys dytours,</L>
<L N="1336">&THORN;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-&yogh;ens &thorn;e D.</NOTE> fals men, &thorn;at beyn sysours,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, for hate, a trewman wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">trwman wyle O, trewe man dy&yogh;tte D.</NOTE> endyte,</L>
<L>And a &thorn;efe for syluer<NOTE PLACE="foot">seluyr O, &amp; for gold a strong &thorn;ef D.</NOTE> quyte?</L>
<L>Be he neuer so strong<NOTE PLACE="foot">stronge O, strong D.</NOTE> a &thorn;efe,</L>
<L N="1340">&YOGH;yf he may &yogh;yue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyn D.</NOTE> he shal be lefe;</L>
<L>A por&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">pore trewe D.</NOTE> man &thorn;at may nat so,</L>
<L>&THORN;e de&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">de&thorn; O.</NOTE> &thorn;ey wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, to &thorn;e deth he dampneth D.</NOTE> dampne hym to.</L>
<L>Also hyt ys of &thorn;ys dormers<NOTE PLACE="foot">al is of fals demerys D.</NOTE> yn tounne,&mdash;</L>
<L N="1344">Fals&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fals H.</NOTE> treytours &amp; feloune,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e false tretourys to-gedere rowne D.</NOTE>&mdash;
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>&thorn;at falslych&euml;, for enuye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at falsly &amp; felounly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>On here neghburs wyl gladly<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle g. O, wil &thorn;ey D.</NOTE> lye,</L>
<L N="1347">And seye<NOTE PLACE="foot">to seyn D<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio">.</NOTE> forso&thorn;e &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wroght</L>
<L>&THORN;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> &thorn;at neuer &yogh;yt was do ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">no O, he neuere dede ne D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey sle hem all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, slen hym al D.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ey may,</L>
<L>whan here gode los &thorn;ey fordo for ay.<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan &thorn;ei &thorn;e wrong don say D.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, slen hym al D.</NOTE> &thorn;e wrlde, no ys more felonye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">felounly D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1352">&THORN;an of &thorn;y neghbur next &thorn;e by.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'They <I>byed</I> on him.' Halliwell's Gloss. '<I>O.</I> Norse <I>bia</I>, to spot or besmirch.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dedyst euere D.</NOTE> &thorn;yn entent</L>
<L>yn fals cuns&eacute;l<NOTE PLACE="foot">cunseyl O.</NOTE> or c&oacute;maundment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man to &thorn;e de&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">de&thorn; O, to dethe D.</NOTE> were dyght</L>
<L N="1356">with wrong dome, or euyl syght;</L>
<L>&THORN;oght hyt semyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">semede &yogh;if al semede it D.</NOTE> with &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue &thorn;e dome, hyt ys grete awe<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawhe . . . awhe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>who-so demy&thorn; felunsly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">deme felounly D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1360">And no&thorn;er wy&thorn; pyte ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">and hath no pyte no no D.</NOTE> mercy;</L>
<L>he [ne] shal no mercy haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle wyl sle, and no man<NOTE PLACE="foot">al wyle . . . O, alle wil slen &amp; non wil D.</NOTE> saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>y shal &yogh;ow telle for swych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych O, of suyche a D.</NOTE> dome</L>
<L N="1364">A tale &thorn;at sum tyme fyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">fil sumtyme D.</NOTE> yn Rome.</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="foot">out of D.</NOTE> holy wryt, &thorn;e englysh<NOTE PLACE="foot">englysshe O, ynglysch D.</NOTE> y toke,</L>
<L>'Dialogus,'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dealogo D.</NOTE> men clepyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">clepe O, clepyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e boke.</L>
<L N="1367">&THORN;ys tale ys wryte &thorn;er-yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er yn ys wrete O, wretyn &thorn;er-in D.</NOTE> redy,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">It D.</NOTE> fyl yn &thorn;e tyme of seynt Gregory.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Narracio' <I>in margin</I> D.</NOTE> The Tale of the Knight who had a Vision of the Judgment.]</HEAD>
<L>yn Rom&euml; fyl a grete moreyne,<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">gret moryne O, gret moreyn D.</NOTE> <NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>A pestelens<NOTE PLACE="foot">pestlensse O, A man-qualm, a veniaunce of peyn D.</NOTE> of men, a veniaunce to pyne,</L>
<L>For some &thorn;at &yogh;ed&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eden D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e strete
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="50"></L>
<L N="1372">Sawe arwys fro heuene shete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sey&yogh;en . . . shetyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And smote<NOTE PLACE="foot">smete O, smet D.</NOTE> men to &thorn;e de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to dethe D.</NOTE> doun ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And one of &thorn;e arwys wounded<NOTE PLACE="foot">wndede O.</NOTE> a kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="1375">&THORN;e kny&yogh;t ful sor&euml; syke gan lye,</L>
<L>And was yn poynt as he shuld deye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">poynt for to dey&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>hys spyryt was take to see a<NOTE PLACE="foot">sen &thorn;at D.</NOTE> cas,</L>
<L>Ryght as goddys wyll&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyl O, wille D.</NOTE> was.</L>
<L>hys frendys &thorn;at stode hym by<NOTE PLACE="foot">stodyn hym be syde D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1380">wende &thorn;at he hadde be dede bodely.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hildyn hym for ded in &thorn;at tyde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But son&euml;, yn a lytyl &thorn;rowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone after it gan falle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e body quaked &thorn;at &thorn;ey alle sowe:<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-wok &thorn;at &thorn;ei sey&yogh;en it alle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;&euml; he tolde where he hadde be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwere he had ben D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1384">And moch&euml; &thorn;yng &thorn;at he hadde see.<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche . . sen D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"y sagh a brygge of moch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">saw a bregge of meche D.</NOTE> wndyr,</L>
<L>A grymly<NOTE PLACE="foot">grysly D.</NOTE> watyr was &thorn;er vndyr,</L>
<L>Blak and depe &amp; ful stynkyngge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">foul styngkende D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1388">Dredeful noyse hyt made rynnyngge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a dredful . . rennende D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dunward yn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn-to D.</NOTE> helle hyt &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>whan y sagh<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan I saw D.</NOTE> hyt, y hadde grete drede.</L>
<L>Be-&yogh;unde &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> brygge was a cuntre,</L>
<L N="1392">&THORN;e feyreste<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyrest O.</NOTE> &thorn;at euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere O.</NOTE> god lete be;</L>
<L>As a medue hyt was grene,</L>
<L>So feyre of syght<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyr of syght O, fayr of sy&yogh;t D.</NOTE> ys noun, y wene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is non sene D.</NOTE></L>
<L>So ful of flourys logh and hygh,</L>
<L N="1396">And saueryd swete<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; saueredyn D.</NOTE> as spycerye.</L>
<L>&THORN;arto so feyre syght of coloure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fayr . . kolour O, &thorn;erto fayr . . colour D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Delytable, &amp; swete of sauoure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sauour O, &amp; delectable &amp; swete sauvur D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y dar weyl seye<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;at euermore</L>
<L N="1400">A man myght leu&euml; &thorn;at were &thorn;ore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyuyn &thorn;at &thorn;er were D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>Dey&euml; certys shuld he neuere,</L>
<L>For lyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffe O, lyf D, <I>om</I>. For, for.</NOTE> and hele ys &thorn;ere for euere.</L>
<L N="1403">y sagh &thorn;ere folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">y saghe &thorn;er folke O.</NOTE> <SUP>3</SUP>[of so feyr syghte,</L>
<L>Here wonynge placys yn joye were dyghte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">her wonyngstede in joy&yogh;e was dy&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>All &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o D.</NOTE> folke]<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 These two lines (from "of so" to "folke") printed from O, are omitted in the Harleian MS.</NOTE> &thorn;at I saghe &thorn;ere</L>
<L>were<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits "were"; as fayre aungelys alle &thorn;ey D.</NOTE> as feyre as aungelys were.</L>
<L>y sagh &thorn;ere housys of ful ryche atyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of ry&yogh;t fayr tyr D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1408">Alle of gletryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al of gleterynge O.</NOTE> golde as fyre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">as bry&yogh;t schynyng as gold wyr D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Blesful<NOTE PLACE="foot">Blysful O.</NOTE> bryghtenes was<NOTE PLACE="foot">bernys were D.</NOTE> &thorn;erynne;<MILESTONE N="10a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e syght was cely, &amp; wel&thorn;e to wynne;</L>
<L>For, some of &thorn;o wynly wones<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e wur&thorn;i wonys D; <I>O</I>. gloss, 'sekyr dwell|yngys.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="1412">were peynted with<NOTE PLACE="foot">al wy&thorn; O, weryn al peynted with D.</NOTE> precyus stones,</L>
<L>Some were caste<NOTE PLACE="foot">dy&yogh;t D.</NOTE> with ryche colours</L>
<L>And feyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">proudly OD.</NOTE> peynted with frute &amp; floures.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere ys noun lyuyng here a<NOTE PLACE="foot">no man &thorn;at is o D.</NOTE> lyue,</L>
<L N="1416">But criste, &thorn;at may<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;te D.</NOTE> hyt alle dyscryue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;&euml; myght y neuer wytte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he neuere wete D.</NOTE></L>
<L>who shuld yn &thorn;o stedys<NOTE PLACE="foot">in &thorn;at place D.</NOTE> sytte.</L>
<L>But yn &thorn;e watyr &thorn;at was<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at water &thorn;at is D.</NOTE> hydus,</L>
<L N="1420">Sstynkyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">styngkende &amp; D.</NOTE> blak, &amp; merueylus,</L>
<L>y say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe O, saw D.</NOTE> moche folk falle &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>Caytyuys charged ful of<NOTE PLACE="foot">false caytyuys chargyd with D.</NOTE> synne.</L>
<L>A myste out of &thorn;e watyr come,</L>
<L N="1424">And to sum housys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hows O, hous D, <I>om</I>. And.</NOTE> hyt gan gone,</L>
<L>And to sum, come<NOTE PLACE="foot">com O, hous it cam not D.</NOTE> hyt noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me merueyled yn my &thorn;oght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bregge &thorn;at ouere &thorn;e watyr lay,</L>
<L N="1428">Hyt was euer of swyche a-say,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er-ouere myght no man passe
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>But he were clene of euery trespas<NOTE PLACE="foot">trespasse O, of his trespas D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne shulde yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">but he schulde in-to D.</NOTE> &thorn;e watyr falle</L>
<L N="1432">To &thorn;e mayster fende<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuel D.</NOTE> of alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o men &thorn;at loue to do ryghtly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e man &thorn;at louede to do ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey shal passe &thorn;ere sau&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">he schulde passe &thorn;er safly a ply&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Into<NOTE PLACE="foot">In-to D, To HO.</NOTE> &thorn;at blesful cuntre,</L>
<L N="1436">&THORN;ere ioy&euml; withoute ende shal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A preste y sagh passe &thorn;ere weyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">saw &thorn;er passede wel D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hadde no lettyng of any deyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a deyl O, hadde lettyng neuere a del. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he hadde leuyd yn hys lyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">In his lyf he had lyued D.</NOTE> clene,</L>
<L N="1440">At hys passyng was hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">it was D.</NOTE> weyl sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A man y kneugh &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">kn. &thorn;ere also H, kneghe &thorn;. a. O, saw &thorn;ere (<I>om</I>. also) D.</NOTE> yn peynys strong.<NOTE PLACE="foot">stronge O, peyne strong D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at felunlyche dyde euer wrong;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wronge O, felounly euere dede wrong D.</NOTE></L>
<L>I knegh<NOTE PLACE="foot">knew D.</NOTE> hym here yn grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret OD.</NOTE> bayly,</L>
<L N="1444">He loued veniaunce with-oute mercy.</L>
<L>'Pers,' y wote<NOTE PLACE="foot">woot O, wot D.</NOTE> weyl, was hys name,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> watyr he suffred shame.</L>
<L>y sagh hym bere<NOTE PLACE="foot">saw &thorn;er D.</NOTE> vpp-on hys krowne<NOTE PLACE="foot">crown Brennynge . . . down O, brennende yryn beryn D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1448">Brynnyng eryn &thorn;at bare hym downe<NOTE PLACE="foot">crown Brennynge . . . down O, brennende yryn beryn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e watyr, blak<NOTE PLACE="foot">so blac D.</NOTE> as kole.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;e paynes y sagh hym &thorn;ole!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'suffre.' &thorn;e peyne I say . . D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Moche y desyred<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil I askyd D.</NOTE> to wete certeyne</L>
<L N="1452">why<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwy D.</NOTE> he suffred al &thorn;at peyne;</L>
<L>And asswy&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">also swy&thorn;e D.</NOTE> hyt was me tolde,</L>
<L>For to do veniaunce he was euere<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer O, ay D (<I>om</I>. For).</NOTE> bolde;</L>
<L>And whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;e).</NOTE> he shuld&euml; deme &thorn;e ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1456">To felunly he dyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">felunnye he dede O, to deme wrong he deed D.</NOTE> hys my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>At hym myght no man hau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha D.</NOTE> grace,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>Myldenesse, ne mercy, for any trespace;<NOTE PLACE="foot">meknesse ne m. to purchase D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for he dede so moch&euml; wogh,</L>
<L N="1460">Suffre&thorn; he now shame ynogh.<NOTE PLACE="foot">suffred he so meche now D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swyche ys goddys ordynaunce,</L>
<L>'For veniaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">for his cruelte D.</NOTE> to take veniaunce.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt of a-no&thorn;er y had a syght,</L>
<L N="1464">'Steuene,' forso&thorn;e, hys nam&euml; hyght;</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche<NOTE PLACE="foot">same D.</NOTE> Steuene was wont<NOTE PLACE="foot">wnt O.</NOTE> to be</L>
<L>wonyng yn Rom&euml;, &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">duellynge in Rome, &thorn;at D.</NOTE> cyte.</L>
<L>As he wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> passe &thorn;e brygge, betydde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bregge &thorn;at tyde D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1468">Hys fete begunne to slyde besyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-gunne for to slyde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, was yn poynt for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to OD, to H.</NOTE> falle</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e watyr bytterer &thorn;an galle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml;s wende weyl hym to<NOTE PLACE="foot">wendyn hym a D.</NOTE> fonge,</L>
<L N="1472"><SUP>12</SUP>But by &thorn;e bregge &thorn;an gan he<SUP>12</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">12_12 be &thorn;e bregge he gan D.</NOTE> honge.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendys here crokys fasted yn hys knees,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fest in his leggis D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al to-drowe &amp; rente hys &thorn;ees;<NOTE PLACE="foot">thes O, to-drowyn . . &thorn;ey&yogh;is D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Feyr men come &thorn;edyr,&mdash;but y not<NOTE PLACE="foot">noot O, not D (<I>om</I>. but).</NOTE> how,&mdash;</L>
<L N="1476">And by hys armys vp hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">be &thorn;e . . . hym vp D.</NOTE> drow;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> nat suffre hym falle al<NOTE PLACE="foot">to falle D.</NOTE> downe<NOTE PLACE="foot">down O.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;at grete confucyoun;</L>
<L>He plesyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyed D.</NOTE> god with sum gode dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore &thorn;ey hylpe hym yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">holpyn hym at D.</NOTE> nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1481">Almysdede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Almasdede O, almesse deede D.</NOTE> men vndyrstonde</L>
<L>By &thorn;e drawyng vp<NOTE PLACE="foot">vp <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> of hys honde.</L>
<L>Y trowe he trespast<NOTE PLACE="foot">trespacyd D.</NOTE> yn lecherye</L>
<L N="1484">&THORN;at &thorn;ey &thorn;e &thorn;e&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">thes O, to-drowyn . . &thorn;ey&yogh;is D.</NOTE> drow<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey&yogh;is drowyn D.</NOTE> hym by.</L>
<L>But forso&thorn;e y can<NOTE PLACE="foot">can y O.</NOTE> nat telle<MILESTONE N="10b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whe&thorn;yr<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwe&thorn;er D.</NOTE> he shulde to heuene or helle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tal&euml; haue y<NOTE PLACE="foot">I haue D.</NOTE> tolde to &yogh;ow,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="54"></L>
<L N="1488">&YOGH;yf hyt my&yogh;t fall&euml; &yogh;ow to<NOTE PLACE="foot">falle to &yogh;oure D.</NOTE> prow,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys domus men, to chastyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deme men wrong &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">demyn wrong be D.</NOTE> fals asyse.</L>
<L>Many beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn D.</NOTE> now, as Pers was,</L>
<L N="1492">Harde domys men as Satanas.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;erfore &thorn;ei stonde in gret caas D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at man &thorn;at deme&thorn; alle to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">al on D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of mercy get he no<NOTE PLACE="foot">non I- D.</NOTE> ply&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he deme&thorn; pytyffully<NOTE PLACE="foot">pytysfully O, &amp; he &thorn;at demyth pytously D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1496">At hys demyng gety&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">demyngge get O, endyng he get D.</NOTE> he mercy;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">And <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &yogh;yf he deme fals iugg&euml;ment,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere falsnes ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;orwh &thorn;at falshed D.</NOTE> he shalle be shent;</L>
<L>He shal be slayn, &thorn;at al wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, alle wil D.</NOTE> slo;</L>
<L N="1500">&THORN;at peyne wyl deme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at to pyne demy&thorn; D.</NOTE> to pyne shal go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou with-drowe any mannys wyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O, he my&yogh;t not to god D.</NOTE> &thorn;e gode fulfyl</L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">as &yogh;if D.</NOTE> he &thorn;oght to haue wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O.</NOTE> doun,</L>
<L N="1504">Or entycedest any<NOTE PLACE="foot">entysyd ony D.</NOTE> fro relygyoun,</L>
<L>Gostly &thorn;ou mayst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dost D.</NOTE> hym slo</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he to ou&thorn;er wykkednes go:&mdash;</L>
<L>As, &yogh;yf a man haue a chylde,</L>
<L N="1508">And to relygyun hys wyl be<NOTE PLACE="foot">is D.</NOTE> mylde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Harl.; &thorn;ou O <I>om</I>.; &yogh;if &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> eggyst hym away</L>
<L>To folue &thorn;e fals wrld&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to folwe &thorn;e wordis D.</NOTE> pay;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he &thorn;arefore be lore<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er&thorn;orw be lorn D.</NOTE> yn synne,</L>
<L N="1512">For hym grete perel &thorn;ou fallyst ynne;</L>
<L>Byfor&euml; god &thorn;ou hast hym slayn,</L>
<L>And for hym &thorn;ou shalt<NOTE PLACE="foot">schalt &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> suffre payn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what sey &yogh;e of &thorn;ys bakbyters<NOTE PLACE="foot">bakbyterys O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1516">&THORN;at wykked wurdes<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O.</NOTE> about&euml; bers<NOTE PLACE="foot">berys O.</NOTE>?</L>
<L>&THORN;ey mak&euml; oft&euml; moch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche D.</NOTE> stryfe,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>And a-peyryn many<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyryn many a D.</NOTE> mannys lyfe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou bryng<NOTE PLACE="foot">bryngge O, he brynge D.</NOTE> a man yn fame,</L>
<L N="1520">&THORN;at he haue euer lastyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at after eueremor it is a D.</NOTE> shame,&mdash;</L>
<L>Byfor&euml; god, &thorn;ou hym slos</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou hym reuyst hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan . . . . of his D.</NOTE> gode los.</L>
<L>Bakbyter, &thorn;urgh ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">a bacbitere &thorn;orw D.</NOTE> resun,<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1524">Of &thorn;re mennys de&thorn; ys enchesun.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost weyl, with-outyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at wete &yogh;e wel with-out D.</NOTE> les,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bakbyter fyrst hym self<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym selfe ferst O.</NOTE> sles;</L>
<L>He slek&thorn; hym &thorn;at trowy&thorn; hys lesyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesyngge O, sleth . . eryth &thorn;e lesyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1528">whan he for&thorn; bery&thorn; hys bakbytyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&thorn; ber&thorn; hys bakbytyngge O, qwan he beri&thorn; forth &thorn;is b. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hym algate<NOTE PLACE="foot">also D.</NOTE> &thorn;at hyt ys on leyde,</L>
<L>He ys slayn; god help &thorn;e vpbreyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">slayn be &thorn;at vpbreyd D.</NOTE></L>
<L>As moch&euml; &thorn;an he ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil is be &thorn;an D.</NOTE> to blame</L>
<L N="1532">&THORN;at &yogh;eue&thorn; a man a vyle ekename;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at causith a sclaundrous name D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hys ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">good D.</NOTE> name be withdrawe,</L>
<L>Gostlych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gostlych O, gostly D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou hast hym slawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er is a D.</NOTE> slaghter gostly</L>
<L N="1536">To vse to spek&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at vsyn to spekyn D.</NOTE> vyleyny.</L>
<L>For many wurdys &thorn;at be&thorn; spoke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn spokyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>were better<NOTE PLACE="foot">betre O, better D.</NOTE> yn brest to be loke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in &thorn;e brest be lokyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, sum owt&yogh;&euml; nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">some owte nat O, so owyn men D.</NOTE> to be</L>
<L N="1540">Of her&euml; wurdys to<NOTE PLACE="foot">ouer O, euere D.</NOTE> fre,&mdash;</L>
<L>By &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O, &thorn;ese D.</NOTE> ordryd men, y mene,</L>
<L>Here wurdys owt&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghte to be feyr &amp; O, owyn euere to be D.</NOTE> to be feyr &amp; clene,</L>
<L>And namlyche to<NOTE PLACE="foot">a namely in D.</NOTE> relygyun</L>
<L N="1544">Men shuld fynde<NOTE PLACE="foot">schuldyn fyndyn D.</NOTE> noun enchesun:</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ey spek&euml; oute of skore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spekyn ony schame D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey be&thorn; to be blamed eft &thorn;arfore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn michel &thorn;e more to blame D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="56"><NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>This Tale is from</I> Gregory's Dialogues, Bk. IV, ch. liii, <I>says Gaston Paris, Hist. Lit. de la France</I>, t. xxviii, p. 195.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Gregori<NOTE PLACE="foot">gregor D.</NOTE> of a nunne tellys<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale<NOTE PLACE="foot">'narracio' in margin D.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L N="1548">&THORN;at &yogh;ede to helle for no &thorn;yng ellys</L>
<L>But for she spake euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte D.</NOTE> vyleyny</L>
<L>Among here felaws al ahy.<NOTE PLACE="foot">felawys al an hy O, felawis euere in hy&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys nunn&euml; was of dedys<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede D.</NOTE> chaste,</L>
<L N="1552">But &thorn;at she spak&euml; wurdys waste<NOTE PLACE="foot">of wast D.</NOTE></L>
<L>She mad&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede D.</NOTE> many of here felawys</L>
<L>&THORN;enke on synn&euml; for her<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;inkyn . . . hir D.</NOTE> sawys.</L>
<L>For many tyme a vyleynys wurde<NOTE PLACE="foot">vylens wrde O, &amp; many to vyleyne wurdis D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1556">Gadry&thorn; foul&euml; &thorn;ou&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oght O, gaderyn foule &thorn;ou&yogh;tis on hordys D.</NOTE> to hurde.</L>
<L>So dede she her felawys alle,</L>
<L>For here wurdys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys O, hir wurdis D.</NOTE> yn synn&euml; falle.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, yn here<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne&thorn;eles in fleschly D.</NOTE> dedys,</L>
<L N="1560">Se was chaste as men er hedys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mene rhedys O, was sche chast . as men redys D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone aftyr &thorn;ys nunn&euml; deyde,<MILESTONE N="11a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As of her&euml; was purueyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A-non &thorn;ei for hir puruey&yogh;d D.</NOTE></L>
<L>She was beryyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">beryde O, &thorn;ei beryed hir D.</NOTE> as fyl to be,</L>
<L N="1564">Be syde an auter<NOTE PLACE="foot">a nautyr O, be sydyn an awter be-forn a gre D.</NOTE> before &thorn;e gre.</L>
<L>Sone aftyr, &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">a D.</NOTE> chaunce gan falle:&mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e cherche &thorn;e wardeynys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wardeyns O, &thorn;o wardeynys D.</NOTE> alle</L>
<L>were waked oute of<NOTE PLACE="foot">out of O, weren I-wakyd of D.</NOTE> here slepe,</L>
<L N="1568">So loude &thorn;ey herde one<NOTE PLACE="foot">herden on D.</NOTE> cry &amp; wepe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey sterte vp all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle O, al Harl., stertyn alle vp D (<I>om</I>. for).</NOTE> for to see</L>
<L>what wundyr &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">wndur &thorn;ynge O, wunder &thorn;ing D.</NOTE> &thorn;at my&yogh;t be.</L>
<L N="1571">&THORN;ey say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saye O, saw D.</NOTE> aboute &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is D.</NOTE> Nunn&euml; stonde,</L>
<L>Fendys, with brynnyng swerdys yn honde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">honde D, hande HO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle O.</NOTE> hem &thorn;oght &thorn;ey wulde here<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle &thorn;ei &thorn;ou&yogh;ttyn hir for to D.</NOTE> slo,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey cloue here mou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">mou&thorn; O.</NOTE> euyn o two;<NOTE PLACE="foot">o two O, &thorn;ei clouyn hir euene doun a two D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>And, &thorn;e to<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir O.</NOTE> syde al to-brent</L>
<L N="1576">Before &thorn;e auter on &thorn;e pament.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wardeynys come eft on<NOTE PLACE="foot">comyn on D.</NOTE> &thorn;e morow</L>
<L>To see where had be<NOTE PLACE="foot">were hadde be O, sen qwere was al D.</NOTE> &thorn;at sorow.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey fonde &thorn;e brenyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">brennynge O, brennyng D.</NOTE> euery deyl</L>
<L N="1580">As &thorn;ey before had seye<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-forn had sen D.</NOTE> hyt weyl;</L>
<L>Half &thorn;e body was brent a-way,</L>
<L>And haluyndele yn her grau&euml; lay.</L>
<L>Seynt Gregorye sey&thorn; &thorn;at hyt was sygne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'a tokene.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="1584">&THORN;at half here lyf&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyf it D.</NOTE> was nat dygne;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'wr&thorn;.'</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ogh here dedys wer&euml; chaste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">al &thorn;owh hir lyf in dede was chast D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here wurdys were al<NOTE PLACE="foot">al <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> vyle &amp; waste.</L>
<L>So was hyt shewyd before here ygne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">as it was s. be-forn here eyne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at haluyndele she<NOTE PLACE="foot">half &thorn;e body D.</NOTE> was &yogh;oue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue O, &yogh;oue D.</NOTE> to pyne.</L>
<L N="1589">Loke how &yogh;euene<NOTE PLACE="foot">euene O, euene dom &yogh;ouyn D.</NOTE> dome &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>Euene lyke<NOTE PLACE="foot">euenelych D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens here trespas.</L>
<L>See how here tungg&euml; made here slayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">slayne O, dede hir slo D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And foul&euml; wurdes broght here to payn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdys . . payne O, wurdys dede hir &thorn;at wo D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1593">By &thorn;ys ensample &thorn;at vs awys<NOTE PLACE="inter">fery&thorn;</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at we here se D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y rede &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> we leue alle oure foule sawys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I rede we letyn alle foule wurdis be D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at we sle nat vs self<NOTE PLACE="foot">vsself O, oure soulys D.</NOTE> gostly,</L>
<L N="1596">Ne noun ou&thorn;er so, ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;er also D.</NOTE> bodyly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be nat with her&euml; brent<NOTE PLACE="foot">not so schent heer D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn hell&euml; fere, no with here shent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne with hir brent in helle feer D.</NOTE></L>
<L>God almyghty shelde vs &thorn;ar fro,<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1600">And late vs neuer no man slo.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment"><PB REF="00000066.tif" N="58">
<HEAD>[The Sixth Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sextum mandatum (in margin) Non mecha|beris &para; Sextum mandatum D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THe syxte comaundy&thorn; vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">sexte comaundement bit D.</NOTE> al so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we shul noun hurdam<NOTE PLACE="foot">hordam O, hordom D.</NOTE> do.</L>
<L>&thorn;ys comaundment<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundement OD, it is D.</NOTE> ys of prys,</L>
<L N="1604">For hyt was stabled<NOTE PLACE="foot">mad D.</NOTE> yn paradys;</L>
<L>God stablede hyt, &thorn;ou shalt beleue,</L>
<L>whan he made of Adam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan he made Adam &amp; D.</NOTE> Eue.</L>
<L>A clene womman here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> he hym betaght,</L>
<L N="1608">Yn clen&euml; lyfe to lyue she aght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue shaghte O, lyue sche au&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al one to be, and of o wyl,</L>
<L>Goddys comaundment<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundement OD, it is D.</NOTE> to fulfyl.</L>
<L>God made womman man to gyue,<NOTE PLACE="inter">kepe</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1612">To be hys help&euml; yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben his helpe whil &thorn;at &thorn;ei D.</NOTE> lyue;</L>
<L><SUP>11</SUP>he mad&euml; here nat, man to greue,</L>
<L>No to be mayster, but felaw leue,<SUP>11</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">11_11 <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>No nat ouer logh, no nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat <I>om</I>. O, nat ouer lowe . ne ouerhy&yogh;e D.</NOTE> ouer hy,</L>
<L N="1616">But euene felaw, to be hym by;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben hym by&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he, mayster, lorde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; lord he must be mayster D.</NOTE> &amp; syre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sere O, syre D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hys wyl she shal meke hyre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">here O, makyn hyre D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament ys for here<NOTE PLACE="foot">s. for &thorn;at ilke D.</NOTE> sake,</L>
<L N="1620">Of two, o fleshe and o<NOTE PLACE="foot">of to fleschis . oo D.</NOTE> wyl, to make.</L>
<L>Grete mede he gety&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">get O, getith you D.</NOTE> with-out&euml; fayle</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil D.</NOTE> hold&euml; hys spousayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now some of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">summe of &thorn;ese D (<I>om</I>. Now).</NOTE> poyntys wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil D.</NOTE> y touche</L>
<L N="1624">&THORN;at men vn-to hurdam<NOTE PLACE="foot">hordam O, to &thorn;o men &thorn;at to holdam D.</NOTE> souche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer &yogh;aue O, &yogh;eue D.</NOTE> trou&thorn;&euml; pryuyly</L>
<L>To bygyle a womman to<NOTE PLACE="foot">and O, &amp; lyn D.</NOTE> lygge here by,
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="59"></L>
<L N="1627">&THORN;ogh no wedlok<NOTE PLACE="foot">wedloke O.</NOTE> were yn &thorn;y &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at wuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou wldyst O, &thorn;. woldyst D.</NOTE> &thorn;y synne were wroght;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf she vndyrstode weddyng of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So shal &thorn;y trou&thorn;&euml; charged be;</L>
<L>&THORN;y trou&thorn;e to &yogh;eue yn swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych O, swych D.</NOTE> a-tent,</L>
<L N="1632">hyt ys a&yogh;ens &thorn;e comaundment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundement OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>No trou&thorn;e oghte to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> omits 'to.' owith to be &yogh;ouyn be D.</NOTE> be &yogh;eue wy&thorn; ryght</L>
<L>But yn holy cherchys sy&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">syght O, cherche sy&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Namlych, &thorn;at falle&thorn; to wedlake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fal&thorn; to wedlak O, namely . . wedlok D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1636">what-so-euer men<NOTE PLACE="foot">men euer O, qwat so men seyn &thorn;inke or D.</NOTE> seyde or spake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">spak OD.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou ly<NOTE PLACE="foot">lye O, lyn D.</NOTE> by here se&thorn;en,<MILESTONE N="11b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Aftyr &thorn;ou hast &thorn;y trou&thorn;&euml; &yogh;yuen,</L>
<L>Y sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye O, sey D.</NOTE> &thorn;e weyl certeynly<NOTE PLACE="foot">for certeynly D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1640">&thorn;at &thorn;ou synnedyst &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnyst &thorn;anne D.</NOTE> dedly.</L>
<L>Fleshly dede &thorn;ou oghteyst noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">owist non D.</NOTE> werche</L>
<L>wy&thorn;-out&euml; leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">wedlok D.</NOTE> of holy cherche;</L>
<L>&thorn;ogh &thorn;ou haue here trou&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">here trow&thorn;e O, al&thorn;owh &thorn;. h. hir tru&thorn;e D.</NOTE> plyght,</L>
<L N="1644">And to here hast so god&euml; ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryghte O, haue so good ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yt holy cherche behoue&thorn; wytte<NOTE PLACE="foot">holi cherche must knowe euerydel D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure cunnaunt, &yogh;yf hyt may sytte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">or &thorn;e comenaunt be endyd wel D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou plyghtyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">ply&yogh;t D.</NOTE> trou&thorn;e to any lyghtly</L>
<L N="1648">To be at holy cherchys cry,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou dedyst with her<NOTE PLACE="foot">with here in margin H, duste wy&thorn; here O, &thorn;ou dost with hir no fleschly dede D.</NOTE> no foly dede</L>
<L>&thorn;at ys fleshly felaurede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">felawrede O, ney&thorn;er be feld ne be thede D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou gost and &yogh;yfst<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyst D.</NOTE> &thorn;y trou&thorn;e anou&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1652">As &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest O, dedyst beforn &thorn;at o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> byfore &thorn;e tou&thorn;er,</L>
<L>And lyst by here, and ys &thorn;y wyfe,</L>
<L>yn hordam bo&thorn;e &thorn;an ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e &yogh;e lede D.</NOTE> &yogh;oure lyfe.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ferst womman &thorn;at &thorn;ou ches</L>
<L N="1656">Ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">sche is D.</NOTE> &thorn;y wyfe, with-out&euml; les.</L>
<L>Ensample hau&euml; we &thorn;erby,</L>
<L>Of Iosep &thorn;at wedyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">weddede O, wedded D.</NOTE> oure lady;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was verry<NOTE PLACE="foot">verry trewe D.</NOTE> matrymony,</L>
<L N="1660">with-out&euml; fleshly dede of any.<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede don ony D.</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;ys ensample mayst<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e fyrst<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferste O, ferst D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at).</NOTE> womman &thorn;y wyfe shulde be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest O, dedyst beforn &thorn;at o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> euer swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych O, ony D.</NOTE> outrage</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">don D.</NOTE> wedde chyldryn or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar O, or D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey hadde age,</L>
<L N="1665">&thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar O.</NOTE>-of may com&euml; grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret OD.</NOTE> folye</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ey so &yogh;unge to-gedyr lye.</L>
<L>Oft haue men<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ofte men haue O, oftyn men han (<I>om</I>. bo&thorn;e) D.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e herde &amp; seyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> of swych lyggyng ha&thorn; foly beyn.</L>
<L N="1669">For some, when &thorn;ey yn age are come,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; summe qwan &thorn;ei comyn to olde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e toon &thorn;e tou&thorn;er may nat loue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at oon to o&thorn;er neuere loue wolde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an make &thorn;ey men<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle men O, &thorn;an fare &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e alle folk to wunder D.</NOTE> on hem to wundyr,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wndre O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1672">And coueyt faste<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei coueyte bo&thorn;e D.</NOTE> to be asundyr;<NOTE PLACE="foot">a sundre O, a sunder D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Also to brek&euml; here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; for brekyn &thorn;e D.</NOTE> spousayle,</L>
<L>And here trou&thorn;e, &thorn;e whych shuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">wheche shulde O, &thorn;at schulde D.</NOTE> nat fayle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou to swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych O, suych D.</NOTE> weddyng consent,<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1676">Hyt ys a&yogh;ens &thorn;e commaundment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundement O.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hast<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue D.</NOTE> auowyd &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;y lyfe to holde<NOTE PLACE="foot">holdyn D.</NOTE> yn chastyte,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou art yn state of prest,</L>
<L N="1680">Or yn two ordrys al&thorn;er nest,</L>
<L>Suddekene, or dekene hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Subdekne . . hy&yogh; D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ys letty&thorn; weddyng &amp; dede fleshly.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer O, neuere D, <I>om</I>. Harl.</NOTE> wedde, ne synne,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; any<NOTE PLACE="foot">non D (<I>om</I>. ha&thorn;).</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;y kyn ha&thorn; weddyd ynne;</L>
<L N="1685">Or &yogh;yf a man haue houe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;ou haue houyn D.</NOTE> a chylde,</L>
<L>God hyt euer forbede and shylde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at chylde shulde any<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ilke . . ony D.</NOTE> haue</L>
<L N="1688">Of hys godfadrys, maydyn or knaue:</L>
<L>Hys bre&thorn;ren or sustren may at here<NOTE PLACE="foot">may o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> pay</L>
<L>wedde; but he &thorn;at houe neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">he hoffe neuer O, he &thorn;at hof neuere ne D.</NOTE> may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt nat,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou schalt neuere D.</NOTE> by &thorn;y lyfe,</L>
<L N="1692">wedd&euml; &thorn;y godfadrys wyfe.</L>
<L>Also shal &thorn;e womman wonde<NOTE PLACE="inter">spare</NOTE></L>
<L>To take<NOTE PLACE="foot">takyn D.</NOTE> here godmodrys husbonde.</L>
<L>Twey godmodrys shul nat wedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See 1. 2237, etc., of the French, next page. wede O, to commatres schal &thorn;ou not wedde D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1696">&THORN;e toon to aske &thorn;e tou&thorn;er to bede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at oon aske &thorn;at o&thorn;er to bedde D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men shul nat wedde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Harl. omits 'wedde.' schuld not wedde for no D.</NOTE> for any gode</L>
<L>Man or womman &thorn;at ys wode;</L>
<L>For many &thorn;yngys hyt ys grete eye,</L>
<L N="1700">&THORN;e whyche falle&thorn; me nat for<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at falli&thorn; me not now D.</NOTE> to seye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a womman haue an husband,</L>
<L>And he fro here go ouer<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; he be gon out of D.</NOTE> land,</L>
<L>She shal noun ou&thorn;er take ne wedde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wed O, sche may take non o&thorn;er for no dred D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1704">But she be certeyn of hys ded.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ded O. <I>O</I>. gloss. 'de&thorn;.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shalt O, schalt tru&thorn;e no w. D.</NOTE> nat betrou&thorn;e a womman with hand</L>
<L>&thorn;e whylys<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhylys D.</NOTE> here husband ys lyuand;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e trou&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou here &yogh;euys</L>
<L N="1708">&THORN;e whylys &thorn;at here husbund lyuys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er qwhylis his husbonde leuyth. &thorn;at ilke tru&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou hir &yogh;euyth D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>hyt ys hope, hurdam<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is opyn hordom D.</NOTE> to be,</L>
<L>And slaghter, but<NOTE PLACE="foot">but &yogh;yf O, &amp; manslauter &yogh;if D.</NOTE> he deye or she.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1711"><SUP>3</SUP>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou madest euer any wyche,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh whycch&euml;craft, wedlak to flycche,<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to destruble<NOTE PLACE="foot">desturble O, distorble D.</NOTE> &thorn;e ry&yogh;t weddyng,<MILESTONE N="12a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a-cursed yn &thorn;at &thorn;yng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">doyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou fordost &thorn;e weylfare<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem &thorn;at welfare.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1716">Betwyx &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-twen hem D.</NOTE> &thorn;at weddyde are,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest certys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er D.</NOTE> wykkydly,</L>
<L>And brekyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">brekst O, &thorn;ou brekist &thorn;er D.</NOTE> spousayle &amp; cumpany.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;y chylde, mayden<NOTE PLACE="foot">mayde D.</NOTE> or knaue,</L>
<L N="1720">wulde a-no&thorn;er yn wedlak<NOTE PLACE="foot">wil in wedlok a no&thorn;er D.</NOTE> haue,</L>
<L>And with here wylle &thorn;ey trou&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tru&thorn;is &thorn;ei (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> ply&yogh;t</L>
<L>withoute cunseyl of fadrys<NOTE PLACE="foot">fadery D.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1723">&YOGH;yf fadyr or modyr be &thorn;er a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ey haue trou&thorn;ed &amp; beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ei be tru&thorn;id &amp; arn D.</NOTE> certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey dysturble &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou stourblyst &thorn;e D.</NOTE> sacrament</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys ych&euml; comaundment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a &yogh;ens goddis comaundement D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a man be<NOTE PLACE="foot">were D.</NOTE> of Ioly lyfe</L>
<L N="1728">And mysdo<NOTE PLACE="foot">mysdede D.</NOTE> onys vndyr hys wyfe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf she be gode and certeyn,</L>
<L>To gode state she turne&thorn; hym a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ere &thorn;e wyfe haunte&thorn; foly<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; foly&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1732">Vndyr here husbunde a ludby,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir lord a loteby&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comunly she wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil not D.</NOTE> neuer blynne,</L>
<L>But euere<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer O, euere be ardent D.</NOTE> be brennyng yn here synne;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e deuyl confounde<NOTE PLACE="foot">confunde O, confoundith D.</NOTE> her here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here her O, hir &thorn;er D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1736">And bryng&euml; her<NOTE PLACE="foot">here . . . fer O, bryngi&thorn; her . . . fer D.</NOTE> to hell&euml; fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens swyche maner wyuys<NOTE PLACE="foot">A namelych suych a m. wyf D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>&thorn;at wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil not D.</NOTE> nat amende here lyuys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">amenden her lyf D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal y<NOTE PLACE="foot">I schal D ('narracio' in margin).</NOTE> tell&euml; &yogh;ow a tale,&mdash;</L>
<L N="1740">To swych&euml; wyuys byttyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">suyche wyuys han bitter D.</NOTE> bale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Adulterous Wife, whose Skeleton split in two.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>Source not found by G. Paris</I>, Hist. Lit. de la France, xxviii. 195.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er ys an Ile be-&yogh;unde &thorn;e see,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er men were wunt<NOTE PLACE="foot">wnt O, wunt duellyng D.</NOTE> wonyng to be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; yl&euml; wax<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilke yle wex D.</NOTE> al waste,</L>
<L N="1744">And &thorn;e folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">folke O.</NOTE> drogh &thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;enne O, &thorn;e folk &thorn;ens drow (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> yn haste;</L>
<L>So with-ynne a lytyl whyle<NOTE PLACE="foot">so &thorn;at . . qwyle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men helde hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hylden it D.</NOTE> a forsakyn yle.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">si&thorn;&thorn;in D ('dragoun' in margin).</NOTE> wonede &thorn;ere a dragun,</L>
