<L>he preyd&euml; god<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. god D.</NOTE> vpp-on a day,</L>
<L N="1920">And seyd&euml; "lorde, as &thorn;ou weyl may,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf O, &yogh;if D.</NOTE> me grac&euml; for to wete</L>
<L>who shal with me yn heuene sytte;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wulde y wyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete D.</NOTE> on al manere,</L>
<L N="1924">who yn heuene shal be my pere."</L>
<L>A voys spak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">spak O.</NOTE> to hym ful fayre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;are D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"wete<NOTE PLACE="foot">wethe D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wele, for so&thorn;e, Makayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere be&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;yr by&thorn; O. It arn to D.</NOTE> twey wymmen yn a cyte,</L>
<L N="1928">Of so moche boneryte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'godenesse,' of ful mechil honoryte D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst do</L>
<L>Ne may nat reche here godenes to."</L>
<L>he told&euml; hym &thorn;e cyte ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryght O, to &thorn;at c. ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1932">And the wommen what &thorn;ey hyght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyght O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Makayr&euml; wulde no lenger byde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-byde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But to &thorn;at cyte gan<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde (<I>om</I>. But) D.</NOTE> he ryde;</L>
<L N="1935">As son&euml; as he com&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">com O, &amp; . . . cam D.</NOTE> &thorn;ere</L>
<L>he askede where swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">aspyed where &thorn;o D.</NOTE> wymmen were.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Men taghte hym son&euml; to hem weyl;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tawtyn hym soone with wil D.</NOTE></L>
<L>he come and toke &thorn;ere hys osteyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'herborue.'</NOTE></L>
<L>"wymmen," he seyde, "y wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> me reste</L>
<L N="1940">yn &yogh;oure Ine<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn O, hous &amp; ben &yogh;oure gest D.</NOTE> as<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. <I>omits</I> 'as.'</NOTE> a ny&yogh;tys geste."</L>
<L>"Syr," &thorn;ey seyde, "we graunte hyt &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="13b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hyt aske pur<NOTE PLACE="foot">for D.</NOTE> charyte."</L>
<L>To a chambre &thorn;ey hym broghte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">broght O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1944">&thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;o D.</NOTE> hys erende for&yogh;ate he noughte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght O.</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>he mad&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. inserts 'hem.'</NOTE> bo&thorn;&euml; by hym sytte,</L>
<L>And seyde, "y am come, at &yogh;ow to wytte<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">10_10 <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete O.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn what manere &yogh;e lede<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat maner lede &yogh;e D.</NOTE> &yogh;oure lyuys</L>
<L N="1948">yn holynes, and by&thorn; here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;e arn D.</NOTE> wyuys:</L>
<L>Forhele&thorn; hyt nat,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for ellis not D.</NOTE> y &yogh;ow forbede,</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;our O.</NOTE> lyuys lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, y am come<NOTE PLACE="foot">I cam D.</NOTE> to &thorn;ys cyte,</L>
<L N="1952">And haue trauayled many a iurne."<NOTE PLACE="foot">many Iourne D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;es wymmen answered al at gesse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss. 'hap'; ansuerden D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Syr, we knowe no<NOTE PLACE="foot">noun O, knowyn non D.</NOTE> holynesse,</L>
<L>But whan oure husbandys by&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben D.</NOTE> vs by</L>
<L N="1956">&THORN;an be&thorn; we yn loue ry&yogh;tly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar . . loue all ry&yogh;tfully D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And yn parfyte charyte</L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhan D.</NOTE> oure husbandys with vs be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys moste of our&euml; lyuys,</L>
<L>And euer ha&thorn; be, sy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">syn O.</NOTE> we were wyuys."</L>
<L N="1961">"y beseche<NOTE PLACE="foot">beseke D.</NOTE> &yogh;ow, on my blessyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e forhele fro me<NOTE PLACE="foot">forhile for D.</NOTE> no &thorn;yng."<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e toon<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at oon D.</NOTE> answered to seynt Makayre<NOTE PLACE="foot">macare O, machure D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1964">"To twey bre&thorn;ryn we weddyd are</L>
<L>A-passyd be<NOTE PLACE="foot">And passyde by&thorn; O, &amp; passid arn D.</NOTE> twenty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at we to-gedyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">gedere OD.</NOTE> haue lyuyd here,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer with hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">with hem, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> were we onys wroth</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ey with vs &thorn;at wedded vs both,</L>
<L N="1969">Ne for no &thorn;yng &thorn;at euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne . . euer, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> may betyde</L>
<L>To-gedyr shul we neuer chyde.</L>
<L>Yn relygyun we wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">woldyn D.</NOTE> vs do;</L>
<L N="1972">Oure husbondys graunte nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">grauntyn not D.</NOTE> &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt haue we leuer leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">to letyn D.</NOTE> oure wylle</L>
<L>&THORN;an oure hosbundys greue with<NOTE PLACE="foot">to greuyn D</NOTE> ylle.</L>
<L>So moche loue ys vs among</L>
<L N="1976">&THORN;at none to o&thorn;er wyl do<NOTE PLACE="foot">meche . . . non of vs wil o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> wrong."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle o&thorn;er H, of many D.</NOTE> &thorn;ynges to hym &thorn;ey spake,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'seyde.'</NOTE></L>
<L>"We &thorn;enke so moche on oure wedlake,</L>
<L>For hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">was O, It was D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e olde testament,<MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1980">And yn &thorn;e newe hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is &thorn;e D.</NOTE> sacrament;</L>
<L>And God<NOTE PLACE="foot">God OD, <I>om</I>. Harl.</NOTE> ha&thorn; ordeyned hyt for &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;eryn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. <I>to</I> inserted in a later hand. &thorn;er in to (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> be bore he ches,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne shul, by oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">our O, &thorn;erfore we schul not be oure D.</NOTE> lyue,</L>
<L N="1984">Neuermore to-gedyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">gedere OD, ben at D.</NOTE> stryue,</L>
<L>Ne foly wrdys be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be O, <I>om</I>. Harl., no foly wurdis betwen vs be D.</NOTE> betwyxe vs seyd&mdash;</L>
<L>As ou&thorn;er wymmen makyn vpbreyd,&mdash;</L>
<L>For noun enuye ne coueytyse,</L>
<L N="1988">Ne for noun ou&thorn;er maner<NOTE PLACE="foot">maner of D.</NOTE> wyse;</L>
<L>But seru&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">seruyn D.</NOTE> god and oure husbondys</L>
<L>yn alle &thorn;yng &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> he sende&thorn; hys sondys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Makayre ioyed &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey were so stable,</L>
<L N="1992">And so long whyl&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwyle D.</NOTE> so tretable;</L>
<L>he &thorn;anke&thorn; God<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ankyde god O.</NOTE> &thorn;at he ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade O, &thorn;ankid . . had D.</NOTE> founde</L>
<L>So mylde wymmen yn wedlak bounde;</L>
<L>he toke hys leue and went hys weye,</L>
<L N="1996">As an abbot shulde, to hys abbeye.
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">See ll. 2475-80 of the French.</NOTE>God wuld hyt wer&euml; now so here,</L>
<L>So meke wymmen <SUP>2</SUP>of so fayre<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 of here O, mylde women of here D.</NOTE> manere;</L>
<L>But of ou&thorn;er, men mowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">mow O, may D.</NOTE> fynde</L>
<L N="2000">wymmen yn wedlak ry&yogh;t on-kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnkynde O, ful on-kynde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at for a gam&euml; wurde<NOTE PLACE="foot">gamyn wurd D.</NOTE> yn veyn</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wyl &yogh;yu&euml; forty<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyn .xx<SUP>ti</SUP>. &thorn;er D.</NOTE> a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>Se how &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O.</NOTE> wymmen<NOTE PLACE="foot">women with D.</NOTE> a-cordaunce</L>
<L N="2004">Plesyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">plesedyn D.</NOTE> god with lytyl penaunce,</L>
<L>And preysed hem to<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere preysid he D.</NOTE> seynt Makayre</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey bare hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem bare O.</NOTE> yn wedlak fayre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">so trewe in wedlok ware D.</NOTE></L>
<L>As moch&euml; &thorn;an shal he hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; as meche mote hem of D.</NOTE> blame,</L>
<L N="2008">&THORN;at chydyn to-gydyr, &amp; reysyn shame.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ch. &amp; fy&yogh;ttyn &amp; don meche scame D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer &thorn;y wyfe lay<NOTE PLACE="foot">owher . . ly D.</NOTE> by</L>
<L>Yn tyme of penaunce, to seye flesshly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">it was foly D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou be custumable &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="2012">&THORN;ou synnest gretly, my boke sey&thorn; so.</L>
<L>yn holy tyme and halyday</L>
<L>Forbere &thorn;y wyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lust D.</NOTE> &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt nat know<NOTE PLACE="foot">k. fleschly (<I>om</I>. Ne) D.</NOTE> &thorn;y wyfe</L>
<L N="2016">yn holy plac&euml;, by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be O, &thorn;e h. day be D.</NOTE> &thorn;y lyfe;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do hyt custumably,<MILESTONE N="14a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest, y sey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be hir &thorn;an D.</NOTE> dedly;</L>
<L>Cherche or cherch&euml;&yogh;erd, y sey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye O, or in cherche sawe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2020">yn holy stede hyt ys grete eye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">awe D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn lentyn tym&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is tyme D.</NOTE> of fastyng</L>
<L>Shalt &thorn;ou leue to do swyche &thorn;yng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou schalt leue al swych doyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn estyr tyme also, y<NOTE PLACE="foot">pasche tyme I &thorn;e D.</NOTE> forbede</L>
<L N="2024">&THORN;at &thorn;ou haunte any<NOTE PLACE="foot">vse no D.</NOTE> swyche dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a womman yn hordam<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou in hordam dost D.</NOTE> do swyche outrage<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. 2525 Fr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>&THORN;at a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> wrong eyre bere herytage;</L>
<L>But she wul seye hyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, &thorn;ou wylt seyn it D.</NOTE> y dar wel telle</L>
<L N="2028">&THORN;at she &thorn;arfore may<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou mayst &thorn;erfore D.</NOTE> go to helle;</L>
<L>For she ys cursed, yn stedys sere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei arn a-cursyd also in fere D. D puts lines 2031-2 before 2029-30.</NOTE></L>
<L>Four&euml; tym&euml;s yn &thorn;e &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>And swyche an eyre, y vndyrstande,</L>
<L N="2032">Shal neuer wel reioshe<NOTE PLACE="foot">schal he neuere ioy&yogh;e in D.</NOTE> hys lande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many synn&euml;s to hordam longe;</L>
<L>Sum by&thorn; ly&yogh;t, and sum be&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">many be l. &amp; many arn D.</NOTE> stronge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at be&thorn; a&yogh;ens ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei arn a-&yogh;ens trewe D.</NOTE> spousale,</L>
<L N="2036">&THORN;at y nel rekene, ne telle of<NOTE PLACE="foot">I can not . . . be D.</NOTE> tale,</L>
<L>But opunly &thorn;at seyd may<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at opynly seyd fel to be D.</NOTE> be;</L>
<L>For many longe<NOTE PLACE="foot">longen D.</NOTE> to pryuyte.</L>
<L>For pryuytees,<NOTE PLACE="foot">preuytes O.</NOTE> &yogh;yf y hem named<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. 2039, 2040, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2040">Ly&yogh;t[e]ly my&yogh;t y be blamed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. 2039, 2040, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;ogh a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;owh sum (<I>om</I>. but) D.</NOTE> man sey neuer so weyl</L>
<L>Vnto hys sawys men fyden<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyndyn O.</NOTE> teyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">summe contrarye it euerydel O.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">scorne</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at weddyd be&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o &thorn;at weddid ben D.</NOTE> God &yogh;yue hem my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2044">here wedlak to hold&euml; weyl and ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue hem grace, hordam to fle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn clenesse wuld leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyuyn D (<I>at foot</I> 'Amen. quod. <I>con</I>. Rose:').</NOTE> and be.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Seventh Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Non Furtum Facies. Septimum Mandatum. D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The seuen&thorn;e shul we nat forhele</L>
<L>'No mannys<NOTE PLACE="foot">mans O, mannys good D.</NOTE> god&euml; shalt &thorn;ou stele,'</L>
<L>For &thorn;ys ys one of ten;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e ten D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arefore y pray<NOTE PLACE="foot">prey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> all&euml; men</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey kepe hem fro &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">kepyn . . &thorn;at D.</NOTE> synne,
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ere ys moche veniauuce &thorn;erynne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ynne O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2053">yn &thorn;ys world&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrlde O.</NOTE> shamely dede;<NOTE PLACE="inter">de&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>And se&thorn;yn, helle; for god hyt forbed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lines 2053-4, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>God forbedy&thorn; men<NOTE PLACE="foot">man D.</NOTE> to stele<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2056">Any maner of world&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrldys OD.</NOTE> wele.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou man, be&thorn;enke &thorn;e wel before<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-forn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>how &thorn;ou mayst &thorn;erfore be lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for &thorn;ou . . . for lorn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And what &thorn;ou shalt haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat . . . han D.</NOTE> &thorn;arefore,</L>
<L N="2060">yn &thorn;ys world, and elyswhore."</L>
<L>But manyone wyl neuer beware</L>
<L>Tyl sum myschaunce make hem a&yogh;enchare;<NOTE PLACE="foot">myshap bringi&thorn; hym in car D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Slayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">takyn &amp; slayn D.</NOTE> or, yn prysun<NOTE PLACE="foot">prysone O, presoun D.</NOTE> be,</L>
<L N="2064">Or hanged, &thorn;at al &thorn;e worlde may se.</L>
<L>So shul men &thorn;e body shende;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt to peyne &thorn;e soule shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i soule to peyne D.</NOTE> wende.</L>
<L>wuld&euml; men se what myschaunce</L>
<L N="2068">Cum&thorn; for &thorn;eft,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yfte O, comyth for &thorn;efte &amp; &yogh;it D.</NOTE> and what penaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;eft&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yfte O.</NOTE> shulde nat be so lefe;</L>
<L>A foule poynt<NOTE PLACE="foot">poynt O.</NOTE> ys, be clepyd a &thorn;efe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">name it is to be callyd &thorn;ef D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ou&thorn;er poyntes of wykkednes</L>
<L N="2072">Mow be soffred, sum more, sum les;</L>
<L>But &thorn;efte<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yfte O.</NOTE> serue&thorn; of wykkede note,<NOTE PLACE="inter">seruyse</NOTE></L>
<L>hyt hange&thorn; hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> mayster by &thorn;e &thorn;rote,</L>
<L>Or do&thorn;e hym lese hys god&euml; fame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">good name D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or brynge&thorn; hym oute<NOTE PLACE="foot">ellyswher O, ellis qwere D.</NOTE> of &thorn;e towne forshame.</L>
<L N="2077">'&THORN;efte shal neuere more be hyd,</L>
<L>For, here or elyswhore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. hyt out . . wy&thorn; OD, (D <I>om</I>. hym, hyt, &thorn;e).</NOTE> hyt shal be kyd;'</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e prophete &thorn;at men on leuys,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D (<I>om</I>. <I>2nd</I> to).</NOTE> speke&thorn; to fals men and to &thorn;euys.</L>
<L N="2081">&THORN;e synne ys nat for&yogh;yuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">is not for&yogh;oue D.</NOTE> &thorn;e man</L>
<L>But he restore &thorn;at he haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; O, b. &thorn;ou r. &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast D.</NOTE> tan;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou make any man<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf &thorn;ou ony good D.</NOTE> falsly tyne,<NOTE PLACE="inter">lese</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="75"></L>
<L N="2084">As for &thorn;eft,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;efte OD.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt haue pyne;</L>
<L>And moch&euml; more, for swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil m. for sum D.</NOTE> falsnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;an for any ou&thorn;er falsnes &thorn;at es.<NOTE PLACE="foot">for sum &thorn;at falsnesse isse D.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">&para; <I>A tale</I> in margin HO.</NOTE>A gode ensample &thorn;es clerkys wote<NOTE PLACE="foot">woot O, &thorn;at cl. wot D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2088">Of a tale &thorn;at an abbot wrote,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wroot O, &thorn;at in a bok he wrot D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;euys shulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">schuldyn D.</NOTE> before hem loke</L>
<L>Ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">or D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey ou&thorn;er mennys &thorn;yng toke;&mdash;</L>
<L>yn 'vytas patrum' hyt ys wryte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrete O, wreten D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2092">hyt ys a boke &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ys cl. O, &thorn;at cl. weten D.</NOTE> clerkys wete,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">And a OD.</NOTE> ful fayre techyng ys &thorn;er-ynne<NOTE PLACE="foot">lernyng &thorn;erin D.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="14b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For to leue of &thorn;eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yfte O, to letyn of &thorn;efte &thorn;at s. D.</NOTE> &thorn;e synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Zenon, the would-be Thief: how he reformd himself.]
<NOTE>[<I>Vitas Patrum</I>, ed. Roseweyd, p. 569.&mdash;G. Paris.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ys yche abbot, &YOGH;enon he<NOTE PLACE="foot">It was an ab. &thorn;at &yogh;enan D.</NOTE> hyght,</L>
<L>And wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O.</NOTE> he was with god almyght;</L>
<L N="2097">Vppon a day<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyme D.</NOTE> he went hys wey</L>
<L>To Palestyne, &thorn;at ys an<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys an, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> abbey,</L>
<L>To make hys vysytacyun</L>
<L N="2100">As falle&thorn; yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">it falli&thorn; in his D.</NOTE> relygyun;</L>
<L>And as he went by<NOTE PLACE="foot">wente be O.</NOTE> &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>he behelde a fruyt ry&yogh;t feyre and<NOTE PLACE="foot">frut &thorn;at was ful D (<I>om</I>. he).</NOTE> swete;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys yche fruyt he desyred<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilke frut he coueytid D.</NOTE> faste,</L>
<L>And hys herte moche &thorn;arto<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar to moche O, &thorn;erto mechil (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> he caste,</L>
<L N="2105">'Gourdys'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gourdus O, turcus . . . calle D.</NOTE> &thorn;us men clepe &thorn;e name;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys gode man &thorn;oght, "y am to blame</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y take ou&thorn;er mennys &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="2108">wy&thorn;-out&euml; leue of any<NOTE PLACE="foot">my D.</NOTE> askyng.</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e, he seyde, &thorn;an were y a &thorn;efe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ef OD (<I>om</I>. he seyde D).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>And &thorn;efte ne ys gode, ne gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">gode O, no H, &thorn;. to god is not lefe D.</NOTE> man lefe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lef O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf y stele, y am a felun;</L>
<L N="2112">hanged y shal be, &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">hangen schal I be D.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t resun.</L>
<L>Fyrst y wylle wyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete O, wete &thorn;e certeyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e so&thorn;e certeyne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y may suffre &thorn;at yche<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilke D.</NOTE> peyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;efys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;euys OD.</NOTE> suffre for &thorn;eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;efte O, &thorn;eftis D.</NOTE> sake,</L>
<L N="2116">Ar y wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, or I wil ony D.</NOTE> oght of &thorn;e fruyt take;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf y may nat suffre &thorn;at wo,</L>
<L>To &thorn;eft&euml; wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an wil D.</NOTE> y neuer go."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ryght as he &thorn;oght, he dede eche dele,</L>
<L N="2120">he &yogh;ede and clambe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er he clomb D.</NOTE> vpp on a pele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyl O, pel D.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">perche</NOTE></L>
<L>And hyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">hynge O, heng D.</NOTE> &thorn;eron by &thorn;e hond,<NOTE PLACE="foot">handys D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Nat by &thorn;e nekke, y vndyrstonde<NOTE PLACE="foot">not be . . . we vnderstandis D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>For hyt ys nat oueral &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L N="2124">For to do so, men to<NOTE PLACE="foot">men so to O, don men so of D.</NOTE> dawe.</L>
<L>Fyu&euml; days he hyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">hynge O, hong D.</NOTE> &thorn;ere stylle</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e sunn&euml; by<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at synne be D.</NOTE> hys wylle;</L>
<L>And hyt was<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; was D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e somerys tyde,</L>
<L N="2128">whan &thorn;e hete ys al yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan hete is in al his D.</NOTE> pryde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">spak D.</NOTE> he, to hymself &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ys peyn&euml; wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, of &thorn;. fr. wil D.</NOTE> y suffre no more:</L>
<L>&THORN;efte, he seyde, y here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here I D.</NOTE> forsake;<MILESTONE N="15a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2132">&THORN;ys fruyt, wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> y nat take.</L>
<L>Syn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Si&thorn;&thorn;in (<I>om</I>. for) D.</NOTE> y may nat suffre for grefe</L>
<L>&THORN;e peyne &thorn;at befalle&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">falli&thorn; for D.</NOTE> a &thorn;efe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ensample were gode to kone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">example is good to knowe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2136">Alle hem &thorn;at to &thorn;efte hem wone;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at to &thorn;efte wil hym drawe D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at haue here handys as lyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">han hool handis &amp; lym D.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem were gode to here &thorn;ys ryme;
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>&THORN;an myght &thorn;ey wyt&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete OD.</NOTE> redly</L>
<L N="2140">what<NOTE PLACE="foot">redily; qwat D.</NOTE> sham&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ey were wur&thorn;y,</L>
<L>And swych grace my&yogh;t god<NOTE PLACE="foot">god my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> hem sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey, &thorn;urgh &thorn;ys my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;te &thorn;orwh &thorn;is D.</NOTE> hem amende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>om</I>. A.</NOTE> &thorn;ef&euml; to hys &thorn;efte ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in to &thorn;. hath alwey D.</NOTE> rape,</L>
<L>For he wene&thorn; euer-more for<NOTE PLACE="foot">more HO, <I>om</I>. D; for HD, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> to skape;</L>
<L N="2145">yn &thorn;at hope he do&thorn;e hys euyl,</L>
<L>And al ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">is &thorn;e OD.</NOTE> entycement of &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore be&thorn;enke &thorn;e wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl, man O, man wel D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;arfore).</NOTE> with-ynne</L>
<L N="2148">&THORN;at &thorn;efte ys cumbrement<NOTE PLACE="foot">encumbrement D.</NOTE> of synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a man make a chylde oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">owht a child to D.</NOTE> stele,</L>
<L>Swyche styl<NOTE PLACE="foot">stylle O, stille D.</NOTE> &thorn;efte shal he nat hele;</L>
<L>A &thorn;efte hyt ys, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou do so,</L>
<L>To tyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyce O, teche D.</NOTE> a chylde swyche synne to do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer stale a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou stele ony D.</NOTE> chylde aweye,</L>
<L>yn swych&euml; &thorn;efte ys grete affraye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is gret fray D.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys twey &thorn;ynges and yn &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of &thorn;ese to &thorn;ingis &amp; of swych D.</NOTE> fame</L>
<L N="2156">Are wymmen moch&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn many women meche D.</NOTE> to blame.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">han D.</NOTE> cumlyngys yn and oute;</L>
<L>Of swyche shuld men haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">han D.</NOTE> gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret OD.</NOTE> doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul neuer weyte but wo,</L>
<L N="2160">Swych&euml; cumlyngys, to ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">sueche . . and D.</NOTE> fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are wur&thorn;y to be shent</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys yche<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilke D.</NOTE> comaund&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou brake euer any kyrke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss. 'cherche,' werk D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2164">On day, or yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">on O.</NOTE> ny&yogh;t, yn myrke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">day or ny&yogh;t in &thorn;e merke D.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">derke</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a-cursed, &thorn;ou wost&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wost OD.</NOTE> weyl,</L>
<L>And hange were wur&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; wur&thorn;i to hangen vp D.</NOTE> on a peyl.
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou bere<NOTE PLACE="foot">beryst O, bere D (<I>om</I>. &yogh;yf).</NOTE> awey &thorn;e &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="2168">&THORN;e more &thorn;ou fallest yn cursyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue be a &thorn;efe of pray<MILESTONE N="15a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To robb&euml; men be<NOTE PLACE="foot">vsyd to robbe men D.</NOTE> ny&yogh;t or be<NOTE PLACE="foot">OD <I>om</I>. be.</NOTE> day,</L>
<L>Gretly &thorn;ou dost a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou oghtyst to do swyche men a<NOTE PLACE="foot">o O, of D.</NOTE>dawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2173">Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou swyche foly began<NOTE PLACE="foot">began OD.</NOTE></L>
<L>To rauysh&euml; any<NOTE PLACE="foot">to rauaschyn euere ony D.</NOTE> womman,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to seye, any<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyne ony D.</NOTE> wedded wyfe,</L>
<L N="2176">&THORN;e more ys &thorn;y synne &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in D.</NOTE> perel of lyfe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou rauyssh any<NOTE PLACE="foot">a O, rauasehedyst ony mayde D.</NOTE> mayden clene&mdash;</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens here wyl, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D.</NOTE> ys to mene,&mdash;</L>
<L>hyt ys seyde &thorn;urgh law&euml; wrete,</L>
<L N="2180">&THORN;at &thorn;yn hede shulde be of smete<NOTE PLACE="foot">wretyn . . his hed . . smeten D.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Lawe make&thorn; &thorn;at command&euml;ment)</L>
<L>with-outyn any iugg&euml;ment;</L>
<L>&THORN;at mayst &thorn;ou fynd&euml; al an<NOTE PLACE="foot">and O.</NOTE> sum</L>
<L N="2184">In code 'de raptu virginum.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou rauysshe a mayden powre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rauaschyst . . pure D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art holdyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">holde O, be holde hir to recure O.</NOTE> to here socoure;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at shal be<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at schal be don D.</NOTE> at here wylle,</L>
<L N="2188">For, as she wyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, &amp; al &thorn;at sche wile D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt fulfylle;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast do here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here a O, don hire a D.</NOTE> tresun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast stole here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; stolyn hir chef D.</NOTE> warysun;</L>
<L>hyt may &thorn;e brynge to more cumbryng</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ogh O.</NOTE> &thorn;ou haddest stole moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an &thorn;ou had stole meche D.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>To comun lechours, y &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is I D.</NOTE> seye,</L>
<L>Many with-out&euml; shryfte shul deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a gret D.</NOTE> lordyng,</L>
<L N="2196">And outraiusly<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at outrageusly D.</NOTE> takyst mennys &thorn;yng</L>
<L>yn tyme of werre or tyme of pes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou stelyst hyt, with-out&euml; les,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>But &thorn;urgh ry&yogh;t or &thorn;urgh cunnaunte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;t of comenaunt D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="2200">&THORN;ou art a &thorn;efe &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hyt haunte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;ou be D.</NOTE> a lorde of a tounne</L>
<L>Robbe hys men oute of<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &thorn;i men robbe with-out D.</NOTE> resoune,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt be yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">al be it in his D.</NOTE> bondage,</L>
<L N="2204">A&yogh;ens ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE> he do&thorn;e outrage.</L>
<L>he shal so take, &thorn;at he may lyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue O, schuld . . o&thorn;ere my&yogh;t D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as lawe of londe wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil &yogh;eue D.</NOTE> for&yogh;yue;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; &yogh;if D.</NOTE> he take ouer mesure,<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2208">lytyl tym&euml; shal hyt dure.<NOTE PLACE="foot">endure D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if D.</NOTE> god haue &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue O, &yogh;ouyn D.</NOTE> hym &thorn;e seynorye,<NOTE PLACE="inter">lordshyp</NOTE></L>
<L>he &yogh;af hym no leue to do<NOTE PLACE="foot">make (<I>om</I>. hym) D.</NOTE> robborye;</L>
<L>For god ha&thorn; ordeyned al mennys<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle mens O, for he . . . euery mannys D.</NOTE> state,</L>
<L N="2212">how to lyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue O, schuld . . o&thorn;ere my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> and yn what gate;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'maner.' How he schal lyuyn &amp; on qwat g. D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;t he &yogh;yue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ogh he &yogh;eue O, &yogh;if he &yogh;eue a man meche m. D.</NOTE> one ouer o&thorn;er my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he wyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O.</NOTE> &thorn;at he do hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">he do no man (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> but ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e ry&yogh;t of goddys lokyng,</L>
<L N="2216">"&YOGH;elde euery man hys own&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">owyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng."</L>
<L>But god take&thorn; euermore<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> veniaunce</L>
<L>Of lordys, for swych myschaunce,</L>
<L>For swych robbery &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">as D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey make</L>
<L N="2220">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ey O.</NOTE> oft&euml; of &thorn;e poure<NOTE PLACE="foot">pore O, of &thorn;e pore with wrong ofte &thorn;ei t. D.</NOTE> men take.</L>
<L>y shal &yogh;ou telle a. lytyl wyght</L>
<L>how hyt befel onys of<NOTE PLACE="foot">be fil of suyche D.</NOTE> a kny&yogh;t. <NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">narracio D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Knight who robd a Poor Man.]</HEAD>
<L>Sum tym&euml; was, hyt were twey<NOTE PLACE="foot">it was &thorn;er were to D.</NOTE> kny&yogh;tys</L>
<L N="2224">&THORN;at loued weyl at<NOTE PLACE="foot">louedyn to-gedere with al D.</NOTE> her&euml; my&yogh;tys;</L>
<L>A sykenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">syknes O, syknesse on &thorn;at oon D.</NOTE> on &thorn;e toon gan falle,
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>he deyd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; dey&yogh;ed D.</NOTE> sone, as we shul alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er kny&yogh;t seyd ofte, alas,</L>
<L N="2228">For<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at o&thorn;er . . &thorn;at D.</NOTE> hys felawe so sone dede was.</L>
<L>Fyl hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">it fel . . lyuende D.</NOTE> so, &thorn;ys lyuyng kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>yn hys bed he lay<NOTE PLACE="foot">lay on D.</NOTE> a nyght,</L>
<L>And was yn swyche a-wakyng</L>
<L N="2232">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O, my&yogh;t not D (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at).</NOTE> slep&euml; for no &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e mone shone yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys OD, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> chaumbre flore;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t lay, and lokyd fur&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">foor D.</NOTE></L>
<L>At a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> wyndowe come yn a beme,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e shynyng he saghe a gleme</L>
<L N="2237">Ryght lyche &thorn;at kny&yogh;t euery<NOTE PLACE="foot">eury O.</NOTE>deyl</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum tyme he loued ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">was he louede so D.</NOTE> weyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys kny&yogh;t &thorn;oght 'hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e k. hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t it was D.</NOTE> fantome</L>
<L N="2240">&THORN;at y se &thorn;us yn &thorn;e mon&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn &thorn;e mone &thorn;us O, he saw in &thorn;e mone ly&yogh;t D.</NOTE> come.'</L>
<L>He was a-frayd<NOTE PLACE="foot">a ferd D.</NOTE> with-out&euml; fayle,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at was no grete merueyle.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e kny&yogh;t &thorn;at was dede</L>
<L>Cumfortyd hym sone, &amp; seyde hys rede,</L>
<L N="2245">"Be nat adred,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a ferd D.</NOTE> for hyt am y<MILESTONE N="15b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou louedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e louede D.</NOTE> so specyaly.</L>
<L>Y was &thorn;y felaw, &thorn;y trewe frere,</L>
<L N="2248">For help y come to &thorn;e now here:</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh y be dede, &thorn;ou darst<NOTE PLACE="foot">darst &thorn;ou O, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be ded, &thorn;ar &thorn;e not D.</NOTE> nat drede,</L>
<L>Of helpe had y neuer er nede.</L>
<L>At ned&euml; shul men proue<NOTE PLACE="foot">preue O, preuyn D.</NOTE> here frendys,</L>
<L>And frendes loue o&thorn;er whyle wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, sumtyme wel D.</NOTE> endys.</L>
<L N="2253">help me now, y am yn wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y may come &thorn;e sonner<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e sunner come O, come &thorn;e sonere D.</NOTE> &thorn;erfro."
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is D.</NOTE> kny&yogh;t, &thorn;at lay yn hys bed,</L>
<L N="2256">wax bolder, and lasse<NOTE PLACE="foot">wex boldere &amp; was not D.</NOTE> a-dred,</L>
<L>And seyd "felaw, for charyte,</L>
<L>what ys &thorn;y wo? shewe hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat is &thorn;i wo, &thorn;ou telle it D.</NOTE> me."</L>
<L N="2259">&THORN;an spake to hym &thorn;e ded&euml; kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>"&THORN;oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ogh O, &yogh;if D.</NOTE> y had space a day &amp; a<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>om</I>. 'a.'</NOTE> ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e penaunce ne coude y telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y suffre yn a welle.</L>
<L>A peyne y suffre hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">harde, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L N="2264">For a clo&thorn;e &thorn;at y refte<NOTE PLACE="foot">stal D.</NOTE> ones</L>
<L>Of a poure<NOTE PLACE="foot">pore OD.</NOTE> man with-out&euml; ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at euer y say<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh O, hadde D.</NOTE> &thorn;at sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at clo&thorn;e ys caste on me to peyne</L>
<L N="2268">As heuy as any mounteyne;</L>
<L>Hyl ne mounteyne, er&thorn;e ne stone,</L>
<L>Vndyr heuene so heuy ys none;</L>
<L>No so hote fyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">fere O, fyr D.</NOTE> ys yn no land<NOTE PLACE="foot">is now in londe D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2272">As hyt ys aboute me brennand.<NOTE PLACE="foot">aboue me brennande D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, felaw, y pray<NOTE PLACE="foot">prey&yogh;e to D.</NOTE> &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou haue on me<NOTE PLACE="foot">on me &thorn;ou haue D.</NOTE> pyte,</L>
<L>And, to pore men do noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">do &thorn;ou non D.</NOTE> ylle,</L>
<L N="2276">Ne a&yogh;ens holy chyrches wylle;</L>
<L>But al &thorn;e gode &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alwey good &thorn;at &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> werche</L>
<L>To por&euml; men and<NOTE PLACE="foot">do <I>and</I> O, bo&thorn;e to p. m. &amp; D.</NOTE> to holy chyrche.</L>
<L N="2279">Me were leuere deye an hundyr sy&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">to dey&yogh;e an hundred sy&thorn;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an suffre &thorn;ys peyne &thorn;at noght may<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at may not D.</NOTE> ly&thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyde &thorn;e kny&yogh;t, &amp; wepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is kn. &amp; wepyd D.</NOTE> ful sore,</L>
<L>"My swete felaw, telle me &yogh;yt<NOTE PLACE="foot">now telle me D.</NOTE> more,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any &thorn;yng be so<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony &thorn;ing were ful D.</NOTE> certeyne<MILESTONE N="16a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2284">&THORN;at may delyuer &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;tte delyuere &thorn;e out D.</NOTE> of peyne."
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e kny&yogh;t, "y my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte O, my&yogh;t D.</NOTE> be clere</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t nemnede prestes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. 'p'test,' <I>om</I>. OD.</NOTE> manyone;</L>
<L N="2288">&THORN;an stode &thorn;e ded&euml;, stylle as<NOTE PLACE="foot">stille as a D.</NOTE> stone,</L>
<L>"wylt &thorn;ou &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;at &thorn;ei for D.</NOTE> any of &thorn;ese for &thorn;e syng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">syngge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e of peyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">out of peynys D.</NOTE> for to brynge?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">bryngge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e dede meuede hys hede<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys hede meuede O.</NOTE> to &amp; fro,</L>
<L N="2292">For he was payd of noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">plecyd with non D.</NOTE> of &thorn;o.</L>
<L>wete &yogh;e forso&thorn;e, bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> man and wyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey were nat of<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle of D.</NOTE> clen&euml; lyfe;</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;e dede &yogh;af noun answere,</L>
<L N="2296">he made no fors of here preyere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne&thorn;eles,<NOTE PLACE="foot">No&thorn;eles O, not for &thorn;an &thorn;e self D.</NOTE> &thorn;e seluyn messe</L>
<L>ys no&thorn;er &thorn;e wurs&euml;, ne &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuere &thorn;e wers no of pris D.</NOTE> lesse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne, hys feyrnes neuer he<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> tynes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'lesy&thorn;.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt on &thorn;e muk hepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">mukhyl D.</NOTE> shynes,</L>
<L N="2301">But &thorn;e muk ys &thorn;e more stynkyngge<NOTE PLACE="foot">mukhil . . stynkend D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;e sunne ys more shynyngge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hoot schynyng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No O, no more is lorn D.</NOTE> more hyt ys lore, &thorn;e vertu</L>
<L N="2304">Of &thorn;e messe, but<NOTE PLACE="foot">to D.</NOTE> mannys pru.</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">If D.</NOTE> &thorn;e prest be fals or frow,</L>
<L>&THORN;e messe, ys euer gode ynow;<NOTE PLACE="foot">a now D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;e preyere ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyeris of hym han D.</NOTE> no my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2308">For hys lyfe ys nat clene dy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t nemnede one at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>A gode man, and a ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;t, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> stedefaste:</L>
<L>"wylt &thorn;ou &thorn;at he preye for &thorn;e?"</L>
<L N="2312">&THORN;o seyde &thorn;e dede "wel were &thorn;an me<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou seyde . . were me D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;yf he wuld&euml; for me syngge,</L>
<L>he my&yogh;t me of<NOTE PLACE="foot">out of D.</NOTE> peyn&euml;s bryngge."
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">he seyde D.</NOTE> truly, "truste to me,</L>
<L N="2316">&THORN;at sam&euml; prest shal prey<NOTE PLACE="foot">preye O, ilke p. s. prey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;y peyne mow<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t . . lesse (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> be &thorn;e lasse,</L>
<L>Euery day shal he for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">for &thorn;e shal he O, certeyn day&yogh;is schal he for &thorn;e s. masse D.</NOTE> synge a masse."</L>
<L>"May y &thorn;an trust to &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">trusten &thorn;an to &thorn;e D.</NOTE> sawe</L>
<L N="2320">&THORN;at &thorn;ou be now my<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou wilt be to me (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> trew felawe?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&yogh;e, as y am a trew kny&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="16a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hyt shal be do, at<NOTE PLACE="foot">don with al D.</NOTE> my my&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"A tokene betwyxe<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-twen D.</NOTE> &thorn;e and me,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">me and &thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2324">&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e ded&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e dede seyde &thorn;at D.</NOTE> "shal &thorn;ys be?"</L>
<L>he toke and grepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">grypyd D.</NOTE> &thorn;e kny&yogh;tys arme,</L>
<L>But he felt &thorn;er-of none harme;</L>
<L>Also he touched hys bare &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot">so he touched &thorn;e bare skyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bare bone my&yogh;t men euer after se;<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t be sen D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2329">But sor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sor O, and for D.</NOTE> &thorn;erof felt<NOTE PLACE="foot">felte O D.</NOTE> he noght,</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e felyng, more on hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">on hym more (<I>om</I>. but) D.</NOTE> he &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mark saw alle men comunly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e tokene saw many on &thorn;erby D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2332">But no man wyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyste O, non wyste r. qwy D.</NOTE> redely why.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ded&euml; seyd "&thorn;ou shalt leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">not lyuyn D.</NOTE> here</L>
<L>No lenger but<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an D.</NOTE> &thorn;ys two &yogh;ere."</L>
<L>he tolde what day &thorn;at he shuld deye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">t. he schulde dey&yogh;e &amp; qwat day D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2336">And se&thorn;yn he went for&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ede fur&thorn; O, &thorn;e dede kny&yogh;t &thorn;o &yogh;ede D.</NOTE> hys weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t amended se&thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn;en amendede O, si&thorn;&thorn;e amendyd D.</NOTE> hym weyl,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e dede was as trew<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewe (<I>om</I>. as) D.</NOTE> as steyl;</L>
<L>For he dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>om</I>. For) he dede for hym D.</NOTE> as he hym hette,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest for hym song &thorn;at he hem hette.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym to synge he let D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2341">&THORN;ys aperyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">schewyng D.</NOTE> yn my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myne O, myn D.</NOTE> auys,</L>
<L>Auayled<NOTE PLACE="foot">It a-vayled D.</NOTE> to bo&thorn;e partys.
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Syn O, si&thorn;&thorn;e . . a palmerys D.</NOTE> toke &thorn;e kny&yogh;t palmers wede,</L>
<L N="2344">And yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> to &thorn;e holy londe he &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>Ihesu cryst<NOTE PLACE="foot">crystys O, cristis D.</NOTE> sepulcre he soght,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e synnys<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne hadde D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he had wroght;</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">at &thorn;e, OD, at H.</NOTE> two &yogh;er&euml;s &yogh;ende,</L>
<L N="2348">God almyghty for hym gan sende;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at day &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e same day D.</NOTE> &thorn;e dede kny&yogh;t seyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er knyghte &thorn;at same day<NOTE PLACE="foot">for so&thorn;e &thorn;at o&thorn;er kny&yogh;t D.</NOTE> deyde.</L>
<L>Blessyd be god, of<NOTE PLACE="foot">grace be god D.</NOTE> heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="2352">&THORN;at sent hym &thorn;at yche<NOTE PLACE="foot">to hym &thorn;at D.</NOTE> tokenyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now may &yogh;e se, by &thorn;ys tale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;eft&euml; brewe&thorn; moch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> bale.</L>
<L>Certys &thorn;efte ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful D.</NOTE> wykked ys</L>
<L N="2356">whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> &thorn;e dede bere&thorn; wytnes,</L>
<L>Namly, pore men for<NOTE PLACE="foot">a namely pore men D.</NOTE> to pele</L>
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="foot">And O (<I>om</I>. D), robben &amp; beten w. o. skele D.</NOTE> robbe or bete with-out&euml; skyle.</L>
<L>&THORN;eft&euml; wyl hys mayster shende,<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2360">And hym fordo<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; for don D.</NOTE> wy&thorn;-outyn ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be a ser&iuml;aunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">were euere ony seruaunt D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">toke . . . comnaunt D.</NOTE> more &thorn;an &thorn;y cunnaunt,</L>
<L>Custummablych&euml;, mete or drynk<NOTE PLACE="foot">drynge O, &amp; drynk D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="2364">&THORN;oht for noght hyt be &thorn;e &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is al for nou&yogh;t as &thorn;e &thorn;inkith D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>y red&euml; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">rede sum tyme D.</NOTE> &thorn;ou &thorn;er-of lete,</L>
<L>For many smale make&thorn; a grete.</L>
<L>holy chyrche cally&thorn; hyt &thorn;efte,</L>
<L N="2368">wy&thorn;-out&euml; skylle, for hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">skyl al &thorn;at &thorn;at D.</NOTE> ys refte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer reysyddyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">receydist ony fals D.</NOTE> custome,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst be sykyr of hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t . . ry&yogh;t hard D.</NOTE> dome.</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;ou may for don it &amp; D.</NOTE> felle,</L>
<L N="2372">hyt ys robbery, gostly to telle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">g. &thorn;ou gost to helle D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt so betyde &thorn;at hyt laste&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">laste O, so be it l. D.</NOTE> ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;y med&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">song D.</NOTE> shal be welaway.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou amende hyt nat yn &thorn;y lyue,</L>
<L N="2376">what<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> prest may &thorn;e &thorn;er-of shryue?</L>
<L>Now telle we for&thorn;e, &thorn;at &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">we D.</NOTE> may lere,</L>
<L>how &thorn;eft&euml; com&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">comy&thorn; OD, &amp; on qwat m. D.</NOTE> yn queynt manere:&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> euer &thorn;y werke withdrowe,</L>
<L N="2380">Or dedyst hyt nat weyl to<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede it not wel to &thorn;e ful D.</NOTE> prowe,</L>
<L>Tyde or tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou shuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">shust O, qwhan &thorn;ou schal D.</NOTE> werche,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou art a &thorn;efe,' sey&thorn; holy cherche.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do custummablyche swych<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys OD.</NOTE> lak,</L>
<L>To begyle<NOTE PLACE="foot">falsyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;y mayster be-hynde hys bak,</L>
<L N="2385">&THORN;ou mayst nat excuse &thorn;e with rous,<NOTE PLACE="inter">proud wordys</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">must not defende &thorn;e with ros D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sey, 'al &thorn;e worlde so dous.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;owh al &thorn;e wyde word so gos D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e world&euml; may nat sau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">word may not sauyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Shryue<NOTE PLACE="foot">amende . . word D.</NOTE> &thorn;y defaute, and late &thorn;e world be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2389">&YOGH;yf &thorn;e be leyde a borde<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou ley ony hurd D.</NOTE> to wedde,</L>
<L>Or a clo&thorn;e to bak or bedde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hyt vse a&yogh;ens hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">her D.</NOTE> wylle,</L>
<L>holy cherche sey&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou dost<NOTE PLACE="foot">doust O, &thorn;ou dost (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> ylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yl O, wil . . . il D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2393">And warne&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;erof &yogh;yt efte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt ys bo&thorn;e okyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">gowl D.</NOTE> and &thorn;efte.</L>
<L>Okur<NOTE PLACE="foot">goul D.</NOTE> hyt ys, for &thorn;e outrage</L>
<L>To take &thorn;y catel, and haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> auauntage;</L>
<L N="2397">And for &thorn;efte, he may &thorn;e greue<MILESTONE N="16b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To vse hys &thorn;yng a&yogh;ens hys leue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hyt be so &thorn;at &thorn;us ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">be sueche forth D.</NOTE> gone,</L>
<L N="2400">Charyte ne cristyndome<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewe charyte D.</NOTE> ys &thorn;er none.</L>
<L>&THORN;yn euencristyn &thorn;ou owyst to lene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">releue <I>or</I> relene D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou mayst spare hyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;at y mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">As D.</NOTE> &yogh;yf a &thorn;yng be &thorn;e lent
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="86"></L>
<L N="2404">And &thorn;ou wy&thorn;-out&euml; hys asent</L>
<L>lene fur&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">put &thorn;at &thorn;ing often D.</NOTE> to were,</L>
<L>For &thorn;efte to hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">to hym O, &thorn;er of D, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt answere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost weyl, &thorn;ou dost<NOTE PLACE="foot">doust O, &thorn;ou dost (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> nat ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="2408">&THORN;at a-no&thorn;er hyt use&thorn;, hyt ys &thorn;y ply&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to a-peyre his good forso&thorn;e I ply&yogh;t. D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue a &thorn;yng yn ferme</L>
<L>To a certeyn day of terme,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou ouer &thorn;at terme day</L>
<L N="2412">Trauelyst hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">Traueylyst hyt O, trauaylyst it D; hyt <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens hys pay,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast synned yn a spece,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I telle &thorn;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn &thorn;eft&euml; &thorn;ou art come a grece.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In a spyce of &thorn;efte in &thorn;at degre D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wyl y speke of okerers,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gouleris D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2416">&THORN;at &thorn;efys ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, arn on &thorn;e same D.</NOTE> yn sum maners.</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;at vsery<NOTE PLACE="foot">he &thorn;at to gowle D.</NOTE> ys lefe,</L>
<L>Gost[e]ly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gostly to telle D.</NOTE> he ys a &thorn;efe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou of any okerere<NOTE PLACE="foot">ony gowlere D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2420">wy&thorn; wrong hys &thorn;yng awey dest<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-wey his good D.</NOTE> bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;oghe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if D.</NOTE> he be no cristyn man,</L>
<L>&THORN;efte vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">to D.</NOTE> &thorn;y self &thorn;ou wan;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne owyst nat of hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou owyst not of hym D.</NOTE> to haue</L>
<L>with wrong, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;y self wylt<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylt <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2425">Also, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou haue founde a &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And makyst &thorn;erfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er of D.</NOTE> none askyng</L>
<L>At cherche ne at &thorn;e market an hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hij O, &thorn;e cherche ne market by D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2428">But forhelest<NOTE PLACE="foot">kepist D.</NOTE> hyt pryuyly</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;yng with &thorn;e dwelle,</L>
<L>hyt ys &thorn;efte, &thorn;ys clerkys telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou withdrawest<NOTE PLACE="foot">wy&thorn;draghst O, with-drawe H.</NOTE> a mannys<NOTE PLACE="foot">mans.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2432">Styllyche, &thorn;at hyt be nat yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at he haue &thorn;er-of no D.</NOTE> syght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">al&thorn;owh D.</NOTE> a man parseyue hyt noght,
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou stelyst hyt, and &thorn;efte<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; as a &thorn;ef D.</NOTE> hast wroght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wy&thorn;holdest<NOTE PLACE="foot">withdrawe D.</NOTE> a mannys seruyse<MILESTONE N="17a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2436">For euyl herte or fals<NOTE PLACE="foot">for D.</NOTE> queyntyse,</L>
<L>Or withdrawest<NOTE PLACE="foot">wy&thorn;drahst O, with-drawyst ony mannys D.</NOTE> any manere pay,</L>
<L>And ledyst hym fur&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; taryest hym D.</NOTE> fro day to day,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf hyt be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'be'; be O, be be D.</NOTE> with grete resun,</L>
<L N="2440">Of &thorn;eft&euml; &thorn;ou art<NOTE PLACE="foot">art &thorn;e O, art &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> enchesun.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e gospel commaunde&thorn; ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>'holde nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">withholde non D.</NOTE> hys seruyse ouer nyght;'</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e man ha&thorn; do<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan a m. h. don D.</NOTE> hys dede,</L>
<L N="2444">God wol<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle O, wil D.</NOTE> &thorn;at he haue hys mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat seyn (<I>om</I>. &thorn;es) D.</NOTE> men of &thorn;es fals husbandys</L>
<L>&THORN;at ere aweye falsly<NOTE PLACE="foot">falsly ere awey O, falsly eryn a-wey o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> mennys landys;</L>
<L>Of a land, &thorn;urgh and &thorn;urgh,</L>
<L N="2448">Takyn and eryn awey a furgh?<NOTE PLACE="foot">taki&thorn; welny a wey a forw D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ys bo&thorn;e thefte and<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;it it is a &thorn;efte &amp; a D.</NOTE> robberye,</L>
<L>And hyt ful der&euml; shal he a-bye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H., &amp; ful dere he schal it a-bey D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of swych&euml;, fewe men<NOTE PLACE="foot">fo men god D.</NOTE> hem amende,</L>
<L N="2452">For &thorn;ey beyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o men arn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuylys frende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tauuarsyns<NOTE PLACE="foot">gannokerys D.</NOTE> and vserers,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys are, Lucyfer, &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn lucyferys D.</NOTE> peres;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey are alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei arn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuyl betaght</L>
<L N="2456">&THORN;at okeryn falsly &thorn;e worldes aght.<NOTE PLACE="inter">gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at is for goule &amp; for wordis au&yogh;t D.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>Okyr ys also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">goul it is D.</NOTE> &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hyt haunte,</L>
<L>To len&euml; &thorn;yng to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vp D.</NOTE> certeyn cunnaunt;</L>
<L>Also, to bye<NOTE PLACE="foot">a no&thorn;er to bey&yogh;e D.</NOTE> a &thorn;yng byfore,</L>
<L N="2460">halfe vn-to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e OD, <I>om</I>. Harl.</NOTE> sellers<NOTE PLACE="foot">soweris D.</NOTE> lore;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;e byer may weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;e bey&yogh;ere my&yogh;t wel D</NOTE> lene</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge O.</NOTE> with-out&euml; losse or<NOTE PLACE="foot">trey &amp; D.</NOTE> tene,
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>he ys holde to helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou art bounden to helpyn D.</NOTE> hym with-alle,</L>
<L>Or holy cherche sey&thorn;, &thorn;at he hyt stalle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">seith &thorn;ou it stal D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2465">Okeryng ys on many<NOTE PLACE="foot">goulyng ha&thorn; a no&thorn;er D.</NOTE> manere,</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an y kan telle now here.</L>
<L>But wete &yogh;e weyl, swyche gode shal go</L>
<L N="2468">As hyt come, with sorowe and wo;</L>
<L>For some haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">summe han (<I>om</I>. For) D.</NOTE> so grete cumbrement</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey may make no testament;</L>
<L>For holy cherche neuer vndyrstode</L>
<L N="2472">To haue of okerer[&euml;]s gode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">han ony of goulerys good D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Seint Forsyne's Visit to Hell.]
<NOTE>[<I>Acta Sanctorum</I>, Jan. iii. 404.&mdash;G. Paris, <I>Hist. Litt. de la France</I>, xxviii. 196.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L><MILESTONE N="17a:2" UNIT="folio">A tale ys tolde of Seynt Forsyne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>wharefor he suffryd onys<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwerfore . . meche D.</NOTE> pyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys sam&euml; tale<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ilke D.</NOTE> telly&thorn; seynt Bede</L>
<L N="2476">yn hys gestys &thorn;at men<NOTE PLACE="foot">gestys men it D.</NOTE> rede.</L>
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> seynt Fursyne had lyued long,</L>
<L>&THORN;yr toke hym &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym took &thorn;anne (<I>om</I>. &thorn;yn) D.</NOTE> an euyl strong;</L>
<L>&THORN;at tym&euml; &thorn;at he wende<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyme wende he al for D.</NOTE> to deye,</L>
<L>Come one to hym and<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er cam an aungel to hym D.</NOTE> &thorn;us gan seye,</L>
<L N="2481">"Rys vp, Fursyne, and go with me!</L>
<L>Merueyl moch&euml; shalt &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil &thorn;ou schalt D.</NOTE> see."</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er he wulde, or he ne wulde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhe&thorn;er he wolde or he nolde D.</NOTE></L>
<L>he toke hym vp, and fur&thorn;e he shulde;</L>
<L N="2485">Many stedys he late<NOTE PLACE="foot">lete O, many a place he lete D.</NOTE> hym se,</L>
<L>Merueylys and grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete &amp; of D.</NOTE> pryuyte;</L>
<L>he shewed hym &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;e OD, <I>om</I>. Harl.</NOTE> depnes of helle,</L>
<L N="2488">And &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at &thorn;eryn dwelle;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ey toke a weye ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">gate ful D.</NOTE> euene,
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>As hym &thorn;oght, toward heuene.</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e fyrmament as &thorn;ey &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Foure fyres he sawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferys hi sagh O, fyrys he saw D.</NOTE> of gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret OD.</NOTE> drede;</L>
<L N="2493">&THORN;es foure fyres<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferys O, fyris wexyn D.</NOTE> wax hygh &amp; hote,</L>
<L>And yn-to one, alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al O, to on of &thorn;o (<I>om</I>. And yn) D.</NOTE> foure &thorn;ey smote.</L>
<L>wndurful<NOTE PLACE="foot">wunderfully D.</NOTE> was &thorn;an &thorn;at fyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fere O, fyr D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dredful, and also<NOTE PLACE="foot">And also dredful, &amp; O, &amp; so dredful D.</NOTE> brynnyng shere.</L>
<L N="2497">&THORN;e aungel &thorn;ydyrward<NOTE PLACE="foot">to hym ward D.</NOTE> toke &thorn;e weye;</L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght seynt Fursyne, 'here shal y deye.'</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungel &yogh;ede fur&thorn; ful boldely,</L>
<L N="2500">But seynt Fursyne durst nat come ny.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungel say<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh O, saw D.</NOTE> he gan abyde,</L>
<L>"Come fur&thorn;e," he seyd, "and &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou D.</NOTE> nat hyde;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ys fere ne drede<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyr drede D.</NOTE> &thorn;e noght,</L>
<L N="2504">But &thorn;ou with wrong euer toke oght;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue take any<NOTE PLACE="foot">any <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng with wrong,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt brenne yn &thorn;ys fyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">brennyn in &thorn;is (<I>om</I>. fyre) D.</NOTE> strong.</L>
<L>with moch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mechil D.</NOTE> &thorn;oght, sorowe, and drede,</L>
<L N="2508">Fursyne vnto &thorn;at fyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fyr D.</NOTE> &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">fere O, fyr D.</NOTE> on bo&thorn;&euml; half hym was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">halue was D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But fur&thorn; he &yogh;ede fast<NOTE PLACE="foot">faste he &yogh;ede fur&thorn; O, (forth) D.</NOTE> on hys pas,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at fyre saghe<NOTE PLACE="foot">fere sagh O, fyr saw D.</NOTE> he lye<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2512">Saulys brennyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">soulys brennende D.</NOTE> and ruly crye;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml;s &yogh;ed&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eden D.</NOTE> hem among,</L>
<L>And fast echone on o&thorn;er &thorn;rong</L>
<L>with brynnyng crokys sorowfuly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hokys dolefully D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2516">And pyned hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">sore pyned hem D.</NOTE> with-oute mercy.</L>
<L>None lay by hemself a-lone,</L>
<L>But eche<NOTE PLACE="foot">ache O, eche D.</NOTE> on o&thorn;er, with sorowe and wone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mone D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Echone<NOTE PLACE="foot">eche D.</NOTE> to o&thorn;er was sorowe and peyne,</L>
<L N="2520">with-outyn end&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is is D.</NOTE> certeyn.</L>
<L>For pynyng, for wepyng, for cryyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-pyned and cryed he seyde D.</NOTE> alas,</L>
<L>Fursyne almoste<NOTE PLACE="foot">ny D.</NOTE> confunded was.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>As he sagh &thorn;ys sorowe so grym,</L>
<L N="2524">Come a deuyl rennyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cam . . rennende D.</NOTE> to hym</L>
<L>with glesyng y&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">e&yogh;yn O, grysly ey&yogh;en &amp; hook D.</NOTE> and croke yn hande,</L>
<L>&THORN;e steme stode oute of hys mou&thorn; brennand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;enande O.</NOTE></L>
<L>he broght on &thorn;at brynnyng croke<NOTE PLACE="foot">kroke O, hook D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2528">A brennyng soule &thorn;at al to-shoke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sore quook D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Toward Fursyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e prist D.</NOTE> he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he OD, hys <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> ran hys cours,</L>
<L>And calyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">kalde O, callyd hym feloun of tretours D.</NOTE> hym 'fals, felun, treytours.'</L>
<L>"haue &thorn;ys soule! &thorn;ys hast &thorn;ou slayn!</L>
<L N="2532">&THORN;ou &yogh;eldyst nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym nat O, &yogh;elde hym now D.</NOTE> hys gode a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>he kast &thorn;e soule vpp-on &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L>And brenned hys o<NOTE PLACE="foot">he brent his oo D.</NOTE> syde, and half hys brest.</L>
<L>he went<NOTE PLACE="foot">wende O.</NOTE> &thorn;at tyme haue deyd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wende &thorn;. t. a be left D.</NOTE> &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="2536">For the soule brennyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at saule brende O, &thorn;at soule hadde brent D.</NOTE> hym so sore;</L>
<L>he hopyde neuer to haue come &thorn;en,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e&thorn;en O, wende . . &thorn;enne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>So had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde O, had D.</NOTE> &thorn;e soule broght hym be-ne&thorn;en.<NOTE PLACE="foot">on brenne D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But at &thorn;e last &thorn;an gan he crye,</L>
<L N="2540"><SUP>17</SUP> And seyd, "mayster, me<SUP>17</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">17_17 mayster D.</NOTE> helpe now, or y dey!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyde &thorn;e aungel to Fursyne:</L>
<L>"y tolde &thorn;e langer of &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">er. &thorn;is is &thorn;i D.</NOTE> &thorn;yne;</L>
<L>y sed langer<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde &thorn;e er D.</NOTE> at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="2544">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haddest of o&thorn;er mennys &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou madest nat of, amend&euml;ment,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys fyre hyt shulde be brent.</L>
<L>loke now, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou kanst hyt oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">can it D.</NOTE> knowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule &thorn;at &thorn;e brenned<NOTE PLACE="foot">brennede O, &thorn;at &thorn;er brent D.</NOTE> so lowe."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e,"<MILESTONE N="17b:2" UNIT="folio"> seyde Fursyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an side &thorn;e prist D.</NOTE> "y knowe hyt wele</L>
<L>For whom<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwom D.</NOTE> y suffre &thorn;ys peyne eche dele:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys he dede, whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> he shuld deye,</L>
<L N="2552">he &yogh;af me a clo&thorn;e for hym to preye;</L>
<L>For no maystry, ne for noun eyuyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">non ille D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>he &yogh;af it me; but with<NOTE PLACE="foot">me be D.</NOTE> hys gode wyl.</L>
<L>And now, weyl y hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; wel I knowe now &amp; D.</NOTE> graunte,</L>
<L N="2556">&THORN;at y helde hym nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">not his (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> cunnaunt;</L>
<L>wyllyng, certys, y dyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede O, a&yogh;ens his wil certis dede he D.</NOTE> hyt noght,</L>
<L>But for rechelesshepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">rentylnesse D.</NOTE> of &thorn;oght."</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungel &thorn;o toke &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at (&thorn;o, <I>om</I>. D.)</NOTE> soule forlore,</L>
<L N="2560">And dyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede OD.</NOTE> hyt &thorn;ere hyt was byfore,</L>
<L>yn-to &thorn;e peyne, &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e, &thorn;ere, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> for to dwelle,&mdash;</L>
<L>hyt was an okerere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he was a gowlere D.</NOTE> y &yogh;ou telle;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an touched Fursynys<NOTE PLACE="foot">touched he Fursyns O, &thorn;e aungel touchyd hym D.</NOTE> brest and syde,</L>
<L N="2564">And &thorn;e fyre my&yogh;t no lenger<NOTE PLACE="foot">no lenger myght O, my&yogh;t no lengere (<I>om</I>. And) D.</NOTE> abyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;urghoute &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;orw &thorn;e fyr he hadde hym D.</NOTE> fyre he ledde hym euene,</L>
<L>And shewed hym of &thorn;e blys of heuene:</L>
<L>he shewed hym alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">of al D.</NOTE> &thorn;e pryuyte</L>
<L N="2568">&THORN;ere men befalle&thorn; yn flessh to be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at men falle . . to se D.</NOTE></L>
<L>he broght hym &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">brout hym D.</NOTE> to &thorn;e body a&yogh;en</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="foot">For, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> to shewe &thorn;at hyt was certeyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;re days kept&euml; men<NOTE PLACE="foot">day&yogh;es men keptyn D.</NOTE> &thorn;e body,</L>
<L N="2572">Alle for ded&euml; comunly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;anne contynuelly D.</NOTE></L>
<L>he lyued se&thorn;&thorn;en many &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>A quyk man, and a feres.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;erys . . fers D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;e brynnyng alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">be O.</NOTE> be dene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss. 'rewe.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="2576">Euermore aftyrward was hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt, <I>om</I>. O, it was D.</NOTE> sene;</L>
<L>As long as he here<NOTE PLACE="foot">longe after as he D.</NOTE> lyued,</L>
<L>&THORN;e brynnyng on hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> body cleued.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>y trowe god shewed &thorn;ys merueyle,</L>
<L N="2580">For &thorn;ou ne shuldest of<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne shust of &thorn;y O, &thorn;at non schulde D.</NOTE> trow&thorn;&euml; fayle.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en leuyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">leuede O, lyuede D.</NOTE> he so holyly</L>
<L>&THORN;at men callyn hym nowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">now O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> seynt Fursy;</L>
<L>He was fyrst<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyrst, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> founder and syre</L>
<L N="2584">Of &thorn;e cherche of Knares<NOTE PLACE="foot">Canyes D.</NOTE>-myre;
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>And of Norwyche &thorn;e modyr cherche</L>
<L>he ded hyt fyrst make and werche;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he ly&thorn; be-&yogh;unde &thorn;e see,<MILESTONE N="18a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2588">he ordeyned a mynster<NOTE PLACE="foot">mynstyr O, mynstre D, mynyster H.</NOTE> for to be;</L>
<L>Foure &yogh;ere or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar O, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;e cherche were ful set<NOTE PLACE="foot">was endyd D.</NOTE></L>
<L>was hys soul&euml; to god<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuene O, or h. s. was to heuene sendyd D.</NOTE> fet.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Okerers men oght to weyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gouleris owyn for to whyue D.; <I>O</I>. gloss 'fle.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="2592">&YOGH;eue hem noght, ne of hem receyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if hym nou&yogh;t ne not retyue D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou wet&euml; what &thorn;ey are,<NOTE PLACE="foot">OD. transpose these lines. In 2593, D reads 'qwat &thorn;ei ware.'</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>yn no manere of chaffare.<NOTE PLACE="foot">OD. transpose these lines. In 2593, D reads 'qwat &thorn;ei ware.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sum tyme &thorn;er was yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sumtyme was D.</NOTE> a cyte,</L>
<L N="2596">&THORN;at &yogh;yf an okerer<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if ony goulere &thorn;erin D.</NOTE> my&yogh;t founde<NOTE PLACE="foot">founden O.</NOTE> be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey helde hym vyler<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyldyn hym wers D.</NOTE> &thorn;an a Iew,</L>
<L>For no man wuld&euml; hys prew;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'profyte,' held hem but on-trew D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men clepyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">callyd D.</NOTE> hys hous yn euery strete</L>
<L N="2600">'&THORN;e hous of &thorn;e fend&euml;s sete.'</L>
<L>Fyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fer O, &thorn;e fer &amp; D.</NOTE> watyr, &thorn;at he shuld note,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'okepye.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey cursed hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> euery grote;</L>
<L>And euery syde to ou&thorn;er, "sere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">men seyde to o&thorn;er sone D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2604">lo, &thorn;ere &thorn;e cursed vsurere!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhere &thorn;e cursyd goulere come D.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn cherch&euml; no man &yogh;af<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue D.</NOTE> hym pes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'pax.'</NOTE></L>
<L>For a fend &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">men D.</NOTE> hym ches.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>No man was so hardy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2608">To bryng hym &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">bryngyn hym good D.</NOTE> opunly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne shulde vyly<NOTE PLACE="foot">but &thorn;at he schulde opynly D.</NOTE> be shent</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at by &thorn;e stret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stret O, strete D.</NOTE> went.</L>
<L>And whan any vsurere<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwhan a goulere D.</NOTE> was dede,</L>
<L N="2612">&THORN;e cherch&euml;&yogh;erde &thorn;ey hym forbede.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey wuld nat, for loue ne awe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'drede.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hym crystyn mennys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyn . . mannys D.</NOTE> lawe;</L>
<L>'Requiem' ne shulde be note<NOTE PLACE="foot">wy&thorn; note O, r. schulde noon D.</NOTE> be sunge</L>
<L N="2616">Ne seyd for hym, wy&thorn; mannys tunge.</L>
<L>'Lux perpetua,' and he, were wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="foot">For, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> yn hys lyue he solde hem bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>A ny&yogh;t, when men hadde here<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwen men holde D.</NOTE> reste,</L>
<L N="2621">he okered pens yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">goulyd pens he put in (<I>om</I>. He) D.</NOTE> cheste;</L>
<L>And also, vpp<NOTE PLACE="foot">vpp, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE>-on &thorn;e day ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>he gadered gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">pens D.</NOTE> with alle hys my&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="2623">&THORN;an semy&thorn; hyt weyl yn oure lay</L>
<L>&THORN;at he solde<NOTE PLACE="foot">he selli&thorn; (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e &thorn;e ny&yogh;t and &thorn;e day;</L>
<L>'Requiem,' (&thorn;e reste with outen ende,)<MILESTONE N="18a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ar-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;at D.</NOTE> shal he neuer wende;</L>
<L>Ne 'lux perpetua'<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. p. ne D.</NOTE>&mdash;&thorn;e endles ly&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L N="2628">&THORN;er-of shal he neuer haue sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>where<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er D.</NOTE> he ys wur&thorn;y, &thorn;er shal he be;</L>
<L>yn hym nas neuer no<NOTE PLACE="foot">founde D.</NOTE> charyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;eft haue we<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an haue I D.</NOTE> seyd,</L>
<L N="2632">And &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O, of &thorn;ese gouleris D.</NOTE> vsurers made vp-breyde.</L>
<L>god &yogh;eue vs grac&euml; &thorn;efte to fle,</L>
<L>And al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle O.</NOTE> okerers wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylle D, alle gouleris, euele mote &thorn;ei be D.</NOTE> to amendyd be.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Eighth Commandment.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Non loquaris contra proximum falsum testi|monium:&middot; &para; Octauum mandatum D.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;e eyt&thorn;&euml; wyl we speke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Telle we now of &thorn;e ey&yogh;ttande D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at fals sysours vse moste to breke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">han most in hande D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2637">'&THORN;ous halt no fals wytnes bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn euene crystyn for to dere.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'harme.</NOTE></L>
<L>who-so with hys mou&thorn;e, one,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; how &thorn;at w. his mouth D.</NOTE> seys,</L>
<L>And with hys herte &thorn;enke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;enk&thorn; O, &thorn;inki&thorn; o&thorn;er D.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er weys,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>he ys wur&thorn;y to be shent,</L>
<L>For a do&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>D'.s order is</I> l. 2644, 2643, 2642, 2641; ho so do D.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens &thorn;ys comaundment.</L>
<L>But many one &thorn;at are<NOTE PLACE="foot">But man on er&thorn;e D.</NOTE> &thorn;us fykyl</L>
<L N="2644">Synnyn nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat alle, synnyth not only she O.</NOTE> ylych&euml; mykyl;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'moche.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor behoue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">it behouyth.</NOTE> be tolde &thorn;e skyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">skylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>As holy men seyn vs tyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyll O, seyn it wel D, <I>O</I>. gloss 'to.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>who-so beleuy&thorn; a wycches<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle a fals D.</NOTE> sawe,</L>
<L N="2648">he bere&thorn; wytnes a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>Swyche wycches<NOTE PLACE="foot">suych wikke D.</NOTE> are for to weyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'fle.'</NOTE></L>
<L>For many men &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">it D.</NOTE> wyl dysceyue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">deseyue O.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Some men<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; summe D.</NOTE> wytnessen a lesyng</L>
<L N="2652">For non&euml; ou&thorn;er wynnyng</L>
<L>But for to begyle sum man &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt delyte hym, grete ys &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;if &thorn;ou dely&yogh;t it meche. synne D.</NOTE> synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On ou&thorn;er manere synnen<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne O, on o&thorn;er halue &yogh;it summe (<I>om</I>. synnen) D.</NOTE> sum</L>
<L N="2656">&THORN;at make&thorn; lesyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">makyn lesynges O, maken lesyngis D.</NOTE> &thorn;urgh custum</L>
<L>To plese<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-peyre D.</NOTE> &thorn;e folk yn rybaudy:</L>
<L>&THORN;at y halde no synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">calle no s. but D.</NOTE> dedly,</L>
<L N="2659">But &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">But &yogh;yf &thorn;ey OD.</NOTE> haue &thorn;eryn delyte;</L>
<L>&THORN;an mow &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">mayst &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> synne dedely ful tyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'sone.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sum vs&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vse as O, ly&yogh;en also D.</NOTE> for curtesye</L>
<L>To speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at spekyn D.</NOTE> nobly, and &yogh;yt wyl lye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey synn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou synnyst &yogh;it D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;at feyre spekyng<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2664">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou D.</NOTE> haue delyt yn &thorn;at lesyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And some lye o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; summe ly&yogh;en D.</NOTE> more or lesse,</L>
<L>To preyse one bettere &thorn;an he es;<NOTE PLACE="foot">preysen . . . isse D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swyche lesyng ys nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesyng ys nat D, a lesynge is nat ful HO.</NOTE> grete folye</L>
<L N="2668">But &thorn;ey hyt vs&euml; comunly.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And som&euml; lye<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; summe ly&yogh;en D.</NOTE> as &thorn;ey were wode</L>
<L>For men shuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">a man shulde O, &thorn;at . . &yogh;euyn (<I>om</I>. sum) D.</NOTE> &yogh;yu&euml; hem sum gode,</L>
<L>And seyn &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. Harl., he O.</NOTE> ha&thorn; do so or<NOTE PLACE="foot">sei&thorn; &thorn;at he dede O.</NOTE> so</L>
<L N="2672">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t neuer come-to to do.<NOTE PLACE="foot">come &thorn;erto D.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;ogh no man haue &thorn;er-of euyl,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yt ys hyt O, &yogh;it it is a D.</NOTE> &thorn;e tycement of &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L N="2675">No lesyng ys with-out&euml; synne,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;er ys algate, sum plyght &thorn;erynne<NOTE PLACE="foot">plyght ynne O, &thorn;owh a man &thorn;erfore no &thorn;ing wynne D.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Al aftyr &thorn;at &thorn;e lesyng ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">es O (&thorn;at, <I>om</I>. D).</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum ys more, and sum ys les.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But some<NOTE PLACE="foot">sum O, summe m. synnyn D.</NOTE> men synn&euml; greuusly</L>
<L N="2680">yn &thorn;ys comaundment so hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hy&yogh; D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of grete &thorn;yng fals<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> wytnes beryn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar to-also<NOTE PLACE="foot">also, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> grete o&thorn;ys sweryn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">bere . . suere D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2683">Swyche synn&euml; greue&thorn; now<NOTE PLACE="foot">regnyth now ry&yogh;t D.</NOTE> mekyl,</L>
<L>For many one are bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">many on is D.</NOTE> fals and fykyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or D.</NOTE> for loue, or for awe,</L>
<L>Wyl men swere falsly<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals D.</NOTE> a sawe,</L>
<L>And bere wytnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">beryn a witnesse.</NOTE> of swyche a fals</L>
<L N="2688">To make a man hang<NOTE PLACE="foot">don . . hangen D.</NOTE> be &thorn;e hals.<NOTE PLACE="inter">nek (<I>O</I>. necke)</NOTE></L>
<L>God ha&thorn; sent for swyche veniaunce,</L>
<L>But many trusten of long<NOTE PLACE="foot">lange O, on long D.</NOTE> suffraunce.</L>
<L>Men hope so moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">hopyn so meche D.</NOTE> hys mercy to,</L>
<L N="2692">&THORN;at some neuer recche what<NOTE PLACE="foot">not rekke qwat D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey do.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e wys man sey&thorn; yn hys lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'techyng.'</NOTE></L>
<L>'&THORN;at here synne ys moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">he synnyth meche D.</NOTE> &thorn;e more</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">he.</NOTE> synne custummably</L>
<L N="2696">yn &thorn;e hope of hys mercy.'</L>
<L>Y shal &yogh;ou tell&euml; how hyt fore<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a man &thorn;at hym forswore.
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="96"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Tale of the Rich Forswearer at a Trial in London.]</HEAD>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">narracio D.</NOTE>Yn Londun toune fyl swyche a chek,</L>
<L>A ryche man and pore<NOTE PLACE="foot">a pore O, a pore weryn D.</NOTE> were at cuntek,<NOTE PLACE="inter">debate</NOTE></L>
<L N="2701">And pleted<NOTE PLACE="foot">motedyn D.</NOTE> a-boute a lytyl land<MILESTONE N="18b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tyl a day was take yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">on D.</NOTE> hand;</L>
<L>&thorn;at day was so ny[e]<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyghe O, ny D.</NOTE> dreue</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e othe was to &thorn;e ryche man &yogh;yue:<NOTE PLACE="foot">dreuyn . . . &yogh;euyn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2705">wytnes &thorn;ey all&euml; gan hym bere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wuld[&euml;] falsly<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ei woldyn for hym D.</NOTE> swere;</L>
<L>For rych&euml; men are hold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">arn holdyn D.</NOTE> trewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh here falsnes be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be her falsnesse (<I>om</I>. &thorn;ogh) D.</NOTE> neuer so newe.</L>
<L N="2709">whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> he was charged &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne shulde, for loue ne eye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">say . . ay D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for lef&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">No for lef O, ne f. lef D.</NOTE> no for lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="2712">But trew[&euml;]ly to<NOTE PLACE="foot">schulde D.</NOTE> swere hys o&thorn;e;</L>
<L>A-nou&thorn;er &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">but a no&thorn;er D.</NOTE> was yn hys &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="foot">For, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> falshede he wlde haue fur&thorn; bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And God toke veniaunce apertly,</L>
<L N="2716">&THORN;at alle hyt say &thorn;at stode<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>om</I>. For) alle it sey&yogh;en . . stodyn D.</NOTE> hym by.</L>
<L>For whan he hadde hys o&thorn;&euml; swore,</L>
<L>And kest<NOTE PLACE="foot">kessid D.</NOTE> &thorn;e boke hem alle before,</L>
<L>Vp ne ros he neuer more,</L>
<L N="2720">But, lay dede befor hem &thorn;ore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fil doun ded hem alle be-fore D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an y trowe &thorn;at y dar<NOTE PLACE="foot">I dar wel (<I>om</I>. &thorn;at) D.</NOTE> seye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &yogh;ede an euyl weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;ys tale, &yogh;e mowe se alle</L>
<L N="2724">&THORN;at fals sweryng wyl euyl befalle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of f. s. w. e. falle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Namlyche, on &thorn;e halydom<NOTE PLACE="foot">namely vp-on &thorn;e holydom D.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan he ys charged of any<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan . . ony D.</NOTE> whom.
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>Vndyrstand &thorn;ys weyl yn &thorn;y wyt,</L>
<L N="2728">&THORN;at god sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e holy wryt,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at fals o&thorn;ys, ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; D.</NOTE> wrong Iugement,</L>
<L>Shul neuer mor&euml; be vnshent.'</L>
<L>Se how veniaunce was hys mede</L>
<L N="2732">whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> he hadde of God no drede:</L>
<L>Almyghty God,<NOTE PLACE="foot">God OD, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;at ys so&thorn;fastnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sothfast is D.</NOTE></L>
<L>h&eacute; wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde haue O, wolde haue takyn D.</NOTE> take to fals wytnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fals sweryng ys nat ellys to say,</L>
<L>But 'forsakyng of god, and alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> hys lay.'</L>
<L N="2737">A man &thorn;at swere&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">swer&thorn; O.</NOTE> fals swerynges,</L>
<L>He forsake&thorn; fyu&euml; &thorn;ynges:<NOTE PLACE="foot">sueryng . . &thorn;ing D.</NOTE> &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioye of heuene he forsake&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">forsak&thorn; O.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[I]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="19a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2740">whan he, wetyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan he wetende D.</NOTE> fals o&thorn;ys make&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mak&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle hys blessyd cumpanye</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey hym neuer helpe &yogh;yf &thorn;at he lye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei helpyn hym neuere &yogh;yf he ly&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Ihesu crystys passyun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[II]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2744">&thorn;at for hym to &thorn;e de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to dethe D.</NOTE> was doun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hyt helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at helpith D.</NOTE> hym neuer at<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn O.</NOTE> nede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he swere fals, or falsdom<NOTE PLACE="foot">fals doom D.</NOTE> bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydd&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;redde ys O.</NOTE> &yogh;yf he swer&euml; fals,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[III]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2748">hys crystendom he forsak&thorn; als,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'also.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at hyt helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">helpith D.</NOTE> hym neuer more</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at he ly&euml; &thorn;ore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ly&yogh;e of &thorn;at he ha&thorn; swore D.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">vour&thorn;e O, fer&thorn;e D (<I>om</I>. ys).</NOTE> ys, he forsake&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">forsak&thorn; O, forsaki&thorn; D.</NOTE> &thorn;e preyers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[IV]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2752">&thorn;at holy wryt wytnes of beres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bers O, cherche wytnesse berys D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey neuer stonde hym by</L>
<L>&yogh;yf he swere hys o&thorn;e falsly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyue&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyf&thorn;e O, fyfte D.</NOTE> &thorn;yng wyl hym shende,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[V]</NOTE></L>
<L>For he &yogh;yf&thorn;e hym self wy&thorn;-oute[n]<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>om</I>. For) &yogh;euyth . . outtyn D.</NOTE> ende</L>
<L N="2757">To &thorn;e fende &thorn;at ys yn helle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at he lye, or falsly telle.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>On &thorn;ese fyue maners hymself<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyses hym self he D.</NOTE> dery&thorn;</L>
<L N="2760">&thorn;at on &thorn;e bok&euml; falsly swery&thorn;.</L>
<L>For hys loue &thorn;at deyde on<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;at deyde vp-on D.</NOTE> &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>Forswere &yogh;ow neuer for worldys<NOTE PLACE="foot">forsuerith &yogh;ow not for wordis D.</NOTE> gode.</L>
<L>For &yogh;e wyte weyl, aud haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;e wetyn it wel &amp; han D.</NOTE> hyt herde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at trou&thorn;e ys more &thorn;an alle &thorn;e worlde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">word D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2765">&YOGH;yt &thorn;er ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">is &thorn;er D.</NOTE> ano&thorn;er sweryng</L>
<L>where-&thorn;urgh com&thorn; oft&euml; grete cumbryng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">cumberynge O, &thorn;er &thorn;orw comyth gret coum|bryng D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e whyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> ys, an o&thorn;e oute of mesure,</L>
<L N="2768">&THORN;at he shulde haue a mysauenture</L>
<L>On wyf&euml;, and on chylde, to<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyf &amp; child &thorn;at schulde D.</NOTE> falle,</L>
<L>And on hys ou&thorn;er godys alle,</L>
<L>But he hold&euml; at hys myght</L>
<L N="2772">hys o&thorn;e &thorn;at he swere&thorn; to alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">swer&thorn; to al O, oth he sueri&thorn; it is al D.</NOTE> ryght.</L>
<L>Swyche an o&thorn;e ys grete doute<NOTE PLACE="foot">it is dou&yogh;tte D.</NOTE> to swere,</L>
<L>For chaunc&euml; com&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">chaunsis comyn D.</NOTE> on many manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou settest &thorn;y chylde to mych&euml; rew&thorn;e</L>
<L N="2776">But &thorn;ou holde &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn O, &thorn;in oth with D.</NOTE> o&thorn;e to trew&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-nou&thorn;er oth com&thorn; &yogh;yt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;it comyth D.</NOTE> yn place,<MILESTONE N="19a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> a man swere&thorn; by fallace.</L>
<L>Fallace ys, as who seye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ho sei&thorn; D.</NOTE> 'gyle,'</L>
<L N="2780">As many one sweryn vmwhyle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'sum tyme;' sum qwyle D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou swere to me for oght,</L>
<L>And a-nou&thorn;er ys yn &thorn;y &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>wenyst &thorn;ou &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou swerest wel</L>
<L>when<NOTE PLACE="foot">when, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;yn oth to me ys gyle eche del?</L>
<L N="2785">Nay: for,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; (<I>om</I>. Nay) D.</NOTE> as y vndyrstande of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>So shal &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn O, &thorn;in oth D.</NOTE> as oth&euml; charged be.</L>
<L>&THORN;us techy&thorn; vs seynt Austyne</L>
<L N="2788">&THORN;at was a clerk of gret dyuyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret D, <I>om</I>. HO.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y pray &yogh;ow alle, bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> lefe and lo&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e charge neuer body<NOTE PLACE="foot">chargyn non D.</NOTE> with o&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e suppose wyl be forswore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hopyn . . . forsuorn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2792">For, y warne &yogh;ow wel byfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;erof I w. &yogh;. alle be-forn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; D.</NOTE> who-so putte&thorn; hym to swere,</L>
<L>Grete charg&euml; for hym shal he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he schal D.</NOTE> bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou madest awhere any<NOTE PLACE="foot">euere ony D.</NOTE> vowe</L>
<L N="2796">To wurschyp God for &thorn;y prowe,&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest O, dedist for g. w. D.</NOTE> hyt with &thorn;y gode wylle,</L>
<L>with-out&euml; stresse<NOTE PLACE="foot">out distresse D.</NOTE> or ou&thorn;er ylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art holde to &yogh;elde hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">holdyn to &yogh;eldyn it D.</NOTE> hym</L>
<L N="2800">Or &thorn;y synne ys grete and grym;</L>
<L>wytnes of oth&euml; and of hote:<NOTE PLACE="foot">of o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;in hot D.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">vowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">a vow O.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>Yn heuene, all&euml; &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yngis D.</NOTE> &thorn;ey wote.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>No&thorn;eles, y sey hardly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e hardily D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2804">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou vowe to do foly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a vowe . . . foly&yogh;e D.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="foot">As O, <I>om</I>. Harl. D.</NOTE> a man to bete or<NOTE PLACE="foot">beten or to D.</NOTE> slo,</L>
<L>Or to take hys gode hym fro;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou vowe yn &yogh;ung&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;un&thorn;e O, &yogh;ung&thorn;e D.</NOTE> or elde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou mayst nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">not may D.</NOTE> but wykkedly &yogh;elde,&mdash;</L>
<L N="2809">God wyl nat &thorn;ou hold yt so</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;y vowe yn wykkednes do;</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; leuer &thorn;ou &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ou D.</NOTE> <SUP>20</SUP>wy&thorn;drow</L>
<L N="2812">&THORN;an do<NOTE PLACE="foot">do, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> euyl dede after foly vow,</L>
<L>Bettere ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys . . be, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> a foly wrde be<SUP>20</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">20_20 <I>Harl</I>. omit these two lines.</NOTE> wy&thorn;drawe</L>
<L>&THORN;an wy&thorn; euyl dede to fulfyl &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i (<I>om</I>. wy&thorn;) D.</NOTE> sawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">be D.</NOTE> goddys wurd yn &thorn;e gospel,</L>
<L N="2816">&THORN;ys may be preuyd ry&yogh;t wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Bible-story of John the Baptist's Death.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Mark vi</I>. 22-28]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Hyt speketh<NOTE PLACE="foot">spek&thorn; O, &thorn;er it speki&thorn; D.</NOTE> of seynt Ion<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ioon O, Ioh D.</NOTE> baptyst,<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e best chylde bor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">best barn D.</NOTE> vndyr Cryst.
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Hyt telle&thorn; &thorn;at Eroud<NOTE PLACE="foot">he telli&thorn; &thorn;at herodis D.</NOTE> swore<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L N="2820">To here &thorn;at tumbled<NOTE PLACE="foot">sayled D.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e flore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at what-aseuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwat D.</NOTE> she wuld aske to mede,</L>
<L>he wuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">schulde D.</NOTE> fulfyl hyt here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here O, hire D, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> yn dede;</L>
<L>halfe hys kyngdom, &yogh;yf she wuld craue,</L>
<L N="2824">haluyndele<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hauyndele O, halfuendel (<I>om</I>. hyt) D.</NOTE> she shuld hyt haue.</L>
<L>Eueyl he vowed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er he a vowed D.</NOTE> and swore hys oth,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for with hym ys now god wroth.</L>
<L>For ou&thorn;er mede wuld she haue none,</L>
<L N="2828">But &thorn;e hede of swete seynt Ion;</L>
<L>Here modyr bade here ask&euml; &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hede of seynt Ion<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ioon O, Ioh D.</NOTE> yn a dyssh.</L>
<L>Folylyche, certeyn, Eroud<NOTE PLACE="foot">herodis he (<I>om</I>. certeyn) D.</NOTE> swore,</L>
<L N="2832">And yn dede weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e D.</NOTE> werse he fore.<NOTE PLACE="inter">dede</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;yf she hade asked Eroudes ye,</L>
<L>Troust &thorn;ou he wuld nat a<NOTE PLACE="foot">trust &thorn;erto he schulde haue D.</NOTE> made a lye?</L>
<L>Y trowe he wulde haue be forswore<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha be forsworn D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2836">Ar he hade hys ye forlore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">or . . y&yogh;e lorn D.</NOTE></L>
<L>So had hym better,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be better O, were he b. D.</NOTE> for hys prowe,</L>
<L>For to haue broke &thorn;at ych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">brokyn hys D.</NOTE> vowe,</L>
<L>And with-oute mede haue late here<NOTE PLACE="foot">a letyn hir D.</NOTE> go,</L>
<L N="2840">&THORN;an for hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at D.</NOTE> vowe a man do<NOTE PLACE="foot">do O, to D.</NOTE> slo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt may y preue hyt by<NOTE PLACE="foot">prouyn it be D.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er sawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at wryte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wreten D.</NOTE> ys yn &thorn;e old&euml; lawe;</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e gest of syre Iept&euml;,</L>
<L N="2844">Yn &thorn;e byble men mow hyt se.
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="101"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[&thorn;e Gest of Syre Jepte, &mdash; or the Tale of Jephthah and his Daughter.<NOTE PLACE="foot">narracio D.</NOTE>]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Judges</I> xv. 30-39.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Iept&euml; went onys to batayle</L>
<L>And preyd God<NOTE PLACE="foot">he preyed D.</NOTE> hys powere shuld nat fayle;&mdash;</L>
<L>"Graunte me, Lorde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. (not D) inserts 'he seyde.'</NOTE> &thorn;e maystry nowe,</L>
<L N="2848">And y shal make to &thorn;e a vowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e fyrst &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yng O, &thorn;ing D, <I>Harl</I>. omits.</NOTE> &thorn;at y mete</L>
<L>Befor me homward yn &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof shal y make sacryfyse;"</L>
<L N="2852">For to sle hyt, was &thorn;an &thorn;e asyse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e god. with good a-vyce D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwan D.</NOTE> he had, &thorn;urgh goddys vertu,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e batayle prys and pru,</L>
<L>Homward as syre Iept&euml; &yogh;ede<MILESTONE N="19b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2856">he &thorn;anked god for<NOTE PLACE="foot">of D.</NOTE> hys gode dede.</L>
<L>hys doghtyr was &thorn;e fyrst&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferste D, fyrst HO.</NOTE> &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&thorn;at mette hym and made hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> welcomyng;</L>
<L>She grette here fadyr fayre with mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>And made hym all<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym all, <I>om</I>. D.</NOTE> &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at she cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="2861">&THORN;an &thorn;oght Iept&euml; on<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou&yogh;tte . . . of D.</NOTE> hys vow,</L>
<L>And hadde yn herte<NOTE PLACE="foot">In herte he made D.</NOTE> sorow ynow.</L>
<L>To hys doghtyr &thorn;an seyd he,</L>
<L N="2864">"&THORN;ou art deseyuyd, and y for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Y made my<NOTE PLACE="foot">a D.</NOTE> vow to heuene kyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at y shuld sle &thorn;e fyrst&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferste D, fyrst HO.</NOTE> &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at y mette homwarde fro &thorn;e batayle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">h. be the way D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2868">And my vow y wyl nat fayle."<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; myn a-vow me muste holde ay D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys doghtyr answered myldly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">myldely D.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Fadyr," she seyde, "y am redy</L>
<L>For to take my de&thorn;e of<NOTE PLACE="foot">for D.</NOTE> &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="2872">But y am glade &thorn;at y &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow D.</NOTE> se.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>But, swet&euml; fadyr, y pray &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">D. puts this line after 2874, and reads, 'Now s. f. I &yogh;ow prey&yogh;e.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Graunte me two mone&thorn;es ar y dye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">or I dey&yogh;e D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at y may wepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">wepyn D.</NOTE> my virginite</L>
<L N="2876">with hem &thorn;at noryst be<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn O, weryn norysched D.</NOTE> with me."</L>
<L>Here fadyr graunted weyl &thorn;arto,</L>
<L>And she forso&thorn;&euml; ded ry&yogh;t so;</L>
<L>She wept&euml; nat for any<NOTE PLACE="foot">non D.</NOTE> outrage,</L>
<L N="2880">But for of here come<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at of hem cam D.</NOTE> no lynage;</L>
<L>&THORN;at no fruyt of here my&yogh;t spryng,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for she mad&euml; here wepyng,</L>
<L>And for here fadyr had chylder<NOTE PLACE="foot">childryn D.</NOTE> no mo</L>
<L N="2884">&THORN;at fur&thorn;er my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;t fer&thorn;ere D.</NOTE> yn kynd&euml; go.</L>
<L>But, ry&yogh;t &aacute;t &thorn;e mone&thorn;es ende,</L>
<L>here fadyr dede nat &thorn;erof<NOTE PLACE="foot">as &thorn;e D.</NOTE> hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hys own&euml; doghtyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at his owyn child D.</NOTE> slowe</L>
<L N="2888">For a foly and a wykked vowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">foly wikkyd a-vow D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Austyne sey&thorn; certeynly</L>
<L>&THORN;at he synned ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful D.</NOTE> dedly;</L>
<L N="2891">For he auowede, and nedyd naght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght O, &amp; trust not D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;yt yn dede wel werse he wroght.</L>
<L>Seynt Austyn sey&thorn; so<NOTE PLACE="foot">a D.</NOTE> redy wey<MILESTONE N="20a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y to &yogh;ou dar<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &yogh;ow &thorn;at dar I. [The Dulwich fragment stops with 1. 2894, and the catchwords at foot, '&yogh;oure wikkid vowys.']</NOTE> weyl seye</L>
<L>'&YOGH;oure wykked vowys shul &yogh;e nat fylle,</L>
<L N="2896">Ne make no vowe to any ylle,</L>
<L>But chaung&euml; hem to better prow,</L>
<L>And take penaunce for foly vowe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God shelde vs alle wykkedly to swere,</L>
<L N="2900">And late vs neuer fals wytnes bere,</L>
<L>Ne foly vow for to make,</L>
<L>lord&euml;, for &thorn;y wurschyp<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshepe O.</NOTE> sake.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. adds 'Amen.'</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment"><PB REF="00000111.tif" N="103">
<HEAD>[The Ninth Commandment.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The nyn&thorn;e comaundment yn oure tellyng</L>
<L>Ys "coueyt nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> &thorn;y neghbours &thorn;yng,"</L>
<L N="2905">For to reue hyt hym wykkedly</L>
<L>with wrong pleys or ou&thorn;er maystry,</L>
<L>No with glosyng, no with queyntyse,</L>
<L N="2908">No wy&thorn; destress&euml;, on noun wyse,</L>
<L>No wy&thorn; wykked procurement,</L>
<L>To make hym lese hys tenement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for hyt ha&thorn; &thorn;e same assyse</L>
<L N="2912">&THORN;at longe&thorn; vn-to coueytyse,</L>
<L>y wyl now ouer-lepe hyt here,</L>
<L>And aftyrwarde &yogh;e mowe hyt lere</L>
<L>whan y speke of &thorn;e dedly synne</L>
<L N="2916">Of coueytyse, hyt ys &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>For hyt ys one of &thorn;e seuene,</L>
<L>Among hem y wyl hyt neuene;</L>
<L>And of hys spycys telle &yogh;ow neyde,</L>
<L>As holy man<NOTE PLACE="foot">men.</NOTE> haue wryten<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrete.</NOTE> and seyde.</L>
<L N="2921">Of &thorn;ys nyn&thorn;e wyl y end&euml; now,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e ten&thorn;&euml; speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle.</NOTE> to &yogh;ow.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="commandment">
<HEAD>[The Tenth Commandment.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The ten&thorn;e comaundment ys, "by &thorn;y lyfe</L>
<L N="2924">Coueyt&euml; nat &thorn;y neghburs wyfe."</L>
<L>And &thorn;ys ys now a comun synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at many on&euml; fallyn ynne,</L>
<L>For almost hyt ys euery-whore</L>
<L>A gentyl man ha&thorn; a wyfe and a hore;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[All future various readings are from O.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="104"></L>
<L N="2929">And wyu&euml;s haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">hauen.</NOTE> now comunly</L>
<L>here husbondys and a ludby.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn euery place now mow men se<MILESTONE N="20a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2932">&THORN;e wyfe wyl gladly &thorn;e mayster be;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf she onys &thorn;e maystry<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e maystry onys.</NOTE> wynne</L>
<L>Alle new&euml; lawys she wyl bygynne;</L>
<L>For &thorn;an wyl she make hyt alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an maky&thorn; she hyt al.</NOTE> newe,</L>
<L N="2936">And bygynne&thorn; to be a shrewe;</L>
<L>And whan she ha&thorn; wune<NOTE PLACE="foot">wnne.</NOTE> &thorn;e maystry</L>
<L>Oure syre ys noght but 'veyes moy sy.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cp. <I>Ves me ci</I> tot en ta bont&eacute; De faire volon|t&eacute;. <I>Roman de Dolopatos</I> (in Roquefort).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an wyl folys fonde and fare<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'go.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="2940">To chep&euml; &thorn;e wyuys chaffare.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;e wyfe lestene here<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'here.'</NOTE> lore,</L>
<L>here wurschyp ys lost for euer more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. euery more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us wyl bygynn&euml; wykked lyfe</L>
<L N="2944">To coueyte a-no&thorn;er mannys wyfe;</L>
<L>For no man ful comunly</L>
<L>Beseche&thorn; a wyf&euml; of foly,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ere &thorn;e wyf&euml; ys aboute,</L>
<L N="2948">&THORN;e god&euml; man, for to stoute.</L>
<L>Y dar no mor&euml; telle for drede</L>
<L>Of vnkynd&euml; wyuys hede;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, y haue grete skylle</L>
<L N="2952">To sey mor&euml; &thorn;an y wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer, &thorn;at &thorn;ou wystyst,</L>
<L>A-nou&thorn;er mannys wyf&euml; kystyst,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;aue here &yogh;yft for &thorn;at enchesoun</L>
<L N="2956">&THORN;at sum synn&euml; myght be doun;</L>
<L>&THORN;an as yn &thorn;e, &thorn;ou fallyst yn synne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou to foly wuldest here wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;ys foly haunte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syll</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2960">Ou&thorn;er mennys wyuys for to daunte,</L>
<L>yn foly wurdys, or yn foly play,</L>
<L>yn vntyme, be ny&yogh;t or day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here herte to &thorn;e myght tourne,</L>
<L N="2964">And late of here husbunde skorne,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e &thorn;ou synnest &thorn;er dedly
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou lygge neuer here by.</L>
<L>By foly wurdys mow men a fole kenne;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'knowe.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;urgh blast of mou&thorn;e &thorn;e fyre wyl brenne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2969">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer dedyst &thorn;y myght<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A womman to tylle with foly syght,</L>
<L>As men haunt&euml; now alle day,</L>
<L N="2972">To hau&euml; glysyng y&yogh;en and gay,</L>
<L>A weddyd wyfe y &thorn;e forbede,</L>
<L>For, &thorn;at ys most for to drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest euer.</NOTE> letter sende</L>
<L>To weddyd wyfe, or wrote or kende;</L>
<L N="2977">Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. inserts 'euer.'</NOTE> letter bare,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou were &thorn;erof weyl ware,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt were ou&thorn;er mennys synne</L>
<L N="2980">&YOGH;yt art &thorn;ou part&aacute;ble &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys comaundment &thorn;at ys &thorn;e ten&thorn;e,</L>
<L>wylle y no lenger drawe or<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> leng&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For yn &thorn;e syxt&euml; &thorn;er y spake,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 58-73]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2984">y touched of &thorn;ys ych&euml; lake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;ys ten wylle we lete,</L>
<L>And speke of ou&thorn;er synnys grete;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. adds '&THORN;at ys to sey&euml;, of &thorn;e seuene, How &thorn;ey forbarre &thorn;e blys of heuene.'</NOTE></L>
<L>God graunte vs grac&euml; so to sey</L>
<L N="2988">Of trou&thorn;e to shew&euml; &thorn;e ry&yogh;t weye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. has 'Here begynne &thorn;e s. d. synnys.'</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[The Seven Deadly Sins;&mdash;and first of Pride.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;e seuene wyl we telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ben &thorn;e dedly doghters of helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eldyst, men kall&euml; pryde;</L>
<L N="2992">She was &thorn;e fyrst &thorn;at walkyd wyde</L>
<L>Yn euery land, to euery man,
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>&THORN;urgh alle &thorn;e worlde, ouer alle she ran,</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; here<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> gete many wonynges,</L>
<L N="2996">Specyally wy&thorn; grete lordynges,</L>
<L>And with ou&thorn;er many ynowe;</L>
<L>For where<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er.</NOTE> she ys, he wylle nat bowe,</L>
<L>She wyl be mayster ouer hem alle;</L>
<L N="3000">And alle at onys she make&thorn; hem falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fadyr of pryde &thorn;at fyrst here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here O, hem H.</NOTE> knew</L>
<L>To hell&euml; pyt she down hym threw;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at are of here coueyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">couyne, glossed 'cumpany.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3004">Alle she brynge&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bryn&thorn;.</NOTE> to hell&euml; peyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor y wylle warn&euml; &yogh;ow<MILESTONE N="20b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whare-yn she make&thorn; &yogh;ow synne, and how,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mowe parceyue vmwhyle</L>
<L N="3008">Yn what &thorn;yng she do&thorn; &yogh;ow gyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e fyrst &thorn;at y fynde</L>
<L>Vnbuxumnesse a&yogh;ens &thorn;y kynde;<NOTE PLACE="inter">fadyr &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>O</I>. or]</NOTE> modyr,</NOTE></L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ys vnbuxum al</L>
<L N="3012">A&yogh;ens hys fadyr spiritual,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spyrytual.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sette&thorn; hym ry&yogh;t at &thorn;e leste,</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; 'prut for &thorn;y cursyng, prest!'</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &yogh;ou speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">spekst.</NOTE> foule wrdys or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>.</NOTE> rowe,</L>
<L N="3016">And to &thorn;y souereyn wylt &thorn;at bowe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;y prout wurdys make hym wroth,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou neuer so lefe no loth,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest &thorn;er gretly<NOTE PLACE="foot">gretly &thorn;er.</NOTE> yn pryde,</L>
<L>Man or<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;er.</NOTE> womman, whe&thorn;er hyt betyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3021">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou, o&thorn;er man or wyfe,</L>
<L>were preysed for &thorn;yn holy lyfe;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wuldest men seyde of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3024">&thorn;at &thorn;ou dedyst grete charyte,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou were bo&thorn;e meke and chaste,</L>
<L>And wuldest speke no wurd&euml;s waste;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wuldest men seyd &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="3028">&THORN;ou synnest yn pryde, y sey, ywys.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>Ouer al<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of alle.</NOTE> folyys hyt ys &thorn;e floure,</L>
<L>For &thorn;y godenesse to haue wurldys honoure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for pryd&euml; art outrage</L>
<L N="3032">&thorn;at &thorn;ou are<NOTE PLACE="foot">art.</NOTE> come of hygh lynage,</L>
<L>Be&thorn;enke &thorn;e weyl fro when<NOTE PLACE="foot">whenne.</NOTE> &thorn;ou cam;</L>
<L>All&euml; we were of Adam:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be com&euml; of hygh blode,</L>
<L N="3036">And &thorn;ou dost<NOTE PLACE="foot">doust.</NOTE> more euyl &thorn;an gode,</L>
<L>Vnwr&thorn;yly art &thorn;ou made gentyl</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn wurdys and dedys be yl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be prout<NOTE PLACE="foot">proud.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou art wys</L>
<L N="3040">And for &thorn;y cunseyl art holde yn prys,</L>
<L>Or yn &thorn;yn queynt&euml; wurdys hast pryde,</L>
<L>wys yn wrong, euyl shal betyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be proute<NOTE PLACE="foot">proud.</NOTE> of &thorn;y bewte,<MILESTONE N="21a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3044">No shoch<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych.</NOTE> kote to &thorn;e shulde be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at feyrhede ne shal long with &thorn;e wende;</L>
<L>Swych pryde endy&thorn; foule at &thorn;e last ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for strenk&thorn;&euml; be mysproute,</L>
<L N="3048">And hast bostful wrdys and loude;</L>
<L>Do no-body &thorn;arfore despyte ne ska&thorn;e</L>
<L>Swych&euml; men go to shame ful ra&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="inter">sone</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be prout<NOTE PLACE="foot">proud.</NOTE> of &thorn;y rychesse</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt come neuer wy&thorn; no falsnesse,</L>
<L N="3053">Hyt may passe &thorn;e more lyghtly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sunner, &thorn;at &thorn;ou beryst &thorn;e hyy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be prout<NOTE PLACE="foot">proud.</NOTE> of &thorn;y song,</L>
<L N="3056">Seld&euml; laste&thorn; &thorn;at vertu long;</L>
<L>Synger ha&thorn; hert&euml; prout<NOTE PLACE="foot">proud.</NOTE> with-ynne,</L>
<L>And tycy&thorn; many on to synne;</L>
<L>Ful selde ys synger gode yn thew,</L>
<L N="3060">But &thorn;at yn sum poynt he ys a shrew.</L>
<L>yn feyr&euml; wurdys, and yn qeynte,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; pryd&euml; are swych men ateynte;</L>
<L>Flourshed wurdys, and o&thorn;erwhyle louely,
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="108"></L>
<L N="3064">Are ful of pryde and trechery.</L>
<L>Be a man uncouth or couthe,</L>
<L>And he haue laghyng wurdys yn mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>y warne &thorn;e wel &thorn;at o&thorn;er whyle,</L>
<L N="3068">Swych a man ys ful of gyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer bare &thorn;e hyghly</L>
<L>yn ouerdo pryde for &thorn;y bayly,</L>
<L>Bere &thorn;e lowe; men se al day,</L>
<L N="3072">&THORN;y bayly shal nat laste alway;</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou, and sy&thorn;en y,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syll</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L>So shal go, oure bayly.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syll</I>.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be prout of &thorn;y cunnyng,</L>
<L N="3076">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast lerned moch&euml; &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>As sum man ys, &thorn;at ys scolere,</L>
<L>weny&thorn; &thorn;at none ys to hym pere,</L>
<L>He weny&thorn; weyl &thorn;at he kan</L>
<L N="3080">To be mayster, and ouer-man,</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e end&euml; ys al shewyd,<MILESTONE N="21a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an ys he almost al lewyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou delyte &thorn;e oftyn stoundes,</L>
<L>yn horsys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">horsys O, hors H.</NOTE> haukys, or yn houndes;</L>
<L N="3085">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou clerk auaunsed be,</L>
<L>Swyche game ys nat graunted to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>To emperorus<NOTE PLACE="foot">emperours.</NOTE> and to kyngys</L>
<L N="3088">ys graunted swych<NOTE PLACE="foot">sweche.</NOTE> pleyyngys;</L>
<L>Erl&euml;s, barons, also y graunte,</L>
<L>And kny&yogh;t&euml;s, &thorn;ey mow hyt haunte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey ne be tempted of ou&thorn;er synne,</L>
<L N="3092">For ydulnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">are.</NOTE> ynne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt y rede, &thorn;ey haunte hyt so,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens god &thorn;at &thorn;ey nat mysdo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou art wel wy&thorn; &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="3096">Or with ano&thorn;er lordyng,</L>
<L>Bere &thorn;e nat ouer prout &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>To &thorn;y perys out of skore;</L>
<L>For men se hyt yn a &thorn;rowe,
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="109"></L>
<L N="3100">To day ys hegh, te morwe<NOTE PLACE="foot">to morne.</NOTE> ys lowe.</L>
<L>And a lorde ful oft&euml; laty&thorn;,</L>
<L>Now he louy&thorn;, and now<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone.</NOTE> he haty&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer vndyrstode</L>
<L N="3104">&THORN;at &thorn;y wyt, or &thorn;y gode,</L>
<L>Come of &thorn;y self, and nat of god,</L>
<L>Hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> ys grete pryde and falsly troud.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf god almyghty haue &yogh;eue &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3108">Many &thorn;ew&euml;s &thorn;at with &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>werre nat a&yogh;ens &thorn;e commaundment</L>
<L>with &thorn;o &yogh;yftes &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &thorn;e lent;</L>
<L>Make nat &thorn;y saule so wykked a wem</L>
<L N="3112">To do wykkednes for pryde of hem.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e auaunte of goddys &yogh;yfte,</L>
<L>Or worldly gode, or bodly<NOTE PLACE="foot">bodyly.</NOTE> &thorn;ryfte,</L>
<L N="3115">Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou be se moch&euml; mad</L>
<L>To auaunte &thorn;e of &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuer had,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys pryde and arrogaunce,</L>
<L>Vnwr&thorn;yly &thorn;e to auance.</L>
<L>Arrogaunce ys certeynly<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3120">Behold&euml; bettyr &thorn;an ys wr&thorn;y;</L>
<L>To sey a &thorn;yng &thorn;ou shuldest haue do</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou neuer myghtyst come &thorn;er-to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A vyl&euml; synne men haunte alle now,</L>
<L>Of pryde hyt com&thorn;,&mdash;lestne&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesteny&thorn;.</NOTE> how,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at none can preyse hym self by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be.</NOTE> name</L>
<L>But he wy&thorn; euyl anou&thorn;er blame;</L>
<L N="3127">&THORN;ys cum&thorn; of grete enuye</L>
<L>And pryde of herte and felonnye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou skornedyst euer any man,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;aue cunseyl &thorn;at scorne began,</L>
<L>hyt ys a pryde, and wykked &thorn;yng,
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="110"></L>
<L N="3132">At crystyn man to make scornyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e holy prophete Dauy&thorn;,</L>
<L>And Neomas a prophete hym wy&thorn;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at scorners, at &thorn;e hegh Iugement,</L>
<L>Of goddys mou&thorn; &thorn;ey shul be shent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3137">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for pryd&euml; haue delyte</L>
<L>For to be holde an ypocryte,</L>
<L>To be preysed wel for &thorn;y gode dede,</L>
<L N="3140">And &thorn;at holylech &thorn;ou canst &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L>Or to be preysed &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast wroght</L>
<L>&THORN;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ou dedyst now&yogh;t,</L>
<L>wet&euml; &thorn;ou,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou weyl.</NOTE> syre ypocryte,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mede of god &thorn;an art &thorn;ou quyte;</L>
<L N="3145">&thorn;at ych&euml; preysyng ys &thorn;y mede</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou receyuest for &thorn;y gode dede.</L>
<L>Ful fellych&euml; God to hem flytes,<NOTE PLACE="inter">chyde&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L N="3148">To &thorn;es fals[&euml;] ypocrytes;</L>
<L>And sey&thorn;, "at &thorn;e ende shul men se</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e begyle &yogh;ou self, and nat me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And her&euml; y shal telle as tyte</L>
<L N="3152">Of a cursed ypocryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Hypocritical Monk of the Abbey Tangabaton.]
<NOTE>[Bk. IV, ch. xi, of St. Gregory's Dialogues: the place is Iconium, the monastery &tau;&omega;&nu; &Gamma;&alpha;&lambda;&alpha;&tau;&omega;&nu;, <I>ton Galaton</I>, then <I>Tongalaton, Tangabaton</I>. The story is in the <I>Libro de los Exemplos</I> (no. 395), but the abbey is not named.&mdash;G. Paris, <I>Hist. Litt. de la France</I>, xxviii. 197.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Seynt Gregory sey&thorn;, as y shal sey,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>hyt was on&euml;s an abbey</L>
<L>&THORN;e nam&euml; hyght 'tangabaton,'</L>
<L N="3156">And munk&euml;s &thorn;ey were echon.</L>
<L>Of a munke &yogh;ede &thorn;e wurde ful ryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryf.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="21b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he was of holy lyue;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;at he was nat so,</L>
<L N="3160">So holy as men tolde hym to,</L>
<L>Fals preysyng shal wykkedly wende,</L>
<L>As hyt ys wur&thorn;y, so shal hyt ende.</L>
<L>A seknes toke &thorn;e munke ful grym
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="111"></L>
<L N="3164">As god had purueyd of hym.</L>
<L>he was so traueyled, shortly to sey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wyst weyl &thorn;at he shuld dey.<NOTE PLACE="foot">deye.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan he wyst &thorn;at, he made do calle</L>
<L N="3168">Bo&thorn;e one and o&thorn;er, hys bry&thorn;ryn alle,</L>
<L>"Byddy&thorn; hem come byfore me here;</L>
<L>&THORN;at may hem auayle, y shal hem lere."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'teche.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey come rennyng, bo&thorn;e lesse and more,</L>
<L N="3172">And wende haue herd sum holy lore.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ey wer&euml; come echone,</L>
<L>To hem he made of sorow hys mone:</L>
<L>"hyt may no lenger be forholne;</L>
<L N="3176">Falsly, wurschyp haue y stolne;</L>
<L>y am nat, bre&thorn;ren, as &yogh;e wene,</L>
<L>Of holy lyfe, as ha&thorn; be sene;</L>
<L>&THORN;at y fasted when &yogh;e lete;</L>
<L N="3180">For twyys pryuyly y &yogh;ete;</L>
<L>And whan &yogh;e wende y had be holy,</L>
<L>Y ete and drank ful lustyly.</L>
<L>To warn&euml; &yogh;ow, &thorn;us y telle,</L>
<L N="3184">For me ys come &thorn;e fende of helle.</L>
<L>wy&thorn; hys tayle my knes he ha&thorn; kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And wy&thorn; hys hede my mou&thorn; y-dyt.<NOTE PLACE="inter">stoppyd</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at y was bore!</L>
<L N="3188">As an ypocryte y am forlore.</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t now shal he me strangle and cheke,</L>
<L>Ne shal y neuer aftyr speke."</L>
<L>Be-fore hem alle he deyde astyte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'anone.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3192">&THORN;at ych&euml; proud ypocryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys was shewed, hem for to warne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at, God, no man shuld scorne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde no man scarne, 'scorne' gloss.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ypocrysye, &thorn;ys ys &thorn;e synne<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Feyre wy&thorn;-oute, and foule<NOTE PLACE="foot">wykkede.</NOTE> with-ynne.</L>
<L N="3197">&THORN;ys ych&euml; synn&euml; cum&thorn; of pryde,
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>Yn feyre shewyng, here falsnes hyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou art prout of &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> her,</L>
<L N="3200">(As prout men ben euery where,)</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou tyfyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyffyst; <I>O.N.</I> 'typpa,' adorn.</NOTE> &thorn;e ouer proudly,</L>
<L>Ouer mesure on &thorn;y body,</L>
<L>Swych&euml; synne ys nat &thorn;e leste;</L>
<L N="3204">Y rede &thorn;e telle hyt to &thorn;e preste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be nat proud of &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">a.</NOTE> croket,<NOTE PLACE="inter">chaplet</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e cherche to tyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyffe.</NOTE> and set.</L>
<L>At home mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;y croket werche,</L>
<L>And nat at &thorn;y messe yn &thorn;e cherche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3209">And of &thorn;ese berded buckys<NOTE PLACE="foot">bukkes.</NOTE> also,</L>
<L>with hem-self &thorn;ey moche mysdo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leu&euml; crystyn mennys acyse</L>
<L N="3212">And haunt&euml; alle &thorn;e new&euml; gyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;erwhylys &thorn;ey had &thorn;at gyse on hand,</L>
<L>was neuer grac&euml; yn &thorn;ys land.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of proud wymmen wuld y telle,</L>
<L N="3216">But &thorn;ey are so<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone.</NOTE> wroth and felle;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ese &thorn;at are so foule and fade,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make hem feyrere &thorn;an god hem made</L>
<L>with oblaunchere or<NOTE PLACE="foot">or wy&thorn;.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er floure,</L>
<L N="3220">To make hem whytter of coloure.</L>
<L>Grete pryde hyt ys, and<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. inserts 'vyle.'</NOTE> outrage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at she ys nat payd of goddys ymage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>heuedys tyfed wy&thorn; grete pryde,</L>
<L N="3224">with heer,<NOTE PLACE="foot">her.</NOTE> and<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> wy&thorn;.</NOTE> horn&euml;s syde,<NOTE PLACE="inter">long</NOTE></L>
<L>Men mow wete hyt ys grete synne</L>
<L>To hau&euml; moch&euml; pryde &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>Men sey, and haue seyd, here before,</L>
<L>For swych pryde are wymmen forlore.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3229">Ryche ladyys of grete renouns,<NOTE PLACE="inter">name</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey do make hem ryche corouns,<NOTE PLACE="inter">hauyng</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey may make to here auenaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'hauynge.'</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="113"></L>
<L N="3232">But ouer mesure ys nat cunnaunt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">couenaunt. Glossed 'semely.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of ladyys wulde y leue my sawe,<MILESTONE N="22a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But y dar nat for goddys awe;<NOTE PLACE="inter">drede</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hem behoue&thorn; to sey sumdeyl,</L>
<L N="3236">yn what poynt&euml;s &thorn;ey do nat wel.</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; shewed, and shewe&thorn; euery day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych&euml; pryde ys noght to pay.</L>
<L>A tale y shal &thorn;erfor&euml; telle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L N="3240">How a lady was pyned yn helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Proud Lady, who was burnt to ashes again and again in Hell by a Burning Wheel.]</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;er was a lady, a lordys wyfe,</L>
<L>here fayrhede was yn renoun ryfe;</L>
<L>Moche she loued feyre tyfyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyffynge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3244">On here hede, ouer al &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>For to be holde &thorn;e feyryst lady</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;o &thorn;at woned here by;</L>
<L>And whan she wened best<NOTE PLACE="foot">best wende.</NOTE> to haue lyuyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e de&thorn; here toke; here dayys were fyllyd;</L>
<L>For when men wene to lyfe haue space,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys de&thorn; sunnest yn place.</L>
<L>Whan she was dede, sone aftyrward</L>
<L N="3252">here squyer toke a syknes hard,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here lorde helde of grete prys,</L>
<L>For he was a man yn seruyse wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he lay yn hys bed a ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>hym &thorn;oght hys lady come to hym ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3257">And seyd &thorn;us, "rys, and go wy&thorn; me,</L>
<L>A merueyle shal y shewe to &thorn;e."
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; man graunted here noght,</L>
<L N="3260">For hyt ran weyl hym yn &thorn;oght</L>
<L>&THORN;at sh&eacute; was dede and leyd yn graue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym of hys bedd&euml; wulde haue.</L>
<L>But whe&thorn;er he wulde or noght, wy&thorn; wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">wele.</NOTE> &amp; wo,</L>
<L N="3264">She had hym vp with here to go.</L>
<L>&THORN;us tolde he se&thorn;yn with moche drede;</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens hys wylle with here he &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>She ledde hym to a moch&euml; felde,</L>
<L N="3268">So grete one neuer he behelde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an stod&euml; styl, &thorn;ys lady,</L>
<L>And he by here ful dredfully.</L>
<L N="3271">As &thorn;ey hadd stond&euml; but a &thorn;rowe,<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Come fur&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">foure.</NOTE> deuylys &thorn;at fast gun blowe;</L>
<L>With hem &thorn;ey broght a brennyng wheyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on here hede was set eche deyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys whel &thorn;at was set on here heuede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuede O, hede H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Brende here alle, &thorn;at noght was leued.</L>
<L N="3277">Efte she ros, when she was brent,</L>
<L>And had &thorn;e sam&euml; turment,</L>
<L>And brende ry&yogh;t as she dede before;</L>
<L N="3280">To se &thorn;at peyne hys herte was sore.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt she ros &thorn;e sam&euml; wey;</L>
<L>For saule may neuer for peyn&euml; deye.</L>
<L>And efte &thorn;ey set<NOTE PLACE="foot">sette.</NOTE> hyt on here krowne,</L>
<L>And brende here al to asshen doune;</L>
<L N="3285">And euermore she leuyd a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>For peyn&euml; my&yogh;t she neuer be sleyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an askede he here, why &thorn;at hyt was</L>
<L>&THORN;at she suffred swyche peyne. "alas, alas,"</L>
<L N="3289">She seyd, "y suffre &thorn;ys mys-auenture
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>For on my heuede<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede.</NOTE> ouer feyre tyfure;</L>
<L>For when y shuld agher go or ryde,</L>
<L N="3292">y dyghte my heuede<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful.</NOTE> moche with pryde</L>
<L>For to be presyd ouer alle ladyys,</L>
<L>And of pryd&euml; to bere &thorn;e prys,</L>
<L>And among kny&yogh;t&euml;s yn halle</L>
<L N="3296">y wulde be holde feyrest of alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er-for &thorn;ys ych&euml; peyne y drygh<NOTE PLACE="inter">suffre</NOTE></L>
<L>For y bare me yn pryde so hygh.</L>
<L>But warne my lord&euml;, y pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>hys pryde and bobaunce &thorn;at he late be;</L>
<L N="3301">But &yogh;yf he do, he shal be forlore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y warne hym weyl before;</L>
<L>For on one of &thorn;ys dayys shul &yogh;e deye,</L>
<L N="3304">My lorde and &thorn;ou: &thorn;e so&thorn;e y seye."</L>
<L>Ryght at &thorn;e term&euml;, as<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> she seyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t, and &thorn;at squyer, deyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;at tokenyng wel men knew</L>
<L N="3308">&THORN;at &thorn;e tale was ry&yogh;t and trew.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor hyt ys gret&euml; doute,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. gloss 'drede.'</NOTE><MILESTONE N="22b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wymmen to tyfe here hedys aboute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf god haue lent &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, &thorn;e lent H.</NOTE> handys and fete,</L>
<L N="3312">Arm&euml;s, legg&euml;s, feyre and swete,&mdash;</L>
<L>Be nat ouer proude of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are nat &thorn;yne, but &thorn;ey ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyn.</NOTE> hys;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf he wylle, he may hem &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e hem.</NOTE> reue;</L>
<L>with-oute hys leue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue.</NOTE> shal none beleue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Despyse noun ou&thorn;er &thorn;at so haue noght,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ogh.</NOTE> &thorn;ey be nat so feyre y-wroght;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou doust, &thorn;ou mayst hem tyne,<NOTE PLACE="inter">lese</NOTE></L>
<L N="3320">And for &thorn;at pryd&euml; go to pyne.</L>
<L>Ne dysgyse nat &thorn;y clo&thorn;yng</L>
<L>Ouer mesure, for &thorn;y preysyng.
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>Alas! hyt shuld&euml; so betyde,</L>
<L N="3324">Many one are lost for here pryde.</L>
<L>Shal grace come neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer come.</NOTE> yn &thorn;at land</L>
<L>&THORN;ere men haue swych&euml; gyse yn hand;</L>
<L>God and grace are wy&thorn; hem wroth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haue, for pryde, dysgysed here cloth.</L>
<L N="3329">No&thorn;eles<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, No&thorn;ele H.</NOTE> euery<NOTE PLACE="foot">eury.</NOTE> man may,</L>
<L>Aftyr hys astate, make hym gay;</L>
<L>But when he &thorn;asse&thorn; ouer mesure,</L>
<L N="3332">&THORN;erof cum&thorn; mysauenture.</L>
<L>Gentyl men ofte, for swyche desert</L>
<L>Fal<NOTE PLACE="foot">Falle.</NOTE> at &thorn;e laste yn grete pouert.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A weddyd wyfe may atyre here</L>
<L>&THORN;at here husbunde loue noun but here;</L>
<L N="3337">For hys loue she may hyt do,</L>
<L>But for none ou&thorn;er mannys so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt swyche y rede, &thorn;at &thorn;ey so fare</L>
<L N="3340">&THORN;at here pryde make hem nat bare.</L>
<L>Gretly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gretlych.</NOTE> &thorn;ey synne yn &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> queyntyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at nouelrye al day areyse,</L>
<L>For to be preysed and of grete syght,</L>
<L N="3344">Al day dysgyse hem at here myght;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e hyt seme&thorn; weyl to be</L>
<L>Al here lyfe yn vanyte.</L>
<L>But wlde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'wlde.'</NOTE> &thorn;ey &thorn;enke &thorn;at make swyche strut,</L>
<L>yn what robe, yn er&thorn;e, &thorn;ey shul<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey shul yn er&thorn;e.</NOTE> be put,</L>
<L N="3349">&THORN;ey shulde nat make hyt so a-mys,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey &thorn;oght oft of<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> &thorn;ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y shal &yogh;ou telle a lytyl wyght<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>wiht</I>, space]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>How hyt befyl onys of a kny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Knight and Monk who lovd new Fashions.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er was a kny&yogh;t &thorn;at loued nouelrye,</L>
<L N="3354">As many one haunte now &thorn;at folye;
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>he dede to make,<NOTE PLACE="foot">do make hym.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e somers tyde,</L>
<L>A kote perced queyntly with pryde;</L>
<L N="3357">And God was nat &thorn;er-of payd,</L>
<L>For yn hys pryde he was betrayd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys kny&yogh;t &yogh;ede, vpp-on a day,</L>
<L N="3360">Aboute roberye, to gete hys pray;</L>
<L>Homward as he hys pray ledde</L>
<L>with hys enmys he was bestedde;</L>
<L>with fors &thorn;ey gun with hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym to.</NOTE> fyght,</L>
<L N="3364">And slogh &thorn;ere &thorn;ys ych&euml; kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;tys frendys herd&euml; seye</L>
<L>how he was slayn by &thorn;e weye;</L>
<L>Ful feyre &thorn;an gun &thorn;ey for hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">for hym &thorn;an gunne &thorn;ey.</NOTE> werche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey byryed &thorn;e body feyre at &thorn;e cherche;</L>
<L N="3369">hys frendys departed hys katel</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e pore men, and &thorn;at was wel.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey come at &thorn;e kote gysyng,</L>
<L N="3372">To dele hyt among hys ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e pore men hyt was broght;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore men seyd &thorn;ey wulde hyt no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A clerk stod&euml; &thorn;o &thorn;ere be syde,</L>
<L N="3376">And, prayd for &thorn;e kote of pryde.</L>
<L>To werne hyt hym, &thorn;ey &thorn;oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem &thorn;ught.</NOTE> lo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey toke and &yogh;aue &thorn;ys clerk &thorn;e clo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys clerk was glad whan he hyt hadde;</L>
<L N="3380">&THORN;ys kote asswy&thorn;e on hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">on hym asswy&thorn;e.</NOTE> he cladde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se now here a grete myschaunce</L>
<L>Come ry&yogh;t as for veniaunce:</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as he was yn &thorn;e kote al dyght,</L>
<L N="3384">A fyre brennyng on hym gan lyght,</L>
<L>And brend hys body dounne to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>whylys oght of hym my&yogh;t be founde.<MILESTONE N="23a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er shewed God weyl by &thorn;at kas
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="118"></L>
<L N="3388">&THORN;at &thorn;e kote a-cursed was,</L>
<L>And tokened wel sorowe and wrake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> pore man wulde hyt take</L>
<L>For pryd&euml; of &thorn;e new&euml; gyse</L>
<L N="3392">A&yogh;ens crystyn mennys wyse;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e clerk was wode al gate</L>
<L>To were a clo&thorn;e a&yogh;ens hys state.</L>
<L>here mow &yogh;e se &thorn;at god ys wroth</L>
<L N="3396">with hem &thorn;at dysgyse here clo&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a clerk ys moche for to blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at bryngy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">brynth.</NOTE> hym self yn foule fame,</L>
<L>Clerk ordeyned yn dignyte</L>
<L N="3400">&THORN;at haunte&thorn; swyche Iolyte;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, of &thorn;e new&euml; gyse</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuyl ha&thorn; made hymself chefe iustyse;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he yn folye begynne to stoute,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bere&thorn; he &thorn;e deuylys baner aboute;</L>
<L N="3405">Moch&euml; folk ys &thorn;erwy&thorn; blent;</L>
<L>God do &thorn;erof amendment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hau&euml; grete desyre</L>
<L N="3408">To be clepyd lorde or syre,</L>
<L>For to glos&euml; &thorn;e, and slyppe,</L>
<L>And to haue &thorn;e wurdys of wurschyp;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;e wymmen also, comunly,</L>
<L>wulde be kallede 'madame' or 'lady;'</L>
<L N="3413">Al &thorn;ys com&thorn; of gret&euml; pryde;</L>
<L>yn &thorn;y shryfte &thorn;ou noght hyt hyde.</L>
<L>he ys ry&yogh;t lorde, &thorn;e kyng of heuene;</L>
<L>wrong hyt ys &thorn;at men any o&thorn;er neuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3417">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou delyte &thorn;e yn grete meyne,</L>
<L>For men shulde hau&euml; drede of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;y meyn&euml; wuldyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">wst.</NOTE> preysed be,</L>
<L N="3420">&yogh;yf harme to o&thorn;er &thorn;an do &thorn;at meyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou for &thorn;y meyn&euml; shalt dampned be</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou to euyl vowe &thorn;y meyn&euml;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou delyte &thorn;e yn grete hallys,<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="119"></L>
<L N="3424">Yn a foule pryd&euml; &thorn;an &thorn;ou fallys;</L>
<L>For y se many &thorn;at nowe &thorn;ey bygge,</L>
<L>And now son&euml;, dede &thorn;ey lygge.</L>
<L>y sey for &thorn;o &thorn;at haue grete pryde</L>
<L N="3428">yn hygh hallys and yn wyde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou delyte &thorn;e yn ryche beddyng,</L>
<L>yn hors, yn harneys, or yn feyre rydyng,</L>
<L>Alle ys pryde and vanyte;</L>
<L N="3432">Of al shalt &thorn;ou a-couped be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y seyd langere, yn gode cunnaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">couenaunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euery man may haue to hys auenaunt,</L>
<L>Cytes, tounnes, castellys, and hallys,</L>
<L N="3436">hors, armour, and &thorn;at &thorn;ar to fallys;</L>
<L>But, yn al &thorn;at moch&euml; &thorn;rong,</L>
<L>Do holy cherche, ne pore man,<NOTE PLACE="foot">men.</NOTE> wrong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what sey &yogh;e men of ladyys pryde</L>
<L N="3440">&THORN;at gon&euml; traylyng ouer syde:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'longe.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf a lady were ryghtly shreue,</L>
<L>Better hyt were yn alm&euml;s &yogh;eue;</L>
<L>To soul&euml; helpe hyt my&yogh;t do bote,</L>
<L N="3444">&THORN;at trayle&thorn; lowe vndyr &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> fote.</L>
<L>wymples, kerchyues, saffrund betyde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;elugh vnder &yogh;elugh &thorn;ey hyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;an wete men neuer, whe&thorn;er ys whe&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="3448">&thorn;e &yogh;elugh wymple or &thorn;e le&thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="inter">skyn</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wymmen &thorn;at go fro strete to strete,</L>
<L>One or ou&thorn;er for to mete,</L>
<L>Of pryd&euml; com&thorn; swych&euml; desyre,
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="120"></L>
<L N="3452">For &thorn;ey haue on hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> feyre atyre:</L>
<L>But she wul to &thorn;e prest &thorn;at telle,</L>
<L>She may &thorn;erfor&euml; go to helle;</L>
<L>For yn as moche &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">as.</NOTE> she dou&thorn; men synne,</L>
<L>yn so moche shal she haue plyght ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3457">And, wymmen, y<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue y.</NOTE> seye of &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at borwe clo&thorn;es yn carol to go;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn to karol go.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at por&euml; pryd&euml;, god hyt lo&thorn;es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make hem proude of ou&thorn;er mennys clo&thorn;ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hast spok&euml; wurdys of pryde,<MILESTONE N="23b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lettyst ou&thorn;er men any tyde</L>
<L>Of here bedys and<NOTE PLACE="foot">or.</NOTE> of here fastyng,</L>
<L N="3464">Or of any<NOTE PLACE="foot">sum.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er holy &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Or of any ou&thorn;er god&euml; dede,</L>
<L>to telle hyt &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> prest, behoue&thorn; &thorn;e nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer lett&euml; began</L>
<L N="3468">&THORN;at was wurshep to god or man,</L>
<L>As yn cherche to synge or rede,</L>
<L>Or of sum o&thorn;er holy dede;</L>
<L>Or also for boste or for pryde,</L>
<L N="3472">with prest or with clerk to chyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;at pryde &thorn;ou fallyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">falst.</NOTE> yn synne,</L>
<L>And cursednes &thorn;erwith to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also &thorn;at clerk ys moche to blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at lette&thorn; to shaue hys krowne for shame;</L>
<L N="3477">Y rede &thorn;at he yn tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn tyme &thorn;at he.</NOTE> hyt shaue,</L>
<L>For he wote neuer what nede he shal &thorn;erto haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn ernest, or yn game,</L>
<L N="3480">yn scorn&euml; blessedyst Goddys name;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou were so wundyrly proude</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mysseydyst God al aloude,</L>
<L>For any chaunce &thorn;at may betyde</L>
<L N="3484">Skorne nat God, ne wy&thorn; hym chyde:
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>Mor&euml; pryde, no<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> mor&euml; synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;an skorn&euml; god, mayst &thorn;ou falle ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou grucchedest, and seydyst noght,</L>
<L N="3488">But to God haddyst euyl &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>wete &thorn;ou wel, hyt ys grete pryde,</L>
<L>Grucchyng with God, or<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. <I>om</I>. 'or.'</NOTE> for to chyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a man haue mysdo or seyde,</L>
<L>And men hym blame for &thorn;at mysbreyde,</L>
<L N="3493">&YOGH;yf he susteyn&euml; hys mysdede,</L>
<L>And hys mysawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">myssawe.</NOTE> wyl nat drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cum&thorn; of mysprout herte and hy</L>
<L N="3496">&THORN;at wyl nat knowe hys owne foly.</L>
<L>Of al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle.</NOTE> folyys &thorn;at beryn name,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys foly ys moste for to blame;</L>
<L>who-so-euer to &thorn;ys ys custummable,<MILESTONE N="24a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3500">hys amendment may neuer be stable.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what sey men of &thorn;ese loseniours</L>
<L>&THORN;at haue here wurdys feyre as flours?</L>
<L>Now ys &thorn;e flour&euml; whyte and rede,</L>
<L N="3504">And now hyt ys bo&thorn;e drye and dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e losenioure spek&thorn; now &thorn;y pay,</L>
<L>And behynde &thorn;y bak hyt ys away.</L>
<L>&thorn;ere one ha&thorn; smylyng semelaunt</L>
<L N="3508">And behety&thorn; &thorn;e to holde cunnaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">cuuinaunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>kepe &thorn;e &thorn;an fro losengrye,</L>
<L>For feyre spekyng man kan weyl lye.</L>
<L>who-so-euer ys custummable to banne</L>
<L N="3512">For pryd&euml;, sum tym&euml; or whanne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostyl sey&thorn; &thorn;at he may noght</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e blysse of heuene be broght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-no&thorn;er spyce hyt ys of pryde,</L>
<L N="3516">who so haunte&thorn; for to chyde.</L>
<L>For holy cherche forbede&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>To chyde wy&thorn; any of &thorn;y meyn&euml;.</L>
<L>Teche hym ferst, yn feyre manere;
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he wyl nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat so.</NOTE> with feyre lere,</L>
<L N="3521">&THORN;an mayst &thorn;ou speke stoutly to hym,</L>
<L>with-out&euml; wra&thorn;&thorn;e, wurdys ful grym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he be chasted at &thorn;y fre wylle,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;ou bere yn herte none ylle.</L>
<L N="3525">Chydyng cum&thorn; of hert&euml; hy,</L>
<L>And gret&euml; pryde, and vylany.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-nou&thorn;er spyce &thorn;er ys &thorn;at moche deres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'harmy&thorn;.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3528">&THORN;at ys, &thorn;ese cursed bakbyteres.</L>
<L>Of al<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle.</NOTE> men, &thorn;ey do most euyl,</L>
<L>here lorefadyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">? teacher, or for 'forefadyr.'</NOTE> ys &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende vs bewreye&thorn; of oure synne</L>
<L N="3532">whan he ha&thorn; made vs fal &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>So are &thorn;ese bakbyters wunne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey seye &thorn;e werst &thorn;at &thorn;ey kunne;</L>
<L>Euer behynde a mannys bak,</L>
<L N="3536">with euyl &thorn;ey fynde hym to lak.</L>
<L>Swyche men god almy&yogh;ty hatys<MILESTONE N="24a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with here foul&euml; synne hym wlatys.<NOTE PLACE="inter">lo&thorn;e&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Austyn speky&thorn; of swyche &thorn;ynges</L>
<L N="3540">yn a bok&euml; of lesyngys.</L>
<L>No custummable bakbytyng</L>
<L>God for&yogh;eue&thorn;, ne no lesyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;arfore shalt algate drye<NOTE PLACE="inter">suffre</NOTE></L>
<L N="3544">Sum manere peyne for euery lye;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e lesyng ys lesse or more,</L>
<L>Shalt &thorn;ou suffre peyne &thorn;ar-fore.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may weyl preuyd be</L>
<L N="3548">with a tale of an autoryte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at moch&euml; peyn&euml; shal he bere</L>
<L>wy&thorn;-out&euml; ende, &thorn;e bakbytere;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">And here.</NOTE> y shal tell&euml; &yogh;ou a lyte</L>
<L N="3552">Of one &thorn;at coude hys felaus byte.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="123"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the backbiting English Monk.]</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;er was a man of relygyun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A Tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at yn &thorn;ys he was a felun,</L>
<L>Yn bakbytyng, as &yogh;e han herde,</L>
<L N="3556">As many one are now yn &thorn;ys werlde.</L>
<L>He was wunt to seye wykked sawes</L>
<L>Behynde &thorn;e bak of hys felaws;</L>
<L>For he wulde be holde &thorn;e beste</L>
<L N="3560">Of all hys bre&thorn;er, and &thorn;e wylyeste.</L>
<L>A syknes toke &thorn;ys munke, and deyde,</L>
<L>As God had of hym purueyde,</L>
<L>And went yn-to peyn&euml; hard,</L>
<L N="3564">As was shewed aftyrward.</L>
<L>Befel &thorn;e tyme, as hyt ys ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Munk&euml;s to rys&euml; at mydny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And when matynes were al done,</L>
<L N="3568">&THORN;e couent &yogh;ede to bedd&euml; sone.</L>
<L>A munk&euml; lefte be-hynde a throwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a trowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e dede was wunt to knowe;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ys munke come before &thorn;e chapytyl,</L>
<L N="3572">As ordyr asky&thorn;, he louted a lytyl;</L>
<L>And as he louted, hys ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">e&yogh;e.</NOTE> gan blenche,</L>
<L>And say<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh.</NOTE> one sytte before &thorn;e benche,</L>
<L>A foul&euml; &thorn;yng, and a grysly,<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3576">he sagh neuer none so lo&thorn;ly;</L>
<L>he shette hys tunge<NOTE PLACE="foot">tunge out.</NOTE> before &thorn;e grecys,</L>
<L>And gnogh hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. hys.</NOTE> ynwarde al to pecys.</L>
<L>hys tunge was brennynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, brenned <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at he so gnogh,</L>
<L N="3580">yn-to hys mou&thorn;e a&yogh;en he hyt drogh;</L>
<L>And eft, oute<NOTE PLACE="foot">out.</NOTE> he dede hyt shete,</L>
<L>And gnogh hyt eft with peyn&euml;s grete.</L>
<L>Many tymes &thorn;an dede he so;
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="124"></L>
<L N="3584">&THORN;ys munke stode and loked &thorn;arto,</L>
<L>And had &thorn;erof so moch&euml; drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wende hau&euml; go to wede.<NOTE PLACE="inter">mad</NOTE></L>
<L>As he stode so sore a glyfte,<NOTE PLACE="inter">feryd</NOTE></L>
<L N="3588">Hys ry&yogh;t hand vp he lyfte</L>
<L>And blessede hym-self stedfastly;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en, he wax more hardy,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oght, '&thorn;ys ys sum pryuyte</L>
<L N="3592">&THORN;at God almy&yogh;ty shewe&thorn; to me.'</L>
<L>hastyly<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, hastly <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;er-to he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And hadde &thorn;er-of no mor&euml; drede;</L>
<L>And seyd, "best, y c&oacute;niure &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="3596">Yn God &thorn;at ys pers&oacute;n&euml;s thre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me telle why &thorn;ou syttest here,</L>
<L>Yn swych forme, and yn swych manere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To answere, he ne my&yogh;t wy&thorn;-drawe,</L>
<L N="3600">"y was a munke, &thorn;yn owne felawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at suffre all &thorn;ys peyne and shame;</L>
<L>Hyt am y,"&mdash;and tolde hys name,&mdash;</L>
<L>"y was a wykked bakbytere,</L>
<L N="3604">Euyl wurdys aboute for to bere;</L>
<L>Of my felaws, wykkedly to seye</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at euer y my&yogh;t bewreye;</L>
<L>And mystrowyng was y ay<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. gloss 'eure.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3608">Of my felaws bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wykked wurdys &thorn;at y haue seyd,</L>
<L>wykkedly are &thorn;ey on me leyde;</L>
<L>Y shal abeye hem ful dere</L>
<L N="3612">with peyn&euml;s strong, as &yogh;e se here."</L>
<L>he wente, an<NOTE PLACE="foot">and.</NOTE> was no more sene;<MILESTONE N="24b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dampned he was, as y wene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ys tale y wote and vndyrstand</L>
<L N="3616">where hyt fyl, yn Yngland,</L>
<L>At a ful namecouthe abbey</L>
<L>&THORN;at y ne wyl telle, ne bewrey.
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>Swych peyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> ys for hem dy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3620">&THORN;at kunne nat kepe here tung&euml; ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e byble men mow se,</L>
<L>yn a boke of pryuyte,</L>
<L N="3623">Apocalyps &thorn;ese clerkys wote,</L>
<L>Seynt Ioun &thorn;e euangylyst hyt wrote;</L>
<L>Oure lord&euml; sey&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ey shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shul.</NOTE> ete</L>
<L>here tunges in peynes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne.</NOTE> and al to-frete,</L>
<L>&THORN;ese lyers and &thorn;ese bakbyters;</L>
<L N="3628">&THORN;e tal&euml;, of &thorn;ys, wytnes berys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ys synne, y rede we vs shryue,</L>
<L>And take oure penaunce by oure lyue;</L>
<L>For but we yn &thorn;ys so do,</L>
<L N="3632">harder peyne shul we go to.</L>
<L>with what lyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyme O, lyne H.</NOTE> &thorn;on dost most synne,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at shalt &thorn;ou have most pyne ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer wy&thorn; bakbytyng</L>
<L N="3636">&yogh;aue cunsel to wykked &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys a wundyr grete foly;</L>
<L>Hyt may be pryd&euml; with enuye;</L>
<L>who-so-euer haunte&thorn; &thorn;at yche dede,</L>
<L N="3640">Hym shal fayle cunsel at hys nede.</L>
<L>And swyche are preued with resun,</L>
<L>wykked treytours ful of tresun.</L>
<L>&yogh;yue gode cunsel, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou kan,</L>
<L N="3644">And auowe hyt, byfore god and man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pryde ha&thorn; &yogh;yt ano&thorn;er tresun,</L>
<L>And a<NOTE PLACE="foot">an.</NOTE> vnkyndhede as a felun;</L>
<L>&THORN;at now ys vnne&thorn;&euml; none</L>
<L N="3648">&THORN;at yn &thorn;at synne ne ys mys gone.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any shewe to o&thorn;er a pryuyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at for cunseyl oght to be,</L>
<L>&yogh;yf he &thorn;at cunseyl fyr&thorn;er fame,<MILESTONE N="25a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;erof cum&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">come.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e synne and shame,</L>
<L N="3653">Y kan nat se, as yn &thorn;ys kas,</L>
<L>How h&eacute; may &aacute;mende &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> trespas;
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>And specyaly to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto.</NOTE> a preste</L>
<L>Cunsel of shryfte sperd yn hys breste,</L>
<L N="3657">He ne oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghte nat hyt.</NOTE> for to telle</L>
<L>For lyfe ne de&thorn;, what so euer befelle.</L>
<L>Shryfte ys goddys pryuyte</L>
<L N="3660">&THORN;at euer for cunsel oght to be.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf a synn&euml; neuer so grym,</L>
<L>To a prest, yn shryfte, were shewede hym;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh men aforced hym for drede,</L>
<L N="3664">To sey &thorn;at, '&thorn;at man dyd &thorn;at dede'</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en he had hys penaunce take,</L>
<L>And yn shryfte hys synne forsake,</L>
<L>He shuld ra&thorn;er swere on &thorn;e halydam</L>
<L N="3668">'Nay!' or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar.</NOTE> he tolde hyt any man,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'he.'</NOTE> ne my&yogh;t with noun answere</L>
<L>Or ou&thorn;er manere hym seluen were.<NOTE PLACE="inter">saue</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at telle&thorn; goddys cunsel,</L>
<L N="3672">he shal se hyt wro&thorn;er yn helle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wro&thorn;er heyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn er&thorn;e hys tunge oght to<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. <I>om</I>. 'to.'</NOTE> be oute drawe,</L>
<L>And yn helle be al to-gnawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hyt ys also grete pryde and herte hy,</L>
<L N="3676">To speke foule wurdys yn rybaudy;</L>
<L>Seynt Poule sey&thorn;, vs to chastyse,</L>
<L>'kepy&thorn; &yogh;oure tung&euml;s on al wyse,</L>
<L>And speke&thorn; no fyl&thorn;e oute of skore,</L>
<L N="3680">&THORN;at noun ou&thorn;er synne &thorn;arfore.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou any man<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'man.'</NOTE> manasse</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh force or power &thorn;at &thorn;ou hasse,</L>
<L>Hyt ys grete pryde, y &yogh;eue &thorn;e a &yogh;yfte;</L>
<L N="3684">&THORN;enk&euml; &thorn;er-on, yn &thorn;y shryfte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer &yogh;aue iogolours of &thorn;y &thorn;yng</L>
<L>For to be yn here preysyng,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou madyst wrastlyng yn place</L>
<L N="3688">&THORN;at non&euml; were<NOTE PLACE="foot">were holde.</NOTE> to &thorn;y pygace,&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="inter">so grete as &thorn;ou</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>Alle ys pryde and vanyte;<MILESTONE N="25a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of al behoue&thorn; &thorn;e shryu&euml; be.</L>
<L>No pryd&euml; ne may be stole,</L>
<L N="3692">No yn shryft&euml; be forhole;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'hed.'</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;yf hyt be forhol&euml; here</L>
<L>Yn o&thorn;er stede &thorn;ou shalt abye hyt dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of pryde shul we leue and dwelle,</L>
<L N="3696">And fur&thorn;er of o&thorn;er synnys telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh y &thorn;er-of spake euere<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, euere &thorn;er of spake Harl.</NOTE> and oo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt my&yogh;t menne telle of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'of.'</NOTE> many mo;</L>
<L>For of pryde ys &thorn;e bygynnyng</L>
<L N="3700">Of al manere wykked &thorn;yng:</L>
<L>God shelde vs &thorn;er-yn to falle,</L>
<L>And haue mercy on vs alle!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. adds 'Amen.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[Of Anger, the 2nd Deadly Sin.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tou&thorn;er synne men call&euml; yre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuylys doghtyr of hell&euml; fyre.</L>
<L N="3705">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou art so wundyr wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>with one &thorn;at to &thorn;e ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys to &thorn;e.</NOTE> dedly lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou nat sone repent&euml; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3708">To helle &thorn;ou fallest &thorn;e fyrst gre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e man wra&thorn;&thorn;y&thorn; hym lyghtly,</L>
<L>For lytyl, as yn malyncoly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at synn&euml; ne ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne ys nat.</NOTE> ryght gref</L>
<L N="3712">&THORN;at sone ys wro&thorn;e, and lyghtly lef.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, hyt were weyl to done,</L>
<L>wysman shulde nat wra&thorn; hym sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;er be o&thorn;er lorde or syre</L>
<L N="3716">&thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;yth hym with gret&euml; yre,</L>
<L>And euermore <SUP>7</SUP>yn strenk&thorn;e<SUP>7</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">7_7 ylych yn stren&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wra&thorn;&thorn;&euml; drawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">dragh&thorn;e.</NOTE> yn len&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ych&euml; wra&thorn;&thorn;e ys synn&euml; strong</L>
<L N="3720">&THORN;at lasty&thorn; yn any man so long.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for wra&thorn;&thorn;e madyst chydyng,</L>
<L>Or repreuedyst a man of vyle &thorn;yng,
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Yre ha&thorn; kast &thorn;e yn &thorn;ys kas</L>
<L N="3724">Ano&thorn;er grece to hell&euml; pas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for yre bygynne wykkednes</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man may lette &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e lette.</NOTE> ne stres,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche yre ys wy&thorn; pryde,<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3728">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for wra&thorn;&thorn;e wylt nat abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn yre a man hate,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;&euml; wylt nat late,</L>
<L>Greuusly &thorn;ou art yn synne,</L>
<L N="3732">But &thorn;ou for&yogh;eue, and &thorn;er-of blynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy man sey&thorn; hardly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hardyly.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast slayn hym gostly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;y wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou wylt not<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat.</NOTE> blynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'leue.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3736">But bryngest ano&thorn;er to &thorn;y synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt haue charg&euml; of<NOTE PLACE="foot">for.</NOTE> &thorn;o bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;urgh &yogh;oure wra&thorn;&thorn;e are o&thorn;er wro&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;y defaute &thorn;an synne&thorn; he,</L>
<L N="3740">&THORN;e mor&euml; perel &thorn;yn shal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &yogh;aue euer cunsel or rede</L>
<L>For yre, &thorn;at a man were dede;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou yn any strut,</L>
<L N="3744">For Ire wundedyst a man, or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>.</NOTE> hurt,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys synn&euml; ys outrage,</L>
<L>To helle &thorn;ou makyst &thorn;y vyage.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;an wrote &thorn;e holy man</L>
<L N="3748">At wham<NOTE PLACE="foot">whom.</NOTE> &thorn;ys wurd&euml; lerne y gan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for yre a man slogh</L>
<L>&THORN;at myghtyst haue lefte<NOTE PLACE="foot">left hyt.</NOTE> weyl ynogh,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt was nat &thorn;e defendyng,</L>
<L N="3752">But for wra&thorn;&thorn;e and yre brennyng,&mdash;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at euer God shope to be</L>
<L>Shal come and fy&yogh;t a&yogh;ens &thorn;e</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L N="3756">And a&yogh;ens alle &thorn;ou shalt be shent.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="129"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou art wunt custummably</L>
<L>For to curse for lytyl why,</L>
<L>&THORN;y tunge bere&thorn; &thorn;erof wytnesse</L>
<L N="3760">&THORN;at men nowe weyl wra&thorn; yn &thorn;e gesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a man curse as yn game,</L>
<L>And yn hys herte wyl hym no shame,</L>
<L>he ne synne&thorn; nat &thorn;an dedly,</L>
<L N="3764">For hyt ys seyd al yn rybaudy.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys synne ys nat dampnable<MILESTONE N="25b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But hyt be seyd custummable.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou shal vndyrstand and wete,</L>
<L>with resun, mayst &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou mayst.</NOTE> &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e and flyte<NOTE PLACE="inter">chyde</NOTE></L>
<L N="3769">A&yogh;ens vyleynye and synne,</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou ne mayst do o&thorn;er bote &thorn;erynne;</L>
<L>wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e with mannys vyleynye,</L>
<L N="3772">But nat<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. with nat.</NOTE> with his gode ne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. and.</NOTE> hys body.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at God loue&thorn;, &thorn;ou shalt loue,</L>
<L>here yn er&thorn;e, and yn heuene aboue.</L>
<L>&THORN;at God neuer louyd, &thorn;ou shalt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at shalt &thorn;ou.</NOTE> hate,</L>
<L N="3776">wra&thorn;&thorn;e, and o&thorn;er synne foolate.<NOTE PLACE="foot">forlate.</NOTE></L>
<L>God louy&thorn; euery cre&auml;ture</L>
<L>&THORN;at he formed to hys fygure;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e synn&euml; &thorn;at ys wroght,</L>
<L N="3780">&THORN;at loued he neuer noght.</L>
<L>Loue euery man yn hys gode dede;</L>
<L>hys wykkednes shalt &thorn;ou hate &amp; drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou mayst spek&euml; wurdys smerte</L>
<L N="3784">&THORN;ogh wra&thorn;&thorn;&euml; be nat yn &thorn;yn herte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst be wro&thorn;e, sum body to chastyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hate nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> yn &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> hert&euml; ryse;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hate and sone for&yogh;yuyst,</L>
<L N="3788">with God hymself &thorn;an &thorn;ou lyuyst;</L>
<L>For God loue&thorn; no &thorn;yng more specyaly</L>
<L>&THORN;an for hys loue to haue mercy.</L>
<L>For he commaunde&thorn; yn &thorn;e gospel</L>
<L N="3792">&THORN;at man shuld for&yogh;eue wra&thorn; eche del,
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>And sey&thorn; "blessyd be al mercyable!</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul se God, and haue hym stable."</L>
<L>And &thorn;at shal y shewe &yogh;ow by a kny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3796">&THORN;at loued more mercy &thorn;an my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Merciful Knight, and how the Crucifix kist him.]</HEAD>
<L>Betwyxe twey kny&yogh;tes be-&yogh;unde &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Fyl a grete cuntek to be;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>Betwyxe hem fyl swyche wra&thorn; &amp; wo</L>
<L N="3800">&THORN;at &thorn;e toon weyted &thorn;e to&thorn;er to slo:</L>
<L>&THORN;ey mette to-gedyr, y ne wote how;</L>
<L>Algate &thorn;e toon &thorn;e to&thorn;er slow.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; slayn kny&yogh;t had a chylde,<MILESTONE N="26a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3804">A doghty bachelere, and a wylde;</L>
<L>&thorn;ys ych&euml; chylde toke hym to rede</L>
<L>For to venge hys fadrys ded;</L>
<L>He gate hym grete powere and my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3808">And beseged &thorn;e to&thorn;er kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er kny&yogh;t perseyued hym wel,</L>
<L>And drogh hym to hys best castel.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was he beseged so streytly,</L>
<L N="3812">&THORN;at he durst come oute on no party</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e twelue<NOTE PLACE="foot">twel.</NOTE> mon&thorn;e with no deseyt,</L>
<L>So was he beseged streyte;</L>
<L>Messe ne matyns he ne herde</L>
<L N="3816"><SUP>2</SUP>Ne nagher to &thorn;e cherge<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 No neuer nagher to cherche.</NOTE> he ferde;<NOTE PLACE="inter">&yogh;ede</NOTE></L>
<L>And hyt was yn &thorn;e lentyn tyde,</L>
<L>when men shuld leu&euml; wra&thorn; &amp; pryde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fyl hyt on &thorn;e gode fryday,</L>
<L N="3820">&THORN;e kny&yogh;t &thorn;at yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits '&thorn;e.'</NOTE> castel lay</L>
<L>loked oute, and say<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh.</NOTE> men go</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cherch&euml;, to and fro;</L>
<L>Barfote to &thorn;e cherche &thorn;ey &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="3824">To aske mercy for here mysdede.
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>"Ey," &thorn;oght &thorn;e kny&yogh;t, "long ys gone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at messe at &thorn;e cherch&euml; herd y none.</L>
<L>what so euer God wyl for me<NOTE PLACE="foot">for me wyle.</NOTE> werche,</L>
<L N="3828">y wyl ryse, and go to &thorn;e cherche."</L>
<L>He drogh of hys hosyn and hys shone,</L>
<L>And ded &thorn;e &yogh;atys be on-done.</L>
<L>Barfote his &yogh;ede, as ys &thorn;e acyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'maner.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="3832">To cherche, for to her&euml; Goddys seruyse.</L>
<L>And as he &thorn;e wey to &thorn;e cherch&euml; name,<NOTE PLACE="foot">namme.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e chylde, hys enmye, a&yogh;ens hym came,<NOTE PLACE="foot">camme.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyd, "treytur, now shalt &thorn;ou deye,</L>
<L N="3836">And my fadyr de&thorn; ful dere a-beye;</L>
<L>No wurld&euml;s gode ne shal &thorn;e saue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e de&thorn; of me shalt haue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t say<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh.</NOTE> non&euml; ou&thorn;er bote,</L>
<L N="3840">But fel on knees byfore hys fote,</L>
<L>And seyd, "haue on me mercy<MILESTONE N="26a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For hym &thorn;at ly&yogh;t yn &thorn;e vyrgyne mary,</L>
<L>And suffred de&thorn; on &thorn;e rod&euml; tre</L>
<L N="3844">&THORN;ys day, to saue bo&thorn;e &thorn;e and me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">me and &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for&yogh;aue hem &thorn;at hys blode spylte;</L>
<L>Ryght so for&yogh;yue &thorn;ou me my gylte;</L>
<L>y am as a presun here yn &thorn;ys place,</L>
<L N="3848">y putte me now alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> yn &thorn;y grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;at goddys grace be on &thorn;e lent</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of Iug&euml;ment!"</L>
<L>&THORN;ys chylde, &thorn;at was hys enmye,</L>
<L N="3852">herde hym prey so rufully,</L>
<L>And seyd, "syn &thorn;ou hast me besoght<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'pryde.'</NOTE></L>
<L>For Ihesu loue &thorn;at dere vs boght,</L>
<L>And for hys modyr loue so dere,</L>
<L N="3856">For hem y graunte &thorn;e my pes here."</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; chylde down swy&thorn;e alyghte,</L>
<L>And yn gode lou&euml; kest &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">keste &thorn;at.</NOTE> kny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>"Now are we frendys, &thorn;at ere were wro&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="132"></L>
<L N="3860">Go we nowe to &thorn;e cherch&euml; bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>yn gode loue, and parfyte charyte,</L>
<L>For hys sake &thorn;at ordeyned pes to be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;t was glad, and no ferly,<NOTE PLACE="inter">wndyr</NOTE></L>
<L N="3864">And so were al &thorn;at cumpanye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for&yogh;aue hym hys mysdede,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e cherch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherche &thorn;at.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e &thorn;ey &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e cros &thorn;[e]y knelyd downe</L>
<L N="3868">yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. <I>om</I>. '&thorn;e.'</NOTE> wurschyp of Ihesu<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ihesus.</NOTE> passyowne,</L>
<L>For to kesse &thorn;e cros &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>As custume ys yn crystyn lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e elder kny&yogh;t, for honoure,</L>
<L N="3872">&YOGH;ede fyrst, and kyst hys cre&auml;ture;<NOTE PLACE="foot">creatour.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftyr &thorn;an, &yogh;ed&euml; &thorn;e chylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was becom&euml; meke and mylde;</L>
<L>wy&thorn; &thorn;e tokene he gan hym blesse,</L>
<L N="3876">And kneled down, &thorn;e cros to kesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e crucyfyx, &thorn;at &thorn;ere was leyd,</L>
<L>hys arm&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">arme.</NOTE> fro &thorn;e cros vpbreyd,</L>
<L>And clepd<NOTE PLACE="foot">clypte.</NOTE> &thorn;e chyld&euml; hym betwyx,<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And aftyrward kyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">aftyr keste.</NOTE> hym, &thorn;at crucyfyx.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e parshe, bo&thorn;e olde and &yogh;onge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ynge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Parseyued, and say,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sagh.</NOTE> &thorn;at clyppynge,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e crucyfyx hym kyste;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey sagh hyt alle, and weyl hyt wyste.</L>
<L N="3885">Alle &thorn;ey &thorn;anked swete Ihesu</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;at myr&aacute;cle and &thorn;at vertu.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ys chylde was grete selkou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="3888">&THORN;at &thorn;e crycyfyx kyst wy&thorn; mouthe.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, forso&thorn;e and ywys,</L>
<L>Y trowe &thorn;at yn hys herte were moche blys;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e folke &thorn;at sagh &thorn;ys &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="3892">Made to God grete &thorn;ankyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ese twey kny&yogh;t&euml;s, how hyt betyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e myracle was sone oueral<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone oueral was.</NOTE> kyd;
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="133"></L>
<L N="3895">And euery man &thorn;erof gan telle,</L>
<L>Prestys &thorn;erof yn prechyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn prechynge &thorn;er-of.</NOTE> gun spelle,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at euery man yn &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> cuntre</L>
<L>lyued wel &thorn;e more yn charyte,</L>
<L N="3899">And all&euml; men &thorn;e sunner for&yogh;aue</L>
<L>Here wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ey to ou&thorn;er dyd haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sekyr &thorn;ou be &thorn;at he was dygne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god shewed for hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">for hym shewede.</NOTE> swyche a sygne;</L>
<L>A sygne hyt was of gret&euml; loue</L>
<L N="3904">That God almy&yogh;ty, of heuene aboue,</L>
<L>Profrede hym to kesse so louely,</L>
<L>For he meked hys herte so hy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now mowe &yogh;e se &thorn;at God<NOTE PLACE="foot">se God.</NOTE> loue&thorn; hem dere</L>
<L N="3908">&THORN;at for&yogh;yuen here wra&thorn; in &thorn;ys wrlde here.<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, here wra&thorn; here <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So shal hys wra&thorn; on hem be sene</L>
<L>&THORN;at here wyl nat for&yogh;eue here<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. he.</NOTE> tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Ire and wra&thorn;, wul<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle.</NOTE> we now blynne,</L>
<L N="3912">And telle fur&thorn;er of a-no&thorn;er synne</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue vs grace, so wra&thorn;&thorn;e for&yogh;yue</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may alle wy&thorn; Ihesu lyue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[Of Envy, the 3rd Deadly Sin.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>T[h]e &thorn;ryd[&euml;] synn&euml; ys enuye,</L>
<L N="3916">&THORN;at ys ful of felunnye;</L>
<L>Holy wryt wytnessy&thorn; hyt wel,<MILESTONE N="26b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt com&thorn; of &thorn;e fende eche del.</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;at ys ful of enuye,</L>
<L N="3920">He ys euer sorowful, we se with ye;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode &thorn;at he se&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">syk&thorn;.</NOTE> alle do&thorn; hym euyl.</L>
<L>And alle ys &thorn;e tycement of &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke now &thorn;arfore, at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="3924">&yogh;yf &thorn;ou were euer payde of myschaunceful &thorn;yng
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>&THORN;at befyl to any man,</L>
<L>Of grete enuye hyt fyrst began.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer haddyst sorow o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp;.</NOTE> kare</L>
<L N="3928">Of &thorn;y negh&euml;burs welfare,</L>
<L>Enuye ha&thorn; &thorn;e yn hys hand</L>
<L>Bound&euml; wy&thorn; &thorn;e deuylys band.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for&thorn;enke a mannys prowe,</L>
<L N="3932">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; hegher state &thorn;an &thorn;ow</L>
<L>Yn any manere of dygnyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may to, auaunssede be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou come nat to hys state,</L>
<L N="3936">But wust apeyre hyt and abate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may nat haue hys bayl&egrave;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">baylye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dedly synne ys swyche enuye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou make one so hard stresse</L>
<L N="3940">&THORN;at hys godnesse wexe &thorn;e lesse,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer yn plac&euml; were</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys harme &thorn;e mor&euml; were,</L>
<L>Shryue &thorn;e wel ar &thorn;ou deye,</L>
<L N="3944">For al &thorn;ys cum&thorn; of grete enuye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer on any manere</L>
<L>Lettydyst any man for to lere</L>
<L>Craft&euml;, or<NOTE PLACE="foot">or any.</NOTE> ou&thorn;er queyntyse,</L>
<L N="3948">But fordeddyst hys apryse<NOTE PLACE="inter">lernyng,</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shuldest fur&thorn;eryd be,</L>
<L>And more yn prys preysed &thorn;an he;</L>
<L>Be&thorn;enke &thorn;e weyl, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou do &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="3952">&THORN;at &thorn;yn herte ys ful enuyus;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shalt neuere, with gode ye,</L>
<L>Se hym &thorn;at lery&thorn; &thorn;y maystrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be enuyus, and no man trowe,<MILESTONE N="27a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And behynde hys bak make hym &thorn;e mowe,</L>
<L N="3957">As who seye &thorn;at "he naght can,</L>
<L>No ys wur&thorn; as a-nou&thorn;er man,"
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>Al ys &thorn;ys enuy&euml; grete;</L>
<L N="3960">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue do &thorn;us, y rede &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou.</NOTE> lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou here preyse one for sum &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou for&thorn;enkyst hys preysyng,</L>
<L>And felyst weyl yn &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> herte</L>
<L N="3964">Of a lytyl sorow or smerte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne art preysed fur&thorn;er &thorn;an he,</L>
<L>Enuye hyt ys, &thorn;ou mayst wel se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many one are of so enuyus wyl</L>
<L N="3968">&THORN;at &thorn;ey may preyse none but with yl;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;enke&thorn; hym euyl &thorn;at &thorn;ey se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are enuyus, what-so<NOTE PLACE="foot">as.</NOTE>-euer &thorn;ey be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Enuyus man ys so ful of susspecyun</L>
<L N="3972">&THORN;at euyl hym &thorn;enketh al, as a felun.</L>
<L>who-so kan knowe &thorn;e properte,</L>
<L>Enuyus man may lyknyd be</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Iawnes, &thorn;e whyche ys a pyne</L>
<L N="3976">&thorn;at men mow se yn mennys yne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ye &thorn;at ys ful of Iawnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iawnys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;enke&thorn; hym &yogh;elogh yn hys auys:</L>
<L>So hyt fare&thorn; on hys party,</L>
<L N="3980">Hys &thorn;oght ys euer ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> of enuye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Enuyus men, euyl &thorn;ey sowe;</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t men telle hem, to euyl &thorn;ey trowe;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey se &thorn;at one do&thorn; more,</L>
<L N="3984">Enuy&uacute;s &thorn;an angre&thorn; sore;</L>
<L>Alle godenes &thorn;ey turne to euyl;</L>
<L>Enuyus men are lyke &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at yn &thorn;ys world&euml; are,</L>
<L N="3988">Enuy&uacute;s man<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e enuyus.</NOTE> werst shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shul.</NOTE> fare.</L>
<L>Gladnes her&euml; haue &thorn;ey none,</L>
<L>But whan here neghburs haue mysgone.</L>
<L>Yn any maner defaute &thorn;at ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">es.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3992">&thorn;an make &thorn;ey ioye for &thorn;at wykkednes.</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e to&thorn;er worlde &thorn;er &thorn;ey shul be,<MILESTONE N="27a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey are nat wur&thorn;y any ioye to se.</L>
<L>Here and &thorn;ere &thorn;ey shul haue greuaunce,
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="136"></L>
<L N="3996">But &thorn;ere shal be here most veniaunce.</L>
<L>Enuye ys on&euml; &thorn;e werst synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e deuyl maketh any man fal ynne.</L>
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn; a tale &thorn;ar-by;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4000">And as he sey&thorn;, so wyl y.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Bear which kept the Hermit's Sheep, and how it was slain by envious Monks.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;er were twey men of holy wyl</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuyd to-gedyr, with-outen yl,</L>
<L>A-lon&euml; yn an ermytage,</L>
<L N="4004">And, as meke as bryd yn kage;</L>
<L>&THORN;e toon, men calle Eutycyus,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er hyght Florentyus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">florencyus.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gode clerk was &thorn;e toon,</L>
<L N="4008">he turned to &thorn;e fey&thorn; many on.</L>
<L>Eutycyus was &thorn;e clerk</L>
<L>&THORN;at taght &thorn;e folk of goddys werk.</L>
<L>Florens was nat so moche yn lore,</L>
<L N="4012">Yn preyours he was euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er besyde was an abbey,</L>
<L>And yn here tyme &thorn;e abbot gan deye;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ys ych&euml; abbot was dede,</L>
<L N="4016">Alle &thorn;e munk&euml;s toke hem to<NOTE PLACE="foot">toke here.</NOTE> rede,</L>
<L>And chese hem syre Eutycyus</L>
<L>To be abbot of here hous.</L>
<L>On alle manere fyl so here lot,</L>
<L N="4020">Eutycyus &thorn;ey made here abbot.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aftyr Eutycyus, Florens gan dwelle</L>
<L>And woned a-lon&euml; yn hys celle.</L>
<L>Florens mad&euml; gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore gret.</NOTE> mone</L>
<L N="4024">For &thorn;at he shuld dwel<NOTE PLACE="foot">wone.</NOTE> alone;</L>
<L>And had grete sorowe, and was drery,</L>
<L>As many be &thorn;at lese gode cumpany.
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>On a day, he bad hys orysun,</L>
<L N="4028">And was yn grete afflyccyon,</L>
<L>And preyd God he wulde hym &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Sum gode cumforte with-al to leue.</L>
<L>&THORN;us preyd Florens yn hys bede<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Gode shuld sende hym sum felaurede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan he ros vp of his orysown,</L>
<L>he &yogh;ede yn hys celle vp and down,</L>
<L>And opened hys &yogh;ate, and loked oute,</L>
<L N="4036">And sagh a ber&euml; wylde and stoute.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; bere come to &thorn;e gate<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e gate, glossed <I>wey</I>, O, gate H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Florens &thorn;at stode yn &thorn;e &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>But when &thorn;e bere come at hym nere,</L>
<L N="4040">&THORN;e bere to hym loutede, and made feyre chere,&mdash;</L>
<L>Feyre chere as a bere myght make,&mdash;</L>
<L>And was so meke &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hym take.</L>
<L>&thorn;ys ych&euml; Florens hym be&thorn;oght</L>
<L N="4044">&thorn;at God hadde herd &thorn;at he besoght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked hym of hys swete grace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hym sent hadde swyche solace.</L>
<L>For a myracle, &yogh;e may hyt vndyrstande,</L>
<L N="4048">&thorn;at a wyld&euml; bere was tame to hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys god&euml; man hadde syx&euml; shepe,</L>
<L>And noun hyrde hem for to kepe;</L>
<L>He badde &thorn;e bere &thorn;at he shulde go</L>
<L N="4052">And dryue hys shep&euml; to and fro,</L>
<L>And kepe hem weyl &thorn;at noun hem dere,</L>
<L>"And &thorn;ou shalt be my god&euml; bere."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bere hym louted with semblant glad,</L>
<L N="4056">For to do as Florens hym badde;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bere, he seyde hys auys,</L>
<L>"Euery day whan y ete twyys,</L>
<L>Come &thorn;ou home at hygh vndurne,</L>
<L N="4060">And no lenger yn &thorn;e felde soiurne;</L>
<L>And euery day, when y faste,
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>Come at &thorn;e noun, home, at &thorn;e laste."</L>
<L>So dyd &thorn;e bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bere &thorn;an.</NOTE> euery day,</L>
<L N="4064">One oure passed hym neuer away</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne come home, &thorn;e yche cele<NOTE PLACE="inter">godly</NOTE>,</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e tymeus<NOTE PLACE="foot">tymes.</NOTE> he knew hem wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys Florens hadde cumforte and game</L>
<L N="4068">At hys bere, &thorn;at hyt was so tame,</L>
<L>And loued h&yacute;t moche with-oute fayle<MILESTONE N="27b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e myracle and &thorn;e grete meruayle:</L>
<L>For so&thorn;&euml; so<NOTE PLACE="foot">so&thorn;e to seye.</NOTE> hym byrde<NOTE PLACE="inter">moste</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="4072">For he was a merueylus hyrde.</L>
<L>A bere &thorn;urgh kynde shulde et&euml; shepe;</L>
<L>And here as an hyrde he &yogh;afe to hem kepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yt yche merueyle my&yogh;t nat be hyd,</L>
<L>But yn alle &thorn;e cuntre hyt was weyl kyde</L>
<L>&THORN;at Florens had a tam&euml; bere,</L>
<L>And was an hyrd&euml;, shepe to were<NOTE PLACE="inter">kepe</NOTE>.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e abbot &thorn;at hyghte Eutycyus</L>
<L N="4080">Had foure dyscyplys ful enuyus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle day of &thorn;ys ber&euml; spakk</L>
<L>with grete enuye, gretely to lakk;</L>
<L>And seyd, alle four&euml; hem betwene</L>
<L N="4084">wy&thorn; grete enuy&euml;, scorne, and tene,</L>
<L>"More merueyl do&thorn;e Florencyus</L>
<L>&THORN;an do&thorn;e oure mayster Eutycyus."</L>
<L>&THORN;ey seyd&euml; "hyt shal nat so go;"</L>
<L N="4088">And made forward, &thorn;at bere to slo.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey seyd, &thorn;ey dyd &thorn;at woghte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. reads 'wogh,' and then has the two lines&mdash; &THORN;e ber&euml; in &thorn;e felde &thorn;ey slogh; For gret enuye &thorn;us &thorn;ey wroghte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e whych&euml; dede ful soure &thorn;ey boghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e tyme, &thorn;e bere, o day<NOTE PLACE="foot">o day &thorn;e bere hom.</NOTE> come noghte;</L>
<L N="4092">Florens had &thorn;er-of<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar fore.</NOTE> grete &thorn;oghte;</L>
<L>He ros and &yogh;ede yn-to &thorn;e felde,
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>And aftyr hys ber&euml; faste behelde.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste, hys bere he fonde,</L>
<L N="4096">Besyde hys shepe, slayn on a londe.</L>
<L>Asswy&thorn;&euml; hym self gan to rede</L>
<L>who hadde do &thorn;at ych&euml; dede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt pleyned he more &thorn;e myschaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er shulde falle on hem veniaunce,</L>
<L N="4101">&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at H, O.</NOTE> he pleyned hys own&euml; dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey had slayn his god&euml; bere.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles he pleyned wundyrly sore</L>
<L N="4104">&THORN;at hys solas shulde be no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eutycyus &thorn;e abbot, his felawe,</L>
<L>herd sey hys bere was do adawe;</L>
<L>And come to hym on hys dysport,<MILESTONE N="28a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4108">To mak&euml; Florens gode cumfort.</L>
<L>Florens seyd Eutycyus vn-to,</L>
<L>"Yn God truly y tryst so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at veniaunce shal on hem take</L>
<L N="4112">Yn &thorn;ys lyf&euml; for my sake.</L>
<L>Of Ihesu Cryst &thorn;ey hade no<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. non, with dots under n.</NOTE> drede,</L>
<L>To sle &thorn;at hylpe me yn my nede,</L>
<L>Felunlyche, as<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> for enuye,</L>
<L N="4116">And he ded no man folye;</L>
<L>He was me sent, &thorn;urgh Goddys grace,</L>
<L>To be myn helpe and my solace;</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wuld&euml; hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">dotted under in red ink.</NOTE> me &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="4120">why wuld &thorn;ey nat suffre hym lyue?</L>
<L>God almy&yogh;ty shal do hys wyl</L>
<L>wy&thorn; hem, and mo, &thorn;at do<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun.</NOTE> so yl."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he seyde, so gan hyt falle;</L>
<L N="4124">Gode toke veniaunce on hem alle;</L>
<L>Meseles &thorn;ey wax&euml; &thorn;an to pyne,</L>
<L>Here lemes roted before here yne;</L>
<L>Aboue &thorn;e er&thorn;e &thorn;ey were stynkyng,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="140"></L>
<L N="4128">&THORN;at to &thorn;e beres de&thorn; were consentyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e pope seynt Gregory</L>
<L>Telly&thorn; &thorn;ys tal&euml;, resun why,</L>
<L>&THORN;at enuye ys a cursed synne,</L>
<L N="4132">Any man to falle &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Moche are they wur&thorn;y to suffre shame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;an H.</NOTE> for enuye brynge a man yn blame,</L>
<L>Or make hym lese hys wurldly aght,<NOTE PLACE="inter">gode</NOTE></L>
<L N="4136">Or frendys also to be vnsaght.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'at debate.'</NOTE></L>
<L>who-so &thorn;at do&thorn;, he may hym drede,</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng but peyne shal be hys mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syn &thorn;ys wurld&euml; fryst bygan,</L>
<L N="4140">Enuye ha&thorn; be euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">eure be.</NOTE> yn man;</L>
<L>Lucyfer had fyrst enuye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man was made to state so hye;</L>
<L>Yn paradys he made hym<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. hem.</NOTE> falle,</L>
<L N="4144">And se&thorn;en of hys ofspryng alle;</L>
<L>So that enuye ha&thorn; reyned ay<MILESTONE N="28a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yn alle mankynde vnto &thorn;ys day;</L>
<L>And, Englys men nam&euml;ly</L>
<L N="4148">Are &thorn;urgh kynde of hert&euml; hy:</L>
<L>A forbyseyn ys told&euml; &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>Seyd on Frenshe men<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. <I>om</I>. 'men.'</NOTE> and on Englys,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at Frenshe men synne yn lecherye,</L>
<L N="4152">And Englys men yn enuye.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>John Morley, Speech in <I>Daily News</I>, June 27, 1894:&mdash;</P><P>"There is no better test of character in my judgment&mdash;whether individually or in public life&mdash;there is no better test of character than being able to work with other people. A friend of mine came back from the States the other day, and he said the worst feature in American life is the extraordinary distrust and suspicion which men there entertain of one another, and the readiness in which an inferior motive is found for conduct. I do not know whether that is a true account of America or not, but I am perfectly sure it is not true of my own country. (Hear, hear.) Englishmen are not suspicious, they are not jealous, <I>they are not envious</I>, and I think if they find themselves differing from this man or that upon this question or the other, that does not prevent them from being willing to listen to him upon other subjects upon which they have the happiness to agree. (Hear, hear.) Gentle|men, we hear a great deal of war between in|dividualists and collectivists. Well, I tell you frankly in practical affairs I for one am not very fond of these tickets and labels and solemn nick|names. They are very convenient for the purpose of vituperation, and no doubt a compact and handy nickname saves a lazy mind the trouble of thinking things out for itself; but I for one will never quarrel about a word, providing we are working for the same ends and marching towards the same goal. A great poet, who is the glory of the English race, name, and tongue, once used a sublime phrase. He speaks of the prophetic soul of the wide world dreaming on things to come. [Tennyson.] These beneficent dreams of a society elevated, purified, and renewed, must lead by many diverse ways and many hidden paths to their own realisation. I find no fault with them. They will enrich and vivify Liberalism. The great mission of realising, so far as realisation is practicable, those golden dreams, is the mission confided to our party, and I hope and believe that neither you nor I, in the various calls that may be made upon us, will be found unworthy of our trust." (Great cheering, amid which Mr. Morley resumed his seat.)</P></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>lecherye ys flesshly synne;</L>
<L>Enuye cum&thorn; of &thorn;e soule wy&thorn;-ynne;</L>
<L>lechery ys &thorn;e lesse, we fynde,</L>
<L N="4156">And enuye ys &thorn;e more vnkynde;</L>
<L>For y se noun yn hys lyue</L>
<L>&THORN;at of enuye kan hym shryue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh euery day a man hyt haunte,</L>
<L N="4160">&YOGH;yt wyl no man be hyt a-graunte.</L>
<L>Telle to any &thorn;at he ha&thorn; enuye,</L>
<L>He sey&thorn; a&yogh;en "hyt ys a lye."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'lesynge.'</NOTE></L>
<L>how mow &thorn;&eacute;y &thorn;an shryue &thorn;at synne,</L>
<L N="4164">&THORN;at seyn &thorn;ey haue no gylt &thorn;erynne?</L>
<L>we Englys men &thorn;eron shulde &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at enuy&euml; vs nat blynk.<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght blynke.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bakbytyng cum&thorn; also of enuye;</L>
<L N="4168">y haue &yogh;ow tolde of &thorn;at folye;</L>
<L>lykenes of hem men mowe bere,</L>
<L>A nedder and a bakbytere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e nedder make&thorn; &thorn;e semblant mylde,</L>
<L N="4172">And yn hys tayle ys venym wylde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bakbytere fary&thorn; ry&yogh;t so:</L>
<L>wy&thorn; mylde semblant he spekth &thorn;e to,</L>
<L>And yn hys tayle he bery&thorn; venym;</L>
<L>Behynde &thorn;y bak, he speky&thorn; wurdys grym.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4177">&THORN;e wys kyng Salamon</L>
<L>Sey&thorn; &thorn;ese wurdys to men echon:&mdash;</L>
<L>"hys lyppes," he sey&thorn;, "he shal make swete,</L>
<L N="4180">wy&thorn; feyr&euml; wurdys he shal &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L>But yn hys hert&euml; he shal &thorn;ynke</L>
<L>For to do &thorn;e a wykked blynke."</L>
<L>So ded &thorn;e traytur, fals Iudas,<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="142"></L>
<L N="4184">&THORN;at dampned ys wy&thorn; Satanas,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ys Iudas, foule felun,</L>
<L>weytede Ihesu with tresun.</L>
<L>Fyrst he grete hym and gan lagh,</L>
<L N="4188">And sy&thorn;en he kest hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn;en hym keste.</NOTE> &thorn;at alle men sagh,</L>
<L>And yn hys herte was tresun bolde,</L>
<L>For to &thorn;e Iew&euml;s he had hym solde.</L>
<L>'Treytur! recorde what &thorn;ou hast herde</L>
<L N="4192">Seyde and sunge yn al &thorn;e werlde.'</L>
<L>Vndyr heuene ne ys so moche tresun</L>
<L>As yn feyre wurd of hert felun.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, treytur, y tolde &thorn;e er,</L>
<L N="4196">&THORN;y wonyng ys wy&thorn; Lucyfer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yr may no man so yware be,&mdash;</L>
<L>For fors, ne wysdom, ne pouste,</L>
<L>For byhest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">beheste.</NOTE> ne for rychesse,</L>
<L N="4200">Ne powere, ne hardynesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, hardnesse H.</NOTE></L>
<L>For lynage, ne for onour,</L>
<L>For felawshepe, ne for socour,</L>
<L>Ne for bre&thorn;erhede, ne for spousayle,&mdash;</L>
<L N="4204">&THORN;at treytorhede ne wyl hym asayle;</L>
<L>Ne for sweryng, ne for awe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a treytur ne ha&thorn; yn &thorn;ys sum sawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>who was wyser &thorn;an Salamon?</L>
<L N="4208">who was feyrer &thorn;an Absolon?</L>
<L>who was rycher yn euery &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alaxandre &thorn;e ryche kyng?</L>
<L>who was swetter &thorn;an Ionatas,</L>
<L N="4212">Or better clerk &thorn;an Vyrgyle was?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese coude hem neuer were<NOTE PLACE="inter">kepe</NOTE></L>
<L>From treytur ne fro bakbytere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of a treytur, &thorn;ys ys &thorn;e resun smerte,
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="143"></L>
<L N="4216">with feyr&euml; wurdys, and felun herte;</L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP> Bakbytere, he ha&thorn; a lak,</L>
<L>He ys a treytur behynd &thorn;y bak;<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 <I>Harl</I>. omits these two lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e toon ys treytur yn &thorn;y present,</L>
<L N="4220">&THORN;e to&thorn;er ys whan &thorn;ou arte<NOTE PLACE="foot">art.</NOTE> went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lyer may be on of &thorn;yse,</L>
<L>For he ha&thorn; of bo&thorn;e a queyntyse,</L>
<L>Behynde &thorn;y bak, and eke before,<MILESTONE N="28b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4224">lesyng oueralle<NOTE PLACE="foot">oueral.</NOTE> ys bore,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ese &thorn;re men ys al tresun;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor hyt ys preued with resun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;es&euml; men, all&euml; &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="4228">Mowe neuer lyghtly saued be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostle sey&thorn; &thorn;at God hem hatys,</L>
<L>Ande ouer al ou&thorn;er wy&thorn; hem wlatys.<NOTE PLACE="inter">ys wrothe</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;arefore &yogh;yf any swyche men wore,</L>
<L N="4232">hyt behoue&thorn; betyme repente hem sore;</L>
<L>And leue hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt al.</NOTE> whyl &thorn;ey hau&euml; space,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an y hope &thorn;ey may fynde grace.</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue vs grace enuye to fle!</L>
<L N="4236">And alle treyturs, euyl mote &thorn;ey &thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[Of Sloth, the 4th Deadly Sin.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now shul we speke of sloghnes;</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e to&thorn;er ful wyk hyt ys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">es.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">vour&thorn;e.</NOTE> hyt ys of dedly synnes,</L>
<L N="4240">Alle &thorn;ese rych&euml; men hyt wynnes.</L>
<L>Moche ys a man for to blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at kan nat wurschep Goddys name</L>
<L>with pater noster ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> wy&thorn; crede,</L>
<L N="4244">&THORN;ys beleue shuld hym to heuene lede.</L>
<L>Ful slogh he ys &thorn;at wyl nat lere</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche fram&euml; blessed preyere;</L>
<L>And also he ys ful of slownes</L>
<L N="4248">&THORN;at may, and wyl nat, here hys messe,
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>Specyaly on &thorn;e Sunday</L>
<L>he trespasy&thorn; more<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e more.</NOTE> yn &thorn;e lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn &thorn;e woke, o day, &thorn;urgh ryght,</L>
<L N="4252">&THORN;e Sunday, ys a day of my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>how sey &thorn;ese men &thorn;at are &thorn;us slogh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">so slowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at oute of mesure slepe a throwe?</L>
<L>whan he hery&thorn; a bel ryng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">belle rynge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4256">To holy cherch&euml; men kallyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may he nat hys bedd&euml; lete</L>
<L>But &thorn;an behoue&thorn; hym to lygge and swete,</L>
<L>And take &thorn;e mery mornyng slepe;</L>
<L N="4260">Of matynes ryche men take no kepe</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey mowe ryse<NOTE PLACE="foot">aryse.</NOTE> at tyme of messe.<MILESTONE N="29a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e matynes, no&thorn;er more ne lesse</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys &thorn;ys Terlyncels skylle,</L>
<L N="4264">'Slepe &thorn;ou long, and y shal hele.'</L>
<L>he putte&thorn; heuenys yn hys y&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; hym lenger for to lye;</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; "al betyme mayst &thorn;ou ryse,</L>
<L N="4268">whan &thorn;ey do &thorn;e messe seruyse;</L>
<L>A messe ys ynogh for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er gyblot, late hyt be;</L>
<L>here mayst &thorn;ou bettyr slepe a throwe</L>
<L N="4272">&thorn;an sytte and loke vpp-on a wowe."</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e cunsel of Terlyncel;</L>
<L>yn alle sloghnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">slownes.</NOTE> he bere&thorn; &thorn;e bel;</L>
<L>he ys a deuyl of &thorn;at myster,</L>
<L N="4276">To sloghnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">slownes.</NOTE> he ys cunseler.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;an cum&thorn; one about&euml; pryme</L>
<L>"Rys up," he sey&thorn;, "now ys tyme."</L>
<L>&THORN;an begynne&thorn; he to klawe and to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'to.'</NOTE> raske,</L>
<L N="4280">And &yogh;yue&thorn; Terlyncel hys taske.</L>
<L>he klawy&thorn;, he shrubby&thorn;, wel at hys pay,</L>
<L>And maky&thorn; to Terlyncel a lay;</L>
<L N="4283">To hym &thorn;at kalled, he speke&thorn; stoutly,</L>
<L>"what deuyl! why ha&thorn; &thorn;e prest swych hy?
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>Byd hym &thorn;at he abyde algate;</L>
<L>Hym dar nat syng &yogh;yt ouer late."</L>
<L>For hym shal so Goddys seruyse abyde</L>
<L N="4288">Tyl hyt be passed ouer &thorn;e tyde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt perauenture, at hys rysyng,</L>
<L>Of God speke&thorn; he no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf hyt be of sum vanyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at renny&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ren&thorn;.</NOTE> yn hys &thorn;oght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ogh.</NOTE> &thorn;at speke&thorn; he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he cum&thorn; vnto &thorn;e messe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere behoue&thorn; hym hys here<NOTE PLACE="foot">heer.</NOTE> dresse;</L>
<L>Ful fewe bedys are yn hys mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4296">He vsy&thorn; none; &thorn;ey are vncouthe.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf a frere cum for to preche,</L>
<L>Of a dyner were bettyr speche;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sey&thorn; he, "God shal alle saue;<MILESTONE N="29a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4300">Do wel; wel shalt &thorn;ou haue."</L>
<L>Certys &thorn;at ys nat ynow,</L>
<L>For he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'he.'</NOTE> do&thorn; no &thorn;yng to prow.</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he wulde lestene &thorn;e frere,</L>
<L N="4304">To do weyl &thorn;an my&yogh;t he lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be nat &thorn;an redy, hys dyner,</L>
<L>Take fur&thorn;e &thorn;e chesse or &thorn;e tabler;</L>
<L>So shal he pley tyl hyt be none,</L>
<L N="4308">And Goddys seruyse be al done.</L>
<L>Alas, wykk&eacute;dly he dyspendy&thorn;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at God hym sendyth!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aftyr &thorn;e none, &thorn;an shal he do</L>
<L N="4312">As he dede before none so.</L>
<L>Swyche a lyfe &thorn;an shal he lede,</L>
<L>Noght &thorn;at he shal haue to mede;</L>
<L>yn alle hys lyfe shal he [nat] fynde</L>
<L N="4316">Oght &thorn;at may hym of pyne vnbynde;</L>
<L>No more he halt to God cunnaunt,</L>
<L>But weyl more to Termagaunt;</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="foot">He &thorn;at.</NOTE> ys no mor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">more a.</NOTE> crystyn man
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="4320">&THORN;an who so kally&thorn; a blak oxe 'swan.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>y dar weyl seye to hygh and logh,</L>
<L>yn Goddys seruyse are swych men slogh.</L>
<L>Swych synne men kalle 'accyde,'</L>
<L N="4324">yn Godd&euml;s seruyse slogh betyde.</L>
<L>lord! what shal swych men seye</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at poynt when &thorn;ey shul deye?</L>
<L>yn alle here lyfe ne roght<NOTE PLACE="foot">reyghete.</NOTE> &thorn;ey noght</L>
<L N="4328">Of hym &thorn;at hem ful der&euml; boght.</L>
<L>Ful gretly shul &thorn;ey hem repente</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e dome ys a&yogh;ens hem went;</L>
<L>But &thorn;an mow &thorn;ey do no bote;</L>
<L N="4332">Ylyche logh ly&thorn; bo&thorn;e hande and fote.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many swyche mow haue no grace</L>
<L N="4334">To repentaunce, no to space.</L>
<L>Hyt ys no wundyr &thorn;ogh &thorn;ey haue noun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wyl nat graunte &thorn;ey haue mysdoun,</L>
<L>Yn here lyfe, whyle &thorn;ey haue myght;<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;an shal God &yogh;elde alle with ryght.</L>
<L>Ful slogh &thorn;ey were when &thorn;ey shuld wyrk;</L>
<L N="4340">Yn tyme of traueyle were &thorn;ey yrk<NOTE PLACE="inter">[slow]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>&THORN;&eacute;y &thorn;oght nat of &thorn;at men spelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e gospelle:</L>
<L>"Be&thorn; wakyng," he sey&thorn;, to men alle;</L>
<L N="4344">"what tym&euml; &thorn;at &yogh;oure lorde wyl kalle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &yogh;e lest&euml; wene</L>
<L>He wul &yogh;ow kalle; loke &yogh;e be clene;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &yogh;e slepe at hys kallyng</L>
<L N="4348">&YOGH;e shul nat come yn at &thorn;e weddyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys yche lorde kalle&thorn; vs euery day,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; &thorn;e prechour, alle &thorn;at he may.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e are slogh, and lyen to slepe,</L>
<L N="4352">whan &yogh;e a&yogh;ens &thorn;e prechur &thorn;repe;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mow nat come yn to &thorn;e weddyng,&mdash;</L>
<L>Heuene blys ys &thorn;e menyng;&mdash;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e slepe yn wykked wyl,
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="147"></L>
<L N="4356">And wyl nat shryue &yogh;ow of &yogh;oure yl.</L>
<L>&yogh;e wen&euml; &thorn;at God shal &yogh;ow &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>Yn wykkednes, long to leue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e here sey&euml; &thorn;at sum whyle,</L>
<L N="4360">Yn swych&euml; hope go&thorn; moch&euml; gyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lytyl tale y shal &yogh;ow<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits '&yogh;ow.'</NOTE> vndo</L>
<L>Of a man &thorn;at hoped so,</L>
<L>As telly&thorn; &thorn;e holy man, seynt Bede,</L>
<L N="4364">Yn gestys of Ingland &thorn;at men rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the English Squire who put off his Repentance till too late.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a kyng, 'Conred'<NOTE PLACE="foot">coured O.</NOTE> he hyght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Atale.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Merc&euml; was hys kyngdom ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;e Merce hyght &thorn;an, as y herd seye,</L>
<L N="4368">&THORN;at men kalle now Lynd&euml;seye.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys Conred<NOTE PLACE="foot">coured O.</NOTE> had a seriaunt,</L>
<L>A wys man, and of body vaylaunt;</L>
<L>yn armys was<NOTE PLACE="foot">was he.</NOTE> a doghty squyere,</L>
<L N="4372">yn alle &thorn;e lande ne was hys pere.</L>
<L>Of a vyce, he hadde sum deyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man myght trowe him weyl;</L>
<L>where &thorn;at he myght make a wanlace,<MILESTONE N="29b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4376">And any &thorn;yng to &thorn;e kyng purchace,</L>
<L>He ne lette for no fals oth,</L>
<L>Ne for wra&thorn;&thorn;e of lefe ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> loth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne made ofte dysheresun,</L>
<L>And holy cherche traueylede with tresun.</L>
<L>For wrong ne lefte he ny&yogh;t ne day,</L>
<L>But onely<NOTE PLACE="foot">onely &thorn;at.</NOTE> he serued &thorn;e kyng to pay;</L>
<L N="4383">He ne &yogh;af tale of shame ne synne,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at onely he myght rycchesse wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yr fyl on hym a syknes<NOTE PLACE="foot">a syknes on hym.</NOTE> so stronge</L>
<L>&THORN;at he lay yn hys bedd&euml; long.</L>
<L N="4387">Sone aftyr betydde a lyte
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="148"></L>
<L N="4388">&THORN;e kyng come, hym to vysyte,</L>
<L>And bad hym be of r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>And shryue hys synne for all&euml; chaunce;</L>
<L>"Forsake now," he seyde, "alle &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, &thorn;e H.</NOTE> mys|dede,</L>
<L N="4392">And y shal fynde &thorn;e at &thorn;y nede."</L>
<L>He seyde, "so shall y aftyrwarde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y may skape &thorn;ys euyl harde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an shal y do oueral ryght,</L>
<L N="4396">And &yogh;eue me al to God almyght;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of myght.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;yt wyl y do hyt yn respyte</L>
<L>Tyl y be of &thorn;ys euyl alle quyte;</L>
<L>Y wul<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde.</NOTE> nat be founde so vyl</L>
<L N="4400">&THORN;at myn herte were yn swyche peryl</L>
<L>To repente me for a lytyl syknes,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf y were yn harder stres.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y, for dred&euml;, aske a preste,</L>
<L N="4404">&THORN;at shame shulde al day<NOTE PLACE="foot">al day shulde.</NOTE> be me neste</L>
<L>&THORN;at y were a-ferd of &thorn;e ded.</L>
<L>Y wyl nat &yogh;yt do at &thorn;y rede;</L>
<L>But lef&euml; syre, laty&thorn; me lye;</L>
<L N="4408">Alle &thorn;at &yogh;e seye, me &thorn;ynke&thorn; folye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kyng lettyd &thorn;arfor&euml; no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>To leue hys synne, efte he hym besoght,</L>
<L>For he helde hym of gret&euml; prys</L>
<L N="4412">For &thorn;at he was bo&thorn;e doghty and wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ys ys a custummable &thorn;yng<MILESTONE N="30a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now, wy&thorn; eu&euml;ry lordyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lordynge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;yf his stuwarde hym oght wynne,</L>
<L N="4416">Be hyt wy&thorn; ryght, or wy&thorn; synne,</L>
<L>Hym wyl he hold&euml; most pryue</L>
<L>Of all&euml; &thorn;o &thorn;at wy&thorn; hym be.</L>
<L>But as he take&thorn; &thorn;erof &thorn;e frame,</L>
<L>He shal haue parte of synne and shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4421">&thorn;e kyng come eft to &thorn;e seriaunt,</L>
<L>And bad hym to be r&eacute;pentaunt,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk on hys saluacyun,</L>
<L>And shryue hys synne &thorn;at he had doun.
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>"Syre," he seyd, "&thorn;ys ys my chaunce,</L>
<L>Hyt ys noght my r&eacute;pentaunce;</L>
<L>For, lang&eacute;r as y here lay,</L>
<L N="4428">Ry&yogh;t at &thorn;e oure of mydday,</L>
<L>Twey &yogh;unge men come hedyr to me,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feyrest &thorn;at any man myght se;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;oght, ry&yogh;t whan y sagh &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4432">&THORN;at y felt no &thorn;yng of wo.</L>
<L>Byfore my bedde &thorn;ey stode a &thorn;rowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'whyle.'</NOTE></L>
<L>And behelde me as they shuld me knowe;</L>
<L>when &thorn;ey had stonde a lytyl tyde,</L>
<L N="4436">&THORN;ey set hem doune on my bedde syde.</L>
<L>when &thorn;ey set were, fur&thorn; &thorn;ey toke</L>
<L>And shewed a lytyl feyr&euml; boke,</L>
<L>And bad me &thorn;at y shuld hyt rede,</L>
<L N="4440">For alle hyt was myn own&euml; dede;</L>
<L>And y &thorn;at neuer on bok&euml; cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Alle y hyt red with opun mou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e gode dedys &thorn;at euer y wroght,</L>
<L N="4444">Alle were &thorn;ere before me broght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lest&euml; &thorn;oght &thorn;at y coulde &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of godenesse hadde any blynke,</L>
<L>Alle y sagh hyt before me,</L>
<L N="4448">For lytyl was hyt vnto se;</L>
<L>For less&euml; my&yogh;t neuer haue bene</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any man hyt shulde haue sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"when y hadde redde&thorn;at y myght rede,<MILESTONE N="3012a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey shette here boke, and fur&thorn; &thorn;ey &yogh;ede.</L>
<L N="4453">Sone aftyrward whan &thorn;ey were gone,</L>
<L>Come ou&thorn;er two, sone anone;</L>
<L>Blak &thorn;ey were, and foule stynkyng,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; glesyng y&yogh;en, and mou&thorn;e grennyng;</L>
<L N="4457">&THORN;ey come and stod&euml; on my bedde;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;oght y wax nygh wode for dredde;</L>
<L>Y turned me on euery syde,</L>
<L N="4460">From hem myght y nat me<NOTE PLACE="foot">me nat.</NOTE> hyde;</L>
<L>And as y me went hem to fle
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>Euer &thorn;ey wer&euml; a&yogh;ens me.</L>
<L>But whan y sagh no better bote,</L>
<L N="4464">Y lay stylle bo&thorn;e hand and fote;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey had traueyled me so with yl,</L>
<L>A stound&euml; sate &thorn;ey by me styl</L>
<L>And drogh fur&thorn; a moch&euml; boke,&mdash;</L>
<L N="4468">&THORN;e most &thorn;at y euer on gan loke:</L>
<L>So grete hyt was and so orryble,</L>
<L>&thorn;er-yn was more &thorn;an yn a byble;&mdash;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at y haue do wy&thorn; synne,</L>
<L N="4472">Euery dele ys wryte &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>And euery wurde with sorow and pyne</L>
<L>&THORN;ey made me red&euml;, maugre myne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lest&euml; wurde &thorn;at euer y &thorn;oght,</L>
<L N="4476">&THORN;at vnto synne a-mountede oght,</L>
<L>was yn &thorn;at boke ful &thorn;ykly dreuyn,</L>
<L>was none for&yogh;etyn ne for&yogh;euyn;</L>
<L>And alle y redde, bo&thorn;e lesse and more;</L>
<L N="4480">&THORN;at was &thorn;e pyne &thorn;at pyned me sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan hyt was redd euerydeyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;e boke was shet, and leyd vp weyl.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &yogh;aue to me sy&thorn;en alle here entent,</L>
<L N="4484">For to here wylle, y am alle went.</L>
<L>Twey brennyng knyuys &thorn;ey oute drogh,</L>
<L>And seyd, "Do we oure ded&euml; nowe;</L>
<L>Do we swy&thorn;e, and noght we dwelle,</L>
<L N="4488">And hast we vs wy&thorn; hym to helle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e toon &thorn;urgh myn hed&euml; smote<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wy&thorn; &thorn;e knyfe &thorn;at was so hote;</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er smote me yn-to &thorn;e fete</L>
<L N="4492">&THORN;at almost to-gedyr &thorn;e strok&euml;s mete;</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;ey are to gedyr y-come,</L>
<L>And haue my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn.</NOTE> herte betwyxe hem nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;an shal y dey, and henn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, hen H.</NOTE> wende</L>
<L N="4496">with &thorn;ese to helle with-outyn ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wharto shuld y &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an shulde y.</NOTE> me repente
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>whan y wote my Iug&euml;ment?</L>
<L>And, &thorn;ogh y myght lenger lyue,</L>
<L N="4500">No man my&yogh;t hem me for&yogh;yue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y shulde haue any grace,</L>
<L>y shulde haue asked whan y had space;</L>
<L>But now y wote, ys al to late,</L>
<L N="4504">O poynt of my pyne to abate.<NOTE PLACE="foot">bate.</NOTE></L>
<L>My synnes are grete, and many one;</L>
<L>For&yogh;eu&euml;nes shal be ryght none."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle he tolde &thorn;ys to &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="4508">And asswy&thorn;e made hys endyng;</L>
<L>And &yogh;ede to helle, and was forlore</L>
<L>For sloghnes, as y tolde byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan a man ys slogh, and wyl nat do</L>
<L N="4512">&THORN;at holy cherche techy&thorn; hym to,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens God he ys froward,</L>
<L>And yn hys synne he wexe&thorn; hard;</L>
<L>&THORN;an putty&thorn; &thorn;e fende yn hys &thorn;oght</L>
<L N="4516">&THORN;at hys synne ys lytyl or noght;</L>
<L>And when tyme wer&euml;, mercy calle,</L>
<L>yn wanhope, he make&thorn; hym falle.</L>
<L N="4519">And alle ys &thorn;ys for slogh&thorn;ehede,</L>
<L>whan man betyme wyl haue no drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore sey&thorn; &thorn;e kyng Salamon</L>
<L>"Be&thorn; nat ydul, neuer none,"</L>
<L>For &yogh;oure gode dedys, &yogh;e shul hem fynde,</L>
<L N="4524">Oute of pyne &thorn;ey wyl &yogh;ow vnbynde.</L>
<L>he &thorn;at ys slogh yn euery gode dede,</L>
<L>what shal helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">helpe hym.</NOTE> whan he ha&thorn; nede?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e holyman spek&thorn; of a synne<MILESTONE N="30b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4528">Of sloghnes, &thorn;at men falle<NOTE PLACE="foot">are.</NOTE> ynne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at any shuld oght weyl do,</L>
<L>hym lo&thorn;y&thorn; so gretly &thorn;arto</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fondy&thorn; on all&euml; wyse</L>
<L N="4532">To do hyt on &thorn;e werst asyse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he of Godys wurde oght here,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof hym &thorn;ynke&thorn; an hundred &yogh;ere;
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he be at any pleyyng</L>
<L>At &thorn;e ale house, or at any ou&thorn;er ianglyng</L>
<L N="4540">For to rage wy&thorn; ylka fyle<NOTE PLACE="inter">maydgerle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> eury maydegerlde.</NOTE></NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;enke&thorn; hym but lytyl whyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn goddys seruyse are swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swylke.</NOTE> men yrk<NOTE PLACE="inter">slow</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="4540">when &thorn;ey come vn-to &thorn;e kyrke</L>
<L>To here matynys or mess&euml; song,</L>
<L>hem &thorn;enke&thorn; hyt lasty&thorn; ouer long;</L>
<L>&THORN;an shal he iangle, or telle a tale,</L>
<L>Or wyte where &thorn;ey shul haue &thorn;e beste ale.</L>
<L N="4545">Swyche synne ys kalled 'accyde,'</L>
<L>yn gode dede to be slogh, or long abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf any man be coupable yn &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>yn swyche poyntys &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> omits 'he.'</NOTE> haue do mys,</L>
<L N="4549">Be he hygh or be he logh,</L>
<L>He ys yn Goddys seruyse slogh.</L>
<L>But whan men heryn of &thorn;ys preche,</L>
<L N="4552">&THORN;at god of swyche wyl tak&euml; wreche;</L>
<L>'A!' lyghtly &thorn;ey sey, as hyt may falle,</L>
<L>'God haue mercy on vs alle;'</L>
<L>As who seye '&yogh;yf he wyl vs saue,</L>
<L N="4556">Or &yogh;yf he wyl nat; late vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> beleue.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nay, nay, hyt may nat be so,</L>
<L>&THORN;yr behoue&thorn; more &thorn;arto;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gettyst nat heuene so lyghtly</L>
<L N="4560">But &thorn;ou do yn dede more why.</L>
<L>Prey hym fyrst he &yogh;eue &thorn;e &thorn;at mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayst serue hym wel yn dede:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou praye &thorn;us and sy&thorn;en wel do,</L>
<L N="4564">So mayst &thorn;ou come hys mercy to;</L>
<L>And nat yn ydylnes, as &yogh;e &thorn;ynke,<MILESTONE N="31a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wel to ete and wel to drynke,</L>
<L>And ofte to swer&euml; at youre wyl,
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="153"></L>
<L N="4568">whan no man charge&thorn; &yogh;ow &thorn;ar tyl:</L>
<L>So come to heuene, hyt may nat be,</L>
<L>For, God hadde hyt neuer so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Against Tournaments.]</HEAD>
<L>Of tournamentys &thorn;at are forbede</L>
<L N="4572">yn holy cherch&euml;, as men rede,</L>
<L>Of tournamentys y preue &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>Seuene poynt&euml;s of dedly synne:</L>
<L>Fyrst, ys pryde, as &thorn;ou wel wost,</L>
<L N="4576">Auaunt&euml;ment, bobaunce, and bost;</L>
<L>Of ryche atyre ys here auaunce,</L>
<L>Prykyng here hors with olypraunce.</L>
<L>wete &thorn;ou wel &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yr.</NOTE> ys enuye</L>
<L N="4580">whan one see&thorn; ano&thorn;er do maystrye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">more maystrie.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er yn wurdys, o&thorn;er yn dedys;</L>
<L>Enuye moste of alle hem ledys.</L>
<L N="4583">Yre and wra&thorn;&thorn;e may &thorn;ey nat late;</L>
<L>Ofte are tournamentys made for hate.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf euery kny&yogh;t louede o&thorn;er weyl,</L>
<L>Tournamentes shulde be neuer a deyl;</L>
<L N="4587">And certys &thorn;ey falle yn sloghnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey loue hyt more &thorn;an God o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or.</NOTE> messe;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;erof ys hyt no doute,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey dyspende more gode &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yr.</NOTE> aboute&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;at ys &yogh;eue all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> to folye&mdash;</L>
<L N="4592">&THORN;an to any dede of mercy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;yt may nat, on no wyse,</L>
<L>Be forgete dame coueytyse,</L>
<L>For she shal fonde, on all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> wyse,</L>
<L N="4596">To wynn&euml; hors, and harnyse.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt shal he make sum robbery,</L>
<L>Or bygyle hys hoste &thorn;er he shal lye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Glotonye also ys hem among,
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="154"></L>
<L N="4600">Delycyus metes to make hem strong;</L>
<L>And drynke &thorn;e wyne &thorn;at he were lyght,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; glotonye to make hym wyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;ere dame lecherye;<MILESTONE N="31a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4604">Of here cum&thorn; all&euml; here maystrye.</L>
<L>Many tymes, for wymmen sake,</L>
<L>knyghteys tournamentys make;</L>
<L>And whan he wendy&thorn; to &thorn;e tournament</L>
<L N="4608">She sendy&thorn; hym sum pryuy present,</L>
<L>And byt hym do for hys lemman</L>
<L>Yn vasshelage<NOTE PLACE="foot">vasselage.</NOTE> alle &thorn;at he kan;</L>
<L>So ys he bete &thorn;ere, for here loue,</L>
<L N="4612">&THORN;at he ne may sytte hys hors aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at perauenture, yn alle hys lyue</L>
<L>Shal he neuer aftyr &thorn;ryue.</L>
<L>loke now whedyr swyche tournours<NOTE PLACE="foot">tourneours.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4616">Mow be kall&euml;d turmentours?</L>
<L>For, &thorn;ey turmente alle with synne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere tourment ys, &thorn;er shul &thorn;ey ynne,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey leu&euml; swyche myschaunce,</L>
<L N="4620">And for here synn&euml; do penaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also y tell&euml; by iustyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;&eacute;r-of cum&thorn; myschefful &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>Alle ys &thorn;e toon with &thorn;e tou&thorn;er,</L>
<L>As a shyppe &thorn;at ys turned with &thorn;e ro&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4625">And &thorn;ese bourdys of &thorn;ese squyers,</L>
<L>Also haue &thorn;ey made for swyche maners</L>
<L>Of pryd&euml;, hat&euml;, and enuye,</L>
<L>Sloghtnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sloghnes.</NOTE> coueytyse, and glotonye:</L>
<L N="4629">lecherye mak&thorn; hem alle to bygynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese wymmen are partyners of &thorn;ere synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A clerk of order &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e name,</L>
<L N="4632">&YOGH;yf he iuste, he ys to blame,</L>
<L>Hyt were wur&thorn;y &thorn;at had &thorn;e gre,</L>
<L>Brokyn &thorn;e arm&euml;, legge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">or lege.</NOTE> or thee;</L>
<L>hyt ys forso&thorn;e, &yogh;yf he so werche,
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="155"></L>
<L N="4636">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e state of holy cherche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hyt ys forbode hym, yn &thorn;e decre,</L>
<L>Myr&aacute;cles for to make or se;</L>
<L>For, myr&aacute;cles &yogh;yf &thorn;ou bygynne,</L>
<L N="4640">Hyt ys a gaderyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, gaderynt, H.</NOTE> a syght of synne,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He may yn &thorn;e cherche, &thorn;urgh &thorn;ys resun,<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Pley &thorn;e resurreccyun,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to sey&euml;, how God ros,</L>
<L N="4644">God and man yn my&yogh;t and los,&mdash;</L>
<L>To make men be yn beleu&euml; gode</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ros with flesshe and blode;</L>
<L>And he may pleye, withoutyn plyght</L>
<L N="4648">howe God was bore yn &yogh;ol&euml; nyght,</L>
<L>To make men to beleue stedfastly</L>
<L>&THORN;at he lyght yn &thorn;e vyrgyne Mary.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou do hyt yn weyys or greuys,</L>
<L N="4652">A syght of synne truly hyt semys.</L>
<L>Seynt Ysodre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Isidre.</NOTE> y take to wyttnes,</L>
<L>For he hyt sey&thorn;, &thorn;at so&thorn;e hyt es;</L>
<L>&thorn;us hyt sey&thorn;, yn hys boke,</L>
<L N="4656">&THORN;ey forsak&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ey toke&mdash;</L>
<L>God and her&euml; crystendam&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at make swyche pleyys to any man</L>
<L>As myr&aacute;cles and<NOTE PLACE="foot">or.</NOTE> bourdys,</L>
<L N="4660">Or tournamentys of grete prys.</L>
<L>&thorn;ese are &thorn;e pompes &thorn;at &thorn;ou forsoke,</L>
<L>Fryst<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fyrst.</NOTE> whan &thorn;ou &thorn;y crystendam toke.</L>
<L N="4663">At &thorn;e fonte, sey&thorn; &thorn;e lewed man,</L>
<L>"y forsake &thorn;e, here, Satan,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;y pompes and all thy werkys:"</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;y lore, aftyr &thorn;e clerkys.</L>
<L>haldyst &thorn;ou forward, e, certys nay,</L>
<L N="4668">whan &thorn;ou makyst swyche a-dray?</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens God &thorn;ou brekest cunnaunt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">cumnaunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seruyst &yogh;oure syre, Termagaunt.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="156"></L>
<L>Seynt Ysodre sey&thorn; yn hys wrytyng,</L>
<L N="4672">'Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at delyte to se swyche &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Or hors or harneys leny&thorn; &thorn;ar-tyl;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'to.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yt haue &thorn;ey gylt of here peryl.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf prest or clerk lene vest&euml;ment<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. vestment.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4676">&THORN;at halwed ys &thorn;urgh sacrament;</L>
<L>More &thorn;an ou&thorn;er &thorn;ey are to blame,</L>
<L>Of sacrylege &thorn;ey haue &thorn;e fame:</L>
<L>Fam&euml;, for &thorn;ey falle yn plyght,<MILESTONE N="31b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey shuld be chastysed<NOTE PLACE="foot">chastyed.</NOTE> &thorn;erfor with ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4681">Daunces, karols, somour games,</L>
<L>Of many swych come many shames;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou stodyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">stodyyst.</NOTE> to mak&euml; &thorn;yse,</L>
<L N="4684">&THORN;ou art slogh yn Goddys seruyse;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at synnen yn swych &thorn;urgh &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For hem &thorn;ou shalt a-couped be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what seye &yogh;e by euery mynstral,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn swyche &thorn;ynges delyte hem alle?</L>
<L N="4689">Here doyng ys ful perylous,</L>
<L>Hyt loueth no&thorn;er God ne goddys house;</L>
<L>Hem were leuer here of a daunce,</L>
<L N="4692">Of host, and of olypraunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;an any gode of God of heuene,</L>
<L>Or ou&thorn;er wysdom &thorn;at were to neuene.</L>
<L>Yn foly ys all&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ey gete,</L>
<L>here cloth, here drynk&euml;, and here mete.</L>
<L N="4697">And, for swych &thorn;yng, telle y shal,</L>
<L>what byfyl onys of a mynstral:</L>
<L>Seynt Gregorye telle&thorn; yn hys spell</L>
<L N="4700">how hyt of a mynstral fell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Minstrel who was kild for disturbing a Bishop.]</HEAD>
<L>A mynstralle, a gulardous,</L>
<L>Come onys to a bysshopes hous<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>And asked &thorn;ere &thorn;e charyte;</L>
<L N="4704">&THORN;e porter lete hym haue entre;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At tyme of mete, &thorn;e bourde was leyd,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e benesun shuld be seyd;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys mynstral made hys melody</L>
<L N="4708">with gret&euml; noyse, and loude, and hy.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e bysshope, &thorn;e fam&euml; ran</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was an holy man;</L>
<L N="4711">&THORN;e bysshope sette hym at &thorn;e bourde,</L>
<L>And shuld haue blessed hyt with wurde;</L>
<L>So was he sturbled with &thorn;e mynstral,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde no grace to sey with<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl.</NOTE> -alle</L>
<L>His graces ryght deuout&euml;ly</L>
<L N="4716">For &thorn;e noyse of &thorn;e mynstralsy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bysshope pleyned hym ful sore,<MILESTONE N="32a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seyd to all&euml; &thorn;at were &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne shulde make hys nycete</L>
<L N="4720">Before the graces of &thorn;e charyte.</L>
<L>He sagh hyt weyl, &thorn;urgh &thorn;e spryt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spyryt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er shuld come veniaunce astyt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">alstyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;yue&thorn; hym &thorn;e charyte, &amp; laty&thorn; hym go;</L>
<L N="4724">Hys de&thorn; ys nygh, &thorn;at shal hym slo."</L>
<L>He toke charyte, and toke hys gate;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'weye.'</NOTE></L>
<L>And as he passed out at &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>A ston&euml; fyl down of &thorn;e wal,</L>
<L N="4728">And slogh &thorn;er&euml; &thorn;e mynstral.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at betokened &thorn;at God was noght</L>
<L>Payd of &thorn;at &thorn;e mynstral wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he desturbled &thorn;e benesoun</L>
<L N="4732">And &thorn;e gode mannys deuocyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tolde y for &thorn;e glemennes sake,</L>
<L>To loke whan &thorn;ey here gle shuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">shul.</NOTE> make;</L>
<L>And also for &thorn;o &thorn;at shuld hyt here,</L>
<L N="4736">&THORN;at &thorn;ey loue hyt nat so dere,
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>Ne haue &thorn;erynne so grete lykyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lesse to wurschyp heuene kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[A Tale of Bishop St. Robert Grostest of Lincoln, and why he lovd Music.]</HEAD>
<L>Y shall &yogh;ow telle, as y haue herd,</L>
<L N="4740">Of &thorn;e bysshope Seynt Roberd;</L>
<L>Hys tonam&euml; ys 'Grostest</L>
<L>Of Lynkolne,' so sey&thorn; &thorn;e gest.</L>
<L>he loued moche to here &thorn;e harpe,</L>
<L N="4744">For mannys wytte hyt maky&thorn; sharpe;</L>
<L>Next hys chaumbre, besyde hys stody,</L>
<L>Hys harpers chaumbre was fast &thorn;erby.</L>
<L>Many tymes, be ny&yogh;tys and dayys,</L>
<L N="4748">He had solace of notes and layys.</L>
<L>One asked hym onys, resun why</L>
<L>he hadde delyte yn mynstralsy:</L>
<L>he answerede hym on &thorn;ys manere,</L>
<L N="4752">why he helde &thorn;e harper<NOTE PLACE="foot">harpe.</NOTE> so dere,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e vertu of &thorn;e harpe, &thorn;urgh skylle &amp; ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>wyl destroye &thorn;e fend&euml;s my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e croys by god&euml; skylle<MILESTONE N="32a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4756">Ys &thorn;e harp&euml; lykened weyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er poynt cumf&oacute;rte&thorn; me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God ha&thorn; sent vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, to H.</NOTE> a tre</L>
<L>So moch&euml; ioye to here with eere;</L>
<L N="4760">Moche &thorn;an mor&euml; ioye ys &thorn;ere</L>
<L>with God hym-self&euml;, &thorn;ere he wonys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e harpe &thorn;erof me oft&euml; mones;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ioye and of &thorn;e blys</L>
<L N="4764">where God hym-self wonys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wone&thorn;.</NOTE> and ys.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for, gode men, &yogh;e shul lere,</L>
<L>whan &yogh;e any glemen here,</L>
<L>To wurschep God at &yogh;oure powere,</L>
<L N="4768">As Dauyd sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e sautere,</L>
<L>"yn harpe, yn thabour, and symphan gle,</L>
<L>wurschepe God, yn troumpes, and sautre,
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>yn cordys, an<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn.</NOTE> organes, and bellys ryngyng,</L>
<L>yn al &thorn;ese, wurschepe &yogh;e heuene kyng."</L>
<L N="4773">&YOGH;yf &yogh;e do &thorn;us, y sey hardly,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mow here &yogh;oure mynstralsy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou lygg&euml; long yn synne,</L>
<L N="4776">And wylt nat ryse, ne &thorn;erof blynne,</L>
<L>Certeynly, for euery oure</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt &yogh;elde a-counte ful soure;</L>
<L>For euery oure &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;eryn lay</L>
<L N="4780">Yn purgatorye &thorn;ou gest &thorn;y pay.</L>
<L>Hyt ys sloghnes, and kalled 'accyde,'</L>
<L>Fro Goddys seruyse so long &thorn;e hyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And some, alle &thorn;e &yogh;ere wyllyn abyde</L>
<L N="4784">Of shryft&euml; tyl &thorn;e lentyn tyde;</L>
<L>And nygh tyl lentyn be al gone</L>
<L>Mede for fastyng gete &thorn;ey none;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys, for sloghnes &thorn;ey wyl nat ryse;</L>
<L N="4788">lyggyng yn synne, ys lore seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And, sum men, yn alle here lyue,</L>
<L>Clenly ne wyl&euml; &thorn;ey hem shryue;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey synne alle yn hope of grace,</L>
<L N="4792">At here endyng wene &thorn;ey haue space;</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;enk&euml; &thorn;ey to shryue hem clene:<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To swyche men, God shewe&thorn; hys tene.</L>
<L>Hyt ys seyd al day, for &thorn;ys skyl,</L>
<L N="4796">"he &thorn;at wyl nat whan he may,</L>
<L>He shal nat, when he wyl, [haue pay.]"</L>
<L>And &thorn;er by&thorn; many one ful euyl to wynne</L>
<L N="4800">To any godenes fro vyl&euml; synne;</L>
<L>Euyl tokyn hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits 'ys.'</NOTE> of swyche a man,</L>
<L>God hym deme; for y ne kan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;yr are ou&thorn;er &thorn;at mys dous,</L>
<L N="4804">As a best,<NOTE PLACE="foot">beste.</NOTE> for defaute &thorn;at go&thorn; lous.</L>
<L>But whan men tech&euml; hem &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey wyl do as men hem sey;
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>A tokyn hyt ys, &thorn;ey shul haue grace</L>
<L N="4808">To come to God, and hau&euml; space.</L>
<L>And he may hope of euyl endyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at non&euml; may to God&euml; brynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A slogh messagere, hys wylland,</L>
<L N="4812">&THORN;at charged ys wy&thorn; lordes erand,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he go nat as he ys sent,</L>
<L>He ys wur&thorn;y to be shent.</L>
<L>Man &thorn;at wel spedy&thorn; hym yn dede,</L>
<L N="4816">And mess&aacute;ger smart at nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul stonde byfore &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>And hau&euml; mede to here askyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A persone ys slogh yn holy cherche</L>
<L N="4820">&THORN;at on hys shep&euml; wyl nat werche</L>
<L>How &thorn;ey shul hem-self[&euml;] &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>And God and holy cherche to queme.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hygh&euml; shepard shal hym blame,</L>
<L N="4824">how he late&thorn; hem go to shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf he se yn any &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey haue defaute of chastysyng,</L>
<L>But he teche hem and chastyse so</L>
<L N="4828">&THORN;at &thorn;ey forward better do,</L>
<L>For hem he shal, at &thorn;e assyse,</L>
<L>Be ponysshed before &thorn;e hygh Iustyse.</L>
<L>Also behoue&thorn; hym, for hem pray,</L>
<L N="4832">&THORN;at God, of grace, wysse hem &thorn;e wey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf any of hem defaut&euml; has,<MILESTONE N="32b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he may helpe hem yn &thorn;at kas,</L>
<L>And wyl nat, for vnkyndhede,</L>
<L N="4836">But late hem perysshe &thorn;er for nede,</L>
<L>Ful harde a-count&euml; shal he &yogh;elde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;t helpe whan he ne welde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he kyndly vndyrstode,</L>
<L N="4840">Of hem he ha&thorn; al hys gode;
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>For, God sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e gospel &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>Vpbreydyng hem when &thorn;ey do mys:</L>
<L N="4843">&THORN;e mylke, &thorn;e wulle, &thorn;ey wyl receyue;</L>
<L>And sy&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e shepe &thorn;ey wyle late weyue.</L>
<L>Holy wryt&euml; swyche men holdes</L>
<L>As wyld&euml; wulu&euml;s brekyng foldes.</L>
<L>Swyche a person&euml; ys ful slogh,</L>
<L N="4848">Be he hygh, or be he logh.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Man or womman &thorn;at ha&thorn; a chylde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wy&thorn; vn&thorn;ewys wexy&thorn; wylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyl bo&thorn;e myssey and do,</L>
<L N="4852">Chastysment behoue&thorn; &thorn;arto;</L>
<L>But &yogh;e hem chastyse at &yogh;oure my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e falle, ellys, for hem yn ply&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Better were &thorn;e chylde vnbore</L>
<L>&THORN;an fayle chastysyng, and sy&thorn;&thorn;en lore.</L>
<L N="4857">&THORN;us seyth &thorn;e wys kyng Salamonn</L>
<L>To men and wymmen euerychonn,</L>
<L>"wyle &yogh;e &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. &thorn;et.</NOTE> &yogh;oure chyldryn<NOTE PLACE="foot">chylder.</NOTE> be a-ferd,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;euyf.</NOTE> hem &thorn;e smert ende of &thorn;e &yogh;erde;"</L>
<L>And teche&thorn; hem gode &thorn;ewys echone;</L>
<L N="4862">&YOGH;yt dur &yogh;ow brek&euml; hem no bone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Father that would not chastise his Child.]</HEAD>
<L>y shal &yogh;ow telle a wundyr &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4864">&THORN;at fylle for defaute of chastysyng:</L>
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn;, &thorn;at moch&euml; kan,</L>
<L>Of a fol&euml; husbunde man</L>
<L>&THORN;at hatede a chylde &thorn;at he fur&thorn;e broght</L>
<L>wykkedly, for he chastyed hym noght.</L>
<L N="4869">&THORN;ys chylde was wur&thorn;y for to blame,</L>
<L>For ofte he cursed Goddys name;</L>
<L>whan aght was do a&yogh;ens hys wylle,</L>
<L N="4872">He cursede Goddys name wy&thorn; ylle.
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>Seynt Gregory telly&thorn; hyt wy&thorn; grete eye;</L>
<L>But as he sey&thorn;, &thorn;an dar y seye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; chyld [sone] aftyrward</L>
<L N="4876">Fyl yn[to] a syknes hard;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fadyr hadde &thorn;erof pyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chyld he daunted on hys kne,</L>
<L>And hadd&euml; &thorn;arfor moch&euml; kare</L>
<L N="4880">&THORN;at he sagh hys chylde so fare;</L>
<L>For hyt began to braye and crye</L>
<L>As, &thorn;ogh hyt shuld al to-flye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fadyr asked, why hyt so ferde,</L>
<L N="4884">Or what hyt sagh, or what hyt herde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chyld&euml; seyd "blake men, blake,</L>
<L>Are about&euml;, me to take;</L>
<L>Me, wy&thorn; hem, wyl &thorn;ey lede,</L>
<L N="4888">Y ne shal skap&euml; for no nede."</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e fadrys<NOTE PLACE="foot">faders.</NOTE> bosum hyt wulde hym hyde,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e fende, &thorn;at ych&euml; tyde,</L>
<L>Refte &thorn;e saul&euml; vnto helle.</L>
<L N="4892">&THORN;an began &thorn;e chylde to &yogh;elle,</L>
<L>And cursed onys Goddys name,</L>
<L>And deyde, and &yogh;ede<NOTE PLACE="foot">wente.</NOTE> to helle with shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys yche chylde &thorn;at y haue of tolde,</L>
<L N="4896">was but fyu&euml; wyntyr olde.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e chylde &thorn;at was so &yogh;unge</L>
<L>was lore for faute of chastysynge.</L>
<L N="4899">But &thorn;e fadyr, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits '&thorn;at.'</NOTE> no gode cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>My&yogh;te haue chasty&euml;d hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> with mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Stoutly, for euery a lak,</L>
<L>And bet&euml; hyt, whan hyt so spak.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oueral y se &thorn;ys custome wonys;</L>
<L N="4904">Rych&euml; men haue shrewed sonys,&mdash;</L>
<L>Shrewys yn ded&euml; and yn sawe,&mdash;</L>
<L>why? For &thorn;ey haue nonn&euml; awe.</L>
<L>Yn hys &yogh;ou&thorn;e shal he mysseye
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="163"></L>
<L N="4908">And skorn&euml; ou&thorn;er by &thorn;e weye;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sey&thorn; &thorn;e fadyr "&thorn;ys chyldys wurde<MILESTONE N="33a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne shal nat ley all&euml; yn hurde."</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he lern&euml; gylerye,</L>
<L>Fals wurde and feynt trenlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">tremlynge.</NOTE> with ye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">eye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4913">&THORN;at halte hys fadyr a queyntyse</L>
<L>And of slygh wyt, to knowe &thorn;at wyse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he do ska&thorn;e gladly with fyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sey&thorn; &thorn;e fadyr "he shal be wyght;</L>
<L N="4917">He shal be hardy, and no man drede,</L>
<L>He begynne&thorn; be tyme be doghty<NOTE PLACE="foot">dughty.</NOTE> yn dede."</L>
<L>But ryght so shal hyt of hem falle</L>
<L N="4920">As dyd of Ely sonys alle.</L>
<L>y shal &yogh;ow telle, to preue my sawe,</L>
<L>what fyl yn &thorn;e old&euml; lawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">dawe O. has 1 (dotted under) and d written over.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>yn &thorn;e byble hyt telly&thorn;, &thorn;at touche&thorn; swych &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L N="4924">yn &thorn;e holy boke of kynges;</L>
<L>And wryt&euml; hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys &thorn;ere.</NOTE> opunly,</L>
<L>Of a patryark, syre Ely.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The tale of 'Syre Ely' and his wicked Sons.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ys Ely was a man ry&yogh;t ryche,</L>
<L N="4928">And, to hys chyldr&eacute;n ryght blyche;</L>
<L>he hadde twey sonys, &thorn;at ys no les,</L>
<L>'Ofnee' the toon hyght, &thorn;e tou&thorn;er 'Fynees.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ese twey chyldryn dyd ful wykkedly</L>
<L N="4932">To man and woman &thorn;at &thorn;ey come by;</L>
<L>Lyers, robbours, and lechours,</L>
<L>Skorners, and also auoutours;</L>
<L>wymmen &thorn;at to &thorn;e temple come,</L>
<L N="4936">here offryng from hem &thorn;ey nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese wymmen come to syre Ely,</L>
<L>And pleyned hem of grete vyleynye,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at hys sonys were vnhende,
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="164"></L>
<L N="4940">hem also for to shende.</L>
<L>O defaute was, &thorn;ey by hem lay;</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er, &thorn;ey bare here offryng away.'</L>
<L>"Do &thorn;erof sum ch&aacute;stysyng,</L>
<L N="4944">For &thorn;e loue of heuene kyng!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here fadyr Ely &thorn;an was wo,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at yche fame shulde of hem go.</L>
<L>Ely kalled hys sone, "Ofnee<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4948">And Fyne&euml;s, come &yogh;e to me!</L>
<L>Son&euml;s," he seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'he seyde' O, H. omits.</NOTE> "&yogh;e are me dere;</L>
<L>y bydde &yogh;ow bo&thorn;e, on feyre manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e leue &yogh;oure foly dedes,</L>
<L N="4952">And ou&thorn;er foly &thorn;at &yogh;ow ledys;</L>
<L>Y her&euml; of &yogh;ow foul&euml; fame,</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk&euml; seyn &yogh;e are to blame;</L>
<L>Y rede &yogh;e leue alle swych foly,</L>
<L N="4956">&THORN;at y of &yogh;ow here no more cry."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese chyldryn were strong and stout;</L>
<L>Of fadres byddyng &thorn;ey hadde<NOTE PLACE="foot">had &thorn;ey.</NOTE> no dout,</L>
<L>But wer&euml; shrewys for &thorn;e more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for&thorn;ermore.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4960">Or werse &thorn;an &thorn;ey hadde be byfore;</L>
<L>And God was wro&thorn;e wy&thorn; here mysdede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey ne left&euml; for no drede;</L>
<L>And, God was wy&thorn; Ely wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4964">For he dyd hys sones no lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>To chastyse hem wy&thorn; fyn awe</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e smartnes of &thorn;e lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfor toke god hys ven&iuml;aunce</L>
<L N="4968">Of hem, and mo, for &thorn;at myschaunce;</L>
<L>He lete &thorn;e fals Phylystyens,</L>
<L>&THORN;e folk of Isrel to werre a&yogh;ens.</L>
<L>Ely and hys, &thorn;ey gunne assayle,</L>
<L N="4972">And ouercome hem tweys yn batayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese Phylystyens &thorn;at hadde &thorn;e maystry,</L>
<L>Beleuyd on Dagoun, a maumettry.</L>
<L>On a god &thorn;at &thorn;ey kalled Dagoun,</L>
<L N="4976">Beleued &thorn;e Phylystynes echoun.</L>
<L>&THORN;arefor hyt was but Goddys suffraunce
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>&THORN;at shewyd why &thorn;ey hadde swych chaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e folk of Isrel had &thorn;oght, and syghte,</L>
<L N="4980">For &thorn;ey were twyys scumfyghte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey ordeyned hem on all&euml; wyse</L>
<L>how &thorn;ey shulde best to batayle ryse,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e Phylystynes for to go,</L>
<L N="4984">And hem dyscumfyt&euml; and slo.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey ordeyned hem for to bere<MILESTONE N="33b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Goddys arke with hem yn to were.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'bateyle.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Ely sones were stoute and stark,</L>
<L N="4988">And were chose to bere Goddys ark;</L>
<L>For reuerence &thorn;ey ded hyt, of Ely,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ey were of body doghty.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Goddys ark was of swych manere</L>
<L N="4992">As men make now shryn&euml;s here.</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys ark wer&euml; &thorn;re &thorn;ynges</L>
<L>&THORN;at men &yogh;aue to here offrynges;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-yn was Moyses table</L>
<L N="4996">whar-on God wrote &thorn;e law&euml; stable;</L>
<L>And Aarons &yogh;erd, and a potte of golde:</L>
<L>&THORN;ese &thorn;re relykes &thorn;ey helde ful holde.</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e pott&euml; was a floure,</L>
<L N="5000">whyte, and swete of al sauoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at floure ys kalled 'aungelys mete'</L>
<L>&THORN;at God &yogh;afe &thorn;e folke to ete</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey were yn wyldernes</L>
<L N="5004">Forty wyntyr, yn hard stres.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese &thorn;yng&euml;s &thorn;an bare Ely sones</L>
<L>yn-to &thorn;e batayle &thorn;at &yogh;yt of mones.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e phylystyens come hem for<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'for.'</NOTE> to assayle,</L>
<L N="5008">And slogh Ely son&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">sones bo&thorn;e.</NOTE> yn batayle,</L>
<L>And rauysshed Goddys ark &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And slogh &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e relykys &thorn;at &thorn;ere were<NOTE PLACE="foot">were &thorn;er.</NOTE> ynne:</L>
<L N="5012">Alle were lore for &thorn;e sonys synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;e folk to &thorn;e batayle fore,<NOTE PLACE="inter">&yogh;ede</NOTE></L>
<L>Ely sette hym at &thorn;e temple dore
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>yn a chayre, and was herkenyng</L>
<L N="5016">Fro &thorn;e batayle sum tydyng,</L>
<L>On what manere &thorn;e folk shulde spede,</L>
<L>For of Goddys ark he had grete drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>One come rennyng hastyly,</L>
<L N="5020">And broghte &thorn;ys tydyng to Ely</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys sonys were bo&thorn;e slayn,</L>
<L>And Goddys ark with myght and mayn<NOTE PLACE="inter">strenk&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>was bore away for euermore.<MILESTONE N="34a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5024">Alas, &thorn;e sorow &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;erfore!</L>
<L>whan Ely herd &thorn;ys euyl tydyng,</L>
<L>For sorowe he gan hys handys wryng,</L>
<L>And fyl bakward of hys chayre,</L>
<L N="5028">And brak on<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er on.</NOTE> two hys swyer;<NOTE PLACE="inter">nekke</NOTE></L>
<L>And of hys hede he brake &thorn;e bone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e harn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="inter">brayn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits the gloss.</NOTE></NOTE> lay vpp-on &thorn;e stone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; tale ys no tryfyl,</L>
<L N="5032">For hyt ys wryte yn &thorn;e bybyl;</L>
<L>And to &yogh;ow y telle hyt here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sonys to chastyse and to lere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'teche.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e, ne &thorn;ey, be nat shent</L>
<L N="5036">For defaute of chastysment</L>
<L>Bodyly, yn &thorn;ys worlde here,</L>
<L>And aftyr &thorn;at, &thorn;e soule so dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;enke&thorn; on Ely and on<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. omits 'on.'</NOTE> hys sonys;</L>
<L N="5040">And to gode &yogh;oure chyldryn wones.</L>
<L>For, ryght so as hem gan tyde,</L>
<L>Swyche as &thorn;ey were, &thorn;e same mow byde.</L>
<L>Of sloghnes &thorn;ys ys &thorn;e assyse</L>
<L N="5044">whan &thorn;ou wylt nat betyme chastyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;yr an ydulnes,&mdash;</L>
<L>A grete vnwysdom for so&thorn;e hyt ys,&mdash;</L>
<L>whan a &yogh;unge man dragh<NOTE PLACE="foot">dragh&thorn;.</NOTE> lyte on lenk&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="5048">And wyl nat trauayle yn hys &yogh;ung&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&YOGH;en&thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne lern&euml; hym craft for to wynne,</L>
<L>Yn hys ag&euml; to leue wel ynne.
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>Certes me &thorn;enke&thorn; hym ful slogh;</L>
<L N="5052">Hys &thorn;ryfte wyl melte away with snogh.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh a man haue oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">oght of.</NOTE> erytage</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may lyue wy&thorn; weyl yn age,</L>
<L>Certes &yogh;yt behoue&thorn; hym lere</L>
<L N="5056">Manhede and curtesye yn fere.</L>
<L>A man hys manhed&euml; shal &yogh;erne<NOTE PLACE="inter">desyre</NOTE></L>
<L>hymself and hys meyn&euml; to gouerne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e kyng Salamon,</L>
<L N="5060">And &thorn;ese holy men echone;</L>
<L>"Hyt ys an ydulnes yn here lyfe,<MILESTONE N="34a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at ou&thorn;er man or wyfe</L>
<L>Trauayle&thorn; for &thorn;e lyu&euml;s fode,</L>
<L N="5064">And lytyl for &thorn;e soul&euml;s gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou trauayle alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>Ne be &thorn;ou neuer so ryche ne gay,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou serue God yn alle &thorn;y &thorn;oght</L>
<L N="5068">&THORN;at &thorn;y soule to heuene be broght,</L>
<L>Sykyrlyche alle ys hyt but lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;y grete trauayle syn &thorn;ou were bore;</L>
<L>Alle for sloghthede be tolde hyt shal,</L>
<L N="5072">To werche al day, and lese hyt alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt us &thorn;yr an vnkynde slogh&thorn;hede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man vnne&thorn;, for no gode dede,</L>
<L>wyl wurschep God derwr&thorn;ly,</L>
<L N="5076">But more &thorn;arfor a&yogh;ens hym ly.</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;at.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;&euml; se</L>
<L>Of rych&euml; men, how stout &thorn;ey be;</L>
<L>For many one &thorn;at he &yogh;yf&thorn; to rychesse,</L>
<L N="5080">Of God and man &thorn;ey &yogh;yue no<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> lesse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he &yogh;yue to any hys ryght lemes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lymes.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;anke hym &thorn;erof, no man &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&YOGH;eme.</NOTE> nymes.</L>
<L>loke alle &thorn;y lym&euml;s, fete and hondes,</L>
<L N="5084">And, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou weyl vndyrstondys</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne hast ned&euml; of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;ank hym no&thorn;er yn wele no wo;
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou mayst forber&euml; noun,</L>
<L N="5088">&THORN;ank &thorn;an hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;an.</NOTE> of euerychoun;</L>
<L>y rede we &thorn;anke hym of euery poynt,</L>
<L>Syn we may nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne may.</NOTE> forbere &thorn;e lest Ioynt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yt &thorn;yr ys a slogh&thorn;ehede yn &thorn;ys synne;</L>
<L N="5092">Vnkynde men are alle &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>yn sum man, vnkyndehede ys so rank</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne may cunne no man &thorn;ank</L>
<L>For no gode dede &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;an H.</NOTE> men hym dous.</L>
<L N="5096">A dogge ys kynder, &thorn;at go&thorn; lous,</L>
<L>For, &yogh;yue a dogge &thorn;ryd part hys fode,</L>
<L>And he shal euer weyte &thorn;e gode,</L>
<L>And euermor&euml; be wy&thorn; &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5100">For lyf&euml; ne de&thorn; wyl he fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;ys skyl mayst &thorn;ou se how</L>
<L>An hounde ys kynder &thorn;an art &thorn;ou;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt may hyt preuyd be</L>
<L N="5104">&THORN;at &thorn;ou art as vnkynde as he.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hound&euml;, &thorn;ys y fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at most he hate&thorn; hys owne kynde;</L>
<L>For that yche hound&euml; &thorn;at hym gat,</L>
<L N="5108">Most of all&euml; hate&thorn; he &thorn;at;</L>
<L>And hys modyr he hate&thorn; also;</L>
<L>He byt here, &yogh;yf he may cum here to.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &yogh;e vndyrstond&euml; kan,</L>
<L N="5112">&THORN;us fary&thorn; hyt of a<NOTE PLACE="foot">an.</NOTE> vnkynd man;</L>
<L>For he loue&thorn; more an ou&thorn;er kynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto ys wel mor&euml; mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an he dou&thorn; &thorn;at ych&euml; flesshe</L>
<L N="5116">Of whos kynde he cum for&thorn;e ys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ysse.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-no&thorn;er &thorn;yng &yogh;yt ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'ys.'</NOTE> &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &yogh;eue kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many loue more nete and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and O, &thorn;an H.</NOTE> shepe</L>
<L>&THORN;an he dou&thorn; hys emcrystene,</L>
<L N="5120">Or of hys harme wyl oght bemene.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ys ys a grete vnkyndnes,</L>
<L>And also a&yogh;en manhede hyt ys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">es.</NOTE></L>
<L>And slogh&thorn;&euml;hede wel for to proue,
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="169"></L>
<L N="5124">Vnkyndly, and lowe, to loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou art yn god&euml; wyl</L>
<L>To seru&euml; God, and leue alle yl,</L>
<L>Repente &thorn;e nat, for no feyntyse,</L>
<L N="5128">Ne be nat heuy to hys seruyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shuldyst ra&thorn;er to &thorn;e de&thorn; turne</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ou shust wy&thorn; hys seruyse scorne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou bygynne weyl, y rede &thorn;ou ende,</L>
<L>For fyrst and last &thorn;ou fyndyst hym hende.</L>
<L N="5133">And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou bygynne any &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk what shal be &thorn;e endyng.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou seru&euml; God to pay,</L>
<L N="5136">Alle &thorn;y lyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyue.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e laste ende of &thorn;y lyffe<MILESTONE N="34b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou fallyst a&yogh;ens hym yn stryffe,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou yn &thorn;at ych&euml; synne</L>
<L N="5140">Makyst &thorn;an &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;anne &thorn;yn.</NOTE> endyng ynne,</L>
<L>God forget alle &thorn;y gode dede;</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;erfor gest &thorn;ou no mede.</L>
<L>Ryght so ys he to &thorn;e redy</L>
<L N="5144">whan &thorn;ou wylt leue alle &thorn;y foly,</L>
<L>And come to hym with r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>yn blys he make&thorn; &thorn;y puruyaunce.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e ende shal bo&thorn;e dede and &thorn;oght</L>
<L N="5148">Shewe hym self how hyt ys wroght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne be nat &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou nat.</NOTE> sorowful, y &thorn;e forbede;</L>
<L>hyt semy&thorn;, yn Goddys seruyse &thorn;an &thorn;ou hast drede;</L>
<L>And dred&euml; wyl make a man slogh</L>
<L N="5152">To do &thorn;e seruyse &thorn;at he hogh.<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghe.</NOTE></L>
<L>But serue hym gladly with louely chere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys &thorn;y seruyse to hym dere:</L>
<L>&THORN;us techy&thorn; vs Dauid &thorn;e prophete</L>
<L N="5156">yn &thorn;e sautyr, wurdys swete;
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>"Ne be nat proude &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou weyl dous,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;yn herte to make a rous"<NOTE PLACE="inter">boste</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou holy lyf&euml; ledys,</L>
<L N="5160">Yn fastyng, or yn alm&euml;s dedys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst ys ouer moch&euml; drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er ys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'ys.'</NOTE> proude hauncenhede.</L>
<L>Holde &thorn;e euene hem betwene,</L>
<L N="5164">Nat ouer-drede ne ouer-wene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>No make no sorowe, ne myslyke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wanhope In &thorn;yn hert&euml; styke;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ys &thorn;e werst poynt of alle;</L>
<L N="5168">To hell&euml; &thorn;yt hyt do&thorn;e &thorn;e falle.</L>
<L>Slogh&euml;nes, hyt wyl &thorn;e grope</L>
<L>To bryng&euml; &thorn;e yn-to whanhope;</L>
<L>Sloghnes yn all&euml; god&euml; dedys,</L>
<L N="5172">Ys as moche, as sum men redys,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou shryue &thorn;e of a synne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke no more to falle &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be slogh, and heuy,<MILESTONE N="35a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5176">And doust no gode dede of mercy,</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; God yn hys gospel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at "&thorn;ou art to me a voyde vessel."</L>
<L>Ful lyght &thorn;an art &thorn;ou for to turne</L>
<L N="5180">A&yogh;en to synne, and to soiurne;</L>
<L>&THORN;an art &thorn;ou wers&euml; &thorn;an &thorn;ou was,</L>
<L>Bound&euml; vn-to Satanas;</L>
<L>&THORN;an wylle Satanas begynne to prykke,</L>
<L N="5184">And whanhope yn &thorn;y hert&euml; stykke.</L>
<L>whanhope, God shelde vs &thorn;ar-fro,</L>
<L>hyt stery&thorn; a man hym self to slo;</L>
<L>So ded &thorn;e treytur Iudas,</L>
<L N="5188">And forso&thorn;e, wur&thorn;y he was.</L>
<L>why was he moste wur&thorn;y?</L>
<L>For he hadde wanhope of Goddys mercy;</L>
<L>For he wend&euml; &thorn;at God ne wulde</L>
<L>Haue for&yogh;yue hym, &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, god H.</NOTE> hym solde.</L>
<L N="5193">Sy&thorn;&thorn;en loked God<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ihesu.</NOTE> vpp-on Iudas,
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>As who sey, "aske mercy for &thorn;y trespas."</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf he had asked hyt any sy&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="5196">Ihesu hadde graunted hym asswy&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For hys mercy fayled noght</L>
<L>To any man &thorn;at hym besoght.</L>
<L>Syn God wulde haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha.</NOTE> be to hym so fre,</L>
<L N="5200">&THORN;an ys he redy to &thorn;e and me:</L>
<L>whych&euml; tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whych tyme or when.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wylt hym kalle,</L>
<L>For hys defaute &thorn;ou shalt nat falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be&thorn;enke &thorn;e weyl of &thorn;e &thorn;efe</L>
<L>&THORN;at loued nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">naght.</NOTE> God, no<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> was hym lefe,&mdash;</L>
<L N="5205">he &thorn;at was hanged on a tre</L>
<L>Bysyd&euml; Ihesu for vylte;</L>
<L>he spake o wurde at hys endyng.</L>
<L N="5208">"lord&euml;, haue on me menyng!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">mennynge.</NOTE></L>
<L>And asswy&thorn;e he wan &thorn;e prys,</L>
<L>And was sent yn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'yn.'</NOTE> paradys.</L>
<L>he was &thorn;e fyrst[&euml;] &thorn;at hyt wan</L>
<L N="5212">Syn Adam lost hyt, oure formest man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Er was &thorn;at &thorn;efe yn paradys<MILESTONE N="35a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle &thorn;e.</NOTE> prophetys &thorn;at were of prys.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;efe <SUP>8</SUP>alle manere wys dyd<SUP>8</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">8_8 &thorn;at dede al maner.</NOTE> synne,</L>
<L N="5216">And neuer ere leuyd Ihesu ynne;</L>
<L>For a wurde &thorn;at he spak so myld&euml;ly,</L>
<L>he ha&thorn; pes, blys, and mercy.</L>
<L>And, &thorn;arfor, dysmay &thorn;e noght</L>
<L N="5220">For no &thorn;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast wroght;</L>
<L>For, haue &thorn;ou do neuer so mykyl,</L>
<L>Ne be so fals, ne so fykyl,</L>
<L>Ne ley &thorn;er-ynn&euml; so long whyle,</L>
<L N="5224">And do alle maner synn&euml;s vyle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt, yn strenk&thorn;e and hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;y synne forsake and nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> wy&thorn; dele,</L>
<L N="5227">with sorow of herte and r&eacute;pentaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst pay God with lytyl penaunce.</L>
<L>God sey&thorn; &thorn;ys wurde, to shew vs &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L>"y wyl &thorn;at non&euml; synful deye;
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>To leue hys synne he shal haue space,</L>
<L N="5232">And turne a&yogh;en to lyfe and grace;</L>
<L>what so euer he haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue he.</NOTE> done,</L>
<L>y wyl nat hys dampnacyone."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &yogh;yue a sample, a tale here lys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L N="5236">&THORN;at vs telle&thorn; seynt Dyonys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Priest Carpus's Vision, and how merciful God is.]</HEAD>
<L>Seynt Dyonys of Fraunce sey&thorn; &thorn;us:&mdash;</L>
<L>hyt was a prest &thorn;at hyght Carpus;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest, &thorn;urgh prechyng and sawe,</L>
<L N="5240">Broght a sarysyn to crystyn lawe;</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er sarasyn of paynye</L>
<L>Hadd&euml; &thorn;erwy&thorn; grete enuye,</L>
<L>And turnede &thorn;ys man to hym a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L N="5244">And oure crystyndom was alle veyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest &thorn;ar&euml;for was sory,</L>
<L>And hatyd &thorn;ys man felunly,</L>
<L>And preyd&euml; God he wuld hym sende</L>
<L N="5248">Dampnacyun with-outyn ende,</L>
<L>For he &thorn;e crystendom forsoke,</L>
<L>And to a fals beleue hym toke;</L>
<L>Fast he preyd yn hys atent,<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5252">&thorn;at God on hym veniaunc&euml; sent.</L>
<L>And God &thorn;e prestys prayere herde,</L>
<L>And shewed hym &thorn;at he mysferde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys prest lay yn hys bede a ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5256">And, gostly, he sagh a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys.</NOTE> syght;</L>
<L>he sagh a swy&thorn;e merueylus brygge</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e dep&euml; pytte<NOTE PLACE="foot">putte.</NOTE> gan lygge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e plank &thorn;at on &thorn;e brygg&euml; was,</L>
<L N="5260">was as sledyr as any glas;</L>
<L>But yn &thorn;e put &thorn;at was &thorn;er-vndyr,</L>
<L>he sagh so moche sorowe and wundyr,</L>
<L>Of fend&euml;s fel&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ere wore,
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>&THORN;ogh y tolde moche, &yogh;yt were &thorn;er more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5265">But, shortly to tell&euml; fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;e man<NOTE PLACE="foot">Who had returned to Paganism, and who he had prayd should be damnd.</NOTE> he sagh on &thorn;e brygg&euml; go</L>
<L>Yn ful gret&euml; perel and kare,</L>
<L N="5268">And euer yn poynt to mysfare;</L>
<L>Yn poynt he was to falle adowne,</L>
<L>Of hys hede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuede.</NOTE> formest &thorn;e crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fendys &thorn;at were yn &thorn;e pytte</L>
<L>Smote vpwarde, &yogh;yf &thorn;ey my&yogh;t hym hytte;</L>
<L N="5273">And addres bete hym by &thorn;e fete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest sagh &thorn;at, and ful weyl lete;</L>
<L>He preyd&euml; God &thorn;at he shuld falle</L>
<L N="5276">Down yn-to &thorn;e fendys<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto &thorn;e deueles.</NOTE> alle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er, with-outyn end&euml; be,</L>
<L>'For he turned away fro &thorn;e.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;e prest had sey&euml; &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="5280">He loked vp to heuene blys;</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;oght &thorn;e rofe was cloue yn two,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sky opened also,</L>
<L>And of Ihesu he hadde a syght,</L>
<L N="5284">How he was on &thorn;e rod&euml; dyght;</L>
<L>He sagh hys wundys alle blody,</L>
<L>And spak to hym ful sorowfully,</L>
<L>"Carpus," he seyd, "se wy&thorn; &thorn;yn yne</L>
<L N="5288">what y suffred for mannys pyne;</L>
<L>Man to saue, y lete me slo,<MILESTONE N="35b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>why wust &thorn;ou dampn&euml; hym to wo?</L>
<L>why hast &thorn;ou hym so moche with ylle?</L>
<L N="5292">And for mankynde y lete me spylle</L>
<L>with pyne, and hard&euml; passyoun,</L>
<L>My blode y &yogh;af for hys raunsun;</L>
<L>why wust &thorn;ou he hadde hell&euml; fere</L>
<L N="5296">Syn y haue boght hym so dere?
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yt were y redy man to beye,</L>
<L>Er man with-outyn ende shulde deye.</L>
<L>But y haue shewde hym so moche yn dede</L>
<L N="5300">with my wundes &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest blede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at y &thorn;arfor ne wuld&euml; noght</L>
<L>Lese &thorn;at y so dere haue boght.</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens me ne fynde&thorn; he no<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> omits 'no.'</NOTE> skylle,</L>
<L N="5304">But &yogh;yf hys own&euml; wylle hyt wylle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he be nowe a&yogh;ens me went,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt kepe y hys amend&euml;ment;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, with gode deuocyoun,</L>
<L N="5308">Pray for mannys saluacyoun."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Carpus &thorn;anked God almyght</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde herde and seye &thorn;at syght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore shul we be ful mynde</L>
<L N="5312">To serue hym &thorn;at ys to vs so kynde,</L>
<L>And shewe hym loue whyle we be here</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he love&thorn; vs alle so dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wulde leue eft, for drede,</L>
<L N="5316">To deye for vs &yogh;yf we hadde nede.</L>
<L>Ne be we slogh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat slogh.</NOTE> but sone vpryse,</L>
<L>Ne dred&euml; vs &thorn;an on no wyse,</L>
<L>But, hope alle to gode endyng,</L>
<L N="5320">And serue &thorn;at mercy&aacute;ble kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys mercy be to vs lent</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of Iug&euml;mement;</L>
<L>Amen! so mot&euml; hyt betyde</L>
<L N="5324">To kepe vs fro sloghnes and accyde!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[Of Covetousness, 5th Deadly Sin.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now shul we speke of couetyse,</L>
<L>How hy<NOTE PLACE="foot">he [hy? for A.S. <I>heo</I>, fem., or the t of <I>hyt</I> omitted.]</NOTE> ys haunted on wykked wyse.</L>
<L>Coueytyse ys &thorn;e fryst vyce;<MILESTONE N="36a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at streyte ys holde, y<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> omits 'y.'</NOTE> halte auaryce.</L>
<L N="5329">Coueytyse ys of vs echone,</L>
<L>But auaryce wulde haue echone.</L>
<L>Coueytyse, ys desyryng of &thorn;oght,
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="175"></L>
<L N="5332">But auaryce, wulde &thorn;at none had oght.</L>
<L>Coueytyse, cum&thorn; o&thorn;erwhyle of gode;</L>
<L>But auaryce wy&thorn;drawy&thorn; mannys fode.</L>
<L>Coueytyse, to gode men mowe hyt charge;</L>
<L N="5336">But auaryce, ys no&thorn;er gode ne large.</L>
<L>Coueytyse, ys of wylle, as ys a bayte,</L>
<L>But auaryce, ys nygun haldyng strayte;</L>
<L>Coueytyse, cum&thorn; of kynde of blode;</L>
<L N="5340">But auaryce, ys no&thorn;er kynde ne gode.</L>
<L>As y kan telle, &thorn;ys ys &thorn;e assyse,</L>
<L>Betwyxe auaryce and coueytyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here, y aske at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="5344">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou with wrong &yogh;erned o&thorn;er mennys &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Or falsly purchased: &thorn;at ys grete synne,</L>
<L>So with wrong mennys gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynge.</NOTE> to wynne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou withholde, and &yogh;elde hyt noght,</L>
<L N="5348">Auaryse to hell&euml; ha&thorn; &thorn;e broght.</L>
<L>Yn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'yn.'</NOTE> &thorn;y lyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyue.</NOTE> y rede &thorn;ou &yogh;elde hyt a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>&THORN;y saluacyun ys ell&euml;s alle veyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou madest euer any delay,</L>
<L N="5352">And ledyst one lyte fro day to day</L>
<L>with &thorn;y wurdys pryuyly,</L>
<L>Or perauenture al on hy,</L>
<L>For to haue hys &thorn;yng with wrong,</L>
<L N="5356">Euyl coueytyse &thorn;ou mengest among.</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou broghtest hyt neuer to dede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;y wylle moche for to drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou dedyst euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer dedest.</NOTE> &thorn;y myght</L>
<L>To false a chartre, &thorn;at ys grete plyght.</L>
<L N="5361">&THORN;at ys a dede of tresun</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be of dysheresun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dyserytsun.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er of lond, ou&thorn;er of rent,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er of ou&thorn;er gode &thorn;at God man ha&thorn; lent;</L>
<L N="5365">But &thorn;ou &thorn;e peyn&euml; ny&yogh;t and day<MILESTONE N="36a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To amende &thorn;at charge, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou may,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt ne be, &thorn;ou art to blame;</L>
<L N="5368">Ordeyned to &thorn;e ys moch&euml; shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn batayle, or in fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Toke oght of man with-out&euml; ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And namely of relygyun,</L>
<L N="5372">&THORN;e harder ys &thorn;y synn&euml; doun:</L>
<L>And but &thorn;ou sone amend&euml; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor mayst &thorn;ou acumbred be:</L>
<L>Hyt ys wur&thorn;y hym for to dere</L>
<L N="5376">&THORN;at holy cherche wyl nat forbere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou of rychesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryches.</NOTE> be wel beforne,</L>
<L>And a &yogh;ere or two holdyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">haldest.</NOTE> &thorn;y corne</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghtest.</NOTE> selle hyt ry&yogh;t dere,</L>
<L>And to helpe &thorn;e pore &thorn;ou wylt nat here,</L>
<L N="5381">Salamon sey&thorn;, &thorn;at moch&euml; kan,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt be weryed with many man;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest myys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfst mys.</NOTE> to &yogh;ete<NOTE PLACE="foot">ete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5384">&THORN;at was ordeyned to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for.</NOTE> mannys mete;</L>
<L>For who so wyl hys myys wel fede,</L>
<L>And spare hyt fro &thorn;e pore at nede,</L>
<L>hyghly shal he go a-lone</L>
<L N="5388">To &thorn;e deuyl, body and bone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue of ou&thorn;er tresour,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an susteyne&thorn; &thorn;yn onour,&mdash;</L>
<L>Syluer, clo&thorn;es, or ou&thorn;er store,</L>
<L N="5392">Or of ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng&euml;s more,&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;e pore for defaut&euml; deye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou mayst hym helpe, y seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou are a-couped of &thorn;ys vyce</L>
<L N="5396">Of coueytyse, and of auaryce;</L>
<L>And before God, of &thorn;eft, a &thorn;efe,</L>
<L>And for hys de&thorn;, of slaghter grefe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn falshede so moche &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="5400">For coueytyse or for grete mede
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>To consente to a fals Iuggyng,</L>
<L>Or hyredyst a voket to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for.</NOTE> swyche &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Or myghtyst haue sturbled hyt, &amp; wust noght,<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But for coueytyse &thorn;e wrong were wroght,</L>
<L N="5405">Moche shal God challeng&euml; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;at &thorn;ou Iuged shal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As for<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of.</NOTE> lordynges cunseylours,</L>
<L>wykked legystrys or fals a-countours,</L>
<L N="5409">&THORN;ey ne recche of no ry&yogh;t fey,</L>
<L>Ne more &thorn;e lordynges<NOTE PLACE="foot">lordes.</NOTE> &thorn;an do &thorn;ey;</L>
<L>Cunseyl to wykked lawes &thorn;ey &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="5412">So &thorn;at &thorn;e pore men mow nat lyue:</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, &thorn;ey and here lordyngys</L>
<L>Doun moche wrong yn many &thorn;yngys;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor shul &thorn;ey and here cunsayl</L>
<L N="5416">Go to helle, bo&thorn;e top and tayle.</L>
<L>Many man ys broght ful bare</L>
<L>For cunseylours &thorn;at coueytous are;</L>
<L>And many a land yn grete errours</L>
<L N="5420">Are ouer-turned &thorn;urgh cunseylours.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among hem, stywardes mow be tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lordyng&euml;s courtys holde,</L>
<L>For nyrhand euery a styward,</L>
<L N="5424">&THORN;e dome &thorn;at &thorn;ey &yogh;eue, ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys &yogh;eue.</NOTE> ouer hard;</L>
<L>And namely to &thorn;e por&euml; man,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey greu&euml; hym alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey kan.</L>
<L>who-so-euer to mercy wyl hym drawe,</L>
<L N="5428">he sey&thorn;, he shal do hym but lawe;</L>
<L>But who so shal &thorn;e lawe alle do,</L>
<L>And no mercy do &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>he may neuer for mercy craue</L>
<L N="5432">To God whan he wulde mercy haue;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf God shal deme with lawe ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Shal no man come to heuene ly&yogh;t.</L>
<L>But &thorn;urgh grace and hys mercy,</L>
<L N="5436">&THORN;an are we saued certeynly.
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, &yogh;e stywardes on benche,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-on shulde &yogh;e all&euml; &thorn;enche,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou of &thorn;e por&euml; haue pyte,</L>
<L N="5440">&THORN;an wylle God haue mercy on &thorn;e.'</L>
<L>For hard&euml; dome and coueytyse<MILESTONE N="36b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>y shal &yogh;ow telle of swych a Iustyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Hard Judge.]</HEAD>
<L>Y haue herde, be-&yogh;onde &thorn;e see<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5444">was a Iustyse, yn a cuntre;</L>
<L>Of hym the wurde ful wyd&euml; sprong,</L>
<L>he &yogh;af harde dome, and o&thorn;er whyle wrong.</L>
<L>God&euml; men ofte hym besoght</L>
<L N="5448">For &thorn;e pore, &thorn;at he wo wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shulde haue on hem mercy,</L>
<L>And pylle hem nat but mesurly;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t lyue yn pes by hym,</L>
<L N="5452">And be nat so a&yogh;ens hem grym.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys was hys answere and hys sawe,</L>
<L>'Y shal do hem no &thorn;yng but lawe."</L>
<L>And many lawes are oute of skylle,</L>
<L N="5456">But, &yogh;yf &thorn;&eacute;r<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yr.</NOTE> be mercy tylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>was hyt nat long aftyrward,</L>
<L>He fyl yn a sykenes hard;</L>
<L>Hyt telle&thorn; of hym swych a chaunce,</L>
<L N="5460">He hadde no god&euml; r&eacute;pentaunce;</L>
<L>Hys syk&euml;nes<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, syknes H.</NOTE> wax harde and strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;t nat lyu&euml; long;</L>
<L>For all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle men.</NOTE> hoped weyl y-nogh</L>
<L N="5464">&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> vn-to &thorn;e de&thorn; faste drogh.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men &thorn;at sate a-boute hys bedde</L>
<L>were a-gast, and sore a-dredde;</L>
<L>And hopyd wel, and vndyrstode
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="179"></L>
<L N="5468">&THORN;at here drede was for no gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All&euml; &thorn;ey behelde hym faste,</L>
<L>And sawe hys coloure ofte ouer caste;</L>
<L>And wroth a-bout&euml;, to and fro;</L>
<L>Hys bedde hym &thorn;oght wulde cleue on two;</L>
<L N="5473">And cryd&euml; with a loud&euml; cry,</L>
<L>"Lord&euml;, haue on me mercy!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an spake a voyc&euml; yn &thorn;e sky,</L>
<L N="5476">&THORN;at alle hyt herde &thorn;at stode hym by,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou haddest neuer of man pyte,</L>
<L>Ne y shal neuer haue noun of &thorn;e."</L>
<L>Asswy&thorn;&euml; he d&euml;yd yn haste;<MILESTONE N="37a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5480">&THORN;ere he shulde go, he &yogh;alde &thorn;e gaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e dom&euml;s men &thorn;at &thorn;ys chaunce here,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ys tal&euml; mowe &yogh;e lere</L>
<L>what hyt ys to do euer wreche,</L>
<L N="5484">And to mercy no &thorn;yng reche.</L>
<L>Hauy&thorn; yn &yogh;oure &thorn;oght, mercy, and se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore mow nat so weyl as &yogh;e;</L>
<L>Be&thorn; mercy&aacute;ble for &yogh;oure prow</L>
<L N="5488">&THORN;at God ne take veniaunce on &yogh;ow.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue be so coueytous</L>
<L>To mercs<NOTE PLACE="foot">mercye.</NOTE> men ouer outraious,</L>
<L>And por&euml; men, specyaly,</L>
<L N="5492">&THORN;at ferde &thorn;e wers for &thorn;at mercy,</L>
<L>Sykyr mote &thorn;ou be, syre styward,</L>
<L>&THORN;y mercyment shal be ful hard.</L>
<L>&THORN;y wreched soule &thorn;arfor shal dwelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;y mercyment shal be &thorn;e &thorn;yne of helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5497">&THORN;ou bayl&euml;, owest nat to take</L>
<L>(For drede of soule, and &thorn;yn oth sake,)</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;y lordes prow be &thorn;e lasse,</L>
<L N="5500">Ne noun of hys do harder stresse."</L>
<L>So shulde eche aturne seriaunt;</L>
<L>But many one holde no cunnaunt;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cuuinaunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For, sum<NOTE PLACE="foot">some.</NOTE> take ful greuusly,</L>
<L N="5504">&THORN;at ful sore shal come hem by.
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey tak&euml; now to frest,</L>
<L>&THORN;&eacute;rof sh&aacute;l God take a quest.</L>
<L>&THORN;e quest ys take and draght on hym;</L>
<L N="5508">Accord &thorn;e wy&thorn; &thorn;y lorde, betym.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Of Simony.]</HEAD>
<L>To coueytyse longe&thorn; symonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whych haunte&thorn; almost al clergye.</L>
<L>Symonye ys, as men telle,</L>
<L N="5512">when &yogh;yftys of holy cherche men selle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou o&thorn;er &yogh;aue or sent</L>
<L>Of holy cherche to haue vaunsement,</L>
<L N="5515">Or any &yogh;af hyt for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou art nat wur&thorn;y vaunsed to be,</L>
<L>&thorn;an art &thorn;ou come, &thorn;urgh &thorn;at queyntyse,<MILESTONE N="37a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To symonye and coueytyse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an &thorn;ou.</NOTE> &thorn;at auaunsement holde,</L>
<L N="5520">&THORN;ou art a wulfe of Goddys folde;</L>
<L>A wulf, y sey, take &thorn;ou gode kepe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shalt answere for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o.</NOTE> shepe.</L>
<L>A clerk &thorn;at hys orders take&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tak&thorn; H, O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5524">For &yogh;yft or present &thorn;at he make&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mak&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ys nat wur&thorn;y hem to haue,</L>
<L>Hym were bettyr to be a knaue,</L>
<L>And so were hem &thorn;at so hem selles</L>
<L N="5528">For &yogh;yftys, and for no godenes elles.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese holy men &thorn;at hau&euml; ben,</L>
<L>And holy wryt haue red and sen,</L>
<L>Sey, &thorn;at swych &yogh;yftys are lore,</L>
<L N="5532">And, now ys noun ware before.</L>
<L>For swych men selle &thorn;e holy<NOTE PLACE="foot">hely.</NOTE> gast</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he loue&thorn; last.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Coueytous men and lechours,</L>
<L N="5536">Of holy cherche &thorn;ey haue onours:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys mow men se alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">eury.</NOTE> day with ye;</L>
<L>Cursed be syr symonye!
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="181"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Of Usurers.]</HEAD>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">An.</NOTE> okerere may &thorn;ar-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar to may.</NOTE> be tolde,</L>
<L N="5540">For coueytous man ys okerere bolde.</L>
<L>y haue &yogh;ow told&euml; of &thorn;ys lak</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e comaundement whan y spak.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys to sey, y am hardy,</L>
<L N="5544">&THORN;ese chapmen haunte hyt comunly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou borow of a marchaunte,</L>
<L>And makest<NOTE PLACE="foot">makst.</NOTE> for wynnyng certeyn cun|naunt,</L>
<L>'Gete &thorn;ou wynnyng, or gete &thorn;ou lore,</L>
<L N="5548">&THORN;ou shalt &yogh;yu&euml; so &thorn;ar-fore;'</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e &yogh;e fall&euml; bo&thorn;e yn synne,</L>
<L>And he ys a-cursed &thorn;at take&thorn; &thorn;e wynne.</L>
<L>with oker forso&thorn;&euml; bo&thorn;e &yogh;e lyue;</L>
<L N="5552">&THORN;at he wyl take, &thorn;at wylt &thorn;ou &yogh;yue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Okerers, and kauersyns,</L>
<L>As wykked &thorn;ey are as sarasyns.</L>
<L>who so my&yogh;t preu&euml; whych &thorn;ey wore&mdash;<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5556">were &thorn;ey lewed, or were &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey yn.</NOTE> lore&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shulde nat come yn Crystys herde,</L>
<L>Ne come yn cherche ne chyrch&euml; &yogh;erde.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, &thorn;urgh &thorn;ys skylle</L>
<L>&THORN;ey mowe be saued, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ey wylle,</L>
<L N="5561">leue &thorn;at synne, and do no more,</L>
<L>And do at holy cherches lore;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue a&yogh;eyn &thorn;at ych&euml; &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="5564">&THORN;at &thorn;ey haue take yn okeryng;</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ey mow nat a&yogh;en hyt &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>Helpe &thorn;e pore men &thorn;er-with to lyue,</L>
<L>larg&euml;ly and with gode wylle,</L>
<L N="5568">And &thorn;ey mowe peyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">pese.</NOTE> here dedys ylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A gode ensample now &yogh;e here,
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>Of Pers &thorn;at was a tollere;</L>
<L>And y shal tell&euml; &yogh;ow as quyk,</L>
<L N="5572">How he was bo&thorn;&euml; gode and wyk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Pers the Usurer.]</HEAD>
<L>Seynt Ioun<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iohan.</NOTE> &thorn;e aumenere<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sey&thorn; Pers was an okerere,</L>
<L>And was swy&thorn;&euml; coueytous,</L>
<L N="5576">And a nygun and auarous,</L>
<L>And gadred pens vnto store</L>
<L>As okerers doun aywhore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Befyl hyt so, vp-on a day</L>
<L N="5580">&THORN;at por&euml; men sate yn &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>And spred here hatren on here barme</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e sonn&euml; &thorn;at was warme,</L>
<L>And rekened &thorn;e custome houses echoun,</L>
<L N="5584">At whych &thorn;ey had gode, and at whyche noun;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;ey hadde gode, &thorn;ey preysed weyl,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ey hadde noght, neuer a deyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;ey spak of many what,</L>
<L N="5588">Com&euml; Pers for&thorn; yn &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ayr.</NOTE> gat:<NOTE PLACE="inter">wey</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd echoun &thorn;at sate and stode,</L>
<L>'here com&thorn; Pers, &thorn;at neuer dyd gode!'</L>
<L>Echoun seyd to o&thorn;er Iangland,</L>
<L N="5592">'&THORN;ey toke neuer gode at Pers hand;</L>
<L>Ne noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> pore man neuer shal haue,<MILESTONE N="37b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Coude he neuer so weyl craue.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>One of hem began to sey</L>
<L N="5596">"A waiour dar y wy&thorn; &yogh;ow ley,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y shal haue sum gode at<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> hym,</L>
<L>Be he neuer so gryl ne grym."</L>
<L N="5599">To &thorn;at waiour &thorn;ey graunted alle,</L>
<L>To &yogh;yue hym a &yogh;yft &yogh;yf so my&yogh;t befalle.
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="183"></L>
<L N="5601">&THORN;ys man vp sterte, and toke &thorn;e gate,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'wey.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Tyl he com, at Pers &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>As he stode stylle, and bode<NOTE PLACE="foot">abode.</NOTE> &thorn;e quede,</L>
<L>One come with an asse charged with brede;</L>
<L N="5605">&THORN;at ych&euml; bred&euml; Pers hade boght,</L>
<L>And to hys hous shuld hyt be broght.</L>
<L>He sagh Pers com&euml; &thorn;erwith-alle;</L>
<L N="5608">&THORN;e por&euml; &thorn;oght 'now aske y shal.'</L>
<L>"Y aske &thorn;e sum gode, pur charyte,</L>
<L>Pers, &yogh;yf &thorn;y wyl be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pers stode, and loked on hym</L>
<L N="5612">Felunlyche with y&yogh;en grym.</L>
<L>He stouped down to seke a stone,</L>
<L>But, as hap was, &thorn;an fonde he none.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e stone he toke a lofe,</L>
<L N="5616">And at &thorn;e por&euml; man hyf drofe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pore man hente hyt vp belyue,</L>
<L>And was &thorn;erof ful ferly bly&thorn;e.</L>
<L>To hys felaws faste he ran</L>
<L N="5620">with &thorn;e lofe, &thorn;ys por&euml; man,</L>
<L>"lo," he seyd&euml;, "what y haue</L>
<L>Of Pers &yogh;yft, so God me saue!"</L>
<L>Nay, &thorn;ey swor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">swore alle.</NOTE> by here &thorn;ryft,</L>
<L N="5624">Pers &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> neuer swych a &yogh;yft.</L>
<L>he seyd, "&yogh;e shul weyl vndyrstonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at y hyt had, at<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> Pers honde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at dar y swere on &thorn;e halydom</L>
<L N="5628">Here befor&euml; &yogh;ow echoun."</L>
<L>Gret&euml; merueyle had &thorn;ey alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych a chaunce my&yogh;t hym befalle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">falle.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydd&euml; day, &thorn;us wryte hyt ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">es.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="38a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5632">Pers fyl yn a grete syknes;</L>
<L>And, as he lay yn hys bedde,</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;oght weyl, &thorn;at he was ledde
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>with one &thorn;at aftyr hym was sent,</L>
<L N="5636">To come vn-to hys Iug&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before &thorn;e Iug&euml; was he broght</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde acounte how he hadde wroght.</L>
<L>Pers stode ful sore a-drad,</L>
<L N="5640">And, was &aacute;bashed as<NOTE PLACE="foot">al abashede and.</NOTE> mad;</L>
<L>He sagh a fende on &thorn;e to party,</L>
<L>Bewreyyng hym ful felunly;</L>
<L>Alle hyt was shewed hym before,</L>
<L N="5644">how he had lyued syn he wos<NOTE PLACE="foot">was.</NOTE> bore;</L>
<L>And namely euery wykked dede</L>
<L>Syn fyrst he coud&euml; hym self lede;</L>
<L>why he hem dyd, and for what chesun,</L>
<L>Of alle behoue&thorn; hym to &yogh;elde<NOTE PLACE="foot">behouede hym elde.</NOTE> a resoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;e tou&thorn;er party stode men ful bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wulde haue saued hym at here my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey myght no god&euml; fynde</L>
<L N="5652">&THORN;at my&yogh;t hym sau&euml; or vnbynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feyre men seyd "what ys to rede?</L>
<L>Of hym fynde we no god&euml; dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at God ys payd of, but of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'of.'</NOTE> a lofe</L>
<L N="5656">&thorn;e whych Pers at<NOTE PLACE="foot">at O, a H.</NOTE> &thorn;e pore man drofe:</L>
<L>&yogh;yt &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> he hyt with no gode wylle,</L>
<L>But kast hyt aftyr hym with ylle;</L>
<L>For Goddys loue &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> he hyt no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5660">Ne for almes dede he hyt had &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, &thorn;e por&euml; man</L>
<L>Had &thorn;e lof&euml; of Pers &thorn;an."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5663">&THORN;e fend&euml; had leyd yn balaunce</L>
<L>Hys wykkede dedes and hys myschaunce;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey leyd &thorn;e lofe a&yogh;ens hys dedys,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey had no&yogh;t ell&euml;s, &thorn;ey mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">moste.</NOTE> nedys&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy man telle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tel&thorn;.</NOTE> vs, and seys,</L>
<L N="5568">&THORN;at &thorn;e lofe made euen peys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;ese feyr&euml; men to Pers,<MILESTONE N="38a:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>"&yogh;yf &thorn;ou be wys, now &thorn;ou leres</L>
<L>How &thorn;ys lofe &thorn;e helpe&thorn; at nede</L>
<L N="5672">To tylle &thorn;y soule with alm&euml;s dede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pers, of hys slep&euml; gan blynke,</L>
<L>And gretly on hys dreme gan &thorn;ynke&mdash;</L>
<L>Syghyng with mornyng chere,</L>
<L N="5676">As man &thorn;at was yn gret&euml; were,&mdash;</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he acouped was</L>
<L>with fend&euml;s fele for hys trespas,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;ey wulde haue dampned hym &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="5680">&YOGH;yf mercy of Ihesu Cryst ne were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;ys yn hys herte he kast,</L>
<L>And to hym self he spak at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at, for a lofe yn eueyl wylle</L>
<L N="5684">Halpe me yn so grete perel,</L>
<L>Moch&euml; wlde hyt helpe at nede,</L>
<L>with god&euml; wyl do alm&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">almas.</NOTE> dede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fro &thorn;at tym&euml; &thorn;an wax Pers</L>
<L N="5688">A man of so feyr&euml; maners,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man my&yogh;t yn hym fynde,</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e pore bo&thorn;e meke and kynde;</L>
<L>A mylder man ne my&yogh;t nat be,</L>
<L N="5692">Ne to &thorn;e pore, more of almes fre;</L>
<L>And reuful of herte also he was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mayst &thorn;ou here lere yn &thorn;ys pas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pers mette, vp-on a day,</L>
<L N="5696">A por&euml; man, by &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>As naked as he was bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn &thorn;e see had all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde al.</NOTE> lore.</L>
<L>He come to Pers, &thorn;ere he stode,</L>
<L N="5700">And asked hym sum of hys gode,&mdash;</L>
<L>Sumwhat of hys clo&thorn;yng,&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of heuene kyng.</L>
<L>Pers, was of reuful herte,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="186"></L>
<L N="5704">He toke hys kyrtyl of, as smert,</L>
<L>And ded hyt on &thorn;e man aboue,</L>
<L>And bad hym were hyt for hys loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e man hyt toke, and was ful bly&thorn;e;<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5708">He &yogh;ede and sold&euml; hyt asswy&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Pers stode and dyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede.</NOTE> beholde</L>
<L>How &thorn;e man &thorn;e kyrtyl solde,</L>
<L>And was &thorn;arwith<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore.</NOTE> ferly wro&thorn;e</L>
<L N="5712">&THORN;at he solde so sone hys clo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>He my&yogh;t no lenger for sorow stande,</L>
<L>But &yogh;ed&euml; home ful sore gretand,</L>
<L>And seyd, 'hyt was an euyl sygne,</L>
<L N="5716">And &thorn;at hym self was nat dygne</L>
<L>For to be yn hys preyere,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor nolde he &thorn;e kyrtyl were.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan he hadd&euml; ful long grete<NOTE PLACE="inter">wepte</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="5720">And a party &thorn;erof began<NOTE PLACE="foot">began &thorn;er-of.</NOTE> lete;&mdash;</L>
<L>For, comunlych aftyr wepe,</L>
<L>Fal men sone on slepe,&mdash;</L>
<L>As Pers lay yn hys slepyng,</L>
<L N="5724">Hym &thorn;oght a feyr&euml; sweuenyng.</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;oght he was yn heuene ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And of God he had a syght,</L>
<L>Syttyng yn hys kyrtyl clad</L>
<L N="5728">&THORN;at &thorn;e pore man of hym had,</L>
<L>And spak to hym ful myld&euml;ly,</L>
<L>"why wepest &thorn;ou, and art sory?</L>
<L>Lo, Pers," he sayde, "&thorn;ys ys &thorn;y cloth.</L>
<L N="5732">For he solde hyt, were<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yt were.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wroth;</L>
<L>Know hyt weyl, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou kan,</L>
<L>For me &thorn;ou &yogh;aue hyt &thorn;e pore man.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &yogh;aue hym yn charyte,</L>
<L N="5736">Euery deyl &thorn;ou &yogh;aue hyt me."
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Pers of slep&euml; out&euml; breyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hys slepe vpbreyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;oght grete wunder, &amp; se&thorn;en seyd,</L>
<L>"Blessyd be all&euml; por&euml; men,</L>
<L N="5740">For God almy&yogh;ty loue&thorn; hem;</L>
<L>And weyl ys hem &thorn;at pore are here;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are with God, bo&thorn;e lefe and dere;</L>
<L>And y shal fonde, by ny&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L N="5744">T&oacute; be pore, &yogh;yf &thorn;at y may."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hastly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hastely.</NOTE> he tok&euml; hys kateyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">katel.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="38b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> hyt to por&euml; men echedeyl.</L>
<L N="5747">Pers kalled to hym hys clerk</L>
<L>&THORN;at was hys notarye, and bade hym herk,</L>
<L>"Y shal &thorn;e shewe a pryuyte,</L>
<L>A &thorn;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt do to me;</L>
<L>y wyl &thorn;at &thorn;ou no man hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt no man.</NOTE> telle;</L>
<L N="5752">My body y take &thorn;e here to selle</L>
<L>To sum man, as yn bondage,</L>
<L>To lyue in pouert and yn seruage;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou do &thorn;us, y wyl be wroth,</L>
<L N="5756">And &thorn;ou and &thorn;yne shal be me loth.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do hyt, y shal &thorn;e &yogh;yue</L>
<L>Ten pownd of gold, wel with to lyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ten pownd y take &thorn;e here,</L>
<L N="5760">And me to selle on bonde manere;</L>
<L>Y ne recch&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">recche neuer.</NOTE> vn-to whom,</L>
<L>But onlych he haue &thorn;e crystendom;</L>
<L>&THORN;e raunsun &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt for me take,</L>
<L N="5764">&THORN;arfore &thorn;ou shalt sykernes make,</L>
<L>For to &yogh;yue hyt ble&thorn;ely and weyl</L>
<L>To por&euml; men, eu&euml;ry deyl,</L>
<L>And withholde &thorn;erof no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="5768">&THORN;e mountouns of a fer&thorn;yng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hys clerk was wo to do &thorn;at dede,
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>But only for manas and for drede.</L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>For dred&euml; Pers made hym hyt do,</L>
<L>And dede hym plyghte his trouthe &thorn;er-to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5773">Whan hys clerk had made hys othe,</L>
<L>Pers dede on hym a foul&euml; clothe;</L>
<L>Vnto a cherch&euml; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ey &yogh;ede</L>
<L N="5776">For to fulfylle hys wyl yn dede.<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 <I>Harl</I>. omits these six lines that O. has.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey to &thorn;e cherch&euml; com,</L>
<L>"Lorde, &thorn;oght &thorn;e clerk, now whom</L>
<L>My&yogh;t y fynde, &thorn;ys ych&euml; sele,<NOTE PLACE="inter">man</NOTE></L>
<L N="5780">To whom y my&yogh;t sell&euml; Pers wele!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e clerk loked euery where,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last, he knew where;</L>
<L>A rych&euml; man,<NOTE PLACE="foot">man was.</NOTE> &thorn;at er had be</L>
<L N="5784">Specyal knowlych euer betwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">knowelache hem betwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;urgh myschaunc&euml; at a kas</L>
<L>Alle hys gode y-lor&euml; was;</L>
<L>'&YOGH;ole,' &thorn;us &thorn;at man hyghte,</L>
<L N="5788">And knew &thorn;e clerk wel be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> syghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey spak of old&euml; a-queyntaunce,<MILESTONE N="39a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;ol&euml; tolde hym of hys chaunce.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seyde &thorn;e clerk, "y rede &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> bye</L>
<L N="5792">A man to do &thorn;y marchaundye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayst hold&euml; yn seruage</L>
<L>To restore weyl &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> dammage."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyde &yogh;ole, "on swych chaffare</L>
<L N="5796">wulde y feyn my syluer ware."</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk&euml; seyd, "lo, one here,</L>
<L>A trew man an a dubonure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; a debonurere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wyl seru&euml; &thorn;e to pay,</L>
<L N="5800">Peynebl&euml;, al &thorn;at he may.</L>
<L>'Pers,' shalt &thorn;ou calle hys name;</L>
<L>For hym shalt &thorn;ou haue moch&euml; frame.</L>
<L>he ys a man ful gracyous,</L>
<L N="5804">Gode to wynne vn-to &thorn;yn hous,</L>
<L>And God shal &yogh;yue &thorn;e hys blessyng,
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>And foysyn, yn all&euml; &thorn;yng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e clerk &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> all&euml; hys raunsun</L>
<L N="5808">To &thorn;e pore men of &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>Plenerly, alle &thorn;at he toke,</L>
<L>wy&thorn;helde he nat a fer&thorn;yng noke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'a corner.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure sent hys messageres</L>
<L N="5812">alle aboute for to sek&euml; Pers,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey ne my&yogh;t neuer here</L>
<L>Of rych&euml; Pers, &thorn;e tollere,</L>
<L>yn what sted&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stede &thorn;at.</NOTE> he was nome,</L>
<L N="5816">No whydyrward he was become;</L>
<L>No &thorn;e clerk wuld telle to none,</L>
<L>whydyrward &thorn;at Pers was gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now ys Pers bycom&euml; bryche,<NOTE PLACE="inter">logh</NOTE></L>
<L N="5820">&THORN;at er was bo&thorn;&euml; stoute and ryche.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at euer any man hym do bade,</L>
<L>Pers dyd hyt with hert[&euml;] glad.</L>
<L>he wax so myld&euml; and so meke,</L>
<L N="5824">A mylder man &thorn;urt no man seke;</L>
<L>For he meked hym self ouer skyle,</L>
<L>Pottes and dysshes for to swele.<NOTE PLACE="foot">swyle.</NOTE></L>
<L>To grete penaunce he gan hym take,<MILESTONE N="39a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5828">And moch&euml; for to fast and wake,</L>
<L>And moche he loued &thorn;olmodnesse</L>
<L>To ryche, to pore, to more, to lesse.</L>
<L>Of all&euml; men he wuld haue doute,</L>
<L N="5832">And to here byddyng mekly loute;</L>
<L>wulde &thorn;ey bydde hym sytte or stande,</L>
<L>Euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Euermore.</NOTE> he wuld&euml; be bowande;</L>
<L>And for he bare hym so meke and softe,</L>
<L N="5836">Shrew&euml;s mysded hym ful ofte,</L>
<L>And held&euml; hym folted or wode,</L>
<L>For he was so mylde of mode.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey &thorn;at were hys felaus</L>
<L N="5840">Mysseyd hym most yn her&euml; sawes;</L>
<L>And alle he suffred here vpbreyd,
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>And neuer naght a&yogh;ens hem seyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ole, hys lorde, wel vndyrstode</L>
<L N="5844">&THORN;at al hys grac&euml; and hys gode</L>
<L>Com for &thorn;e loue of Pers,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of so holy maners;</L>
<L>And whan he wyst of hys bounte,</L>
<L N="5848">He kalled Pers yn pryuyte,</L>
<L>"Pers," he seyd, "&thorn;ou were wur&thorn;y</L>
<L>For to be wurscheped more &thorn;an y,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art weyl with Ihesu;</L>
<L N="5852">He shewe&thorn; for &thorn;e grete vertu;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor y shal make &thorn;e fre;</L>
<L>Y wyl &thorn;at my felaw<NOTE PLACE="foot">my felawe &thorn;at.</NOTE> &thorn;ou be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ar-to Pers granted<NOTE PLACE="foot">grauntede.</NOTE> noght,</L>
<L N="5856">To be freman, as he besoght;</L>
<L>he wuld&euml; be, as he was ore,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at seruage for euermore.</L>
<L>he &thorn;anked &thorn;e lorde myld&euml;ly</L>
<L N="5860">For hys gret&euml; curteysy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sy&thorn;&thorn;en Ihesu, &thorn;urgh hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Shewed hym, t&oacute; Pers sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For to be stalwor&thorn;e yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> hys fondyng,</L>
<L N="5864">And to hym haue loue longyng.</L>
<L>"Be nat sorowful to do penaunce;<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>y am with &thorn;e yn euery chaunce;</L>
<L N="5867">Pers, I hau&euml; mynde of &thorn;e;</L>
<L>lo, here &thorn;e kyrtyl &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits '&thorn;at.'</NOTE> &thorn;ou &yogh;aue for me;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor grace y shal &thorn;e sende,</L>
<L>Yn alle godeness&euml; weyl to ende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Byfyl &thorn;at seriauntes and squyers</L>
<L N="5872">&THORN;at were wunt to seru&euml; Pers,</L>
<L>went yn pylgrymage, as yn kas,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at cuntre &thorn;ere Pers was.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ole ful feyr&euml; gan hem kalle,</L>
<L N="5876">And preyde hem hom&euml; to hys halle.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>Pers was &thorn;ere, &thorn;at ych&euml; sele,</L>
<L>And euerychone he knew hem wele.</L>
<L>Alle he serued hem as a knaue</L>
<L N="5880">&THORN;at was wunt here seruyse to haue.</L>
<L>But Pers nat &yogh;yt &thorn;ey knew,</L>
<L>For penaunce chaunged was hys hew;<NOTE PLACE="inter">colour</NOTE></L>
<L N="5883">Nat for&thorn;y &thorn;ey behelde hym fast,</L>
<L>And oftyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte.</NOTE> to hym here y&yogh;en &thorn;ey kast,</L>
<L>And seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyden.</NOTE> "he &thorn;at stont&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stant.</NOTE> here,</L>
<L>Ys lych&euml; to Pers tollere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hydde hys vysege al &thorn;at he my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5888">Out of knowlych<NOTE PLACE="foot">knowlache.</NOTE> of here sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles &thorn;ey behelde hym more,</L>
<L>And knew hym weyl, al &thorn;at were &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>And seyd, "&YOGH;ole, ys &yogh;one &thorn;y page?</L>
<L N="5892">A ryche man ys yn &thorn;y seruage;</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperoure, bo&thorn;e fer and nere,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; do hym seche, &thorn;at we fynde here."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pers lestned, and herd hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> spekyng,</L>
<L N="5896">And &thorn;at &thorn;ey had of hym knowyng;</L>
<L>And pryuyly a-wey he nam,</L>
<L>Tyl he to &thorn;e porter cam.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e porter had hys spech&euml; lore,</L>
<L N="5900">And heryng also, syn he was bore;</L>
<L>But &thorn;urgh &thorn;e grace of swete Ihesu,</L>
<L>was shewed, for Pers, feyre vertu.</L>
<L>Pers seyd, "lat&euml; me fur&thorn; go."<MILESTONE N="38b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5904">&THORN;e porter spak, and seyd&euml; "&yogh;o."</L>
<L>He &thorn;at was def, and doumbe also,</L>
<L>Spak, whan Pers spak hym to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pers out at &thorn;e &yogh;at&euml; wente,</L>
<L N="5908">And &thorn;edyr &yogh;ede, &thorn;ere God hym sente.</L>
<L>&THORN;e porter &yogh;ede vp to &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ys merueyl&euml; tolde hem alle,
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>How &thorn;e squyler of &thorn;e kechyn,</L>
<L N="5912">Pers, &thorn;at ha&thorn; woned here yn,</L>
<L>"He asked leu&euml;, ry&yogh;t now late,</L>
<L>And went fur&thorn; out at &thorn;e &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>Y rede &yogh;ow alle, &yogh;eue&thorn; gode tent,</L>
<L N="5916">whederward &thorn;at Pers ys went.</L>
<L>with Ihesu cryst he ys pryue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ys shewed weyl on me;</L>
<L>For, what tyme he to me spak,</L>
<L N="5920">Out of hys mou&thorn; me &thorn;oght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ughte.</NOTE> brak</L>
<L>A flamme of fyre bryght and clere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e flaumme made me bo&thorn; speke and here;</L>
<L>Speke, and here, now, bo&thorn;e y may,</L>
<L N="5924">Blessed be God and Pers to day!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lord&euml; and &thorn;e gest&euml;s alle,</L>
<L>One and o&thorn;er &thorn;at were yn halle,</L>
<L>Had merueyle &thorn;at hyt was so,</L>
<L N="5928">&THORN;at he my&yogh;te swych myr&aacute;cle do.</L>
<L>&THORN;an asswy&thorn;&euml; Pers &thorn;ey soght,</L>
<L>But al here sekyng was for no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Neuer, Pers &thorn;ey ne founde,</L>
<L N="5932">Ny&yogh;t ne day, yn no stounde;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at toke Ennok and Ely,</L>
<L>He toke Pers, &thorn;urgh hys mercy,</L>
<L>To reste with-outyn ende to lede</L>
<L N="5936">For hys meknes and hys gode dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Take ensample here, of Pers,</L>
<L>And parte&thorn; with &thorn;e pore, &yogh;e okerers,</L>
<L>For &yogh;ow shal neuer come Ioye with-ynne,</L>
<L N="5940">But &yogh;e leu&euml; fyrst &thorn;at synne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue to almes &thorn;at ych&euml; &thorn;yng<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e haue wune wy&thorn; okeryng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now with God, leue we Pers;</L>
<L N="5944">God &yogh;yue vs grace to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. omits 'to.'</NOTE> do hys maners!
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn coueytyse synnen marchauntys<NOTE PLACE="foot">marchaundes.</NOTE> mekyl,</L>
<L>Yn feyr&euml; wurdys and yn fykyl,</L>
<L>And hete&thorn; hym god&euml; &thorn;at he bye&thorn;,</L>
<L N="5948">And swere&thorn; &thorn;arto, and algate lye&thorn;.</L>
<L>For fals peys and<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> for.</NOTE> fals mesure</L>
<L>here soul&euml;s haue mys&aacute;uenture.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also hyt longe&thorn; to coueytyse</L>
<L N="5952">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hyre one out of seruyse</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &yogh;yft or &thorn;urgh procurment,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest gretly yn swych atent:</L>
<L>Enuye hyt ys, and falsnes yn dede,</L>
<L N="5956">But &yogh;yf hyt were for &thorn;e mor&euml; nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou boghtest of any seriaunt</L>
<L>pryuyly, yn stylle cunnaunt,</L>
<L>&THORN;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ou wystyst wel was stole,</L>
<L N="5960">And &thorn;urgh &thorn;y byyng was forhole,</L>
<L>Hyt ys coueytyse and &thorn;eft pryue</L>
<L>To bye &thorn;yng out of commalte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">comnalte.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou receyuedyst any what</L>
<L N="5964">Of on&euml; &thorn;at hys &thorn;yng forgat;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou &yogh;yue hyt hym a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e valeu for certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art falle &thorn;an yn &thorn;e vyce</L>
<L N="5968">Of, coueytyse, &thorn;eft, and auaryce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or &yogh;yf.</NOTE> &thorn;ou ledyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">leddest.</NOTE> any man to &thorn;e ale</L>
<L>And madest hym drunk with troteuale,</L>
<L>And he solde hys &thorn;yng to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="5972">More &thorn;an he wulde yn soberte,</L>
<L>Hyt seme&thorn; &thorn;ou art a gylour,</L>
<L>And coueytous, and trechour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5975">For men &thorn;at loue to do gylerye,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e alehous make &thorn;ey marchaundye,</L>
<L>To loke &yogh;yf &thorn;ey kunne com with-ynne,
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>here neghburs &thorn;yng, falsly to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a ryche man hyt noye&thorn; oftyn tyde<MILESTONE N="40a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5980">&THORN;at a por&euml; man hat oght<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; oght hym.</NOTE> besyde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he may, with euyl he fondys</L>
<L>For to reue hym, and haue hys londys;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he may nat hem at hym bye,</L>
<L N="5984">He wul weyte hym o&thorn;er felunnye,</L>
<L>hym to sle, or to endyte,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;eft he wyl vpon<NOTE PLACE="foot">vpon O, on H.</NOTE> hym wyte,</L>
<L>Or ou&thorn;er ska&thorn;e he wyl hym weyte,</L>
<L N="5988">Hys bestes for to bete or bayte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">beyte.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ete hys grasse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gresse.</NOTE> or foule hys corne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hys gode shal neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">nere.</NOTE> be lorne:</L>
<L>Of swyche men, bo&thorn;e wryte hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wryte ys.</NOTE> &amp; seyd,</L>
<L N="5992">Moche peyne ys before hem leyde;</L>
<L>here synne shal no&thorn;er be for&yogh;yuen ne slakyn</L>
<L>Vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vntyl.</NOTE> &thorn;ey &yogh;elde &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue takyn;</L>
<L>Here mercy ys ful on-<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn.</NOTE> certeyn</L>
<L N="5996">But &thorn;ey &yogh;elde hem here gode a&yogh;eyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ys, before &yogh;e herde me rede,</L>
<L>How seynt Fursyn founde hyt yn dede;</L>
<L N="5999">And here y shal telle a lytyl tale</L>
<L>Of swyche a man &thorn;at brewed hys bale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Lucretius, and how the Devil leapt into him.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a man &thorn;at hyght Lucrecyus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>A swy&thorn;&euml; ryche and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and a.</NOTE> coueytous;</L>
<L>Besyde hym won&egrave;d a mayden wys,</L>
<L N="6004">Here<NOTE PLACE="foot">Here O, He H.</NOTE> name was kalled Beatrys.</L>
<L>Lucrecyus &thorn;oght on felonye;</L>
<L>here land&euml;s he wulde algate bye.</L>
<L>And, shortly &yogh;ow for to telle,</L>
<L N="6008">&THORN;ys lady wuld&euml; nat hem selle.
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>when he wyst hyt, &thorn;an was hym wo;</L>
<L>He weyted here, and ded here slo.</L>
<L>whan he h&aacute;d do here &thorn;at pyne,</L>
<L N="6012">Yn alle here landes he toke sesyne,</L>
<L>And was &thorn;an a ryche lordyng</L>
<L>And bare hym stout&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">stout.</NOTE> as a kyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">kynge.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys Lucrecyus made a feste,</L>
<L N="6016">A ryche, with men of noble geste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lordyng&euml;s &thorn;at he my&yogh;t gete<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>were sett&euml; with hym at &thorn;e mete;</L>
<L>And as he sat yn alle hys pryde,</L>
<L N="6020">Com a pore womman &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>And bare a chylde yn clo&thorn;&euml;s loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pappe yn &thorn;e mou&thorn;e as hyt had soke;</L>
<L>Hyt hade neuer spoke before, saun&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">saunt&yogh;.</NOTE> fayle,</L>
<L N="6024">&THORN;arfor y telle hyt, &thorn;e more meruayle.</L>
<L>As for grete myr&aacute;cle, &thorn;e chyld seyd &thorn;us,</L>
<L>"y sey to &thorn;e, Lucrecyus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast slayn seynt Beatrys,</L>
<L N="6028">To haue here lond &thorn;at by here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e (here <I>adv.</I>).</NOTE> lys.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art come now vn-to here fe,</L>
<L>And syttest &thorn;ere yn &thorn;y pouste;</L>
<L>And y comaunde, &thorn;urgh Goddys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6032">&THORN;e deuyl, yn-to &thorn;e to ly&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As son&euml; as &thorn;e chylde had spoke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml; yn-to hym was lope,</L>
<L>And traueyled hym &thorn;re dayys with pyne</L>
<L N="6036">&THORN;at alle hyt saw&euml; with here yne;</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e &thorn;re day[y]s ende,</L>
<L>He deyd&euml;, and to helle gan wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke now, how &thorn;e deuyl hym laght</L>
<L N="6040">For coueytyse of wurldys aght.</L>
<L>Ful wykked ys &thorn;at coueytyse,</L>
<L>with o&thorn;er mennes gode falsly to ryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt hyt ys wers &thorn;an ys &thorn;e lore
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="196"></L>
<L N="6044">To do a man to de&thorn; &thorn;arfore.</L>
<L>Of God almy&yogh;ty ha&thorn; he noun eye,</L>
<L>Ne he ne &thorn;enke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;enke&thorn; nat.</NOTE> for to deye;</L>
<L>On hys de&thorn; he &thorn;enke&thorn; neuer,</L>
<L N="6048">And &thorn;arfor deye&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dey&thorn;.</NOTE> he for euer.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e ryche men, &yogh;e ryche purchasours,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wene &thorn;at al &thorn;e worlde be &yogh;ours;</L>
<L>And yn alle &yogh;oure moste purch&aacute;ce</L>
<L N="6052">Com&thorn; &yogh;oure de&thorn; sunnest yn place;</L>
<L>God shewe&thorn; hyt oft&euml; to &yogh;ow;</L>
<L>&THORN;enke&thorn; &thorn;&eacute;ron for &yogh;oure prow.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="40b:2" UNIT="folio"> What seye &yogh;e by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be.</NOTE> &thorn;ese streyte negons<NOTE PLACE="foot">nygones.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6056">&THORN;at se al day Godd&euml;s persones<NOTE PLACE="foot">prysones.</NOTE></L>
<L>Before hem dey&euml; for mysese,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey are ryche and wel at ese,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;yt mow &thorn;ey no &thorn;yng spare</L>
<L N="6060">To helpe &thorn;e por&euml; &thorn;at mys fare.</L>
<L>Swyche a man ys auarous,</L>
<L>weyl wers &thorn;an ys coueytous;</L>
<L>For coueytyse ys yn purchace,</L>
<L N="6064">And auaryc&euml; halt long space.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens mokerers wyl y &thorn;repe</L>
<L>&THORN;at gadren pens vn-to an<NOTE PLACE="foot">vntyl a.</NOTE> hepe;</L>
<L>y warne hem all&euml; yn &thorn;ys wurde,</L>
<L N="6068">whan mokerers gadren yn-to hurde</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuyl ys here tresorer,</L>
<L>For auaryce ys hys spenser.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y speke to men of rych&euml; lyfe</L>
<L N="6072">&THORN;at han no charge of chylde ne wyfe,</L>
<L>persones, prestes, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;an H.</NOTE> han here rente,</L>
<L>And ou&thorn;er &thorn;at han<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> grete extente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mow weyl, at all&euml; &yogh;ers,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eres.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6076">lyue as lordes, and be here pers:<NOTE PLACE="foot">peres.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ese nede nat to haue tresourye,
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>But aftyr manhede and curteysye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf an husbond chyldryn haue,</L>
<L N="6080">One or two, mayden or knaue,</L>
<L>He may haue store and tresour</L>
<L>To kepe with hys chyldryn yn honour.</L>
<L>wele ys wur&thorn;y &thorn;at he haue gode,</L>
<L N="6084">&THORN;at wel dyspende&thorn; hyt on hys blode.</L>
<L>As wykkedly, me &thorn;enke&thorn; ys hyt doun,</L>
<L>A man to gadyr oute of resoun,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;erwith noun alm&euml;s dede,</L>
<L N="6088">Por&euml; men to helpe at nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A man &thorn;at ha&thorn; pens in chest,</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;es to slepe ha&thorn; he rest;</L>
<L>with alle &thorn;at go nerhond, hym greues,</L>
<L N="6092">For alle, he wene&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ey be &thorn;eues;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; he &thorn;at gadre&thorn; tresoure,<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at go byfore hys dore.</L>
<L>Swych euyl &thorn;oghtes here soul&euml; &thorn;enke&thorn;,</L>
<L N="6096">And seye of hem euyl, &thorn;at noun hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem.</NOTE> &thorn;enke&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at gadry&thorn; to tresorye,&mdash;</L>
<L>Be he neuer so wys ne slye,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese &thorn;re sorwes<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorous.</NOTE> shal he haue,</L>
<L N="6100">hys tresour for to gete and saue:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst, ys trauayle yn &thorn;e wynnyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er, ys drede to kepe &thorn;at &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ryd ys &thorn;e most wo,</L>
<L N="6104">&THORN;at tyme &thorn;at he shall parte &thorn;arfro.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou rych&euml; man, &thorn;ou lestene weyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gettyst but sorow of euery deyl.</L>
<L>Sykyr lyfe shalt &thorn;ou noun lede;</L>
<L N="6108">&THORN;yn herte ys &thorn;erfor euer yn drede."</L>
<L>And her&euml; y shal telle a lyte,</L>
<L>A wurd&euml; of a gode Ermyte.
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="198"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the good Hermit who gave away the Money he had saved.]</HEAD>
<L>An ermyte woned fer ouer a doune,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6112">yn a wasteyne, fer fro &thorn;e toune;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ermyte &thorn;oght vp-on a day</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was yn febyl aray,</L>
<L>And seyd, he wulde gader to store</L>
<L N="6116">Tyl eftsones he had ned&euml; more.</L>
<L>He gadred vn-to stor&euml; fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys purs he fylled at &thorn;e last.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o was he yn grete stodye</L>
<L N="6120">where he my&yogh;t do hyt pryuylye,</L>
<L>For to lese hyt he was a dred;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">He.</NOTE> &yogh;ede and leyd hyt at hys bed.</L>
<L>whan he shuld slep&euml;, he my&yogh;t noght,</L>
<L N="6124">So moch&euml; on hyt was hys &thorn;oght;</L>
<L>whan he sagh men come or go,</L>
<L>He &thorn;oghte and seyd&euml;, "&thorn;eues are &thorn;o."</L>
<L>Euery man he wened<NOTE PLACE="foot">wende.</NOTE> had be a robbour,</L>
<L N="6128">For dred&euml; &thorn;at he had<NOTE PLACE="foot">hadde.</NOTE> tresoure.</L>
<L>And whan he seyd hys oures of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>He &thorn;oght on hys tresour &thorn;er hyt lay.</L>
<L>And more was he &thorn;an morenande<MILESTONE N="41a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6132">Se&thorn;en &thorn;an befor&euml;hand:</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd hym self, "weyl y ferde</L>
<L>Ar y, yn purs, penys<NOTE PLACE="foot">penys O, pens H.</NOTE> sperde;</L>
<L>Now slepe y neuer but with kare,</L>
<L N="6136">Syn y wyst, wh&eacute;re pens ware."</L>
<L>"y trowe," he seyde, "&thorn;at Goddys curs</L>
<L>ys spred<NOTE PLACE="foot">sperde.</NOTE> with pens, yn &thorn;e purs."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he ros vp and &yogh;ede to hys &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And sagh twey men come yn &thorn;e gate;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'wey.'</NOTE></L>
<L>He parseyued weyl whydyrward &thorn;ey cam,
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="199"></L>
<L N="6142">And swy&thorn;e aftyr hys purs he ran,</L>
<L>And kast hyt to hem euery deyl,</L>
<L>And seyd, "haue&thorn;, and brouke&thorn; hyt weyl,</L>
<L>For, myn herte was neuer yn reste</L>
<L>Syn y had hem a ny&yogh;tys geste;</L>
<L>For shal y neuer, aftyr &thorn;ys day,</L>
<L N="6148">Purs, pens, &yogh;yf &thorn;at y may."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfor he &thorn;at mekel has,</L>
<L>Hys herte ys yn many a kas;</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &thorn;yk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;eke.</NOTE> pore ermyte</L>
<L N="6152">was yn dred&euml; for so lyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Auaryce ys &thorn;y moch&euml; fo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue of God<NOTE PLACE="foot">God O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> hyt draghe&thorn; &thorn;e fro;</L>
<L>And syluer algat[e], nam&euml;ly,</L>
<L N="6156">Hyt ys a god of maumetry;</L>
<L>For maumetry ys mad&euml; alle</L>
<L>Of golde and syluer and swych matalle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sara&yogh;yns and ou&thorn;er wanbodyes,</L>
<L N="6160">&THORN;er-of &thorn;ey make &thorn;at are here goddes;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefor y rede &thorn;at &yogh;e loue hyt noght,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No O.<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></NOTE> ouer moche to haue yn thoght:</L>
<L>&THORN;yr ys no &thorn;yng yn er&thorn;e aboue,</L>
<L N="6164">&THORN;at dragh&thorn; so moch&euml; mann&euml;s loue</L>
<L>Fro God, n&eacute; fro Goddys wurde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrd O.</NOTE></L>
<L>As golde<NOTE PLACE="foot">or O.</NOTE> and syluer leyde yn hurde;</L>
<L>And y haue oft&euml; herd&euml; seye</L>
<L N="6168">Of sum men whan &thorn;ey shuld&euml; deye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ey wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> haue her pens ete<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an any ou&thorn;er had hem gete;</L>
<L>And, here ar y fer&thorn;er go,</L>
<L N="6172">y shal telle of one &thorn;at ded<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at wlde O.</NOTE> so.
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="200"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Cambridgeshire Miser-Parson.]</HEAD>
<L>yn Chambryg-shyr&euml;, yn a toune,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>y herd telle of a persoune:</L>
<L>Shortly to tell&euml;, at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L N="6176">hys de&thorn; euyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">euyl O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> down hym kaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men sente aftyr twey freres,</L>
<L>&THORN;at perauenture were hys cunseylers;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese frer&egrave;s cam, and by hym sate,</L>
<L N="6180">and ask&eacute;d hym of hys state.</L>
<L>&THORN;is persone lay, and loked fur&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">forth O.</NOTE></L>
<L>vn-tyl a cofre yn &thorn;e florth.</L>
<L>&THORN;arto &thorn;e frere &yogh;af god&euml; tente</L>
<L N="6184">whyderward hys y&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">e&yogh;en O.</NOTE> glente;</L>
<L>&THORN;arto he loked euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">eure O.</NOTE> anone,</L>
<L>And lay styll&euml; as a stone;</L>
<L>&THORN;an asked &thorn;e ton<NOTE PLACE="foot">to O.</NOTE> frere,</L>
<L N="6188">"what ys yn &thorn;ys cofre here?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e person&euml; spak no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>But &yogh;af a gret&euml; syghyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e freres kalled men hem to,</L>
<L N="6192">&THORN;at cofre for to vn-do:</L>
<L>&THORN;e persones men come echone:</L>
<L>"Key," &thorn;ey seyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde &thorn;ey had O.</NOTE> "hadd &thorn;ey none."</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyd vp sone &thorn;ey wraste,</L>
<L N="6196">And brak &thorn;e lok<NOTE PLACE="foot">lokes O.</NOTE> at &thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ey fonde &thorn;e cofre ful</L>
<L>Sperd wy&thorn; &thorn;e deuylys mul</L>
<L>Of florens and of goldrynges,</L>
<L N="6200">And of many ou&thorn;er &thorn;ynges</L>
<L>&THORN;at were of syluer, vesseles,</L>
<L>And gold and ou&thorn;er Iuweles.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wrecche saw hys tresoure sperd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spred O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="201"></L>
<L N="6204">And sette hym up yn hys bedde,</L>
<L>And bekened<NOTE PLACE="foot">beknede O.</NOTE> &thorn;er-aftyr with hys hand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">honde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e frer&euml; seyd, "y vndyrstande<NOTE PLACE="foot">-stonde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> haue sum of &thorn;ys."<MILESTONE N="41b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6208">&THORN;ey toke and fylde a syluer dysshe</L>
<L>Ful of pens, and to hym broght,</L>
<L>To se what was yn hys &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>he toke and fyld&euml; ful hys fyst,</L>
<L N="6212">And yn-to hys mou&thorn;e &thorn;e pens kyst,</L>
<L>As &thorn;at he wuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> hem haue ete,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he my&yogh;t hem al haue gete.</L>
<L>And, whan &thorn;ey sagh hym &thorn;us do,</L>
<L N="6216">&THORN;e frer&euml; styrt&euml; hym vn-to,</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e dyssh&euml; of hys hand</L>
<L>Magre<NOTE PLACE="foot">Maugre O.</NOTE> hys wylland.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[5-<I>syll. line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And a-none he fyll&euml; downe,</L>
<L N="6220">And deyd, y wen&euml;, yn a suowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>See&thorn; now how hys louyng</L>
<L>Bro&yogh;t hym to euyl endyng!</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">had O.</NOTE> loued and holde faste,</L>
<L N="6224">with shame &thorn;ey departed at &thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore hyt were bettyr here</L>
<L>Dyspende here &thorn;yng on gode manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an for to ley hyt vp yn mucche,</L>
<L N="6228">O&thorn;er yn cofre, o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or O.</NOTE> yn hucche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Auaryc&euml;, ryche and harde,</L>
<L>ys a &thorn;efe, a mokerad,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mokerard O.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan he mucche&thorn; pryuyly</L>
<L N="6232">&THORN;at many man my&yogh;t lyu&euml; by.</L>
<L>Ryche men gadere ryche tresours</L>
<L>To make with ryche executours:</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyles &thorn;e exec&uacute;tours sekke,<NOTE PLACE="inter">fyl &thorn;e bag</NOTE></L>
<L N="6236">Of &thorn;e soul&euml; &thorn;ey ne rekke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e body, whyl hyt on bere lys,</L>
<L>A day or two ys holde yn prys,</L>
<L>But whan hyt ys yn er&thorn;&euml; broght,</L>
<L N="6240">Body ne soul&euml; gete ry&yogh;t noght;</L>
<L>Be he broght nobly to hys pyt,
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>Dette and soule &thorn;ey &thorn;ynke al quyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke &thorn;erfore, executore,</L>
<L N="6244">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue &yogh;yt hold yn store</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou oghtest for to haue &yogh;yue,<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But fro day to day hast hyt dryue:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest &thorn;an wykkedly,</L>
<L N="6248">And doust &thorn;e soule treytory;</L>
<L>But &thorn;us sey&thorn; holy story,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule &thorn;at ys yn purgatory</L>
<L>loke&thorn; fast aftyr &thorn;e socoure</L>
<L N="6252">Of &thorn;e gode executoure;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he hyt help&euml; for to saue,</L>
<L>Gret&euml; mede &thorn;an shal he haue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he do nat hys ordynaunce,</L>
<L N="6256">hyt aske&thorn; of God to hym veniaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of all&euml; fals &thorn;at beryn name,</L>
<L>Fals executours are maste to blame.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope of &thorn;e courte of Rome,</L>
<L N="6260">A&yogh;ens hem &yogh;yf&thorn; he hard&euml; dome,</L>
<L>And curse&thorn; hem yn cherchys here</L>
<L>Four&euml; tym&euml;s yn &thorn;e &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of alle executours &thorn;at men fynde,</L>
<L N="6264">werst are &thorn;yn own&euml; kynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y chyldryn specyaly</L>
<L>Are to &thorn;y soule vnkynd&euml;ly:</L>
<L>&THORN;y chyldryn all&euml; sey ryght &thorn;us:<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryght &thorn;us O, &thorn;us H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6268">"whom shuld &thorn;ey &yogh;yu&euml; hyt, but vs?"</L>
<L>y graunte weyl hyt ys &yogh;yue to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou to hem &thorn;an sumwhat fre:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was heren, now hyt ys &thorn;yne;</L>
<L N="6272">helpe hem &thorn;erwy&thorn; oute of pyne;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou mayst nat, for auaryce,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e bound&euml; yn &thorn;at vyce,</L>
<L>To spar&euml; no &thorn;yng &thorn;at was hys</L>
<L N="6276">For to bryng&euml; hym to blys.
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>And many tym&euml;s, so hyt gos,</L>
<L>menn&euml;s eyres are here most fos;</L>
<L>Namly, an eyre &thorn;at ys a qued,<NOTE PLACE="inter">shrewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">ashrewe O.</NOTE></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">aqued O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6280">&thorn;at desyre&thorn; hys fadrys<NOTE PLACE="foot">fader O.</NOTE> ded;</L>
<L>For oft&euml; haue men herde and sen</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych eyr&euml;s hau&euml; ben.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn London, &thorn;e wurde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrd O.</NOTE> gan go,<MILESTONE N="42a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6284">&THORN;at eyr&euml;s ded here fadrys slo;</L>
<L>And wyues wundryng was so bolde</L>
<L>To make here husbundes kok&euml;wolde:</L>
<L>Many tym&euml;s, for swych dede,</L>
<L N="6288">Are eyr&euml;s moch&euml; for to drede;</L>
<L>For doute &thorn;erof, &thorn;ys ys &thorn;e skyle,</L>
<L>To que&thorn;e here landys where &thorn;ey wyle;</L>
<L>hous and rente, and ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="6292">Mow &thorn;ey que&thorn;e at here endyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e ryche men, before &yogh;ow se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyles &yogh;e are yn &yogh;oure pouste;</L>
<L>On &yogh;oure soules, y rede &yogh;ow &thorn;enke;</L>
<L N="6296">y warne &yogh;ow of &yogh;oure eyres blenke;</L>
<L>Ne haue&thorn; no trust of &yogh;oure sokoure,</L>
<L>Nat of &yogh;oure owne executoure;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue&thorn; &yogh;eself with &yogh;oure hondys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hendes O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6300">For &thorn;e dede ha&thorn; few[&euml;] frendys;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey &thorn;at &thorn;ou louyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">leuest O.</NOTE> with-alle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;y soule wyl &yogh;yue but smalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;re executurs y shal &yogh;ou rede,</L>
<L>how &thorn;ey halpe ones a soule yn nede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Three Dishonest Executors.]</HEAD>
<L N="6305">A tale y herde a gode man sey,</L>
<L>how a man dyd whan he shuld deye:</L>
<L>he ches hym &thorn;re executours,</L>
<L N="6308">Of al hys godys ordeynours,</L>
<L>Twey lewed men and a clerke,
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>To do gode yn soul&euml; werke.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys clerk was a lordyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="6312">&THORN;e to&thorn;er was an husbunde &thorn;at lyued<NOTE PLACE="foot">husbund lyued O.</NOTE> by hys &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ryd&euml; was a marchaunde<NOTE PLACE="foot">marchound O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at boght and solde with cunnaunte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">cunnound O.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyl auenture he deyd&euml; sone;</L>
<L N="6316">&THORN;ey dyd with hym &thorn;at was to done;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e er&thorn;&euml; &thorn;ey hym dyght,</L>
<L>For, &thorn;at was &thorn;e dedys ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>whan he was dede, for&yogh;ate &thorn;ey no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="6320">&THORN;at al hys god&euml; &thorn;ey fur&thorn;e broght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ey hadde gadred and a-countede<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;rytty mark hys gode amounted;</L>
<L>hys vessel was ten mark wur&thorn;y,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wr&thorn;y O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6324">and ten mark of pens redy,</L>
<L>and ten mark hys ou&thorn;er store:</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ey hyt set, and at no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys clerk seyd: "we are &thorn;re;</L>
<L N="6328">As y rede, so do shul &yogh;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; man &thorn;at ded&euml; ys,</L>
<L>y hope hys soul&euml; be yn blys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">See John of Bromyard's <I>Summa Predicantium</I> (c. 1390, ed. 1485), Executor, E. viij. .xiiij. Exemplum: sicut patet, de executoribus, De quibus scribitur, quod, inter se tractantes de bonis defuncti, dixerunt quod mortuus ille, vel fuit in celo, &amp; tunc bonis illis non indiget; vel in inferno, tunc ei non valerent; vel in purgatorio, &amp; tunc sine illis liberaretur: finaliter, "Ergo," inquiuunt, "inter nos illa diuidamus, quia talibus indigemus."</NOTE></L>
<L>and &yogh;yf hys soul&euml; yn blys be,</L>
<L N="6332">he ha&thorn; no nede of gold ne fe;</L>
<L>hyt may no more but be yn heuene,</L>
<L>&thorn;ogh we &yogh;aue &thorn;ys, and swych[&euml;] seuene;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hys soul&euml; be yn helle,</L>
<L N="6336">Alle &thorn;e pens &thorn;at we mow telle,</L>
<L>ne alle &thorn;e prestes &thorn;at messe mow synge,</L>
<L>Mow nat hyt out of hell&euml; brynge:</L>
<L>So, be hyt yn helle, or be hyt yn blys,</L>
<L N="6340">hyt ha&thorn; no mor&euml; nede of &thorn;ys;
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>"And we are swore to dele hyt ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And euen to parte hyt at oure my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>So we shul, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &yogh;e wylle:</L>
<L N="6344">And sey&thorn; now here an euyn skylle;</L>
<L>he vouchede hyt saufe on vs, he seyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we &yogh;aue hyt whan he deyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ys yche vessel &thorn;at &yogh;e se,</L>
<L N="6348">hyt may wel fall&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">falle weyl O.</NOTE> to me.</L>
<L>&thorn;e store of hous, y vndyrstande,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vndyrstonde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Falle&thorn; weyl to an husbande;<NOTE PLACE="foot">husbonde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ese pens falle on best wyse</L>
<L>To a marchaunde to do hys marchaundyse.</L>
<L N="6353">For so&thorn;&euml;, y kan se no bet,</L>
<L>How euer hyt my&yogh;t be bettyr sette;</L>
<L>No better, certes, my&yogh;t hyt falle:</L>
<L N="6356">&THORN;ys &yogh;e see&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn; O.</NOTE> and wete&thorn; alle.</L>
<L>Tak&euml; eche man hys party,</L>
<L>For y haue parted hyt euenly."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And eche of hem hys part&euml; toke;<MILESTONE N="42b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6360">Hyred &thorn;ey ney&thorn;er messe ne boke</L>
<L>For to synge, ne for to rede;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey seyd &thorn;e soul&euml; had no nede.</L>
<L>y pray God, mysauenture</L>
<L N="6364">hau&euml; swych executure!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Executur &thorn;at wyl nat do</L>
<L>As &thorn;e dede ordeyned to,</L>
<L>he shal haue ful euyl endyng</L>
<L N="6368">&thorn;at so wy&thorn;-halt &thorn;e ded&euml;s &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>Fals executours &thorn;at haue ben,</L>
<L>&thorn;ys chaunce haue men of hem sen,</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er fayle&thorn; hem wurld&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrldes O.</NOTE> grace,</L>
<L N="6372">Or, at here endyng, speche or space;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hyt stonde &thorn;e wurld&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrldes O.</NOTE> aght,</L>
<L>A tokene hyt ys, hys soule ys kaght.
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="206"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And here, at &thorn;ys ych&euml; pas,</L>
<L N="6376">Y shal &yogh;ow tell&euml; of a kas</L>
<L>&THORN;at fyl now late yn Kesteuene;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e name y wyl nat neuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Two wicked Kesteven Executors.]</HEAD>
<L>A man, shortly for to sey,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6380">Whan he wyst &thorn;at he shuld deye,</L>
<L>Twey lewed men hys executours<NOTE PLACE="foot">executurs O, executour H.</NOTE> he ches,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou shalt here, wykked and les.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme hyt happed for to be,</L>
<L N="6384">Hys sone was oute of &thorn;at cuntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;e dede was yn hys graue,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey toke alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t haue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e son&euml; herd[&euml;] &thorn;at tydyng,</L>
<L N="6388">And come home fo &thorn;e &eacute;nteryng;</L>
<L>But he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he ne O.</NOTE> my&yogh;t, with no procurement,</L>
<L>Se ones hys fadres testament,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e katel was a-counted</L>
<L N="6392">More &thorn;an &thorn;e testament amounted,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey wuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> nat fulfylle</L>
<L>&thorn;e testement of &thorn;e ded&euml;s wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6395">&THORN;e sone besoght hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey wylde</L>
<L>&THORN;e testement of hys fadyr were fulfylede:<NOTE PLACE="foot">fulfylde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an bygan<NOTE PLACE="foot">bygunne O.</NOTE> &thorn;ey hym for to &thorn;rete,<MILESTONE N="43a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And spak&euml; to hym wurdys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrdes O.</NOTE> grete;</L>
<L>For tene, &thorn;ey seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">And seyd for tene O.</NOTE> &thorn;ey wulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wlde O.</NOTE> nat do</L>
<L N="6400">For hym &thorn;at &thorn;ey were ordeyned to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e chylde besoght[&euml;] God almy&yogh;t</L>
<L>To take veniaunce on here vnryght.</L>
<L>hyt was nat a mone&thorn; aftyrward,</L>
<L N="6404">&thorn;e ton<NOTE PLACE="foot">toon O.</NOTE> fyl yn a chaunce ful hard:
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>At hys foreyne, y ne wot what,</L>
<L>Strangled hym &thorn;eron<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;eron O, hym H.</NOTE> as he sat;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er executoure &thorn;at had &thorn;e &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="6408">Yn pouert he mad&euml; hys endyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue &yogh;e herde, myschaunce and nede</L>
<L>Cum&thorn; of fals executours dede;</L>
<L>Whedyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whe&thorn;er.</NOTE> hyt be stylle, or loude on hy,</L>
<L N="6412">Fals executours endyn wykkedly;</L>
<L>lyfe or soule, &thorn;e toon ys shent,</L>
<L>Or, bo&thorn;e shul yn fyre be brent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As moch&euml; ioy&euml; and onours</L>
<L N="6416">Shal come to gode executours;</L>
<L>God graunte&thorn; hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym fyrst for O.</NOTE> for hys gode wyl,</L>
<L>hele and wel&thorn;e with-outyn yl;</L>
<L>And for hys dede &thorn;at he dou&thorn; ryght,</L>
<L N="6420">He shal haue mercy a&yogh;ens hys plyght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule praye&thorn; also, with wyl fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys gode dede hym &yogh;ould&euml; be</L>
<L>Yn blys of heuene, wy&thorn;outyn ende,</L>
<L>Whan he out of &thorn;ys wurlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrld O.</NOTE> shal wende;</L>
<L N="6425">And loue of man, he shal fynde,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e syght of alle mankynde:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys god&euml;nesse shal ay be newe</L>
<L N="6428">To &thorn;e executur &thorn;at ys trewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now we &thorn;e executore haue mysseyd,</L>
<L>And of hys wrong he ha&thorn; vpbreyd,</L>
<L>he a&yogh;enssey&thorn; alle &thorn;at tresun,</L>
<L N="6432">And sette&thorn; &thorn;us hys resun,</L>
<L>And praye&thorn; vs &thorn;e so&thorn;e to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e dede ys more to blame &thorn;an he,</L>
<L>And argue&thorn; vp-on &thorn;ys skylle,<MILESTONE N="43a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6436">And byt &thorn;e dede answere &thorn;artylle:</L>
<L>"&yogh;yf &thorn;ou be ryche yn &yogh;ong&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yng&thorn;e O.</NOTE> or elde,</L>
<L>And hast ynowe of wel&thorn;e to welde,</L>
<L>And knowest &thorn;y self yn wyl and dedes,</L>
<L N="6440">&THORN;y wo, &thorn;y wel&euml;, how &thorn;ou ledes,
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;y lyfe, what hyt ys wur&thorn;y,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wr&thorn;y O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost hyt bettyr &thorn;an wote y;</L>
<L>Wyk and god&euml;, &thorn;ou hyt wyst,</L>
<L N="6444">And &thorn;e to sau&euml;, &thorn;ou ne lyst,</L>
<L>And haddest &thorn;y self alle &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e O.</NOTE> powere;</L>
<L>why were &thorn;ou nat &thorn;yn owne spensere?</L>
<L>how shuld y &thorn;an do now for &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="6448">Syn &thorn;y self were nat so fre?</L>
<L>how shulde y loue &thorn;y soul&euml; nowe,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou louedyst nat &thorn;y soul&euml; prowe?</L>
<L>how shulde y &thorn;enke, &thorn;y soule to<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;enke &thorn;e to O.</NOTE> saue,</L>
<L N="6452">Whan &thorn;ou &thorn;oghtyst noun to haue?</L>
<L>how shulde y bryng&euml; &thorn;e to blys,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou &thorn;y self ne wuldest &thorn;e wysse?</L>
<L>how shulde y bring&euml; &thorn;e of pyne,</L>
<L>when<NOTE PLACE="foot">? when, MS. why.</NOTE> &thorn;ou ne wuldest, whyl alle was &thorn;yne?</L>
<L N="6457">how shulde y, frend-man, be &thorn;y frende,</L>
<L>when &thorn;y-self fo-man wald &thorn;y hende?</L>
<L>how shulde y late &thorn;y gode me fro,</L>
<L N="6460">when &thorn;ou lete noun fro &thorn;y-self go?</L>
<L>who shulde &thorn;e oute of sorowe vnbynde,</L>
<L>When to &thorn;y self &thorn;ou were vnkynde,</L>
<L>and wystyst weyl &thorn;ou shuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">shuldest O.</NOTE> deye,</L>
<L N="6464">and nedely &thorn;e behoued passe &thorn;at weye?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ogh y, for &thorn;e, &yogh;af aywhore,<NOTE PLACE="inter">euermore<NOTE PLACE="foot">euermore, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>who shulde kunne me &thorn;ank &thorn;erfore?</L>
<L>what shuld God do &thorn;&egrave; mede?</L>
<L N="6468">&THORN;ou dedyst hyt nat; hyt ys oure dede?</L>
<L>a peny &yogh;yue of &thorn;e, yn &thorn;y lyue,</L>
<L>hadde be bettyr &thorn;an oure fyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gederdyst, and &yogh;aue &thorn;yn executours;</L>
<L N="6472">&THORN;at before was &thorn;yn, now ys hyt ours.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gaderdyst faste, and puttest yn holde;<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So shul we, be &thorn;ou bolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou boghtyst fast, and madyst a ryche eyre,</L>
<L N="6476">&THORN;y sone ys now yn &thorn;e sam&euml; speyre;</L>
<L>he shal nat &thorn;enk &thorn;at he shal deye,
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="209"></L>
<L>"Ne noght of &thorn;e, but alle to beye.</L>
<L>what &thorn;oghtest &thorn;ou on &thorn;y fadyr before,</L>
<L>lesse shal he &thorn;enke on &thorn;e, &thorn;at of &thorn;e ys bore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">line too long.? cut out <I>lesse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6481">Of &thorn;y wofare ne ha&thorn; he &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou myghtyst &thorn;y self, and wuldest noght;</L>
<L>and &thorn;ogh now we &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">we now &yogh;yue O.</NOTE> alle &thorn;y gode</L>
<L N="6484">vntyl por&euml; mann&euml;s fode,</L>
<L>Or dede anou&thorn;er (for &thorn;y sake,)</L>
<L>Cherche to sette, or auter make,</L>
<L>y trowe &thorn;y mede shal be but smal,</L>
<L N="6488">Syn &thorn;ou dedyst no&yogh;t whan &thorn;yn was al.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"loke now &thorn;y-self, and gode skyl why,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art more to blame &thorn;an y.</L>
<L>wharefor ys alle y with &thorn;e stryue,</L>
<L N="6492">&THORN;at &thorn;ou do god&euml; yn &thorn;y lyue;</L>
<L>Make &thorn;y-self &thorn;yn own&euml; weye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yn executor of<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne of O.</NOTE> &thorn;e &thorn;us seye;</L>
<L>For what time &thorn;at &thorn;ou awey gos,</L>
<L N="6496">&THORN;o &thorn;at were &thorn;y frendys are &thorn;an &thorn;y fos,</L>
<L>And comunly &thorn;yn own&euml; wyfe,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t, mayst &thorn;ou se here ful ryfe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Also &thorn;y chyldryn are vnkynde,</L>
<L N="6500">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast be aboute ful mynde;</L>
<L>Of bo&thorn;e mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;y merour se,</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou kanst, or wyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylt O.</NOTE> p&aacute;rseue &thorn;e;</L>
<L>And alle cum&thorn; hyt of coueytyse</L>
<L N="6504">&THORN;at men done vpp-on &thorn;ys wyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;rfore &thorn;enk on &thorn;e endyng,</L>
<L>And spend&euml; weyl &thorn;yn own&euml; &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou fal nat yn auaryce:</L>
<L N="6508">Of vnkyndhede hyt cum&thorn;, &thorn;at vyce."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God, for hys holy my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>late us neuer, with wnry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Coueyte oght a&yogh;ens hys wyl,<MILESTONE N="43b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6512">No with auaryce to holde for yl,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at hyt be, hym to queme,</L>
<L>And body and soule yn clenesse &yogh;eme.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin"><PB REF="00000218.tif" N="210">
<HEAD>[On Gluttony.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The syxt&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sext O.</NOTE> synne ys glotonye;</L>
<L N="6516">&thorn;at ys a shameful vyleynye</L>
<L>&thorn;at men doun of mete and drynk,</L>
<L>For ouermoche ys abominable &amp; stynk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>y wyl now shew&euml; of hys spyces,<NOTE PLACE="foot">speces O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6520">&THORN;at noun fall&euml; on hys grecys:</L>
<L>Ful many on stumble vp and down</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e greces of syre glotown.</L>
<L>y shal &yogh;ow telle &thorn;e sam&euml; wyse</L>
<L N="6524">Ry&yogh;t as 'manuel pecches' seyse:</L>
<L>he comaunde&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">comounde&thorn; O.</NOTE> at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L>'Be mesur&aacute;ble yn alle &thorn;yng.'
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>Of all&euml; wysdom &thorn;at shal dure,</L>
<L N="6528">&THORN;e most wysdom, &thorn;an ys 'mesure';</L>
<L>Mesure and resun, to-gedyr &thorn;ey wone,</L>
<L>And alle manere of vertues &thorn;ey kone.</L>
<L>with whom &thorn;ey won&euml;, he ys wys,</L>
<L N="6532">And ys ryche, and holdyn yn prys.</L>
<L>hyt ys a gode sygne &thorn;at man ys stable,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn resun ys mesur&aacute;ble.</L>
<L>Many a vertu, mesure has,</L>
<L N="6536">&THORN;at touched ys nat yn &thorn;ys pas.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e mesure of etyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t ys bo&thorn;e to olde and &yogh;yng;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore wyl y telle &yogh;ow alle</L>
<L N="6540">Yn what &thorn;yng&euml;s &thorn;at &yogh;e falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be nat to &thorn;y self so large,</L>
<L>Ouer mesure &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. yn.</NOTE> herte to charge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne kast for vylaynye</L>
<L N="6544">Ne for &thorn;e foule lust of glotonye.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk here-on whan &thorn;ou hyt bygynnys,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er-yn are &thorn;re wykked synnes:</L>
<L>Glotonye, and &thorn;efte of &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And cursed yn chyrche, ys mede endyng.
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="212"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6549">And y warne &thorn;e of &thorn;ys kas,<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To comone with any &thorn;at cursyng has,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wystyst opunly</L>
<L N="6552">were cursed with holy cherches cry.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> dedyst hyt by &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L>wy&thorn;-oute destresse or lordys wylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holy cherche ys wroth wy&thorn; &thorn;e astyt,</L>
<L N="6556">And halt hyt pryde and grete dyspyt,</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; &thorn;ou art vnbuxum,</L>
<L>And manteynest an euyl custum.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a cursed man hadde cumpany</L>
<L N="6560">with one or ou&thorn;er, logh or hy,</L>
<L>Or yn mete or yn drynke</L>
<L>At &thorn;e alehous, or ou&thorn;er gaderyng,</L>
<L>He ne wulde recche how long he lay</L>
<L N="6564">yn hys cursyng, ny&yogh;t or day.</L>
<L>For holy cherch&euml; curse&thorn; none</L>
<L>But yn vnbuxumnesse &thorn;at ha&thorn; mysgone;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyl nat stonde at hys Iustyse,</L>
<L N="6568">he defendy&thorn; hym &thorn;e comune acyse,</L>
<L>For to make hym be ashamed</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shulde be so defamed,</L>
<L>And so shulde he wyte he may nat be</L>
<L N="6572">But at holy cherche degre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherches gre.</NOTE></L>
<L>For swych &thorn;yng, men ofte hem meken,</L>
<L>And mercy at holy cherch&euml; sekyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfor hyt ys a grete folye,</L>
<L N="6576">with cursed man haue cumpanye.</L>
<L>Seynt Poule sey&thorn;, &thorn;at moch&euml; wote,</L>
<L>"who-so handly&thorn; pycche wellyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">pycch wellynge.</NOTE> hote,</L>
<L>He shal haue fyl&thorn;e &thorn;erof sumdeyl</L>
<L N="6580">&THORN;ogh he kepe hym neuer so weyl."</L>
<L>And Dauyd sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e sauter,</L>
<L>For felaushepe, on swych maner,</L>
<L>"with holy man, holy shalt &thorn;ou be;
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="213"></L>
<L N="6584">with wykked man, &thorn;ou turnest as he."</L>
<L>On &thorn;ese wurdys y rede &yogh;e &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L>And kep&euml; &yogh;ow fro cursed blynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt, for no mannes prew,<MILESTONE N="44a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6588">Ete, no drynk&euml; wy&thorn; a Iew.</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he wyl crystendom take,</L>
<L>hys felaushepe shalt &thorn;ou forsake.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ys a grete skyl why,</L>
<L N="6592">For &thorn;e Iew ys Ihesus enmye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iew loue&thorn;, on no manere,</L>
<L>Iesu, ne hys modyr dere.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou loue hem ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6596">Forsak&euml; Iew at alle &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hope &thorn;at he wul weyue<NOTE PLACE="inter">forsake</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys lawe, and crystendom receyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Against making Men drunk.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ys custum ys also<NOTE PLACE="foot">also ys.</NOTE> perylous,</L>
<L N="6600">To lede a man to &thorn;e alehous</L>
<L>To do hym drynke out of resun,</L>
<L>Or make hym drunke,&mdash;&thorn;at ys tresun,&mdash;</L>
<L>Or to &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> hous, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hym lede,</L>
<L N="6604">On hym drynk&euml; for to bede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art gylty of hys synne</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou to drunkenes wldest hym wynne.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou ioy&euml; &thorn;erof has,</L>
<L N="6608">&THORN;e more &thorn;ou fallyst yn trespas;</L>
<L>Hyt ys a tokene of felunnye</L>
<L>To weyt&euml; hym with swych gylrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also &yogh;yf &thorn;ou any day shuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulle.</NOTE> fast,</L>
<L N="6612">And &thorn;ou ouertymely &thorn;y met&euml; aske,</L>
<L>Glotony ha&thorn; swych longyng wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou to tyme abydest noght.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="214"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er spyce ys yn glotonye,</L>
<L N="6616">To ete ouer delycyusly,</L>
<L>For to be serued with many messe:<NOTE PLACE="foot">mese.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at haunte &thorn;ese lordyng&euml;s on dese.<NOTE PLACE="inter">on table</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wuld &thorn;ey of euery a messe<NOTE PLACE="foot">mese.</NOTE> &yogh;yue</L>
<L N="6620">To helpe &thorn;e pore wy&thorn; for to lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e boldlyere &thorn;ey my&yogh;t hem self fede</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey dedyn &thorn;at alm&euml;s dede.</L>
<L>But of alm&euml;s &thorn;enk &thorn;ey no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="6624">For lust and lykyng ys more yn &thorn;oght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at louest so many messe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mes.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wuldest &thorn;ou &thorn;enke on syre Dyues,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e por&euml; man<NOTE PLACE="foot">man also.</NOTE> La&yogh;are</L>
<L N="6628">&THORN;at syre Dyues late mysfare, &mdash;</L>
<L>For he asked hym sum gode,</L>
<L>Of hys mete, for hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e.</NOTE> lyu&euml;s fode, &mdash;</L>
<L>y trowe &thorn;ou shuldest nat forgete</L>
<L N="6632">&THORN;e pore man at &thorn;y mete,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou vndyrstode, y wene,</L>
<L>what &thorn;e tal&euml; wulde bemene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Dives and Lazarus.]</HEAD>
<L>A ryche man was sum tyme of prys<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6636">&THORN;at wered bo&thorn;e purpure and bys,</L>
<L>And euery day nobly was led,</L>
<L>And with delycyus metys fed;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er was &thorn;o a por&euml; man,</L>
<L N="6640">Lazare, &thorn;at &thorn;e wurd of ran,</L>
<L>He lay at &thorn;e ryche mannys &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Ful of byl&euml;s, yn &thorn;e gate<NOTE PLACE="inter">wey</NOTE>;</L>
<L>He &yogh;erned moche to ete hys fylle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e crummes &thorn;at &thorn;e ryche man ded spyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spylle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6645">But no man &yogh;aue hym on to byte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at asked he so lyte:</L>
<L>But &thorn;e rych&euml; mann&euml;s houndes
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="215"></L>
<L N="6648">Come and lykked La&yogh;ares woundes.</L>
<L>Sone aftyrward deyd&euml; La&yogh;are</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e mannes &yogh;at&euml; &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Godd&euml;s aungeles &thorn;e soul&euml; nam,</L>
<L>And bare hyt yn-to &thorn;e bosum of Abraham.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6653">Abrahams bosum ys a dwellyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy men haue yn restyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to Ihesu, Goddys sone, cam,</L>
<L N="6656">&THORN;at flesshe and blode yn Mary nam.</L>
<L>Abrahams bosum ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> a stede, men telle,</L>
<L>Betwyx&euml; paradys and helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fylle.</NOTE> auenture, as y er seyde,</L>
<L N="6660">&THORN;ys rych&euml; man sone aftyr deyde.</L>
<L>Hys soule was bore to Lucyfere,</L>
<L>with-outyn ende to dwell&euml; &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>And, as he was &thorn;ere yn pyne,<MILESTONE N="44b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6664">He loked vpwarde with hys yne,</L>
<L>And sagh La&yogh;are, &thorn;e por&euml; man,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e bosum of Abraham;</L>
<L>And as he my&yogh;t, he &yogh;aue a cry,</L>
<L N="6668">And seyd, "Abraham, mercy, mercy!</L>
<L>Late La&yogh;are hys o fynger wete,</L>
<L>And, droppe on my tunge for hete;</L>
<L>For y am yn endles peyne,</L>
<L N="6672">yn fyre and yn leye certeyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Abraham spak<NOTE PLACE="foot">spak O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> as yn vpbreyde,</L>
<L>"Sone! menest &thorn;ou nat what y er<NOTE PLACE="foot">ere.</NOTE> seyd?</L>
<L N="6675">&THORN;ou receyuedyst &thorn;e wurldys blys,</L>
<L>And La&yogh;are, pouert and peyne ywys.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ete and drunke, and were ful bly&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And La&yogh;are hungred, &amp; ful wo sy&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And now shal he, for hys deserte,</L>
<L N="6680">Haue wel&thorn;e y-nogh for hys pouert;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou, for wel&thorn;e, to pyne shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne shalt.</NOTE> go,
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>And for &thorn;y ryches &thorn;ou shalt haue wo.</L>
<L>Now ys La&yogh;are euer yn solace,</L>
<L N="6684">And &thorn;ou yn sorow with-out&euml; grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;e endles ende may no man telle</L>
<L>Betwyxe vs here, &amp; &yogh;ow yn helle;</L>
<L>Betwyxe oure ioye, and &yogh;our&euml; peyne,</L>
<L N="6688">ys endles tyme, and vncerteyne.</L>
<L>Swych sykernes ys betwyx<NOTE PLACE="foot">sekernes ys betwene.</NOTE> &yogh;ow two,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noun of vs to &yogh;ow may go.</L>
<L>None of vs to &yogh;ow may come,</L>
<L N="6692">But echone haue hys own&euml; dome."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an preyde &thorn;e ryche man, Abraham,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wlde sende Lazare, or sum o&thorn;er wham,</L>
<L>To hys bre&thorn;ryn all&euml; fyue,</L>
<L N="6696">&THORN;at &thorn;ey loke hem so, yn here lyue,</L>
<L>Fro auaryce and fro glotonye</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue to por&euml; men ble&thorn;lye,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at &thorn;ey neuer hedyr be sent,</L>
<L N="6700">with me, yn &thorn;ys hete, to be brent."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Abraham ne graunted hym noght<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e ryche man hym besoght,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ey haue," he seyd, "alle &thorn;e prophete dedys,</L>
<L N="6704">And holy wryt, &thorn;at men on redys,</L>
<L>To teche hem bo&thorn;&euml; ry&yogh;t and skyle,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;eraftyr, &yogh;yf &thorn;ey wyle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an spake &thorn;e rych&euml; man,</L>
<L>"Nay, fadyr Abraham, nay, &thorn;ey ne kan;</L>
<L N="6709">But wuldest &thorn;ou do aftyr my rede,</L>
<L>To reyse a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; be dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at my&yogh;t hem &thorn;e peyn&euml;s telle</L>
<L N="6712">&THORN;at &thorn;ey shul suffre and yn dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;an shulde &thorn;ey do ry&yogh;t penaunce</L>
<L>For to askap&euml; &thorn;ys myschaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Abraham wulde nat graunte</L>
<L N="6716">&THORN;e ryche man &thorn;at cunnaunt,</L>
<L>A ded&euml; man vp for to reyse,</L>
<L>"Syn Moyses sawes &thorn;ey wyl nat preyse,
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>How wulde &thorn;ey at a dede man lere,</L>
<L N="6720">whan holy wryt &thorn;ey wyl nat here?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale telly&thorn; oure lorde Ihesu</L>
<L>To rych&euml; men for her&euml; prew,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pru.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey ne be no nythyng</L>
<L N="6724">Of here mete, ne of here &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>To por&euml; men, nam&euml;ly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest hem, &yogh;yue hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> ble&thorn;ly,</L>
<L>with no betyng, ne with noun awe;</L>
<L N="6728">Alm&euml;s ys no&yogh;t wy&thorn; any myssawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>why telly&thorn; he &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> wykkednes of &thorn;ys man alle,&mdash;</L>
<L>And he ne robbed, ne he ne stalle,&mdash;</L>
<L>But for he bare hym ouer hye,</L>
<L N="6732">And ledde hys lyfe yn glotonye,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pore dyd euyl yn dede,</L>
<L>No halp hym no&yogh;t yn hys nede:</L>
<L>Ne La&yogh;are asked nat greuuslyke,</L>
<L N="6736">But a fewe crumm&euml;s for to pyke;</L>
<L>And for he &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;af.</NOTE> hym noun on to byte,</L>
<L>Hym was werned as lyte:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syll</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L>As lytyl as he hym wernede,<MILESTONE N="45a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6740">As lytyl &thorn;yng he &yogh;ernede;</L>
<L>he preyd&euml; La&yogh;are hym to sende</L>
<L>A drop&euml; of hys fynger ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke how euene Iugement,</L>
<L N="6744">&THORN;e tone a&yogh;ens &thorn;e to&thorn;er, was sent:</L>
<L>hyt ys but a lytyl synne,</L>
<L>Of a drope and of a crumme;</L>
<L>&thorn;an wyl hyt be ful harde a-counte</L>
<L N="6748">Of &thorn;yng &thorn;at wylle to moche a-mounte.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor, &yogh;e lordyngys, be&thorn; ful ware,</L>
<L>&THORN;enke&thorn; on Dyues and on La&yogh;are,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e por&euml; na&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> forgete</L>
<L N="6752">whan &yogh;e sytt&euml; at &yogh;oure mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;at fedyst &thorn;e so rychely,</L>
<L>Ouer mesure yn glotonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt stynk and rote,
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="218"></L>
<L N="6756">And wurm&euml;s shul fyl &thorn;y &thorn;rote,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fouler shal &thorn;y body stynke,</L>
<L>For thy ryche met&euml;, and &thorn;y drynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euery man &yogh;yue tente to &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="6760">And se how vyle hys body ys.</L>
<L>Twey dayys or &thorn;re mow hyt loke<NOTE PLACE="inter">kepe</NOTE></L>
<L>Mete, ar man hyt ete or toke;</L>
<L>But as sone as hyt ys yn &thorn;e &yogh;oten,</L>
<L N="6764">Yn half a day &thorn;an ys hyt roten;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t vyle, and al&thorn;er meste,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hyt ys of any ou&thorn;er beste.</L>
<L>Se weyl &thorn;ys! &thorn;an mayst &thorn;ou fynde,</L>
<L N="6768">how vyle &thorn;an ys &thorn;yn own&euml; kynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys rych&euml; man that y of telle,</L>
<L>Wente nat oonly &thorn;arfor to helle,</L>
<L>But, for &thorn;at he wuld&euml; noght</L>
<L N="6772">&YOGH;yue to La&yogh;are &thorn;at he besoght,</L>
<L>Ne no&yogh;t only for glotonye,</L>
<L>Ne auaryce, ne for beryng hye,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t for-&thorn;y, &thorn;e leste of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="6776">My&yogh;t brynge a man to Iuwys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>why was God moste wy&thorn; hym wroth?<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he dyd &thorn;e pore man loth,<NOTE PLACE="inter">harme</NOTE></L>
<L>And for he dyd hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys O, he H.</NOTE> houndes oute late</L>
<L N="6780">To byte &thorn;e La&yogh;are at &thorn;e &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>And, for he dyde hym &thorn;at dyspyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">despyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>God wrathede hym astyte,</L>
<L>And deyne&thorn; nat to nemne hys name,</L>
<L N="6784">For he dede &thorn;e pore man shame,</L>
<L>But calle&thorn; hym yn &thorn;e gospel, ryche,</L>
<L>As vnkynd&euml; and vnbryche.</L>
<L>For ful comunly shalt &thorn;ou fynde</L>
<L N="6788">Oft&euml; rych&euml; men vnkynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lorde! how shul &thorn;ese robbers fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pore pepyl pelyn ful bare,&mdash;</L>
<L>Erl&euml;s, kny&yogh;t&euml;s, and barouns,</L>
<L N="6792">And ou&thorn;er lordyng&euml;s of tounnes;</L>
<L>Iustyses, shryues,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shereues.</NOTE> and baylyuys,
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e law&euml;s alle to-ryues,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pore men alle to-pyle;</L>
<L>To ryche men do &thorn;ey but as &thorn;ey wylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyle.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6797">&THORN;ys ryche man, as &thorn;e gospel seys,</L>
<L>was but to .o. man vncurteys,</L>
<L>And hadde so moch&euml; pyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne.</NOTE> &thorn;arfore;</L>
<L N="6800">On hem wyl fall&euml; moch&euml; more</L>
<L>&THORN;at many pore men pyle and bete,</L>
<L>For God no synne wyl &thorn;ey nat lete.</L>
<L>Swych ryche men<NOTE PLACE="foot">men H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> &thorn;at are a&yogh;ens Goddys<NOTE PLACE="foot">goddes.</NOTE> pes,</L>
<L N="6804">&THORN;enke&thorn; on La&yogh;are and on Dyues;</L>
<L>And be&thorn; nat pynede wy&thorn; Satanas</L>
<L>For por&euml; men, as Dyues was,</L>
<L>And ys, and euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euermor.</NOTE> shal be;</L>
<L N="6808">&YOGH;yt robbed he neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">no&thorn;er.</NOTE> golde ne fee.</L>
<L>By &thorn;ys skylle, &thorn;an mow &yogh;e se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e are wers &thorn;an was he.</L>
<L>He dyde but lete an hounde hym to;</L>
<L N="6812">&YOGH;e rych&euml; men, weyl wers &yogh;e do!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wyl noun hound&euml;s to hem lete,</L>
<L>But, &yogh;e self, hem sle and bete.</L>
<L>He ne dyd but werned hym of hys mete;<MILESTONE N="45b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6816">And &yogh;e, robbe al &thorn;at &yogh;e mow gete;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e are as Dyues, &thorn;at wyl naght &yogh;yue;</L>
<L>And wers, for &yogh;e robbe &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde by lyue.</L>
<L>Of moch&euml; peyne &yogh;e mow &yogh;ow drede,</L>
<L N="6820">For &yogh;e do weyl wers &thorn;an Dyues dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e rych&euml; men, God wyl &yogh;ow charge</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e &yogh;yue &yogh;oure alm&euml;s large;</L>
<L>Nat ouer powere, neuer a deyl,</L>
<L N="6824">But &yogh;yue &thorn;at, &thorn;at &yogh;e mow<NOTE PLACE="foot">may.</NOTE> ful weyl;</L>
<L>And nat allonely larg&euml;ly,</L>
<L>But with loue, &thorn;at ys, curtesy;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yue&thorn; curteysly, and nat to bete,</L>
<L N="6828">&YOGH;ow were bettyr &yogh;oure alm&euml;s lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a pore man take ons or twyys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ones or twys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mysdo hym nat, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou be wys,</L>
<L>Ne seye hym noun o&thorn;er vyleynye;</L>
<L N="6832">&THORN;an doust &thorn;ou larges and curteysye.</L>
<L>More &thorn;ank &thorn;ou getest for swych &yogh;yuyng</L>
<L>&THORN;an seuene so moche with chydyng.</L>
<L>Herefore Seynt Ihon &thorn;e aumenere seys,</L>
<L N="6836">And techy&thorn; men to be curteys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of St. John the Almoner, and his great Liberality and Courtesy.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Hyt sey&thorn; Seynt Ihon &thorn;e aumenere</L>
<L>Pore men called hym Goddys spensere;</L>
<L>He was bysshope and patryarke</L>
<L N="6840">Of Constantyn&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">constantyne O, constatyne H.</NOTE> noble starke.</L>
<L>Of hym &yogh;ede ful fyr &thorn;e name,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful fere &yogh;ede &thorn;e fame.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of large alm&euml;s men &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;afe.</NOTE> hym name.</L>
<L>A pylgryme herde of hym &thorn;us seye,</L>
<L N="6844">And to hys palys he toke &thorn;e weye;</L>
<L>whan he cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">com.</NOTE> &thorn;er, he sagh seynt Ih&omacr;n<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iohone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dele &thorn;e pore folk ful gode wone;</L>
<L>He seyd he wulde hym ouercharge,</L>
<L>To wete whe&thorn;er seynt Ihon were large.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="6849">He com, and asked &thorn;e charyte,</L>
<L>And seynt Ihon, &thorn;at was so fie,</L>
<L N="6851">He commaundede hys seriaunte</L>
<L>For to &yogh;yue hym syxe besaunte.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys pylgrym &yogh;ede and chaunged hys wede,<MILESTONE N="46a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>More to aske, &yogh;yf he my&yogh;t spede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Fr. 221/5624]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>And seyd he hadde goun many a gate,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'wey.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="6856">And to &thorn;e cyte he was com late,</L>
<L>And of spensys had<NOTE PLACE="foot">spenses hadde.</NOTE> he non,</L>
<L>So hadde he yn pylgrymage gon.</L>
<L>Seynt Ih&omacr;n commaundede hys aumenere</L>
<L N="6860">To &yogh;yue hym ou&thorn;er syxe, for he had mystere.<NOTE PLACE="inter">nede</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e aumener parceyued weyl &thorn;at tyme</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt was &thorn;e same pylgryme</L>
<L>&THORN;at toke byfore &thorn;e charyte,</L>
<L N="6864">And seyd, "syre, &thorn;ys ys he."</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, o&thorn;er wroth or glad,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;afe.</NOTE> hym, &thorn;at seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">seynt.</NOTE> Ih&omacr;n bad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys pylgrym eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">eft H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> besyd&euml; nam,<NOTE PLACE="inter">&yogh;ede</NOTE></L>
<L N="6868">And eft&euml; &thorn;e &thorn;ryd tym&euml; cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">he cam.</NOTE></L>
<L>yn a-no&thorn;er wede &thorn;an he was ore,</L>
<L>And asked at seynt Ih&omacr;n &yogh;yt more.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aumenere was wroth &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="6872">&THORN;at he asked so oute of skore,</L>
<L>Syn hym was &yogh;yue so larg&euml;ly,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt he asked, and was gredy.</L>
<L>But Seynt Ih&omacr;n, he was fre,</L>
<L N="6876">And yn ful gret&euml; charyte</L>
<L>He commaunded to hym a-none</L>
<L>To &yogh;yue hym twelue besauntes echone:</L>
<L>"Per&aacute;uenture, God wyl me proue</L>
<L N="6880">what y wyl do for hys loue,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er hyt ys God hym selue;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yue.</NOTE> hym besauntes twelue;</L>
<L>Or he proue&thorn; me a-no&thorn;er wey,</L>
<L N="6884">&YOGH;yf y wyl any of hys myssey;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &yogh;yue&thorn; with god&euml; wyl</L>
<L>And curteysye, with-outyn yl."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale y told&euml; &yogh;ow &thorn;ys tyde,</L>
<L N="6888">&THORN;at &yogh;e with no pore men<NOTE PLACE="foot">man.</NOTE> chyde;
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="222"></L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou chydyng with hym makes,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;yn almes of &thorn;e he takes,</L>
<L>He bye&thorn; hyt dere with hys myssawe,<MILESTONE N="46a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And shame &thorn;erwith, and drede, and awe.</L>
<L N="6893">&YOGH;yf for &thorn;at &yogh;yft &thorn;ou wylt haue mede,</L>
<L>Mysdo hym nat, yn wurde ne dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also hyt ys grete curteysye</L>
<L N="6896">To &yogh;yue &yogh;oure alm&euml;s hastylye;</L>
<L>Nat for to mak&euml; long delay,</L>
<L>To late a wrecch&euml; stonde al day</L>
<L>Cryyng at &thorn;y &yogh;ate yn colde;</L>
<L N="6900">He bye&thorn; &thorn;yn almes on manyfolde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou &yogh;yue hym lytyl or noght,</L>
<L>Algate hyt ys dere y-boghte.</L>
<L>And, &thorn;arfore hyt were weyl doun</L>
<L N="6904">To &yogh;yue &thorn;yn alm&euml;s gladly and soun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And y warne &yogh;ow alle of o &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>For&thorn;enke&thorn; nat of &yogh;oure almes-&yogh;yuyng.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for&thorn;enkest, &thorn;ou getyst maugre,</L>
<L N="6908">&THORN;y &yogh;yft ys nat yn charyte;</L>
<L>Ryght so dyd &thorn;e bysshope Troyle,</L>
<L>For hys almes he made grete doyle,<NOTE PLACE="inter">sorowe</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at a sykenes hym ouer haf<NOTE PLACE="foot">hafe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6912">For larg&euml; almes &thorn;at he &yogh;af.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;afe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Ihoun &thorn;e aumenere telle&thorn; how,</L>
<L>And as he sey&thorn;, y shal telle &yogh;ow;</L>
<L>A gode ensample, as we rede,</L>
<L N="6916">&THORN;at none for&thorn;ynke hys alm&euml;s dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Bishop Troylus and his Thirty Pounds.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ys yche seynt Ih&omacr;n &thorn;e aumenere</L>
<L>was a patryark of grete powere;</L>
<L>Vndyr hym was bysshope Troylus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for to haue tresour was coueytous.
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="223"></L>
<L N="6921">And on a day, as fyl to be</L>
<L>&THORN;at seynt Ih&omacr;n &yogh;af hys charyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshope Troyl&euml;, for cumforte,</L>
<L N="6924">with hym went&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">to O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> dysporte,</L>
<L>To se &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;yrdyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yder.</NOTE> come</L>
<L>Of many cuntres &thorn;at oute were nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ych&euml; tyme &thorn;at chaunce gan falle,</L>
<L>Seynt Ih&omacr;n hadde nat to &yogh;yue hem alle;</L>
<L N="6929">But a man, &thorn;at was &thorn;ere,<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Rouned yn seynt Ih&omacr;ns<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iones.</NOTE> ere,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at he hadde broght &thorn;at ych&euml; stounde<NOTE PLACE="inter">tyme</NOTE></L>
<L N="6932">To syre Troyl&euml; &thorn;yrty<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;rytty.</NOTE> pounde,</L>
<L>And he my&yogh;t help&euml;, &yogh;yf he wylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys dol&euml; were fulfylde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ihon to Troyle bygan to sermun<NOTE PLACE="inter">to speke</NOTE></L>
<L N="6956">with ensamples of<NOTE PLACE="foot">and.</NOTE> gode resun,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at he hadde pyte of here cryyng;</L>
<L>To se hem wepe, was reuful &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>For God shal &thorn;anke alle at &thorn;e laste day yn dede,</L>
<L N="6940">&THORN;at of &thorn;e pore for hys loue han pyte at nede.</L>
<L>what ys hyt wr&thorn; to preche yn cherche,</L>
<L>whan men yn ded&euml; wyl nat werche?</L>
<L>And now hyt ys so on &thorn;y party,</L>
<L N="6944">Thou hast besauntes of golde redy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayst helpe, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou wylt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ys pore peple be nat spylt."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what for almes, and what for despyte,</L>
<L N="6948">Troyl&euml; commaunded al styte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> &thorn;rytty pounde of golde</L>
<L>were &yogh;yue &thorn;ere seynt Ih&omacr;n wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e pore was hyt so delte and dryue,</L>
<L N="6952">&THORN;at euery besaunt was fur&thorn; &yogh;yue.</L>
<L>whan all&euml; hadd&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ere cam,
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>Seynt Ih&omacr;n and Troyl&euml; homward nam:</L>
<L>Troyle fyl yn a grete syknes</L>
<L N="6956">For sorow<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorowe.</NOTE> of hys large almes;</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorow<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorowe.</NOTE> hadde hym so ouercome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e feuer hadde hym nome.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'take.'</NOTE></L>
<L>He wende weyl &thorn;at he hadde be lore,</L>
<L N="6960">So lytyl hope yn hym was bore.</L>
<L>Hys god&euml; hop&euml; was ful badde,</L>
<L>For hym &thorn;oghte lore, &thorn;at pore men hadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ihon wulde nat Troyle forgete,</L>
<L N="6964">He sente aftyr hym to &thorn;e mete;</L>
<L>But he excused hym, and seyd nay,</L>
<L>And seyd &thorn;at he yn &thorn;e feuer lay,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e de&thorn;e he hoped weyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wele.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="46b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="6968">&THORN;arefore ne my&yogh;t he come &thorn;at sele.<NOTE PLACE="inter">&thorn;at tyme</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan Seynt Ih&omacr;n herde &thorn;at seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Troyle supposed<NOTE PLACE="foot">soposede.</NOTE> for to deye,</L>
<L>Asswy&thorn;&euml; to hym he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>And cunseyled hym to haue no drede;</L>
<L N="6973">"Drede &thorn;e noght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat.</NOTE> my god&euml; sone,</L>
<L>Godd&euml;s manere we owe to kone;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;o &thorn;at he loue&thorn; dere,</L>
<L N="6976">he chaste&thorn; hem on many manere;</L>
<L>And as he sende&thorn; to &thorn;&egrave;, sykenes,</L>
<L>He wyl sende hele whan hys wyl es."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ih&omacr;n wyst wele hys herte,</L>
<L N="6980">Hys syk&euml;nes, and alle hys querte;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he seyd&euml; on &thorn;ys wyse&mdash;</L>
<L>For he knew hys coueytyse,&mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;y golde &thorn;at was to me so redy,</L>
<L>To me &thorn;ou lentyst hyt, graunte mercy;</L>
<L N="6985">For y was yn wyl, for &thorn;e feste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euery hadde a peny, who so hadde leste.
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>But y my&yogh;t nat so of myne,</L>
<L N="6988">But y hadde borowed at &thorn;e of &thorn;yne;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;rytty pounde, God ha&thorn; me sente,</L>
<L>And here &thorn;ey are now, &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn.</NOTE> presente;</L>
<L>And asswy&thorn;e &thorn;ey shul be payd,</L>
<L N="6992">No lenger shul &thorn;ey be delayd."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ih&omacr;n called hys chaumberleyn,</L>
<L>And tolde hem to Troyle, be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> summe certeyn.</L>
<L>Anoun cumforted was Troyle so weyl</L>
<L N="6996">&THORN;at hys sykenes he forgate eche deyl,</L>
<L>And so smartly, yn tyme so lyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey all&euml; my&yogh;t wele wyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e feuer &thorn;at hym so shoke</L>
<L N="7000">was for &thorn;e monye<NOTE PLACE="foot">mone.</NOTE> &thorn;at he toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He dyde on hys clo&thorn;ys astyte,</L>
<L>And to Seynt Ihon he wrote a skryte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys skryt<NOTE PLACE="foot">scryte.</NOTE> conteyne&thorn;, as hyt sey&thorn; &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="7004">&THORN;ese sam&euml; wurd&euml;s, lesse ne more:</L>
<L>"God &thorn;e &yogh;elde, my lorde Syre Ih&omacr;n,</L>
<L>&THORN;e besauntes &thorn;at were delte echon,</L>
<L N="7007">&THORN;at y lente &thorn;e, &thorn;rytty pounde,</L>
<L>Yn hande y haue hem hole and sounde."</L>
<L>And Troyle dyde &thorn;e skryt<NOTE PLACE="foot">scryte.</NOTE> weyl sele,</L>
<L>And sy&thorn;en ros vp yn gode hele;</L>
<L>And went hym hom&euml; with seynt Ihon;</L>
<L N="7012">Of euyl felte<NOTE PLACE="foot">felt.</NOTE> he no more non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But Ihesu, &thorn;at se&euml;&thorn; al &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Shewed to Troyle &thorn;ys tokenyng</L>
<L>How he hadde lore a rych&euml; holde,</L>
<L N="7016">And for auaryce he hyt solde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Troyle tolde, he sagh &thorn;ys syght</L>
<L>At &thorn;e fyrst slepe of &thorn;e nyght:
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>Hym was shewed a paleys,</L>
<L N="7020">So fayre was neuer noun, hyt seys;</L>
<L>For alle hyt was of betyn golde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at euer stode on molde.</L>
<L>My&yogh;te no man aym&euml; &thorn;e largenesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">largesse.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7024">Ne tung&euml; tell&euml; &thorn;e feyrnesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-yn was so noble atyre,</L>
<L>Shynyng as golde, flammyng as fyre.</L>
<L>Aboute<NOTE PLACE="foot">aboue.</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;at&euml; wrytyn was</L>
<L N="7028">&THORN;at Troyle beheld&euml; a long space,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spas.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ofte he redd&euml; &thorn;at wrytyng,</L>
<L>And hadd&euml; &thorn;eryn grete lykyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys was &thorn;ere wryte,&mdash;as seynt Ih&omacr;n telles,</L>
<L N="7032">And as men of &thorn;ys story spellys,&mdash;</L>
<L>"Reste and hous with-outyn ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bysshope Troyl&euml; shal to wende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;oght Troyl&euml; yn hys bedde,</L>
<L N="7036">As he ofte on &thorn;e lettyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">lettre.</NOTE> redde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an wende Troyl&euml; sykyrly weyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng hadde &yogh;yue hyt hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym hyt.</NOTE> eche deyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore syre Troyl&euml; was ful gladde</L>
<L N="7040">&THORN;at he swyche a paleys hadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnne&thorn;&euml; &thorn;enne hys y&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye.</NOTE> was glent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at one fro God &thorn;ydyr was sent,</L>
<L>And commaunded alle yn rape<NOTE PLACE="inter">haste</NOTE><MILESTONE N="47a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7044">A-wey &thorn;at wrytyng for to skrape.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at spak&euml; of syre Troyle</L>
<L>was skraped<NOTE PLACE="foot">shrapede.</NOTE> a-wey, as who sey oyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone aftyrward, with-yn a lytyl,</L>
<L N="7048">was &thorn;ere wryte ano&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">a nou&thorn;er.</NOTE> tytyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys tytyl &thorn;at was latter wryte,</L>
<L>&THORN;us moche hyt ys for to wyte,</L>
<L>"Rest, and hous, and wonyng,</L>
<L N="7052">Graunte&thorn;, and &yogh;yue&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfth.</NOTE> heuene kyng,</L>
<L>To Ih&omacr;n &thorn;e patryark so fre,
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>with-outyn ende yn ioye to be,</L>
<L>For &thorn;rytty pound&euml; &thorn;at he boghte,</L>
<L N="7056">And to alm&euml;s dede hem broghte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Troyl&euml; waked sone anone,</L>
<L>And tolde hys drem&euml; to seynt Ih&omacr;n,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Johone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euery deyl how he hadde sen,</L>
<L N="7060">And was ordeyned to haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha.</NOTE> ben.</L>
<L>"&THORN;arfore," he seyde, "fro henne forward</L>
<L>Ne shal y neuer be to pore man hard;</L>
<L>So feyre ys dy&yogh;te to hem to lyue,</L>
<L N="7064">&THORN;at blely wyl to pore men &yogh;yue."</L>
<L>But algate Troyle &thorn;at tyme had tynte</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst paleys &thorn;at God hadde hym mynte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e lordynges &thorn;at haue y-now,</L>
<L N="7068">&THORN;ys tal&euml; haue y tolde for &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne repente &yogh;ow of larg&eacute;s</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e &yogh;yue to &yogh;oure alm&eacute;s;</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke&thorn; on &thorn;e bysshope Troyle</L>
<L N="7072">&THORN;at for large alm&euml;s made grete doyle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne lese nat &thorn;at paleys</L>
<L>&THORN;at God ordeyne&thorn; to alle curteys;</L>
<L>For who so &yogh;yue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfth.</NOTE> curteysly,</L>
<L N="7076">Hyt fordo&thorn;e &thorn;e synne of glotonye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of mete, glotonye wyl bygynne;</L>
<L>Alm&euml;s &thorn;erof fordo&thorn;e &thorn;at synne.</L>
<L N="7079">Alm&euml;s fordo&thorn; alle wykkednes,</L>
<L>And quenchy&thorn; synne, and maky&thorn; hyt les.</L>
<L>Alm&euml;s seme&thorn; hyt cum&thorn; of loue<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfst.</NOTE> to man for God aboue,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for hym &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="7084">Or hym &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfst.</NOTE> hyt fore.</L>
<L>Alm&euml;s, &thorn;ou wost weyl, ys a &yogh;yfte;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e &yogh;yuyng, man ys vplyfte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yue gladly, for God, &thorn;yn alm&euml;s here;</L>
<L N="7088">Hym &yogh;yue &thorn;ou hyt on alle manere,</L>
<L>And for hys loue, to hys meyne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou of hym wylt loued be.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>So wyl &yogh;yftys lou&euml; tylle,</L>
<L N="7092">And gadyr many one to gode wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &yogh;yftys, twey loues mayst &thorn;ou haue,</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> tym&euml;s mow &thorn;e saue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst ys, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &yogh;yue &thorn;y &thorn;ynges</L>
<L N="7096">To hau&euml; lou&euml; of lordynges:</L>
<L>For &thorn;y &yogh;yfte &thorn;ou mayst be herde,</L>
<L>And saue &thorn;y god&euml; yn &thorn;e werlde;</L>
<L>But &thorn;at love laste&thorn; lytyl whyle,</L>
<L N="7100">And a&yogh;ens God hyt wyl &thorn;e fyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er loue is noght for &thorn;ys;</L>
<L>Hyt aske&thorn; noght but heuene blys;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at loue ys, euery deyl,</L>
<L N="7104">loue of God and pore man weyl.</L>
<L>what ys loue vnto men pore?</L>
<L>Alm&euml;s to hem ys recouere;</L>
<L>Alm&euml;s dede of loue ys wey,</L>
<L N="7108">No&thorn;er mysdo, no&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem no.</NOTE> myssey;</L>
<L>&THORN;an wyl God almyghty loue &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;y loue ys &thorn;an with charyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charyte ys, &thorn;e certeyn to lere,</L>
<L N="7112">loue of &thorn;yn euyncrysten dere.</L>
<L>So sone &thorn;erto, noght wyl &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L>Ne so moche, as wyl alm&euml;s dede.</L>
<L>Charyte ys, &thorn;e longyng of loue,</L>
<L N="7116">As y haue tolde &yogh;ow here aboue;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at euer &thorn;ou mayst do,&mdash;</L>
<L>But loue yn charyte be &thorn;erto&mdash;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at euer hast &thorn;ou wroght,<MILESTONE N="47b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7120">Stant &thorn;e ell&euml;s al at noght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se now what seynt Poul&euml; seys</L>
<L>Yn a pystyl, &thorn;e sam&euml; weys,&mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;ogh y speke as weyl with tung<NOTE PLACE="foot">tounge</NOTE></L>
<L N="7124">As any man or aungel ha&thorn; song,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sounge.</NOTE></L>
<L>And y lyue nat with charyte,</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng auayle&thorn; hyt to me.</L>
<L>For y do &thorn;an ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e bras,</L>
<L N="7128">And as &thorn;e tympan, &thorn;at bete was;
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bras, to o&thorn;er, &yogh;yue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf&thorn;e.</NOTE> grete sown,</L>
<L>And bet hym self vp and down.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh y speke al yn prephecye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">prophecye.</NOTE></L>
<L>And haue &thorn;e kunnyng of euery maystrye,</L>
<L N="7133">And, with gode beleue myght seye</L>
<L>&THORN;e hylles to turne yn-to &thorn;e valey,</L>
<L>&yogh;yf hyt ne be with charyte wroght,</L>
<L N="7136">Ell&euml;s, he sey&thorn; &thorn;at y am noght.</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh y &yogh;yue alle my wurld&euml;s gode</L>
<L>Vnto por&euml; mennys fode,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue my body for to brenne</L>
<L N="7140">Opunly o&thorn;er men to kenne,<NOTE PLACE="inter">teche</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;ar be charyte with alle,</L>
<L>My mede &thorn;arfore shal be ful smalle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke now how many godenesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">godenesses.</NOTE> &thorn;er are,</L>
<L N="7144">with-out&euml; charyte noght but bare.</L>
<L>wylt &thorn;ou know<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wyltow knowe.</NOTE> &thorn;y self, and se</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wone yn charyte?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charyte suffre&thorn; bo&thorn;e gode and yl,</L>
<L N="7148">And charyte ys of reuful wyl,</L>
<L>Charyte ha&thorn; noun enuye,</L>
<L>And charyte wyl no felunnye;</L>
<L>Charyte ys nat Irus,<NOTE PLACE="inter">wra&thorn;ful</NOTE></L>
<L N="7152">And charyte ys nat coueytous;</L>
<L>Charyte wyl no bostful preysyng;</L>
<L>he wyl noght but ry&yogh;twys &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>Charyte loue&thorn; no fantome,</L>
<L N="7156">No &thorn;ynges &thorn;at euyl may of come;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; no ioye of wykkednes,<MILESTONE N="48a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But loue&thorn; alle &thorn;at sothfast es;</L>
<L>Alle godenes he vp bere&thorn;;</L>
<L N="7160">Alle he suffre&thorn;, and noun he dere&thorn;;</L>
<L>Gode hope he ha&thorn; yn ryghtwys &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And alle he susteyne&thorn; to &thorn;e endyng;</L>
<L>Charyte ne fayle&thorn; noght,</L>
<L N="7164">Ne no &thorn;yng &thorn;at with hym ys wroght.</L>
<L>when alle prophecyes are alle gone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">agone.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>And alle tunges are leyde echone,</L>
<L>And alle craftys fordo shul be,</L>
<L N="7168">&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;en.</NOTE> laste&thorn; stedfast charyte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; seynt Poule, and moch&euml; more,</L>
<L>Yn hys pystyl of hys lore.</L>
<L>Seynt charyte ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys bo&thorn;e.</NOTE> gode and hende,</L>
<L N="7172">lastyng with God with-outyn ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gode hyt were to loue hyt weyl,</L>
<L>And folowe hyt with oure dede sumdeyl.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf we &thorn;ys charyte wyl haue,</L>
<L N="7176">&YOGH;yue we &thorn;e pore whan &thorn;ey vs craue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue we hem, as hyt ys oure my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>with-oute myssaw or any fy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys hyt curteys alm&euml;s dede;</L>
<L N="7180">&THORN;ank of God &thorn;an ys oure mede,</L>
<L>And shal stonde ful stalwur&thorn;ly</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e synne of glotonye,</L>
<L N="7183">As y haue tolde &yogh;ow here byfore,</L>
<L>And fur&thorn;er shal y telle &yogh;ow<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&yogh;ow' omitted.</NOTE> now more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;e begynnyng y spake of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>Ete ne drynk but &thorn;at nede ys.</L>
<L>who so do&thorn; hyt oute of mesure,</L>
<L N="7188">Hele of body may nat dure,</L>
<L>And to hys soule, hyt ys dedly synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at custummable ys &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>And penaunce harde &thorn;arfore shal go,</L>
<L N="7192">But we kepe vs weyl &thorn;erfro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke yn &thorn;ys sawe what Catoun seys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys wyys and ry&yogh;t curteys,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn hele wylt dure,<MILESTONE N="48a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7196">Ete and drynk of swych mesure</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;y strenk&thorn;e be nat &thorn;e lesse;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For, drynkyng oute of skylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;y body bryng hyt wylle</L>
<L N="7200">To sorowe and to syk&euml;nesse."
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="231"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ou&thorn;er spyces ha&thorn; glotonye:</L>
<L>To ete &thorn;y mete ouer brennynglye</L>
<L>And lustly, whan &thorn;ou hyt getyst,</L>
<L N="7204">And takest noun hede what &thorn;ou etyst.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er spyce ys noght to pay,</L>
<L>As a beste to ete al day,</L>
<L>And kepyst non&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> certeyn tyme,</L>
<L N="7208">&THORN;e settyng at none or pryme,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er ou&thorn;er tyme &thorn;at fally&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fal&thorn;.</NOTE> to man,</L>
<L>But as a beste &thorn;at no resun kan.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; weyl hyt ys resun</L>
<L N="7212">To call&euml; swych a man 'glotoun.'</L>
<L>Twyys on &thorn;e day ys sustynaunce</L>
<L>To man &thorn;at ha&thorn; gode cheuysaunce.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheuysaunc&euml;, woste &thorn;ou how,</L>
<L N="7216">To man &thorn;at ha&thorn; met&euml; ynow,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he be man of trauayle,</L>
<L>Hyt were y-now with-out&euml; fayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &thorn;o men &thorn;at haue no swynk,</L>
<L N="7220">&THORN;at delyte hem yn mete or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>.</NOTE> drynk,</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">apostole.</NOTE> Poul&euml; spek&thorn; of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And dampne&thorn; many one to wo.</L>
<L>He sey&thorn; "woo to &thorn;o &thorn;at erly &yogh;erne,</L>
<L N="7224">&THORN;at go and haunt&euml; &thorn;e tauerne,</L>
<L>Yn wyne or ale to haue lykyng;</L>
<L>Cursednes hem folowy&thorn; at &thorn;e endyng.</L>
<L>Of swych, here womb&euml;s are here Cryst;<NOTE PLACE="foot">kryst.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7228">&THORN;at ys here loue, &thorn;at ys here tryst."</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ys he mene&thorn; sykyrly</L>
<L>For man &thorn;at loue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">loue.</NOTE> moche glotonye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ung&euml; chyldryn, &thorn;ey mow wele,</L>
<L N="7232">On &thorn;e day, et&euml; &thorn;re mele;</L>
<L>For sum of hem wex ful tyte,<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;arefor ys more, here appetyte;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt behoue&thorn; tyme be &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="7236">Or men mowe wy&thorn; hem mysdo;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e old&euml; man</L>
<L>Yn a prouerbe<NOTE PLACE="foot">forbysyn.</NOTE> &thorn;at he can,
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;yue &thorn;y chylde when he<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> wyl kraue,</L>
<L N="7240">And &thorn;y whelpe whyl hyt wyl haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;an mayst &thorn;ou make yn a stounde</L>
<L>A foul&euml; chylde and a feyr&euml; hounde."</L>
<L>So mayst &thorn;ou be enchesoun</L>
<L N="7244">To make &thorn;y chylde a glotoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-nou&thorn;er vyce ys &yogh;yt to graunte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at rych&euml; men mochyl haunte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many one are so daungerous,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare the French lines 5811-16.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7248">And oute of mesure esquaymous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys kok&euml; may no day</L>
<L>Grey&thorn;&euml; hym hys mete to pay.</L>
<L>&THORN;at me &thorn;enke&thorn; a feble manere;</L>
<L N="7252">A vylanye hyt ys to here;</L>
<L>For euery coke wulde, at hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>hys lord&euml;s met&euml; were wel dy&yogh;t:</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er hyt be lorde or lady,</L>
<L N="7256">Me &thorn;enke&thorn; hyt ys a spyce of glotonye.</L>
<L>hyt seme&thorn;, were hyt at &thorn;y wyl,</L>
<L>Ouer mesure &thorn;ou wuldest &thorn;e fyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Rer&euml; sopers yn pryuyte,</L>
<L N="7260">with glotonye, echone &thorn;ey be;</L>
<L>And &thorn;yr ys moch&euml; wast&euml; ynne,</L>
<L>And gadryng of ou&thorn;er synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;efte behoue&thorn; &thorn;e sumdele &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="7264">And glotonye algat&euml; more;</L>
<L>And leccherye ys quene or kyng;</L>
<L>For hym ys all &thorn;at gaderyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7267">&YOGH;yt are &thorn;er ou&thorn;er rere sopers,</L>
<L>with men &thorn;at seru&euml; kny&yogh;tys and squyers;</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e day &thorn;an wyl &thorn;ey be</L>
<L>Before here maysters yn soberte;</L>
<L>But whan here maysters are broght to bedde,<MILESTONE N="48b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7272">&THORN;an wyl &thorn;ey fonde &thorn;at &thorn;ey be fedde,</L>
<L>And sytte vp &thorn;are wy&thorn; recolage<NOTE PLACE="foot">rycolage.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="233"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yt do moch&euml; more outrage;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mydnyght ys but a &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L N="7276">But hyt be, tyl &thorn;e cok krowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese men are clumb&euml; on a grece</L>
<L>To glotony&euml; with &thorn;at spece.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also fall&euml; men yn plyght,</L>
<L N="7280">&THORN;at sytte vp<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at sytte vp on &thorn;e &THORN;ursday nyght.</NOTE> &thorn;e &THORN;arsday at nyght.</L>
<L>And ouerlong ete flesshe and drunke</L>
<L>Aftyr &thorn;at mydnyght ys runge,</L>
<L>Or fysshe or flesshe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or whyte or fysshe.</NOTE> &thorn;at suffre&thorn; dede,</L>
<L N="7284">&THORN;at shulde on &thorn;e Fryday faste watyr &amp; brede;</L>
<L>Swych etyng &thorn;ey shul sore abeye,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey amende hem are &thorn;ey deye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Fryday nyght ys,&mdash;&thorn;ys shalt &thorn;ou leue,&mdash;</L>
<L N="7288">Aftyr &thorn;e &THORN;ursday at eue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e nyght cum&thorn; byfore &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys now of &thorn;e new&euml; lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As y haue tolde of rere sopers,</L>
<L N="7292">&THORN;e same falle&thorn; of erly dyners;</L>
<L>Dyners are oute of skyl and resun</L>
<L>On &thorn;e Sunday, or hye<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar hygh.</NOTE> messe be doun.</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou haue haste, here &yogh;yt a messe,</L>
<L N="7296">Al holy, and no lesse,</L>
<L>And nat symple,<NOTE PLACE="foot">symply.</NOTE> a sakare,</L>
<L>For hyt ys nat y-now<NOTE PLACE="foot">ynogh.</NOTE> for &thorn;e,</L>
<L>But hyt be for lordys powere,</L>
<L N="7300">Or pylgrymage &thorn;at ha&thorn; no pere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Are &thorn;ou oght ete, &thorn;ys ys my rede,</L>
<L>Take holy watyr and holy brede;</L>
<L>For yn auenture kas, hyt may &thorn;e saue,</L>
<L N="7304">&YOGH;yf housel ne shryft&euml; &thorn;ou mayst haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle o&thorn;er tymes ys glotonye,</L>
<L>But hyt be grete enchesun why.</L>
<L>On o&thorn;er hygh dayys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">days.</NOTE> &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou may,&mdash;</L>
<L N="7308">&THORN;ogh &thorn;at hyt be nat Sunday,&mdash;</L>
<L>Here &thorn;y mess&euml; ar &thorn;ou dyne;<MILESTONE N="49a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou do nat, ellys ys hyt pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>lord&euml;s &thorn;at haue prestes at wyl,</L>
<L N="7312">Me &thorn;enketh &thorn;ey trespas ful yl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at any day ete, are<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar.</NOTE> &thorn;ey here messe,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&yogh;yf' omitted.</NOTE> hyt be &thorn;urgh harder dystresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ese.</NOTE> men &thorn;at are of holy cherche,</L>
<L N="7316">&THORN;ey wet&euml; weyl how &thorn;ey shul werche;</L>
<L>But swych y tell&euml; hardyly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych a preste dou&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">do&thorn;.</NOTE> glotonye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at O, &THORN;e H.</NOTE> leuy&thorn; hys messe on &thorn;e auter<NOTE PLACE="foot">Written 'autere' first, and then the final <I>e</I> dotted out.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7320">For to go to a dyner.</L>
<L>So ne shuld he do, for no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>For loue ne awe of no lordyng,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf hyt were for a grete nede</L>
<L N="7324">&THORN;at shuld hym falle, or a grete drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue we tolde yn lytyl space</L>
<L>how &thorn;at glotonye cum&thorn; yn place</L>
<L>On many maner dyuers wyse,</L>
<L N="7328">And how we shul knowe all&euml; &thorn;yse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf any se&thorn; hym so coup&aacute;ble</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn &thorn;ys ys custumm&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>leu&euml; hem, and do no more,</L>
<L N="7332">And ask&euml; penaunc&euml; &thorn;arefore,</L>
<L>And God ys curteys, and wul wele</L>
<L>For&yogh;yue &thorn;e &thorn;y trespas euery dele.</L>
<L>God graunte vs, for hys swete mercy,</L>
<L N="7336">To kepe vs alle fro glotonye!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin">
<HEAD>[Of Lechery.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now shul we speke of leccherye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folowe&thorn; &thorn;e synne of glotonye;</L>
<L>Hyt ys &thorn;e laste of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &thorn;e.</NOTE> seuene,</L>
<L N="7340">And, fyr&thorn;est hyt ys fro heuene.</L>
<L>wharefore &thorn;an hyt ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys hyt.</NOTE> so?</L>
<L>For hyt dampne&thorn; euer two.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst synne &thorn;y self yn wyl,
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="235"></L>
<L N="7344">But with ano&thorn;er &thorn;ou shalt fulfyl.</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;ey are<NOTE PLACE="foot">are O, art H. (In H. '&thorn;ey' is alterd from &thorn;ou.')</NOTE> to folehardy</L>
<L>&THORN;at haunte &thorn;e synne of lecchery;</L>
<L>For why, to do alle ou&thorn;er synnes,<MILESTONE N="49a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7348">&THORN;e lyghtlyer &thorn;e fende hem wynnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On seuene maners shal y shewe</L>
<L>How lecherye &thorn;an ys a shrewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyrst ys 'fornycacyon,'</L>
<L N="7352">whan two vnweddyd haue mysdon,</L>
<L>As sengle knaue and sengle tarne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tharne, glossed 'a wenche.'</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">wenche.</NOTE></L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey synne to-gedyr &yogh;erne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e leste hyt ys of all&euml; seuene,</L>
<L N="7356">&YOGH;yt hyt forbarre&thorn; &thorn;e blys of heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er ys 'awoutry,'</L>
<L>whan weddyd and weddyd to-gedyr lye,</L>
<L>As weddyd man take&thorn; ano&thorn;ers wyfe,</L>
<L N="7360">&THORN;at ys &thorn;e mor&euml; synful lyfe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf weddyd man, sengle woman take&thorn;,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e spousebrech&euml; &thorn;ere he maky&thorn;.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf weddyd wyfe take sengle man,</L>
<L N="7364">Alle spousebreche tel y hyt &thorn;an;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey haue broke with-out&euml; fayle</L>
<L>&THORN;e chast&euml; bond&euml; of spousayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydd&euml; synn&euml; ys &thorn;e werst,</L>
<L N="7368">&THORN;e clerk[es] calle&thorn; hyt 'yncest,'</L>
<L>whan men<NOTE PLACE="foot">men.</NOTE> take kyn yn felawrede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">felaghrede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wy&thorn; hem do&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">doun.</NOTE> flessh&euml;ly dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ner[&euml;] syb she ys hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys B, <I>om</I>. A.</NOTE> kynde,</L>
<L N="7372">&THORN;e mor&euml; ply&yogh;t shal he &thorn;ere fynde.</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf he with a woman synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum of hys kyn ha&thorn; endyd ynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to sey, ha&thorn; ley here by,
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="236"></L>
<L N="7376">&THORN;e more ply&yogh;t ys &thorn;at lecchery;</L>
<L>&THORN;us hyt sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e decre,</L>
<L>He calle&thorn; hyt an 'affynyte';</L>
<L>Affynyte hyt make&thorn; alle an ende,</L>
<L N="7380">hys blode &thorn;arto no more may wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;e synne ys more perylous,</L>
<L>with man and womman relygyus;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey haue made professyoun</L>
<L N="7384">Bo&thorn;e vn-to relygyoun,</L>
<L>Moche ys to charg&euml; &thorn;at folye<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey to-gedyr do leccherye.</L>
<L>Relygyous man also ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys also.</NOTE> to blame,</L>
<L N="7388">&THORN;at yn &thorn;e wurlde take&thorn; a foule fame,</L>
<L>For he may kepe hym weyl &thorn;erfro,</L>
<L>Alon&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Allone.</NOTE> &thorn;ar hym neuer go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7391">&THORN;e fyf&thorn;e ys moch&euml; for to drede,</L>
<L>To rauysh<NOTE PLACE="foot">rauys.</NOTE> a womman here maydenhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to say, a-&yogh;ens here wylle,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf she graunt&euml; weyl &thorn;ar-tylle;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;ogh she<NOTE PLACE="foot">she O, he H. (A.S. <I>heo</I>, she).</NOTE> to hym consente,</L>
<L N="7396">he ys holde to here auaunsement;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf she &yogh;yue here to folye,</L>
<L>She kan nat leu&euml; tyl she deye;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at broght here to &thorn;at bysmere,</L>
<L N="7400">For here foly he shal answere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e syxt&euml; reyse&thorn; gret&euml; stryfe,</L>
<L>To rauys anou&thorn;er mannys wyfe;</L>
<L>For a&yogh;ens God hyt ys euyl dede,</L>
<L N="7404">And to &thorn;e worlde also mochyl drede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be a&yogh;ens here wyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;e more he dou&thorn; hym seluen yl.</L>
<L>A clerk, &yogh;yf [&thorn;at] he ordred be,</L>
<L N="7408">hys synne ys more &thorn;an ou&thorn;er &thorn;re</L>
<L>For he dou&thorn; &thorn;at he shulde forbede,</L>
<L>And chastyse ou&thorn;er of swyche dede,
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>And &thorn;arto mochyl mor&euml; kan</L>
<L N="7412">&THORN;an a-no&thorn;er lewed man.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lewed man, knowest also</L>
<L>what ys to lete, what ys to do;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou knowyst as weyl, euery poynt,</L>
<L N="7416">As &thorn;e prest &thorn;at ys a-noynt,</L>
<L>And wost what peryl ys &thorn;erynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst no&yogh;t sey, to fende &thorn;y synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also do &thorn;es&euml; lordynges,</L>
<L N="7420">&THORN;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ey B, &THORN;e A.</NOTE> trespas moch&euml; yn twey &thorn;ynges;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey rauys a mayden a&yogh;ens here wyl,</L>
<L>And mennys wyuys &thorn;ey lede<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyffes lede.</NOTE> awey &thorn;ertyl;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar tyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>A grete vylanye &thorn;arto<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar to.</NOTE> he dous<MILESTONE N="49b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7424">&YOGH;yf he make &thorn;erof hys rous;<NOTE PLACE="inter">boste</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ded&euml; ys confusyun,</L>
<L>And more ys &thorn;e dyffamacyun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e seuenest<NOTE PLACE="foot">seuen&thorn;e.</NOTE> ys foulest leccherye&mdash;</L>
<L N="7428">Comoun wymmen to lygg&euml; by&mdash;</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e ou&thorn;er &thorn;at we haue seyde.</L>
<L>longyng of loue ys &thorn;er&euml; nede,</L>
<L>For to lou&euml; one a-lone,</L>
<L N="7432">&THORN;an here &thorn;at tak[e]&thorn; euerychone.</L>
<L>Foul ys &thorn;at lust and &thorn;at peryl,</L>
<L>To loue here &thorn;at al men go tyl.</L>
<L>Ful foul&euml; ys &thorn;at forreyne</L>
<L N="7436">&THORN;at ys comon for al, certeyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, what as euer be yn &thorn;y &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>Comun wymmen take &thorn;ou noght,</L>
<L>For many kas &thorn;at may falle,</L>
<L N="7440">&THORN;at pryu&euml; ys to telle &yogh;ow alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And som&euml; told&euml; mow weyl be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at are nat holde yn pryuyte;</L>
<L>One ys, she may take &thorn;y bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="7444">Fadyr, or sybkynd, as wel as ou&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er, for cuntek and foule stryfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst, &thorn;urgh here, lese &thorn;y lyfe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red[d&euml;] ys &thorn;e werst&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e werste B, werst A. (See '&thorn;e &thorn;rydde,' p. 235, l. 7367.)</NOTE> wem;
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="238"></L>
<L N="7448">Meseles, men seye, vsen hem;</L>
<L>And, who take&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">who so tak&thorn;.</NOTE> hem yn &thorn;at hete,</L>
<L>Clennesse of body he may sone lete.</L>
<L>Moche wo &thorn;an, ys swyche to take,</L>
<L N="7452">For &thorn;es&euml; &thorn;re lakk&euml;s sake;</L>
<L>And moche may be &thorn;at wommans mone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mone.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she shal answere for hem echone</L>
<L>&THORN;at haue ydo any synne wy&thorn; hyre,</L>
<L N="7456">At domes day, &thorn;e day of Ire.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arefore, &yogh;e men, take&thorn; none,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;e wymmen, take&thorn; but one.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf man or womman may nat be chaste,</L>
<L N="7460">Take,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Take one.</NOTE> and do no mor&euml; waste,</L>
<L>One of<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> whom &yogh;oure loue wyl be,<MILESTONE N="50a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;yue&thorn; nat &yogh;oure bodyys to alle ylych fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seuene maner synnes y haue &yogh;ow tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whych cumbren men on many folde,</L>
<L N="7465">And &thorn;e leste of alle &thorn;ese seuene</L>
<L>Forbarre&thorn; a man &thorn;e blys of heuene.</L>
<L>who-so wyl be clene of &thorn;yse,</L>
<L N="7468">A&yogh;ens hys flessh behoue&thorn; hym ryse,</L>
<L>And wy&thorn; hyt fy&yogh;t ful faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt be algate dow&uuml;n<NOTE PLACE="foot">down.</NOTE> kaste,</L>
<L>And elles may he neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neure.</NOTE> be clene,</L>
<L>hys flessh hys enmy wyl hym sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">so.</NOTE> tene:</L>
<L>Of swych a fy&yogh;t a sample y kan,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>Of seynt Benet &thorn;at holy man.</L>
<L>Seynt Gregory tel&thorn; for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="7476">how seynt Benet was tempted onys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of St. Benet's Tempta|tion, and how he freed himself by rolling in Thorns and Nettles.]</HEAD>
<L>As seynt Benet sate yn hys celle,</L>
<L>To tempte hym com a fend of helle</L>
<L>Yn a lykenes of a bryd.
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="239"></L>
<L N="7480">A '&thorn;rostyl' ys &thorn;e nam&euml; kyd;</L>
<L>hyt come fleyng by seynt Benet,</L>
<L>And, mery<NOTE PLACE="foot">myry.</NOTE> synggyng, by hym hym set;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, he hadde grete ferly<NOTE PLACE="inter">wundyr</NOTE></L>
<L N="7484">&THORN;at hyt flegh hym so ny.</L>
<L>Seynt Benet wende he my&yogh;t hyt ha take,</L>
<L>For hyt sate by hym so spake.<NOTE PLACE="inter">tame</NOTE></L>
<L>he blessed hym fyrst, and bedde hys hande</L>
<L N="7488">To take &thorn;e brydde &thorn;at was syttande;</L>
<L>As sone as he hadde made &thorn;e croyce,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bryde flegh fur&thorn;, and left hys voys.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;rostel sagh he no more;</L>
<L N="7492">hyt become, he ne wyst whore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an come on hym so sodenly</L>
<L>So grete temptyng of lecchery,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer er, syn he was bore,</L>
<L N="7496">So grete temptyng was hym byfore;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml; &thorn;an put yn hys &thorn;oght</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde, or seye, or wroght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On&euml;s he sagh a feyre womman,<MILESTONE N="50a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7500">And al day yn hys &thorn;oght she ran;</L>
<L>Swych &thorn;oght so hadde hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;oght had hym so.</NOTE> ouercome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e &thorn;oght of God, hyt had ny<NOTE PLACE="foot">nygh.</NOTE> fornome;</L>
<L>And foule longyng had hym so take</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys ermytage he hadde nygh<NOTE PLACE="foot">nygh he had.</NOTE> forsake;</L>
<L N="7505">But Ihesu, &thorn;at see&thorn; al &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>he sagh weyl hys grete temptyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he suffred hym weyl be to-blaste,</L>
<L N="7508">he suffred hym nat be dow&uuml;n kaste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">down kast.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fende may nat but tempte &thorn;y wyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;y.</NOTE> selfe behoue&thorn; &thorn;e dede fulfyl;</L>
<L>And for he stode so stalwr&thorn;ly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O, stalwrly H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7512">&THORN;e holy goste was to hym redy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>with-oute hys cell&euml;, &thorn;orn&euml;s wore,
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>And netles grewe, &thorn;at byten sore;</L>
<L>So hadd&euml; grace made hym stedfaste,</L>
<L N="7516">&THORN;at al hys clo&thorn;ys of he kast,</L>
<L>And alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle he H, al O.</NOTE> naked hym-self he wrappe</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e &thorn;orn&euml;s &thorn;at were sharpe,</L>
<L>And among &thorn;e netles echone,</L>
<L N="7520">Tyl hys temptacyun was al gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes prykked, &thorn;e netles dyd byte,</L>
<L>Of flesshly temptacyun &thorn;ey made hym quyte,</L>
<L>So clene, &thorn;at neuer aftyrward</L>
<L N="7524">was he tempted more so hard</L>
<L>Of hys flessh, &thorn;at was hys fo,</L>
<L>he dyde hyt &thorn;ere so moch&euml; wo.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en, loued<NOTE PLACE="foot">louede O, loue H.</NOTE> he Ihesu cryst wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl O, wel moche H.</NOTE> more</L>
<L N="7528">&THORN;an he dede, euer byfore,</L>
<L>And hadde to hym more loue longyng</L>
<L>&THORN;an byfore hys hard temptyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale y tolde for &thorn;at enchesun,</L>
<L N="7532">To stand a&yogh;ens temptacyun;</L>
<L>For who-so wyl hys soul&euml; saue,</L>
<L>Many a fy&yogh;t behoue&thorn; hym haue</L>
<L N="7535">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e spyces of lecchery,</L>
<L>Ar he wynne of hym &thorn;e maystry.<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Poule techy&thorn; vs for &thorn;at batayle</L>
<L>A sykyr fyght &thorn;at wyl nat fayle;</L>
<L>He sey&thorn;, "y forbede &yogh;ow echoun,</L>
<L N="7540">with womman for to go alone."</L>
<L>For who-so dou&thorn; hyt, sone and ly&yogh;tly</L>
<L>He consenty&thorn; to lecchery;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou alone, alone with hyre,</L>
<L>&thorn;y &thorn;oght, by herte, cum&thorn; sone on fyre;</L>
<L N="7545">Be &thorn;ou neuer so chaste ne straunge,</L>
<L>Be &yogh;e alone, &thorn;yn herte wyl chaunge;</L>
<L>And God commaunde&thorn; bo&thorn;e &thorn;e and me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">me <I>and</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7548">Oure herte to<NOTE PLACE="foot">be.</NOTE> stable yn chastyte.
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>He sey&thorn; nat, to whom he<NOTE PLACE="foot">whom &thorn;at he.</NOTE> wyl kalle,</L>
<L>But speke&thorn; comunly to vs alle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ogh he calle alle comunly,</L>
<L N="7552">Sum are called more specyally;</L>
<L>For specyaly &thorn;at comande&thorn; he</L>
<L>To men &thorn;at are of hygh degre,</L>
<L>As to bysshopes, and persones,</L>
<L N="7556">To prestys, and ou&thorn;er relygyons;<NOTE PLACE="foot">relygyones.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;ese ys specyal comaundement;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;ese to ou&thorn;er hyt shal be sent.</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore he bydde&thorn;, with wurd&euml;s smarte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">smerte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7560">&THORN;at &thorn;ey be all&euml; chaste of herte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what ys hyt wur&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrth.</NOTE> to be, with-outen, clene,</L>
<L>whan fyl&thorn;&euml; ys withynne &thorn;e sene?</L>
<L>For many one, whan &thorn;ey to bedde are bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="7564">Delyten hem yn fyl&thorn;ys of &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>Swych &thorn;oght&euml;s are synn&euml;s greue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey &thorn;&egrave; pay, or be &thorn;&egrave; leue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hyt pay &thorn;&egrave; so, swych foule &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="7568">&THORN;at &thorn;e dede were do, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou moght,</L>
<L>Certes hyt ys nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> to drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;y wyl ne shal answere for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> dede.</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou my&yogh;tyst, &thorn;ou wuldest, do,</L>
<L N="7572">&THORN;y wyl consente&thorn; weyl &thorn;arto;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art a lechoure yn &thorn;at kas,</L>
<L>&THORN;yn hert&euml;wyl ys grete trespas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er spyce, more synne hyt ys,<MILESTONE N="50b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7576">whan &thorn;ou sekest &thorn;y wyl of flesshe,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e lust of lecchery,</L>
<L>Yn handlyng, or dremyng of foly,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;oghtes or syght&euml;s &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees,</L>
<L N="7580">And yn alle ou&thorn;er pryuytes;</L>
<L>God hym-self forbede&thorn; alle &thorn;ys;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey gete no parte of heuene blys:</L>
<L>Yn shryfte forget&euml; noght of &thorn;yse;</L>
<L>How ofte &thorn;ou dedyst, and on what wyse.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="242"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7585">&YOGH;yt &thorn;yr ys a-no&thorn;er spyce<NOTE PLACE="foot">vyce.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at cum&thorn; of &thorn;e fendes malyce,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he dou&thorn; vs alle falle ynne,</L>
<L N="7588">yn dreme slepyng &thorn;at we are ynne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at yche temptacyun</L>
<L>May be twey maner of enchesun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrste ys syghte, &thorn;e tou&thorn;er ys &thorn;oght,</L>
<L N="7592">with-out&euml; &thorn;ese, dremest &thorn;ou noght;</L>
<L>For swyche &thorn;yng &thorn;ou mayst se with ye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt turne&thorn; to &thorn;oght of felonye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Altered to 'vilonye.'</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest ofte of &thorn;at syght,</L>
<L N="7596">&THORN;at wey of &thorn;oght gadre&thorn; my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And knytty&thorn; harde ry&yogh;t as a seme,</L>
<L>And shewe&thorn; on &thorn;e ny&yogh;t yn dreme.</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;at dreme, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou do lecherye,</L>
<L N="7600">hyt make&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;oght of vylayn&eacute;;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vylaynye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any do hyt ones<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt ones O, hyt H.</NOTE> &thorn;urgh chaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys &thorn;erfore but ly&yogh;t penaunce;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be don&euml; &thorn;urgh custome,</L>
<L N="7604">&THORN;an falle&thorn; &thorn;arfore harder dome;</L>
<L>For euery tyme, at al&thorn;er leste,</L>
<L>Behoue&thorn; &thorn;e shewe to &thorn;e preste:</L>
<L>Hyt ys a wysdom to shewe hyt alle;</L>
<L>Hyt may be moche, &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;enke&thorn; smalle.</L>
<L N="7609">&THORN;e prest&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">prest.</NOTE> he can euene charge,</L>
<L>For whyche he shal &yogh;yue penaunce large.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>lecchery ys also grete &yogh;ernyng</L>
<L N="7612">To be desyred &thorn;urgh feyre clo&thorn;yng,</L>
<L>what wymmen hem tyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyffe.</NOTE> with own&euml; wyl,<MILESTONE N="51a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To foly loue, ou&thorn;er men to tylle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf men, &thorn;urgh here feyre atyre,</L>
<L N="7616">wy&thorn; hem to do foly, haue desyre,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul answere for here synne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey are rote, and fyrst bygynne;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, &thorn;e c&oacute;nsentour
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="243"></L>
<L N="7620">Shal be holde for a lechour;</L>
<L>Euene peyn&euml; shul &thorn;ey bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e toon &thorn;e tou&thorn;er shal answere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt sey men yn &thorn;e old&euml; lawe,</L>
<L N="7624">&THORN;at, of a &thorn;efe and hys felawe,</L>
<L>O dome shul &thorn;ey bo&thorn;&euml; haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e toon ne to&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne &thorn;e tou&thorn;er.</NOTE> shul men nat saue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt men sey, as men gos,</L>
<L>As foule ys he &thorn;at halt, as he &thorn;at fos.<NOTE PLACE="foot">flos.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7629">Ano&thorn;er spyce eke he forbede&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many one ful lytyl drede&thorn;:</L>
<L>To suffre a lechour or lechours</L>
<L N="7632">To haunt&euml; foly yn here hous.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prophete speke&thorn; ful euyl of &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul haue part of peyne and wo;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e prophete Osee,</L>
<L>As moche defouled as hordam<NOTE PLACE="foot">hordom.</NOTE> shal be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7637">A-no&thorn;er spyce, &thorn;at moch&euml; dere&thorn;,</L>
<L>haunt&euml; &thorn;ey &thorn;at erandes bere&thorn;</L>
<L>To do a lechour for to spede,</L>
<L N="7640">Or &yogh;yuen conseyl to do &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L>Or susteyne one with maystry:</L>
<L>Swych men are castel of lechery.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e prophete seynt Danyel;</L>
<L N="7644">And holy wryt wytnesse&thorn; hyt wel.<NOTE PLACE="foot">weel.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what sey &yogh;e of &thorn;ese lordynges</L>
<L>&THORN;at a-vowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">auowe.</NOTE> here men to do swych &thorn;yngys?</L>
<L>&THORN;at men dur nat hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat hem O, nat H.</NOTE> chastyse</L>
<L N="7648">with holy cherche, ne o&thorn;er wyse.</L>
<L>Swych men areysen baner</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens holy cherches power,</L>
<L>And hem self are castel and toure<MILESTONE N="51a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7652">For to manteyn&euml; &thorn;e lechoure.</L>
<L>who so a-vowe&thorn; a<NOTE PLACE="foot">'a' omitted.</NOTE> man to do euyl,</L>
<L>he ys no sybber &thorn;an &thorn;e deuyl;
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e fende wulde &thorn;at al shulde be</L>
<L N="7656">Dampned, as weyl as ys he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt of &yogh;ou&thorn;e men shulde haue drede,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at men don&euml; yn chyldhede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at may be turned to lechery,</L>
<L N="7660">For chyldryn ofte to-gedyr ly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou oght dedyst and hopest, hyt ys</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;y wyt, synne of foule flessh:</L>
<L>Y cunseyl &thorn;e to telle &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> prest,</L>
<L N="7664">For peryl may fall&euml;, weyl &thorn;ou seest;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn ynwyt telle&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;at skyl</L>
<L>Of what &thorn;ou dest &thorn;at ys peryl,</L>
<L>For comunly, &thorn;at men done<NOTE PLACE="foot">do.</NOTE> yn &yogh;enk&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="7668">Yn ag&euml; haunte &thorn;ey hyt on lenk&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And mowe nat leue &thorn;at foule<NOTE PLACE="foot">vyle (a late <I>may</I> is interlined above <I>mowe</I>).</NOTE> vsage</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey toke yn &yogh;ou&thorn;e yn rage.</L>
<L>yn a prouerbe of olde Englys</L>
<L N="7672">Tell&euml; men, and so&thorn;e hyt ys,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at &yogh;oug&thorn;&euml; wones, yn ag&euml; mones;"</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest.</NOTE> ones, &thorn;ou dedyst eftsones.</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore loke what &thorn;y &yogh;ou&thorn;&euml; was,</L>
<L N="7676">And yn &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> age amende &thorn;y trespas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-no&thorn;er spyce, ware &thorn;e fro &thorn;ys</L>
<L>Foly, a womman for to kys;</L>
<L>For seld&euml; kys[eth] any frende,</L>
<L N="7680">&THORN;at lechery ne ys &thorn;oght or neuende.</L>
<L>kyssyng ys, for loue to wynne,</L>
<L>And ys erand for flesshly synne;</L>
<L>Man or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>.</NOTE> womman, loke for-&thorn;y,</L>
<L N="7684">wharefore &thorn;ou kyssest, whom, &amp; why.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;er a spyce to mene</L>
<L>For hem &thorn;at shuld be chaste and clene,</L>
<L>As &thorn;o men &thorn;at are of hygh degree,</L>
<L N="7688">Of holy cherches owne meyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;es&euml; men shuld for no &thorn;yng<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>Come yn wymmens hand&euml;lyng;</L>
<L>Ne womman,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne womman no&thorn;er.</NOTE> &thorn;at god&euml; cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="7692">Shuld kyss&euml; any prestys mou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere may nat but synne aryse;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryse.</NOTE></L>
<L>hys mou&thorn; ys halewed to Goddys seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne prest oghte no woman touche,</L>
<L>For, of foule touchyng, synne men souche.</L>
<L N="7697">Seynt Ierom sey&thorn; 'he shuld no&yogh;t</L>
<L>haue any woman yn hys &thorn;oght;'</L>
<L>For swych &thorn;oght, shal neuer weyl werche,</L>
<L N="7700">with man &thorn;at ys of holy cherche.</L>
<L>lestene now what Ierom seyde</L>
<L>To hys suster &thorn;at hym preyde;</L>
<L>She besoghte hym on alle maners</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wulde haue here yn hys preyers;</L>
<L N="7705">Seynt Ierom spake a&yogh;en to hyre,</L>
<L>Haluyndele as hyt were yn Ire,</L>
<L>"Y prey God, &thorn;at mynde of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="7708">Yn my &thorn;oght&euml;, neuer be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wenest &thorn;ou nat he dred hym nede,</L>
<L>whan he to hys suster<NOTE PLACE="foot">syster.</NOTE> &thorn;us seyde?</L>
<L>he dredde hym of sum wykked wrenche</L>
<L N="7712">whan he ne durst&euml; on here &thorn;enche.</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e &thorn;an shulde &thorn;ey moch&euml; drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at are alday with hem yn dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare French, lines 6107-10.</NOTE>&THORN;e fende whan he may any tyce&mdash;</L>
<L N="7716">&THORN;at ys, yn handlyng of sum vyce&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ych&euml; cum&thorn; hym wel to pay,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ynke&thorn; he, he ha&thorn; wonne a pray;</L>
<L>And namely of &thorn;ese holy men,</L>
<L N="7720">&THORN;at were hym leuer &thorn;an ou&thorn;er ten,</L>
<L><SUP>5</SUP>And a holy<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 An holy.</NOTE> man were hym leuer tylle</L>
<L>To flesshly lust or wykked wylle</L>
<L>&THORN;an an hundred ou&thorn;er mo</L>
<L N="7724">&THORN;at rekk&euml; neuer whedyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">where.</NOTE> &thorn;ey go.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="246"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Jew who heard some Devils' Reports of their Deeds to Satan; and how the Devil who got a Bishop to pat a Nun on the Back was most praisd.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>This Tale, says Gaston Paris (<I>Hist. Litt. de la France</I>, xxviii. 201), is made up from two distinct stories. All that relates to the Jew, the temple of Apollo, the narrative of the devil who tempted the bishop (St. Andr&eacute; de Fondi), the saying about the empty and markt vessel (p. 2444, l. 7854: <I>v&aelig;! v&aelig;! vas vacuum et signatum!</I>) is borrowd from St. Gregory's Dialogs, III. vii.; but the feats of the different devils, the punishments of some, and the reward of the other, are from the <I>Vitas Patrum,</I> p. 580 (compare p. 576 and 556), which is the source of Wadington's Tale, tho' it substitutes a pagan for the Jew, and greatens the fault of the holy man who is tempted. Guillaume Peraut (Guill. Peraldi, Summa de vitiis: de luxuria, II. 19) tells the two stories, one after the other, with|out mixing them; but we see the mixture going on under our eyes in <I>Libro de los Exemplos</I> (no. 21), which, following without doubt a lost Latin original, tells us, as to Satan's questioning of the other devils: "St. Gregory tells briefly the manner of this questioning; but we can see it more in detail by an example in the Life of the Holy Fathers," etc. This Tale was often retold in the Middle Ages, and a summary of it, after St. Gregory, is certainly found in these verses, <I>De triumphis Ecclesi&aelig;</I> of Johannes de Garlandia (ed. Wright, p. 37) as to the power of the sign of the Cross:</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>D&aelig;monis in fanum Jud&aelig;us tempore noctis</L>
<L>Venit, et advenit d&aelig;monis horror ei.</L>
<L>Se cruce signavit; signatum vas bene d&aelig;mon</L>
<L>Sed vacuum dixit: credidit ergo timens.</L>
<L>Nec pr&aelig;sul tetigit monialem quam tetigisse</L>
<L>Proposuit, sicut dixerat unus ibi.</L>
</LG><P>One must not then recognise here (as was suggested that one might, in 'Notices et Extraits des MSS.,' t. xxvii, 2<SUP>e</SUP> part., p. 71) the legend of Cyprian and Justine (see p. 258-60 below), or see in <I>Jud&aelig;us</I> a mistake of the copyists or editor for <I>Julianus</I>.</P></NOTE>]</HEAD>
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tel&thorn;.</NOTE> for gode mennys prew,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at sum tyme was<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyme &thorn;yr was.</NOTE> on&euml;s a Iew,</L>
<L>And trauayled o tyme by &thorn;e cuntre,<MILESTONE N="51b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7728">By iurnes &thorn;ydyr &thorn;at he wulde be.</L>
<L>Fyl so, he nyghtede yn a wasteyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he sagh no stede certeyne;</L>
<L>he sagh no stede where wast<NOTE PLACE="foot">was.</NOTE> best</L>
<L N="7732">To lygge a nyght and take hys rest.</L>
<L>But an<NOTE PLACE="foot">an O, and H.</NOTE> olde temple he sagh stondyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at, sum tyme, folke mysbeleuyng</L>
<L>Made here sacrifyse &thorn;er-ynne</L>
<L N="7736">To here god, &thorn;at hyght Apolyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys Iew restede &thorn;ere &thorn;at ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And toke hys es&euml; as he my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;e Iew lay &thorn;ere alone,</L>
<L N="7740">To hym-self he made hys mone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he beleued on swych a lawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at my&yogh;t nat saue hym on<NOTE PLACE="foot">wy&thorn;.</NOTE> no sawe.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>Of Ihesu Cryst, he hadde herd speke,</L>
<L>How Iewes dyd hym on &thorn;e rod&euml; steke.</L>
<L N="7745">&THORN;urgh grete &thorn;an ynspyracyun,</L>
<L>He &thorn;oght so on hys passyun</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure fey&thorn; yn hys hert&euml; ran,</L>
<L N="7748">Al be hyt he were no crysten man;</L>
<L>So, what for trou&thorn;e, and what for doute,</L>
<L>He made &thorn;e croys hym al a-boute,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en leyd hym downe to slepe;</L>
<L N="7752">Of ou&thorn;er, &yogh;af he no more kepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone at &thorn;e mydny&yogh;t he gan to wake</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh grete noyse and cry, &amp; sore to quake;</L>
<L>He lok&egrave;d vp, and sagh &thorn;ere sytte</L>
<L N="7756">Fend&euml;s fele &thorn;at fouly flytte;<NOTE PLACE="inter">chydde</NOTE></L>
<L>he sagh one sytt&euml; yn a cheyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chayere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at foule lok&egrave;d, and foule gan bere;</L>
<L>He bad hem all&euml; &yogh;elde a-counte,</L>
<L N="7760">Here ded&euml;s what &thorn;ey wulde amounte;</L>
<L>what &thorn;ey hadde do many &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>He aresoned hem on hys maners;</L>
<L N="7763">To oon he cast enchesoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret enchesoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sey &thorn;ou, felaw, what &thorn;ou hast doun!"</L>
<L>"At a weddyng," he seyde, "y was,<MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And, &thorn;ere y dyd grete trespas;</L>
<L>Y slogh, &thorn;urgh my&yogh;t of honde,</L>
<L N="7768">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e wyfe and &thorn;e husbonde;</L>
<L>And y dyd &yogh;yt a-no&thorn;er chek,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e ou&thorn;er y broght on cuntek,</L>
<L>And euery, y made ou&thorn;res foo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7772">&THORN;at euery man gan ou&thorn;er slo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e mayster fend gan hym beholde,</L>
<L>And sette at no&yogh;t &thorn;at he hadde tolde.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;at, how long<NOTE PLACE="foot">lange.</NOTE> hast &thorn;ou be &thorn;ore?"</L>
<L N="7776">"A twelue mon&thorn;e," he seyd, "and no more."
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>"For &thorn;y dede &thorn;ou getyst maugre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto &yogh;yt shalt &thorn;ou bete be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>with hym wulde he no more stryue;</L>
<L N="7780">He called<NOTE PLACE="foot">But calde.</NOTE> an-ou&thorn;er furthe belyue;</L>
<L>Felunlyche, with y&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">eyen.</NOTE> grym,</L>
<L>"where hast &thorn;ou be?" seyd he to hym.</L>
<L>"Yn &thorn;e se&euml;, haue y bene,</L>
<L>And moche sorow made men betwene;</L>
<L N="7785">Y haue broght to grete encumbre</L>
<L>Shyppes and men with-out&euml; noumbre,</L>
<L>what yn cuntek, and yn tempest,</L>
<L N="7788">Twenty &thorn;ousand at &thorn;e lest."</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuyl seyd, "&thorn;at ys no doute;</L>
<L>how long hast &thorn;ou be &thorn;ere-aboute?"</L>
<L>"Seuene wyntyr, al to-gydyr,</L>
<L N="7792">hau&euml; y be haunted<NOTE PLACE="foot">hauntynge.</NOTE> &thorn;edyr."</L>
<L>Satan comaunded, for hys seruyse</L>
<L>He shuld be put to hys Iuwyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red deuyl was for&thorn;&euml; fette<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&thorn; fet.</NOTE></L>
<L N="7796">Byfore Satan, &thorn;er he was sette;<NOTE PLACE="foot">set.</NOTE></L>
<L>Satan seyd, "where ware &thorn;ou?</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou hast sped, sey me now."</L>
<L>"A-boute a bysshope y haue be long,</L>
<L N="7800">&YOGH;yf y my&yogh;t hym yn synn&euml; fong;</L>
<L>But yn hym ys so grete bounte</L>
<L>&THORN;at y my&yogh;t neuer turne hym to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>But, &thorn;ys ny&yogh;t y haue so sped,<MILESTONE N="52a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hym with temptyng so fer haue led,</L>
<L N="7805">&THORN;at y hope, y haue hys &thorn;oght</L>
<L>A party to my wyll&euml; broght.</L>
<L>&THORN;yr com to hym, for hys godenesse,</L>
<L N="7808">A nunne, y wene a pryores,</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;yng of hym for to here</L>
<L>&THORN;at she perauenture my&yogh;t of lere;</L>
<L>Algate, y broght hyt so to an ende,
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="249"></L>
<L N="7812">&THORN;at, what tyme &thorn;at she shul wende,</L>
<L>He smote here a lytyl on &thorn;e bak</L>
<L>Yn pleyyng, whan he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, she H.</NOTE> to here spak.</L>
<L>God wyst what was yn hys &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>And yn hys herte, for y wyst hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">'hyt' omitted.</NOTE> no&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7817">Satan asked 'how long whyle</L>
<L>he hadde be aboute, hym to gyle.'</L>
<L>"Fourty wyntyr, and alle yn drede,</L>
<L N="7820">&YOGH;yt my&yogh;t y neuer so<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer er so.</NOTE> moche spede,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No.</NOTE> neuer er bryng hym to plyght</L>
<L>But &thorn;at y ded &thorn;ys sam&euml; ny&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ful weyl payd was Satanas</L>
<L N="7824">&THORN;at he hadde broght hym to &thorn;at cas:</L>
<L>He ros a&yogh;ens hym, and made hym blysse,</L>
<L>And profred hym hys mou&thorn;e to kysse,</L>
<L>And seyd, 'he was weyl wur&thorn;y</L>
<L N="7828">For to come and sytte hym by.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before hem alle, &thorn;at ych&euml; tyde,</L>
<L>he sette hym by hym, syde be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> syde,</L>
<L>And seyd, "ende &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bygunne;</L>
<L N="7832">For &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast do, my loue &thorn;ou hast wunne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; Iew &thorn;at &thorn;er&euml; lay,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e temple with grete affray,</L>
<L>Y trowe for so&thorn;e he slept<NOTE PLACE="foot">slepe.</NOTE> ful lytyl,</L>
<L N="7836">whan he herde &thorn;at grete chapytyl;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he hadde slept, hym neded awake,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he were wakyng, he shulde a<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha.</NOTE> quake,</L>
<L>For Satan asked &thorn;ere he sat,</L>
<L N="7840">"who ly&thorn; &thorn;ere, and what ys &thorn;at?</L>
<L>who durst so hardy be<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syll. line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>To lye &thorn;ere with-oute leue of me?</L>
<L>Go&thorn;e swy&thorn;e, one or two to-gedyr,</L>
<L>And, what he be, brynge&thorn; hym hedyr."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7845">&THORN;e deuylys come un-to hys bedde,
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>And styrte a&yogh;en, &thorn;ey were so dredde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bedde, ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> hym, ne durst &thorn;ey touche,</L>
<L>So had he marked hym with &thorn;e crouche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. has above a &cross;.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7849">&THORN;ey turned a&yogh;en to syre Satan,</L>
<L>And seyd, &thorn;ey durst nat brynge &thorn;at man.</L>
<L>He asked 'why &thorn;at chaunce byfel;'</L>
<L N="7852">&THORN;ey seyd, hyt was "a lore<NOTE PLACE="foot">ler.</NOTE> vessel,</L>
<L>An empty vessel &thorn;at marked was</L>
<L>From &thorn;e and &thorn;yne, syre Satanas;</L>
<L>&THORN;e vessel, whan hyt &thorn;ere was leyde,</L>
<L N="7856">Vn-to vs hyt longed nede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">al nede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alas &thorn;e whyle &thorn;ey gunne to reme!</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; hys mark &thorn;at wyl hym &yogh;eme."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Iew &thorn;ey called 'a voyde vessel,'</L>
<L N="7860">And forso&thorn;&euml;, so hyt fel;</L>
<L>Voyd&euml; he was of hys lawe,</L>
<L>For he forsoke hyt for fyne awe;</L>
<L>'Lore,'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ler.</NOTE> for he hadde nat oure lawe take</L>
<L N="7864">Se&thorn;&thorn;e he hadde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. hadde nat.</NOTE> hys owne forsake.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ys &thorn;yng, y hope &thorn;ey seyd,</L>
<L>And called &thorn;e Iew a vessel voyd.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey my&yogh;t nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">'nat' omitted.</NOTE> do hym no dere,</L>
<L N="7868">No&thorn;er to Satanas lede ne bere;</L>
<L>So hadde he hym with &thorn;e croyce blessed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hym algate &thorn;ey myssed.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml;s and syre Satanas</L>
<L N="7872">&THORN;an wente awey, cryying 'alas!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Iew&euml; &thorn;o asswy&thorn;e a-ros,&mdash;</L>
<L>hyt was no wundyr &thorn;o&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ogh.</NOTE> hym gros,&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="inter">dred</NOTE></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e bysshope sone he &yogh;ede</L>
<L N="7876">And tolde hym what he sagh yn dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e crystendome at hym he toke,</L>
<L>And, hys fals[&euml;] lawe forsoke,</L>
<L>And beleued oure lawe echedeyl,<MILESTONE N="52b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7880">And &thorn;e bysshope amended hym weyl.
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="251"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tal&euml; to &yogh;ow haue y tolde,</L>
<L>how &thorn;e fend&euml; halt hym bolde</L>
<L>whan he ha&thorn; tyced an holy man</L>
<L N="7884">with any temptacyun &thorn;at he kan,</L>
<L>hym &thorn;enke&thorn; he ha&thorn; do a grete chaffare;</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;o &thorn;at ordred are,</L>
<L>whedyr hyt be yn a womman handlyng,</L>
<L N="7888">Or yn any o&thorn;er lusty &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore lordynges &thorn;at kun wel se,</L>
<L>Amende&thorn; &yogh;ow, pur charyte,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; nat a-mys &thorn;e toye,</L>
<L N="7892">&THORN;at &thorn;e fende of &yogh;ou haue Ioye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prest wel y<NOTE PLACE="foot">'y' omitted.</NOTE>-lettred ys to blame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lette&thorn; nat, for drede ne shame,</L>
<L>To pley with wommen, and to rage;</L>
<L N="7896">For, aftyr pleyyng, cum&thorn; outrage.</L>
<L>Ofte men se, and haue herd seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swyche men go an euyl weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yue &thorn;ou a-mong hem mayst na<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat.</NOTE> lyue,</L>
<L N="7900">But some algat&euml; on &thorn;e clyue,</L>
<L>Take &thorn;ou ensample at seynt Ierom;</L>
<L>Do as he dyd, and go fro hom.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ierom wente yn-to deserte,</L>
<L N="7904">For drede of synne and foly grete.</L>
<L>Men asked hym why he &thorn;edyr &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Syn he was an holy man yn dede;</L>
<L>"y went&euml; &thorn;edyr, synne to fle,</L>
<L N="7908">Y dredde hyt wlde ha maystred me;</L>
<L>Synne of womman wyl with me fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And y fele me yn moche vnmy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf y a-byd&euml; &thorn;at batayle,</L>
<L N="7912">Y drede &thorn;at y shal falle or fayle;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf y fle &thorn;at ych&euml; bekyr,</L>
<L>Y hop&euml; &thorn;an y may be sekyr:"</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore me &thorn;enke&thorn;, foles are &thorn;o</L>
<L N="7916">&THORN;at fy&yogh;t, and mow[&euml;] be &thorn;ar-fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fy&yogh;t[&euml;] so &thorn;e de&thorn; to haue<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey mow fle, hem self to saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arefore, &yogh;e prestes &thorn;at dwel at hom,
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="252"></L>
<L N="7920">&THORN;enke&thorn; on &thorn;e drede of seynt Ierom,</L>
<L>And wommans<NOTE PLACE="foot">wommens.</NOTE> felawshepe for to fle</L>
<L>For doute of synne, for so ded he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But of wymmen hyt ys grete wundyr,</L>
<L>hyt fare&thorn; with hem as fyre and tundyr;</L>
<L N="7925">Comunly forsake &thorn;ey none</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer ys made of flessh and bone.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf she wulde to foly here take,</L>
<L N="7928">&THORN;e prest algate she my&yogh;t forsake;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er ys none, &thorn;at she ne may</L>
<L>Haue a sengle man to here pay.</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf she wulde algate mysdo,</L>
<L N="7932">A knaue my&yogh;t best beseme here to,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hyt were to take a prest,</L>
<L>For synne and sclaunder were &thorn;ere lest.</L>
<L>But how as euer men preche or spelle,</L>
<L N="7936">Of prest&euml;s wyues men here euer telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of ou&thorn;er wyues y wyl naght say,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey do nat wrong, but al day;</L>
<L>But y dare sey, as y haue herde,</L>
<L N="7940">On Englys toung<NOTE PLACE="foot">tonge.</NOTE> to alle &thorn;e werlde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;yr be o&thorn;er mayden or wyfe</L>
<L>&THORN;at dysturble&thorn; &thorn;e holy lyfe</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prest, &thorn;urgh lecchery,</L>
<L N="7944">A&yogh;ens here shal kalle and crye</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at are yn paradys,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at yn purgatory lys;</L>
<L>And all&euml; &thorn;at are yn &thorn;ys lyue</L>
<L N="7948">A&yogh;ens here shul aryse and stryue;</L>
<L>For euery prest, aftyr &thorn;e sacr&eacute;,</L>
<L>He parte&thorn; &thorn;ere Goddys body yn &thorn;re,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er &thorn;e vble yn &thorn;re.</NOTE></L>
<L>And offre&thorn; hem to &thorn;e fadyr yn heuene</L>
<L N="7952">On &thorn;ys wyse, as y shal neuene;</L>
<L>The fyrst he offre&thorn; hem to blys,</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at yn heuene ys;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'ben.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er he offre&thorn; for vs alle here,<MILESTONE N="53a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="7956">&THORN;at we to hym be bo&thorn;e lefe and dere;
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ryde he offre&thorn; to haue mem&oacute;ry</L>
<L>For soules &thorn;at are yn purgat&oacute;ry,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God bryng hem oute of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of here.</NOTE> peyne</L>
<L>And brynge to<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem to.</NOTE> &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at ys certeyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="7961">Certys, she dou&thorn; ful moche a-mys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e womman &thorn;at dysturble&thorn; alle &thorn;ys.</L>
<L>For, &thorn;o soul&euml;s are no &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="7964">wurscheped with &thorn;at offryng,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er vs to cunseyl, or to rede,</L>
<L>Ne hyt helpe&thorn; nat &thorn;e dede;</L>
<L>All&euml; &thorn;arefore &thorn;at now are,</L>
<L N="7968">And &thorn;at shul be, and now are fare,<NOTE PLACE="inter">go</NOTE></L>
<L>Shul dampne &thorn;at womman to be lore,</L>
<L>And curse &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at she was bore;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arwith-alle, ne shal she be quyt,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt shal hyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> dampne hyre owne ynwyt</L>
<L N="7973">&THORN;at ych&euml; day &thorn;at alle shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shal O, &thorn;at H.</NOTE> ryse</L>
<L>Before Ihesu, &thorn;at hygh Iustyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke&thorn;, &yogh;e wymmen, what &yogh;e do</L>
<L N="7976">&YOGH;yf &yogh;e dyd oght, do&thorn;e no more so,</L>
<L>Or harder penaunce, with bytter teres,</L>
<L>Shul &yogh;e do here, or ell&euml;s wheres.</L>
<L>And shame hyt ys euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys euer O, ys H.</NOTE> aywhare</L>
<L N="7980">To be kalled 'a prest&euml;s mare.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of swych one, y shal &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend&euml; bare to helle;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys chaunc&euml; fyl, &thorn;at ys so hard,</L>
<L N="7984">Yn &thorn;e tyme of gode Edward,&mdash;</L>
<L>Edward, syre Henry&euml;s sone,&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tale ys weyl to mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Priest's Concu|bine, and how Fiends carried off her Dead Body.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a prest ry&yogh;t amerous,&mdash;</L>
<L N="7988">And amerous men are lechours;&mdash;
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest, &thorn;e moste part of hys lyfe,</L>
<L>Helde a womman as hys wyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no tym&euml; he hare<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> lete,</L>
<L N="7992">S&oacute; &thorn;oght hym &thorn;e synn&euml; swete.</L>
<L>Yn synne, and yn foly desyre,<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Foure chyldryn he gate on hyre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese chyldryn, as &thorn;ey wox<NOTE PLACE="foot">woxe.</NOTE> more,</L>
<L N="7996">He sette hem vn-to scole to lore;</L>
<L>So &thorn;ey lernede, &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;re</L>
<L>were ordeyned, prestes to be;</L>
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;&euml; sone was a scoler,</L>
<L N="8000">To lern&euml; more he dyde hys power.</L>
<L>when &thorn;ey were prestys, here fadyr deyde,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at y er of<NOTE PLACE="foot">er of O, er H.</NOTE> seyde,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; womman lefte a-lyue</L>
<L N="8004">Aftyr hym foure &yogh;ere or fyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese foure chyldryn had grete &thorn;oght</L>
<L>How &thorn;ey were yn synne fur&thorn;e broght,</L>
<L>And how here modyr leued ynne,</L>
<L N="8008">Alle here lyfe, yn dedly synne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey preyde here, for all&euml; chaunce,</L>
<L>To be of god&euml; r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ynk&euml; here mysdede</L>
<L N="8012">with sorow of hert, and wy&thorn; drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &thorn;us answered she to hem alle,</L>
<L>"For no &thorn;yng &thorn;at may befalle,</L>
<L>Shal y neuer repent&euml; me</L>
<L N="8016">whyle y haue &yogh;ow prest&euml;s &thorn;re</L>
<L>&THORN;at for me mow<NOTE PLACE="foot">mowen</NOTE> rede and synge,</L>
<L>And, ful weyl, me to blys brynge;</L>
<L>So may my soule to God be broght</L>
<L N="8020">For any synne &thorn;at I haue wroght;</L>
<L>But wylle &yogh;e all&euml; four&euml; do</L>
<L>A &thorn;yng &thorn;at y prey &yogh;ow to?</L>
<L>kepy&thorn; my body, at &yogh;oure my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8024">&THORN;re dayys, and &thorn;re ny&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ys hous whan y am dede,</L>
<L>And y hope be saued fro &thorn;e quede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh y haue lyued a synful lyfe,</L>
<L N="8028">And haue be called a prest&euml;s wyfe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at graunted &thorn;ey euery deyl,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey wende ha<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> do hyt wele.</L>
<L>Sone aftyrward she euyld,<MILESTONE N="53b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8032">And deyd sunner &thorn;an she wylde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>here chyldryn, as &thorn;ey hadde here<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey here hade.</NOTE> het,</L>
<L>To wake here body were &thorn;ey set:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst nyght &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde here wake,</L>
<L N="8036">At mydny&yogh;t &thorn;e ber&euml; gan to quake;</L>
<L>Here four&euml; sonys &thorn;at saye hyt stere,</L>
<L>leyd on hond,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hande.</NOTE> and helde &thorn;e bere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ou&thorn;er men hadde swych&euml; drede</L>
<L N="8040">&THORN;at euery man hys w&euml;y &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>with moch&euml; drede and hydous syght</L>
<L>Askaped &thorn;ey on &thorn;e fyrst ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er ny&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;e chyldryn woke,</L>
<L N="8044">At &thorn;e mydny&yogh;t &thorn;e ber&euml; quoke,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at sate or &thorn;erby stode,</L>
<L>For dred&euml; wend&euml; ha wox<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue woxe.</NOTE> wode:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ny&yogh;t shewed he more hys ire,</L>
<L N="8048">&THORN;at hys power was moche yn hyre.</L>
<L>with sorowful sy&yogh;t and grete affray</L>
<L>He drogh &thorn;e body &thorn;ere hyt lay,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e dore &thorn;e fende hyt broght;</L>
<L N="8052">&THORN;at tym&euml; fyr&thorn;er my&yogh;t he noght.</L>
<L>Here four&euml; sones, with moch&euml; peyne,</L>
<L>Efte hadde &thorn;e body yn a&yogh;eyne;</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e body a rope &thorn;ey wonde,</L>
<L N="8056">And to &thorn;e ber&euml; fast &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> bonde;</L>
<L>So algate &thorn;e body with hem lefte;</L>
<L>At &thorn;at ny&yogh;t was hyt nat refte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red ny&yogh;t, moste sorow gan falle;
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="256"></L>
<L N="8060">At &thorn;e mydny&yogh;t, as &thorn;ey woke alle,</L>
<L>Come fend&euml;s fele, with lo&thorn;ely brous,</L>
<L>And fylden all&euml; ful &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey toke &thorn;e body and &thorn;e bere</L>
<L N="8064">wy&thorn; lothly cry, &thorn;at alle my&yogh;t here;</L>
<L>And bare hyt fur&thorn;e &thorn;at none wyst whore,</L>
<L>with-outen ende for euermore.</L>
<L>here sones hyt seyd, and hoped wel,</L>
<L N="8068">&THORN;at body and soule was lore eche deyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ongest sone &thorn;at was a scolere,</L>
<L>He preched &thorn;ys yn stedys here;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;urgh Ingland, yn euery cuntre,</L>
<L N="8072">he tolde &thorn;ys tale of grete pyte,</L>
<L>Oueral as he went a-boute,</L>
<L>(He spared no&thorn;er for shame ne doute)</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens wymmen &thorn;at prest&euml;s take,</L>
<L N="8076">For hys own&euml; modyr sake;</L>
<L>For to dampne and stroye &thorn;at synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no womman falle &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e wommen, &thorn;enke&thorn; on &thorn;ys tale,</L>
<L N="8080">And take&thorn; hyt for no troteuale!</L>
<L>Goddes veniaunce was hyt, and hys Ire,</L>
<L>To amende vs alle for loue of hyre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn a prouerbe, telle men &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="8084">"He wyys ys, &thorn;at ware ys,"<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syll. line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And wysdom es,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> and feyre maystrye,</L>
<L>To chastyse vs wy&thorn; ou&thorn;res folye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of prest&euml;s kan y sey no &thorn;yng,&mdash;</L>
<L N="8088">So seyd y at &thorn;e bygynnyng,&mdash;</L>
<L>No&thorn;er of clerkys neuer a deyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;&eacute;y wote<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete.</NOTE> what ys ylle and weyl;</L>
<L>But &thorn;us haue y herde for certeyn,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e worlde ys none so gode skryueyne&mdash;</L>
<L N="8093">&THORN;ogh he were wyser &thorn;an Salamon</L>
<L>And bettyr langaged &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an.</NOTE> was Mercyon
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="257"></L>
<L>And leued yn age a &thorn;ousend &yogh;ere&mdash;</L>
<L N="8096">Ne my&yogh;t telle &thorn;e sorow and were,<NOTE PLACE="inter">dysesc</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e peyne, &thorn;at &thorn;e preste shal drye,<NOTE PLACE="inter">suffre</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at haunte&thorn; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> synne of lecchery.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are wroth whan any &thorn;us preche&thorn;,</L>
<L>But holy wryt &thorn;us vs telle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs &thorn;us tel&thorn;.</NOTE> and teche&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8101">Now turne we a&yogh;en &thorn;ere we spak</L>
<L>Of handlyng synn&euml;, &thorn;at yche lak;</L>
<L>Y tolde of handlyng synne as y kou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And now wy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> foly kyssyng with mou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8105">kyssyng do&thorn;e moche more euyl</L>
<L>whan handlyng cum&thorn; of &thorn;e deuyl;</L>
<L>Some wene &thorn;at kyssyng ys no synne,<MILESTONE N="54a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8108">But grete peryl falle&thorn; &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou neuer so chaste and straunge,</L>
<L>kyssyng wyl &thorn;yn hert&euml; chaunge;</L>
<L N="8111">Hyt ys forbode, be &thorn;ou weyl ware,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf hyt be here, &thorn;at fur&thorn;e &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fur&thorn;.</NOTE> bare;</L>
<L>&THORN;y wyf&euml; &thorn;ou mayst kysse with ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt yn sum poynt mayst &thorn;ou falle yn ply&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Seynt Ierom, he speke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">spek&thorn; <I>O</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="8116">Ouer moche for to daunte and kysse;</L>
<L>Daunte a womman oute of skylle,</L>
<L>when no tyme were, she wyl &thorn;er-tyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maner &thorn;er ys of foule kyssyng,</L>
<L N="8120">As ys of dede and of handlyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at falle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fal&thorn;.</NOTE> ofte yn pryuyte,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at shal nat be tolde for me;</L>
<L N="8123">No&thorn;eles, hyt mote be tolde</L>
<L>Yn shryft&euml;, bo&thorn;e with &yogh;unge and olde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sum maner kyssyng ys ful grete vyce,</L>
<L>And wommens hertys to s&ymacr;nne wyl tyse;</L>
<L>And who so delyte&thorn; hym &thorn;er-ynne,</L>
<L N="8128">wommen to foly for<NOTE PLACE="foot">so.</NOTE> to wynne,</L>
<L>Y do hym weyl to vndyrstande,
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>So may he go yn deuyl hande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt mayst &thorn;ou synne yn lecherye</L>
<L N="8132">Yn &thorn;e lokyng of &thorn;yn y&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot">eye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beholde nat wymmen ouer mochyl;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mykyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here sy&yogh;te make&thorn; mennys &thorn;oghtes fykyl;</L>
<L>And who-so ha&thorn; a feble herte,</L>
<L N="8136">hys ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">eye.</NOTE> ys euer ouerthuerte.</L>
<L>&THORN;yn ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">eye.</NOTE> ys &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> messager</L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;y ded&euml; yn powere;</L>
<L>Yn swych&euml; sy&yogh;t ys moch&euml; gylte;</L>
<L N="8140">Shryue &thorn;e &thorn;erof &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wylt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yr.</NOTE> more of lecherye</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys do with sorsorye,</L>
<L>Sorsorye &thorn;at ys wycch&euml;crafte;</L>
<L N="8144">He &thorn;at ys with &thorn;e fend&euml; lafte</L>
<L>Grete synne hyt ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt ys O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> y &yogh;eue &thorn;e a &yogh;yfte;<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;enk &thorn;er-on yn &thorn;y shryfte.</L>
<L>To man &thorn;at ys yn gode beleue,</L>
<L N="8148">wycchecrafte shal hym neuer greue;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou yn gode lyfe, and byleue ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e wecches<NOTE PLACE="foot">wycches.</NOTE> wy&thorn; alle here my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Shul neuer drecche &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> where-so &thorn;ou art</L>
<L N="8152">with no queyntys&euml; of here artt:</L>
<L>&THORN;at shewe&thorn; weyl seynt Cypryene,</L>
<L>he was a nygromancyene,</L>
<L N="8155">how he my&yogh;t neuer a mayden wynne</L>
<L>with wycch&euml;crafte here &thorn;oghte to synne:</L>
<L>why? For here lyfe was gode and clene,</L>
<L>And stedfaste byleue yn here was sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of St. Justyne, and how the Sign of the Cross protected her from Devils.]</HEAD>
<L>Yn Antyoche, &thorn;at noble cyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8160">wonede &thorn;ys mayden of grete bounte;</L>
<L>here name men call&euml; seynt Iustyne,</L>
<L>For Ihesu Cryst she suffred pyne.
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>whan she had tak&euml; crystendam</L>
<L N="8164">Euery day to scole she nam,<NOTE PLACE="inter">&yogh;ede</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e scol&euml;, for to lere</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue of God, and haue hyt dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as she went to &thorn;e scole hous,</L>
<L N="8168">A lorde &thorn;at hyghte 'Agladyus'&mdash;</L>
<L>A gret&euml; mayster and a syre&mdash;</L>
<L>was a-namourd so on hyre</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wyst what do he my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8172">She was so sem&euml;ly by sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He com&euml; vn-to Cypryene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys clerk, &thorn;ys nygromancyene,</L>
<L>And tolde hym al &thorn;e enchesun</L>
<L N="8176">Of hys grete temptacyun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fast he preyde, and hette hym mede</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at he coud&euml; do sum dede,</L>
<L>were hyt <SUP>1</SUP>god&euml;, were hyt ylle,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 wy&thorn; gode, were hyt wy&thorn; yl.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8180">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t haue of here hys wylle.</L>
<L>"Iustyne," he seyd &thorn;an, "hatt&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hat.</NOTE> she</L>
<L>&THORN;e feyre mayden &thorn;at marre&thorn; me."</L>
<L>And Cypryene hette hym for of hys<MILESTONE N="54b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8184">&THORN;at &thorn;e mayden shulde be hys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cypryene made &thorn;an hys queyntyse,</L>
<L>And ded &thorn;e fendys many one<NOTE PLACE="foot">manye.</NOTE> vpryse,</L>
<L>And comaunded<NOTE PLACE="foot">comaundede hem.</NOTE> &thorn;at Iustyne were lede</L>
<L>Vn-to syre Agladyous bed.</L>
<L>&THORN;e forme of here fadyr and modyr &thorn;ey nam,<NOTE PLACE="inter">toke</NOTE></L>
<L>And yn here lykenes to Iustyne cam,</L>
<L>And badde, here wyl shuld&euml; be went</L>
<L N="8192">To Agladyous comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iustyne hadde grete wundyr of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>And wy&thorn; &thorn;e croys she gan here blys,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">And &thorn;ey O, &thorn;an &thorn;e H.</NOTE> vanysshed aweye asswy&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="8196">She &thorn;anked God and was ful bly&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ryys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;rys.</NOTE> &thorn;ey come, on &thorn;re manere,</L>
<L>Befor&euml; Iustyne to apere;
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="260"></L>
<L>And here cunseyl was euer &thorn;us</L>
<L N="8200">"we rede &yogh;ow take Agladyus."</L>
<L>At euery tyme &thorn;at &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;us' omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;ey here besoght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e croys was euer yn here &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>And made hyt euer hem betwene,</L>
<L>And alle here cunseyl was no more sene;</L>
<L N="8205">hadde none of hem lenger powere</L>
<L>with here to speke, or come here nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ryys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;rys.</NOTE> ouercom&euml; hadde &thorn;ey bene,</L>
<L N="8208">And &thorn;us &thorn;ey tolde to Cypryene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cypryene hadd&euml; grete ferly,<NOTE PLACE="inter">wundyr</NOTE></L>
<L>And asked 'for whom hyt was, and why</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey ne my&yogh;t&euml; of here spede,</L>
<L N="8212">But euer ouercome awey &thorn;ey &yogh;ede.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an spak to hym a fende of helle,</L>
<L>"Syker me here with me to dwelle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne shalt, for loue ne eye,</L>
<L N="8216">Beleue on &thorn;at y shal &thorn;e seye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan he hadde seyde hym hys certeynte,</L>
<L>"Now," seyd &thorn;e fende, "y shal telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L>She beleue&thorn; on one men calle Ihesus,</L>
<L N="8220">He &thorn;at confounde&thorn; euermore vs;</L>
<L>She ouercome&thorn; vs with a croys;<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>when we se hyt, we haue no voys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sygne &thorn;erof euer we fle,</L>
<L N="8224">And drede we haue when we hyt se;</L>
<L>Oure my&yogh;t ys noght, no neuer shal,</L>
<L>Ouer any &thorn;at blesse&thorn; hym with-al.</L>
<L>Iustyne &thorn;erwy&thorn; defende&thorn; here so</L>
<L N="8228">&THORN;at we ne may haue with here to do;</L>
<L>And, for here lyfe ys gode and clene,</L>
<L>Oure maystry may ry&yogh;t no&yogh;t be sene;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf she lyued yn wykkednes,</L>
<L N="8232">&THORN;an my&yogh;te we do to here sum stres."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cypryen seyd vnto &thorn;at fende,</L>
<L>"Ihesus ys nat &thorn;an &yogh;oure frende,
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>Hyt may weyl be hym-self ha&thorn; my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="8236">Syn &yogh;e drede hys croys be syght;</L>
<L>And ys nat &yogh;yt &thorn;e sam&euml; tre,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; &thorn;at tokene more my&yogh;t &thorn;an &yogh;e?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ee," seyde the fend&euml;, "certaynly,</L>
<L N="8240">Ouer vs alle he<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> ha&thorn; maystry;</L>
<L>And euermore so shal be doun</L>
<L>For hyt was hys owne passyoun;</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng &thorn;at man may of hym sey,</L>
<L N="8244">Do&thorn;e oure powere so moche a-weye</L>
<L>As nemne &thorn;at passyun and &thorn;at rode</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shedde on, hys swet&euml; blode;</L>
<L>Heuene and helle &thorn;at passyun douten,</L>
<L N="8248">And creatures all&euml; &thorn;arto louten,</L>
<L>And specyaly 'Ihesus,' &thorn;at name</L>
<L>Ys our shenshyp and oure shame."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>when Cypryen &thorn;ys vndyrstode,</L>
<L N="8252">He forsoke hem, and bycom gode,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e crafte &thorn;at he hadde haunted,</L>
<L>And Crystendome to take he graunted;</L>
<L>He dyd breke his maumetrye,</L>
<L N="8256">And dyd hyt brenne byfore hys ye;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en at &thorn;e bysshope of &thorn;e cyte</L>
<L>He dyd hym crysten man to be,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en he was so stedfast<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8260">Yn &thorn;e beleue, &thorn;urgh &thorn;e holy gast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was ordeyned dekene hye,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en bysshope he was wur&thorn;y;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en made he Iustyne, abbas</L>
<L N="8264">Of alle &thorn;e ladyes, as wur&thorn;y was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swyche grace fel se&thorn;&thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn;en fyl.</NOTE> on hom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bo&thorn;e &thorn;ey suffred martyrdom;</L>
<L>And now<NOTE PLACE="foot">now O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> ys Cypryen with God so herd</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ys wurschypde yn alle &thorn;e werlde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>O</I>. inserts&mdash;</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For yn &thorn;e pryuyte of &thorn;e messe,</L>
<L>Hys nam&euml; euer nemnede ys:&mdash;</L>
</LG></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="262"></L>
<L N="8269">And she ys callede Seynt Iustyne,</L>
<L>A martyr and an holy vyrgyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale y tolde to &yogh;ow aboute,</L>
<L N="8272">&THORN;at &yogh;e ne dur no wycchecrafte doute,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be&mdash;&thorn;at ys to mene&mdash;</L>
<L>Yn beleu&euml; gode, and lyf&euml; clene.</L>
<L>who-so &thorn;urgh wycch&euml;crafte ha&thorn; tene,</L>
<L N="8276">Prey to God and seynt Cypryene</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e mayden Seynt Iustyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey delyuer hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym.</NOTE> fro &thorn;at pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arefore, &thorn;ou man and &thorn;ou wyfe,</L>
<L N="8280">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be of clen&euml; lyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar &thorn;e noght drede no wycch&euml;crafte</L>
<L>No&thorn;er temptyng of &thorn;e deuylys shafte;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou be yn dedly synne,</L>
<L N="8284">To hys temptyng he may &thorn;e wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt &thorn;er ys spekyng of vylaynye</L>
<L>&THORN;at longe&thorn; vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto O, to H.</NOTE> lecherye,</L>
<L>And oft&euml; tyme of foul&euml; speche</L>
<L N="8288">Falle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fal&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;arfor hard[&euml;] wreche;</L>
<L>Of foul&euml; herte cum&thorn; foul&euml; &thorn;o&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Of foul&euml; &thorn;o&yogh;t, foule wurdys are bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e foul&euml; wurde, &thorn;e speker dere&thorn;,</L>
<L N="8292">And &thorn;at hyt here&thorn; and fur&thorn; bere&thorn;;</L>
<L>Y hau&euml; told&euml; of &thorn;ys lak</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e fyf&thorn;e comaundement, &thorn;er y spak,</L>
<L>whan y of a nunn&euml; tolde,</L>
<L N="8296">&THORN;at coud&euml; nat here tung&euml; holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;yr a spyce of leccherye,<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Auaunt&euml;ment of olde folye:</L>
<L>A kaynard and an<NOTE PLACE="foot">an O, a H.</NOTE> old&euml; folte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ryfte ha&thorn; loste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lore.</NOTE> and boghte a bolte,</L>
<L N="8301">he shal become[n] a dyssour,</L>
<L>And telle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle.</NOTE> how he was a lecchour;</L>
<L>Ioye he ha&thorn;, hym-self to dyffame</L>
<L N="8304">Of alle hys synnes &thorn;at he kan name,</L>
<L>And auante hym alle an hye,
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="263"></L>
<L>And make men lagh at hys foly;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ys nat &thorn;e synn&euml; leste,</L>
<L>Auaunte &thorn;y synne to hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou sest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8309">Sodom sank, and Gomore,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey kryed here synne aywhore;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese twey cytees, bo&thorn;e &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;ey' omitted.</NOTE> sank,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey hadde ioye at synne &thorn;at stank.</L>
<L N="8313">Feyrer hyt were, oure synne forhele,</L>
<L>&THORN;an make auauntement &thorn;er-of to fele;</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostle sey&thorn; &thorn;ys autoryte,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be<NOTE PLACE="foot">art.</NOTE> nat chaste, be &thorn;ou pryue;"</L>
<L N="8317">Telle hyt &thorn;y prest, and to no mo;</L>
<L>For o&thorn;er tellyng, ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys O, hyt ys H.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e synne and wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt ys &thorn;yr a specyal spece</L>
<L N="8320">&THORN;at do&thorn; leccherye klymbe by a grece:</L>
<L>who so wyll&euml; &yogh;yft&euml;s &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>On lechery&euml; he may cleue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">clyue.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8323">For synne, no &yogh;yftys &thorn;ou receyue;</L>
<L>For doute of gyle &thorn;ou shalt hem weyue<NOTE PLACE="inter">forsake</NOTE>;</L>
<L>For whan a lechour ha&thorn; &yogh;yue hys mede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hope&thorn; he weyl &thorn;at he shal spede.</L>
<L>Y rede, &yogh;e wommen, &yogh;yue&thorn; gode entent,</L>
<L N="8328">For med&euml; &yogh;e wyl sone consent;</L>
<L>Many one for mede do&thorn; ful euyl,</L>
<L>Men sey ofte 'mede ys &thorn;e deuyl.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt speke&thorn; he of a more tresun</L>
<L N="8332">&THORN;at for lechery ys doun;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf men or womman be so wylde</L>
<L>To fordo a getyng of a chylde</L>
<L>wy&thorn; wurde or dede, syn hyt ys gete,<MILESTONE N="55b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8336">with mete or drynk &thorn;at &thorn;ey do &yogh;ete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey ete.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er strenk&thorn;&euml;, &thorn;at hyt dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ey doun ful grete folye;</L>
<L>with slaghter hast &thorn;ou &thorn;ere hyd,</L>
<L N="8340">&THORN;at &thorn;y lecherye ys nat kyd;</L>
<L>Gretly yn euyl &thorn;ou art coup&aacute;ble</L>
<L>Yn twey synn&euml;s, and dampn&aacute;ble.
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-no&thorn;er vyleynye &thorn;yr ys,</L>
<L N="8344">To do a womman synne &thorn;urgh stres:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf a womman mete par&aacute;uenture</L>
<L>Yn pryu&euml; sted&euml;, a lechour,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he wyl do with here synne,</L>
<L N="8348">And she ne may a-wey&euml; wynne</L>
<L>But she swer&euml; o&thorn;ys grym</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er tyme to come to hym,</L>
<L>Or he make&thorn; here trouth-plyght</L>
<L N="8352">Ano&thorn;er tym&euml; when she my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at trou&thorn;&euml;, y answere</L>
<L>&THORN;at no perel shal she bere;</L>
<L>She nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> synne&thorn; nat dedly,</L>
<L N="8356">Hyt ys n&oacute; wyl, but maystry;</L>
<L>Better ys to skape with an o&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;an synne dedly, and God be wrothe.</L>
<L>Here-of my&yogh;t men moch&euml; speke,</L>
<L N="8360">Of trou&thorn;&euml; &thorn;at men alle day breke,</L>
<L>For, fals trou&thorn;&euml;s, and fykyl,</L>
<L>For lechery, are &yogh;yue mechyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou a womman trou&thorn;&euml; plyght</L>
<L N="8364">Out of holy cherch&euml;s sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Men oght nat so for to do</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at frendes consente &thorn;arto;</L>
<L>For holy cherche oght fyrst for to wyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8368">Of here gederyng, &yogh;yf hyt may sytte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of all&euml; fol&euml;s are &thorn;ey fyles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gentyl wymmen begylys</L>
<L>with a trou&thorn;&euml; of tresun</L>
<L N="8372">To reu&euml; here, here warysun,</L>
<L>But she do by here ordynaunce<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at shuld&euml; here auaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a womman loue&thorn; ofte yn pryuyte</L>
<L N="8376">&THORN;at for here falle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fal&thorn;.</NOTE> nat weyl to be;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf she to &thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf&thorn;.</NOTE> here treu&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys to.</NOTE> here ful moch&euml; reu&thorn;e;
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>&THORN;at trew&thorn;e dar she nat be a-knowe,</L>
<L N="8380">For drede &thorn;at she ha&thorn; loued so lowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh cunseyl of here frendys wylle,</L>
<L>She ys &thorn;an &yogh;yue a-no&thorn;er vntyl;</L>
<L>Y dar sey hyt hardyly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hardyly O, hardly H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8384">'&THORN;at womman leue&thorn; yn lechery;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ych&euml; man also</L>
<L>To whom she &yogh;af fyrst trou&thorn;&euml; to,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he any ou&thorn;er wedde,</L>
<L N="8388">Or with any go to bedde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey bo&thorn;e wulde haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha.</NOTE> do &thorn;at</L>
<L>&THORN;at here mou&thorn;es to-gedyr spak,</L>
<L>And haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha.</NOTE> fulfylled, at here my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8392">Here pryue trou&thorn;&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ey ply&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A wers[&euml;] spyc&euml; &yogh;yt men holdes,</L>
<L>To begyle a womman with wordys;</L>
<L>To &yogh;yue here trou&thorn;&euml; but lyghtly</L>
<L N="8396">For no &thorn;yng but for lygge here by;</L>
<L>with &thorn;at gyle &thorn;ou makest here asent,</L>
<L>And bryngest &yogh;ow bo&thorn;e to cumbrement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore now y warne &yogh;ow alle,</L>
<L N="8400">Man and woman, for &thorn;yng may falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e be neuer so fole-hardy</L>
<L>To &yogh;yue &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">trou&thorn;e O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> so pryuyly,</L>
<L>Ne wommans trou&thorn;&euml; for to take,</L>
<L N="8404">Ne trou&thorn;&euml; &yogh;yue for weddyng sake,</L>
<L>Tyl holy cherche haue demyd ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>wy&thorn; lokyng of frendes syght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pryuytes manye falle &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">her.</NOTE>-ynne;</L>
<L N="8408">&THORN;yn ynwyt &thorn;e telle&thorn; whych ys synne;</L>
<L>Sum pryuytes of lechery</L>
<L>Yn opun speche are vyleynye;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor wyl y nat hem alle descryue,<MILESTONE N="56a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8412">But alle behoue&thorn; vs &thorn;er-of shryue;
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>&THORN;yn ynwyt wote what &thorn;ou hast wroght,</L>
<L>And whych ys synne, and whych ys no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese spyces &thorn;at y haue tolde,</L>
<L N="8416">On dyuers maners are synn&euml;s folde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;y flessh&euml; ofte aryse</L>
<L>Yn wyl or dede to many of &thorn;yse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayst nat &thorn;y flessh&euml; daunte,</L>
<L N="8420">&THORN;at sum algate behoue&thorn; &thorn;e haunte,</L>
<L>Be nat &thorn;arfor yn wanhope;</L>
<L>Alle may be quenchyde with a drope,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou mayst for &thorn;y synn&euml; grete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'wepe.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="8424">And be yn wyl hyt for to lete.</L>
<L>For many a gode man, olde and &yogh;onge,</L>
<L>ha&thorn; be yn flessh&euml;ly temptyng;</L>
<L N="8427">So was seynt Poule, &thorn;e holy man,</L>
<L>Hys flesshe was temptyde with Satan;</L>
<L>Seynt Benet was so, &yogh;e herde me telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">p. 238.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was yn poynt to leue hys celle;</L>
<L>And ou&thorn;er men mo of relygyun</L>
<L N="8432">Haue be yn hard temptacyun;</L>
<L>But man behoue&thorn; pryue<NOTE PLACE="foot">preue.</NOTE> hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens hys own&euml; flesshe to fy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou late hyt haue hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> wyl,</L>
<L N="8436">wyltou, neltou,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyltou.</NOTE> hyt wyl &thorn;e spylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And y shal telle here, &yogh;yf &yogh;e wyl,</L>
<L>A tal&euml; for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys.</NOTE> sam&euml; skylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">skyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at a man myshop&euml; noght</L>
<L N="8440">&THORN;ogh he haue grete temptyng of &thorn;oght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the tempted Hermit, or How we should never Despair.]</HEAD>
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn;, for oure profyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>How &thorn;yr was onys an ermyte:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ermyte had grete temptyng</L>
<L N="8444">yn hys &thorn;oght, ouer alle &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ys temptyng on hym ran,
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>He &yogh;ede vnto an old&euml; man</L>
<L>And tolde hym all&euml;, vp an downe,</L>
<L N="8448">Of hys grete temptacyun.</L>
<L>&THORN;at olde man seyd to hym astyte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O.</I> gloss 'anoun.'</NOTE><MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'He was nat wur&thorn;y to be an Ermyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych&euml; &thorn;oght&euml;s shuld&euml; &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oght of womman wulde hym synke.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8453">&THORN;ys old&euml; man gan hym so stoute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys gode hope was alle yn doute;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wurdes &thorn;at &thorn;e olde man gan seye,</L>
<L N="8456">Yn-to &thorn;e wurlde he toke &thorn;e weye.</L>
<L>As he cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">com.</NOTE> goyng yn &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>An holy abbot gan he mete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbotys name was Apollo,</L>
<L N="8460">And sone he spake &thorn;e ermyte to;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ermyte hadde so sory &thorn;oght,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en to &thorn;e abbote spake he noght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys abbot was a ful wys man,</L>
<L N="8464">And yn hys &thorn;o&yogh;t ful sone hyt ran,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e semlant of &thorn;e ermyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was yn grete sorowe and syte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot asked hym ones or twyys;</L>
<L N="8468">At &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">At &thorn;e H, At O.</NOTE> laste &thorn;e ermyte seyd hys auys.</L>
<L>"Y am," he seyd, "bro&yogh;t all&euml; down</L>
<L>with flesshly temptacyun;</L>
<L>And at an old&euml; man y was,</L>
<L N="8472">And tolde hym alle my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn.</NOTE> hard&euml; kas;</L>
<L>And he seyd, y was nat wur&thorn;y,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ermytag&euml; to com ny,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nyghe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne was yn wey me to saue,</L>
<L N="8476">whyl y shulde swych &thorn;o&yogh;t&euml;s haue;</L>
<L>And, for he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O., H. <I>om</I>.</NOTE> comforted me so yl,</L>
<L>Yn-to &thorn;e worlde now ys my wyl,
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>And lyue &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> best wyse &thorn;at y may,</L>
<L N="8480">Syn y serue nat God to pay."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyde &thorn;e abbot syre Apollo,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e olde man wyst nat what was to do;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst se now, by my vysage,</L>
<L N="8484">&THORN;at y am olde, and weyl yn age,</L>
<L>And y fele a ful hard prykyl</L>
<L>&THORN;at my flesshe tempte&thorn; me mykyl,</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;&euml; ys hyt day ne oure<MILESTONE N="56b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y ne am &thorn;ar-with tempted soure;</L>
<L N="8489">But &thorn;ogh my &thorn;oght be oute of skyl,</L>
<L>To do &yogh;yt wers[&euml;], y ne wyl;</L>
<L>Ne more<NOTE PLACE="foot">No more.</NOTE> shalt &thorn;ou &thorn;y self mysdo,</L>
<L N="8492">&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou be tempted neuer so.</L>
<L>Y rede, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;at' omitted.</NOTE> yn godenes &thorn;at &thorn;ou dwelle,</L>
<L>And turne a&yogh;en vnto &thorn;y celle,</L>
<L>And fonde a&yogh;ens &thorn;y flesshe to fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8496">And late hyt nat haue alle &thorn;e my&yogh;t."</L>
<L>He bro&yogh;te &thorn;ys ermyte to swyche certeyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to hys celle he turned a&yogh;eyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e abbot knew [wel] alle &thorn;e pas</L>
<L N="8500">where &thorn;e olde man wonyng was;</L>
<L>&THORN;edyrwarde &thorn;e wey he nam.</L>
<L>And when he a lytyl besyd&euml; cam,</L>
<L>He sette hym dowun, and preyd Ihesu</L>
<L N="8504">Ful of my&yogh;t and [of] vertu,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e olde man my&yogh;t fele sum &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ermytes flesshely temptyng,</L>
<L>To chastyse hym for hys bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="8508">&THORN;at he myscumfort eft noun o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>when he hadde leye yn orysun</L>
<L>long with grete deuocyun,</L>
<L>He ros vp, and byhelde,</L>
<L>And sagh a blak man stonde yn &thorn;e felde,</L>
<L N="8513">And to &thorn;e olde man arwes<NOTE PLACE="foot">arewes.</NOTE> ded shete
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t many, and sum wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful.</NOTE> grete.</L>
<L>So many arwes<NOTE PLACE="foot">arewes.</NOTE> to hym he drogh,</L>
<L N="8516">&THORN;at &thorn;e olde man felt temptyng ynogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;e arwes were temptacyons,</L>
<L>And sharp&euml; sterynges, and felons;</L>
<L>So many and smart, he hem hadde,</L>
<L N="8520">&THORN;at he sate as he hadde be madde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wytte hadde lor&euml;, as he sat,</L>
<L>Or was yn a were<NOTE PLACE="foot">wer.</NOTE> to do sum-what.</L>
<L>Ar he aght seyd, ar dyd any dede,</L>
<L N="8524">&THORN;e same weye &thorn;at &thorn;e ermyte &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche wey &thorn;e ermyte &yogh;ede ynne<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e worlde, to do hys synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e abbot Appollo say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe.</NOTE> euerydeyl;</L>
<L N="8528">And how he was temptede, he wyst hyt weyl,</L>
<L>And fonded for to take &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>with &thorn;at olde man for to mete:</L>
<L>he seyd, "olde man! what dost &thorn;ou here,</L>
<L N="8532">And why hast &thorn;ou so mornyng chere?</L>
<L>whydyr hast &thorn;ou &thorn;oght to go?</L>
<L>Be<NOTE PLACE="foot">By.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t hyt seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e were wo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e old&euml; man seyd ry&yogh;t no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8536">But hyt ran hym weyl yn &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e abbot had<NOTE PLACE="foot">had O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> inspyracyun,</L>
<L>And wyst hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> grete temptacyun;</L>
<L>For shame he my&yogh;t nat telle how smart<NOTE PLACE="foot">smert.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8540">&THORN;e temptyng &thorn;at come to hys hert;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e abbot wyst for certeyn,</L>
<L>And bad<NOTE PLACE="foot">bade O, had H.</NOTE> hym to turne a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>And shewed hym weyl for two &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L N="8544">why &thorn;at he hadde no temptynges;</L>
<L>He seyd, '&thorn;e fende of hym ne ro&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ne hym to tempte about&euml; so&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;oght hys lyfe so moche wur&thorn;y,
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="270"></L>
<L N="8548">For he helde hym self so holy,</L>
<L>And blamed o&thorn;er for here fallyng,'</L>
<L>"&THORN;y lyfe hym &thorn;ynke&thorn; ys wur&thorn; no &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>To gode men ys hyt grete passyun</L>
<L N="8552">To fele &thorn;e fendes temptacyun;</L>
<L>And for he tempted<NOTE PLACE="foot">tempte&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;e no&yogh;t here,</L>
<L>Yn ou&thorn;er stede &thorn;ou shalt by<NOTE PLACE="foot">bye.</NOTE> hyt dere;</L>
<L>Ne late &thorn;ou nat ly&yogh;tly by &thorn;o</L>
<L N="8556">&THORN;at are tempted of flesshly wo,</L>
<L>But, &thorn;enk weyl &thorn;at &thorn;ey are gode,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey &thorn;at temptyng with-stode,</L>
<L N="8559">And are sykerer aftyr temptynges,</L>
<L>And kepe hem better with many &thorn;ynges;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yt O, hyt H.</NOTE> men sey God loue&thorn; hem no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haue no temptyng yn dede ne &thorn;oght.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys temptyng was for &thorn;y despyte<MILESTONE N="57a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8564">&THORN;at &thorn;ou haddest of &thorn;e gode ermyte</L>
<L>whan he hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> temptyng to &thorn;e shrofe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y cumforte awey hym drofe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At &thorn;ys pas<NOTE PLACE="foot">'p' erased.</NOTE> &thorn;ys tale tolde ys</L>
<L N="8568">For temptacyons<NOTE PLACE="foot">temptacyun.</NOTE> of mannys flesshe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none ne myscumforte hym</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at hys flesshe be brysl and brym.</L>
<L N="8571">So holy man was neuer none</L>
<L>&THORN;at temptacyun ne hat<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn;.</NOTE> hym ouergone,</L>
<L>were hyt lytyl, or were hyt mykyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hys flesshe ne ha&thorn; hadde sum prykyl;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at wyl be ry&yogh;t certeyne,</L>
<L N="8576">Cumforte hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem O, hym H.</NOTE> weyl to fy&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>For no man may yn certeyn be,</L>
<L>But he fy&yogh;t flesshly lustys<NOTE PLACE="foot">lust.</NOTE> to fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God graunte vs all&euml; now fro he&thorn;en</L>
<L N="8580">Oure flessh&euml; so to holde be-ne&thorn;en,<NOTE PLACE="foot">byne&thorn;en.</NOTE></L>
<L>And oure soules so to save<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God of heuene vs all&euml; loue.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sin"><PB REF="00000279.tif" N="271">
<HEAD>Here bygynne&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bygyn&thorn;.</NOTE> Sacrylage.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8583">Of &thorn;ese dedly synn&euml;s seuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we wra&thorn;&thorn;e with, God of heuene,</L>
<L>Of hem haue we touched neyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">nede.</NOTE></L>
<L>As holy men haue wryten and seyd;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt mow[&euml;] we n&aacute;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl nat.</NOTE> weyl werche</L>
<L N="8588">&YOGH;yf we forget&euml; holy cherche,</L>
<L>holy cherche, our modyr dere,</L>
<L>Of here shul we telle &yogh;ow here,</L>
<L>How men synne, and on what wyse,</L>
<L N="8592">A&yogh;ens &thorn;at falle&thorn; to here fraunchyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at a&yogh;ens here fraunchyse falles,</L>
<L>'Sacryleg&euml;' men hyt calles;</L>
<L>'Sacryleg&euml;,' frenche hyt ys,</L>
<L N="8596">Menyng of 'mysdede' or 'mys.'</L>
<L>'Mysded&euml; to holynes,'</L>
<L>'Sacrylege' on Englysshe ys;</L>
<L>All&euml; &thorn;yng &thorn;at men with-holde,<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8600">Stole or reft&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">reft.</NOTE> &yogh;yue or solde,</L>
<L>with-out&euml; leue of here wytyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kep&euml; holy cherches &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Alle swych &thorn;yng ys sacrylege,</L>
<L N="8604">with-out&euml; leue ys alle outrage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;e fyrst &thorn;at we haue spoke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;at hau&euml; cherches broke,</L>
<L>And stole &thorn;o &thorn;ynges &thorn;at were &thorn;er-ynne,</L>
<L N="8608">'Sacrylage' men calle &thorn;at synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;yng vnhalewed were forgete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn holy cherche were lete,</L>
<L>Or halewed &thorn;yng yn ou&thorn;er stede lay,</L>
<L N="8612">And oght &thorn;erof were bore away,</L>
<L>where<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whe&thorn;er.</NOTE> hyt wer&euml; &yogh;yue or solde,</L>
<L>For sacrylege, alle ys hyt tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many vyces &thorn;erto<NOTE PLACE="foot">her to.</NOTE> longe;</L>
<L>Alle are &thorn;ey synne, but sum are stronge;</L>
<L N="8617">y shal &yogh;ow telle of<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> sum maners
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>As 'manuel pecch&eacute;s' me lers.<NOTE PLACE="foot">manuele pecche . . leres.</NOTE></L>
<L>But, vnkynde and enuyous,</L>
<L N="8620">Ouerdo, proud, and daungerous,</L>
<L>Euermor&euml; fynde &thorn;ey teyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh a man sey neuer so weyl;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles, so weyl y nat seyd,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at to my sawe, blame may be leyd</L>
<L N="8625">For foule englyssh, and feble ryme</L>
<L>Seyde oute of resun many tyme;</L>
<L>But God &yogh;elde hem at here endyng,</L>
<L N="8628">&THORN;at wyl amende myn vnkunnyng;</L>
<L>But who so blame&thorn; and wyl nat amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mende.</NOTE></L>
<L>He do&thorn;e nat as &thorn;e curteys kende.</L>
<L>Go we fur&thorn;e now<NOTE PLACE="foot">now fur&thorn;.</NOTE> on oure werk:&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8632">&YOGH;yf a man yn euyl smyte a clerk,</L>
<L>Yn sacrylage he falle&thorn; ylle</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he dyde hyt by hys wylle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he be man of relygyoun,</L>
<L N="8636">&THORN;ou art to blame with more resun;</L>
<L>Twey skyles are ful perylous,<MILESTONE N="57b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e ordred and relygyous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also relygyous are<NOTE PLACE="foot">men are.</NOTE> to wyte,</L>
<L N="8640">&THORN;at for maystry wyl gladly smyte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghte.</NOTE> to be suffr&aacute;ble and meke,</L>
<L>And no foly on ou&thorn;er men seke;</L>
<L>Hys tung shuld be hys fauchoun;</L>
<L N="8644">Hys strokes shulde be hys orysun;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any be yn foly stoute,</L>
<L>Holde yn cloystre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Holde hym yn cloustre.</NOTE> and com nat out.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also may he be sore a-ferde</L>
<L N="8648">&THORN;at do&thorn; vyleynye yn chyrche &yogh;erde,</L>
<L>Namly, syn hyt halewed was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e more he do&thorn;&euml; of trespas.</L>
<L>Vnkynde man ys he hardly<NOTE PLACE="foot">hardyly.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8652">&THORN;at yn cherche &yogh;erde<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherche &yogh;erde O, cher&yogh;erde H.</NOTE> do&thorn; vyleyny;
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="273"></L>
<L>Oure long hous hyt ys to come,</L>
<L>To reste yn, tyl &thorn;e day of dome.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore we shuld, &yogh;yf we were kynde,</L>
<L N="8656">kepe hyt clene with god&euml; mynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ese prestes me &thorn;ynke&thorn; do synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at late here bestys fyle &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gres ys hys &thorn;at &thorn;er&euml; grenes,</L>
<L N="8660">&THORN;e plac&euml; ys &thorn;e parysshenes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But lord&euml;s &thorn;at haue seynorye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey do &thorn;eryn most vyleynye;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">here.</NOTE> hope ys, whan &thorn;ey shul deye,</L>
<L N="8664">&THORN;at yn &thorn;e cherche men shul hem leye;</L>
<L>And y shal telle a lytyl wy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>how a bonde man bourded with a kny&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="8667">And &thorn;e borde ys gode to here,</L>
<L>who-so loue&thorn; wurdes to lere.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Reproof that a Norfolk Bondman gave a Knight for not respecting the Sanctity of a Churchyard.]</HEAD>
<L>Yn Northfolk, yn a tounne,</L>
<L>wonede a kny&yogh;t besyde a persone;</L>
<L>Fyl hyt so, &thorn;e kny&yogh;tes manere</L>
<L N="8672">was nat fro &thorn;e cherche ful fere;</L>
<L>And was hyt &thorn;an, as oftyn falles,</L>
<L>Brok&euml; were &thorn;e cherche-&yogh;erde walles.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8675">&THORN;e lord&euml;s hyrd&euml;s often lete<MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hys bestys yn-to &thorn;e cherche<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherche <I>om</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;erde &amp; ete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bestys dyd as &thorn;ey mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">moste.</NOTE> nede,</L>
<L>Fyled oueral &thorn;ere &thorn;ey &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>A bond man say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe.</NOTE> &thorn;at, and was wo</L>
<L N="8680">&THORN;at &thorn;e bestys shuld &thorn;ere go;</L>
<L>He com to &thorn;e lorde, and seyd hym &thorn;ys:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Lorde," he seyde, "&yogh;oure bestys go mys;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure hyrde do&thorn; wrong, and &yogh;our&euml; knauys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at late &yogh;oure bestys fyle &thorn;us &thorn;ese grauys;</L>
<L N="8685">&THORN;ere mennys bonys shuld&euml; lye,</L>
<L>Best&euml;s shuld do no vyleynye."
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lordes answere was sumwhat vyle,</L>
<L N="8688">And &thorn;at falle&thorn; euyl to a man gentyle;</L>
<L>"weyl were hyt do ry&yogh;t for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>To wurschy&thorn; swych[&euml;] cherl&euml;s bones;</L>
<L>what wurschyp shuld men make</L>
<L N="8692">Aboute swych cherl&euml;s bodyes blake?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e bonde man answer&euml;d and seyd</L>
<L>wurdys to-gedyr ful weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful weyl to-gedyr.</NOTE> leyd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e lorde &thorn;at made of er&thorn;&euml;, erles,</L>
<L N="8696">Of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> same er&thorn;e made he cherles;</L>
<L>Erl&euml;s my&yogh;t, and lord&euml;s stut,</L>
<L>As cherl&euml;s shal yn er&thorn;e be put;</L>
<L N="8699">Erl&euml;s, cherl&euml;s, alle at ones,</L>
<L>Shal none knowe &yogh;oure, fro oure, bones."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lorde lestened &thorn;e wurd&euml;s weyl</L>
<L>And recorded hem euery deyl;</L>
<L>No mor&euml; to hym wulde he seye,</L>
<L N="8704">But, lete hym go fur&thorn;e hys weye;</L>
<L>He seyd &thorn;e bestys shulde no more,</L>
<L>By hys wyl, com&euml; &thorn;ore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syll. line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;en he closed &thorn;e cherche&yogh;erde so</L>
<L N="8708">&THORN;at no best my&yogh;t come &thorn;arto</L>
<L>For to ete, ne fyle &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>So &thorn;o&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ught.</NOTE> hym se&thorn;en, &thorn;at hyt was synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yr are but few&euml; lord&euml;s now</L>
<L N="8712">&THORN;at turne a wrde so wel to prow;</L>
<L>But, who<NOTE PLACE="foot">who so.</NOTE> sey&thorn; hem any skylle,<MILESTONE N="58a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mysseye a&yogh;en, fouly &thorn;ey wylle.</L>
<L>Lordynges,&mdash;&thorn;yr are ynow of &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="8716">Of gentyl men, &thorn;yr are but fo.<NOTE PLACE="inter">fewe</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt ys defended yn &thorn;e decre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none yn cherche shal beryed be,</L>
<L>But bysshope, or abbot of relygyun,</L>
<L N="8720">Or prest &thorn;at ys of gode renoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A man &thorn;at ha&thorn; no gode fame ryfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">ryffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of dede, of hew, of holy lyfe,</L>
<L>Of gode fey&thorn;, ne of charyte
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="275"></L>
<L N="8724">Yn almes dede, ne of ou&thorn;er bounte,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; hyt were ful perylous</L>
<L>To berye swych one yn Goddes house;</L>
<L>with swych ys holy cherche but fyled,</L>
<L N="8728">And hem self are moste bygyled.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;e soul&euml; be nat wur&thorn;y</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e body lygge so solempny,<NOTE PLACE="foot">solemply.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an ha&thorn; &thorn;e soul&euml; mor&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">more of.</NOTE> peyne;</L>
<L N="8732">&THORN;at men wurschyp &thorn;e body, ys veyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wykked men and vserers,</L>
<L>lechours, and lordys of foule maners,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mow &yogh;yue pens ful god&euml; wone,</L>
<L N="8736">&THORN;ey shul be leyde yn toumbe of stone,</L>
<L>And hys ym&aacute;ge ful feyre depeynte,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as h&eacute; were a cors seynt;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrecched soule, &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seye,</L>
<L N="8740">Shal a-bye alle &thorn;e noblye,</L>
<L>And sum for euer be bro&yogh;t to bale;<NOTE PLACE="inter">sorow</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erby wyl y telle a tale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Valentine, and how Devils puld his Body out of its Grave in the Church.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a man &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;at' omitted.</NOTE> hyght Valentyne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>Playtour he was, and ryche man fyne,</L>
<L N="8745">For of &thorn;e cherche of Myleyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">mylon.</NOTE> was he playtour,</L>
<L>More for mede &thorn;an Goddes onour.</L>
<L>Besyde Gen&euml;, a noble cyt&euml;,</L>
<L>Deyde Valentyne, and beryed shuld be;</L>
<L>Yn seynt Syxtes cherch&euml; shuld he lye;</L>
<L N="8750">So ordeyned men whan he shuld deye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrste ny&yogh;t &thorn;at he was &thorn;ere leyde,<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wardeynes of &thorn;e cherche vpbreyde,</L>
<L>And herd one cry, rewly and shyl,
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>As he were put oute a&yogh;ens hys wyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wardeynes asked what &thorn;at my&yogh;t be,</L>
<L N="8756">"Ryse we vp<NOTE PLACE="foot">vp we.</NOTE> alle, and go we se."</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he was beryed, &thorn;ydyr &thorn;ey ran,</L>
<L>And sagh many fendes aboute &thorn;ys man;</L>
<L>And of hys graue &thorn;ey oute<NOTE PLACE="foot">vp.</NOTE> hym pulde;</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;e cherche, drawe hym &thorn;ey wulde;</L>
<L N="8761">&THORN;e deuylys dro&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">drowe.</NOTE> hym by &thorn;e fete</L>
<L>As hyt were careyne &thorn;at dogges ete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wardeynes wer&euml; sore affryght</L>
<L N="8764">For &thorn;at noys&euml; and &thorn;at syght;</L>
<L>A&yogh;en to here bedde &thorn;ey &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey durst no lenger dwelle for drede.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morne whan &thorn;ey were ryse,</L>
<L N="8768">&THORN;ey &yogh;ede to &thorn;e graue, &thorn;ere &thorn;ey were so agryse;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-yn alle aboute &thorn;ey soght,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e body founde &thorn;ey no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey opende &thorn;e dores, and loked aboute,</L>
<L>And fonde &thorn;e body lygge<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyggynge.</NOTE> &thorn;ere with-oute;</L>
<L N="8773">&THORN;e fete ybounde to-gedyr ful faste,</L>
<L>And as a foul&euml; careyne caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Gregory sey&thorn; hardly,</L>
<L N="8776">&THORN;ere he lay fyrst, he was nat wur&thorn;y;</L>
<L>But hys soule hadde pyne &thorn;e more</L>
<L>For &thorn;e pompe and pryde &thorn;at he was leyd &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>lordes are besy aboute to haue</L>
<L N="8780">Proude stones lyggyng an hye on here graue;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;at pryde &thorn;ey mowe be lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ey hadde do no synne byfore;</L>
<L N="8783">Hyt helpy&thorn; ry&yogh;t noght, &thorn;e toumbe of pryde,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e soule fro pyne may hyt nat hyde.
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer vsedest halewed &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And wystyst hyt fyl to cherches offryng,</L>
<L>Hyt ys grete synne, y do &thorn;e to knowne,</L>
<L N="8788">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou helde hyt as for &thorn;yn owne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wy&thorn;helde any &thorn;yng se&thorn;yn<MILESTONE N="58b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt was to holy cherche &yogh;euyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yuen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8791">&THORN;yn or ou&thorn;res, with-out&euml; leue</L>
<L>Of parsone, or prest, or cherch&euml; reue;</L>
<L>Hyt ys sacrylage, y &thorn;e ply&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To wy&thorn;holde &thorn;at falle&thorn; to cherch&euml; ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8795">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou dedyst euer &thorn;at vnlawe,</L>
<L>A man oute of holy cherche to drawe</L>
<L>Se&thorn;en &thorn;at he toke hym &thorn;ar-tyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast synned yn moche vnskyl.</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he hadde do a&yogh;ens &thorn;e assyse</L>
<L N="8800">&THORN;at fyl to holy cherches fraunchyse,</L>
<L>Slayn one &thorn;ar-ynne, or robbed hyt,</L>
<L>Hyt shulde nat &thorn;an saue hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">saue hym &thorn;an.</NOTE> by my wyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lewed man, holy cherche wyl forbede</L>
<L>To stounde yn &thorn;e chaunsel whyl men rede:</L>
<L N="8805">who-so-euer &thorn;arto ys custummer,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he be of grete powere,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e he synne&thorn; and do&thorn;e greuaunce</L>
<L N="8808">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e clergy ordynaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &yogh;yt do wymmen gretter folye</L>
<L>&THORN;at vse to stonde among &thorn;e clergye,</L>
<L><SUP>3</SUP>O&thorn;er at matyns, or at messe,</L>
<L N="8812">But &yogh;yf hyt were yn cas of stresse;<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 Omitted in <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;erof may come temptacyun,</L>
<L>And dysturblyng of deuocyun;</L>
<L>For foule &thorn;oght cum&thorn; of feble ye-sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8816">And fordo&thorn;&euml; grace with ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And with a tale hyt may be shewed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys gode bo&thorn;e for lered and lewed.
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Temptation of St. John Chrysostom's Deacon.]</HEAD>
<L>An holy man telle&thorn; vs &thorn;us,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L N="8820">Men calle hym Ion Crysostomus;</L>
<L>He was a bysshope, and ful gode clerk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shewe hys bok&euml;s of hys werk;</L>
<L>Swych grace of God, grauntede hym was,</L>
<L N="8824">At euery tyme &thorn;at he song hys masse</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy goste to hym was sent</L>
<L>whan he shulde receyue &thorn;e sacrament;</L>
<L>Certeynly, aftyr &thorn;e sacr&euml;,</L>
<L N="8828">Yn a dowue lyknes he my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">myghte hyt se.</NOTE> se,</L>
<L>So whyte and<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> so blesful, and so clere,<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan he vsed vpp-on &thorn;e autere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;at cumfort, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and of.</NOTE> &thorn;at sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8832">He &thorn;anked oft&euml; God almy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&euml; hadde &thorn;arwith enuye,</L>
<L>And wulde shewe hys wykked maystry.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A day seynt Ion shulde synge hys messe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende made hym yn womman lyknesse,</L>
<L N="8837">weyl atyrede, with moch&euml; pryde,</L>
<L>And stod&euml; ou&thorn;er men besyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e dekene &thorn;at serued seynt Ion,</L>
<L N="8840">At here turnyng tymes echon</L>
<L>He behelde &thorn;ys womman weyl,</L>
<L>And hys herte chaunged euery deyl;</L>
<L>Temptacyun of &thorn;ys womman,</L>
<L N="8844">Ouer al yn hys &thorn;o&yogh;t hyt ran.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bysshope, aftyr &thorn;e sacr&euml;,</L>
<L>Shulde receyue God, as byfyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyl.</NOTE> to be;</L>
<L>As he stode and heylde<NOTE PLACE="foot">helde.</NOTE> &thorn;e oste,</L>
<L N="8848">He loked vp aftyr &thorn;e holy goste;</L>
<L>But &thorn;at tyme ne come hyt no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Seynt Ion hadde &thorn;arfor<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arfore hade.</NOTE> grete &thorn;o&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="279"></L>
<L>He soght yn hys herte aboute,</L>
<L N="8852">But &thorn;eryn found&euml; he no doute</L>
<L>&THORN;at fyl to synne, ne dedly &thorn;yng</L>
<L>To lette &thorn;e holy gostes comyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He called hys dekene to hym bylyue,</L>
<L>And cunseyled hym 'he shuld hym shryue</L>
<L N="8857">&YOGH;yf he felt oght hym wy&thorn;-ynne,'</L>
<L>"Any maner of dedly synne</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;oght or dede &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst mene;</L>
<L N="8860">Of alle, y pray &thorn;e, shryue &thorn;e clene."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e dekene &thorn;an opunly with mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Shroue hym of all&euml; &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>He seyde, "of o &thorn;yng y haue gret doute:</L>
<L N="8864">Yn &thorn;oght&euml;s, whan we turnede aboute,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 Omitted in <I>Harl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On a womman myn <SUP>2</SUP>y&yogh;e ys y<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 ye y.</NOTE>-caste;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sy&yogh;te of here myn herte to-blaste</L>
<L>And, swal yn my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn.</NOTE> herte so grete,</L>
<L N="8868">&THORN;e &thorn;o&yogh;t of here ne coude y lete;</L>
<L>But God and &yogh;ow, mercy y crye<MILESTONE N="59a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;o&yogh;t and &thorn;at folye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bysshope seyd hyt was tresun</L>
<L N="8872">Of &thorn;e fendes temptacyun.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at synne he asoyled hym fre,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ede a&yogh;en to hys degre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e dekene loked at &thorn;e nexte turnyng,</L>
<L N="8876">She was a-wey, he sagh no &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy goste come fur&thorn;e a-none,</L>
<L>And shewed hym to &thorn;e bysshope Ione;</L>
<L>And seynt Ioun was &thorn;er-of bly&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="8880">And &thorn;anked God ful fel&euml; sy&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For wommens sake, &thorn;ys tale y tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey hem.</NOTE> oute of &thorn;e chaunsel holde</L>
<L>wy&thorn; here kercheues,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kercheuers.</NOTE> &thorn;e deuylys sayle,</L>
<L N="8884">Elles shal &thorn;ey go to helle, bo&thorn;e top and tayle;
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="280"></L>
<L>For at hym &thorn;ey lern&euml; alle</L>
<L N="8886">To tempt&euml; men yn synne to falle.</L>
<L>To synne &thorn;ey calle men, alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey may,</L>
<L>why shuld &thorn;ey ell&euml;s make hem so gay?</L>
<L>For no-&thorn;yng elles are &thorn;ey so dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But for to blynd&euml; menn&euml;s sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Certes hyt seme&thorn;, at alle endes,</L>
<L N="8892">&THORN;at many of hem are but fendes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;e clerkes<NOTE PLACE="foot">clerkes &yogh;ow.</NOTE> nede&thorn; to be wyse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow nede&thorn; cune &yogh;ow<NOTE PLACE="foot">cunne &yogh;oure.</NOTE> self chastyse;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mow&euml; se yn holy wryt</L>
<L N="8896">How &yogh;e shul kepe &yogh;oure own&euml; wyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &yogh;e at Godd&euml;s seruyse are,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shul nat &thorn;an aboute &yogh;ow stare,</L>
<L>Specyaly wymmen to be-holde,</L>
<L N="8900">Ne for to Iangle wurd&euml;s bolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Clerk with skyl shulde be pryue,</L>
<L>And nat yn cherche of wurd&euml;s fre;</L>
<L>Ne dysturble men with hys rage,</L>
<L N="8904">For hyt ys called<NOTE PLACE="foot">callede al.</NOTE> sacrylage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>kepe &thorn;y body yn cherche fro synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;y menbrys and &thorn;y wyt with-ynne;</L>
<L>Specyally &thorn;y &thorn;o&yogh;t and &thorn;y sy&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8908">&THORN;an may &thorn;y preyer be made alle ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also hyt ys vyleynye to werche,</L>
<L>A lewed man to plete yn cherche,</L>
<L>lay courte, or elles counte,</L>
<L N="8912">&THORN;er any man my&yogh;t dampned be;</L>
<L>Ne quest take of endyt&euml;ment</L>
<L>yn holy cherche, o&thorn;er &yogh;erde purseynt;<NOTE PLACE="foot">pursent.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne sysours oght nat to enquere</L>
<L N="8916">Of felonye, ne of &thorn;eft&euml; &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at hym wreyest, &thorn;ou mayst weyl se</L>
<L>&THORN;ou demyst hym with &thorn;at ys yn &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn cherche dest any of &thorn;yse,</L>
<L N="8920">&THORN;ou trespast a&yogh;ens &thorn;e fraunchyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou euer hauntedest swych outrage,
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="281"></L>
<L>yn holy cherche with wymmen to rage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so ferfur&thorn; was &thorn;y wyl</L>
<L N="8924">&THORN;at &thorn;y natur&euml; dyd&euml; spyl,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere, y sey, &thorn;ou synnest<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnedest.</NOTE> dedly;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ee.</NOTE> mor&euml; &thorn;an &thorn;ou lay here by.</L>
<L>For &thorn;us sey &thorn;ey &thorn;at clergy can,</L>
<L N="8928">he<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hyt.</NOTE> my&yogh;t betyde slaghter of man;</L>
<L>Also holy wryt hyt forbedes,</L>
<L>with womman to do flesshely dedes;</L>
<L>Yn holy stede, hyt ys grete awe</L>
<L N="8932">&THORN;e dede to do, or speke with sawe;</L>
<L>And nam[&euml;]ly &thorn;er men do messe,</L>
<L>Many more folde &thorn;e synn&euml; ys.</L>
<L>And, for to fle[en] swych trespas,</L>
<L N="8936">Y shal &yogh;ow telle an auenturs kas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Sacrilegious Husband and Wife who stuck together.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a man, and hyght Rychere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>A ryche of pens and of powere;</L>
<L>hyt telle&thorn; algate he hadde enmys,</L>
<L N="8940">O&thorn;er for hys gode, or for folys;</L>
<L>Of hem hadde he swyche drede &amp; eye,</L>
<L>he fled and woned yn an abbeye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e abbot ded hym a chambre werche</L>
<L N="8944">For hys ese, fast by &thorn;e cherche;</L>
<L>And he and hyse hadde here wonnyng,<MILESTONE N="59b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wyfe and chylde, and ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O ny&yogh;t &thorn;yr was, he knewe hys wyfe</L>
<L N="8948">Of flesshely dede, as fyl here lyfe;</L>
<L>And God was nat payd, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> wlde hyt no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So ny &thorn;e cherche, swyche dede were wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey myghte no more be broghte a-sondre<SUP>5</SUP>
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="282"></L>
<L>&THORN;an dog and bych &thorn;at men on wondre.<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 In the <I>Harl. MS.</I> these two lines have been inked over and scraped out by some ancient fig|leafite.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8953">Betydde a shame, &thorn;ey gun to crye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wundyr fyl on here folye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men asked sone what was &thorn;at drede;</L>
<L N="8956">At &thorn;e laste, hyt shewed yn dede.</L>
<L>Sone oueral &yogh;ed&euml; &thorn;at fame;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow &thorn;ar nat aske &yogh;yf &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem.</NOTE> &thorn;o&yogh;t shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys man dyd &thorn;e munkes to kalle,</L>
<L N="8960">And specyaly besoghte hem alle</L>
<L><SUP>2</SUP>To praye for hem yn orysun</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey myght&euml; be undoun.<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 The figleafite has scratched over these two lines too.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8963">"And larg&euml;ly we wul &yogh;ow &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>And wurschyp &thorn;ys stede whyl &thorn;at we lyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;at God almy&yogh;ty graunte hyt be so</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure synne he wyl vndo."</L>
<L>&THORN;ese munkes besoghte for hem a bone,</L>
<L N="8968">And God almy&yogh;ty graunted hyt sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ere, &thorn;urgh alle here ordynaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey dede to<NOTE PLACE="foot">do.</NOTE> wryte yn boke &thorn;ys chaunce,</L>
<L>For to shewe hyt euer more,</L>
<L N="8972">&THORN;at ou&thorn;er my&yogh;t beware &thorn;ar-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys chaunce fyl nat for hem allone,</L>
<L>But for to warne vs euerychone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we shul euermor&euml; drede,</L>
<L N="8976">Yn holy place to do &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L>For, moche more dampnacyun</L>
<L>wyl falle of fornycacyun,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;yt more for auowtrye</L>
<L N="8980">Of prestys or wyu&euml;s lecherye,</L>
<L>whan God toke wreche, &thorn;at many of spake,</L>
<L>For a dede &thorn;at was do yn ry&yogh;t wedlake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys yche chaunce, to &yogh;ow y tolde,<MILESTONE N="60a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="8984">For hyt ys gode yn herte to holde,</L>
<L>Namly men of holy cherche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey &thorn;er-ynne no swyche dede werche.
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="283"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>karolles, wrastlynges, or somour games,</L>
<L>who-so euer haunte&thorn; any swyche shames</L>
<L N="8989">Yn cherche, o&thorn;er yn cherch&euml;&yogh;erd,</L>
<L>Of sacrylage he may be a-ferd;</L>
<L>Or entyrlud&euml;s, or syngynge,</L>
<L N="8992">Or tabure bete, or o&thorn;er pypynge,</L>
<L>Alle swych&euml; &thorn;yng forbodyn es,</L>
<L>whyle &thorn;e prest stonde&thorn; at messe.</L>
<L>Alle swyche, to euery gode preste ys lothe,</L>
<L N="8996">And sunner wyl he make hym wroth</L>
<L>&THORN;an h&eacute; wyl, &thorn;at ha&thorn; no wyt,</L>
<L>Ne vndyrstonde&thorn; nat holy wryt;</L>
<L>And specyaly, at hyghe tymes,</L>
<L N="9000">karolles to synge, and red&euml; rymys,</L>
<L>Noght yn non&euml; holy stedes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at my&yogh;t dysturble &thorn;e prest&euml;s bedes,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf he were yn orysun</L>
<L N="9004">Or any ou&thorn;er deuocyun,</L>
<L>Sacrylage ys alle hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">al ys hyt.</NOTE> tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys and many o&thorn;er folde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But for to leue, yn cherche to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to O, for to H.</NOTE> daunce,</L>
<L N="9008">Y shal &yogh;ow telle a ful grete chaunce,</L>
<L>And y trow, &thorn;e most &thorn;at fel</L>
<L>Ys as so&thorn; as &thorn;e gospel;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ys as soth as &thorn;e gospel O, Ys so&thorn;e as y &yogh;ow telle H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fyl &thorn;ys chaunc&euml; yn &thorn;ys londe,</L>
<L N="9012">Yn Ingland, as y vndyrstonde;</L>
<L>Yn a kynges tyme &thorn;at hyght Edward,</L>
<L>Fyl &thorn;ys chaunce &thorn;at was so hard.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Sacrilegious Carollers, and how they danst together for twelve Months without stopping, and then went hopping about singly ever afterwards.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Found in William of Malmesbury, but is earlier. It often occurs singly, and no doubt followed the <I>Itinerarium Clementis</I> in the MS. where Wadington read it.&mdash;G. Paris, <I>Hist. Litt.</I> xxviii. 204.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<L>Hyt was vpp-on a crystemesse ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="9016">&THORN;at twelue folys a karolle dy&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="284"></L>
<L>yn wodehed, as hyt were yn cuntek</L>
<L>&THORN;ey come to a tounne men calles<NOTE PLACE="foot">calle.</NOTE> Colbek;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cherche of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> tounne &thorn;at &thorn;ey to come,</L>
<L N="9020">Ys of seynt Magne &thorn;at suffred martyr|dome;</L>
<L>Of seynt Bukcestre hyt ys also,<MILESTONE N="60a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seynt Magnes suster, &thorn;at &thorn;ey come to.</L>
<L>here names of alle, &thorn;us fonde y wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9024">And as y wote, now shul &yogh;e wyte:<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete.</NOTE></L>
<L>here lod&euml;s-man &thorn;at made hem glew,</L>
<L>&THORN;us ys wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrete.</NOTE> he hy&yogh;te Gerlew;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>O. inserts wrongly&mdash;</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e ou&thorn;er twelue, here nam&euml;s alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;us were &thorn;ey wrete as y can kalle.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Twey maydens were yn here coueyne,</L>
<L N="9028">Mayden Merswynde and Wybessyne;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese come &thorn;edyr for &thorn;at enchesone,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prest&euml;s doghtyr of &thorn;e tounne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest hy&yogh;t Robert, as y kan ame;</L>
<L N="9032">A&yogh;one, hyght hys sone by name;</L>
<L>Hys doghter, &thorn;at &thorn;ese men wulde haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;us ys wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrete.</NOTE> &thorn;at she hy&yogh;t Aue;</L>
<L>Echoune consented to o wyl,</L>
<L N="9036">who shuld go, Aue oute to tyl:</L>
<L>&THORN;ey graunted echone out to sende</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Wybessyn&euml; and Merswynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese wommen &yogh;ede and tolled here oute</L>
<L N="9040">wy&thorn; hem to karolle &thorn;e cherche aboute.</L>
<L>Beune ordeyned here karollyng;</L>
<L>Gerlew endyted what &thorn;ey shuld syng:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e karolle &thorn;at &thorn;ey sunge,</L>
<L N="9044">As telle&thorn; &thorn;e latyn tunge,</L>
<L>"<I>Equitabat Beuo per siluam frondosam</I>,</L>
<L><I>Ducebat secum Merswyndam formosam</I>,</L>
<L>Quid stamus, cur non imus?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Equitabat dux Bovo per silvam frondosam</I>, etc. See the study of this legend of the Curst Dancers by Schr&ouml;der of Marburg before the Congress of German Philologists and Teachers in 1895 (since publisht). The first couplet of the song that the C&ouml;lbigk dancers sang in 1013 is traced back to a certain Dietrich (<I>Theodoricus</I>), who pretended that he'd been one of those dancers, and who was cured of his convulsive malady at Wilton in England, at the tomb of St. Edith. The original song, latinised above, was Low-Saxon.&mdash;Romania, xxv. 340-1.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9048">. . . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">A gap in the MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="285"></L>
<L>"By &thorn;e leued wode rode Beuolyne,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; hym he ledd&euml; feyre Merswyne;</L>
<L>why stond&euml; we? why go we noght?"</L>
<L N="9052">&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e karolle &thorn;at Grysly wroght.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys songe sunge &thorn;ey yn &thorn;e cherche&yogh;erd,&mdash;</L>
<L>Of foly were &thorn;ey no &thorn;yng aferd,&mdash;</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e matynes were alle done,</L>
<L N="9056">And &thorn;e messe shuld bygynn&euml; sone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preste hym reuest to begynne messe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey ne left &thorn;erfore, neuer &thorn;e lesse,</L>
<L>But daunsed fur&thorn;e as &thorn;ey bygan;<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9060">For alle &thorn;e mess&euml; &thorn;ey ne blan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preste, &thorn;at stode at &thorn;e autere</L>
<L>And herde here noys&euml; and here bere,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e auter down he nam,</L>
<L N="9064">And to &thorn;e cherch&euml; porche he cam,</L>
<L>And seyd, "on Goddes behalue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">halfe.</NOTE> y &yogh;ow forbede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e no lenger do swych dede;</L>
<L>But come&thorn; yn, on feyre manere,</L>
<L N="9068">Godd&euml;s seruys&euml; for to here,</L>
<L>And do&thorn; at Crystyn mennys lawe;</L>
<L>karolle&thorn; no more for Crystys awe,</L>
<L>wurschyppe&thorn; hym with alle &yogh;oure my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9072">&THORN;at of &thorn;e vyrgyne was bore &thorn;ys ny&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For alle hys byddyng, lefte &thorn;ey no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But daunsed fur&thorn;, as &thorn;ey &thorn;o&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;arefore was sore a-greued,</L>
<L N="9076">he preyd God &thorn;at he on beleuyd,</L>
<L>And for seynt Magne, &thorn;at he wulde so werche,</L>
<L>yn whos wurschyp, sette was &thorn;e cherche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swych a veniaunce were on hem sent</L>
<L N="9080">Are<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ar.</NOTE> &thorn;ey oute of &thorn;at sted&eacute; were went,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey O, om. H.</NOTE> my&yogh;t euer, ry&yogh;t so wende</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at tym&euml; tweluemonth ende:
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="286"></L>
<L N="9083">(Yn &thorn;e latyne &thorn;at y fonde &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>he sey&thorn; nat 'tweluemonth,' but 'euermore.')</L>
<L>He cursed hem &thorn;ere alsaume</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey karoled on here gaume.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9087">as sone as &thorn;e preste hadde so spoke,</L>
<L>Euery hande yn ou&thorn;er so fast was loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man my&yogh;t with no wundyr</L>
<L>&THORN;at tweluemon&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">tweluemon&thorn;e H, twelfmon&thorn;e O.</NOTE> parte hem asundyr.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preste &yogh;ede yn, whan &thorn;ys was done,</L>
<L N="9092">And commaunded hys sone A&yogh;one</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> shulde go swy&thorn;e aftyr Aue,</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;at karolle algate to haue.</L>
<L N="9095">But al to late &thorn;at wurde was seyd,</L>
<L>For on hem alle was &thorn;e veniaunce leyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;one wende weyl for to spede;<MILESTONE N="60b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e karolle asswy&thorn;e he &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>hys systyr by &thorn;e arme he hente,</L>
<L N="9100">And, &thorn;e arme fro &thorn;e body wente.</L>
<L>Men wundred all&euml;, &thorn;at &thorn;ere wore,</L>
<L>And merueyle mowe &yogh;e her&euml; more,</L>
<L>For se&thorn;en he had &thorn;e arme yn hande,</L>
<L N="9104">&THORN;e body &yogh;ede fur&thorn; karoland;</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">no&thorn;er &thorn;c.</NOTE> body, ne &thorn;e arme,</L>
<L>Bledde neuer blod&euml;, colde ne warme,</L>
<L>But was as drye, with al &thorn;e haunche,</L>
<L N="9108">As of a stok were ryue a braunche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;one to hys fadyr went,</L>
<L>And broght hym a sory present:</L>
<L>"loke, fadyr," he seyd, "and haue hyt here,</L>
<L N="9112">&THORN;e arm&euml; of &thorn;y doghtyr dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at was myn own&euml; syster Aue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y wende y my&yogh;t a<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> saue.</L>
<L>&THORN;y cursyng, now sene hyt ys</L>
<L N="9116">with veniaunce on &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn O, &thorn;y H.</NOTE> own&euml; flessh;</L>
<L>Fellyche &thorn;ou cursedest, and ouer sone;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou askedest veniaunce, &thorn;ou hast &thorn;y bone."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ow &thorn;ar nat aske &yogh;yf &thorn;ere was wo
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="287"></L>
<L N="9120">with &thorn;e preste and with many mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at cursed for &thorn;at daunce,</L>
<L>On some of hys, fyl hard&euml; chaunce.</L>
<L>he toke hys doghtyr arme forlorn</L>
<L N="9124">And byry&euml;d hyt on &thorn;e morn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e next&euml; day, &thorn;e arme of Aue,</L>
<L>he fonde hyt lyggyng aboue &thorn;e graue.</L>
<L>he byryed hyt on<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt on O, on H.</NOTE> anou&thorn;er day,</L>
<L N="9128">And eft aboue &thorn;e graue hyt lay;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydd&euml; tyme he byryed hyt,</L>
<L>And eft was hyt kast oute of &thorn;e pyt.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest wulde byrye hyt no more;</L>
<L N="9132">h&eacute; dredde &thorn;e veniaunce ferly sore;</L>
<L>yn-to &thorn;e cherche he bare &thorn;e arme,</L>
<L>For drede and doute of mor&euml; harme,</L>
<L>h&eacute; ordeyned hyt for to be,<MILESTONE N="61a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9136">&THORN;at euery man my&yogh;t with ye hyt se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese men &thorn;at &yogh;ede so karolland</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &yogh;er&euml; hand yn hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey neuer oute of &thorn;at stede &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="9140">Ne non&euml; my&yogh;t hem &thorn;enn&euml; lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;e cursyng fyrst bygan,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at place, a-boute &thorn;ey ran,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">'ne' omitted.</NOTE> felte<NOTE PLACE="foot">felt O, fette H.</NOTE> &thorn;ey no werynes&mdash;</L>
<L N="9144">As many bodyes, for goyng, dos&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne met&euml; et&euml;, ne drank drynke,</L>
<L>Ne slept&euml; onely a-lepy wynke;</L>
<L N="9147">Ny&yogh;t, ne day, &thorn;ey wyst of none,</L>
<L>whan hyt was come, whan hyt was gone;</L>
<L>Frost ne snogh, hayle ne reyne,</L>
<L>Of colde ne hete, felte &thorn;ey no peyne;</L>
<L>Heere ne nayl&euml;s neuer grewe,</L>
<L N="9152">Ne solowed clo&thorn;es, ne turned hewe;</L>
<L>&THORN;undyr ne ly&yogh;tnyng dyd hem no dere,</L>
<L>Goddes mercy dyd hyt fro hem were;</L>
<L>But sungge &thorn;at songge &thorn;at &thorn;e wo wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9156">"why stond&euml; we, why go we no&yogh;t?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what man shuld &thorn;yr be, yn &thorn;ys lyue,
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ne wulde hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt ne wulde O, hyt ne wulde hyt H.</NOTE> see, and &thorn;edyr dryue?</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure Henry come fro Rome</L>
<L N="9160">For to see &thorn;ys hard[&euml;] dome;</L>
<L>whan he hem say,<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe.</NOTE> he wept&euml; sore</L>
<L>For &thorn;e myschefe &thorn;at he sagh &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>He ded come wry&yogh;t&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="inter">carponters</NOTE> for to make</L>
<L N="9164">Coueryng ouer hem, for tempest sake;</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;ey wroght, hyt was yn veyn,</L>
<L>For, hyt come to no certeyn;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ey sett&euml; on oo<NOTE PLACE="foot">o.</NOTE> day,</L>
<L N="9168">On &thorn;e tou&thorn;er, downe hyt lay;</L>
<L>Ones, twyys, &thorn;ryys, &thorn;us &thorn;ey wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And alle here makyng was for no&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="9171">Myght no coueryng hyle hem fro colde</L>
<L>Tyl tyme of mercy, &thorn;at Cryst hyt wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tyme of grace fyl &thorn;urgh hys my&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="61a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e twelvemonth ende, on &thorn;e &yogh;ol&euml; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same oure &thorn;at &thorn;e prest hem banned,</L>
<L N="9176">&THORN;e sam&euml; oure, atwynne &thorn;ey woned;</L>
<L>&THORN;at houre &thorn;at he cursed hem ynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, &thorn;e H.</NOTE> sam&euml; oure &thorn;ey &yogh;ede atwynne:</L>
<L>And, as yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn a.</NOTE> twynkelyng of an ye,</L>
<L N="9180">Yn-to &thorn;e cherch&euml; gun &thorn;ey flye,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e pauement &thorn;ey fyl alle downe,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey hade be dede, or fal yn a swone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;re days, styl, &thorn;ey lay echone,</L>
<L N="9184">&THORN;at none steryd, o&thorn;er flesshe or bone,</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e &thorn;re days ende,</L>
<L>To lyfe God grauntede hem to wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey sette hem vpp, and spak apert</L>
<L N="9188">To &thorn;e parysshe prest, syre Robert:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou art ensample and enchesun</L>
<L>Of oure long confusyun;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou maker art of oure trauayle,</L>
<L N="9192">&THORN;at ys to many grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">ful gret.</NOTE> meruayle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;y traueyle shalt &thorn;ou sone ende,
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>For to &thorn;y long home, sone shalt &thorn;ou wende."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;ey ryse &thorn;at ych&euml; tyde,</L>
<L N="9196">But Au&euml;; she lay dede besyde;</L>
<L>Grete sorowe had here fadyr, here bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Merueyle and drede had all&euml; ou&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="9199">Y trow no drede of soul&euml; dede,</L>
<L>But with pyne was broght &thorn;e body dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst man was &thorn;e fadyr, &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, deyd aftyr &thorn;e do&yogh;tyr nest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ych&euml; arme &thorn;at was of Aue,</L>
<L N="9204">&THORN;at, non&euml; my&yogh;t leye yn graue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperoure dyd a vessel werche</L>
<L>To do hyt yn, and hange yn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;e' omitted.</NOTE> cherche,</L>
<L N="9207">&THORN;at alle men my&yogh;t se hyt and knawe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enk on &thorn;e chaunce when men<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey.</NOTE> hyt sawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese men &thorn;at hadde go &thorn;us karolland</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e &yogh;ere, fast hand yn hand,</L>
<L N="9211">&THORN;ogh &thorn;at &thorn;ey were &thorn;an asunder,<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yt alle &thorn;e worlde spake of hem wunder:</L>
<L>&THORN;at same hoppyng &thorn;at &thorn;ey fyrst &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at daunce &yogh;ede<NOTE PLACE="foot">wente.</NOTE> &thorn;ey &thorn;urgh land and lede;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ey ne my&yogh;t fyrst be vnbounde,</L>
<L>So efte to-gedyr my&yogh;t &thorn;ey neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">mighte &thorn;ey neuer to-gedyr.</NOTE> be founde,</L>
<L N="9217">Ne my&yogh;t &thorn;ey neuer come<NOTE PLACE="foot">come neuer.</NOTE> a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>To-gedyr, to oo stede certeyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure &yogh;ede to &thorn;e courte of Rome,</L>
<L N="9220">And euer hoppyng aboute &thorn;ey nome;</L>
<L>with sundyr lepys come &thorn;ey &thorn;edyr,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey come neuer efte to-gedyr;</L>
<L>Here clo&thorn;es ne roted, ne nayl&euml;s grewe,</L>
<L N="9224">Ne heere ne wax, ne solowed hewe,</L>
<L>Ne neuer hadde &thorn;ey amend&euml;ment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we herde, at any corseynt,</L>
<L N="9227">But at &thorn;e vyrgyne Seynt Edyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was he botened, seynt<NOTE PLACE="foot">'seynt' omitted.</NOTE> Teodryght;</L>
<L>On oure lady day, yn lenten tyde,</L>
<L>As he slepte<NOTE PLACE="foot">slepe.</NOTE> here toumbe besyde,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="290"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere he hade hys medycyne,</L>
<L N="9232">At seynt Edyght, &thorn;e holy vyrgyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Brunyng, &thorn;e bysshope of seynt Tolous,</L>
<L>wrote &thorn;ys tale so merueylous;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e was hys name of more renoun,</L>
<L N="9236">Men called hym &thorn;e pope Leoun;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys at &thorn;e court of Rome &thorn;ey wyte,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e kronykeles hyt ys wryte,</L>
<L>Yn many stedys be-&yogh;ounde &thorn;e see,</L>
<L N="9240">More &thorn;an ys yn &thorn;ys cuntre;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor men seye, an weyl ys trowed,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e nere &thorn;e cherche, &thorn;e fyr&thorn;er fro God."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So fare men here by &thorn;ys tale:</L>
<L N="9244">Some holde hyt but a<NOTE PLACE="foot">but for a.</NOTE> trot&euml;uale;</L>
<L>Yn o&thorn;er stedys hyt ys ful dere,</L>
<L>And for grete merueyle &thorn;ey wyl hyt here;</L>
<L>A tale hyt ys of feyre shewyng,</L>
<L N="9248">Ensample and drede a&yogh;ens cursyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys tale y tolde &yogh;ow, to make<NOTE PLACE="foot">to make H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> &yogh;ow aferde,<MILESTONE N="61b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yn cherche to karolle, or yn cherche &yogh;erde,</L>
<L>Namely a&yogh;ens &thorn;e prestys wylle;</L>
<L N="9252">leue&thorn;, whan he bydde&thorn; &yogh;ow be stylle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ianglyng longe&thorn; to sacrylage;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-of take&thorn; &thorn;e fende taylage;</L>
<L>Iangle we yn cherche neuer so lyte,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at we do<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iangle O, do Iangle H.</NOTE> Iangle, &thorn;e fende do&thorn;e wryte,</L>
<L N="9257">And shal shewe hyt before oure face</L>
<L>whan hys rolle ys broght yn place:</L>
<L>And y shal tell&euml;, as y kan,</L>
<L N="9260">A bourd&euml; of an holy man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Devil's Disappointment with the Chattering Women.]</HEAD>
<L>Shortly to tell&euml;, and nat longe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>An holy man hys mess&euml; songe;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e messe, whan tym&euml; fel</L>
<L N="9264">&THORN;e dekene to red&euml; &thorn;e gospel,
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>Yn hys redyng, none wyst why,</L>
<L>he logh a grete laghter an hy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preste, and o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ere stode,</L>
<L N="9268">helde hym a fole, &thorn;at coude no gode.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;&euml;, whan &thorn;e messe was done,</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste asked &thorn;e dekene sone,</L>
<L>'why &thorn;at he so ferde, and how</L>
<L N="9272">&thorn;at he, yn hys gospel, logh?'<NOTE PLACE="foot">low.</NOTE></L>
<L>Moche &thorn;arfore he gan hym blame,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lewed folk &thorn;oght hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym.</NOTE> shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e dekene told hym why hyt fel</L>
<L N="9276">&thorn;ere to laghe<NOTE PLACE="foot">laghhe.</NOTE> yn hys gospel:</L>
<L>"As y redde &thorn;at ych&euml; tyde,</L>
<L>Twey wymmen Iangled &thorn;ere besyde;</L>
<L>Betwyx hem to,<NOTE PLACE="foot">two.</NOTE> y say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe.</NOTE> a fende</L>
<L N="9280">with penne and parch&euml;men yn honde,</L>
<L>And, wrote alle &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey spake,</L>
<L>Pryuyly be-hynde here bake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan hys rolle was wryte alle ful,</L>
<L N="9284">To drawe hyt oute he gan to pul;</L>
<L>with hys te&thorn;e he gan to drawe,</L>
<L>And hard&euml; for to tugge and gnawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys rolle to-braste and rofe;<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9288">And hys hede a&yogh;ens &thorn;e walle drofe</L>
<L>S&oacute; hard, and so ferly sore,</L>
<L>Whan hys parchemen was no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan y say &thorn;at, y lete so gode,</L>
<L N="9292">Y brast on laghter &thorn;ere y stode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he so moch&euml; sorow hadde,</L>
<L>As hys wrytyng was alle to-fade;</L>
<L>And when he parceyued &thorn;at y wyste,</L>
<L N="9296">He al to-drofe hyt with hys fyste,</L>
<L>And went a-wey, alle for shame;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore y logh and hadde gode game."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest hym asked 'whedyr he say mo.'</L>
<L N="9300">"Many," he seyd, "y sagh &thorn;ere go,</L>
<L>And wrote oueral &thorn;ere men tolde,</L>
<L>But none so moche &thorn;at y dyde beholde;</L>
<L>Hym behelde y weyl ynogh,
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="292"></L>
<L N="9304">For &thorn;at he dyd, &thorn;ere-at y logh."</L>
<L>&THORN;an wyst &thorn;e prest, &thorn;urgh &thorn;at sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was weyl with God almy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For Ianglers, &thorn;ys tale y tolde,</L>
<L N="9308">&THORN;at &thorn;ey yn cherche here tung&euml;s holde.</L>
<L>Speke to God yn &thorn;y preyere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at shal nat &thorn;e fend&euml; here.</L>
<L N="9311">&THORN;ou Iangler, take &thorn;ou god&euml; kepe,</L>
<L>hyt were wel bettyr &thorn;ou were on slepe;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf nyt ne be amended here,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. inserts&mdash;Wy&thorn; shryfte of mouth <I>and</I> pen|aunce clere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Elleswere shalt &thorn;ou a-bye hyt dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sacrylage also may be for ty&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="9316">yn &thorn;at, synne men ful oft&euml; sy&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Of all&euml; &thorn;yng, &thorn;at &thorn;e newe&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ty&thorn;e ry&yogh;tly, &oacute;r elles hyt &thorn;e rewe&thorn;.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e werst &thorn;ou shalt nat &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an lesest &thorn;ou &thorn;y gode yn &thorn;y lyue;</L>
<L N="9321">Ne &yogh;yue hyt nat with wykked wyl,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e tou&thorn;er, mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;an spyl;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue God &thorn;e best &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst haue,</L>
<L N="9324">And alle &thorn;e tou&thorn;er he wyl &thorn;e saue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>O</I>. inserts&mdash;</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &thorn;ou do so, wyte &thorn;ou weyl</L>
<L>He wyl &thorn;e reu&euml; eury deyl.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure &thorn;ynges are &yogh;yu&euml; specyaly<MILESTONE N="62a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To euery man &thorn;at ty&thorn;e&thorn; ry&yogh;tly;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota bene</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst ys, long lyfe to haue;</L>
<L N="9328">&THORN;e tou&thorn;er, &thorn;e yn gode hele to saue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ryd ys, grac&euml; gode with-ynne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to wynne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;e, for&yogh;yuenes of &thorn;y synne:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt haue any of &thorn;yse,</L>
<L N="9332">Ty&thorn;&euml; weyl, and on gode syse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">assyse.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou turnedest, for worldes wynnyng,</L>
<L>halewed place, or holy &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Cherche &yogh;erde, or &thorn;ere chapyl was,</L>
<L N="9336">Tymber, stones, eren, or glas,</L>
<L>Curteynes, or ou&thorn;er vestyment,</L>
<L>Or any o&thorn;er vesselement</L>
<L>&THORN;at falle&thorn; to holy cherches seruyse,
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="293"></L>
<L N="9340">And vsest hem on ou&thorn;er wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;y wytyng;&mdash;&thorn;ou synnest dedly</L>
<L>Yn sacrylage certeynly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arto shal y preue my sawe</L>
<L N="9344">By a tale of &thorn;e old&euml; lawe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ys tale yn &thorn;at tyme fyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fel.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was of &thorn;e prophete Dany&euml;l.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Belshazzar's Feast, and the Prophet Daniel.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a kyng of grete powere;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9348">yn hys tyme was none hys pere;</L>
<L>ynogh he hadde of world&euml;s my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And Baltazar<NOTE PLACE="foot">Crost out, and 'Nabygodonosore' inserted.</NOTE> hys nam&euml; hy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys kyng was a paynym,</L>
<L N="9352">and with oste he come to Ierusalem,</L>
<L>And robbed &thorn;e temple, &thorn;ys Balta&yogh;are,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tresour awey bare;</L>
<L>&THORN;e vessel &thorn;at was of ryche metalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Goddes temple was seruede with-alle,</L>
<L N="9357">&thorn;at, and more, he dyd aloyne,</L>
<L>And ledde hem yn-to Babyloyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone aftyrward, &thorn;ys ych&euml; kyng</L>
<L N="9360">Deyd, and mad&euml; hys endyng.</L>
<L>hys sone reyned yn &thorn;at same,</L>
<L>And Balta&yogh;ar&euml; was hys name;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e vessel with hym lefte,<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9364">&THORN;at hys fadyr hadd stole and refte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A day he made a noble feste</L>
<L>with barons and with rych&euml; geste;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys vessel &thorn;at hys fadyr stale,</L>
<L N="9368">Rychely he dyd hym serue with-alle;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e vessel &thorn;ey ete and dranke,</L>
<L>But to God made &thorn;ey no &thorn;anke;</L>
<L>But yn alle here moste gladyng,</L>
<L N="9372">To fals goddys &thorn;ey made wurschypyng.
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>A kandelstyke stode &thorn;e kyng before,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oute of Ierusalem was bore;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng lokede to &thorn;at candelstyke,</L>
<L N="9376">And sagh besyde a grete ferlyke:</L>
<L>Vndyr &thorn;e kandelstyke, a lytel logh,</L>
<L>He sagh an hande wryte on &thorn;e wogh;</L>
<L>No mor&euml; he sagh &thorn;an &thorn;e hande,</L>
<L N="9380">But &thorn;e lettres were weyl farande;</L>
<L>he redde hyt as he sate on &thorn;e des,</L>
<L>"Mane. techel. fares.<NOTE PLACE="foot">phares.</NOTE>"</L>
<L>No more &thorn;yr was &thorn;ere wryte;</L>
<L N="9384">On englys &thorn;us ys hyt to wyte,</L>
<L>'To morn&euml; shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shal &thorn;e.</NOTE> departyng be,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;y ryche kyngdom fro &thorn;e.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kyng vndyrstode no &thorn;yng of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="9388">Ne none of hys&euml; coude hym wys.</L>
<L>As he &thorn;ys hand began to holde,</L>
<L>hys herte bygan to tremle and colde;</L>
<L>he shewed hyt to alle hys &aacute;ssemble,</L>
<L N="9392">And cryd&euml; hyt &thorn;urgh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;urghe out.</NOTE> &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at &yogh;yf any coude do hym to wyte,</L>
<L>what hyt mente, &thorn;at &thorn;ere was wryte,</L>
<L>He shulde haue of hym grete mede,</L>
<L N="9396">&THORN;at coud&euml; vndo &thorn;at yn dede.'</L>
<L>But none of alle, forso&thorn;e to wene,</L>
<L>Coude telle &thorn;e kyng what hyt wlde mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &thorn;e quene seyd sone anone:</L>
<L N="9400">"Syre kyng, y wot&euml; where ys one,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kan do &yogh;ow alle to knowe<MILESTONE N="62b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>what ys wryt&euml; on &thorn;e wowe.</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys cyte, yn a strete,</L>
<L N="9404">wone&thorn; a ful wys prophete,</L>
<L>hys name men call&euml; Dany&euml;l,</L>
<L>he shal vndo &thorn;e wrytyng wel."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e kyng aftyr Dany&euml;l sente,</L>
<L N="9408">And &thorn;e prophete to hym wente;
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng hym preyd, byfore hem alle,</L>
<L>To tell&euml; hem what shulde befalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9411">&THORN;e prophete wuld&euml; no &thorn;yng hyde:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e hand &thorn;at &thorn;ou sawe yn &thorn;e euyntyde,</L>
<L>hyt was sent fro God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys wra&thorn;&thorn;e ys to &thorn;e dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou were serued of &thorn;e vesseles</L>
<L N="9416">&THORN;at of hys temple were Ieuwels;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iuelles.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys day before, of hem &thorn;ou ete,</L>
<L>And no wurschyp of hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym O, hem H.</NOTE> &thorn;ou lete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys God, alle &thorn;yng weldande,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e and &thorn;yne ha&thorn; yn hys hande;</L>
<L N="9421">But to fals goddes &thorn;ou madest onour</L>
<L>with vessel of hys owne tresour;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ou dedyst bo&thorn;e euyl, and seyd,</L>
<L N="9424">&THORN;y kyngdom ys yn balaunce leyd,</L>
<L>Tyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tyl H O.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t be-deme&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be-demede.</NOTE> with euyn hand,</L>
<L>To wham hyt shal be &yogh;yue, &thorn;y land.</L>
<L N="9427">&THORN;urgh dome of God, hyt ys so dryue,</L>
<L>To twey maner of folke &thorn;y land ys &yogh;yue;</L>
<L>Medys, and Persys, &thorn;y land shul haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e, ne &thorn;yne, mayst &thorn;ou nat saue.</L>
<L>Here ys wryte &thorn;e sam&euml; wyse,</L>
<L N="9432">Y sey to &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e O, to H.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t as hyt seyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at.</NOTE> sam&euml; ny&yogh;t &thorn;e lande was lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng was slayn, and awey bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here mayst &thorn;ou se, euyl-wunne &thorn;yng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. has in margin, 'note. of euill goten goodes.'</NOTE></L>
<L>with eyre shal neuer make gode endyng,</L>
<L N="9437">Namly, with &thorn;yng of holy cherche</L>
<L>Shalt &thorn;ou neuer spede wel to werche.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mayst &thorn;ou se by parsones eyres,<MILESTONE N="63a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hyt fare&thorn; with hem as do&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">'do&thorn;e' omitted.</NOTE> with &thorn;ese feyres;</L>
<L>Now ys &thorn;e feyr&euml; bygged weyl,</L>
<L N="9442">And on &thorn;e morne ys &thorn;er neuer a deyl:
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="296"></L>
<L>Ryche tresoure, now fur&thorn;e men leye,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e tou&thorn;er day hyt ys alle aweye;</L>
<L N="9445">O day, to-gedyr men mowe hyt se,</L>
<L>A-nouther,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A nou&thorn;er day.</NOTE> sprede &thorn;urgh all &thorn;e cuntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us fare&thorn; hyt by &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> parsones cosynes;</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t &thorn;e parsone wynny&thorn;, &thorn;e cosyne tynes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'lest.'</NOTE></L>
<L>yn &thorn;e parsones tyme, rychely he lyue&thorn;,</L>
<L>Aftyr hym, no man of hym &yogh;yue&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hym no man oghte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9451">yn hys tyme, ofte pens he telle&thorn;,</L>
<L>Aftyr hym, for pouert, penys he selle&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also with purchasours ry&yogh;t so hyt fare&thorn;,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey bygge, here eyr&euml;s bare&thorn;;</L>
<L>A purchasoure may beye &thorn;yng, &amp; with lawe,</L>
<L>with-oute any dede of wrong or sawe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">any wronge of dede or of sawe.</NOTE></L>
<L>But loke&thorn;, &yogh;yue he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, &yogh;e H.</NOTE> wynne &thorn;at katel weyl,</L>
<L>wharewith he bye&thorn; hyt euerydeyl.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he haue wunne &thorn;e penys<NOTE PLACE="foot">penys O, pens H.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9460">&THORN;an ha&thorn; he &thorn;e lande with-out&euml; ply&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue he haue wunne &thorn;e penys<NOTE PLACE="foot">penys O, pens H.</NOTE> falsle,</L>
<L>with ry&yogh;t to &thorn;e lande com neuer he.</L>
<L>with fals[&euml;] weyght, or fals[&euml;] peys,</L>
<L N="9464">And many falshede ou&thorn;er weys;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt moste, with fals sweryng,</L>
<L>wynne&thorn; manyone moche &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>with swyche &thorn;yng, wene &thorn;ou hyt no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="9468">&THORN;at &thorn;e hous ne lande was ry&yogh;tly bo&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnne&thorn; laste&thorn; aght &thorn;at men bye</L>
<L>with &thorn;at ys wunne with marchaundye;</L>
<L N="9471">Yn erytage nat long hyt vayle&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red eyre lese&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lest.</NOTE> &thorn;at ou&thorn;er trauayle&thorn;;</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e ys any &thorn;at ha&thorn; gode grace</L>
<L>To lyu&euml; weyl with swych purchace,</L>
<L N="9475">O&thorn;er lyue &thorn;ey a bysyly lyfe,</L>
<L>Or lese hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> for pouert and for<NOTE PLACE="foot">for H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> stryfe;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ys men se, and seye alday,<MILESTONE N="63a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;e &thorn;red eyre selle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sel&thorn;.</NOTE> alle away."
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="297"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9479">For sacrylage, alle &thorn;ys ys tolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vesselment of cherche ys wy&thorn;holde,&mdash;</L>
<L>Chaleys, cloth, boke, or lome,<NOTE PLACE="foot">LOOME or instrument, <I>utensile, instrumentum</I>. Prompt. Parv.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>For sacrylage cum&thorn; ofte hard dome;</L>
<L>yn alle &thorn;e poynt&euml;s seyd before,</L>
<L N="9484">&THORN;at fro holy cherche, oght ha&thorn; bore,</L>
<L>Or aght mysdo on any wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at longe&thorn; vn-to &thorn;e fraunchyse,</L>
<L>Y or &thorn;ou, yn any outrage,</L>
<L N="9488">we synne dedly yn sacrylage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gode &yogh;yue vs grace so to serue here<NOTE PLACE="foot">to serue so here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holy cherche, oure modyr dere,</L>
<L>Here so to serue, and wurschyp make,</L>
<L N="9492">&THORN;at we be hyre, and she vs take.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Here bygynne the Seuen&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">seuen.</NOTE> Sacra|mentys of holy cherche.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>Baptism</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fyrst sacrament ys holy bapteme,</L>
<L>Houe of watyr, and noyted<NOTE PLACE="foot">smerede.</NOTE> with creme;</L>
<L>'Crystendom,' or 'crystynyng,'</L>
<L N="9496">&THORN;at ys on englys, oure spekyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Crystendom, to cryst hyt longe&thorn;,</L>
<L>And to alle &thorn;at crystendom vndyrfonge&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e fyrst and pryncypalle,</L>
<L N="9500">&THORN;urgh &thorn;e whych we are saued alle;</L>
<L>Saued we are, &thorn;urgh crystendam,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e heued synne of Adam,</L>
<L>yn whych synne alle mankynde ys bore,</L>
<L N="9504">&YOGH;yt, and shal be, and was byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Adams synn&euml; was so grefe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yr was to God, none<NOTE PLACE="foot">noun to God.</NOTE> so lefe,</L>
<L>&THORN;yt he ne shulde to hell&euml; gone</L>
<L>But he were wasshe yn &thorn;e fonte stone,
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="298"></L>
<L N="9509">yn fonte stone and watyr baptysed,</L>
<L>As Ihesu cryst ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">had.</NOTE> dyuysed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou beleue &thorn;at any wham</L>
<L N="9512">ys saued with-oute crystyndam,</L>
<L>y seye, forso&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast mys went<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys holy sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte we here &thorn;e lewed men seye,</L>
<L N="9516">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">And.</NOTE> erre ful moche oute of &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e Iew&euml;s seye sum oun,</L>
<L>'&THORN;ey ne wote whe&thorn;er &thorn;ey be saued or noun;'</L>
<L>But of sum prestes ys gretter tene,</L>
<L N="9520">&THORN;at so of &thorn;e Iew&euml;s also wene;</L>
<L>Certes, &thorn;ey are alle yn were,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e fey&thorn; &thorn;ey are nat clere,</L>
<L>For, shal neuer Iewe &thorn;at deye&thorn; Iewe,</L>
<L N="9524">Of heuene blys haue part ne prewe,</L>
<L>But he be crystened yn &thorn;e holy gaste,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e sacrament be ful stedfast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo, here a wurde to leue &yogh;oure drede!</L>
<L N="9528">yn &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at we rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god Ihesu vs all&euml; teche&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh seynt Mark, &thorn;at hyt preche&thorn;,</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at beleue&thorn; and ys baptysed,</L>
<L N="9532">He shal be saued, so ys dyuysed;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at beleue&thorn; nat, forso&thorn;e &amp; ywys,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e body and soul&euml;, lore he ys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Loke&thorn;.</NOTE> how &yogh;e mow be a-bawed,</L>
<L N="9536">&thorn;at seye &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewe ys saued!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewe, &thorn;e old&euml; law&euml; kan,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at alone may saue no man;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore was hyt fyled and left,</L>
<L N="9540">For heuen&euml; blys, vs hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt vs.</NOTE> refte</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh Adams synne fro vs echone,</L>
<L>Tyl hyt was clensed yn flume Iordone,</L>
<L>whan Ihesu was baptysed &thorn;er-ynne</L>
<L N="9544">For to wasshe awey &thorn;at synne;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at euer to Cryst wyl teme,</L>
<L>Behoue&thorn; be baptysed yn watyr and creme:
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="299"></L>
<L>&THORN;an art &thorn;ou clene, &thorn;ou shalt beleue,</L>
<L N="9548">Of Adams synn&euml;, and of Eue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore hyt ys &thorn;e fyrst sacrament</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art to, fyrst made present;</L>
<L>Lok&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ou kunne hyt knowe;<MILESTONE N="63b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hyt make&thorn; &thorn;e hygh, &thorn;ere &thorn;ou were lowe,</L>
<L N="9553">hyt make&thorn; &thorn;e fre, &thorn;at er were &thorn;ralle,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e fend&euml;s seruage alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e &thorn;ar neuer &thorn;e fend&euml; drede</L>
<L N="9556">But hyt be &thorn;urgh &thorn;yn owne mysdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf a chylde be ded&euml; bore&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt were quyk yn wombe byfore&mdash;</L>
<L>And, receyue nat &thorn;e bapteme,</L>
<L N="9560">Of heuene may hyt neuer cleme;</L>
<L>with-out&euml; doute, beleue &yogh;e &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt shal neuer come to blys;</L>
<L>Ne peyne of het&euml;, ne of colde,</L>
<L N="9564">Hyt shal non fele, no ry&yogh;t hyt wolde;</L>
<L>Hyt noght mysdyd, ne serued wo,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No.</NOTE> to non&euml; shal hyt go;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys peyne with-outen ende,</L>
<L N="9568">hyt shal neuer to Ioy&euml; wende.</L>
<L>Gret&euml; grace ys to hem lent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here receyue &thorn;ys sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, &yogh;e &thorn;at heue chyldryn al day,</L>
<L N="9572">loke &yogh;e be stedfast yn oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;oure.</NOTE> lay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non&euml; haue yn hert&euml; doute,</L>
<L>Ne to wycchecrafte leste no<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> loute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou settest &thorn;y self yn borghgage</L>
<L>To teche &thorn;e chylde whan hyt ha&thorn; age;</L>
<L N="9577">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou se hyt mysdo or seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt teche hyt better wey,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou maght,</L>
<L N="9580">&THORN;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou O, &thorn;at H.</NOTE> art holde &thorn;at hyt be taght;</L>
<L>Quyte &thorn;e weyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">weyl so.</NOTE> oute of borghgang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne haue for hyt no wrang.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>loke also, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer ware
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>Yn place &thorn;ere wymmen chyldryn bare;</L>
<L N="9585">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou sawe hyt yn perel of dede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou ne coudest do bote ne rede,</L>
<L>Ne sey&euml; wurde, ne helpe at nede,</L>
<L N="9588">So &thorn;at hyt to &thorn;e de&thorn;&euml; &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt &thorn;erfor&euml; perel haue;<MILESTONE N="64a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vnkunnyng shal &thorn;e nat saue;</L>
<L>For euery man, bo&thorn;e hygh and logh,</L>
<L>&THORN;e poyntes of bapteme owe&thorn; to knowe,</L>
<L N="9593">To helpe chyldryn yn many kas;</L>
<L>Men wete neuer what nede one has.</L>
<L>who so ne kan, y rede hym lere</L>
<L N="9596">Yn sy&yogh;te, yn dede, and he may here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y shal &yogh;ow teche, as y herde telle</L>
<L>On&euml;s a frer&euml; menor spelle:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou se a chylde yn swyche perel</L>
<L N="9600">&THORN;at none may saue hyt with no wylle,</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;an &thorn;us, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou haue haste,</L>
<L>"y crysten &thorn;e yn &thorn;e name of &thorn;e fadyr &amp; sone &amp; holy gast,"</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue, what &thorn;ou wylt, hyt a name,</L>
<L>And kast on water; &thorn;an ys hyt frame;</L>
<L N="9605">And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &yogh;yue hyt nam&euml; none,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er Robert, Wyllyam, no<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> Ione,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ese wurd&euml;s be weyl seyd,</L>
<L N="9608">And water &thorn;er-on algate leyde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;yr be none ou&thorn;er waste,</L>
<L>But yn &thorn;e fadyr and sone, and holy gaste;</L>
<L N="9611">&THORN;ese wurdes for&yogh;ete &thorn;ou naght,</L>
<L>Ne watyr, what as euer elles be<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> wro&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mydwyu&euml;s &thorn;at wy&thorn; wymmen wone,</L>
<L N="9614">Alle &thorn;e poyntes, behoue&thorn; hem kone;</L>
<L>Prestes shuld teche hem &thorn;e ordynaunce,</L>
<L>what &thorn;ey shuld sey and do yn chaunce,</L>
<L>And examyne her<NOTE PLACE="foot">examyne here O, examyne H.</NOTE> what she couthe,</L>
<L>what she shuld do, and seye with mou&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="301"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Midwife who christend a Child wrongly.]</HEAD>
<L>Y shal &yogh;ow telle of a mydwyfe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L N="9620">&THORN;at loste a chylde, bo&thorn;e soule &amp; lyfe.</L>
<L>he tolde hyt yn hys sermoun,</L>
<L>And &yogh;aue here ofte hys malysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys mydwyfe, whan &thorn;e chylde was bore,</L>
<L N="9624">She helde hyt on here lappe before;</L>
<L>And whan she sawe &thorn;at hyt shulde deye,</L>
<L>She bygan, loud&euml; for to crye,</L>
<L N="9627">And seyd, "God and seynt Ione<MILESTONE N="64a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Crysten &thorn;e chylde, bo&thorn;e flesshe and bone."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The next twelve lines, from O, are omitted in <I>H.</I></NOTE>&THORN;ys mydwyffe noghte ell&euml;s seyde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Bodl. MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e cherche-&yogh;erde &thorn;ey wulde hyt haue leyde,</L>
<L>As a-nou&thorn;er chyld shuld ha be</L>
<L N="9632">&THORN;at hade receyuede &thorn;e solempte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest askede &thorn;e mydwyffe,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yfe hyt were cristenede whan hyt hade lyffe,</L>
<L N="9635">And who hyt cristened, and on what manere,</L>
<L>And what was seyde, &thorn;at any myghte here.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e mydwyffe seyde unto &thorn;e prest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Margin, 'a note for mydwyffes.'</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ys herde &thorn;ey &thorn;at stode me nest,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at God almyghty and Seynt Ioun</L>
<L N="9640">&yogh;yue &thorn;e chylde cristendom yn flesshe and boun."'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e preste, "God and seynt Iame<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Harl. MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yue &thorn;e bo&thorn;e sorow and shame,</L>
<L>And Crystys malysun haue &thorn;ou for-&thorn;y,</L>
<L N="9644">And alle &thorn;e ou&thorn;er &thorn;at were &thorn;e by!</L>
<L>Yn euyl tym&euml; were &thorn;ou bore,</L>
<L>For yn &thorn;y defaute, a soule ys lore."</L>
<L>She was commaunded she shuld no more</L>
<L>Come eftesones &thorn;ere chyldryn were bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mydwyues, y tolde thys tale for &yogh;ow,
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="302"></L>
<L N="9650">&THORN;at &yogh;yf &yogh;e kunnat, lerne&thorn; how</L>
<L>To sau&euml; &thorn;at, God bo&yogh;t ful dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e poyntes of bapteme y rede &yogh;ow lere;</L>
<L N="9653">Mydwyfe ys a perylus &thorn;yng</L>
<L>But she kunne &thorn;e poyntes of crystenyng;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne beleue&thorn; nat on &thorn;ese shappers,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shapperes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9656">&YOGH;oure mysdede ful mykyl deres;</L>
<L>y wolde &thorn;o shappers were on lowe,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;o &thorn;at on hem trowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e beleue ys, '&thorn;e fadyr and sone &amp; holy gaste;'</L>
<L>Alle ou&thorn;er beleue ys wykked and waste;</L>
<L N="9661">&THORN;urgh hem ys alle &thorn;yng shape &amp; wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ou&thorn;er shappers<NOTE PLACE="foot">shapperes.</NOTE> ne are no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>God ys shapper of alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="9664">he wote &thorn;e mydward, and &thorn;e endyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;er shappers, &thorn;at men of seye,</L>
<L>Hyt ys a beleue of deuyl weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e mete &thorn;at &yogh;e leye at &thorn;e chyld&euml;s hede<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuede.</NOTE></L>
<L>For swyche shappers, were bettyr leued;</L>
<L N="9669">&YOGH;yf hyt for hem &thorn;er&euml; lye,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys hyt<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys hyt O, ys H.</NOTE> a wykked erysye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">heresye.</NOTE></L>
<L>ley hyt for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e holy gaste,</L>
<L N="9672">Fadyr, and sone, oo God stedfaste,</L>
<L>As wysly as he become a chylde,</L>
<L>Bore of Marye, mayden mylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &yogh;yue hyt to lyue yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">'yn' omitted.</NOTE> gode grace,</L>
<L N="9676">And gode endyng, and se hys face.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou were euer so vnwys<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For to crystene a chyld&euml; twys,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf &thorn;ou euer consentedest &thorn;ar-to</L>
<L N="9680">&THORN;at any ou&thorn;er shulde so do,&mdash;</L>
<L>At home, as yn pryuyte,</L>
<L>Anou&thorn;er tyme, &thorn;at men my&yogh;t se,&mdash;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf hyt were baptysed at hame</L>
<L N="9684">wy&thorn; alle &thorn;e poyntes of bapteme name,
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="303"></L>
<L>&THORN;an were hyt a&yogh;ens &thorn;e fey&thorn;e to werche,</L>
<L>Eftesones<NOTE PLACE="foot">Eftsone.</NOTE> to baptyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">baptyse O, baptysed H.</NOTE> hyt at cherche;</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;ou suppose &thorn;yr fayle&thorn; a poynte</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e crystendom shuld a-mounte,</L>
<L N="9689">&THORN;an were hyt nat for to drede</L>
<L>For to fulfyl &thorn;at shulde be nede;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e poyntes of watyr &amp; creme,</L>
<L N="9692">&THORN;urgh alle crystendom ys o bapteme,</L>
<L>O baptem&euml;, and nat two,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o.</NOTE> poyntes &thorn;at &thorn;ou sest do.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he &thorn;at ys ones baptysed,</L>
<L N="9696">Ones for euer ys; &thorn;us ys auysed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, &yogh;e &thorn;at chyldryn heue,</L>
<L>&yogh;e shul nat for&yogh;ete ne leue</L>
<L>To teche hyt pater noster &amp; crede;</L>
<L N="9700">&YOGH;yf &yogh;e ne do, hyt ys to drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To foly &thorn;ou shalt nat drawe ne wone</L>
<L>&THORN;y goddo&yogh;tyr ne &thorn;y godsone,</L>
<L>Namely to &thorn;at vylayny</L>
<L N="9704">&THORN;at falle&thorn; vn-to lechery,</L>
<L>Ne to no foly &thorn;at may be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt teche hem synne to fle.</L>
<L>Ne nat be so fole hardy,</L>
<L N="9708">&THORN;y goddo&yogh;tyr to lye &thorn;e by,</L>
<L>Ne for to dwelle a-lone with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For perel &thorn;at may falle and be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many a pryuy peryl &thorn;yr ys,</L>
<L N="9712">And specyaly yn drunkenes;</L>
<L>yn drunkenes men wyl rage,</L>
<L>And, ragyng wyl reyse korage;</L>
<L>And son&euml; may a man be shent<MILESTONE N="64b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9716">&THORN;at do&thorn;e a&yogh;ens &thorn;e comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn; yn hys spelle</L>
<L>Of swyche a shame &thorn;at on&euml;s felle.
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="304"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Bad Bourgeois<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Curialis,' Common-Councilman, bourgeois.</NOTE> who lay with his God-daughter and was kild for it.]</HEAD>
<L>A man hefe on&euml;s at &thorn;e fonte</L>
<L N="9720">A mayd&euml; chylde, as men are wonte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys mayde wax, and bygan to belde</L>
<L>weyl yn-to womans elde;</L>
<L>And at Ester tyme gan hyt falle</L>
<L N="9724">whan men hadde fast&euml; lenten alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys man bysoghte, for specyalte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys god-do&yogh;tyr wy&thorn; hym my&yogh;t be,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at ych&euml; Esterday</L>
<L N="9728">And lenger, &yogh;yf hyt were here pay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fadyr and &thorn;e modyr graunted sone;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &thorn;o&yogh;t none euyl my&yogh;t be done.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys man, for drunkenes &amp; vnry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>lay by hys god-do&yogh;tyr &thorn;at yche ny&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="9733">&THORN;ys man on &thorn;e morn&euml; &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>How synfully &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> hadde wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ful grete &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;an was he ynne,</L>
<L N="9736">&THORN;at he hadde do so greuus a synne;</L>
<L>Twey &thorn;oghtes yn hys hert&euml; come,</L>
<L>To go<NOTE PLACE="foot">go O, gode H.</NOTE> to &thorn;e cherche, or byde at home:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf y vnto &thorn;e cherch&euml; &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="9740">Of ven&iuml;aunce y haue grete drede;</L>
<L>And, &yogh;yf y nat &thorn;edyr go,</L>
<L>Men wyl wene y haue do sum wo."</L>
<L>So algate vnto &thorn;e cherche he name;</L>
<L N="9744">he drede nat God, but mor&euml; shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyrst day, he dred hym sore</L>
<L>he shuld be cumbred sumwore,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt a-no&thorn;er he lokede ay,</L>
<L N="9748">whyche tyme &thorn;e fende wulde bere hym a|way;
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="305"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e woke, for world&euml;s shame,</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede to &thorn;e cherche, but lytyl to frame;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan he hadde long a-byd&euml; so,</L>
<L N="9752">And, no ska&thorn;&euml; come hym to,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys &thorn;oght he yn hys herte ful ra&thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="65a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he hadde &thorn;arfore no ska&thorn;e,</L>
<L>he wend&euml; God had hyt forgete</L>
<L N="9756">As ou&thorn;er men do &thorn;at haue forlete;</L>
<L>Or &thorn;o&yogh;t &thorn;at he hadde hyt for&yogh;yue,</L>
<L>And hym neded nat &thorn;er-of be shryue,</L>
<L>Ne shulde &thorn;erof come no myschaunce,</L>
<L N="9760">For he was of so longe suffraunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But God, &thorn;at f&oacute;r&yogh;ete&thorn; no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>he sente &thorn;arfore grete heuenyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e day &thorn;ys man deyde,</L>
<L N="9764">As &thorn;e holy man vs seyde;</L>
<L>Sone aftyr &thorn;at byryed he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he byryede.</NOTE> was,</L>
<L>Veniaunce come for &thorn;at trespas;</L>
<L>Vpp of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Out of.</NOTE> hys graue a fyre vpp smote&mdash;</L>
<L N="9768">Ful stynkyng and ful hote&mdash;</L>
<L>And brenned<NOTE PLACE="foot">brende.</NOTE> &thorn;at cursed body alle,</L>
<L>And stone and er&thorn;e, bo&thorn;e grete and smalle;</L>
<L>Alle was so brend yn-to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L N="9772">&THORN;at of hys body my&yogh;t no&yogh;t be founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here mow &yogh;e here apertly why</L>
<L>God toke veniaunce greuusly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God shewed so moche hys Ire,</L>
<L N="9776">For he synned &thorn;at tyme with hyre</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> lyfte of &thorn;e fonte stone:</L>
<L>hyt ys a warnyng to vs echone</L>
<L>&thorn;at we kepe &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L N="9780">Oure bapteme &thorn;at God ha&thorn; sent;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lent.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at we bettyr hyt holde</L>
<L>For &thorn;ys tale &thorn;at y &yogh;ow tolde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e, Ihesu lord&euml;, &thorn;ou hyt graunte
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="306"></L>
<L N="9784">&thorn;at we mow hold&euml; &thorn;at cunnaunte</L>
<L>&thorn;at we at &thorn;e fonte ston&euml; make,</L>
<L>Ihesu to serue, and Satanas forsake.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>[Of Confirmation.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The secunde sacrament, y vndyrstonde,</L>
<L>Ys graunted of &thorn;e bysshop honde;</L>
<L N="9789">Men kalle hyt 'confyrmacyon,'</L>
<L>A sykernesse neuer more vndon</L>
<L>wy&thorn; no lawe, ne with no skylle,<MILESTONE N="65a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9792">But &yogh;yf &yogh;e self algat&euml; wylle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, 1. 7232, next page.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &yogh;yf &thorn;ou boghtest house and<NOTE PLACE="foot">or.</NOTE> land</L>
<L>with charter at &thorn;y neghburs hande,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mayst holde hyt for euer-more,</L>
<L N="9796">So bapteme &thorn;e saue&thorn; ones &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hyt be graunted of &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast boght, &thorn;an ys syker &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>Syker ys, &thorn;at yn rolle ys leyde,</L>
<L N="9800">For &thorn;an may hyt neuer be wy&thorn;seyde;</L>
<L>&thorn;e rollyng fordo&thorn;e croppe and rote,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t of &thorn;o &thorn;at wulde &thorn;e mote;<NOTE PLACE="inter">plete</NOTE></L>
<L>Rollyng, and &thorn;e grete assyse,</L>
<L N="9804">Aftyr hem may no law&euml; ryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us fare&thorn; hyt of confyrmacyun</L>
<L>Aftyr tyme &thorn;at bapteme ys doun;</L>
<L>Confyrmacyun ys more ne lesse,</L>
<L>But aftyr crystenyng, gode sykernesse;</L>
<L N="9809">&THORN;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> bapteme ys charter of ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at fordo&thorn;&euml; Adams<NOTE PLACE="foot">adames.</NOTE> ply&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at ys of grete pouste,</L>
<L N="9812">&THORN;at fro &thorn;e fende hyt bye&thorn; &thorn;e fre,</L>
<L>And defende&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn O, yn H.</NOTE> erytage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mayst holde hyt yn alle &thorn;yn age,</L>
<L>And saue &thorn;y stat&euml; euery deyl,</L>
<L N="9816">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;y charter weyl;</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;ys, &yogh;yf hyt be &thorn;y lordes wylle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;y charter wyl fulfyle,
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="307"></L>
<L>&THORN;an art &thorn;ou stalworth &thorn;urgh hys powere,</L>
<L N="9820">And &thorn;y charter made more clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bysshope ys as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as O, a H.</NOTE> lorde or<NOTE PLACE="foot">or &thorn;e.</NOTE> kyng</L>
<L>To conferme &thorn;y crystenyng;</L>
<L>He conferme&thorn; &thorn;at we haue take</L>
<L N="9824">whan we haue Satan forsake,</L>
<L>Oure crystendom, &thorn;at hyt be sekyr</L>
<L>To fende vs a&yogh;ens &thorn;e fend&euml;s bekyr,</L>
<L N="9827">&THORN;an ys oure charter quyte and clere,</L>
<L>Confermyng with &thorn;e bysshopes powere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;e shul alle weyl vndyrstande,<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan chyldryn are blessed of &thorn;e bysshopys<NOTE PLACE="foot">of bysshop.</NOTE> hande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blessyng ys contermacyoun</L>
<L N="9832">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fendes temptacyun,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; vs stalwur&thorn;e yn batayle</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e fende wyl vs asayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;an are we made Goddes champyons,</L>
<L N="9836">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fend&euml;s, Goddys felons;</L>
<L>&thorn;an haue we receyued fully my&yogh;t</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fend&euml; for to fy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf we be yn beleue stedfaste,</L>
<L N="9840">we haue powere, dowun hym to kaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Certes, &thorn;o men moche mysdo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at &thorn;ey H, &THORN;at O.</NOTE> a-byde long, are &thorn;ey go &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>And wommen, gretly ouer alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="9844">&thorn;at wyl nat here chyldryn bryng</L>
<L>To receyue &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>At &thorn;e bysshopes confyrment;<NOTE PLACE="foot">conferment O, cofyrment H.</NOTE></L>
<L>For some wete weyl, &thorn;at chyldryn kepe,</L>
<L N="9848">&THORN;at many are drecched yn here slepe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende hem shewe&thorn; grete affray,</L>
<L>To some on ny&yogh;t, and some a<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> day,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he, may hem greue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="9852">To make ou&thorn;er men mysbeleue;
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="308"></L>
<L>Some men hyt here, &amp; some men<NOTE PLACE="foot">'men' H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> hyt sees,</L>
<L>Yn many stedys, vanytes,</L>
<L>More before &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L N="9856">&THORN;an aftyr,<NOTE PLACE="foot">afterwarde.</NOTE> whan he ys shent;</L>
<L>Hys powere ys &thorn;an moche fordoun</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;ys confyrmacyun;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at oght we, to beleu&euml; ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9860">&thorn;at &thorn;ys sacrament ha&thorn; &thorn;at my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ano&thorn;er poynt, here-to longe&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lewed men nat vndyrstandy&thorn;:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou man or womman, be nat so wylde</L>
<L>To holde to &thorn;e bysshope &thorn;yn owne chylde;</L>
<L N="9865">For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou do, &thorn;ou art commare</L>
<L>To hym &thorn;at hyt, gat or bare;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf a frende man holde hyt &thorn;ore,<MILESTONE N="65b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To wedde &thorn;at chylde, he may neuer more;</L>
<L N="9869">&thorn;ys longe&thorn; to &thorn;ys sacrament;</L>
<L>&THORN;arefor<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;arfore y rede.</NOTE> &yogh;yue&thorn; gode entent."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn &thorn;ys skyll&euml;, as y kan,</L>
<L N="9872">hyt ys grete perel to an vncou&thorn;e man,</L>
<L>A mayd&euml; chyld&euml; for to holde</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e bysshope, as y er tolde,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he ask&euml; fyrst byfore,</L>
<L N="9876">what hyt ys, and where was bore;</L>
<L>Elles perauenture yn hys lyue</L>
<L>he my&yogh;t haue &thorn;at chylde to wyue;</L>
<L>Or &yogh;yf she &yogh;yue here to folye,</L>
<L N="9880">he my&yogh;t, yn kas, lygge here by;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys kas<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ys kas O, &THORN;ys H.</NOTE> ys nat often seen,</L>
<L>But hyt may fall&euml;, or ha&thorn; ben;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, no&thorn;er mo<NOTE PLACE="foot">more.</NOTE> ne lesse,</L>
<L N="9884">But 'wyys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wys.</NOTE> ys, &thorn;at ware ys.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now of &thorn;ys confyrmacyun</L>
<L>wyl we leue oure sermoun;</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue vs grac&euml;, for hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9888">yn &thorn;e beleue to ferme vs ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e holy goste with vs wone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cum&thorn; of &thorn;e fadyr and of &thorn;e sone.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament"><PB REF="00000317.tif" N="309">
<HEAD>[Of the Sacrament of the Altar.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This Section, to p. 336, is copied into the Vernon MS. (with a few changes of words and forms) as '7 Miracles of Corpus Christi,' and is printed in 'Minor Poems of the Vernon MS.,' ed. Hortsmann and F. J. F.; E. E. T. Soc. 1891.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9891">God almy&yogh;ty, &thorn;at al &thorn;yng weldes,</L>
<L>wynd&euml;s, watrys,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> watres.</NOTE> wodes, &amp; feldes,</L>
<L>As so&thorn;ely as &thorn;ou madest of no&yogh;t</L>
<L>Alle cr&eacute;atures &thorn;at euer were wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For&yogh;yue me, to day, Lorde, my synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y &thorn;ys wr&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">'wr&thorn;y' should be cut out.</NOTE> sacrament mowe begynne,</L>
<L N="9897">And wurschypfully &thorn;ar-of to speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we &thorn;e beleu&euml; neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer &thorn;e beleuc.</NOTE> breke;</L>
<L>Ne for to tell&euml;, yn &thorn;ys long,</L>
<L N="9900">&THORN;yng, &thorn;at falle-of, may any wrong,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at m&aacute;y be, &thorn;e to queme,</L>
<L>And vs yn stedfaste beleue to &yogh;eme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Godd&euml;s sone, of heuene a-boue,</L>
<L N="9904">He shewed vs alle, for gret&euml; loue;</L>
<L>For whan hys passyun neyghed nye,<MILESTONE N="66a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To hys dyscyplys &thorn;at were hym bye,</L>
<L>He &yogh;aue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&YOGH;afe.</NOTE> hys body hem to fede,&mdash;</L>
<L>More loue ne my&yogh;t he shewe yn dede,&mdash;</L>
<L N="9909">&THORN;at &thorn;ey shuld&euml; mynd&euml; haue</L>
<L>On hym, &thorn;at he my&yogh;t hem saue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt aftyrward he lete hym slo</L>
<L N="9912">with ful vyle de&thorn;, and pynyng wo;</L>
<L>For vs, and hem, ded he &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>To bryng&euml; vs echone to blys,</L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No.</NOTE> more loue ne my&yogh;t he do,</L>
<L N="9916">Ne neuer man, my&yogh;t so do;</L>
<L>For vs he ded hyt, &thorn;ys ys certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we shuld loue hym weyl a&yogh;en;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh we vs self &yogh;af an hundryd sy&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="9920">O poynt of loue ne my&yogh;t we ky&thorn;e</L>
<L>vn-to &thorn;e loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; vs doun,</L>
<L>For hyt ys oure saluacyun;</L>
<L>And of vs, aske&thorn; he ry&yogh;t no&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="310"></L>
<L N="9924">But &thorn;at may weyl y-nogh be wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng but loue-longyng,</L>
<L>To loue hym weyl ouer alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And for hys loue to leu&euml; synne;</L>
<L>hys loue, hys blys, &thorn;an mow we wynne;</L>
<L N="9929">For &thorn;ou mayst neuer haue hym to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>But, &thorn;ou wylt fyrst synn&euml; fle;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;yng he loue&thorn;, but synne he hates;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hym louest, with synne &thorn;ou wlates.<NOTE PLACE="inter">steynyst</NOTE></L>
<L N="9933">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">louest.</NOTE> one, &thorn;e behoue&thorn; nedes</L>
<L>Forsake &thorn;at &thorn;yng &thorn;at he &thorn;e forbedes;</L>
<L>Elles, hyt ys tolde no loue,</L>
<L N="9936">And nam&euml;ly to God a-boue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou mayst nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> loue hym with no greyth,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou haue of hym gode fey&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to seye, to beleue hyt weyl,</L>
<L N="9940">Alle &thorn;at ys wryte of hym euerydeyl.</L>
<L>Stedfast beleue, of loue hyt comes;</L>
<L>And of beleu&euml;, loue men nomes:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'taketh.'</NOTE></L>
<L>So ys &thorn;e toon with &thorn;e tou&thorn;er;<MILESTONE N="66a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9944">with stedfast beleue, loue ys &thorn;e bro&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To whom ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghte.</NOTE> &thorn;an oure loue be went,</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e beleue of &thorn;ys sacrament?</L>
<L>&THORN;ys, oght to beleue, euery crysten man,</L>
<L N="9948">And lerne &thorn;e beleue of one &thorn;at kan,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at &thorn;e bred &thorn;at sacred ys</L>
<L>At &thorn;e auter, ys Goddys flessh:'</L>
<L N="9951">Bo&thorn;e flesshe and blod&euml; &thorn;er ys leyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh &thorn;e wurdes &thorn;at &thorn;e prest ha&thorn; seyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ly&yogh;te with-ynne &thorn;e vyrgyne Marye,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e rode for vs wulde deye,</L>
<L>And fro de&thorn; to lyue he ros,</L>
<L N="9956">God and man, yn my&yogh;t and los.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For who so beleue&thorn; nat clere</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere,
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="311"></L>
<L>He shal neuer &thorn;e blys a-byde,</L>
<L N="9960">For no &thorn;yng &thorn;at may betyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn &thorn;e old&euml; law&euml;, &thorn;us ys wryte,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Iewes and crysten weyl hyt wete,</L>
<L>"God seyd, and hyt was wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="9964">he commaunded alle &thorn;yng of no&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;ese wurd&euml;s are verry and clere;</L>
<L>Dauyd hem seyth yn &thorn;e sautere;</L>
<L>Syn he made alle &thorn;at no&yogh;t er was,</L>
<L N="9968">lesse maystry were hyt &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an were hyt.</NOTE> yn kas,</L>
<L>For to chaunge &thorn;e lek&euml;nes<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyknes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn-to an ou&thorn;er &thorn;yng &thorn;at es;</L>
<L N="9971">&thorn;e lyk&euml;nes of bred and wyne,</L>
<L>Yn flesshe and blode to turne hyt ynne;</L>
<L>Yn flessh and blode &thorn;e brede be bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Syn he mad&euml; alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al byfore of noght.</NOTE> of no&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="9975">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou se hyt nat with bodly<NOTE PLACE="foot">bodyly.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;y soule with-ynne shal beleue hyt ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou fel&euml; no sauour,</L>
<L>But ryghtely wyne, and brede of flour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">But . . . flour O. But ry&yogh;t bred and wyne of flour H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ys &thorn;e wysdom of Goddys ordynaunce</L>
<L N="9980">For to saue vs alle fro &thorn;ys chaunce;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf hyt fyl, as flesshe to take,<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wlate we shulde, and hyt forsake;</L>
<L>And for he wulde nat men hyt forsoke,</L>
<L N="9984">But &thorn;at alle men hyt vndyrtoke,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore hys wysdom, hys own&euml; rede,</L>
<L>Sauer&thorn; hyt yn wyne and brede;</L>
<L>Hyt seme&thorn; bred&euml;, as be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="9988">And as brede, sauer ha&thorn; ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>No&thorn;yr &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> sy&yogh;t, no&thorn;er &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">no &thorn;y.</NOTE> felyng,</L>
<L>Ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hast &thorn;ou on no (but altered in the same hand).</NOTE> &thorn;er-of any certeyn &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>what shal &thorn;an, &thorn;e most saue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>But stedfast beleue &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt haue?</L>
<L N="9993">Stedfast beleue of euery deyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shal &thorn;an, saue &thorn;e weyl.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="312"></L>
<L>And some haue sey hyt bodyly,</L>
<L N="9996">To whom he shewed hys mercy;</L>
<L>Lo here a tale for of &yogh;ow sum,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y fonde yn 'vitas patrum.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Priest for whom the Sacramental Bread and Wine were turnd into a Child's Flesh and Blood.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a man of relygyoun;</L>
<L N="10000">Of alm&euml;s he had grete renoun;</L>
<L>But, for &thorn;e fende<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e fende O, &thorn;e H (? &thorn;e = they).</NOTE> wulde haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">had.</NOTE> hym shent,</L>
<L>He beleued nat yn &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>And seyd 'hyt was nat Ihesu</L>
<L N="10004">&THORN;at conceyued was &thorn;urgh vertu;</L>
<L>Ne Ihesu was nat &thorn;e obl&eacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vbble.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at reysed was<NOTE PLACE="foot">was reysede.</NOTE> at &thorn;e sacr&eacute;;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at wurschep ded &thorn;arto,</L>
<L N="10008">To beleue hyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt. hyt.</NOTE> was nat to do.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Byfore twey abbotes &thorn;us he tolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese abbotes wryte &thorn;ys tale to holde;</L>
<L>hyt oght be tolde to euery wham</L>
<L N="10012">&THORN;at ys a&yogh;ens &thorn;e crystendam,</L>
<L>Tyl hyt be preued with<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> clergye</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er hyt be beleue or erysye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese abbotes shewed hym &thorn;e ry&yogh;t weye</L>
<L>with alle &thorn;e ensamples &thorn;at &thorn;ey coude seye;</L>
<L N="10017">And he seyd '&thorn;at hyt was lye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>. gloss 'fals.'</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;yf he sagh<NOTE PLACE="foot">saye.</NOTE> hyt with hys ye.'</L>
<L>"Do&thorn;e &thorn;an so &thorn;at y hyt se,<MILESTONE N="66b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10020">&THORN;an wyl y beleue &thorn;at hyt may be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese abbotes preyd a ful seuen ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wulde shewe hym, &thorn;urgh hys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Yn flesshe and blode on &thorn;e autere,
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="313"></L>
<L N="10024">To c&oacute;nferme hys beleu&euml; clere;</L>
<L>And hym-self preyd specyaly</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wulde shewe hym also yn body;</L>
<L>"Lorde," he seyde, "for no mysbeleue</L>
<L N="10028">&THORN;at &thorn;ou shuldest, with me &thorn;e greue,</L>
<L>But for to shewe &thorn;e ry&yogh;t so&thorn;enes</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e messe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y may make ou&thorn;er certeyn</L>
<L N="10032">whan y with y&euml;n haue &thorn;e seyn!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ese.</NOTE> abbotes lay yn orysun</L>
<L>Tyl alle &thorn;e seuen ny&yogh;t were<NOTE PLACE="foot">were alle H, were O.</NOTE> doun;</L>
<L>&thorn;e seuen&thorn;e day, to &thorn;e cherche &thorn;ey cam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e tou&thorn;er man with hem &thorn;ey nam;<NOTE PLACE="foot">nome.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10037">A sege was ordeyned for hem &thorn;re</L>
<L>To behold&euml; alle &thorn;e pryuyte</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at holy sacrament</L>
<L N="10040">&THORN;at shewed was yn here present:</L>
<L>Betwyxe hem sate &thorn;ys ych&euml; man</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;e myracle fyrst began.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;e vble was on &thorn;e auter leyd,</L>
<L N="10044">And &thorn;e prest &thorn;e wurdes had seyd,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;re &thorn;o&yogh;t &thorn;an verrylyk,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e prest, &thorn;at a chyld lay quyk</L>
<L>Yn feyr&euml; forme of flesshe and blode;</L>
<L N="10048">&THORN;ys say &thorn;ey &thorn;re, &thorn;ere &thorn;ey stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;e preste shulde parte &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>An aungel dowun from heuene was sent,</L>
<L>And sacryfyed &thorn;e chylde ry&yogh;t &thorn;are;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e prest hyt brak, &thorn;e aungel hyt share;</L>
<L N="10053">&thorn;e blode yn-to &thorn;e chaleys ran</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at chylde, bo&thorn;e God and man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys man &yogh;ede to &thorn;e hey&yogh;est degre,</L>
<L N="10056">To housel hym, as fyl to be;
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="314"></L>
<L>Hym &thorn;oght &thorn;e prest bro&yogh;te on &thorn;e pateyn<MILESTONE N="67a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Morselles of &thorn;e chylde alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Leave out 'alle.'</NOTE> newe sleyn,</L>
<L>And bedde hym a morsel of &thorn;e flesshe</L>
<L>with alle &yogh;e blode &thorn;er-on alle fresshe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an gan he cry, with loud&euml; steuene,</L>
<L N="10062">"Mercy! Goddys sone of heuene!</L>
<L>&THORN;e brede &thorn;at y sagh on &thorn;e auter lye,</L>
<L>Hyt ys &thorn;y body; y se hyt with ye.</L>
<L N="10065">Of &thorn;e brede, &thorn;urgh sacrament,</L>
<L>To flesshe and blode hyt ys alle went;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys y beleue, and euer y shal;</L>
<L N="10068">For verryly we se hyt alle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan he and &thorn;ey were alle certeyn,</L>
<L>yn forme of brede hyt turned a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>He ded hym housel as ou&thorn;er wore,</L>
<L N="10072">And was a gode man for euermore;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle ou&thorn;re.</NOTE> be&thorn; &thorn;e better,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heren &thorn;ys tale, or redyn &thorn;ys lettyr.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest &thorn;at sacre&thorn; Goddys body,</L>
<L N="10076">Hym behoue&thorn; b&eacute; clene ned&euml;ly:</L>
<L>A lewed man &thorn;at shal hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> receyue,</L>
<L>Alle maner of fyl&thorn;e, behoue&thorn; hym weyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be &thorn;ou neuer so gode a preste,</L>
<L N="10080">Ne so grete wytt&euml; yn &thorn;y breste,</L>
<L>Y rede &thorn;e here how &thorn;e propertes are shewed,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;oghe &thorn;at.</NOTE> &thorn;e langage be but lewed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou wost weyl &thorn;at &thorn;e vbl&egrave;</L>
<L N="10084">Ys but a lytyl &thorn;yng to se;</L>
<L>So shal we be lytyl yn wyl,</L>
<L>lytyl and meke, with-outyn yl,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t yn pryde, ne na&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">'na&yogh;t' omitted.</NOTE> yn hegh&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="315"></L>
<L N="10088">For no wysdom ne for no slegh&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne falle with Lucyfere,</L>
<L>For proude men won&euml; with hym &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e vbl&egrave; ys made of whete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French 1. 7421-5.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10092">&THORN;e louelyest corn&euml; &thorn;at men ete;</L>
<L>So shal<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde.</NOTE> we be meke and louely</L>
<L>To all&euml; &thorn;o &thorn;at be&thorn; vs by;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys mek&euml;nes ys a&yogh;ens Ire,<MILESTONE N="67a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10096">&THORN;at ys with Lucyfere yn fyre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">See French 1. 7389-94.</NOTE>&THORN;e paste of &thorn;e vbl&egrave;, nat ne ogh<NOTE PLACE="foot">ogh&thorn; (the last letter has been added on).</NOTE></L>
<L>Be made of any maner of<NOTE PLACE="foot">cut out 'maner of.'</NOTE> soure dogh;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e soure dogh make&thorn; alle soure</L>
<L N="10100">&THORN;e swetnes &thorn;at cum&thorn; of &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>By &thorn;ys soure dogh ys tokenyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at enuye ys a wykked &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>For hyt fordo&thorn;e swetnes of dede</L>
<L N="10104">&THORN;at God shulde &yogh;yue for soul&euml; mede;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore make&thorn; he none herbergerye</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he fynde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyndes.</NOTE> byfore, enuye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A vertu also yn &thorn;e whete ys,</L>
<L N="10108">&THORN;at ys moche a&yogh;ens sloghnes;</L>
<L>For whet&euml; corn&euml;s wyl nat prykke,</L>
<L>As ot&euml;s dow&uuml;n, or barlykke;</L>
<L>Ne we shulde nat haue any prykyl</L>
<L N="10112">Of ydylnes ouer mykyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ydylnes grucche&thorn;, and ys heuy of &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And also son&euml; wro&thorn;e for no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;&euml; cum&thorn; of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of a.</NOTE> sorowe,</L>
<L N="10116">&THORN;at of wanhope wyl moch&euml; borowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys sacrament of &thorn;e messe</L>
<L>loue&thorn; noun swyche ydulnesse,</L>
<L>Ne, with noun, wyl he dwelle,
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="316"></L>
<L N="10120">But &thorn;ere men of Ioy&euml; spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e paste to &thorn;e vbl&egrave; seyd byforne,</L>
<L>Shal nat be <SUP>1</SUP>of no medel<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 of medlede.</NOTE> corne,</L>
<L>But all&euml; on&euml;ly of wete;</L>
<L N="10124">&THORN;e mastlyoun shul men lete.</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche mene&thorn;, with no wyse</L>
<L>we shul vs medel with coueytyse,</L>
<L>And nam&euml;ly with auaryce,</L>
<L N="10128">For &thorn;at ys tolde a wykked vyce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">See French l. 7413-20.</NOTE>Also &thorn;ou seest &thorn;e vbl&egrave; ys &thorn;ynne,</L>
<L>And grete dunhede ys noun &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at wyl weyl sygnyfye</L>
<L N="10132">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e synne of glotonye;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere ne wyl &thorn;e sacrament reste,<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;ere glotonye wyl hym oute keste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">keste O, kaste H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">See French l. 7389-94.</NOTE>And &thorn;ou seest, &thorn;e vbl&egrave; ys whyte;</L>
<L N="10136">And we shul hau&euml; noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> delyte</L>
<L>Of no maner of flesshely lak,</L>
<L>Of lechery, &thorn;at make&thorn; vs blak.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese are &thorn;e seuene propertes</L>
<L N="10140">Yn &thorn;e vbl&egrave;, as &thorn;ou sees;</L>
<L>And euery properte<NOTE PLACE="foot">a properte.</NOTE> &thorn;er-ynne</L>
<L>Ys a&yogh;ens a dedly synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys sacrament, &thorn;an do &thorn;o</L>
<L N="10144">&THORN;at are yn synne, and &thorn;ar-to go,</L>
<L>Or are yn wyl a&yogh;en to wende</L>
<L>To synne, and hemself shende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also a preste &thorn;at go&thorn;, synge&thorn; hys messe,</L>
<L N="10148">&thorn;at yn dedly synn&euml; ys,</L>
<L>An hunder folde he synne&thorn; more</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;yf he, a lewed man wore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;ey &thorn;at receyue &thorn;ys sacrament</L>
<L N="10152">yn dedly synne, or wykked entent,
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="317"></L>
<L>yn any &oacute;f &thorn;ese ych&euml; seuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast me herd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hast here herde me.</NOTE> neuene,</L>
<L>Hyt ys to here dampnacyun,</L>
<L N="10156">And &thorn;arfore veniaunce shal be doun.</L>
<L>And, here y shal telle a tale,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>How hyt ys to &thorn;o men bale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Priest who was enabled to see Folk's sins in their Faces.]</HEAD>
<L>A parysshe prest was yn a tounne,</L>
<L>A man of ful grete dyscrecyounne;&mdash;</L>
<L N="10161">Dyscrecyun, a ry&yogh;t wyt ys,</L>
<L>On bo&thorn;e partys ry&yogh;tly to ges;&mdash;</L>
<L>Of hys parysshenes he vndyrstode,</L>
<L>whyche were yl, and whych were<NOTE PLACE="foot">'were' omitted.</NOTE> gode;</L>
<L N="10165">Tweyn he hadd&euml; for to gete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer wuld&euml; synn&euml; lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And fyl hyt at an esterne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a prest shul<NOTE PLACE="foot">shulde.</NOTE> none ou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">housel.</NOTE> werne</L>
<L N="10169">But &yogh;yf hyt be &thorn;e gretter synne,</L>
<L>As yn cursyng, or yn vnbuxyme.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest was yn gret&euml; &thorn;o&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="67b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whe&thorn;er he shulde housel hem or no&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="10173">he preyd God, of heuene kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wulde sende hym sum tokenyng</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er h&eacute; shulde hem forbede;</L>
<L N="10176">To housel hem, he<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym.</NOTE> &thorn;o&yogh;t grete drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fro God he had &thorn;ys answere:</L>
<L>'&THORN;at echone shuld hys owne charge bere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he shulde warne hyt none,</L>
<L N="10180">But &yogh;yue hyt fur&thorn;e to euerychone;'</L>
<L>"Do &thorn;ou as Ihesu dyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede.</NOTE> yn dede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou shalt no man hyt forbede,</L>
<L>Ne mor&euml; &thorn;an he ded Iudas,</L>
<L N="10184">&THORN;at hadd&euml; do ful grete trespas."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he &yogh;aue hyt to alle with myld&euml; mode</L>
<L>whan brede was turned to flessh &amp; blode.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="318"></L>
<L>For some &thorn;at hyt take&thorn;, hyt shal hem saue,</L>
<L N="10188">And some &thorn;arfor&euml; peyne shal haue;</L>
<L>Aftyr &thorn;ey are of synn&euml; clene,</L>
<L>So shal hyt on hem be sene."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt preyde he God of mor&euml; grace,</L>
<L N="10192">&THORN;at he my&yogh;t know&euml; hem by face,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whyche receyued hyt wur&thorn;yly,</L>
<L>And whyche to have hyt were wur&thorn;y.</L>
<L>And God graunted hym hys wyl,</L>
<L N="10196">To knowe &thorn;e god&euml; fro &thorn;e yl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e folk<NOTE PLACE="foot">folke.</NOTE> &thorn;at to &thorn;e prest&euml; went</L>
<L>For to receyue &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>Of some &thorn;e faces were as bry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="10200">As &thorn;e sunne ys, &oacute;n days ly&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And some, here vysages al blake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no &thorn;yng my&yogh;t hem blaker make;</L>
<L>And som&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">In <I>Harl</I>. the remainder of the line is scratched out.</NOTE> were as rede as blode,</L>
<L N="10204">Staryng ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ey had be wode;</L>
<L>And sum were swolle, &thorn;e vyseges<NOTE PLACE="foot">vysege.</NOTE> stout,</L>
<L>As &thorn;o&yogh; here y&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">yen.</NOTE> shulde burble out;</L>
<L>And sum gnapped here fete &amp; handes,</L>
<L>As dogg&euml;s doun &thorn;at gnawe here bandes;</L>
<L>And sum hadde vysages of meselrye;<MILESTONE N="68a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And some were lyke foule maumetrye:</L>
<L>Many wundrys were on hem sene,</L>
<L N="10212">Mo &thorn;an he my&yogh;t se at &thorn;at tyme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prest, whan he say<NOTE PLACE="foot">saghe.</NOTE> alle &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at sy&yogh;t he gan hym grys;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at sy&yogh;t was hydous,</L>
<L N="10216">And dreful,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dredful.</NOTE> and perylous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt preyd he God, with gode entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;t wyte, what al &thorn;at ment;</L>
<L>And God almy&yogh;ty loued hym weyl,</L>
<L N="10220">And wuld&euml; shewe hym euerydeyl;</L>
<L>"&THORN;o men &thorn;at are so bry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;e sun, on day[e]s ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;o men are &yogh;yt yn charyte,</L>
<L>And clene of synne, &amp; wurschepe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrshype.</NOTE> me;
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="319"></L>
<L N="10225">&THORN;o men &thorn;at were so blake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no &thorn;yng my&yogh;t hem blaker make,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are lecchours foule with-ynne,</L>
<L>And haue no wyl to leue here synne;</L>
<L N="10229">&THORN;o men &thorn;at wer&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">In <I>Harl</I>. the words after 'were' have been scratched out, but a later hand has written 'face full of blode' for them; an original 'of' can be made out before the 'full.'</NOTE> rede as blode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are Irus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yrous.</NOTE> and wykked of mode,</L>
<L>here euene crystyn for to slo</L>
<L N="10232">with de&thorn;, or, with pyne do wo;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sagh with swolle vysage,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey are enuyous ouer outrage;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at gnapped here finger endes,</L>
<L N="10236">Are bakbyters betwyx&euml; frendys;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sagh, meselles be sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey loue more gode &thorn;an God almy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sagh lyke maumetrye,</L>
<L N="10240">On worldly &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrly (<I>sic</I>) &thorn;ynge.</NOTE> &thorn;ey most affye;</L>
<L>More loue &thorn;ey gode &thorn;at h&eacute; ha&thorn; sent</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;ey do hym &thorn;at alle ha&thorn; lent;</L>
<L>&thorn;ese maner men are &yogh;yt yn wyl,</L>
<L N="10244">yn here synne to lyu&euml; stylle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore shal &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>On hem aske hard&euml; Iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey haue receyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">receyuede.</NOTE> hyt vnwur&thorn;yly,<MILESTONE N="68a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10248">And serued &thorn;e fende, hys enemy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale y tolde for loue of &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn synne to housel go,</L>
<L N="10251">Or be&thorn; yn wylle to turne a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>For alle here trauayle &thorn;ey do yn veyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou, whan &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yn.</NOTE> housel shalt take,</L>
<L>Be yn wylle &thorn;y synne to forsake</L>
<L N="10255">For euermore yn stedfaste herte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ou synne sone aftyr,<NOTE PLACE="foot">after synne sone.</NOTE> and smert,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt God take&thorn; hyt nat to so grete grym</L>
<L>As &yogh;yf &thorn;ou yn tresoun receyuedest hym.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn no &thorn;yng wote y more tresun,</L>
<L N="10260">&THORN;an brynge &thorn;y lorde to<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> hys felun;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt men sey here synne ys grefe,
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="320"></L>
<L>&THORN;at brynge&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">brynge.</NOTE> a trew man on a &thorn;efe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou do &thorn;us, &thorn;y wytande,</L>
<L N="10264">&thorn;an charg&euml; men hyt most yn hande;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou wyte no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>No synne hyde yn herte ne &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne wyl nat wyte for neuer more</L>
<L N="10268">whan &thorn;ou receyuest God ry&yogh;t &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at haunte&thorn; synne,</L>
<L>But he leue, and &thorn;er-of blynne,</L>
<L>He shal nat serue at &thorn;e auter,</L>
<L N="10272">No&thorn;er halewed &thorn;yng to com&euml; ner.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y touched langer of &thorn;ys outrage</L>
<L>whan y spake of sacrylage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e holy gost shewed hym no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="10276">For &thorn;e dekene synned yn &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e tale of Ion<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ion.</NOTE> Crysostomus;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 278]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys tale ys tolde for &yogh;ow and vs.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also he ys wur&thorn;y to be shent,</L>
<L N="10280">&THORN;at, sone aftyr &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>To foly and to synne hym drawe&thorn;:</L>
<L>lytyl of Goddes veniaunce hym awe&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou forgete or ouersyttes</L>
<L N="10284">Tyme of housel, &thorn;at &thorn;ou weyl wytes,</L>
<L>lytel fors of hym &thorn;ou &yogh;yues,<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou louest hym nat &thorn;at &thorn;ou by lyues,</L>
<L>And ouer alle &thorn;yng he loue&thorn; &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L N="10288">And &thorn;ou ne wylt, a ny&yogh;tys geste,</L>
<L>lete hym herber yn hys hous;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art vnkynde ry&yogh;t merueylous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e &yogh;ere &thorn;ou latest hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt.</NOTE> weyue,</L>
<L N="10292">And with wurschy&thorn; &thorn;ou wylt nat hyt receyue.</L>
<L>God manace&thorn; swyche, for swyche enchesun,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t hyt wyl, and gode resun;</L>
<L N="10295">For swych&euml; men are holde vntrewe</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e olde lawe, and eke yn &thorn;e newe.
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="321"></L>
<L>Comaundement yn &thorn;e olde lawe was,</L>
<L>'Ones yn &thorn;e &yogh;ere to shewe &thorn;y trespas;'</L>
<L>&thorn;e newe law ys of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &thorn;e.</NOTE> more onour</L>
<L N="10300">'Ones to receyue &thorn;y creatoure,'</L>
<L>Ones yn &thorn;e &yogh;er&euml;, to knowleche,</L>
<L>&THORN;y lorde to pes, for drede of wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at prest, y blame ouer alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="10304">&THORN;at with-oute skylle letty&thorn; to synge;</L>
<L>For many a soul&euml; my&yogh;t be saued</L>
<L>with &thorn;e messe &thorn;at he ha&thorn; leued;</L>
<L>For al[l&euml;] &thorn;at yn peyn&euml; ys,</L>
<L N="10308">Abyde&thorn; &thorn;e socoure of &thorn;e messe;</L>
<L>For euery messe make&thorn; mem&oacute;rye</L>
<L>Of soules &thorn;at are yn purgat&oacute;rye;</L>
<L>Moch&euml; &thorn;anke shal &thorn;at prest haue,</L>
<L N="10312">&THORN;at helpe&thorn;, hem for to saue;</L>
<L>For no &thorn;yng may hem so moche auayle</L>
<L>Of here peyne and here trauayle,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere,</L>
<L N="10316">Ne make&thorn; hem of peyne so clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at may y<NOTE PLACE="foot">y O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> shewe apertly</L>
<L>By a tale of seint Gregorye;</L>
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn; for &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Priest who was waited on by a Dead Lord whom he afterwards sang out of Purgatory.]</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;er was a prest, Felyx was<NOTE PLACE="foot">was H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> hys name;</L>
<L N="10321">Bysyde hys wonyng yn a pa&thorn;</L>
<L>was a wasshyng yn an hote ba&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys prest &thorn;edyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte &thorn;yder.</NOTE> oft&euml; &yogh;ede<MILESTONE N="68b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To wasshe hym whan he hadd&euml; nede.</L>
<L N="10325">&THORN;ys prest &thorn;ere euer redy fonde
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="322"></L>
<L>A man &thorn;at serued hym to fote and honde;</L>
<L>he drogh hys hosen of, and hys shone,</L>
<L N="10328">And efte was redy hem on to done;</L>
<L>At euery tyme &thorn;at he &thorn;edyr cam,</L>
<L>hys shone and hys hosen, of he nam,</L>
<L>And serued hym at euery a tyde,</L>
<L N="10332">Yn &thorn;e water, and eke besyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys prest, &thorn;at cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">com.</NOTE> &thorn;edyr so ofte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ys man serued so softe,</L>
<L>he ne asked hym neuer more</L>
<L>when he was, ne how he come &thorn;ore;</L>
<L N="10337">But euery tym&euml; was redy</L>
<L>And serued hym peynybl&euml;ly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">penyblely O, peynybly H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys prest &thorn;o&yogh;t he serued hym weyl,</L>
<L>"hys trauayle wyl y quyte sum deyl."</L>
<L N="10341">On o day he &thorn;edyr &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And, twey loues with hym he bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>yn-to &thorn;e ba&thorn;, &yogh;ede &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L N="10344">And, wesshe<NOTE PLACE="foot">wysshe.</NOTE> hym, as he dyd neste:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys man was &thorn;ere hym a&yogh;ayne;</L>
<L>To serue hym weyl, he dyde hys mayne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys preste, whan he shuld fur&thorn;&euml; go,</L>
<L N="10348">He &yogh;aue &thorn;e man &thorn;ese lou&euml;s two,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked hym moche, hys seruyse,</L>
<L>And more he wuld&euml; ou&thorn;er wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys man answered &thorn;e prest a&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ys brede &thorn;ou bro&yogh;test to me yn veyn,</L>
<L N="10353">For neuer mor&euml; shal y ete</L>
<L>Bred&euml;, ne noun ou&thorn;er mete.</L>
<L>Y am a man, &thorn;at ys dede,</L>
<L N="10356">&THORN;at neuer more shal et&euml; brede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e preste asked "on what manere</L>
<L>Ys hyt &thorn;at &thorn;ou wonest &thorn;us here?"</L>
<L>&THORN;ys yche man answered and seyd,</L>
<L N="10360">"Y was lorde here, are y deyde;
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="323"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ys seruyse &thorn;at y am ynne,<MILESTONE N="69a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ys &thorn;e peyn&euml; for my synne;</L>
<L>But y pray &thorn;e, pur charyte,</L>
<L N="10364">Offre on &thorn;e auter &thorn;ese loues for me;</L>
<L>And y beseche &thorn;e, ouer alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at syxe messys for me &thorn;ou synge,</L>
<L>For, were &thorn;ey sunge, y hope to wende</L>
<L N="10368">Yn-to &thorn;e ioye with-outen ende.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e syxt&euml; messe ys lefte,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou ne fynd&euml; me here efte,</L>
<L>know &thorn;ou &thorn;an so&thorn;&euml;ly ywys</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;y prayere y am bro&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">'bro&yogh;t' omitted.</NOTE> yn blys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10373">&thorn;ys prest, alle &thorn;at wok&euml; long,</L>
<L>F&oacute;r &thorn;ys same man preyd and song;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e wok&euml; was alle gone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest cam<NOTE PLACE="foot">com.</NOTE> &thorn;edyr, and fond&euml; none.</L>
<L>he beleued &thorn;an weyl &thorn;at he was bro&yogh;t</L>
<L>To blys, for, he fonde hym no&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;ys tale &thorn;an mowe &yogh;e se,</L>
<L N="10380">&thorn;at hyt ys grete charyte,</L>
<L>Messes for the dede to synge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soul&euml;s oute <SUP>3</SUP>of &thorn;yne to<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 of pyne for to.</NOTE> brynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Passyng alle &thorn;yng, hyt ha&thorn; powere,</L>
<L N="10384">&THORN;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere,</L>
<L>And nam&euml;ly whan hyt ys doun</L>
<L>with god&euml; mannes deuocyun;</L>
<L>Hym, wyl God sunner here</L>
<L N="10388">&thorn;an one &thorn;at ys nat hym so dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e comaundement<NOTE PLACE="marg">[page 73]</NOTE></L>
<L>Touche&thorn; to &thorn;ys sacrament,</L>
<L>Yn a tal&euml; of a kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10392">How &thorn;e prest &thorn;at lyue&thorn; nat ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of hys preyer ys lytyl prowe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere telle&thorn; hyt weyl how;</L>
<L>And y shal telle a-nou&thorn;er here,</L>
<L>Of a mess&euml; of a frere.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="324"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Suffolk Man who was taken out of Purgatory by two Masses his Wife got sung for him.]</HEAD>
<L>A man yn Sou&thorn;folke on&euml;s deyde</L>
<L>Besyd&euml; Sudbyry, men seyde.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at man, swych grace was dy&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="69a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hym was graunted to come a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="10401">For to spek&euml; wy&thorn; hys wyfe</L>
<L>To amende &thorn;e defaute of hys lyfe:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf a messe were for me doun</L>
<L N="10404">with gode mannes deuocyoun,</L>
<L>y hope," he seyd, "to blys go,</L>
<L>And be delyuerd of alle my wo;</L>
<L>Y prey &thorn;e, pur charyte,</L>
<L N="10408">To trauayle so moche for me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She graunted hym &thorn;at ych&euml; bone,</L>
<L>And ros vp on &thorn;e morn&euml; sone,</L>
<L>And, vn-to &thorn;e frer&euml;s &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="10412">For &thorn;ere hoped she best to spede.</L>
<L>She cam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">com.</NOTE> and spak with a frere,</L>
<L>And preyd she my&yogh;t hys mess&euml; here,</L>
<L>And for here housbunde soule to synge,</L>
<L N="10416">And she wulde &yogh;yu&euml; hym offrynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e frere ded here a messe</L>
<L>yn comune, as &thorn;e seruyse ys;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ys mess&euml; sung&euml; was</L>
<L N="10420">She went home a god&euml; pas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ny&yogh;t aftyr, &thorn;an come he,</L>
<L>"Slepest &thorn;ou?" he seyd; 'nay,' seyd she,</L>
<L>'Be &yogh;e &yogh;yt,' she seyd, 'yn blys?</L>
<L N="10424">&thorn;e mess&euml; for &yogh;ow sungen<NOTE PLACE="foot">sunge.</NOTE> ys.'</L>
<L>"&thorn;e messe," he seyde, "&thorn;ou dedyst be do,</L>
<L>A party hyt halp&euml; &thorn;er-vn-to;</L>
<L>My parte y had, of &thorn;at messe,</L>
<L N="10428">As of &thorn;yng &thorn;at comune ys;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf one for me were specyale<NOTE PLACE="foot">were specyaly for me.</NOTE> seyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ou&thorn;er for me blys had nede,&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;e prest were of lyfe so gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">gode O, go H.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="325"></L>
<L N="10432">&THORN;at God hys preyer vndyrstode&mdash;</L>
<L>Y hop&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hopede.</NOTE> &thorn;an, grace to haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys mess&euml; my&yogh;t me saue."</L>
<L>Ofte he seyd[&euml;] to hys wyfe</L>
<L N="10436">"A prest! A prest! of clen&euml; lyfe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;e morn&euml;, sone she &yogh;ede<MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e frer&euml;s eft god spede,</L>
<L>And shewed hyt to &thorn;e pryour,</L>
<L N="10440">And prey[ed] hym of socour,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf he had any bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hoped, were better &thorn;an o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyl syng&euml; me a messe</L>
<L N="10444">For a man &thorn;at ded&euml; ys;</L>
<L>And at myn es&euml; he shal haue,</L>
<L>To a pytaunce, &thorn;at he wyl craue.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e pryor spake vn-to a frere,</L>
<L N="10448">And prey[ed] hym on alle manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wulde a mess&euml; synge</L>
<L>For &thorn;at soule &thorn;at she made preyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e frer&euml; was an holy man;</L>
<L N="10452">And ar &thorn;at he hys messe bygan,</L>
<L>He preyde to God hys orysoun</L>
<L>Yn ful grete afflyccyoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt my&yogh;t be, hym to pay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e messe &thorn;at he shulde synge &thorn;at day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10457">whan &thorn;e messe was do to ende,</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;e womman home to wende;</L>
<L>"And, whan &thorn;ou more eft&euml; heres,</L>
<L N="10460">Cum and sey to our&euml; freres."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e ny&yogh;t aftyr, lestene&thorn; now,</L>
<L>He come,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cum.</NOTE> and seyd, "slepest &thorn;ou?"</L>
<L>'Nay,' she sayd, 'how far&euml; &yogh;e?'</L>
<L N="10464">"weyl," he seyd, "and so wur&thorn; &thorn;e."<NOTE PLACE="inter">most &thorn;ou</NOTE></L>
<L>'were &yogh;e pay[ed] of &thorn;at messe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, for &yogh;ow, sungyn ys?'</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," he seyd, "graunte mercy,</L>
<L N="10468">&THORN;ys messe to me ys more wur&thorn;y</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e worlde, an hunder sy&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="326"></L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;t haue made me halfe so bly&thorn;e;</L>
<L>hys preyer was to God so dere,</L>
<L N="10472">&THORN;at he besoghte, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> wlde he here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he had preyd for an hundred mo,</L>
<L>Fro pyne to blys, he had bro&yogh;t &thorn;o;</L>
<L>For what &thorn;yng he hade asked bone,<MILESTONE N="69b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10476">God had graunted hyt hym as sone;</L>
<L>And haue gode day, for now y wende</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ioye with-outyn ende."</L>
<L>God late vs neuer &thorn;er-of mysse,</L>
<L N="10480">with-outyn ende to haue &thorn;at blys!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys wyfe come son&euml; on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>And fyl on knees &thorn;e frere byforne,</L>
<L N="10483">And told&euml; hym weyl, euery deyl,</L>
<L>How he, for hys prayer, yn ioye was weyl;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e frere ful weyl &thorn;arby lete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked God; and<NOTE PLACE="foot">'and' omitted.</NOTE> for ioye he grete.<NOTE PLACE="inter">wepte</NOTE></L>
<L>weyl were hym at hys endyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at had swych a prest for hym to synge!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10489">Yn &thorn;ys tale, &thorn;an, shewed ys,</L>
<L>Ouer alle gode &thorn;an ys &thorn;e messe;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere</L>
<L N="10492">Oueral passe&thorn; hys powere;</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;at messe, &thorn;ey hem affye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;o.</NOTE> soules &thorn;at are yn purgatorye,</L>
<L>For hyt make&thorn; mencyun of &thorn;e passyun</L>
<L N="10496">As Ihesu Cryst to de&thorn; was doun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone ys offred to &thorn;e fadyr yn heuene</L>
<L>For &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o.</NOTE> soules &thorn;at &thorn;e prest wyl neuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, &thorn;ys tal&euml; wyl mene</L>
<L N="10500">&THORN;at &thorn;e preste be gode and clene;</L>
<L>&THORN;an wyl Ihesu Cryst hym here,</L>
<L>For what &thorn;yng he make&thorn; preyere:</L>
<L>Preye he for body, or for soule,<NOTE PLACE="foot">soule or for bodye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10504">&THORN;at ys yn pyne, or here yn noye,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wyl God almy&yogh;ty saue,</L>
<L>what-so &thorn;e god&euml; prest wyl craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nat only for soules ys he herd,
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="327"></L>
<L N="10508">But also for vs, yn &thorn;ys world;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs here yn &thorn;e werlde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be a man yn sykenes, or yn prysoun,</L>
<L>weyferyng, or yn temptacyun,</L>
<L>Or yn any ou&thorn;er trauayle,</L>
<L N="10512">&THORN;e sacrament wyl vs auayle;</L>
<L>hyt wyl delyuer vs out of peyne,<MILESTONE N="70a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf oure beleu&euml; be certeyne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was weyl shewed yn dede</L>
<L N="10516">Yn Ingland, so sey&thorn; seynt Bede;</L>
<L>Yn hys bokys wrytyn &thorn;yr ys<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>A feyre myr&aacute;cle of &thorn;e messe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Bede's Tale of Jumna and Tumna; or, How an Abbot's Mass|singing made the Fetters fall off a Knight in Prison.]</HEAD>
<L>what tyme seynt Bede was man lyuand,</L>
<L N="10520">were many kyng&euml;s yn &thorn;ys land;</L>
<L>Betwyx&euml; tweyn was grete batayle,</L>
<L>For whych &thorn;yng y telle &thorn;ys merueyle;</L>
<L>&thorn;e toon hyght Edfryde of &thorn;e nor&thorn;e cuntre,</L>
<L N="10524">&thorn;e to&thorn;er of Lynd&euml;seye was he:</L>
<L>Edfryde had grete seygnourye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">seynurrye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Audre housbonde, of Ely.<NOTE PLACE="foot">husb. of St. A. of E.; l. 10689.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ys batayle was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">was O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;urgh here bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e her.</NOTE> assent,</L>
<L N="10528">Besyde a watyr, men calle Trent:</L>
<L>Syre Edfrydes bro&thorn;er hy&yogh;t Elfwynne,</L>
<L>He was slayn &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at.</NOTE> batayle ynne;</L>
<L>On bo&thorn;e partyys, ne was none</L>
<L N="10532">So feyre a kny&yogh;t of flesshe and bone,</L>
<L>Ne so do&yogh;ty was of armes;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore seynt Bede pleyne&thorn; hys harmys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An no&thorn;er kn&yogh;yt also was felte<NOTE PLACE="foot">eke was felde.</NOTE> dowun</L>
<L N="10536">Almoste dede, and fyl yn swoun:</L>
<L>&THORN;e nam&euml; of &thorn;ys &yogh;ung&euml; kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>'Iumna,' sey&thorn; seynt Bede, he hy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ys Iumna had long leyn,</L>
<L N="10540">He couerd, and sette hym vp a&yogh;eyn,
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="328"></L>
<L>And stopped hys woundes, &thorn;ey shuld nat blede,</L>
<L>And as he my&yogh;t, &thorn;enn&euml; he &yogh;ede</L>
<L N="10543">To seke hym helpe agher to haue,</L>
<L>Or frend&euml;s fynde, &thorn;at hym my&yogh;t saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as he wente with moch&euml; drede,</L>
<L>He was take with kyng Eldrede,</L>
<L>And, broght vn-to a lordyng,</L>
<L N="10548">An Erle &thorn;at held&euml; of &thorn;at kyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erle asked hym 'what he was,</L>
<L>And where he had be yn hard kas?'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For drede of de&thorn;, he was affry&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="70a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10552">And durst nat sey he was a kny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He seyd, "seyre, &yogh;yf &thorn;y wyl be,</L>
<L>Y am an husband of &thorn;e cuntre;</L>
<L>Y was wunt to lede vytayle</L>
<L N="10556">To kny&yogh;t&euml;s &thorn;at were yn batayle;</L>
<L>And now y am a por&euml; man,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ys maner fro &thorn;e batayle wan,</L>
<L>And wyl fonde to saue my lyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10560">Tyl y may com&euml; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto.</NOTE> my wyfe."</L>
<L>&THORN;e erle &thorn;an made<NOTE PLACE="foot">made &thorn;an.</NOTE> a leche be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by.</NOTE> stoundes</L>
<L>Tende to hym, to hele hys woundes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at tyme were here many thedys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thedes countries.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10564">Many vs&aacute;ges yn many ledys;</L>
<L>For euery kyng, yn &thorn;at dawe,</L>
<L>Beleued on dyuers lawe;</L>
<L>Sum were crystyn, on oure fay,</L>
<L N="10568">And some beleued on paynyms lay;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;at tyme was mykyl &thorn;ro,</L>
<L>And ofte was bo&thorn;&euml; werre and wo;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf any kyng my&yogh;t of o&thorn;ers men take,</L>
<L>He shuld hem selle, or yn seruage make.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10573">wharfore y telle so of &thorn;ys kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle dyd hym bynde euery ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne shuld[&euml;] fro hem fle,</L>
<L N="10576">Ne stele awey to hys cuntre;</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles,<NOTE PLACE="foot">No&thorn;eles O, No&thorn;ele H.</NOTE> for alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t hym bynde,
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="329"></L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er tyme, lose, &thorn;ey my&yogh;t hym fynde;</L>
<L>S&oacute; fast, &thorn;ey neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer &thorn;ey.</NOTE> hym bonde,</L>
<L N="10580">&THORN;at lose a-no&thorn;er tyme &thorn;ey hym fonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys bound&euml; kny&yogh;t hyght Iumna,</L>
<L>And had a bro&thorn;er &thorn;at hy&yogh;t Tumna;</L>
<L>&thorn;ys Tumna was prest relygyous,</L>
<L N="10584">For he was abbot of an house;</L>
<L>So long he leued yn &thorn;at estre<NOTE PLACE="inter">toune<NOTE PLACE="foot">Oxf. gloss 'a toune.'</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at for hys name he hy&yogh;t Tuncestre;</L>
<L>&THORN;at tounne, as y vndyrstande,</L>
<L N="10588">hyt was yn Northhumber-lande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ys abbot herd tydyng certeyn<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Iumna was yn batayle slayn;</L>
<L>He come to Trent, &thorn;ys abbot Tumna,</L>
<L N="10592">And fonde a body ry&yogh;t lyke Iumna;</L>
<L>On&oacute;urablye he dyd hyt graue</L>
<L>Yn hys cherche, &thorn;ere he wulde hyt haue,</L>
<L>And song &thorn;arfor&euml;, day and ou&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="10596">For he went he<NOTE PLACE="foot">wende hyt (but <I>he</I> is used for the neuter, see ll. 10586, 10786, &amp;c.).</NOTE> had be hys bro&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;at Tumna had chose wrong,</L>
<L>hys bro&thorn;er had &thorn;e godenesse of hys song;</L>
<L>For God alle wote, and wyst hyt &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="10600">For whom he mad&euml; hys preyere;</L>
<L>how as euer men, &thorn;ys kny&yogh;t at eue bonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bondes, on &thorn;e morne, vndo &thorn;ey fonde;</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;t neuer hym yn bondes so feste</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey &thorn;at tyme ne gunne al to-braste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">breste.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10605">&THORN;o men &thorn;at had &thorn;ys man yn holde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys wundyr to &thorn;e erle &thorn;ey tolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e erle had &thorn;er-of gret&euml; wundyr</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10608">&THORN;at hys bondes<NOTE PLACE="foot">bondes O, landes H.</NOTE> were so a sunder,</L>
<L>He seyd 'hym self wulde with hym speke,</L>
<L>To wyt&euml; why hys bondes dyd breke.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before &thorn;e erl&euml; was he fette,</L>
<L N="10612">And &thorn;e erle, ful feyre he grette,</L>
<L>"Sey me now," he seyd, "bele amye,
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="330"></L>
<L>"kanst &thorn;ou weyl on sorcerye?</L>
<L>Sum wycchecrafte &thorn;ou doust aboute bere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">aboute &thorn;ou doust bere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10616">&THORN;at &thorn;y bondes mow &thorn;e nat dere.</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e," he seyd, "sum what &thorn;ou dos,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer-more &thorn;ey fynde &thorn;e los."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he seyd, "on whycchecrafte beleue y no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10620">Ne for me shal none be wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne wyl nat be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;urgh fendys crafte,</L>
<L>Vnbonde, ne with no whycch&euml;crafte.</L>
<L>Syre erle," he seyd, "hyt ys a-nou&thorn;er;</L>
<L N="10624">Yn my cuntre y haue a bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at supposy&thorn; weyl &thorn;at y am<NOTE PLACE="foot">be.</NOTE> slayn,</L>
<L>For y come nat home agayn;</L>
<L>For me he synge&thorn; euery day a messe;<MILESTONE N="70b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10628">Prest, and abbot, for so&thorn;e he ys;</L>
<L>Y wote weyl, &thorn;&aacute;t ys &thorn;e enchesun</L>
<L>&THORN;at my bondes are so ondoun,</L>
<L>For, no &thorn;yng ha&thorn; powere</L>
<L N="10632">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e sacrement of &thorn;e autere;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf y were dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">dede O, de H.</NOTE> yn ou&thorn;er werlde,</L>
<L>hys preyer shulde for me be herde,</L>
<L>To bryng&euml; me of pyne and wo</L>
<L N="10636">And aftyrward to blys[s&euml;] go."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e meyne &thorn;an, and &thorn;e erle,</L>
<L>Supposed weyl he was no cherle,</L>
<L>As he to hem byfore hadde seyd,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ey on hym fyrst hand&euml;s leyd;</L>
<L N="10641">By hys semblant and feyre beryng</L>
<L>Hym semed weyl to be a lordyng;</L>
<L>By hys speche, &thorn;ey vndyrstode</L>
<L N="10644">&THORN;at he was man of gentyl blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e erle toke hym yn pryuyte;</L>
<L>Of when<NOTE PLACE="foot">wenne.</NOTE> he was, telle hym shulde he;</L>
<L>"Sey me &thorn;e so&thorn;e, and, as y am kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne shalt haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">for me haue.</NOTE> for me, ska&thorn;e ne ply&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Syn &yogh;e me behete &yogh;oure pes and gryth,</L>
<L>Y am &thorn;e kyng&euml;s man Edfryth;</L>
<L>Arm&euml;s y bare yn &thorn;e batayle,
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="331"></L>
<L N="10652">with alle my powere hym to auayle."</L>
<L>"So me &thorn;o&yogh;t," seyd &thorn;e erle,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e semed nat to be a cherle;</L>
<L>But, for &thorn;&aacute;t y here &thorn;e seye,</L>
<L N="10656">&THORN;ou were wur&thorn;y for to deye,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hylp&euml; &thorn;er to slo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle my kyn ys dede me fro;</L>
<L>But, langer &thorn;at y sykerd &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="10660">Shalt &thorn;ou haue no ska&thorn;e for me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &yogh;ede and solde hym for raunsoun</L>
<L>At London to a Frysoun,&mdash;</L>
<L>A Frysoun &yogh;e shul vndyrstande</L>
<L N="10664">To a marchaunde of Fryslande;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys Frysun wulde &thorn;ys man fur&thorn;e lede,<MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And, dyd on hym bondes for drede;</L>
<L>For he ne shulde skape<NOTE PLACE="foot">eschape.</NOTE> by &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L>He dyd on hym, bondes for to leye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">He dede bondes on hym to leye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10669">But hyt auayled hym no &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Neuer a day, &thorn;at byndyng;</L>
<L>For yn &thorn;at oure &thorn;at &thorn;e messe was sunge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bondes to-braste, and alle to-sprunge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10673">&THORN;ys Frysoun &thorn;o&yogh;t 'how may &thorn;ys be?</L>
<L>h&eacute; may ry&yogh;t weyl fro me fle;</L>
<L>Chaunsfullyche hyt vayled no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10676">&thorn;e katel &thorn;at y wy&thorn; hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym wy&thorn;.</NOTE> bo&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e Frysoun seyd, "wylt &thorn;ou weyl</L>
<L>Restore a&yogh;en alle my katel,</L>
<L>And y shal &yogh;yue &thorn;e leue to go</L>
<L N="10680">To &thorn;y cuntre, &thorn;ere &thorn;ou come fro;</L>
<L>But fyrst &thorn;ou shalt me trou&thorn;&euml; plyght,</L>
<L>And trewly holde hyt at alle &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;e katel, and &yogh;yue for &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="10684">And ell&euml;s y graunt&euml; &thorn;e nat fre."</L>
<L>he graunted hym alle &thorn;at he seyd,</L>
<L>And trou&thorn;e yn hande with hand[&euml;] leyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ys Iumna went to &thorn;e kyng Loyre,</L>
<L N="10688">&thorn;at was kyng of Kaunterbyre;</L>
<L>he was seynt Audre syster sone,</L>
<L>And Iumna was wonte with here to wone;
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="332"></L>
<L>Of alle hys state, bo&thorn;e wo and wele,</L>
<L N="10692">Iumna tolde &thorn;e kyng euery deyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;an &yogh;aue hym hys raunsoun,</L>
<L>And he bare hyt to Londoun to &thorn;e Frysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sy&thorn;en &yogh;ede he home, &thorn;ys kny&yogh;t Iumna,</L>
<L N="10696">To hys bro&thorn;er &thorn;e abbot Tumna,</L>
<L>And tolde hym of alle hys wo-fare,</L>
<L>And of alle hys cumforte yn alle hys care.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot ful weyl &thorn;an vndyrstode</L>
<L N="10700">&THORN;at hys messe dyd hym grete gode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrament gan hym borowe</L>
<L>Oute of seruage and out of sorowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys tale telle&thorn; vs seynt Bede,<MILESTONE N="71a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10704">Yn &thorn;e gestys of Inglond &thorn;at we rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;ys tal&euml;, mow men lere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e messe helpe&thorn; vs weyl here;</L>
<L>For vs lyuyng, hyt make&thorn; mem&oacute;rye,</L>
<L N="10708">As weyl as for soules yn purgat&oacute;rye;</L>
<L>Euery man shal beleue &thorn;at ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holpe wyl be, as was &thorn;e kny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys sacrament helpe&thorn; nat &yogh;yt a-lone,</L>
<L N="10712">But deuoute offrynges also echone;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at we offre at &thorn;e messe,</L>
<L>Alle oure saluacyun hyt ys;</L>
<L>Nat onely for to saue &thorn;o &thorn;at dede be&thorn;,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e quyke also hyt saue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt saueth also.</NOTE> and rede&thorn;;</L>
<L N="10717">As weyl haue &thorn;e quyke, &thorn;e pru,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e dede, &thorn;ereof vertu;</L>
<L>Quyke and ded&euml;, more and lesse,</L>
<L N="10720">Alle are saued &thorn;urgh &thorn;e masse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e offryng ys also a present</L>
<L>&thorn;at hyt be oure helpe, &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L N="10723">To &thorn;e fadyr of heuene bysyly,</L>
<L>For whom &thorn;ou offrest, to haue mercy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A tale y fond&euml; on&euml;s wryte;</L>
<L>And as y wote, &thorn;an shul &yogh;e wyte;<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>And weyl a-corde&thorn; yn alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="10728">&THORN;at God ys payd of gode offryng.
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="333"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of the Miner, and how his Wife's Offerings for his Soul fed him while he was buried alive in a Mine.]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was a man be&yogh;unde &thorn;e see,</L>
<L>A mynour, woned yn a cyte,&mdash;</L>
<L N="10731">Mynurs, &thorn;ey make yn hyllys holes,</L>
<L>As yn &thorn;e west cuntre men seke coles.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys mynur so&yogh;te stones vndyr &thorn;e molde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men make of, syluer and golde;</L>
<L>he wro&yogh;t on a day, and holed yn &thorn;e hyl;</L>
<L N="10736">A perylous chaunc&euml; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto.</NOTE> hym fyl;</L>
<L>For, a grete party of &thorn;at yche myne</L>
<L>Fyl dowun yn &thorn;e hole, and closed hym ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hys felaus alle, &thorn;at were hym hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he were dede, weyl so&thorn;ely wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &yogh;ede and toke hem alle to rede,<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10742">And tolde hys wyfe &thorn;at he was dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys womman pleyned here husbonde sore&mdash;</L>
<L>wulde God &thorn;at many swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swyche many.</NOTE> wommen wore!&mdash;</L>
<L N="10745">She hylpe hys soule yn all&euml; &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>In alm&euml;s dede, and yn offryng;</L>
<L>She offred for hym to &thorn;e auter,</L>
<L N="10748">Ful of wyn&euml;, a pecher,</L>
<L>And a feyr&euml; lofe with-alle,</L>
<L>Euery day as for a pryncypalle;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at twelue mone&thorn; stab&euml;ly,</L>
<L N="10752">But o day &thorn;at passed forby.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fewe swyche wymmen now we fynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to here husbondes are so kynde!</L>
<L>But &thorn;ys wyfe, at alle here my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10756">Ded for hym bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyl hyt at &thorn;e twelue mone&thorn; ende,</L>
<L>Hys felaws to &thorn;e mounteyne gun wende,</L>
<L>And com&euml; to &thorn;e same stede efte,
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="334"></L>
<L N="10760">&THORN;ere &thorn;ey last here werk [i-]lefte.</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere, &thorn;ey fyrst bygan,</L>
<L>And perced &thorn;urgh vn-to &thorn;ys man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e man yn god&euml; state &thorn;ey fonde,</L>
<L N="10764">lyuyng with-out&euml; wem or wounde;</L>
<L>Euerychone, &thorn;ey hadde grete ferly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was gret&euml; resun why;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o men were yn grete were,</L>
<L N="10768">How he had lyued alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>But he tolde hem euerychone</L>
<L>How he hadde lyued &thorn;ere alone;</L>
<L>"Y haue lyued gracyous lyfe,</L>
<L N="10772">&THORN;urgh &thorn;e curtesye of my wyfe,</L>
<L>For euery day she ha&thorn; me sent</L>
<L>Brede and wyn&euml; to present;</L>
<L>But o day certys ete y no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="10776">For, no mete was to me bro&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ey led<NOTE PLACE="foot">ledde.</NOTE> &thorn;ys man vnto &thorn;e tounne,</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;ys myracle vp and dounne,</L>
<L>Fyrst, &thorn;ur[o]gh &thorn;e cyte,<MILESTONE N="71b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="10780">And se&thorn;&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn;&thorn;e O, se&thorn; H.</NOTE> &thorn;ur[o]gh &thorn;e cuntre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey asked hym, at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;at he dyd[&euml;] faste;</L>
<L>He tolde hem &thorn;e day[&euml;]s name,</L>
<L N="10784">And hys wyf&euml; seyd &thorn;e same;</L>
<L>&THORN;at day she offred neuer a deyl;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode fryday, he my&yogh;t be weyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now mow &yogh;e here, &thorn;at alm&euml;s dede,</L>
<L N="10788">Gost&euml;ly a man wyl fede,</L>
<L>And so mow &yogh;e weyl vndyrstande</L>
<L>&THORN;at God ys payd of gode offrande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But f&oacute;r alle &thorn;ys tale, yn &yogh;oure lyues,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>note</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10792">Truste &yogh;e nat moche &oacute;n &yogh;oure wyues,</L>
<L>Ne on &yogh;oure chyldryn, for no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>But make&thorn; &yogh;e self, &yogh;oure offryng:
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="335"></L>
<L>For, so kynde a womman as y of tolde,</L>
<L N="10796">lyue&thorn; nat now, be &thorn;ou bolde;</L>
<L>Ne no clerk, &thorn;at &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> ryme redys,</L>
<L>Shal fynde a womman of so kynde dedes.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e men &thorn;at are now yn present,</L>
<L>&thorn;at haue herd me rede &thorn;ys sacrament,</L>
<L N="10801">how ouer alle &thorn;yng hyt ha&thorn; powere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere,</L>
<L>As y haue here to &yogh;ow shewed</L>
<L>&mdash;Nat to lered onely, but eke to lewed,&mdash;</L>
<L N="10805">&YOGH;e lewed men, y telle hyt &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>&THORN;ese clerkys kun<NOTE PLACE="foot">kunne.</NOTE> hyt weyl y-now,</L>
<L>Pray we<NOTE PLACE="foot">Preye we now.</NOTE> alle oure creatoure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">creatour O, creature H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10808">&THORN;e sacrament oure sauyoure,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sauueour.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at body and soule he wyl vs saue,</L>
<L>And we hym loue, and he vs haue!<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Vernon MS. borrowing ends here.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>[Of Penance.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The four&thorn;e sacr&aacute;ment ys penaunce,</L>
<L N="10812">&THORN;at ys for synn&euml; a quytaunce;</L>
<L>God graunte vs alle, penaunce to do,</L>
<L>For we haue gret&euml; nede &thorn;arto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys, &thorn;an, synn&euml; &thorn;o</L>
<L N="10816">&THORN;at to shryft&euml; onely go</L>
<L>with-oute any man&eacute;r of smert<MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of felyng, of sorowe of hert;</L>
<L N="10819">Euery man shulde haue a-fore &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>How and whan hys synne was wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And be&thorn;enke hym weyl on<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> euery dede,</L>
<L>Fyrst are he to shryft&euml; &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>Elles, asoyled may he nat be clene,</L>
<L N="10824">Of for&yogh;et&euml; synnes, y mene.</L>
<L>Ouer lytyl fors certys he &yogh;yue&thorn;</L>
<L>Of any penaunce, or how he lyue&thorn;;
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>Swych&euml; men, here synne &thorn;ey synke,</L>
<L N="10828">&thorn;at recch&euml; nat &thorn;er-on to &thorn;ynke.</L>
<L>Some men, whan here synne ys wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hyt no more<NOTE PLACE="foot">more eft.</NOTE> cum&thorn; yn here &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue&thorn; no fors,<NOTE PLACE="foot">force.</NOTE> &thorn;at he for&yogh;ete&thorn;</L>
<L N="10832">hys synne; and hym &thorn;e fend ete&thorn;.</L>
<L>leuer ys hym late hem alle weyue,</L>
<L>&thorn;an any hard penaunce receyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt haue &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L N="10836">&THORN;e behoue&thorn; &yogh;yue weyl bettyr entent,</L>
<L>And record&euml; euery dede</L>
<L>with sorow of herte, and with drede,</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ynke, with moch&euml; mone,</L>
<L N="10840">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne mayst &thorn;enk on echone;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou shryue &thorn;e euery deyl</L>
<L>Of &thorn;o, &thorn;at &thorn;e mene&thorn; weyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne lett&euml; for no shame</L>
<L N="10844">To tell&euml; opunly &thorn;y blame:</L>
<L>Swyche a man &thorn;at &thorn;us ys shryue,</L>
<L>May be asoyled, and penaunce &yogh;yue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>penaunce may be &yogh;yue to none</L>
<L N="10848">But he shryue hys synnes echone,</L>
<L>And be of god&euml; r&eacute;pentaunce;</L>
<L>No prest may elles &yogh;yue hym penaunce;</L>
<L>Penaunce pyne&thorn; &thorn;y flessh and<NOTE PLACE="foot">'and' omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L>And plesy&thorn; God, and maky&thorn; hym frende.</L>
<L N="10853">Aftyr, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;enk on &thorn;at</L>
<L>Synne &thorn;at &thorn;ou yn shryfte for&yogh;at,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art holde to telle hyt &thorn;y prest<MILESTONE N="72a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou hast mynde &thorn;er-of yn brest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;ou hast &thorn;y synne forsake,</L>
<L N="10858">And &thorn;y penaunce &thorn;er-for&euml; take,</L>
<L>For&yogh;ete nat &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne do
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="337"></L>
<L N="10860">&THORN;e penaunce &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> ioyne&thorn; &thorn;e to.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou for&yogh;etest, &thorn;ou shalt bey<NOTE PLACE="foot">bye.</NOTE> hyt harde</L>
<L>yn purgat&oacute;rye aftyrwarde;</L>
<L>For o day &thorn;at &thorn;ou for&yogh;etest here,</L>
<L N="10864">A &yogh;ere, &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt by hyt dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou fallest eft yn synne,</L>
<L>Efte &thorn;y shryfte alle newe bygynne,</L>
<L N="10867">And do gode ded&euml;s &thorn;er-with-alle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at es<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> of penaunce pryncypalle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou ne do, verrement</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest yn &thorn;ys sacrament;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;at man, hyt ys grete drede,</L>
<L N="10872">&THORN;at wy&thorn;dragh&thorn; hym fro god&euml; dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many man also &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;ys &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>'&thorn;at werk of penaunce auayle&thorn; no&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e whylys &thorn;at he ys yn synne;'</L>
<L>But &thorn;an had he most nede to bygynne;</L>
<L N="10877">For god&euml; ded&euml;s and penaunce</L>
<L>Reysyn a man to r&eacute;pentaunce;</L>
<L>For many &thorn;yng&euml;s, gode hyt ys,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt auayle hym naght yn blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e prest wote neuer what he menes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for lytyl, curse&thorn; hys parysshenes;</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche shepard &yogh;yue&thorn; no gode kepe,</L>
<L N="10884">&THORN;at beteche&thorn; &thorn;e wulfe hys shepe;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last acounte shal he mysfalle,</L>
<L>whan he shal answere for hem alle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lord&euml; shal &thorn;e shepard hate,</L>
<L>&thorn;at waste&thorn; hys store, and brynge&thorn; o gate;</L>
<L N="10889">&THORN;e lord&euml; bo&yogh;t &thorn;e shepe ful dere,</L>
<L>lese hem nat &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat &thorn;an O, no&yogh;t H.</NOTE> so ly&yogh;tly here;</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh; &thorn;ey outrage, and do foly,</L>
<L N="10892">He shal nat sle hem with felony;
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="338"></L>
<L>he shal hem chastyse with smert<NOTE PLACE="foot">lewede.</NOTE> speche,<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with small baytynges, and nat with wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;e gode shepard kepy&thorn; hys shepe,</L>
<L>So shalle &thorn;e prest, hys parysshenes kepe;</L>
<L N="10897">&THORN;ere shepe gone wrong besyde &thorn;e pa&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e shepard crye&thorn; for drede of ska&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ey wyl nat at hys crye</L>
<L N="10900">Turne a&yogh;en to here pasture nye,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sette&thorn; he on hys hounde,</L>
<L>And bayte&thorn; hem a wel gode stounde,</L>
<L>And brynge&thorn; hem to her pasture weyl,</L>
<L N="10904">Ne sle&thorn; he &yogh;yt none, neuer a deyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>with &thorn;ese prestes hyt shulde fare so,</L>
<L>whan here parysshenes oghte mysdo;</L>
<L>wy&thorn; feyre techyng, and god&euml; spelles,</L>
<L N="10908">And stoutly, whan &thorn;ey wyl nat elles,</L>
<L>And with ordynaryys of holy cherche,</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;at &thorn;ey wyl ry&yogh;tly werche;</L>
<L>Nat with cursyng, &thorn;at es<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> slaghter euyl,</L>
<L N="10912">So sone betake hem to &thorn;e deuyl.</L>
<L>Haue to hem swych charyte</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wuldest God hadde to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>kowardyse hyt ys, and foule maystry,</L>
<L N="10916">To &thorn;rowe a faucoun at euery flye;</L>
<L>Of flyes men mow hem weyl spourge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;rowe to hem naght but a scourge;</L>
<L>No more shal no prest &thorn;rawe,</L>
<L N="10920">But a scorge, &thorn;at ys loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ys loue.</NOTE> awe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lewed man, &thorn;ou shalt cursyng doute,</L>
<L>And to<NOTE PLACE="foot">'to' omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;y prest &thorn;ou shalt nat stoute;</L>
<L>Be he wykked, or be he gode,</L>
<L N="10924">&THORN;ou shalt to hym be &thorn;ol&euml;mode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt ys nat a lytyl &thorn;yng</L>
<L>For to fall&euml; yn cursyng,</L>
<L>For hyt reue&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;y gostly frendes,</L>
<L N="10928">And beteche&thorn; &thorn;e vn-to &thorn;e fendes,</L>
<L>And hyt forbarre&thorn; alle gode dedes
<PB REF="00000347.tif" N="339"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e shuld helpe yn alle &thorn;y nedes,</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;ou com to amend&euml;ment<MILESTONE N="72b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with penaunce, &thorn;at ys, &thorn;ys sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10933">Yn sacrylage, y tolde a tale</L>
<L>how cursyng brewe&thorn; moch&euml; bale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e &yogh;ere hopped aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wulde nat &thorn;e prestys byddyng doute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10937">Now wyl we leu&euml;, at &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ys O, &thorn;s H.</NOTE> tyme,</L>
<L>Of penaunce mor&euml; for to ryme,</L>
<L>For y shal tell&euml; &thorn;er-of more</L>
<L N="10940">At shryft&euml;, whan y com&euml; &thorn;ore;</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue me grac&euml; so to telle,</L>
<L>To sham&euml; alle &thorn;e fendes of helle!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>[Of the Fifth Sacrament&mdash;Holy Orders.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw of &thorn;e fyf&thorn;&euml; sacrament,</L>
<L>&THORN;e order of &thorn;e bysshopes presentement.</L>
<L N="10945">&thorn;ys falle&thorn; to &thorn;ese lordynges,</L>
<L>As pop&euml;s, emperoures, and kynges,</L>
<L>And to alle &thorn;at clerkys auaunce</L>
<L N="10948">To holy cherches portynaunce;<NOTE PLACE="foot">purtynaunce.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swyche men, &thorn;at are of grete nobley,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ys sacrament &thorn;an synne &thorn;ey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey graunte, for mede &thorn;at &thorn;ey take,</L>
<L N="10952">Vnwur&thorn;yly, a bysshope to make,</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at ys &thorn;e fam&euml; ryfe</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ys, of febyl lyfe,</L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er to auaunce, hyt ys folye,</L>
<L N="10956">wy&thorn;outyn resonable clergye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Clerk behoue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">behouede.</NOTE> hym for to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shulde receyue swyche dygnyte</L>
<L>For to gouerne holy cherche;</L>
<L>with clergy, behoue&thorn; hym algate werche.</L>
<L N="10961">But now ys fulfylled &thorn;e prophecye</L>
<L>&THORN;at, sor&euml; wepyng, sey&thorn; Isaye,</L>
<L>"Ry&yogh;t swych shal be &thorn;e prest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syllables</I>]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="340"></L>
<L N="10964">As &thorn;e lewed man lyue, &thorn;ou sest."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>lytyl kan lasse &thorn;e lewed man</L>
<L>&thorn;an some of &thorn;es&euml; prest&euml;s kan.</L>
<L>who &yogh;yuen hem more to worldly &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&thorn;an prest&euml;s do, for alle here prechyng?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10969">&yogh;yf he be clerk, and euyl dous,<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of hym ys nat to make no rous.</L>
<L>what vayle&thorn; to vndyrstonde &thorn;e lettyr,</L>
<L N="10972">And hys lyfe be neuer &thorn;e bettyr?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at clergye, y telle it but lore,</L>
<L>when he lyue&thorn; neuer &thorn;e bettyr &thorn;er-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But how sey&thorn; Salamon yn hys spellyng,</L>
<L N="10976">"wo &thorn;e land, &thorn;ere chylde ys kyng!"</L>
<L>And wo &thorn;e folk, &thorn;at kan nat lyue</L>
<L>whan holy cherch&euml; ys mys-&yogh;yue!</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e husbonde, wo ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> hys lyfe,</L>
<L N="10980">&thorn;at ha&thorn; yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">'hys' omitted.</NOTE> hous a fole to wyfe!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;e lordes, do &yogh;e Goddes ordynaunce,</L>
<L>And god&euml; men &yogh;e shul auaunce;</L>
<L N="10983">To gode men &yogh;yue&thorn; &yogh;oure benefyces</L>
<L>&THORN;at kun hem kepe fro wykked vyces;</L>
<L>&THORN;an make &yogh;e gode present&euml;ment</L>
<L>To order of &thorn;ys sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, ha&thorn; he wykkedly doun</L>
<L N="10988">&THORN;at lette&thorn; gode mannes eleccyoun;</L>
<L>'Eleccyoun' ys, 'weyl chesyng</L>
<L>A gode man to kepe holy &thorn;yng.'</L>
<L>&THORN;ese hygh&euml; men do grete trespas,</L>
<L N="10992">&THORN;at chese nat ry&yogh;t, alas! alas!</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t were wur&thorn;y, hem &thorn;ey spare,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e vnwur&thorn;y auaunced are;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at ys nat lytyl synne</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at hyt &yogh;yuen, and eke so wynne;</L>
<L N="10997">Hyt may be tolde for symonye,</L>
<L>For &yogh;yfte to auaunce &thorn;e vnwur&thorn;y.
<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="341"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By a tale, y may &yogh;ow shewe</L>
<L N="11000">&thorn;at hyt ys synne to chese a shrewe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt ys he yn wers entent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at lette&thorn; gode mannes auaunc&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Gregory telle&thorn; &thorn;arfore a tale<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at tel&thorn; many one, what grete and smale,</L>
<L N="11005">he telle&thorn; mo hymself a-lone,</L>
<L>&thorn;an alle &thorn;e doctours do echone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of Paschasius's Punish|ment for not agreeing to the Election of the best Man for Pope.]</HEAD>
<L>Yn &thorn;e cherche of Rome, he telle&thorn; &thorn;us,<MILESTONE N="73a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11008">A dekene was &thorn;at hyghte Pascasyus,</L>
<L>A man of alm&euml;s &thorn;an was he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ofte of &thorn;e por&euml; had pyte;</L>
<L>&THORN;at yche tyme was elleccyone</L>
<L N="11012">To chese here pope, as er<NOTE PLACE="foot">ere.</NOTE> was wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twey men were yn choys to take,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er Laurence, o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">or.</NOTE> Symake;</L>
<L>hys felaus alle, Symakus chese,</L>
<L N="11016">So &thorn;at Laurence hys voys lese;</L>
<L>Pascasyus graunted neuer &thorn;artyl,</L>
<L>But chese Laurence at hys owne wyl;</L>
<L>He repented hym neuer no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11020">But yn Laurenc&euml; stode hys &thorn;o&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn &thorn;ys popes tyme, syre Symakus,</L>
<L>Deyde &thorn;e dekene Pascasyus:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys dekene was an holy man,</L>
<L N="11024">As yn &thorn;e cuntre &thorn;e fam&euml; ran,</L>
<L>And dyd &thorn;ys myr&aacute;cle, as &yogh;e mowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">may.</NOTE> here:</L>
<L>A wode man touched on hys bere,</L>
<L>And a party of hys clo&thorn;yng,
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="342"></L>
<L N="11028">And a-none he hadde botenyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>long&euml;, aftyr &thorn;at &thorn;ys was,</L>
<L>Fyl of &thorn;ys dekene a merueylous kas;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere besyd&euml;, yn a pa&thorn;</L>
<L N="11032">was a wasshyng, at an hote ba&thorn;;</L>
<L>'Termes' men calle &thorn;at watyr wasshele,</L>
<L>For many one had &thorn;erat here hele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e holy bysshope seynt Germyne</L>
<L N="11036">Com &thorn;edyr to be wasshe &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere fonde he &thorn;ys dekene Pascas,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> watyr seruyng was:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys bysshope merueyled yn hys &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11040">whe&thorn;er hyt were Pascas or no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste, seynt Germyne seyde</L>
<L>"Art &thorn;ou nat Pascas &thorn;at deyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we helde a man holy?"</L>
<L N="11044">"&YOGH;ys," seyd Pascas, "hyt am y;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;ys water, serue y &thorn;us,<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For y graunted neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat.</NOTE> to Symakus,</L>
<L>But to Laurence, with alle my my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11048">&THORN;at was nat so gode yn Goddys sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>y ne repented yn alle my hope,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat in al myn hope.</NOTE></L>
<L>For y wulde haue hadde hym pope.</L>
<L>But wuldest &thorn;ou prey for me, Germyne,</L>
<L N="11052">y shulde come sone oute of &thorn;ys pyne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> mayst &thorn;ou wete yn &thorn;ys manere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou fynde me no more here."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e bysshope Germyne, home he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L N="11056">And preyd to God for hys mysdede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e next&euml; tyme &thorn;at he come &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Of Pascas, sagh he no more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lok&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Loke&thorn;.</NOTE> lordes, how &yogh;e mysdo,</L>
<L N="11060">&THORN;at eleccyoun dystrouble&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dystourble&thorn;.</NOTE> so;</L>
<L>For a &yogh;yfte, or a pres&eacute;nt,
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="343"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e suffre holy cherche to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> be shent;</L>
<L>&YOGH;our&euml; synn&euml; shal be greuous,</L>
<L N="11064">whan &thorn;ys dekene Pascasyus,</L>
<L>For so lytyl, to purgatorye &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>For whom was shewed myr&aacute;cle yn dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens God, he ys nat quyte,</L>
<L N="11068">&THORN;at suffre&thorn; for hys owne profyte,</L>
<L>Holy cherche, wrongly be &yogh;yue</L>
<L>To &thorn;o men &thorn;at wykkedly lyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey shul be a-couped of tresoun,</L>
<L N="11072">As traytours yn eleccyoun;</L>
<L>Many shul go a deuyl wey,</L>
<L>Or be encumbred or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar.</NOTE> &thorn;ey dey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt shal y telle, among &thorn;ese talys,</L>
<L N="11076">A tale &thorn;at now late fyl yn Wales:</L>
<L>yn &thorn;e tyme of seynt Dauy</L>
<L>Fyl &thorn;ys &thorn;yng, a grete ferly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[A Tale of Warning against buying Bishoprics, and worshipping Bad Bishops' Bodies.]</HEAD>
<L>As &thorn;e munk&euml;s shulde do werche</L>
<L N="11080">werk &thorn;at fyl vn-to here cherche,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey dalue dowun yn &thorn;e clay,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey fonde a bysshope alle hole lay,</L>
<L>with flesshe and blode, and hole sendal,<MILESTONE N="73b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11084">And, wy&thorn; ou&thorn;er vestement alle,</L>
<L>As fressh&euml; as he were depeynt.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wende he had be a corseynt;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey toke hym vp, euerychone,</L>
<L N="11088">And, leyd hym vppon a stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a tumbe of stone.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wurscheped hyt moche with-alle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey wende myr&aacute;cles shulde falle.</L>
<L>At hygh feste tym&euml;s of &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;ey ensensed &thorn;e body as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as H O,? for 'at.'</NOTE> &thorn;e hygh autere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11093">A ny&yogh;t, whan &thorn;e sekesteyn yn bede was leyd,</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;o&yogh;t one come, and to hym seyd,
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="344"></L>
<L>"Ensense &thorn;e body no more so,</L>
<L N="11096">Ne do no wurschep &thorn;ar-vnto."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sekesteyn, for alle &thorn;at defense,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt he &yogh;aue &thorn;e body ensense.</L>
<L>Anou&thorn;er ny&yogh;t, f&oacute;r &thorn;at same,</L>
<L N="11100">Efte &thorn;e sekesteyn he gan blame,</L>
<L>and seyd, "holde hyt no more yn prys,</L>
<L>&thorn;at yche body, &thorn;at &thorn;ere lys."</L>
<L>&thorn;e munk&euml; seyd, "telle me why</L>
<L N="11104">&thorn;at he to wurschep<NOTE PLACE="foot">to be wrshepede.</NOTE> ne ys wur&thorn;y."</L>
<L>"loke to morne, and &thorn;ou mayst wyte</L>
<L>what ly&thorn; yn hys mytyr wryte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e munk&euml; ros vp on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L N="11108">And, fonde yn hys mytyr horne</L>
<L>&THORN;es&euml; verse wryte on a scrowe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he shulde &thorn;e bettyr trowe:</L>
<L>&THORN;ese are &thorn;o ych&euml; twey verse,</L>
<L N="11112">&THORN;at to holynes are reuers,</L>
<L><I>Quem lapis ille tegit, sandalia viliter emit;</I></L>
<L><I>Estuat in baratro, pessimus ille latro</I>.</L>
<L>"he &thorn;at &thorn;ys stone hyle&thorn; one<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> lyche,</L>
<L N="11116">wykkedly bo&yogh;t hys bysshopryche.</L>
<L>yn helle he welle&thorn; pyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn pyne.</NOTE> grefe,</L>
<L>For al&thorn;erwerst<NOTE PLACE="foot">al&thorn;erwest.</NOTE> &thorn;an was he &thorn;efe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al&thorn;erwerst<NOTE PLACE="foot">al&thorn;erwest.</NOTE> &thorn;en shal hem be,</L>
<L N="11120">&THORN;at for mede come to dygnyte.</L>
<L>hyt ys nat to speke, ne to<NOTE PLACE="foot">'to' omitted.</NOTE> preche,<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e clergye werche<NOTE PLACE="foot">werche&thorn;.</NOTE> moche aftyr wreche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt no ded&euml; werche,</L>
<L N="11124">No&thorn;er to iangle, yn holy cherche;</L>
<L>Namely yn tyme of holy feste,</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;n shuld&euml; men iangle leste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme make many one, gaderyng</L>
<L N="11128">yn holy cherche of ydul &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>And of alle shalt &thorn;ou &yogh;elde acounte,</L>
<L>To whos godenesse hyt shuld amounte.</L>
<L>y haue touched of &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych.</NOTE> outrage
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="345"></L>
<L N="11132">whan y spake of sacrylage.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 292]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou oghtes<NOTE PLACE="foot">oghtest.</NOTE> nat to be enchesun</L>
<L>To sturble mannys deuocyoun.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou ne wylte Goddes seruyse here,</L>
<L N="11136">lette none ou&thorn;er of here preyere;</L>
<L>Fole ys, &thorn;at foly &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;at' omitted.</NOTE> wyl nat drede,</L>
<L>And more &thorn;at lette&thorn; alle o&thorn;er gode dede.</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t so<NOTE PLACE="foot">so O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> sey&thorn; Salamon &thorn;e wyse,</L>
<L N="11140">Vs alle of foly to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to.</NOTE> chastyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Clerk to bete, or handes on ley</L>
<L>yn vyolence, hyt ys grete eye;</L>
<L>Hyt longe&thorn; to &thorn;ys sacrament</L>
<L N="11144">&THORN;urgh bysshop&euml;s commaund&euml;ment;</L>
<L>yn sacrylag&euml; &thorn;er y spake,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 280]</NOTE></L>
<L>y touched of &thorn;at ych&euml; lak;</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e ten commaund&euml;mens,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 72, 77]</NOTE></L>
<L N="11148">y wene y touched of &thorn;ys defens;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor&euml;, now hyt ys beste,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ys sacrament to reste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God graunt&euml; &thorn;es&euml; lordynges,</L>
<L N="11152">weyl to do yn all&euml; &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L>And late hem neuer here soul&euml;s lese</L>
<L>For no wrong&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">no wrons O, wronges H.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ey chese!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>[Of the Sixth Sacrament,&mdash;Marriage.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The syxte sacrament ys matrymony,</L>
<L N="11156">&THORN;&eacute;re hyt ys do ry&yogh;twusly;</L>
<L>God comaunde&thorn; yn hys boke</L>
<L>&THORN;at man shuld&euml; hyt weyl loke;</L>
<L>For he stabled hyt yn paradys,<MILESTONE N="74a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11160">hyt ys holde yn &thorn;e mor&euml; prys;</L>
<L>And yn Kana<NOTE PLACE="foot">kana of.</NOTE> Galyle</L>
<L>He turnede water yn wyne to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ys ych&euml; sacrament
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="346"></L>
<L N="11164">Do many on&euml; verrement;</L>
<L>yn &thorn;ys, do &thorn;o men ful ylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wedden any a&yogh;ens here wylle;</L>
<L>Here wyl behoue&thorn; to-gedyr consente,</L>
<L N="11168">Are &thorn;e prest do &thorn;e sacrament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou ne shalt [not] do &thorn;y my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at two be weddyd with vnry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Synne &thorn;ou wystest &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="11172">with no skyl togedyr be bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou synnest moche &thorn;urgh &thorn;ys resun,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey mow neuer be weyl vndoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ou shalt nat, for no gode&mdash;</L>
<L N="11176">&thorn;o&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ogh.</NOTE> hyt be &thorn;yn own&euml; blode&mdash;</L>
<L>Dysturble hyt &thorn;ere hyt o&yogh;t to be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey haue do h&eacute;re wyl fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11179">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wost &thorn;e so&thorn;e of euery deyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at two are weddyd, and o&yogh;t nat weyl,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou shewe hyt, &thorn;ou dost grete synne</L>
<L>To one &thorn;at may do bote &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;us ys &thorn;e gospel sawe,</L>
<L N="11184">And &thorn;e same sey&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sey&thorn; &thorn;e.</NOTE> land&euml;s lawe,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at who so consente&thorn; to a &thorn;efe,</L>
<L>Euene peyne shul &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey shul.</NOTE> haue grefe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of foly trou&thorn;&euml;s &thorn;at are &yogh;yue,</L>
<L N="11188">&THORN;are-of byfore y haue &yogh;ow shryue;</L>
<L>Y haue tolde hyt as y cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>How men falsen here trou&thorn;es with mou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>whan y spake of lecherye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 234]</NOTE></L>
<L N="11192">Y spak&euml; &thorn;er of &thorn;at foly,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;e syxt&euml; commaundment<NOTE PLACE="marg">[p. 58]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere spek&thorn; hyt of &thorn;ys asent;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore nede&thorn; me nat here</L>
<L N="11196">To spek&euml; more of &thorn;ys matere;</L>
<L>But, y pray euery man<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at hys crystendom loue&thorn;, or kan,
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="347"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey neuer swych &thorn;yng graunte,</L>
<L N="11200">Two to wedde of fals cunnaunte;</L>
<L>For many come neuer yn wedlak</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e fyrst cunnaunt &thorn;at men spak.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also, for men by-hete hem largely,</L>
<L N="11204">Are chyldryn wedded ofte for-&thorn;y;</L>
<L>For &thorn;yr are many wedded for gode,</L>
<L>And for no stedfast loue of blode,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at ys no<NOTE PLACE="foot">no O, &thorn;e H.</NOTE> ry&yogh;t weddyng;</L>
<L N="11208">Hyt queme&thorn; nat to heuene kyng.</L>
<L>Many one wedde&thorn; euery deyl</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of syre kateyl;</L>
<L>whan hyt ys go, and ys alle bare,</L>
<L N="11212">&thorn;an ys &thorn;e weddyng sorowe &amp; kare;</L>
<L>loue ande catel &thorn;an ys awey,</L>
<L>And 'welaweye' &thorn;ey cry and sey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;e men &thorn;at brekyn cunnaunte,</L>
<L N="11216">&YOGH;e selfe falsen &thorn;at &yogh;e fyrst graunte;</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys weddelak &thorn;urgh &yogh;ow shent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e fyrst sacrament;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shende hyt wy&thorn; &yogh;oure fals behetyng,</L>
<L N="11220">And &thorn;ey no&yogh;t wedd&euml; but &thorn;e &thorn;yng;</L>
<L>So, betwyxe fals and coueytous,</L>
<L>ys welawey&euml; bro&yogh;t to hous.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ys my&yogh;t men moch&euml; speke,</L>
<L N="11224">But leuer ys me my mou&thorn;e to steke</L>
<L>&THORN;an y spak o&yogh;t oute of skore,</L>
<L>For sone y my&yogh;t be blamed &thorn;arfore.</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue hem grace, &thorn;o &thorn;at shul wedde,</L>
<L N="11228">Yn ry&yogh;t wedlak be bro&yogh;t to bedde;</L>
<L>And delyuer hem of here wyues</L>
<L>&THORN;at oute of skyle chyden and stryues!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sacrament">
<HEAD>[Of the Seventh Sacrament,&mdash;Aneylyng or Extreme Unction.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11231">Now of &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e sacrament:</L>
<L>&THORN;ese clerkys kalle hyt 'oynament,'</L>
<L>On Englys hyt ys 'anelyng'</L>
<L>whan man shal make hys endyng;
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="348"></L>
<L>Seynt Iam&euml; stable[d] hyt for to be<MILESTONE N="74b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11236">A sacrament &thorn;urgh crystyanyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou aske hyt wy&thorn; gode wyl,</L>
<L>Of wykked gostes gest<NOTE PLACE="foot">getest.</NOTE> &thorn;ou noun yl,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e fende ha&thorn; no powere</L>
<L N="11240">&thorn;y body for to com&euml; nere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou of dedly synne be shryue,</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at are venyal be&thorn; &thorn;e for&yogh;yue;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou mayst &thorn;an sykerly go &thorn;y weye,</L>
<L>what tyme as euer &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11245">&YOGH;e &thorn;at loue &thorn;ys sacrament,</L>
<L>Here mowe &yogh;e lerne, &yogh;yue&thorn; gode entent.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tym&euml; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ou trowest &thorn;at.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt wende,</L>
<L N="11248">And draghest vn-to &thorn;y lyu&euml;s ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt aske deuout&euml;ly</L>
<L>Anelyng to &thorn;y body;</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ogh.</NOTE> hyt be bro&yogh;t redy to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="11252">Asked behoue&thorn; hyt algate be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou vnwetyng hyt haue,</L>
<L>hyt helpe&thorn; &thorn;e nat so moche to saue</L>
<L>As &yogh;yf &thorn;ou asked<NOTE PLACE="foot">askedest.</NOTE> hyt by name;</L>
<L N="11256">&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e apostle seynt Iame;</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ou askest hyt with gode wyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mekyst &thorn;e &thorn;an to fulfyl</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacramentes of holy cherche</L>
<L N="11260">with beleue, and gostely to werche;</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys holy cherche holde &thorn;urgh ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>To pray for &thorn;e bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt ys to be holde yn prys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn gret prys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="11264">For hyt saue&thorn; man on twey partys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule hyt brynge&thorn; to saluacyoun,</L>
<L>And for hele of body hyt ys doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But many one &thorn;us hope and seye,</L>
<L N="11268">'Anele hem nat but &thorn;ey shulde deye;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf he turne a&yogh;en to lyfe,</L>
<L>He shulde lygge no more<NOTE PLACE="foot">no more lygge.</NOTE> by hys wyfe.'</L>
<L>Al &thorn;o &thorn;at beleue&thorn; &thorn;ys,
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="349"></L>
<L N="11272">wykkedly &thorn;ey beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">beleue&thorn;.</NOTE> a-mys.</L>
<L>Holy cherche make&thorn; no menyng,<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For swyche &thorn;yng defende anelyng;</L>
<L>But yn euery an euyl strong&mdash;</L>
<L N="11276">lygge &thorn;ou short&euml; whyle or long&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt aske &thorn;ys sacrament,</L>
<L>with gode wyl and gode entent,</L>
<L>Syn hyt auayle&thorn; but lyghtly</L>
<L N="11280">But hyt be asked derwurly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">derwr&thorn;ely.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;y gode wyl shal stonde for oght,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hyt aske, and haue hyt no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For some are now a-lyue &thorn;ou seest,</L>
<L>And dede are he may haue &thorn;e preste;</L>
<L N="11285">&THORN;arfore, ask&euml; hyt be tyme,</L>
<L>For, de&thorn; cum&thorn; now as yn swyme;</L>
<L>yn euery sykenes, aske hyt al-weys;</L>
<L N="11288">God almy&yogh;ty ys ry&yogh;t curteys,</L>
<L>he see&thorn; &thorn;y wyl, what &thorn;ou wuldest<NOTE PLACE="foot">wst.</NOTE> haue,</L>
<L>Hys mercy ys &thorn;e more &thorn;e to saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, y &thorn;anke &thorn;e of &thorn;y grace,</L>
<L N="11292">&THORN;at hast lent me<NOTE PLACE="foot">me lent.</NOTE> wyt and space,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys yn Englys for to drawe,</L>
<L>As holy men haue seyd yn sawe;</L>
<L>For lewed men hyt may auayle,</L>
<L N="11296">For hem y tok&euml; &thorn;ys trauayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;ys sacrament wyl y blynne;</L>
<L>Of shryfte, to telle, y wyl bygynne;</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue me grac&euml; so to seye,</L>
<L N="11300">Of shryfte to shew&euml; &thorn;e ry&yogh;t weye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shewe ryghtly weye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at we receyue, are we be went,</L>
<L>with-out&euml; synne, &thorn;ys sacrament.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="confession">
<HEAD>Here bygynne&thorn; shryfte.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prologue">
<HEAD>[prolog]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The ly&yogh;t of grace &thorn;at neuer ha&thorn; ende,</L>
<L N="11304">From whom al cum&thorn;, and to al men sende;
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="350"></L>
<L>Of alle godenes, wel and bygynnyng</L>
<L>Ys God of heuene, and of er&thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Hym wurschepe&thorn; alle, as wel ys wur&thorn;y,</L>
<L N="11308">Gostly &thorn;ynges as weyl as dedly,</L>
<L>Alle creatures doun hym onoure,<MILESTONE N="75a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at ryche emperoure;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou, Ihesu, ly&yogh;t my soule with-ynne,</L>
<L N="11312">And graunte me swych&euml; to bygynne</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt mowe be, &thorn;e to queme,</L>
<L>And vs alle fro synn&euml; &yogh;eme!</L>
<L>Namly, of shryft&euml; so<NOTE PLACE="foot">now.</NOTE> to seye,</L>
<L N="11316">&THORN;at we mow make vs redy wey</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fende, &thorn;at ys oure fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;arto God graunte vs alle to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, 1. 9605, p.351, note <SUP>e</SUP>.</NOTE>Twelu&euml; poyntes &thorn;yr are yn shryfte,</L>
<L N="11320">And twelu&euml; graces of here &yogh;yfte,</L>
<L>And yn alle &thorn;es&euml;, are but &thorn;re</L>
<L>whych are to do, and whych are to fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To telle hyt shortly, alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> at gesse,</L>
<L N="11324">&THORN;e fyrst ys &thorn;e grete god&euml;nesse,</L>
<L>How yt &yogh;yue&thorn; hem grace to &thorn;ryue,</L>
<L>&THORN;o men &thorn;at wyl ble&thorn;ely hem shryue;</L>
<L>Sy&thorn;en, fro what &thorn;yng men shulde hem loke</L>
<L N="11328">&THORN;at shryft&euml; blely vndyrtoke;</L>
<L>And how many &thorn;ynges, behoue&thorn; hem haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, ry&yogh;tly, here shryfte wyl craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn tokenyng, to holde vs lowe,</L>
<L N="11332">And oure wykkednes for to knowe,</L>
<L>Hyt ys ordeyned, &thorn;urgh Goddys &yogh;yfte,</L>
<L>To man, f&oacute;r to knowe oure shryfte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For vnbuxumnesse of oure fadyr Adam</L>
<L>And Eue&mdash;&thorn;urgh pryd&euml; &thorn;at fyrst cam,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Goddes commaund&euml;ment &thorn;ey brake&mdash;
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="351"></L>
<L>knowlachyng behoue&thorn; vs all&euml; make;</L>
<L>And &thorn;urgh a-nother resun ry&yogh;t gode,</L>
<L>Syn Ihesu Cryst toke flesshe and blode,</L>
<L N="11341">And was clo&thorn;ed yn oure man-hede,</L>
<L>And wyst oure wykkednes &amp; oure nede,</L>
<L>To man behoue&thorn; vs to telle oure trespas,</L>
<L N="11344">Syn he knew alle &thorn;at yn man was.</L>
<L>For whan we shryue vs to &thorn;e preste,</L>
<L>To God we shewe vs yn mannes<NOTE PLACE="foot">mannes O, goddes H.</NOTE> breste;</L>
<L N="11347">&THORN;an wot&euml; bo&thorn;&euml; God and man,<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure lyfe, &thorn;at alle may wete<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyte.</NOTE> and kan;</L>
<L>Now we shul, telle &yogh;ow sone,</L>
<L>what ys to leue, and what to done.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[12 points of shrift]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>The fyrste poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyrst poynt of &thorn;y shryfte owe&thorn; to be,</L>
<L N="11352">'with &thorn;y gode wyl and hert&euml; fre,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou art yn &thorn;y lyf&euml; best,</L>
<L>Awey &thorn;ou shalt &thorn;y synn&euml; kest;'</L>
<L>For &thorn;an wurschepest &thorn;ou God aboue,</L>
<L>And forsakest &thorn;y synne for hys loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11357">Dauyd sey&thorn;, yn wurde to fulfyl,</L>
<L>God shrofe hym with hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> gode wyl;</L>
<L>Abyde nat tyl &thorn;ou most nedly,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an hyt ys with fors and maystry;</L>
<L N="11361">&THORN;ou shryuest &thorn;e &thorn;an for drede,</L>
<L>Nat for loue, but more for nede;
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="352"></L>
<L>&THORN;an seme&thorn; hyt &thorn;at hyt shulde be</L>
<L N="11364">&THORN;at &thorn;y synne forsake&thorn; &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Swyche shryft&euml; made Acor &thorn;e &thorn;efe:</L>
<L>whan he shulde go to pyn&euml; grefe,</L>
<L>He shrof hys synne, how he hadde stole</L>
<L N="11368">&THORN;re &thorn;yng&euml;s &thorn;at he hade forhole,</L>
<L>A mantle of skarlet, a rolle of golde,</L>
<L>And syluer, he hydde vndyr molde;</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e byble men mow hyt se,</L>
<L N="11372">Yn &thorn;e story of Iosue.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point"><PB REF="00000361.tif" N="353">
<HEAD>The Secunde poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e secunde poynt ys next &thorn;yr-by,</L>
<L>'&thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt shryue &thorn;e hastyly;'</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ou doust<NOTE PLACE="foot">dost hyt.</NOTE> yn longe respyte,</L>
<L N="11376">hyt ys for&yogh;ete, &thorn;at long ys olyte.</L>
<L>Seynt Bernard &thorn;arfore, to swych chyt,</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; 'moche for&yogh;yt, &thorn;at longe abyt.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anou&thorn;er skyl ys, &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt hyt haste,</L>
<L N="11380">For yn &thorn;y synne &thorn;y lyfe ys waste;
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="354"></L>
<L>For, as moche as &thorn;e tyme do&thorn; amounte,</L>
<L>For euery oure, shalt &thorn;ou &yogh;elde acounte,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt so were, &thorn;ou my&yogh;test had space,<MILESTONE N="75b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wuldest nat come to shryfte ne grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11385">&YOGH;yt, &thorn;yr ys &thorn;e &thorn;red resun<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, l. 9719, &amp;c. last page.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at hastyly shal &thorn;y shryfte be doun;</L>
<L>For yn &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;y synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne O, shryfte H.</NOTE> ys,</L>
<L N="11388">&THORN;ou art departed fro heuene blys,</L>
<L>And fro alle &thorn;e felawrede</L>
<L>&THORN;at shulde &thorn;e help&euml; at &thorn;y nede,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;e preyers of holy cherche,</L>
<L>And fro alle gode dedes, &thorn;at men &thorn;er werche;</L>
<L N="11393">Alle &thorn;e prayers, with-out&euml; fayle,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blys of heuene, &thorn;e mow nat auayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Algate y rede, &thorn;ou do gode dede;</L>
<L N="11396">To ryse fro synne, hyt wyl &thorn;e spede,</L>
<L>And bettyr wyl hyt pay God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y penaunce shal be &thorn;e more ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;e more grace shalt &thorn;ou haue,</L>
<L N="11400">&THORN;e for to shryue and saue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syll.</I>]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point"><PB REF="00000363.tif" N="355">
<HEAD>The &thorn;red poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ryd poynt of &thorn;y shryfte,</L>
<L>'Opunly &thorn;yn herte vp lyfte:'</L>
<L>So byt God to me and &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="11404">&THORN;at opunly shal &thorn;y shryft&euml; be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Salamon to vs sey&thorn;, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">sey&thorn; &amp; to us.</NOTE> kalle&thorn;,</L>
<L>'Seuene tymes on a day &thorn;e ry&yogh;twys man falle&thorn;;'</L>
<L>As oft&euml; &thorn;an behoue&thorn; &thorn;e ryse,</L>
<L N="11408">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou lyue yn ry&yogh;t seruyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e clerke seynt Austyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a mayster of dyuyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou to many prestes atwynne,</L>
<L N="11412">Al holyche wylt shryue &thorn;y synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt fynde grace and for&yogh;yuenes,</L>
<L>And mede to &thorn;e, for &thorn;y mekenes.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;re &thorn;yng&euml;s mayst &thorn;ou fynde,</L>
<L N="11416">&THORN;at wyl &thorn;e oute of synn&euml; bynde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyrst ys, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst lere,</L>
<L>And many dyuers samples<NOTE PLACE="foot">sample.</NOTE> here,</L>
<L>Of euery prest, a lessoun,</L>
<L N="11420">To know&euml; &thorn;y saluacyoun;<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou haue herde of many a-pryse,</L>
<L>&thorn;e mor&euml; &thorn;ou canst, of queyntyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e tou&thorn;er me &thorn;enke&thorn; a gode resoun,</L>
<L N="11424">&THORN;at quyte&thorn; &thorn;e fro dampnacyoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ofter &thorn;at &thorn;ou shewest &thorn;y blame,</L>
<L>&thorn;e more me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;ou hast of shame;</L>
<L>&thorn;e shame &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast yn &thorn;y shewyng,</L>
<L N="11428">hyt ys for&yogh;yuenes, to gode endyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red, ys, &thorn;at &thorn;e weyl weres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Glossed 'kepe&thorn;' in Oxf.; 'kepy&thorn;' in Harl., by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shalt be yn alle preyers
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="356"></L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e prestes &thorn;at &thorn;e haue shryue,</L>
<L N="11432">As long&euml; tyme as euer &thorn;ey lyue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey are hold&euml; &thorn;ar-vn-to;</L>
<L>&thorn;e order of prest wyl hyt be so;</L>
<L>&thorn;e mo prest&euml;s &thorn;at for &thorn;e prey,</L>
<L N="11436">&thorn;e sunner<NOTE PLACE="foot">soner.</NOTE> art &thorn;ou yn gode wey;</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e day of Iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>To God &thorn;ey shul make &thorn;y present,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou wer&euml; clen&euml; shryue,</L>
<L N="11440">And &thorn;at &thorn;ey mow be &thorn;e for&yogh;yue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast here hyd,</L>
<L>&thorn;urgh alle &thorn;e werld &thorn;ey shul be kyd,</L>
<L>And ask&euml; dom&euml; on &thorn;e &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="11444">&thorn;at &thorn;ou, of hem, neuer shryu&euml; were;</L>
<L>For all&euml; &thorn;yng &thorn;at euer &yogh;yt was,</L>
<L>Shal &thorn;e acoupe of &thorn;y trespas;</L>
<L>&THORN;e synn&euml; hymself shal forwreye;</L>
<L>&THORN;yn Inwyt, on &thorn;e self, &thorn;e dome shal leye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>&thorn;e four&thorn;e poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;&euml; poynt, ful feyre hyt ys,</L>
<L>'yn shryft&euml; to haue mek&euml;nes.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11451">She chese &thorn;at vertu, oure lady,</L>
<L>So sey&thorn; "magnificat," here owne storye,</L>
<L>'&THORN;e gret&euml; mekenes many folde</L>
<L>Yn hys hand-mayden, God wlde beholde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syn mekenes ys so noble a &yogh;yfte,
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="357"></L>
<L N="11456">For-&yogh;ete<NOTE PLACE="foot">For&yogh;ete&thorn;.</NOTE> hyt nat yn &yogh;our&euml; shryfte.</L>
<L>So speke&thorn; &thorn;e gospel of &thorn;ys vertu,<MILESTONE N="76a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>How a mesyl come to Ihesu</L>
<L>with gode wyl, and on knees hym sette,</L>
<L N="11460">And ful myldely, Ihesu he grette;</L>
<L>"lorde," he seyd, "&thorn;ou mayst me saue</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt, and y hele haue."</L>
<L N="11463">Ihesu sagh hys myld&euml;nes,</L>
<L>And seyd "y wyl hele, alle &thorn;y sykenes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at ys yn dedly synne,</L>
<L>Gostely he ys a mesyl with-ynne;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wyl hys hel&euml; seke,</L>
<L N="11468">To hys prest he mote be meke;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou meke &thorn;e to &thorn;y prest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mek&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">mekest.</NOTE> &thorn;e to Godd&euml;s brest;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be to hym ful stour,</L>
<L N="11472">&THORN;ou doust to God grete dysonour;</L>
<L>he sytte&thorn; &thorn;ere, yn Goddys se;</L>
<L>To deme &thorn;y synne, he ha&thorn; pouste;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he blame &thorn;e for &thorn;yn euyl,</L>
<L N="11476">&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast serued moche &thorn;e deuyl,</L>
<L>Defend&euml; nat &thorn;y folye,</L>
<L>yn pryde ne yn ypocrysye;</L>
<L>No&thorn;er on &thorn;y self lye &thorn;ou no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11480">To seye &thorn;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuer wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ne forsake nat &thorn;y synne to wreye;</L>
<L>More and<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an.</NOTE> lesse, behoue&thorn; &thorn;e seye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>&thorn;e fyue&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e fyf&thorn;e.</NOTE> poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Go we now to &thorn;e fyf&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyf&thorn;e O, fythe H.</NOTE> poynt:</L>
<L N="11484">To &thorn;e &thorn;rydde hyt ys a ioynt,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere y spake of ofte shryuyng,
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="358"></L>
<L>To tell&euml; many prestes a &thorn;yng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what men are &thorn;o &thorn;at shryue hem ble&thorn;ly,</L>
<L N="11488">But &thorn;o &thorn;at synne but ly&yogh;tly?</L>
<L>For &thorn;o &thorn;at haue do synn&euml;s grete,</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vnne&thorn;e O, Vnne&thorn; H.</NOTE> wyl &thorn;ey any lete.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey here any predycacyoun,</L>
<L N="11492">Or sum ou&thorn;er chaunse be doun,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt wyl &thorn;ey neuer shryue here shame,</L>
<L>So are &thorn;ey bounde yn &thorn;e fend&euml;s hame.<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And som&euml; lette, for hard penaunce,</L>
<L N="11496">For to telle here grete cumberaunce.</L>
<L>And som&euml; lette here synne to seye,</L>
<L>For doute of prest, &thorn;at wyl hem bewreye:</L>
<L>No shame my&yogh;t to moch&euml; be</L>
<L N="11500">To &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;e' omitted.</NOTE> prest &thorn;at telle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tel&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;at pryuyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>lette&thorn; nat, &yogh;oure synne to telle;
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="359"></L>
<L N="11502">&THORN;enke&thorn; on &thorn;e peynes of helle;</L>
<L>what day &thorn;at &yogh;e dyd &yogh;oure synne,</L>
<L>And how long &yogh;e haue lyued &thorn;er-ynne,</L>
<L>what tyme, &aacute;nd how, hyt was wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Alle hyt nede<NOTE PLACE="foot">nede&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;urghout be soghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Dauyd, &thorn;e holy prophete,</L>
<L N="11508">Sey&thorn;, &thorn;ese wurdes, ful swete,</L>
<L>"Alle my shryft&euml; and my shame</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; so couerd and hyd my blame,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e fende may haue no sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11512">Me to bewrey&euml; with no ply&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ne God of heuene wyl nat se</L>
<L>Any &thorn;yng &thorn;at wyl dampn&euml; me."</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou shryue &thorn;e apertly,</L>
<L N="11516">&THORN;ou mayst be sekyr to haue mercy.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>The syxte poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e syxte poynt ys, sorowe of herte;</L>
<L>&THORN;at oght to be bytter and smerte</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest on &thorn;e gode dedes,</L>
<L N="11520">&thorn;at, God ha&thorn; do for &thorn;y nedes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast do, as &thorn;ou weyl wost,</L>
<L>&THORN;yng, &thorn;at, he hate&thorn; moste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>No creatures ne hate&thorn; he no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11524">But synn&euml; &thorn;at ys do or wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ne he hate&thorn; nat &thorn;e fende of helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cr&euml;ature of hym y telle,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e wykkednes, pryde and synne</L>
<L N="11528">&THORN;at yn hym ys, and wyl nat blynne;</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;yr neuer aungel so bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne man so weyl with God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;yf he had synned dedly,<MILESTONE N="76b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11532">To hell&euml; pyne he was wur&thorn;y;</L>
<L>&THORN;at oght &thorn;ey bo&thorn;e to sorowe and kare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn dedly synn&euml; are.
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="360"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym O, hym hym H.</NOTE> self, of mageste,</L>
<L N="11536">Vnto hys lykenes he formed &thorn;e;</L>
<L>he made &thorn;y soule bo&thorn;e fayre and clene,</L>
<L>And to hys own&euml; godhede sene;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ou synnest, &thorn;ou turnest wyk,</L>
<L N="11540">And makest &thorn;y soul&euml; black as pyk;</L>
<L>&THORN;&aacute;t God had made to hym so weyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makest hyt lyke &thorn;e fende echedeyl.</L>
<L>Sorowe oghte &thorn;an, &thorn;yn hert&euml; bynde,</L>
<L N="11544">&THORN;at &thorn;ou art t&oacute; hym so vnkynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou dysonourest hym yn &thorn;at outrage,</L>
<L>And reuylyst hys feyre ymage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11547">Of &thorn;ys &thorn;yng &thorn;an &yogh;yuest<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yfst.</NOTE> &thorn;ou leste,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou cumst laghyng to &thorn;e prest;</L>
<L>Euyl oghtest &thorn;ou laghe, coudest &thorn;ou se</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou bryngest &thorn;y dome with &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;y nekke, hangge&thorn; a wy&thorn;&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e departed fro Goddys gry&thorn;&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="11553">&THORN;y self beryst &thorn;an, on &thorn;y bak,</L>
<L>&THORN;y vyl&euml; synne &thorn;at make&thorn; &thorn;e blak;</L>
<L>May non&euml; fro &thorn;at dome &thorn;e borowe,</L>
<L N="11556">But &yogh;yf hyt be with byttyr sorowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Goddys treytour, and ry&yogh;t vyleyn!</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou no mynde of Marye Maudeleyn,</L>
<L>How she so&yogh;t oure lorde Ihesus</L>
<L N="11560">Yn Symund&euml;s hous leprous?</L>
<L>Opone &thorn;yn herte, &thorn;y gostly eres,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke on her&euml; byttyr teres!</L>
<L>She cam nat laghyng to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">com . . . . to &thorn;at.</NOTE> feste,</L>
<L N="11564">No&thorn;er for game, no&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">no.</NOTE> for geste;</L>
<L>She com wepyng with here yne,</L>
<L>Of Ihesu to haue medycyne;</L>
<L>She bro&yogh;t a smel of grete sauour,</L>
<L N="11568">&THORN;at tokene&thorn; loue and grete onour;
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="361"></L>
<L>with here ter&euml;s &thorn;at she lete,<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;arwy&thorn; she wyssh Ihesu<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ih&umacr;.</NOTE> fete:</L>
<L>So behoue&thorn; vs with here to grete,</L>
<L N="11572">&YOGH;yf we, oure synne, wyl truly lete;</L>
<L>And, but we haue sorowe for oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">for oure O, with here H.</NOTE> synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mercy of God mow we nat wynne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e O, Te H.</NOTE> seuen&thorn;e poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The seuen&thorn;e poynt ys a gode resun,</L>
<L N="11576">'&THORN;at &thorn;y shryfte be wysly doun,'</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys to sey, to a wys man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;y shryfte vndyrstond&euml; kan;</L>
<L>Nat to one &thorn;at ha&thorn; no wyt</L>
<L N="11580">Of vndyrstondyng of holy wryt.</L>
<L>Seynt Austyn sey&thorn; &thorn;ys skyl,</L>
<L>Do &thorn;yr-aftyr who so wyl,</L>
<L N="11583">'Of synn&euml;, who so wyl hym lese,</L>
<L>A wyse shryftfadyr behoue&thorn; hym chese;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may bynd&euml; and vnbynde,</L>
<L>Swych a man behoue&thorn; hym fynde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11587">A prest &thorn;at ys no clergye ynne,</L>
<L>How can he weyl dystyncte &thorn;y synne?</L>
<L>But now, oueralle, se we mowne</L>
<L>An holywatyr clerk of a tounne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at lytyl ha&thorn; lerned yn hys lyue,</L>
<L N="11592">he ys ordeyned a prest to shryue.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he shulde a shryfadyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">shryftefader.</NOTE> be,</L>
<L>hym behoue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">behouede.</NOTE> haue lerned of sum degre,</L>
<L>Or lerned, or herde, of some &thorn;at cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="11596">Ar he had be prest yn hys &yogh;ou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And moche behoue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">behouede.</NOTE> hym stody and se,</L>
<L>Or lerne at sum, yn pryuyte.</L>
<L>he may lyue, as a gode man,
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="362"></L>
<L N="11600">&THORN;oghe he lytyl clergy kan;</L>
<L>But for to preche, or her&euml; shryfte,</L>
<L>Of clergy behoue&thorn; hym sum &thorn;ryfte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And all&euml; prestes haue nat powere</L>
<L N="11604">For to assoyl&euml; &thorn;e ry&yogh;t clere,</L>
<L>But hyt be &thorn;y parysshe preste,</L>
<L>Or haue hys leu&euml; at &thorn;e leste,<MILESTONE N="77a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or at &thorn;y parsone or vycary,</L>
<L N="11608">For &thorn;ese haue of &thorn;y soule maystry:</L>
<L>Aske hem leue, and haue no gylt,</L>
<L>And shryu&euml; &thorn;e &thorn;an, where &thorn;ou wylt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>The ey&yogh;t&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">eyghte&thorn;e.</NOTE> poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The eyght&thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e twelue,</L>
<L N="11612">'&THORN;y shryfte shal be alle of &thorn;y selue,'</L>
<L>Of &thorn;yn own&euml; proper dede,</L>
<L>And bewreye none ou&thorn;er, y &thorn;e forbede.</L>
<L>&THORN;yn own&euml; foly &thorn;ou shalt seye,</L>
<L N="11616">And none ou&thorn;er body bewreye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dauyd sey&thorn; yn &thorn;e sautere</L>
<L>&THORN;ese wurdes, &thorn;urgh Goddys powere,&mdash;</L>
<L>he speke&thorn; <SUP>2</SUP>as weyl to lerned as to lewed,<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 to lernede as weyl as lewede.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>"Myn owne lyfe, lorde, y haue &thorn;e shewed;</L>
<L N="11621">None ou&thorn;er mannes y wyl dyscrye,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at were bo&thorn;e synne and vyleynye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yue gode tent, to &thorn;ys poynt,</L>
<L N="11624">&THORN;ou prest &thorn;at art a-noynt!</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf a man telle &thorn;e hys synne,</L>
<L>And a-no&thorn;er be menged &thorn;er-ynne,&mdash;</L>
<L>As &yogh;yf hyt were yn lecherye,</L>
<L N="11628">Or hylp to sle, or robborye,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ese may nat a man weyl do</L>
<L>Alone, but ou&thorn;er be &thorn;ar-vnto,&mdash;</L>
<L>Aske aftyr none ou&thorn;er name,</L>
<L N="11632">But lestene wyl hys own&euml; blame;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou any ou&thorn;er man namest,
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="363"></L>
<L>Y dar weyl seye &thorn;ou hym dyffamest;</L>
<L>hyt ys grete synne to hym and &thorn;e</L>
<L N="11636">To aske or telle &thorn;at shulde nat be;</L>
<L>hyt ys bakbytyng, and no shryfte;</L>
<L>hyt ys a spyce of euyl &thorn;ryfte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11639">&THORN;ou lewed man, y forbede &thorn;e weyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;e prest aske, bewreye &thorn;ou no deyl;</L>
<L>Bewrey&euml; weyl &thorn;yn own&euml; dede,</L>
<L>But none ou&thorn;er, y &thorn;e forbede.</L>
<L>y tolde langer yn myn auys,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11644">Loke algate &thorn;y preste be wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Do nat as &thorn;e pharysu,</L>
<L>Preyd&euml; God a&yogh;ens hys pru;</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede to &thorn;e cherche with a man</L>
<L N="11648">&THORN;at men calle a publycan,&mdash;</L>
<L>A publycan ys, yn oure sawe,</L>
<L>A synful man, oute of &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys pharysu ys to mene 'byfore,'</L>
<L N="11652">As forby alle, and fro ou&thorn;er shore,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys pharysu bygan to prey,</L>
<L>And seyd, as a shrewe shulde sey,</L>
<L>"Lord&euml;, &thorn;anked mote &thorn;ou be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, lines 10111-15.</NOTE></L>
<L N="11656">y am nat, as y ou&thorn;er se,</L>
<L>Coueytous, ne lecherous of flesshe,</L>
<L>And nat as he, &thorn;ys publycan, ys:</L>
<L N="11659">Euery woke y fast&euml; twys,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue my ty&thorn;es of rych&euml; prys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke how he made hys auauntement</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at gode &thorn;at God hadde hym sent;</L>
<L>&yogh;e, syre, on a wykked wyse,</L>
<L N="11664">O&thorn;er men for t&oacute; despyce;</L>
<L>hys owne godenes, coude he nat sey,</L>
<L>But algate ou&thorn;er, behoue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">behouede.</NOTE> hym wreye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11669">Besyd&euml; stode &thorn;e pupblycan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">publykan.</NOTE></L>
<L>And knew<NOTE PLACE="foot">knegh.</NOTE> hym self a wykked man,
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="364"></L>
<L>And durst nat loke to God vpward,</L>
<L>But knokked on hys brest ful harde,</L>
<L>And seyd with herte ful drefully,</L>
<L N="11672">"Lorde, &thorn;ou haue on me mercy!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ublycan had moch&euml; &thorn;anke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pharysu, byfore God he stanke.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;at we alle knowe,</L>
<L N="11676">"who so make&thorn; hym hygh, he shal be lowe;</L>
<L>And, who loghy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">who so loghe&thorn;.</NOTE> hym yn skylle,</L>
<L>Gode heghnes he shal come tylle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Some, whan &thorn;ey here shryfte<NOTE PLACE="foot">shryfte O, synne H.</NOTE> bygynne,</L>
<L N="11680">he shal hepe on God hys synne,</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; algate, 'he ne may no&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="77b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>kepe hym, but synne be wro&yogh;t.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And some sey, whan &thorn;ey do euyl,</L>
<L N="11684">Hyt was algate &thorn;urgh &thorn;e deuyl;</L>
<L>And some sey, as y haue herde,</L>
<L>'A! syre! so synne&thorn; alle &thorn;e werlde.'</L>
<L>Of &thorn;y self, shal nat be seyd;</L>
<L N="11688">On &thorn;e, shal alle &thorn;e blame be leyd;</L>
<L>God blame&thorn; &thorn;e for &thorn;y mysdede,</L>
<L>why seyst &thorn;ou &thorn;an, '&thorn;e behoue&thorn; nede?'<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt behoue&thorn; be nede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no fende may but tempt&euml; &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="11692">&THORN;e dede shal alle &thorn;yn own&euml; be;</L>
<L>Ne at &thorn;e worlde mayst &thorn;ou no&yogh;t kest;</L>
<L>Do &thorn;y self weyl, hyt ys &thorn;e best;</L>
<L>Here mayst &thorn;ou se wy&thorn; god&euml; skyl,</L>
<L N="11696">Alle hyt ys at &thorn;yn own&euml; wyl.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>The ny&yogh;n&thorn;e poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e ny&yogh;n&thorn;&euml; sey&thorn; 'hyt ys foly</L>
<L>On &thorn;y self for to lye.'
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="365"></L>
<L>Sey of &thorn;y self no<NOTE PLACE="foot">to.</NOTE> trespas,</L>
<L N="11700">Ne more synne, &thorn;an &thorn;ou done has;</L>
<L>Ne forhele nat &thorn;y mysdede;</L>
<L>Goddes veniaunce shalt &thorn;ou drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Bible-Tale of Ananias and Sapphira.]</HEAD>
<L>Seynt Luke sey&thorn; hys autoryte,</L>
<L N="11704">Yn &thorn;e bygynnyng of crystyanyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostoles wente<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ede.</NOTE> aboute to preche&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e crystyndom for to preche<NOTE PLACE="foot">teche.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>how men shuld &thorn;e worlde forsake,</L>
<L N="11708">And what mede &thorn;arfor&euml; take;</L>
<L>Ryche men solde here lande and fee,</L>
<L>And come to &thorn;e apostoles yn pouerte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A ryche man, &thorn;at hyghte Ananye,</L>
<L N="11712">He solde hys god&euml; plenerlye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">al plenerlye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e syluer &thorn;at he &thorn;arfore tolde,</L>
<L>&thorn;erof a party he ded withholde;&mdash;</L>
<L>Hys wyfe cunseyled wel &thorn;ar-to</L>
<L N="11716">&THORN;at he shulde nat awey alle do;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tou&thorn;er part&euml;, alle he lete,</L>
<L>And keste hyt at seynt Peter fete.<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Petyr parceyued anoun</L>
<L N="11720">&thorn;at &thorn;yr was &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;yr was &thorn;ere O, &thorn;er was H.</NOTE> gyl&euml; doun:</L>
<L>he seyd, "y comaund&euml; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;yr was, &thorn;ou shewe hyt me."</L>
<L>Ananyas &thorn;an swore hym &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="11724">he solde hys &thorn;yng, for no more.</L>
<L>Seynt Peter, &thorn;an seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyde &thorn;an.</NOTE> astyt,</L>
<L>"why lyest &thorn;ou on &thorn;e holy spyryt?"</L>
<L>&thorn;ys Ananyas fyl dowun dede,</L>
<L N="11728">As, blak, as any lede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6 <I>syll.</I>]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="366"></L>
<L>Men tok&euml; &thorn;e body asswy&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And byryed hyt, &thorn;at ych&euml; sy&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hys wyfe come byfore hem alle,&mdash;</L>
<L N="11732">Saphyra, men here calle;&mdash;</L>
<L>She cunseyled &thorn;at hyt was hyd,</L>
<L>But she ne wyst what was betyd.</L>
<L>Seyn Peter asked here &thorn;e so&thorn;e ywys,</L>
<L>"hast &thorn;ou no more &thorn;an now here ys?"</L>
<L N="11737">Saphyra answered and seyd,</L>
<L>"Y haue no more &thorn;an here ys leyd."</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou lyest," he seyde, "&thorn;e so&thorn;e y se,</L>
<L N="11740">And nat &yogh;yt al onely to me,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou lyest vnto &thorn;e holy goste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;yng wote, and my&yogh;t ha&thorn; moste."</L>
<L>Asswy&thorn;&euml;, yn a lytyl stounde,</L>
<L N="11744">She fyl dowun dede vnto &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>Men byryed sone here body</L>
<L>Besyde here husbonde Anany.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here-fore y rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou so&thorn;e seye</L>
<L N="11748">To &thorn;y prest, as &thorn;ou shust deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn &thorn;y shryfte, lye &thorn;ou neuer a deyl;</L>
<L>holy wryt forbede&thorn; hyt weyl.</L>
<L N="11751">&thorn;ou seyst hyt nat vnto &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou shewest hyt vnto Goddys breste;</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to God and to man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure defaute, see&thorn; alle, and kan.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11755">Gode graunte vs &thorn;e so&thorn;e to sey,</L>
<L>And clene be shryu&euml; ar we dey!<MILESTONE N="78a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>&thorn;e ten&thorn;e poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e ten&thorn;&euml; poynte of shryfte, &thorn;ys ys:</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou shalt haue for&yogh;yu&euml;nes,</L>
<L>&THORN;y synne naked shalt &thorn;ou make,</L>
<L N="11760">And opunly, hyt forsake.'
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="367"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hyle hem nat with feyr&euml; wurde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seme&thorn; to gadyr &thorn;y synnes to hurde:</L>
<L>yn tyfed<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyffede.</NOTE> wurdys &thorn;at slyked are,</L>
<L N="11764">Seme&thorn; &thorn;y synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ey no&yogh;t were;</L>
<L>yn swyche wurdys, &thorn;e fende ys queynte</L>
<L>To make &thorn;y shryft&euml; fals and feynte.</L>
<L N="11767">No queyntyse make &thorn;ou &thorn;erynne,</L>
<L>But sey ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou dedyst<NOTE PLACE="foot">dest.</NOTE> &thorn;y synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou mayst nat &thorn;y synn&euml;s wryte,</L>
<L>Yn shryft&euml; &thorn;e so to quyte,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou mayste speke, and haste<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> space</L>
<L N="11772">To fynde a preste yn any place,</L>
<L>with mou&thorn;e to speke, and nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">noght.</NOTE> to hyde,</L>
<L>Elles hyt ys a spyce of pryde:</L>
<L>Seynt Austyn sey&thorn;, algate &thorn;y lyue,</L>
<L>'wy&thorn; mou&thorn;e opunly, &thorn;ou &thorn;e shryue.'</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point">
<HEAD>&thorn;e eleuen&thorn;e poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11777">&thorn;e elleuen&thorn;e poynt shul we<NOTE PLACE="foot">we shul.</NOTE> knowe,</L>
<L>'To &thorn;y prest &thorn;ou bere &thorn;e lowe,</L>
<L>Blelyche yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y.</NOTE> penaunce for to do</L>
<L N="11780">Alle &thorn;at he ioyne&thorn; &thorn;e vnto.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou shalt make no fals delay,</L>
<L>Penaunce to tak&euml; at &thorn;y pay;</L>
<L>Hyt ys sloghnes and feynt&eacute;s</L>
<L N="11784">To take penaunce at &thorn;y dyuys;</L>
<L>For &thorn;y synne, &thorn;e ry&yogh;t penaunce</L>
<L>Shal be &thorn;e prest&euml;s ordynaunce:</L>
<L N="11787">&THORN;us sey&thorn; &thorn;e clerk, seynt Austyn,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e prestes mercy, &thorn;ou do &thorn;e ynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest ys crystys vycarye;</L>
<L>Do &thorn;e alle yn hys mercy."
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="368"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11791">&YOGH;yf &thorn;e prest be of any resun,</L>
<L>He wote weyl what shal be doun;<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he wote what penaunce &thorn;e falle&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fal&thorn;.</NOTE> to haue,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;y state ys, and what hyt wyl craue.</L>
<L>And, &thorn;us &thorn;ou wost weyl at gesse,</L>
<L N="11796">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou were now yn a sykenes,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> wuldest &thorn;ou do, for to lyue,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;y leche wulde &thorn;e &yogh;yue;</L>
<L>To &thorn;y soule, do &thorn;e sam&euml; wyse,</L>
<L N="11800">&THORN;y penaunce, as &thorn;e prest seyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many a&yogh;ens &thorn;e prest &thorn;ey kaste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey mowe no&thorn;er bydde ne faste,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;ey algate penaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">penaunce O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> shul do,</L>
<L N="11804">&THORN;an &thorn;ay seye hyt behoue&thorn; be so;</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng aftyr hys dedys ylle,</L>
<L>But algate at hys own&euml; wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11807">wenest &thorn;ou so to come to heuene,</L>
<L>with lyghte penaunce as &thorn;ou wylt neuene?</L>
<L>But y warne &thorn;e of &thorn;ys cas;</L>
<L>&THORN;arto ys many a streyt&euml; pas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e manhede of God wulde no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="11812">Haue heuene, but hyt were bo&yogh;t.</L>
<L>what wenest &thorn;ou haue hyt for so lytyl here,</L>
<L>whan God and man bo&yogh;t hyt so dere?</L>
<L>By heuene with &thorn;y penaunce,</L>
<L N="11816">Or, ell&euml;s-where, kepe harder chaunce.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="point"><PB REF="00000377.tif" N="369">
<HEAD>&thorn;e twelue&thorn; poynt of shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e twelue&thorn;e poynt of oure resun:</L>
<L>'Alle holy owe&thorn; &thorn;y shryfte be doun;</L>
<L N="11819">No poynt &thorn;ou shalt with-holde,</L>
<L>For, alle holy, hyt owe&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">'to' omitted.</NOTE> be tolde;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;at shal y shew&euml; &thorn;e</L>
<L>On two maners; &thorn;y shryfte al hole shall be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11823">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e shryue by parcelles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy man sey&thorn;, &thorn;y shryfte &thorn;ou steles;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou shewe one, o party,</L>
<L>And ano&thorn;er prest &thorn;ou tellest ano&thorn;er foly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shryfte ys no&yogh;t, &thorn;y soule ys betrayd,</L>
<L N="11828">And God almy&yogh;ty ys mys-payd;</L>
<L>For to echoun &thorn;yn herte was stoken,<MILESTONE N="78b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A synne &thorn;ou held&euml; &thorn;er-ynne loken;</L>
<L N="11831">&thorn;at &thorn;ou with-helde, was nat for&yogh;yue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shewedest hyt nat, hyt ys vnshryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Body ne soul&euml; ys payd weyl</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;ou haue tolde &thorn;y synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne O, soule H.</NOTE> eche deyl;</L>
<L>Telle alle &thorn;y synnes, and with-holde noun;</L>
<L>Or elles, y seye, shryfte ys &thorn;yr noun;</L>
<L N="11837">For, &yogh;yt ha&thorn; &thorn;e fende pouste</L>
<L>For to make sorowe yn &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>lo here, ensample &thorn;at ys certeyn,</L>
<L N="11840">&THORN;at noun<NOTE PLACE="foot">no man.</NOTE> may sey &thorn;er-a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou yn &thorn;y body haue wound&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">wndes.</NOTE> fyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;e leste may for-do &thorn;y lyue,</L>
<L N="11843">And hele hem all&euml; but o wunde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt may &thorn;at on,<NOTE PLACE="foot">one.</NOTE> brynge &thorn;e to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e H, to O.</NOTE> grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of how Shrift made a Woman's unconfest Sin fly out of her Mouth as a 'Blak,' a 'Fende of Helle.']</HEAD>
<L>Of a womman y herde onys spelle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at alle here synn&euml;s wulde nat telle;
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="370"></L>
<L>&thorn;ys wumman hadde do a synful dede;</L>
<L N="11848">here shamed to telle hyt for drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On a<NOTE PLACE="foot">o.</NOTE> day, grace was here &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at she &thorn;o&yogh;te she wulde be shryue:</L>
<L>&thorn;ys womman come vnto a frere,</L>
<L N="11852">And, preyd hym, here lyfe to here.</L>
<L>As she sat here shryft&euml; ynne,</L>
<L>She &thorn;o&yogh;te vppon &thorn;ys ych&euml; synne;</L>
<L>&THORN;e frer&euml; cumforted here weyl,</L>
<L N="11856">Boldely to sey euery deyl;</L>
<L>hys cumforte mad&euml; here ry&yogh;t bolde,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at she fur&thorn;e &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> synn&euml; tolde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at she hadd&euml; longe forhole,</L>
<L N="11860">&thorn;urgh cunseyl of &thorn;e deuyl stole;</L>
<L>But, at &thorn;at ych&euml; breyde</L>
<L>&thorn;at she fur&thorn;e &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> synn&euml; seyde,</L>
<L>Come fleyng oute, at<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> here mou&thorn;e a blak,</L>
<L N="11864">Ry&yogh;t as she &thorn;e wurd&euml; spak:</L>
<L>&thorn;e frer&euml; sagh hyt apertly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked God of hys mercy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at ych&euml; blak, y dar wel telle<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11868">&thorn;at hyt was a fende of helle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at my&yogh;t no lenger yn here reste</L>
<L>whan &thorn;e synn&euml; oute gan breste;</L>
<L>But as longe as she &thorn;e synne forhale,</L>
<L N="11872">&THORN;e deuyl helde ful stylle hys stale;</L>
<L>For euer-more he wyl a-byde</L>
<L>whyl o synn&euml; may hym hyde;</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;at yche resun why,</L>
<L N="11876">Shryue we oure synn&euml;, alle holy;</L>
<L>Nat by parcelles, to prestes atwynne;</L>
<L>To one, alle holy, shryue &thorn;y synne;
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="371"></L>
<L>To o preste telle<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle &thorn;ou.</NOTE> hyt euery deyl,</L>
<L N="11880">&THORN;an art &thorn;ou shryu&euml; holy weyl:</L>
<L>At oure shryfte, God &yogh;yue vs my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;ese poyntes to kunne, and shewe hem ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue &yogh;e herde &thorn;e poynt&euml;s twelue,</L>
<L>how euery man shal shryue hym selue,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;ese' omitted.</NOTE> poyntes lerned sum deyl,</L>
<L>how &yogh;e mow[&euml;] shryue &yogh;ow weyl.</L>
<L>Prest&euml;s oghte hem alle to kunne,</L>
<L N="11888">lewed men to teche and monne;</L>
<L>And but &thorn;ey tech&euml; hem &thorn;ys lore,</L>
<L>Here perel ys weyl &thorn;e more.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[8 graces that shrift gives]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="prologue">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Moche ys shryft&euml; for to preyse;</L>
<L N="11892">&THORN;e dede, to lyue, he may vpreyse;</L>
<L>A soul&euml; &thorn;at ys dede &thorn;urgh synne,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh shryft&euml; com&thorn; grac&euml; &thorn;er-ynne.</L>
<L N="11895">Many godenesse my&yogh;t men telle,</L>
<L>How shryfte confounde&thorn; &thorn;e deuyl<NOTE PLACE="foot">fende.</NOTE> of helle.</L>
<L>Lestene&thorn;, god&euml; men, to lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grace of shryft&euml; &yogh;e mow here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>The fyrste grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e fyrst grace &thorn;at &thorn;y shryfte shal &yogh;yue,</L>
<L N="11900">he make&thorn; &thorn;y soul&euml; for to lyue.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;y mou&thorn;e with shryfte ys opun,</L>
<L>De&thorn; and synne are bo&thorn;e oute lopun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Salamon sey&thorn;, &thorn;at ys wys,</L>
<L N="11904">Yn a bok&euml; of Prouerbyys,<MILESTONE N="97a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;e weye of lyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffe.</NOTE> with-outyn ende,</L>
<L>Oute of ry&yogh;twys mannes mou&thorn;e shal wende."</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mou&thorn;e &thorn;at ys vnry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11908">hyd hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys.</NOTE> synne fro grace and<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> ly&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;y mou&thorn;&euml;, no grac&euml; cum&thorn; ynne,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;yn herte ys ded yn synne:</L>
<L>De&thorn; and lyfe, &yogh;e mowe weyl se,
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="372"></L>
<L N="11912">To-gedyr mow &thorn;ey neuer be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer mowe &thorn;ey be.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For som&euml;, whan &thorn;ey come to shryfte,</L>
<L>No more wyl &thorn;ey here herte vp lyfte</L>
<L>To God for grace, but be&thorn; harde as stone,</L>
<L>So longe haue &thorn;ey with here synne gone;</L>
<L>Sorowe of synn&euml; haue &thorn;ey no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So ys here soule bene&thorn;&euml; bro&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="11919">For, a lymme &thorn;at ys ded or drye</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh sykenes, or smete yn pall&euml;sye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh men prykk&euml; hyt wy&thorn; oghte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, l. 8729 below.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hyt ys dede, hyt fele&thorn; no&yogh;te;</L>
<L>No more of grace, &thorn;e soule may fonge,</L>
<L N="11924">&THORN;at ha&thorn; ley yn synne so longe;</L>
<L>But Ihesu cryst, &thorn;at none wyl tyne,</L>
<L>he boghte alle mankynde wy&thorn; pyne,</L>
<L N="11927">And graunte&thorn; hym grace, hys shryfte by|gynne,</L>
<L>And yn hys shryfte, to sorowe hys synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;urgh swyche sorow, cum&thorn; &thorn;e lyfe of grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;e de&thorn; of synne awey to chace.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys &thorn;ys a feyr&euml; &yogh;yfte,</L>
<L N="11932">&THORN;e lyfe of euer, &thorn;urg &thorn;y shryfte;</L>
<L>&THORN;y soule &thorn;at was for synn&euml; lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh shryfte ha&thorn; grace and lyfe byfore;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys &thorn;e grace and &thorn;e fyrst vertu,</L>
<L N="11936">&THORN;at shryfte do&thorn; to &thorn;y soul&euml; pru.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e O, Te H.</NOTE> secunde grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-no&thorn;er &yogh;yfte he &yogh;yue&thorn; large;</L>
<L>hyt alegge&thorn; &thorn;e of heuy charge;</L>
<L>For euery synne, as hyt amounte&thorn;,
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="373"></L>
<L N="11940">Shalt &thorn;ou haue, whan de&thorn; acounte&thorn;;</L>
<L>But yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">yn H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> euery tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou shryuest &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of pyne shalt &thorn;ou vncharged be;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;e prest ha&thorn; powere</L>
<L N="11944">To asoyle &thorn;e quyte and clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou for synne mayst haue sorowe,</L>
<L>Fro heuy pyne hyt wyl &thorn;e borowe;</L>
<L>Body and soule moche ys a-legged,</L>
<L N="11948">whan of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &thorn;y.</NOTE> synne &thorn;ou art a-bregged;</L>
<L>kyndly, ys &thorn;at man heuy</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loke what Iope sey&thorn;, &thorn;at was of suff|raunce;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; synned wykkedly.</L>
<L>He speke&thorn; to God for swyche a chaunce,</L>
<L N="11953">"Lorde," he sey&thorn;, "weyl y hyt se,</L>
<L>My synne ys all&euml; &aacute;&yogh;ens me;</L>
<L>For, whan y &thorn;enke on my synne,</L>
<L N="11956">Ful of angwys y am with-ynne;</L>
<L>For heuy byrdon, &thorn;at y of hem bere,</L>
<L>Y am confounded, my self to were."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And y haue oft&euml; herd men seye,</L>
<L N="11960">And y wote my self &thorn;e certeyn wey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, when men haue synned dedly,</L>
<L>Here soule ys mornyng and heuy,</L>
<L>And cumbred ful of &thorn;o&yogh;t and drede,</L>
<L N="11964">Ne he ha&thorn; no wyl to do gode dede;</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;ey haue be clen&euml; shryue</L>
<L>And do &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at was hem &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;o&yogh;t hem self wundyr ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="11968">And, lesse dremed on &thorn;e ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn alle &thorn;ys worlde [n]ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Neither of the MSS. has a 'no.'</NOTE> so heuy &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>As yn synne to haue dwellyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;e synne God hate&thorn;, &thorn;at on hem hange&thorn;;</L>
<L>And Godd&euml;s hatred, helle hyt fange&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;an ys wundyr, &thorn;at &thorn;e er&thorn;e hym bere&thorn;,</L>
<L>But onely &thorn;at Goddys mercy hym were&thorn;,
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="374"></L>
<L>And wyl [nat] &thorn;at he were cumbred or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>.</NOTE> shent,</L>
<L N="11976">But a-bydeth hys amend&euml;ment;</L>
<L>So ys &thorn;e &yogh;yfte of shryft&euml; large,</L>
<L>And lese&thorn; men of heuy charge;</L>
<L>Y rede we loue hyt, at alle our my&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="79b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="11980">For body and soule, hyt make&thorn; ly&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>The &thorn;red grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;red grace of hys &yogh;euyng</L>
<L>ys, as hyt were, anoyntyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot">anoytyng H, anoyntyng O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="11983">Anoyntyng ys gode for body sore,</L>
<L>And shryfte ys a-noyntyng for euermore;</L>
<L>For, shryfte ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys as a.</NOTE> a sacrament,</L>
<L>hyt ys a grace, to alle men lent;</L>
<L>And, who-so cum&thorn; weyl &thorn;ar-tyl,</L>
<L N="11988">Four&euml; &thorn;ynges he ha&thorn; &thorn;urgh skyl;&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyrst &thorn;yng &thorn;ou shalt beleue ynne,</L>
<L>To haue for&yogh;yuenes for<NOTE PLACE="foot">of.</NOTE> &thorn;y synne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou truly &thorn;e shryue,</L>
<L N="11992">And weyl holde hyt yn &thorn;y lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mekenes ys &thorn;e tou&thorn;er, men telle,</L>
<L>And yn god&euml; hope to dwelle,</L>
<L N="11995">&THORN;at &thorn;e shryfte, &thorn;at we to go,</L>
<L>Alle oure synne may quenche and slo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;red ys, &thorn;at he shal fonde</L>
<L>To brynge hym oute of &thorn;e fend&euml;s bonde;</L>
<L N="11999">For &thorn;us hyt sey&thorn;, weyl y wote,</L>
<L>yn a boke &thorn;at seynt Austyn wrote:</L>
<L>'Yn wey to heuene, may no man be,</L>
<L>But he haue wyl, hys bande to fle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;&euml; &thorn;yng &thorn;at shal be dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12004">Alle hole &thorn;y wyl, to God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hym to wurschepe ouer alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wulde to shryfte &thorn;e calle,</L>
<L>And brynge &thorn;e &aacute;&yogh;en to hys grace
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="375"></L>
<L N="12008">&THORN;at &thorn;ou lostest with &thorn;y wanlace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;ou art &yogh;olde to be hys seruaunt,</L>
<L>Fals hym nat, but holde hym cunnaunt;</L>
<L>Hyt ys alle hys, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lyuest by,</L>
<L N="12012">Serue nat &thorn;an hys en[e]my!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>The four&thorn;e grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e four&thorn;&euml; grace ys weyl to telle,</L>
<L>how shryfte shende&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shent.</NOTE> &thorn;e fende of helle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;y[f] &thorn;ou wylt make &thorn;e deuyl shent,<MILESTONE N="80a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12016">And with-stonde hys tyc&euml;ment,</L>
<L>with no &thorn;yng mayst &thorn;ou do hym so wo</L>
<L>As lou&euml; ofte to shryft&euml; go;</L>
<L N="12019">&THORN;an ys he a-shamed to tempte &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ou bewreyyst hys pryuyte:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys sey&thorn; Salamon &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou shewe &thorn;y frende a &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at pryuyte bewreye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&thorn;er bewreye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12024">&THORN;e loue betwen&euml; &yogh;ow shal deye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sykyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">Syker ynogh.</NOTE> &thorn;ou be, certeynly,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende &thorn;e fle&thorn; ful hastyly:</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou shryuest &thorn;e for hys shame,</L>
<L N="12028">&THORN;at ys shenshepe vnto hys name;</L>
<L>Hym shame&thorn; &thorn;at he ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys so.</NOTE> ouercome,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an ys moche of hys my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys hys myghte moche.</NOTE> ouernome,</L>
<L>And euermore he ys &thorn;e more coward</L>
<L N="12032">For to tempte &thorn;e aftyrward.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syn &thorn;at God ha&thorn; swyche grace lent</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh oure shryfte to make hym shent,</L>
<L>Fonde we &thorn;an, and leu&euml; no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12036">&THORN;at he were to sham&euml; bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Certys we shuld haue gode wyl</L>
<L>To shend&euml; hym &thorn;at wulde vs spyl.
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="376"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12039">Anou&thorn;er cumfort ys wel to mene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at shent &thorn;e fende, and do&thorn;e hym tene:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he ys aboute to tempt&euml; &thorn;e</L>
<L>To any synne, what so hyt be,</L>
<L N="12043">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou with-stonde &thorn;e temptacyoun,</L>
<L>And parceyuest what he wld haue doun,</L>
<L>&THORN;an halt he hym shamly dysceyued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hys queyntyse &thorn;ou art parceyued;</L>
<L>Ne he shal neuer efte haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue eft.</NOTE> &thorn;at powere,</L>
<L N="12048">Of &thorn;at synne to tempte &thorn;e nere;</L>
<L>For &thorn;y wy&thorn;stondyng ha&thorn; hym rafte,</L>
<L>Of hys temptyng, alle &thorn;e crafte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessed ys shryfte with God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For hyt confounde&thorn; &thorn;e deuyl doun ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>God &yogh;yue vs grace, &thorn;e fende to shende,<MILESTONE N="80a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And vn-to shryfte oure wyl alle wende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>The fyfue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyf&thorn;e.</NOTE> grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12055">&YOGH;yt &thorn;yr ys a feyr&euml; &yogh;yfte</L>
<L>&THORN;at vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">vus.</NOTE> purch&aacute;ce&thorn; &thorn;e grace of shryfte;</L>
<L>hyt make&thorn; vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">vus.</NOTE> lefe, &thorn;ere we were lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>hyt pese&thorn; God whan he ys wro&thorn;e.</L>
<L>wro&thorn;&euml; shul we neuer hym make,</L>
<L N="12060">But hyt were for synn&euml; sake;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue &thorn;ou &thorn;e shryue, and mercy cry,</L>
<L>God for&yogh;yue&thorn; all &thorn;y foly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>weyl o&yogh;t we loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">to loue.</NOTE> hym as lorde and syre,</L>
<L N="12064">&THORN;at wyl so sone for&yogh;yue hys yre;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore sey&thorn; seynt Bernard,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noun, to shryfte, be slogh ne hard.</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;ou mekenes with r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L N="12068">And hope yn shryfte gode &aacute;ffyaunce,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou hast my&yogh;t merueylusly</L>
<L>Ouer God, and hyse &thorn;at are hym by,</L>
<L>And ouercomest hym gracyously,</L>
<L N="12072">&THORN;at noun may wynn&euml; with maystry;
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="377"></L>
<L>For all&euml; &thorn;yng, for drede hym doute&thorn;,</L>
<L>And to hys dom&euml;, alle &thorn;yng loute&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Shryfte, &thorn;ou art of grete vertu,</L>
<L N="12076">And purchacest to vs grete pru;</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ou comst byfore &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Forgyu&euml;nes ys &thorn;yn askyng;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at yche kyng loue&thorn; &thorn;e so wel,</L>
<L N="12080">&THORN;at he for&yogh;yue&thorn; &thorn;e euery deyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Shryfte, &thorn;ou art Goddes messangere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makyst synful, aungelys pere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou purchasest vs, pes<NOTE PLACE="foot">pees.</NOTE> and gry&thorn;;</L>
<L>So sey&thorn; to vs &thorn;e prophete Dauyd:<NOTE PLACE="foot">dauy&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12085">whan he was yn synn&euml; shent,</L>
<L>And dampnable yn Iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>A wurde he seyde to &thorn;e prophete,</L>
<L N="12088">"Y haue synned; y wyl of lete."</L>
<L>Natan &thorn;e prophete for&yogh;aue hys synne</L>
<L>whan he seyd &thorn;at he wulde blynne.<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e glose here-on sey&thorn; redyly,</L>
<L N="12092">'he &thorn;at shryue&thorn; hym parfytely,</L>
<L>Asswy&thorn;&euml;, for &thorn;at shryfte,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; for&yogh;yuenes, of Goddys &yogh;yfte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; for to be shryue,</L>
<L N="12096">And hope hyt ys to be for&yogh;yue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt so be &thorn;at he with-drawe</L>
<L>Hys mys-dede, for Goddys awe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may y, ful weyl proue</L>
<L N="12100">&THORN;at &thorn;e prophete Dauyd seyde aboue:</L>
<L>&THORN;us he seyd yn hys lyue,</L>
<L>"Y haue &thorn;o&yogh;t&euml; me to shryue,</L>
<L>And God for&yogh;au&euml; me, as sone,</L>
<L N="12104">Alle &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at y haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade.</NOTE> done."</L>
<L>Yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">See French, l. 8885-86.</NOTE> &thorn;e byble men fynde &thorn;ese &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L>Yn a boke &thorn;at ys of kynges.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace"><PB REF="00000386.tif" N="378">
<HEAD>The syxte grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The syxt&euml; grace of shryfte to neuene,</L>
<L N="12108">Hyt ioye&thorn; alle &thorn;e court of heuene.</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou &thorn;e mekest to make &thorn;y shryfte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungelys of heuene &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest a &yogh;yfte;</L>
<L>A swetnes of ioye ys hem among,</L>
<L N="12112">&THORN;at ys confermed with gospel song;</L>
<L>'Yn heuene, ys more ioye auenaunt,</L>
<L>Of a synful man repentaunt,</L>
<L N="12115">&THORN;an of nynty aungelys and nyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer synned, ne were wur&thorn;y pyne;'</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ys Goddys own&euml; wurde,</L>
<L>And redde yn chyrch&euml; at hys borde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;ou repentest with &thorn;y gode wyl,</L>
<L N="12120">And clene art shryue of alle &thorn;yn yl,</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungelys make for &thorn;e a &thorn;ankyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou fulfyllest here grete longyng;</L>
<L N="12123">Longyng, ful ofte &thorn;e aungelys make,</L>
<L>what tyme we wyl oure synnes forsake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we<NOTE PLACE="foot">we O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> were redy to haue &thorn;at blys</L>
<L>That for vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs alle.</NOTE> ordeyned ys;</L>
<L>For &thorn;urgh &thorn;e manhede of Ihesus,<MILESTONE N="80b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12128">Ys here ioye fulfylled yn vs.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an ys hyt on &thorn;e tou&thorn;er party</L>
<L>whan we synn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnen.</NOTE> dedly;</L>
<L>we lese &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at &thorn;ey are ynne,</L>
<L N="12132">For long lyggyng yn oure synne.</L>
<L>Y trowe euery man &thorn;at had &thorn;ys &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>wulde ful sone of synne be bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh hyt were for noun o&thorn;er &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="12136">But for &thorn;e aungelys grete longyng;</L>
<L>Shryue we vs &thorn;an, most and leste,</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e aungelys a feyre feste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Shryft&euml; ys &thorn;e &yogh;ate of heuene,</L>
<L N="12140">Hyt ys a wey &thorn;at lede&thorn; vs euene;
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="379"></L>
<L>And at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> entre, ys none forsake</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys weyl shryue, and ha&thorn; penaunce take;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;o &thorn;at vnshryu&euml; be,</L>
<L N="12144">&thorn;ere &thorn;ey get&euml; none entre.</L>
<L>Allas, &thorn;at oure synne ys so grefe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lese&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lesse&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at we are lefe!</L>
<L>God graunte vs alle swych shryfte to take,</L>
<L N="12148">&THORN;at we, &thorn;e aungeles, ioye mow make!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace">
<HEAD>The seuen&thorn;e grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yue&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The seuen&thorn;e ys, and &thorn;at weyl endy&thorn;,</L>
<L>'&THORN;at oure shryfte, &thorn;e deuyl blynde&thorn;.'</L>
<L>whan he made vs falle yn plyght,</L>
<L N="12152">He refte vs all&euml; gostely sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Fro synne to synne he made vs falle,</L>
<L>And oure fadres byfore vs alle.</L>
<L>Y rede we &yogh;elde hym &thorn;e countre paye,</L>
<L N="12156">And blynd&euml; we hym fro hys praye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>we put oute hys y&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye.</NOTE> gostly</L>
<L>whan we shryue vs opunly;</L>
<L N="12159">Certes he may nat knowe vs efte,</L>
<L>For oure shryfte ha&thorn; hym &thorn;e sy&yogh;t refte.</L>
<L>&thorn;at may weyl y-shewed<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-shewede O, shewed H.</NOTE> be</L>
<L>with<NOTE PLACE="foot">By.</NOTE> a tale of an autoryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[A Tale of How to put the Devil's Eye out spiritually, or How by Shrift a Man made himself invisible to the Fiend who before used to lead him about chaind.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I have read many analogous stories in the religious writings of the Middle-Age, but the present one I have not found.&mdash;G. Paris, <I>Hist. Litt.</I> xxviii. 205.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;yr was onys an ermyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12164">&THORN;at was euer yn Gode parfyte;<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So moche he hadde of Goddys grace,
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="380"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he coude knowe, yn euery place,</L>
<L>whych men were yn dedly synne,</L>
<L N="12168">And who was god&euml; lyfe with-ynne;</L>
<L>And also, he my&yogh;t se weyl</L>
<L>&THORN;yng &thorn;at was spyrytuele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An halyday fyl, as ys &thorn;e acyse,</L>
<L N="12172">Men to go to Goddys seruyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;ys erymyte lened hym on a walle,</L>
<L>And badde hys bedys, and loked ouer-alle,</L>
<L>And beheld &thorn;e folke &thorn;at come yn &thorn;e gate,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. gloss 'wey.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="12176">whyche come erlye, and whyche late,</L>
<L>whyche come with<NOTE PLACE="foot">for.</NOTE> gode deuocyoun,</L>
<L>And whyche for ou&thorn;er enchesoun:</L>
<L N="12179">Alle sagh &thorn;ys ermyte euerydeyl,</L>
<L>who come wrong, and who come weyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he stode, he toke gode hede,</L>
<L>How a deuyl, a man gan lede;</L>
<L>with hym he com alle weyl &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L N="12184">And ledde hym to &thorn;e chyrch&euml; &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And yn to &thorn;e cherch&euml;&yogh;erde;</L>
<L>For&thorn;er durst he nat, for ferde.</L>
<L>And whan he yn-to &thorn;e cherch shuld go,</L>
<L N="12188">&THORN;an brast &thorn;e fend&euml;s chayn yn two;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende stode stylle, and loked a-boute,</L>
<L>And a-bode &thorn;ys man wy&thorn;-oute;</L>
<L N="12191">On hys clawys he helde &thorn;ys cheyne,</L>
<L>And loked what tyme he come a&yogh;eyne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy man &yogh;aue god&euml; tent</L>
<L>whyder &thorn;at ych&euml; man was went.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ych&euml; man, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at O, '&thorn;at' struck thru in H.</NOTE> was yn synne,</L>
<L N="12196">And hadd&euml; long&euml; leye &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh grace &oacute;f &thorn;e holy spyryt,</L>
<L>he &yogh;ede and shrou&euml; hym astyt,</L>
<L N="12199">And &thorn;o&yogh;t neuer to turne a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>But sorowed &thorn;at h&eacute; &thorn;er-ynne had leyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>whan &thorn;at &thorn;ys man shryu&euml; was,
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="381"></L>
<L>And was passed &thorn;at synful pas,<MILESTONE N="81a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &thorn;ys man come out&euml; &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="12204">&THORN;e fende loked aboute euery-where,</L>
<L>And coude nat fynde hym, for no nede,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e ou&thorn;er, &thorn;ere &thorn;ey &yogh;ede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sy&yogh;t&euml; of hym hadde he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he O, hym H.</NOTE> lore,</L>
<L N="12208">Al &thorn;ogh he &yogh;ede next hym byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Long loked &thorn;at foul&euml; wyght,</L>
<L>And coude nat se hym with no sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He stode stylle tyl alle men were goun,</L>
<L N="12212">But sy&yogh;t&euml; of hym hadde he noun.</L>
<L>&THORN;ys holy ermyte to hym &yogh;ede:</L>
<L>"Treytur," he seyd, "for what nede</L>
<L>Stanst &thorn;ou here; telle hyt me,</L>
<L N="12216">Yn Goddys name, y c&oacute;niure &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an answered &thorn;at glotoun,</L>
<L>"y abyde here my prysoun,</L>
<L N="12219">&THORN;at long ha&thorn; be vndyr my<NOTE PLACE="foot">myn.</NOTE> hande,</L>
<L>And haue led hym aboute with &thorn;ys bande;</L>
<L>Langer wente he yn fro me,</L>
<L>He come nat oute &yogh;yt, &thorn;at y coude<NOTE PLACE="foot">may.</NOTE> se;</L>
<L N="12223">Among many, y haue hym so&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ynke.</NOTE> wundyr, y fynde hym no&yogh;te."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ermyte hyed fast and ran,</L>
<L>And ouertoke &thorn;ys ych&euml; man,</L>
<L>And, preyd hym a stounde to dwelle,</L>
<L N="12228">And of hys lyfe, sumwhat to telle:</L>
<L>"Y graunte," he seyd, "to &thorn;e to seye.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cherche, as y wente my weye</L>
<L>y felte me charged yn a synne,&mdash;</L>
<L N="12232">And, long had y leye &thorn;ere-ynne,&mdash;</L>
<L>y &thorn;o&yogh;te y wulde me &thorn;er-of shryue,</L>
<L>And amende &thorn;e trespas yn my lyue.</L>
<L N="12236">At &thorn;e cherche, y shroue me weyl,</L>
<L>Plenerly of euery deyl;
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="382"></L>
<L>Blessed be now God almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ynke&thorn; y am wundyrly ly&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12239">&THORN;an &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;e Ermyte astyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at whan men haue yn synne delyte,<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an ha&thorn; &thorn;e fend&euml; enchesoun</L>
<L>To bynd&euml; hym as a presun;</L>
<L>And whan he ha&thorn; wyl, hym to shryue,</L>
<L N="12244">Hys bandys brest, and al to-ryue;</L>
<L>And, whan he ys clen&euml; shryuyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuyl knowe&thorn; hym no more sy&thorn;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e holy man come &thorn;an to &thorn;e deuyl,</L>
<L N="12248">And bad he shulde do no man euyl,</L>
<L>But go to helle, &thorn;ere he come fro,</L>
<L>Euer to dwelle yn pyne and wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore, y rede &thorn;at we bygynne</L>
<L N="12252">To shryu&euml; vs of alle our synne.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="grace"><PB REF="00000391.tif" N="383">
<HEAD>The eyghte<NOTE PLACE="foot">eyghte&thorn;e.</NOTE> grace &thorn;at shryfte &yogh;yne&thorn;.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>New&euml; &thorn;y shryft&euml; euer ylyke,</L>
<L>hyt make&thorn; Iesu cryst to &thorn;e meke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">myke.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt &thorn;yr ys a properte,</L>
<L N="12256">&THORN;at euer ylyke &thorn;y shryfte shal be;</L>
<L>As ofte as &thorn;ou yn synne doust falle,</L>
<L>As oft&euml; rys vp fro hem alle,</L>
<L>Nat, wy&thorn; no feyntyse,</L>
<L N="12260">with verry shryft&euml; shalt &thorn;ou ryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Baptem, fro Adams synne vs drewe,</L>
<L>But shryfte clense&thorn; vs euery day newe;</L>
<L>we synful mow &thorn;arfore be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be &thorn;arfore.</NOTE> bolde;</L>
<L N="12264">To vs ys shryfte a blysful holde;</L>
<L>As ofte as &thorn;ou to shryfte art went,</L>
<L>As ofte helpe&thorn; &thorn;e, &thorn;e sacrament:</L>
<L>Here-of speke&thorn; Isay&euml;</L>
<L N="12268">A wurde yn hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> prophesye,</L>
<L>"whan man ha&thorn; fylled hys soule with ylle
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="384"></L>
<L>&THORN;urgh hys own&euml; wykked wylle,</L>
<L N="12271">y rede hym &thorn;at he oft&euml; synge</L>
<L>wurschyp vn-to oure heuene kynge."</L>
<L>&THORN;ys song to mene, yn my resoun,</L>
<L>Ys trew&euml; shryfte, and oft&euml; doun.</L>
<L>&THORN;yr ys no &thorn;yng &thorn;at man may neuene,</L>
<L N="12276">&THORN;at more stere&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">styre&thorn;.</NOTE> God of heuene,</L>
<L>Of vs synful to haue mercy,</L>
<L>&THORN;an do&thorn; shryfte, &thorn;ere hyt ys do trewly.
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="385"></L>
<L>who so synge&thorn; to God with shryfte,</L>
<L N="12280">For hys song he &yogh;yue&thorn; hym a &yogh;yfte;</L>
<L>Hys &yogh;yfte ys ioye with-outyn wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend&euml; was kast fro.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[properties of shrift]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="property">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12283">On many maner my&yogh;t men proue</L>
<L>How shryfte ys gode to oure byhoue;</L>
<L>But longe hyt wer&euml; for to dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">And.</NOTE> propertees, alle for<NOTE PLACE="foot">'for' omitted.</NOTE> to telle,</L>
<L>But touche y wyl, two or &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="12288">&THORN;at &yogh;e mow weyl warned be.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="property"><PB REF="00000394.tif" N="386">
<HEAD>That &thorn;ou falle nat yn wanhope.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Haue no wanhope, for no maner of kas;</L>
<L>Be nat lyke Kaym ne Iudas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e werst &thorn;arfore, y wylle fyrst grope,</L>
<L N="12292">&THORN;at man kalle 'wanhope:'</L>
<L>Al tymes ys God more<NOTE PLACE="foot">'more' omitted.</NOTE> wro&thorn;er with &thorn;ys</L>
<L>&THORN;an with any o&thorn;er &thorn;yng<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne.</NOTE> &thorn;at ys;</L>
<L>&THORN;yr ys no synne &thorn;at men of rede,</L>
<L N="12296">S&oacute; moche withsey&thorn; &thorn;e godhede;</L>
<L>For wanhope weny&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e foly</L>
<L>Be more &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an ys.</NOTE> Godd&euml;s mercy;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at synne be more,</L>
<L N="12300">&THORN;ou wenest &thorn;at &thorn;e godhede, so moche ne wore,</L>
<L>Ne had so moch&euml; my&yogh;t hym ynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt my&yogh;t f&oacute;r&yogh;yue alle &thorn;y synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se how wanhope, man wyl shende</L>
<L N="12304">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e godhede with-outyn ende!</L>
<L>Hyt ys no wundyr, &thorn;ogh he be wro&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Hyt a&yogh;ensey&thorn; hys my&yogh;t &amp; hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">'hys' omitted.</NOTE> mercy bo&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swych shryfte mad&euml; wreched Kaym,</L>
<L N="12308">whan he hadde hys bro&thorn;er slayn;</L>
<L>'Of God,' he seyd, 'he was nat wur&thorn;y,</L>
<L>For hys grete synne, to haue mercy.'</L>
<L>For hys wanhope, &thorn;at foule glotoun,</L>
<L N="12312">God &yogh;aue hym hys malysun;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;o, &thorn;at trowe synne may be</L>
<L>Mor&euml; &thorn;an Godd&euml;s pyte.<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And swych shryft&euml;, made Iudas;</L>
<L N="12316">He shrou&euml; hym of hys trespas,</L>
<L>He hadde grete sorowe and contrycyun</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ded hys lorde tresun;</L>
<L N="12319">&THORN;er-of he repented hym so gretly,</L>
<L>he &yogh;ede and hyng hym self ful hy;</L>
<L>He shroue hym with grete r&eacute;pentaunce,
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="387"></L>
<L N="12322">But of Goddys mercy he hadde none affy|aunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here mowe &yogh;e se, &thorn;at shryfte and sorowe</L>
<L>Alle only may no man borowe,</L>
<L>But he haue gode hope, whan he ys shryue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys synne shal be for&yogh;yue:</L>
<L>&THORN;ys shal &yogh;e beleue, with-out&euml; nay,</L>
<L N="12328">&THORN;at, God wyl for&yogh;yue, and may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An holy man &thorn;ys sam&euml; spelle&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of Iudas wanhope telle&thorn;,</L>
<L>'For hys wanhope, God wro&thorn;er was,</L>
<L>&THORN;an for hys tresun or ou&thorn;er trespas;</L>
<L>Hys wanhope toke he more to grefe,</L>
<L N="12334">&THORN;an hys takyng, as a &thorn;efe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, ful of mercy mylde,</L>
<L>Fro wanhope vs all&euml; shylde,</L>
<L>And graunte vs alle swych <SUP>1</SUP>hope &amp; sted|fast<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[1_1 <I>overline: leave out</I> stedfast]</NOTE> trou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="12338">&thorn;at &thorn;y mercy on vs haue rou&thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="property">
<HEAD>That &thorn;ou excuse nat &thorn;y synne.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt &thorn;er ys an vn&thorn;ryfte</L>
<L N="12340">&THORN;at do&thorn; moche ska&thorn;e yn shryfte;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou defendest &thorn;e fro ply&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And puttest &thorn;y synne on God almy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So dyd oure fadyr Adam,</L>
<L N="12344">whan God of heuene to hym cam,</L>
<L>And seyd, "Adam, why art &thorn;ou yn synne?"</L>
<L>"lorde," he seyd, "my wyfe made me bygynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ych&euml; wyfe &thorn;at &thorn;ou me wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12348">She synned fyrst, and y no&yogh;t."</L>
<L>See&thorn; how Adam bygan to lye,
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="388"></L>
<L>And put on God hys owne folye!</L>
<L>For, God forbede &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym &thorn;at.</NOTE> tre,<MILESTONE N="82a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12352">&THORN;at he ne shulde ete &thorn;er-of, ne she:</L>
<L>See&thorn; how he ded, &thorn;at God forbede,</L>
<L>And dyd aftyr hys wyu&euml;s rede;</L>
<L>He wulde haue excused hys fame,</L>
<L N="12356">As who sey&thorn; 'God was to blame;'</L>
<L>&THORN;ese lewed men sey, and erre ful ylle,</L>
<L>And seye 'hyt was alle Goddys wylle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at hyt Goddys wyl shulde be,</L>
<L N="12360">why forbede he hym &thorn;at tre?</L>
<L>Hyt may nat be, for no nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wulde be do, he shulde forbede;</L>
<L N="12363">Syn he forbed, hyt shulde be no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens hys byddyng, Adam hyt wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;an hyt seme&thorn;, hyt was but suffraunce,</L>
<L>Nat hys wyl, nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne.</NOTE> hys ordynaunce,</L>
<L>But lete hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym O, <I>om</I>. A.</NOTE> haue alle hys fre wyl,</L>
<L N="12368">Hym self for to saue or spyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nay, nay! Adam, alle mys &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>On God to put alle hys mysdede,</L>
<L>As who sey&thorn; 'he shulde nat be shent,</L>
<L N="12372">But Eue brak &thorn;e commaund&euml;ment,</L>
<L>For she &yogh;aue hym &thorn;e appul here lete,</L>
<L>And God was gylty &thorn;at he hyt ete.'</L>
<L>He my&yogh;t a<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue.</NOTE> f&oacute;rsake, and seyd nay,</L>
<L>But whan he toke hyt, he brake &thorn;e lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12377">&YOGH;yf a man me now forbede</L>
<L>&thorn;yng &thorn;at y ne shulde haue of dede,</L>
<L>y were to blame &yogh;yf y hyt toke;</L>
<L N="12380">Bettyr were fyrst &thorn;at y hyt forsoke;</L>
<L>So my&yogh;t Adam haue hyt forsake,</L>
<L>For God for-bede &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;at' omitted.</NOTE> none shuld be take.</L>
<L>Syn he dyd &thorn;us a&yogh;ens hys forbode,</L>
<L N="12384">Ho dar sey hyt was &thorn;e wyl of God?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt &thorn;yr are many &thorn;at &thorn;us seye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle here wyte on God wul leye,
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="389"></L>
<L>And tell&euml; men &thorn;us apertly</L>
<L N="12388">&THORN;ey mow nat hold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">holde hem.</NOTE> fro foly,</L>
<L>And sey &thorn;ey mowe nat lyu&euml; chaste,<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But nedly hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem.</NOTE> behoue&thorn; do waste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y seye, as &thorn;e holy man seys,</L>
<L N="12392">He lye&thorn; apertely on alle weys;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;at he wulde do now folye</L>
<L>wy&thorn; a womman yn lecherye,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf a-no&thorn;er, hyt my&yogh;t se,</L>
<L N="12396">At &thorn;at tyme he wulde late be;</L>
<L>He ne lette&thorn; for Goddes comaundement,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits these two lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>But for hym &thorn;at &thorn;ere ys present.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Harl</I>. omits these two lines.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;o &thorn;at sey 'hem byhoue&thorn; nedely,'</L>
<L N="12400">&THORN;ey acoupe God of here folye.</L>
<L>why shulde he &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;an.</NOTE> &thorn;yng forbede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedely moste be do yn dede?</L>
<L>hyt were foly, comaunde a &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="12404">&THORN;at my&yogh;t nat &yogh;yue no warantyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>yn twey &thorn;ynges, wykkedly &thorn;ey sey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on God here blame alle leye;</L>
<L N="12407">Lyers algate &thorn;ey are strong;</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er, &thorn;ey hepe on God here wrong;</L>
<L>wykkedly &thorn;ey synne on &thorn;ese maners,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey make hym wers &thorn;an ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">be.</NOTE> here peres.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="property">
<HEAD>That &thorn;ou make nat &thorn;y synne lytyl to<NOTE PLACE="foot">'to' omitted.</NOTE> seme.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12411">Make nat &thorn;y synne, lytyl to seme;</L>
<L>Telle smale and grete, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou God queme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt &thorn;er ys an enchesun</L>
<L>ys kalled 'dymynucyun':</L>
<L>On englys, hyt ys to mene,</L>
<L N="12416">To make &thorn;y synne lytyl to<NOTE PLACE="foot">'to' omitted.</NOTE> seme;</L>
<L>Hyt ys to mene also ano&thorn;er &thorn;yng,
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="390"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;y synne to make shedyng;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ys may be on two manere,</L>
<L N="12420">whan hyt shuld be hole and clere:&mdash;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou tellest but &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L>&thorn;e smal&euml; synnes &thorn;an wylt &thorn;ou lete;</L>
<L>&thorn;ese clerkys kalle hem 'cyrcumstauncys,'</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete synnes are &thorn;ey puruyaunces;<NOTE PLACE="foot">purueyaunces.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12425">&thorn;ou puru&eacute;yst fyrst, yn &thorn;y &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>How &thorn;e grete synnes shulde<NOTE PLACE="foot">shul.</NOTE> be wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Oftyn tyme, a foule &thorn;o&yogh;t and an<NOTE PLACE="foot">'an' omitted.</NOTE> yl,</L>
<L>wy&thorn; lykyng &thorn;er-yn, gadere&thorn; a wyl<MILESTONE N="82b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12429">Aftyr &thorn;at wyl, cum&thorn; a sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Aftyr a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e.</NOTE> syghte, a speche ful ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>weytyng yn wey, and &thorn;arto &yogh;yftes;</L>
<L N="12432">Alle &thorn;ese, to &thorn;e dede a man lyftes;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese kalle men 'cyrcumstaunces,'</L>
<L>&THORN;at vn-to &thorn;e grete dede men haunces.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo here ensample of oure tale;</L>
<L N="12436">&THORN;ou s&euml;est<NOTE PLACE="foot">sest.</NOTE> stykk&euml;s &thorn;at are smale,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey brenne fyrst, feyre<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyght.</NOTE> and shyre,</L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;e grete stokkes<NOTE PLACE="foot">stokes.</NOTE> sone on fyre:</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t so do &thorn;&eacute;se smale, &thorn;e with-ynne,</L>
<L N="12440">A gret&euml; synn&euml; to bygynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore y warne &thorn;e, yn &thorn;y lyfe,</L>
<L>Of swych&euml; smale &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e shryue;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou for-hele hem with &thorn;y wyl,</L>
<L N="12444">So mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;y soul&euml; spyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t so fare&thorn; forholen synne,</L>
<L>As fyre, bor&euml; bosum ynne;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last&euml;, hyt hym dere&thorn;,</L>
<L>And brenny&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">br&emacr;n&thorn;.</NOTE> &thorn;at hym about&euml; bere&thorn;;</L>
<L N="12449">For no synne may be hyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt ne behoue&thorn; opunly be kyd;
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="391"></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf hyt be shewed here apert,</L>
<L N="12452">Yn ou&thorn;er stede hyt ys couert;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hyd&euml; here &thorn;y blame,</L>
<L>hyt shal be shewed to &thorn;y shame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Austyn sey&thorn; a wurde to charge,</L>
<L N="12456">Of Goddys &yogh;yfte, how hyt ys large:</L>
<L>"Shryue&thorn; &yogh;oure ded&euml;s and &yogh;oure &thorn;o&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For God for&yogh;yue&thorn; alle or no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for&yogh;yue&thorn; he alle with gladehede,</L>
<L N="12460">Or alle abyde&thorn; to hys wra&thorn;hede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou be all&euml; fully shryue,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;an be &thorn;ey all for&yogh;yue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e shryue of alle but one,</L>
<L N="12464">No&thorn;er he for&yogh;yue&thorn; &thorn;at, ne none."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yn ry&yogh;t resun &thorn;ese clerkys telle,</L>
<L>yn &thorn;at stede &thorn;ere God shal dwelle<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Plenerly, hyt behoue&thorn; be clene,</L>
<L N="12468">&THORN;at no synn&euml; mowe be sene.</L>
<L>whan synne ys shryue, and clene eche deyl</L>
<L>&THORN;ere wyl God, holde hys hostele;</L>
<L>&THORN;e mantel of loue ys leyd ful euene,</L>
<L N="12472">&THORN;at hele&thorn; Ihesu and kyng of heuene.</L>
<L>Yn o stede ne mowe &thorn;ey reste;</L>
<L>God or &thorn;e fend&euml;, out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e toon oute O.</NOTE> keste;</L>
<L>One of &thorn;ese, behoue&thorn; &thorn;e chese;</L>
<L N="12476">Take &thorn;e toon, &thorn;e tou&thorn;er &thorn;ou lese.</L>
<L>Y wulde holde hym more &thorn;an wode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chese&thorn; &thorn;e wykked, and leue&thorn; &thorn;e gode.</L>
<L>Take we God on oure party,</L>
<L N="12480">And fle we &thorn;e fend&euml;s cumpany.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="property">
<HEAD>That &thorn;ou make no skornyng yn shryfte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Skorne nat, and seye &thorn;ou wylt forsake</L>
<L>&THORN;y synne, and eft a&yogh;en hyt take.
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="392"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;yt wyl y warne &thorn;e of o &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="12484">Yn shryft&euml; make &thorn;ou no skornyng.</L>
<L>Lytyl mayst &thorn;ou spede &thorn;at whyle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou shryu&euml; &thorn;e with gyle;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou make &thorn;y shryft&euml; feynt,</L>
<L N="12488">Sykyr &thorn;ou be, &thorn;ou shalt be a-teynt,</L>
<L>whan [&thorn;at] &thorn;ou art nat yn wyl</L>
<L>&THORN;e to wy&thorn;draw&euml; fro &thorn;yn yl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>what doust &thorn;ou byfore &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L N="12492">And, hast d&eacute;seyt yn &thorn;y brest?</L>
<L>Asoyled mayst &thorn;ou neuer be,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou wylt &thorn;y synn&euml; fle.</L>
<L>with skorn&euml; wenest &thorn;ou &thorn;e quyte</L>
<L N="12496">As a fals ypocryte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou holdest nat cunnaunt,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hetest and takest an hand.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lytyl tale y wyl &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L>How he was shryue, &thorn;e fende of helle.<NOTE PLACE="marg">A tale.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Tale of how the Devil came to be Shriven.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[Not found elsewhere by G. Paris.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>An holy man, &thorn;at God was dere,</L>
<L N="12502">On&euml;s sat, shryft&euml; to here;</L>
<L>To hym come &thorn;e fende of helle,<MILESTONE N="83a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yn form of a<NOTE PLACE="foot">of a O, a H.</NOTE> man, hys synne to telle;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy man wende hyt had be</L>
<L>A man yn flessh as<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> he dyd se;</L>
<L>On hys knees he sett hym downe,</L>
<L N="12508">with &thorn;e prest, for to roune,</L>
<L>And tolde hys wykkednes ful bostely.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode man lestned, &thorn;at satte hym by;</L>
<L>He seyde, "y haue be yn &thorn;e se;</L>
<L N="12512">&THORN;ere &thorn;re &thorn;ousend shyppes were dreynt &thorn;urgh me;
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="393"></L>
<L>"And alle &thorn;e folk with-out&euml; numbre,</L>
<L>All&euml; bro&yogh;t y hem to kumbre;</L>
<L N="12515">Aboue, yn-to &thorn;e wynde y wente,</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;t hem alle to &thorn;at turment;</L>
<L>On land y haue do more tresun</L>
<L>wy&thorn; fyre and slaghtyr yn euery toune,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e ska&thorn;e y my&yogh;t of mone,</L>
<L N="12520">T&oacute; hem &thorn;at yn borw&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">borewes.</NOTE> wone;</L>
<L>y haue made wra&thorn;&thorn;e and euyl wyl</L>
<L>Betwyx&euml; hem &thorn;at wulde none<NOTE PLACE="foot">none O, mone H.</NOTE> yl,</L>
<L>And sle<NOTE PLACE="foot">sle O, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> echoun ou&thorn;er at here my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="12524">More with wrong, &thorn;an with ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Yn pryde, yn Ire, yn enuye,</L>
<L>yn slou&thorn;&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">slou&thorn;e O, slogh H.</NOTE> and yn coueytyse,</L>
<L>yn glotonye, and yn lecherye,</L>
<L N="12528">Y delyte me yn euery vyleynye;</L>
<L>Foule flessh dedes &thorn;at are ouer rank,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an ou&thorn;er y take to &thorn;ank;</L>
<L>But, pryde algate, and coueytyse,</L>
<L N="12532">Y may nat leue, ne none of &thorn;yse;</L>
<L>Ten &thorn;ousend men dampned be</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;ese two, for loue of me;</L>
<L>when y fynde hem custummably</L>
<L N="12536">Yn &thorn;ese two synn&euml;s alle redy,</L>
<L>Ful weyl paye&thorn; me &thorn;at synne,</L>
<L>And bounde are &thorn;ey to me &thorn;er-ynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;an do &thorn;ey, ry&yogh;t as y wyl,</L>
<L N="12540">All&euml; wrong wy&thorn;-out&euml; skylle;</L>
<L>Fro wykked to wers, y do hem falle,<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For y am mayster ouer hem alle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey wulde wake, y do hem slepe,</L>
<L N="12544">And yn ydulnes to lepe;</L>
<L>For whan &thorn;ey are yn bedd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bedde O, bed H.</NOTE> bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>y do hem synne yn ydul &thorn;o&yogh;t;</L>
<L>yn &thorn;o&yogh;t of folye, and foule delyte,
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="394"></L>
<L N="12548">"I do hem &thorn;enk&euml; &thorn;an ful tyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Certes y may nat telle hyt alle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e synne &thorn;at y haue do, and more shal.</L>
<L>Cryst, loue y neuer a deyl,</L>
<L N="12552">Ne none &thorn;at on hym byleue&thorn; weyl,</L>
<L>For, yn euery dedly synne</L>
<L>y am bounde, and may nat blynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Y dyd neuer commaundement</L>
<L N="12556">&thorn;at God vn-to &thorn;e folk ha&thorn; sent.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacramentys of holy cherche,</L>
<L>y loued hem neuer, ne neuer wulde werche.</L>
<L>Pryue synne and sacrylage,</L>
<L N="12560">&THORN;at loue y moste, and rycolage.</L>
<L>holy cherche, despyse and fyle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wyl y ble&thorn;ly, alle my whyle."<NOTE PLACE="inter">tyme</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e holy man, lestn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">lystene.</NOTE> bygan,</L>
<L N="12564">And, had wundyr of &thorn;at o man</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;t so moche synn&euml; do,</L>
<L>As he a-couped hym self vn-to:</L>
<L>&THORN;e god&euml; man, for alle &thorn;ys chaunce,</L>
<L N="12568">Sagh yn hym no r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>Ne no sorowe made of contrycyun</L>
<L>For no synne &thorn;at he had doun.</L>
<L>He seyd, "hast &thorn;ou any shame of &thorn;y synne</L>
<L N="12572">&THORN;at &thorn;ou h&aacute;st be so moche ynne?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fende answered to hym a&yogh;en:</L>
<L>"Wyt&euml; &thorn;ou weyl for certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y dyd but one or two,</L>
<L N="12576">Y wulde haue do twenty and mo."</L>
<L>"&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an O, &THORN;at H.</NOTE> art &thorn;ou," he seyd, "a wykked denyl,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou repentest &thorn;e of none euyl."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, certeys," he seyd, "so y am,<MILESTONE N="83b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12580">A fende of helle, to &thorn;e y cam."</L>
<L>"Y coniure &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou me telle&mdash;</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;ou art a fende of helle&mdash;</L>
<L>For what maner &thorn;yng a lyue,
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="395"></L>
<L>"&THORN;at &thorn;ou come hedyr, &thorn;e to shryue?"</L>
<L N="12585">"Now behoue&thorn; me nedely</L>
<L>Telle &thorn;e euerydel, and why.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Y se men come to shryfte so &thorn;ykke,&mdash;</L>
<L>Of some, here soules as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as H, <I>om</I>. O.</NOTE> blak as pykke,</L>
<L N="12589">And as grymly on to se</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="foot">And as H, As O.</NOTE> any fende yn helle may be,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o sam&euml; men, when &thorn;ey are shryue,</L>
<L N="12592">So moche bry&yogh;tnes ys hem &yogh;yue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no sonn&euml; ys so bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>As here soules yn Goddys sy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y wyst my self hydus and blak,</L>
<L N="12596">And no &thorn;yng ha&thorn; so moch&euml; lak;</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh my shryfte, y wende to spede,</L>
<L>To haue turned so bry&yogh;t as ou&thorn;er &yogh;ede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ou art dyceyued, foule treytoure!</L>
<L>&THORN;y shryfte may haue no swyche onour;</L>
<L N="12601">Hyt may neuer do &thorn;e pru,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feyrehede of shryfte, ne &thorn;e vertu.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou sawe so blak with-ynne,</L>
<L N="12604">&THORN;ey are repentaunt of here synne,</L>
<L>And are now come to ry&yogh;t gode wyl,</L>
<L>To do penaunce, and no more yl;</L>
<L>And &thorn;urgh &thorn;e shryfte &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue take,</L>
<L N="12608">&THORN;ey are asoyled, and synne forsake.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er.</NOTE>-of cum&thorn; alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">al.</NOTE> here beute</L>
<L>Yn here soules, as &thorn;ou mayst se;</L>
<L N="12611">But &thorn;ou &thorn;at hast no r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>But loue and lykyng yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">in &thorn;y.</NOTE> cumbraunce,</L>
<L>To feyrehede shalt &thorn;ou neuer wende,</L>
<L>But blak<NOTE PLACE="foot">blake.</NOTE> and foule wy&thorn;-outyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">outen.</NOTE> ende;</L>
<L>A deuyl &thorn;ou come; to Satan &thorn;ou go!
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="396"></L>
<L N="12616">To &thorn;at sorowe &thorn;at &thorn;ou come fro."</L>
<L>he wente a-wey, alle for-lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">al forlore.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A deuyl, as he was byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;arfore, gode men, wyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wete.</NOTE> &yogh;e weyl,</L>
<L N="12620">Shryfte saue&thorn; nat a-lone eche dyl,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alone yche deyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;e haue gode r&eacute;pentaunce,</L>
<L>And of fory&yogh;uenes gode affyaunce,</L>
<L>And yn gode wyl, &yogh;ow to withholde</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o.</NOTE> synnes &thorn;at byfore are tolde.<MILESTONE N="84a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12625">God graunte vs grace, swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych.</NOTE> shryfte to make,</L>
<L>And for oure synne swyche<NOTE PLACE="foot">swych.</NOTE> penaunce take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we be neuer more a-teynt<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuermor ateynt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12628">For fals shryuyng, ne for feynt;</L>
<L>But graunte vs alle vs self<NOTE PLACE="foot">selfe.</NOTE> to &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>And yn oure shryfte Ihesu to queme! Amen!<NOTE PLACE="foot">O. adds 'Explicit.'<NOTE PLACE="end">The next Treatise to Man. Pecch&eacute;, in the same scribe's hand, is no. 60 in the E. E. T. Soc.'s Original Series, the "Medytacyuns of &thorn;e soper of oure lorde Ihesu, And also of his Passyun, And eke of &thorn;e peynes of hys swete modyr, Mayden Marye, &thorn;e whyche made yn latyn, Bonauenture Cardynall,"&mdash;edited by Mr. J. Meadows Cowper. After this, follows 'Roberd of Cysylle' in another hand, and ends the MS.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endy&thorn; Manuel Pecch&eacute;.</TRAILER>
